const PB_DATA = {"alabama": {"name": "Alabama", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Alabama’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative drug therapy management agreement” (CDTMA). ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(1)(d) (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThere is no definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alabama law. The definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alabama regulation does not expressly include prescribing by a pharmacist. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-x-2-.14(1) (2024).\nThere are no provisions in Alabama pharmacy laws or regulations expressly authorizing a pharmacist to prescribe drugs or medications generally or to obtain state/DEA registrations to prescribe controlled substances.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Alabama cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Alabama practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Alabama pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Alabama laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, the answer is likely “no.”\nThe definition of “dispense” in Alabama law includes to “administer . . . a drug or medicine” to an ultimate user. ALA. CODE § 34-23-1(5) (West 2024). In addition, the description of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alabama regulation includes “administering . . . drugs and devices.” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-x-2-.14(1) (2024). Neither of these provisions limits the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore supports the conclusion that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine outside of a collaborative drug therapy management agreement (CDTMA).\nHowever, while there is an Alabama regulation expressly covering the administration of immunizations, including training necessary to do it, there are no provisions expressly addressing administration of any other kinds of drugs or medications, including controlled substances. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.46 (2024). This could mean a pharmacist cannot administer buprenorphine as a matter of general practice.\nThe deciding factor may be the response to the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, which calls into question whether an Alabama pharmacist can administer a controlled substance outside of a CDTMA. As detailed in the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, an Alabama pharmacist cannot administer buprenorphine under a CDTMA without submitting a special request that can be approved or rejected. Given this limitation, the most logical conclusion is that an Alabama pharmacist would not have more authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CDTMA than within one.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Alabama to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe description of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alabama regulation does not expressly include either ordering or evaluating lab tests. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-x-2-.14(1) (2024).\nMoreover, Alabama pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address ordering or evaluating lab tests by pharmacists outside of CDTMAs.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Alabama to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nUnder Alabama regulation, a CDTMA covers “collaborative drug therapy management” (CDTM) which includes having a pharmacist “monitor, modify, and discontinue drug therapy as directed by the physician.” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(1)(d) (2024).\nAlabama regulation expressly provides that the scope of a CDTMA “shall NOT include . . . the prescribing of controlled substances listed or to be listed in the schedules under federal law and in [Alabama law and regulation].” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(5)(a) (2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Alabama laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CDTMAs.\nExpressly specify in Alabama laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CDTMAs.\nAllow Alabama pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "No, based on the information described below. [However, there exists a process whereby Alabama’s Joint Committee on Pharmacy Collaborative Practice (Joint Committee) could approve a special request. The Joint Committee involves the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners (BME) and Alabama Board of Pharmacy (BOP)]\nUnder Alabama regulation, a CDTMA covers CDTM which includes having a pharmacist “monitor, modify, and discontinue drug therapy as directed by the physician.” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(1)(d) (2024). Although the regulation uses the words “monitor” and “modify,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nAlabama regulation requires BME/BOP to “promulgate standard protocols consistent with the recommendation of the Joint Committee establishing the patient care services that may be rendered under [a CDTMA].” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(14)(a) (2024). Moreover, BME/BOP “shall promulgate a standard formulary of legend drugs and/or drug classes consistent with the recommendations of the Joint Committee that may be utilized” under a CDTMA. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(15)(a) (2024).\nAs of October 2024, the CDTMA formulary does not include buprenorphine. In addition, the formulary and standard CDTMA protocol only list the following “disease states” as potentially coverable by a CPA: anticoagulation, asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, chronic heart failure, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, hypertension, osteoporosis, point-of-care testing, and smoking cessation.\nCDTMA parties can submit protocols/formularies deviating from the standard CDTMA protocol/formulary to the Joint Committee for approval. The Joint Committee can approve or reject such requests in whole or in part. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(14)(c) (2024).", "5B": null, "5C": "Expressly specify in Alabama laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CDTMA include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below. However, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nAlabama regulation provides that a pharmacist can “perfom[] testing or screening for and treatment of acute, uncomplicated illness or injury conditions.” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(4)(a)(3)(ii) (2024).\nWithin the definition of “acute, uncomplicated illness or injury,” Alabama regulation notes that a pharmacist can use “any” CLIA-waived tests. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(1)(q) (2024).\nThe list of tests that a pharmacist can order and evaluate is in the standard CDTMA protocol developed by BME/BOP. This list may not include all types of tests desired for a patient initiated or maintained on buprenorphine.\nCDTMA parties can submit protocols deviating from the standard CDTMA protocol to the Joint Committee for approval. The Joint Committee can approve or reject such requests in whole or in part. ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44(14)(c) (2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CDTMA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Revise Alabama laws and/or regulations to expressly allow Alabama pharmacists to order and evaluate the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine under a CDTMA.", "7": "A state licensed pharmacist and a physician licensed by the Alabama Medical Licensure Commission may enter into a CDTMA. ALA. CODE § 34-23-77(a) (West 2024).\nThe following Alabama laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CDTMAs and required elements of CDTMAs – ALA. CODE § 34-23-77 (West 2024); ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 680-X-2-.44 (2024).", "8A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAlabama does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. Alabama also does not have a Medicaid or other health insurance law addressing telemedicine/telehealth.\nAlabama laws/regulations reference telehealth/telemedicine only with respect to physicians (and other practitioners of healing arts), optometrists, nurses, and several professions in which Alabama is a part of interstate compacts (audiologists/speech pathologists, counselors, social workers, dieticians, and occupational therapists).\nAlabama pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address telehealth, telemedicine, or telepharmacy.", "8B": "Expressly provide in Alabama laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment under a CDTMA.", "8C": "Although a physician can issue a controlled substance prescription as a result of providing telehealth medical services, the prescriber must have “had at least one in-person encounter with the patient within the preceding 12 months.” ALA. CODE § 34-24-704(b)(1) (West 2024).\nAlabama laws governing telehealth provided by physicians, including what it means and how/when a telehealth provider can provide telehealth, are here – ALA. CODE §§ 34-24-700 to 34-24-707 (West 2024).", "9A": "“Medicaid may reimburse for professional services provided by licensed pharmacists” which “may include vaccine administration, medication maintenance therapy adherence and other clinical services as designated by the [Alabama Medicaid] Agency.” ALA. ADMIN. CODE R. 560-X-16-.06(6) (2024).", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Alabama Medicaid program.\nExpressly specify in Alabama laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CDTMA are covered under the Alabama Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://alabama.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Alabama's online PDMP portal (AL PDMP AWARxE) for practitioners and pharmacists to query controlled substance dispensing records."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Homepage", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pdmp/", "description": "Alabama Department of Public Health PDMP homepage with program information, goals, and links to resources. The PDMP is part of the ADPH Pharmacy Division."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pdmp/registration.html", "description": "Registration page for pharmacists, prescribers, and other authorized users to obtain access to the Alabama controlled substance database. Includes links to user manuals and training guides."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Prescribers are required to enroll in and check the PDMP. Pharmacists (dispensers) are required to report daily dispensing of Schedule II-V controlled substances to the database. Alabama participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://alabama.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Delegates can be registered through the AL PDMP AWARxE system. Prescribers and dispensers can designate authorized delegates to query the PDMP on their behalf. See the Requestor User Support Manual linked from the registration page."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://albop.com/", "description": "Alabama State Board of Pharmacy homepage. Provides licensing information, permit applications, news, and links to statutes and rules. Please verify this link before publishing (Cloudflare protection may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://albop.com/statutes-rules/", "description": "Alabama Practice of Pharmacy Act (Act 205) and Alabama Administrative Code Chapter 680 governing pharmacy practice. Full text of statutes and current/proposed rule changes available here. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://admincode.legislature.state.al.us/api/chapter/680-X-2", "description": "Alabama Administrative Code Chapter 680-X-2, containing the Board of Pharmacy's administrative rules for pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statutes", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/alabama/title-34/chapter-23/article-3/section-34-23-77/", "description": "Alabama Code Section 34-23-77, the Collaborative Practice Agreement statute authorizing eligible pharmacists and physicians to enter collaborative practice agreements for joint patient care plans."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Rules and Application", "url": "https://www.albme.gov/licensing/md-do/registrations/collaborative-pharmacy-practice/", "description": "Alabama Board of Medical Examiners page on collaborative pharmacy practice, including qualifications, application process, fees, and links to collaborative practice rules (540-X-26). Applications are submitted through the Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Administrative Code", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/alabama/Ala-Admin-Code-r-680-X-2-.44", "description": "Alabama Administrative Code Rule 680-X-2-.44 governing collaborative practice between pharmacists and physicians."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Alabama does not have independent pharmacist prescribing authority. Pharmacists may provide patient care services under a collaborative practice agreement with a physician."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator (Alabama)", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator (FindTreatment.gov) to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Alabama, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/locators/opioid-treatment-program-directory", "description": "SAMHSA directory of certified opioid treatment programs. Can be filtered to find OTPs in Alabama that provide methadone, buprenorphine, and naltrexone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Substance Use Treatment Services", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/division-of-mental-health-substance-abuse-services/substance-abuse-treatment-services/", "description": "Alabama Department of Mental Health page on substance use treatment services, including medication-assisted treatment (MAT) and opioid treatment programs (OTPs). There are 21 certified OTP programs in Alabama."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Nicole Walden, Alabama Department of Mental Health, 100 N. Union St, Montgomery, AL 36130. Phone: (334) 353-7287. Email: nicole.walden@mh.alabama.gov", "description": "Alabama's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority contact as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA SOTA Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA's full directory of State Opioid Treatment Authorities by state."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), healthcare providers are no longer required to hold an X-waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of DEA registration or renewal. Alabama does not impose additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine: Alabama follows the DEA's federal telehealth regulations for prescribing buprenorphine. The Alabama Board of Medical Examiners has telehealth guidelines that apply broadly to medical practice, including prescribing controlled substances via telehealth."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama OUD Resources (ADMH)", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/understanding-the-opioid-crisis/", "description": "Alabama Department of Mental Health page on opioid use disorder prevention, treatment, and recovery, with links to resources, the Opioid Council, and data."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://medicaid.alabama.gov/content/4.0_Programs/4.3_Pharmacy-DME.aspx", "description": "Alabama Medicaid Agency's Pharmacy and DME services page, including billing information, policy updates, provider manuals, and links to the buprenorphine primer for prescribers and pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://medicaid.alabama.gov/content/4.0_programs/4.3_Pharmacy-DME/4.3.7_Preferred_Drug_List.aspx", "description": "Alabama Medicaid preferred drug list (PDL), updated quarterly. Generic buprenorphine products are generally covered. Brand Suboxone has moved to non-preferred status with enhanced prior authorization for buprenorphine-experienced patients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prior Authorization Information", "url": "https://medicaid.alabama.gov/alert_detail.aspx?ID=16580", "description": "Alabama Medicaid alert regarding buprenorphine prior authorization requirements, including automatic processing for buprenorphine-experienced recipients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Medicaid Fee Schedules", "url": "https://medicaid.alabama.gov/content/Gated/7.3G_Fee_Schedules.aspx", "description": "Alabama Medicaid fee schedule page. Access may require provider login. Includes fee schedules for various service types."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Primer for Prescribers and Pharmacists", "url": "https://medicaid.alabama.gov/documents/4.0_Programs/4.3_Pharmacy-DME/4.3_Buprenorphine_A_Primer_for_Prescribers_and_Pharmacists_3-28-16.pdf", "description": "CMS guide on buprenorphine for prescribers and pharmacists, hosted on the Alabama Medicaid site."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State-Specific Pharmacist Billing Codes: Alabama Medicaid does not currently have a comprehensive set of billing codes specific to pharmacist-provided clinical services beyond dispensing. Pharmacist services under collaborative practice agreements may be billable under applicable medical codes. Contact Alabama Medicaid Pharmacy Division for specific guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Alabama receives State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA and has received opioid settlement funds. The Alabama Department of Mental Health administers these funds. Contact ADMH for current grant opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alabama CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.aparx.org/page/63/Alabama-State-Board-Continuing-Education-Requirements.htm", "description": "Alabama Pharmacy Association page on state CE requirements. All pharmacists must complete 15 hours of approved continuing education each year (30 hours per biennial renewal cycle), with 3 hours being live CE each year."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy CE Information", "url": "https://albop.com/continuing-education/", "description": "Alabama Board of Pharmacy continuing education page with requirements for pharmacists and technicians. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADPH Pharmacy Division CE Events", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pharmacy/continuing-education.html", "description": "Alabama Department of Public Health Pharmacy Division continuing education page, including training on controlled substance laws and regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://www.aparx.org/page/OnDemand", "description": "Alabama Pharmacy Association on-demand continuing education resources for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD provides free training on medications for opioid use disorder, including 8-hour DEA training options that meet MATE Act requirements. Funded by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS 8-Hour MOUD Training Options", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/medications-for-opioid-use-disorder/8-hour-moud-education-options/", "description": "PCSS page listing multiple training options that meet the DEA 8-hour education requirement for prescribing buprenorphine and other controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division website for DEA registration, practitioner resources, and controlled substance regulations."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Alabama does not have state-specific board-approved SUD or buprenorphine training programs beyond federal MATE Act requirements. ACPE-accredited programs are accepted."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Syringe services programs (needle exchange) are not permitted under Alabama state law. Individuals cannot purchase syringes without a prescription in Alabama."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro Alabama Resources", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/alabama", "description": "NEXT Distro page for Alabama providing harm reduction information, naloxone access options, and Good Samaritan law details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/faq/standing-order-for-naloxone/", "description": "Alabama Department of Mental Health page on the Standing Order for Naloxone. HB208 (2015) provided immunity for prescribing and administering naloxone. HB379 (2016) authorized the State Health Officer to issue standing orders for naloxone dispensing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADPH Naloxone Dispensing Page", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pharmacy/opioid-reversal.html", "description": "Alabama Department of Public Health page on naloxone and other opioid overdose reversal agents, including the current standing order, training resources, and availability information. Naloxone kits are available free at Elmore County and Montgomery County Health Departments."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADPH Overdose Resources", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pharmacy/overdose-resources.html", "description": "ADPH page with overdose resources including naloxone information, safe medication disposal, recovery organization contacts, and crisis numbers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Not One More Alabama (Naloxone and Good Samaritan Law)", "url": "https://www.notonemorealabama.org/narcan--good-samaritan-law.html", "description": "Community organization providing naloxone and information about Alabama's Good Samaritan Law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: In June 2022, Alabama legalized fentanyl test strips (SB-168), removing them from the list of banned drug paraphernalia. Fentanyl test strips are distributed through programs funded by ADMH."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://druguse.alabama.gov/", "description": "Alabama Drug Use Central Data Repository (CDR) providing interactive dashboards on drug use outcomes including opioid-related deaths, treatment data, and more."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Certified Recovery Support Specialist Training", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/certified-recovery-support-specialist-training-program/", "description": "Alabama Department of Mental Health program for training and certifying recovery support specialists. Requires 2 years of continuous recovery, 40 hours of ADMH-approved training, and passing an exam."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Programs (ADMH)", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/division-of-mental-health-substance-abuse-services/peer-programs/", "description": "ADMH peer programs page for certified peer specialist training in mental health and substance use provider settings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Council on Substance Abuse (COSA-NCADD)", "url": "https://cosancadd.org/training/certified-recovery-support-specialist-training/", "description": "Council on Substance Abuse-NCADD in Alabama offering peer recovery support services and certified recovery support specialist training."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing Directory: Alabama does not maintain a centralized state-operated recovery housing directory. The National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) directory at https://narronline.org/ can be used to search for certified recovery residences in Alabama."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/", "description": "Alabama Department of Mental Health homepage, the state behavioral health authority serving citizens with mental illnesses, developmental disabilities, and substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Division of Mental Health and Substance Use Services", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/division-of-mental-health-substance-abuse-services/", "description": "ADMH Division overseeing community-based services for serious mental illness and substance use disorders, including contracting, monitoring, and certifying service programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Alabama's 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is available 24/7. ADMH Recovery Organization of Support Specialists (ROSS) 24/7 Helpline provides peer support for substance use issues. Contact ADPH crisis numbers at https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/suicide/crisis-numbers.html"}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://albop.com/", "description": "Alabama State Board of Pharmacy. Phone: (205) 981-2280. Address: 111 Village Street, Birmingham, AL 35242. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Medicaid Agency Pharmacy Division", "url": "https://medicaid.alabama.gov/content/4.0_Programs/4.3_Pharmacy-DME.aspx", "description": "Alabama Medicaid pharmacy services page with contact information and pharmacy links."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Nicole Walden, Alabama Department of Mental Health, 100 N. Union St, Montgomery, AL 36130. Phone: (334) 353-7287. Email: nicole.walden@mh.alabama.gov"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.aparx.org/", "description": "Alabama Pharmacy Association (APA). Contact page at https://www.aparx.org/page/A1"}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Health Department OUD Program", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pdmp/", "description": "ADPH Pharmacy Division manages the PDMP and opioid-related public health programs. Phone: (334) 290-6707."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Drug Use Central Data Repository", "url": "https://druguse.alabama.gov/", "description": "Statewide central data repository for opioid and drug use data, established by the Governor's Opioid Overdose and Addiction Council. Includes interactive dashboards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid-Related Deaths Dashboard", "url": "https://druguse.alabama.gov/opioidrelateddeaths.html", "description": "Interactive dashboard showing Alabama opioid-related overdose death data from CDC Wonder, including trends and county-level data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADPH Overdose Surveillance Summary", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pharmacy/assets/overdosesurveillancedatasummary.pdf", "description": "Alabama Department of Public Health overdose surveillance data summary report, funded through CDC Overdose Data to Action (OD2A) grant."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Opioid Overdose and Addiction Council Reports", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/faq/alabama-opioid-overdose-and-addiction-council/", "description": "ADMH page with annual reports from the Alabama Opioid Overdose and Addiction Council, including data on overdose trends, treatment utilization, and recommendations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "2024 Annual Report", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/2024-Alabama-Opioid-Overdose-and-Addiction-Council-Annual-Report.pdf", "description": "Most recent annual report from the Alabama Opioid Overdose and Addiction Council with comprehensive state opioid data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "2025 Council Report", "url": "https://www.alabamapublichealth.gov/pharmacy/assets/council-report-2025.pdf", "description": "2025 annual report showing updated opioid prevalence data, including an 8% decrease in fentanyl cases compared to 2024."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Opioid Overdose and Addiction Council", "url": "https://mh.alabama.gov/faq/alabama-opioid-overdose-and-addiction-council/", "description": "The state's primary opioid task force, established by Executive Order 708. Composed of members from state agencies, healthcare, law enforcement, and community organizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.aparx.org/", "description": "APA advocacy resources. The association provides legislative updates and advocacy tools for Alabama pharmacists. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alabama Legislature", "url": "https://www.legislature.state.al.us/", "description": "Alabama State Legislature website for tracking current legislation related to pharmacy practice and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Your Alabama Legislator", "url": "https://www.legislature.state.al.us/aliswww/ISD/ALRepresentatives.aspx", "description": "Find and contact your Alabama state representative."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Your Alabama Senator", "url": "https://www.legislature.state.al.us/aliswww/ISD/ALSenators.aspx", "description": "Find and contact your Alabama state senator."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Pharmacy Practice Policy Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy templates for state-level pharmacy practice issues. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Recent Legislation: SB-168 (2022) legalized fentanyl test strips. HB208 (2015) and HB379 (2016) established naloxone access and standing order authority. Alabama Code Section 34-23-77 authorizes collaborative practice agreements."}]}]}, "alaska": {"name": "Alaska", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Alaska’s term for a CPA is a “protocol” for “collaborative practice authority.” ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240 (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alaska law includes “the independent prescribing, dispensing, and administration of drugs in accordance with [§] 08.80.168.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.480(30) (West 2024). Such authority only extends to overdose reversal agents and vaccines, however. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.168 (West 2024).\nPharmacists are allowed to provide “patient care services” independent of a collaborative practice protocol for “general health and wellness,” disease prevention, and certain “minor” conditions. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(b) (West 2024). However, such authority “does not authorize a pharmacist to prescribe a prescription drug that the pharmacist is not otherwise authorized to prescribe.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(c) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Alaska cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Alaska practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Alaska pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Alaska laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alaska law includes “drug administration.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.480(30) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition further specifies that it includes “the independent prescribing, dispensing, and administration of drugs in accordance with [§] 08.80.168.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.480(30)\n(West 2024). Such authority only extends to overdose reversal agents and vaccines, however. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.168 (West 2024).\nAnother Alaska law expressly provides that “a pharmacist may prescribe, dispense, and administer nonprescription drugs or devices.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.045(c) (West 2024).\nMoreover, while there is an Alaska regulation expressly covering the administration of “vaccines, epinephrine, and related emergency medications,” including training necessary to do it, there are no provisions expressly addressing administration of any other kinds of drugs, including controlled substances. ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.992 (2024).\nIn summary, if the general “drug administration” language in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in Alaska may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Alaska practice of pharmacy to include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Alaska laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, based on the information described below, even if it is allowed, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Alaska law does not expressly provide for ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.480(30) (West 2024).\nHowever, Alaska law provides that “a pharmacist may independently provide patient care services” for “general health and wellness,” disease prevention, and certain minor conditions outside of a collaborative practice protocol. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(b) (West 2024).\nIncluded among the allowable conditions are conditions that are: (1) “minor and generally self-limiting”; (2) have a test used to guide diagnosis or clinical decision-making that is a CLIA-waived test; or (3) fall under a standing order from the state department of health. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(b) (West 2024). It is unclear if this provision authorizes the pharmacist to perform the CLIA-waived test, however.\nPatient care services are “medical care services given in exchange for compensation intended to achieve outcomes related to the cure or prevention of a disease, elimination or reduction of a patient’s symptoms, or arresting or slowing of a disease process.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(d) (West 2024). It is possible that ordering lab tests and evaluating the results could be considered a patient care service.\nIn summary, Alaska law is unclear if a pharmacist can order lab tests or evaluate the results outside of a collaborative practice protocol. Even if allowed, however, it appears limited only to CLIA-waived tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Alaska to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nCollaborative practice protocols allow for “initiating or modifying drug therapy” by a pharmacist. ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(a) (2024). Although the provision uses the phrase “initiating or modifying,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nHowever, the written protocol must include “an agreement in which practitioners authorized to prescribe legend drugs in this state authorize pharmacists . . . to administer or dispense in accordance with that written protocol.” ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(b)(1) (2024). This statement appears to limit pharmacists to only administering or dispensing drugs under a protocol.\nMoreover, Alaska regulations governing protocols do not account for the fact that a pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol directs.\nIn summary, Alaska regulation does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing drugs under a protocol. Even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, however, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Alaska pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Alaska laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under protocols for collaborative practice authority.\nExpressly specify in Alaska laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under such protocols.\nAllow Alaska pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nA written collaborative protocol must include “an agreement in which practitioners authorized to prescribe legend drugs in this state authorize pharmacists licensed in this state to administer or dispense in accordance with that written protocol.” ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(b)(1) (2024). This provision does not limit the drugs for which a pharmacist can administer.\nPrior to January 2024, this regulation prohibited protocols from allowing the administration or dispensing of any schedule I-IV controlled substance. ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(b)(9) (2024). Regulators repealed this restriction on January 19, 2024.", "5B": "Enter into a collaborative protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Alaska laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, based on the information described below, even if it is allowed, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nCollaborative practice protocols allow for “initiating or modifying drug therapy” by a pharmacist. ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(a) (2024). ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(a) (2024). This provision does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating tests when describing the process for initiating or modifying drug therapy.\nHowever, a separate law provides that a pharmacist may “provide patient care services” under a protocol with a written protocol approved by a practitioner. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(a) (West 2024). Patient care services are “medical care services given in exchange for compensation intended to achieve outcomes related to the cure or prevention of a disease, elimination or reduction of a patient’s symptoms, or arresting or slowing of a disease process.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337(d) (West 2024). It is possible, but not expressly clear, that ordering lab tests and evaluating the results could be considered a patient care service.\nIn addition, as described in the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, although it is unclear, Alaska pharmacists may have some authority to perform CLIA-waived tests outside of a collaborative protocol, with such authority possibly applying under such protocol.\nIn summary, Alaska law is unclear if a pharmacist can order lab tests and evaluate the results as part of a collaborative protocol. Even if allowed, however, it may be limited only to CLIA-waived tests.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Alaska laws and/or regulations that under a collaborative protocol, pharmacists can order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A collaborative protocol is an agreement between “practitioners authorized to prescribe legend drugs” in Alaska and licensed pharmacists. ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(a) (2024).\nThe protocol regulation “does not apply to participation, by a pharmacist practicing in an institutional facility in drug therapy protocols and guidelines approved by the institutional facility’s pharmacy and therapeutics committee or by another medical staff governing body of that institutional facility, if records related to the drug therapy protocols and guidelines are maintained and made available to the board upon request.” ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 52.240(h) (2024). \nThe following Alaska laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering protocols and required elements of protocols – ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.80.337 (West 2024); ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, §§ 40.983, 52.240 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below. Note, however, that there are limitations related to controlled substances (see the telehealth provisions related to buprenorphine section).\nAlaska has a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law that provides that a “health care provider licensed in this state may provide health care services within the health care provider’s authorized scope of practice to a patient in this state through telehealth without first conducting an in-person visit.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.02.130(a) (West 2024).\n“Health care provider” includes a licensed pharmacist. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.02.130(j)(1)(A) (West 2024).", "8B": "Expressly specify in Alaska laws and/or regulations that the health care services pharmacists can provide via telehealth include services involving controlled substances.", "8C": "All businesses engaged in or planning to engage in telemedicine to a patient located in Alaska must register with the Alaska Telemedicine Business Registry. ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 44.33.381 (West 2024).\nThe general rule is that a health care provider “may not prescribe, dispense, or administer through telehealth under this section a controlled substance.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.02.130(g) (West 2024). There are a few exceptions to this rule, but pharmacists are not among the exceptions.\nThe exceptions are: (1) physicians, physician assistants, and APRNs (if certain statutory conditions are met); and (2) dentists/optometrists (but only after an in-person exam).\nDuring “a public health emergency declared by the governor or commissioner of health and social services,” a health care provider does not need to present with the patient to assist a physician or physician assistant with examination, diagnosis, and treatment if the physician or physician assistant is “prescribing, dispensing, or administering buprenorphine to initiate or continue treatment for opioid use disorder” and the physician or physician assistant: (1) “is a waived practitioner under 21 U.S.C. 823(g)(2) (Drug Addiction Treatment Act (DATA))”; (2) documents all attempts to conduct a physical examination, the reason why the examination cannot be performed, and the reason why another health care provider cannot be present with the patient; and (3) “requires urine or oral toxicology screening as part of the patient’s medication adherence plan.” ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 40.943(b) (2024).\nAlaska laws and regulations governing telehealth include – – ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.02.130 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 21.42.422 (West 2024) (insurance); ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 44.33.381 (West 2024)\n(business registry); ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 47.07.069 (West 2024) (Medicaid); ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 7, §§ 110.620 to 110.639, 145.270 (2024) (Medicaid); (2024); ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, §§ 02.106, 02.600 (2024) (business registry); ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 40.943 (2024) (physicians).57", "9A": "Alaska’s Medicaid program regulations provide that a pharmacist is one of the provider types “eligible to enroll with the department [Alaska Department of Health] and bill directly for services rendered.” ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 7, § 105.200(a)(1)(F) (2024). However, researchers who examined Medicaid coverage for pharmacist services note that “depending on the service provided and the setting of care, it may require the pharmacist to have an established collaborative practice agreement in place.”", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "State medical board regulations about delegation of duties must include a requirement that “a physician, podiatrist, osteopath, or physician assistant may not delegate duties related to pain management and opioid use and addiction.” ALASKA STAT. ANN. § 08.64.106(2) (West 2024).\nAccordingly, Alaska regulations prohibit such delegation. ALASKA ADMIN. CODE tit. 12, § 40.920(f)(5) (2004)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://alaska.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Alaska's online PDMP portal (AWARxE platform) for practitioners and pharmacists to query controlled substance dispensing records for Schedule II-IV substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Homepage", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/ProfessionalLicensing/PrescriptionDrugMonitoringProgram.aspx", "description": "Alaska PDMP homepage administered by the Board of Pharmacy through the Division of Corporations, Business and Professional Licensing. Includes registration information, contact details, and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration Instructions", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/ProfessionalLicensing/PrescriptionDrugMonitoringProgram/RegistrationInstructionsForms.aspx", "description": "Registration instructions and forms for practitioners and pharmacists to enroll in the Alaska PDMP."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Registration with the Alaska PDMP is mandatory for actively licensed practitioners who hold a DEA registration valid in any state and pharmacists who dispense Schedule II-IV controlled substances. Prescribers must review a patient's prescription history prior to prescribing Schedule II-III controlled substances. Prescriptions for Schedule II, III, and IV controlled substances must be reported daily."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Alaska participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate PDMP data sharing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the AWARxE system. Prescribers and pharmacists can designate authorized delegates to query the PDMP on their behalf."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Use and Exemptions", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/ProfessionalLicensing/PrescriptionDrugMonitoringProgram/UseExemptions.aspx", "description": "Information on PDMP query requirements and exemptions for specific circumstances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Notification FAQs", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/ProfessionalLicensing/PrescriptionDrugMonitoringProgram/PDMPNotificationFAQs.aspx", "description": "Frequently asked questions about PDMP notifications and requirements. Alaska monitors only federally scheduled II-IV controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/professionallicensing/boardofpharmacy.aspx", "description": "Alaska Board of Pharmacy homepage. The board consists of five pharmacists, one pharmacy technician, and one public member. Makes licensing decisions and adopts regulations under AS 08 and 12 AAC 52."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Statutes)", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/portals/5/pub/PharmacyStatutes.pdf", "description": "Full text of Alaska pharmacy statutes and regulations (AS 08.80 and 12 AAC 52) governing pharmacy practice, updated April 2025."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statutes and Regulations Page", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/ProfessionalLicensing/BoardofPharmacy/StatutesRegulations.aspx", "description": "Alaska Board of Pharmacy page linking to statutes (AS 08.80) and regulations (12 AAC 52) that govern pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice Agreements: Under AS 08.80.337, a pharmacist may provide patient care services under a collaborative practice agreement with a written protocol approved by a practitioner. However, the statute explicitly prohibits a CPA from giving a pharmacist authority to prescribe a controlled substance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Alaska allows pharmacist prescribing for certain items (e.g., naloxone under standing orders). HB 112 (introduced in the 33rd Legislature) proposed updates to pharmacy practice statutes including collaborative practice provisions."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's FindTreatment.gov to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Alaska, including buprenorphine providers and opioid treatment programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/locators/opioid-treatment-program-directory", "description": "SAMHSA directory of certified opioid treatment programs, filterable to Alaska."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Provider Resources for OUD", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/education/drugs-and-alcohol/opioids-prevention-and-recovery/provider-resources/", "description": "Alaska Department of Health provider resources page including OUD treatment guidance, prescribing guidelines, training resources, UW TelePain, and the UW Medicine Pain and Opioid Consult Hotline (1-844-520-PAIN)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska SUD Treatment FAQs", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/education/sud-treatment-faqs/", "description": "Alaska Department of Health page explaining substance use disorder treatment steps and frequently asked questions, including information on MAT with buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Elana Habib, 3601 C Street, Ste. 878, Anchorage, AK 99503. Phone: (907) 269-3600. Email: elana.habib@alaska.gov", "description": "Alaska's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority contact as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Alaska follows federal MATE Act requirements. The X-waiver is no longer required. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders for DEA registration or renewal. No additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations: Alaska has broad telehealth authority. The Alaska State Medical Board has issued guidelines regarding prescribing controlled substances. Alaska allows telehealth for buprenorphine prescribing consistent with federal DEA rules."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Medicaid Pharmacy Information", "url": "https://manuals.medicaidalaska.com/docs/pharmacy.htm", "description": "Alaska Medicaid pharmacy provider manual and drug lookup tools through the Health Enterprise Portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/education/pdl-preferred-drug-list/", "description": "Alaska Medicaid PDL page. The Pharmacy and Therapeutics Committee determines preferred drugs. Non-preferred drugs require prescriber documentation of medical necessity."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Medicaid P&T Committee", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/division-of-health-care-services/medicaid-pharmacy-and-therapeutics/", "description": "Alaska Medicaid Pharmacy and Therapeutics Committee page with meeting information and drug class review updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Medicaid Prescription Drug Coverage", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/services/division-of-public-assistance-dpa-services/apply-for-medicaid/medicaid-prescription-drug-coverage/", "description": "General information about Alaska Medicaid prescription drug coverage including the PDL program."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Services Billing: Alaska Medicaid does not currently have comprehensive billing codes specifically for pharmacist-provided clinical services beyond dispensing. Pharmacist services may be billable under collaborative practice agreements using applicable medical codes. Contact Alaska Medicaid for specific guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Alaska receives State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA. The Alaska Mental Health Trust Authority also funds opioid-related initiatives. Contact the Division of Behavioral Health for current grant opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Alaska CE Requirements: Alaska pharmacists must complete 30 hours of continuing education per biennial renewal cycle. Check the Board of Pharmacy regulations (12 AAC 52) for specific CE requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy CE Page", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/professionallicensing/boardofpharmacy.aspx", "description": "Alaska Board of Pharmacy homepage with links to CE requirements and renewal information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://alaskapharmacy.org/", "description": "Alaska Pharmacy Association, dedicated to empowering and engaging the pharmacy profession to elevate the health of Alaskans. Offers educational resources and advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System offering free training on medications for opioid use disorder, including 8-hour DEA training options."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS 8-Hour MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/medications-for-opioid-use-disorder/8-hour-moud-education-options/", "description": "PCSS training options meeting the MATE Act 8-hour education requirement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division for DEA registration and controlled substance regulations."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Alaska allows syringe services programs. I Know Mine (Alaska Native Tribal Health Consortium) provides mail-based harm reduction supplies including syringes, fentanyl test strips, and naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "I Know Mine Harm Reduction Supplies", "url": "https://www.iknowmine.org/shop/", "description": "Mail-based harm reduction supply access through the Alaska Native Tribal Health Consortium, including syringes, fentanyl test strips, condoms, and HIV/STI self-test kits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Project HOPE Naloxone Distribution", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/services/project-hope-get-naloxone/", "description": "Alaska Department of Health Project HOPE program providing free naloxone to Alaskans through a medical standing order under AS 17.20.085. Approved Overdose Response Programs distribute naloxone kits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Map", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/education/drugs-and-alcohol/opioids-prevention-and-recovery/find-naloxone/", "description": "Map of Alaska sites providing free Narcan nasal spray through Project HOPE participation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro Alaska", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/alaska", "description": "NEXT Distro Alaska page with naloxone access information, harm reduction resources, Good Samaritan law details, and crisis hotline contacts."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Alaska Good Samaritan Law: Alaska has a limited Good Samaritan law protecting people seeking help during an overdose from prosecution for controlled substances, but does not protect against probation/parole violations or drug paraphernalia charges."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: Fentanyl test strips are available in Alaska through harm reduction programs such as I Know Mine. They are not classified as drug paraphernalia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Opioid Task Force", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/AKOpioidTaskForce/Pages/default.aspx", "description": "Alaska Opioid Policy Task Force addressing opioid abuse, including harm reduction practices, naloxone access, and syringe services."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Peer Support Certification", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/en/services/alaska-peer-support-certification/", "description": "Alaska Department of Health page on peer support certification, including training options and certification requirements through the Alaska Commission for Behavioral Health Certification."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Commission for Behavioral Health Certification", "url": "https://akcertification.org/", "description": "Organization managing peer support specialist and behavioral health certification in Alaska."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Behavioral Health Peer Support Training", "url": "https://alaskabehavioralhealth.org/trainings/peer-support-training/", "description": "Alaska Behavioral Health page on peer specialist training, including information sessions on the path to state certification."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Alaska does not maintain a centralized state recovery housing directory. Use the National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) at https://narronline.org/ or contact the Alaska Division of Behavioral Health for local recovery housing resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/", "description": "Alaska Department of Health homepage. The Division of Behavioral Health oversees substance use disorder services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (call or text 988). Alaska crisis hotlines are listed at the Department of Health. Careline Alaska: 1-877-266-4357."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/cbpl/professionallicensing/boardofpharmacy.aspx", "description": "Alaska Board of Pharmacy. Phone: (907) 465-2550. Email: BoardOfPharmacy@Alaska.Gov"}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Elana Habib, 3601 C Street, Ste. 878, Anchorage, AK 99503. Phone: (907) 269-3600. Email: elana.habib@alaska.gov"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://alaskapharmacy.org/", "description": "Alaska Pharmacy Association for professional development, education, and advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Department of Health", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/", "description": "Alaska Department of Health, overseeing public health programs including substance use disorder initiatives."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Alaska PDMP Contact: Phone: (907) 269-8163 (for medical/PA inquiries) or email BoardOfPharmacy@Alaska.Gov for pharmacy PDMP registration questions."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Opioid Data Dashboard", "url": "https://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Director/Pages/opioids/dashboard.aspx", "description": "Alaska opioid data dashboard with summary statistics, emergency department visits, overdose deaths, naloxone statistics, PDMP data, and neonatal abstinence syndrome data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Opioid Task Force Data", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/AKOpioidTaskForce/Pages/data.aspx", "description": "Alaska Opioid Policy Task Force data page with resources on opioid crisis extent both nationwide and in Alaska."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Nonfatal Overdose Bulletin", "url": "https://epi.alaska.gov/bulletins/docs/b2025_05.pdf", "description": "Alaska Epidemiology Bulletin on nonfatal opioid overdose rates by region and quarter."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Alaska Substance Use Dashboard: Available through Project HOPE page at https://health.alaska.gov/en/services/project-hope-get-naloxone/", "description": "Interactive substance use dashboard accessible from the Alaska Department of Health."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Reports and Data", "url": "https://www.commerce.alaska.gov/web/Portals/5/pub/PDMP_PHAreport_2023_Q1.pdf", "description": "Alaska PDMP quarterly report with prescribing data and trends (example: Q1 2023)."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Opioid Policy Task Force", "url": "https://health.alaska.gov/AKOpioidTaskForce/Pages/default.aspx", "description": "Multi-agency task force addressing the opioid epidemic in Alaska, covering prescribing practices, harm reduction, treatment access, and Medicaid roles."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://alaskapharmacy.org/", "description": "Alaska Pharmacy Association advocacy and legislative resources for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alaska State Legislature Bill Search", "url": "https://www.akleg.gov/", "description": "Alaska State Legislature website for tracking current legislation, including bills related to pharmacy practice and OUD treatment. HB 112 (pharmacy practice updates) and HB 145 (pharmacy practice act modernization) are notable recent bills."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Your Alaska Legislator", "url": "https://www.akleg.gov/prior.php", "description": "Alaska Legislature website with links to find and contact your state representatives and senators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy resources. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Recent Legislation: HB 112 and HB 145 proposed updates to the Alaska Pharmacy Practice Act, including collaborative practice agreement provisions. Alaska's Good Samaritan law (AS 11.71.311) provides limited overdose immunity."}]}]}, "arizona": {"name": "Arizona", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arizona law provides a detailed list of “health care services” that a pharmacist can furnish. This list does not expressly include prescribing. In terms of “initiating” drugs, the definition expressly provides only for pharmacists initiating immunizations and vaccines. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1901(79) (West 2024).\nMoreover, within Arizona’s pharmacy laws, pharmacists are not expressly listed in the definition of a “medical practitioner,” which is defined as “a medical doctor, doctor of osteopathic medicine, dentist, podiatrist, veterinarian or other person who is licensed and authorized by law to use and prescribe drugs and devices to treat sick and injured human beings or animals.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1901(56) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Arizona cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Arizona practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Arizona pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Arizona laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arizona law includes “participating in . . . drug administration.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1901(79)(a)(iv) (West 2024).\nThis provision does not limit the drugs for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition further specifies that it includes “initiating and administering immunizations or vaccines pursuant to section 32-1974.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1901(79)(a)(x) (West 2024).\nThe referenced section covers the administration of “immunizations, vaccines, and emergency medications.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1974 (West 2024).\nIf the general “participation in . . . drug administration” in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in Arizona may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Arizona practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arizona law provides a detailed list of “health care services” that a pharmacist can furnish. This list contains no express mention of ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1901(79) (West 2024).\nMoreover, Arizona pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests by pharmacists outside of CPAs.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Arizona to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nArizona law provides that a CPA is an agreement that outlines drug therapy management which includes a pharmacist “initiating, monitoring and modifying prescription drug and laboratory test orders that are authorized by the provider.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970(G)(1) (West 2024).\nThe law further provides that “initiate, monitor and modify does not include a pharmacist’s selection of drug products that are not prescribed by the provider unless the selection of specific drug products is authorized” by the CPA. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970(G)(2) (West 2024). This suggests, although not clearly, that pharmacist prescribing may be allowed under a CPA, at least in general.\nHowever, Arizona law does not expressly specify whether the pharmacist’s prescriptive authority (if any) under a CPA includes controlled substances.\nMoreover, Arizona law governing CPAs does not account for the fact that a pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPA directs.\nIn summary, Arizona law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing drugs under a CPA. Even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, however, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Arizona pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Arizona laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPAs.\nExpressly specify in Arizona laws and regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under such protocols.\nAllow Arizona pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Arizona laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nArizona law provides that a CPA is an agreement that outlines drug therapy management which includes a pharmacist “initiating, monitoring and modifying prescription drug . . . orders that are authorized by the provider.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970(G)(1) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiating, monitoring and modifying,” there is no express reference to “administering” drugs. It is possible that the phrase encompasses the act of administering.\nHowever, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arizona law also specifies that it includes “initiating and administering immunizations or vaccines pursuant to section 32-1974.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1901(79)(a)(x) (West 2024). If “initiating” includes “administering,” then the Arizona legislature would not need to include the word “administering” in this provision unless the scope of activities covered by initiating an immunization does not encompass administering it. This calls into question whether the phrase “initiating, monitoring, and modifying” in the CPA provision includes the act of administering buprenorphine.", "5B": null, "5C": "Expressly specify in Arizona laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CPA include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests.\nArizona law provides that a CPA must specify that the pharmacist must follow written drug therapy and disease management guidelines provided by the provider. These guidelines must specify, among other things, “the laboratory tests the pharmacist may order.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970(A)(3) (West 2024).\nThere is no express mention of evaluating lab tests in the law governing CPAs.", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Revise Arizona laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to evaluate lab tests under a CPA.", "7": "One or more licensed pharmacists may enter into a CPA with one or more licensed “providers.” ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970(A) (West 2024).\nA “provider” is a licensed physician, registered nurse practitioner, licensed nurse midwife, or a licensed physician assistant. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970(G)(3) (West 2024).\nThe following Arizona law provides more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 32-1970 (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nArizona has a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law that provides a “health care provider” may provide telehealth services within their scope of practice. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 36-3601 to 36-3608 (West 2024).\n“Health care provider” includes individuals licensed under more than a dozen chapters within Title 32 of the Arizona statutes. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 36-3601(2)(a) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "Other than schedule II controlled substances, limitations in scope of practice laws, and limitations in practice guidelines adopted by the state telehealth advisory committee, no restriction on prescribing controlled substances in the absence of an in-person exam is enforceable. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 36-3602(E) (West 2024).\nA health care provider not licensed in Arizona must register with Arizona’s “applicable health care provider regulatory board or agency that licenses comparable health care providers in this state” before providing telehealth. ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. § 36-3606(A)(1) (West 2024).\nThere are fees to do this.\nArizona laws and regulations governing telehealth, include – ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 36-3601 to 36-3608 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); ARIZ. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 20-841.09, 20-1057.13, 20-1376.05, 20-1406.05 (West 2024) (insurance); ARIZ. ADMIN. CODE §§ R9-16-1001 to R9-16-1007 (2024) (out of state providers).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Arizona Medicaid program.\nExpressly specify in Arizona laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CPA are covered under the Arizona Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (CSPMP)", "url": "https://pharmacypmp.az.gov/", "description": "Arizona Controlled Substances Prescription Monitoring Program (CSPMP) homepage, administered by the Arizona State Board of Pharmacy. Includes login, registration, resources, and annual reports."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSPMP Login", "url": "https://arizona.pmpaware.net/", "description": "Arizona CSPMP AWARxE portal for practitioners and pharmacists to query controlled substance dispensing records. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSPMP Registration and Resources", "url": "https://pharmacypmp.az.gov/resources", "description": "CSPMP resources page including patient report requests, naloxone dispensing guide, and naloxone standing order link."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Arizona requires mandatory PDMP enrollment for both prescribers and dispensers. Since April 26, 2018 (Arizona Opioid Epidemic Act), dispensing pharmacists must review the PDMP record of a patient receiving a Schedule II controlled substance for the preceding 12 months. Prescribers must check the PDMP before prescribing Schedule II opioids."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Arizona participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the AWARxE system. Prescribers and pharmacists can designate authorized delegates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSPMP Training Videos", "url": "https://youtu.be/OGEsepmVzRQ?si=b0nwXxk3biDBuNX1", "description": "Board of Pharmacy instructional videos on CSPMP registration, patient record lookup, and report interpretation."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://pharmacy.az.gov/", "description": "Arizona State Board of Pharmacy homepage with licensing information, complaints, and regulatory resources. Please verify this link before publishing (Cloudflare protection may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist License Statutes and Rules", "url": "https://pharmacy.az.gov/pharmacists/pharmacist-license-statutes-rules", "description": "Common statutes and rules associated with pharmacist licenses in Arizona. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://www.azleg.gov/viewdocument/?docName=https://www.azleg.gov/ars/32/01901.htm", "description": "Arizona Revised Statutes Title 32, Chapter 18 (Pharmacy) - definition of the practice of pharmacy under ARS 32-1901."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules", "url": "https://apps.azsos.gov/public_services/Title_04/4-23.pdf", "description": "Arizona Administrative Code Title 4, Chapter 23 - Board of Pharmacy administrative rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements", "url": "https://www.azleg.gov/ars/32/01970.htm", "description": "ARS 32-1970 authorizing collaborative practice agreements between pharmacists and providers. Allows pharmacists to initiate, monitor, and modify drug therapy under an agreement."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Arizona allows pharmacist prescribing under collaborative practice agreements (ARS 32-1970). Pharmacists can also prescribe naloxone under the State Health Officer standing order and dispense certain medications including hormonal contraceptives and tobacco cessation products under specific statutes."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS OUD Treatment Locator", "url": "https://opioidservicelocator.azahcccs.gov/", "description": "Arizona Health Care Cost Containment System (AHCCCS/Medicaid) opioid services locator to find OUD treatment providers in Arizona."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS OUD Treatment Information", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Members/BehavioralHealthServices/OpioidUseDisorderAndTreatment/Locating_Treatment.html", "description": "AHCCCS page for accessing and locating OUD treatment, including 24/7 OTP access points, regional behavioral health authority contacts, and crisis line numbers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's FindTreatment.gov to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Arizona."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Prescriber Resources", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Members/BehavioralHealthServices/OpioidUseDisorderAndTreatment/For_Prescribers.html", "description": "AHCCCS provider training and resources for OUD treatment, including Arizona Opioid Epidemic Act information, prescribing guidelines, CSPMP training, MATE Act resources, and the AzMAT Mentors Program."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Kate Dobler, 801 E. Jefferson St., Phoenix, AZ 85034. Phone: (602) 417-4768. Email: catherine.dobler@azahcccs.gov", "description": "Arizona's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority contact as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AzMAT Mentors Program", "url": "https://crh.arizona.edu/mentor", "description": "Arizona Center for Rural Health mentoring program connecting new providers with experienced MAT practitioners to increase buprenorphine prescribing capacity."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act, the X-waiver is no longer required. Arizona follows federal requirements for 8 hours of SUD training. The Arizona Opioid Epidemic Act imposed additional state-level requirements for opioid prescribing and CSPMP checking."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Opioid Prescribing Guidelines", "url": "https://azdhs.gov/documents/audiences/clinicians/clinical-guidelines-recommendations/prescribing-guidelines/az-opioid-prescribing-guidelines.pdf", "description": "ADHS clinical guidelines for opioid prescribing in Arizona."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations: Arizona follows DEA federal telehealth regulations for buprenorphine prescribing. AHCCCS covers telehealth services for behavioral health including OUD treatment."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Pharmacy Updates", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Members/Pharmacy/", "description": "AHCCCS pharmacy updates and information page, including P&T Committee, drug list, biosimilar updates, and pharmacy department contacts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Drug List", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Resources/Downloads/PharmacyUpdates/AHCCCSDrugList.pdf", "description": "AHCCCS Acute/Long-Term Care Drug List. Buprenorphine HCL-Naloxone HCL generic formulations are preferred drugs. Buprenorphine extended-release injection (Sublocade) is preferred with PA required."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Annual Opioid Data Report", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Members/BehavioralHealthServices/AnnualOpioidDataReport.html", "description": "AHCCCS annual report on opioid treatment program data, including OTP standards, provider locations, and annual findings."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Services Billing: Arizona Medicaid (AHCCCS) covers pharmacist-provided services under certain conditions. Contact AHCCCS Pharmacy Department at ahcccspharmacydept@azahcccs.gov for specific billing guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Arizona receives State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA. The Governor's Office Substance Use Disorder Service Funds and opioid settlement funds support treatment, recovery, and harm reduction programs. Contact AHCCCS or ADHS for current grant opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arizona CE Requirements", "url": "https://pharmacy.az.gov/sites/default/files/2022-04/2021%20CE%20Requirements_Rev07232021.pdf", "description": "Arizona Board of Pharmacy CE requirements. Pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE per biennial renewal. Three (3) of the 30 hours must be in opioid-related, substance use disorder-related, or addiction-related continuing education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.azpharmacy.org/", "description": "Arizona Pharmacy Association (AzPA), founded in 1910, supporting pharmacy professionals across all practice settings. Offers education, advocacy, and professional development."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AzPA Peer Assistance (PAPA) Program", "url": "https://azpharmacy.org/papa/", "description": "Arizona Pharmacy Foundation PAPA program for peer assistance helping healthcare professionals enter safe recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System offering free OUD treatment training, including 8-hour MATE Act requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS 8-Hour MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/medications-for-opioid-use-disorder/8-hour-moud-education-options/", "description": "PCSS training options meeting the 8-hour education requirement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Training Requirements (MATE Act)", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/medications-substance-use-disorders/training-requirements-mate-act-resources", "description": "SAMHSA page on MATE Act training requirements and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division for registration and controlled substance regulations."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Arizona legalized syringe service programs and fentanyl test strips in 2021, removing them from the definition of drug paraphernalia (previously a class 6 felony). Programs like Sonoran Prevention Works operate in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AZ Public Health Association - SSP Legalization", "url": "https://azpha.org/2021/06/10/syringe-services-fentanyl-test-strips-finally-legalized/", "description": "Arizona Public Health Association article on the legalization of syringe services and fentanyl test strips in Arizona (2021)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Sonoran Prevention Works", "url": "https://spwaz.org/", "description": "Arizona-based harm reduction organization providing syringe services, naloxone, fentanyl test strips, and community health services. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADHS Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://www.azdhs.gov/documents/prevention/womens-childrens-health/injury-prevention/opioid-prevention/naloxone-standing-order.pdf", "description": "Arizona Department of Health Services Standing Order authorizing any Arizona-licensed pharmacist to dispense naloxone without a patient-specific prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADHS Opioid Prevention Page", "url": "https://www.azdhs.gov/opioid/", "description": "Arizona Department of Health Services opioid prevention page with data, resources, and the OARLine crisis number (1-888-688-4222)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSPMP Naloxone Information", "url": "https://pharmacypmp.az.gov/resources", "description": "Board of Pharmacy resources including the pharmacist naloxone dispensing guide and standing order."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maricopa County Substance Use Resources", "url": "https://www.maricopa.gov/5833/Substance-Use", "description": "Maricopa County resources for substance use, including naloxone distribution and fentanyl test strip access funded by opioid settlement and marijuana tax funds."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips were legalized in Arizona in 2021 when syringe services were also legalized. They are distributed through harm reduction programs and county health departments."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Overdose Data Dashboard: The ADHS opioid data dashboard was established in 2017 following the Declaration of Emergency. Access the latest data through the ADHS opioid page."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Behavioral Health Services", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Members/BehavioralHealthServices/", "description": "AHCCCS behavioral health services page covering substance use disorder treatment, recovery support, and peer services. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Opioid Services Locator", "url": "https://opioidservicelocator.azahcccs.gov/", "description": "Interactive map to find OUD treatment and recovery support services across Arizona."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Arizona licenses behavioral health residential facilities and sober living homes through ADHS. The National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) at https://narronline.org/ can also be used to find certified recovery residences."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADHS Recovery Housing Information", "url": "https://directorsblog.health.azdhs.gov/how-we-license-facilities-that-provide-substance-abuse-recovery-resources/", "description": "ADHS information on licensing substance abuse recovery facilities, including the distinction between behavioral health residential facilities and sober living homes."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Behavioral Health Agency: AHCCCS administers behavioral health services in Arizona through Regional Behavioral Health Authorities (RBHAs). ADHS handles licensing and public health oversight."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Arizona Crisis Line (Mercy Care/Maricopa): 602-222-9444 or 1-800-631-1314. Arizona Complete Health Crisis Line: 866-495-6735. OARLine: 1-888-688-4222. 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline available 24/7."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://pharmacy.az.gov/", "description": "Arizona State Board of Pharmacy. Phone: (602) 771-2727. Address: 1616 W. Adams St., Suite 120, Phoenix, AZ 85007. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Kate Dobler, 801 E. Jefferson St., Phoenix, AZ 85034. Phone: (602) 417-4768. Email: catherine.dobler@azahcccs.gov"}, {"type": "note", "text": "AHCCCS Pharmacy Department: Email: ahcccspharmacydept@azahcccs.gov"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.azpharmacy.org/", "description": "Arizona Pharmacy Association. Contact: admin@azpharmacy.org"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Department of Health Services", "url": "https://www.azdhs.gov/", "description": "ADHS manages opioid prevention, harm reduction, and public health programs. OARLine: 1-888-688-4222."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ADHS Opioid Data Reports", "url": "https://www.azdhs.gov/opioid/", "description": "Arizona Department of Health Services opioid prevention page with links to data, surveillance reports, and dashboard access."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADHS Opioid Surveillance Reports", "url": "https://www.azdhs.gov/opioid/documents/opioid-report-2023.pdf", "description": "2023 Opioid Overdoses Surveillance Report for Arizona (published April 2025)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ADHS 2020-2021 Surveillance Report", "url": "https://www.azdhs.gov/opioid/documents/opioid-surveillance-report-2020-2021.pdf", "description": "Opioid overdoses surveillance report for Arizona covering 2020-2021."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AHCCCS Annual Opioid Data Report", "url": "https://www.azahcccs.gov/Members/BehavioralHealthServices/AnnualOpioidDataReport.html", "description": "AHCCCS annual report on opioid treatment program standards, provider locations, and findings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Governor's Office Substance Abuse Resources", "url": "https://goyff.az.gov/content/arizona-substance-abuse-prevention-resource", "description": "Arizona Governor's Office of Youth, Faith and Family substance abuse prevention resource page with links to real-time opioid data, drug drop-off locations, and treatment locators."}, {"type": "note", "text": "CSPMP Annual Report: Available at https://pharmacypmp.az.gov/", "description": "Arizona CSPMP annual report with prescription monitoring data trends, including buprenorphine prescribing patterns."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Opioid Epidemic Act", "url": "https://apps.azleg.gov/BillStatus/GetDocumentPdf/456195", "description": "Full text of the Arizona Opioid Epidemic Act that established emergency rulemaking for opioid prescribing rules and CSPMP checking requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.azpharmacy.org/", "description": "AzPA advocacy resources for Arizona pharmacists. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona State Legislature", "url": "https://www.azleg.gov/", "description": "Arizona State Legislature website for tracking current legislation related to pharmacy practice and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Your Arizona Legislator", "url": "https://www.azleg.gov/findmylegislator/", "description": "Tool to find and contact your Arizona state representatives and senators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arizona Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute", "url": "https://www.azleg.gov/ars/32/01970.htm", "description": "ARS 32-1970 establishing the framework for collaborative practice agreements between pharmacists and providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations model legislation and policy templates. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Recent Legislation: The 2021 law legalizing syringe services programs and fentanyl test strips. The Arizona Opioid Epidemic Act (2017-2018). ARS 32-1970 collaborative practice agreements. SB1370 regarding CSPMP data sharing."}]}]}, "arkansas": {"name": "Arkansas", "q": {"CPA_Term": "It appears that CPAs are included within Arkansas’s use of the terms “statewide protocol” and “written protocol” for drug therapy management (DTM). ARK. CODE ANN. § 17-92-101(18), (21), (26) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arkansas law allows a pharmacist to “prescribe . . . medications that treat adverse reactions associated with the administration of vaccines and immunizations, vaccines, and immunizations to or for a person three (3) years of age or older.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(i)(c) (West 2024).\nAlso, the practice of pharmacy involves “providing pharmacy care,” which includes a prescribing component. Under this provision, however, the formulary of drugs that a pharmacist can prescribe for certain specified conditions “shall not include any controlled substance in schedules I-IV.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(x) (West 2024).\nIn addition, when providing pharmacy care, a pharmacist can prescribe “over-the-counter medications, supplies, and devices.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(x) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Arkansas cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Arkansas practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Arkansas pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arkansas law includes the general ability to administer medications, “except as limited by rules adopted by the Arkansas State Board of Pharmacy.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(i)(b) (West 2024).\nIn addition, the practice of pharmacy provides that “a pharmacist may administer medications other than [certain specified medications] under a patient-specific order or prescription or general written protocol.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(i)(e) (West 2024).\nUnder Arkansas regulation, a “licensed pharmacist, intern or pharmacy technician has the ability to administer medications they have been trained to administer.” 007.39.9 ARK. ADMIN. CODE § 09.00.0002 (2024).", "2B": "Obtain a patient-specific order or prescription or act pursuant to a general written protocol.\nAdhere to the administration, recordkeeping, and training requirements contained in Arkansas laws and regulations. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A) (West 2024); 007.39.9 ARK. ADMIN. CODE § 09.00.0002 (2024).", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arkansas includes “providing pharmacy care.” As part of providing pharmacy care, a pharmacist “shall only treat conditions for which the pharmacist has tested and that are approved under subdivision (18)(A)(x)(b).” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(x)(c) (West 2024).\nThe approved conditions are influenza, pharyngitis caused by streptococcus A, or “other health conditions that can be screened utilizing” CLIA-waived tests. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(x)(b) (West 2024).\nArkansas pharmacy laws and regulations do not use either the word “order” or “evaluate” with respect to tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Arkansas to expressly allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arkansas law includes “performing a specific act of drug therapy management [DTM] or disease state management delegated to a pharmacist” based upon a written protocol or patient care plan approved by a physician. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(ix)(a) (West 2024).\nDTM “shall not include the selection of drug products not prescribed by the physician unless the drug products are either named in the physician-initiated protocol or the physician-approved patient care plan.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(ix)(b) (West 2024). This suggests, although not clearly, that a pharmacist can prescribe drugs that physician does not prescribe under a DTM protocol if the physician allows it.\nHowever, Arkansas law does not expressly specify whether the pharmacist’s prescriptive authority under a protocol (if any) includes controlled substances.\nMoreover, Arkansas law governing DTM protocols does not account for the fact that an Arkansas pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol directs.\nIn summary, Arkansas law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing drugs under a DTM protocol. Even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, however, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Arkansas pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Arkansas laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under DTM protocols.\nExpressly specify in Arkansas laws and regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under such protocols.\nAllow Arkansas pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Arkansas laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arkansas law includes performing DTM based upon a written protocol or patient care plan approved by a physician. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(ix)(a) (West 2024).\nArkansas law does not define DTM nor explain what actions are included as part of DTM.\nAs a result, Arkansas law is unclear about whether a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a DTM protocol. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that pharmacists have the general authority to administer drugs under a patient-specific order or prescription, the logical conclusion is that the answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a written protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in Arkansas law and/or regulation that as part of providing DTM under a protocol, a pharmacist can administer drugs, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Arkansas laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Arkansas law includes performing DTM based upon a written protocol or patient care plan approved by a physician. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(ix)(a) (West 2024).\nArkansas law does not define DTM nor explain what actions are included as part of DTM. Moreover, the law covering DTM does not reference ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nAs a result, Arkansas law is unclear about whether a pharmacist can order or evaluate the results of lab tests under a DTM protocol. However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that Arkansas pharmacists have some authority to perform very limited types of tests outside of a DTM protocol, the logical conclusion is that pharmacists have the same limited authority under such protocol.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Arkansas laws and/or regulations that part of DTM that can be delegated to a pharmacist is ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "The written DTM protocol or a patient care plan must be approved by a state licensed physician. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(ix)(a) (West 2024).\nThere is little information in Arkansas law about the requirements for entering written protocols and required elements of written protocols. The information that exists is here – ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-92-101(18)(A)(i)(e), (i)(f), (ix) (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nArkansas has a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law that allows a “healthcare professional” to offer medical services through telemedicine. The law specifies the treatment is without limitation, including prescriptions, as long as the provider is held to the standard of care. ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-80-404(c) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “healthcare professional” is broad covering any individual “who is licensed, certified, or otherwise authorized by the laws of this state to administer health care in the ordinary course of the practice of his or her profession.” ARK. CODE. ANN. § 17-80-402(2) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "Arkansas regulations contain provisions related to Medicaid coverage for “medication assisted treatment” (MAT). The regulation provides “providers are required to follow SAMHSA guidelines for the full provision of MAT” and “providers are encouraged to use telemedicine services when in-person treatment is not readily accessible.” ARK. CODE R. 016.06.36-230.000 (2024).65\nArkansas laws governing telehealth include – ARK. CODE. ANN. §§ 17-80-401 to 17-80- 407 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); ARK. CODE. ANN. § 20-77-141 (West 2024) (Medicaid); ARK. CODE. ANN. §§ 23-79-1601 to 23-79-1602 (West 2024) (insurance); ARK. CODE R. 007.29.1-38, (2024) (telemedicine providers); ARK. CODE R. 016.06.36-292.920 (2024) (Medicaid); ARK. CODE R. 016.06.84-201.00 to 016.06.84-265. (2024) (telemedicine COVID-10 response); ARK. CODE R. 016.25.5-305.000 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "According to Arkansas Medicaid information for providers, “the Arkansas Medicaid Program will allow pharmacists to enroll individually as atypical providers to prescribe and administer specified drugs and test and screen for certain health conditions, per current allowable protocols.\nPharmacists are not billing providers, but they may be rendering providers on medical claims. Pharmacists will be allowed as prescribing providers on pharmacy claims for drugs identified in current protocol.”", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Arkansas Medicaid program.\nExpressly specify in Arkansas laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a DTM protocol are covered under the Arkansas Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Arkansas regulations contain provisions related to Medicaid coverage for MAT. The regulation specifies that “in accordance with SAMHSA guidelines, MAT requires at a minimum” certain evaluation, diagnostic, drug screening, outreach, office visit, and counseling visit requirements as specified in the regulation. ARK. CODE R. 016.06.36-230.000 (2024). 69"}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://arkansas.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Arkansas PDMP AWARxE portal for authorized users to query controlled substance dispensing records. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Homepage", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/prevention-healthy-living/substance-misuse-injury-prevention/prescription-drug-monitoring-program/", "description": "Arkansas Department of Health PDMP homepage. The AR PDMP is an electronic database of all controlled prescriptions dispensed at Arkansas pharmacies and mail-order pharmacies delivered into Arkansas. Access is granted to prescribers, pharmacists, delegates, professional licensing boards, and certified law enforcement investigators. Please verify this link before publishing (site may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP for Healthcare Providers", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/prevention-healthy-living/substance-misuse-injury-prevention/prescription-drug-monitoring-program/pdmp-for-healthcare-providers/", "description": "Provider-specific PDMP information. Dispensers are required to report dispensation of Schedule II-V controlled substances. Pharmacies must report the next business day; veterinary clinics every 30 days. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Arkansas mandates PDMP registration for prescribers and dispensers. Dispensing of all Schedule II-V controlled substances must be reported to the PDMP. Prescribers are required to check the PDMP before prescribing certain controlled substances."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Arkansas participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates of prescribers and pharmacists can be registered through the AWARxE system to query the PDMP on behalf of their supervising practitioner."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Data Reports and Resources", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/prevention-healthy-living/substance-misuse-injury-prevention/prescription-drug-monitoring-program/pdmp-reports-resources/", "description": "PDMP data hub with statewide evaluation data, annual reports, quarterly reports, county maps, mortality reports, and academic detailing resources. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacyboard.arkansas.gov/", "description": "Arkansas State Board of Pharmacy website with licensing information, rule changes, FAQs, and practice resources. Please verify this link before publishing (site may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy (via ADH)", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/boards-commissions/boards/pharmacy-arkansas-state-board/", "description": "Arkansas State Board of Pharmacy page hosted on the Arkansas Department of Health website. The agency licenses, permits, and oversees pharmacists, pharmacies, and the prescription drug distribution system. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/wp-content/uploads/2-Appendix-A-Pharmacy-Practice-Act-NO-Subchapters-September-2024-Final-Format.pdf", "description": "Full text of the Arkansas Pharmacy Practice Act (September 2024 format)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Law Book", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/wp-content/uploads/Lawbook-2025-May-9.pdf", "description": "Complete Arkansas Board of Pharmacy Law Book (May 2025 edition) containing statutes, regulations, and appendices."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (Controlled Substances)", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/wp-content/uploads/4-Appendix-C-Uniform-Controlled-Substances-Act-September-2024-Final-Format.pdf", "description": "Arkansas Uniform Controlled Substances Act, including drug paraphernalia provisions."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice Agreements: Arkansas law authorizes collaborative practice agreements between pharmacists and physicians. Under the Pharmacy Practice Act, a pharmacist may initiate therapy and administer or dispense drugs under a protocol approved by both the Board of Pharmacy and the Arkansas State Medical Board. The collaborative practice agreement statute is found in the Pharmacy Practice Act (Section 17-92-101 et seq.)."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Arkansas pharmacists may prescribe under collaborative practice agreements. Pharmacists can dispense naloxone under the state's standing order. Arkansas pharmacists can also administer immunizations under approved protocols."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's FindTreatment.gov to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Arkansas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/locators/opioid-treatment-program-directory", "description": "SAMHSA directory of certified opioid treatment programs, filterable to Arkansas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Opioid Recovery Partnership (ARORP)", "url": "https://www.arorp.org/", "description": "Arkansas Opioid Recovery Partnership providing prevention, treatment, and recovery resources. The ReviveAR app offers access to resources and naloxone instructions for Arkansans."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas DHS Substance Abuse Treatment Locator", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/samh-treatment/", "description": "Arkansas Department of Human Services page for finding substance abuse or mental health treatment providers, including directories and service descriptions. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Jennifer Shuler, 700 Main Street, Little Rock, AR 72203. Phone: (501) 534-4018. Email: jennifer.shuler@dhs.arkansas.gov", "description": "Arkansas's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority contact as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Arkansas follows federal MATE Act requirements. The X-waiver is no longer required. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders for DEA registration or renewal. No additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations: Arkansas follows DEA federal telehealth regulations for buprenorphine prescribing. The Arkansas Medical Board has telehealth practice guidelines."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/medical-services/pharmacy/preferred-drugs-list/", "description": "Arkansas Department of Human Services Medicaid preferred drug list page. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Medicaid Pharmacy Provider Information", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/medical-services/helpful-information-for-providers/manuals/pharmacy-prov/", "description": "Arkansas Medicaid pharmacy provider manual and resources, including Prime Therapeutics Medicaid Administration information. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Coverage: Buprenorphine/naloxone products are covered under Arkansas Medicaid for use in accredited outpatient narcotic treatment programs and physician offices. Contact the Division of Medical Services for current PA requirements and formulary status."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Medicaid Fee-For-Service Drug Utilization", "url": "https://www.medicaid.gov/Medicaid/Prescription-Drugs/Downloads/2022-AR-DUR.pdf", "description": "Federal Medicaid drug utilization review report for Arkansas (FFY 2022), including information on MAT coverage, naloxone dispensing, and pharmacist authority."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Services Billing: Arkansas Medicaid reimburses pharmacies for administration fees for certain services. The Medicaid program has expanded pharmacy benefits. Contact DHS Division of Medical Services for specific billing codes for pharmacist-provided services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Arkansas receives State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA. Opioid settlement funds are also distributed statewide. Contact the DHS Office of Substance Abuse and Mental Health for current grant opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/arkansas/", "description": "Overview of Arkansas pharmacist CE requirements. Pharmacists must complete 30 hours of ACPE-approved CE per biennial renewal. Additional hours required for nursing home consultants (3 hours) and immunization-administering pharmacists (2 hours)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy CE Regulations", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/arkansas/070-00-01-Ark-Code-R-SS-013", "description": "Arkansas Administrative Code on implementation of pharmacy continuing education requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://arrx.org/", "description": "Arkansas Pharmacists Association (APA), dedicated to professional advancement, advocacy, and safeguarding health. Offers education and resources for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System offering free OUD treatment training, including 8-hour MATE Act requirement options."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS 8-Hour MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/medications-for-opioid-use-disorder/8-hour-moud-education-options/", "description": "PCSS training options meeting the 8-hour education requirement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division for DEA registration and controlled substance regulations."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Arkansas does not currently have state-specific board-approved SUD or buprenorphine training programs beyond federal MATE Act requirements. ACPE-accredited programs are accepted."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Syringe services programs (needle exchange) are not explicitly authorized under Arkansas state law. Access to sterile syringes may be limited."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/wp-content/uploads/Naloxone_Standing_Order_Dr_Bala.pdf", "description": "Arkansas Opioid Antagonist Protocol (standing order) authorizing pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a patient-specific prescription. Issued pursuant to Arkansas law. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Substance Misuse Education and Prevention", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/prevention-healthy-living/substance-misuse-education-and-prevention/", "description": "Arkansas Department of Health page on substance misuse prevention, including links to nonfatal overdose data, EMS naloxone administrations, Dose of Reality campaign, peer recovery support specialists, and naloxone training/distribution. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Take Back Program", "url": "http://artakeback.org/take-back/naloxone/", "description": "Arkansas Take Back website with naloxone access information and training programs for first responders."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Narcansas App: The free Narcansas app provides Arkansans access to naloxone training, overdose response instructions, and links to prevention, treatment, and recovery services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro Arkansas", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/arkansas", "description": "NEXT Distro page for Arkansas with harm reduction resources. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: As of the most recent information available, fentanyl test strips remain classified as drug paraphernalia under Arkansas law (Ark. Code Ann. Section 5-64-443). Possession or distribution may be prosecuted as a felony. Check for any recent legislative updates."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Overdose Data: See Category 9 for surveillance dashboards and data resources."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Peer Recovery Program", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/arkansas-peer-recovery/", "description": "Arkansas DHS peer recovery program managing peer specialist certification and placement, and administering state and federal recovery support funds. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Resources and Service Directory", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/arkansas-peer-recovery/peer-resources/", "description": "Directory of services available in Arkansas including inpatient treatment, outpatient, detoxification, MOUD/MAT/OUD, housing, recovery support groups, employment services, and more. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Office of Substance Abuse and Mental Health", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/", "description": "Arkansas DHS Office of Substance Abuse and Mental Health (OSAMH) overseeing prevention, treatment, and recovery programs. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Treatment Locator", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/samh-treatment/", "description": "DHS page for finding substance abuse or mental health treatment providers in Arkansas, with multiple directories. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Arkansas does not maintain a centralized state-operated recovery housing directory. The Peer Resources page (above) includes housing categories. Use the National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) at https://narronline.org/ to search for certified recovery residences."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/", "description": "Arkansas Department of Human Services homepage. The Office of Substance Abuse and Mental Health oversees behavioral health services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (call or text 988). Arkansas Crisis Center: 1-888-274-7472. SAMHSA National Helpline: 1-800-662-4357."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas State Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.pharmacyboard.arkansas.gov/", "description": "Arkansas State Board of Pharmacy. Address: 101 E. Capitol Ave., Suite 218, Little Rock, AR 72201. Phone: (501) 682-0190. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Board of Pharmacy (ADH)", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/boards-commissions/boards/pharmacy-arkansas-state-board/", "description": "Board of Pharmacy page on the Arkansas Department of Health website. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Jennifer Shuler, 700 Main Street, Little Rock, AR 72203. Phone: (501) 534-4018. Email: jennifer.shuler@dhs.arkansas.gov"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://arrx.org/", "description": "Arkansas Pharmacists Association. Professional organization for pharmacists in Arkansas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Department of Health", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/", "description": "Arkansas Department of Health. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Office of Substance Abuse and Mental Health", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/", "description": "DHS OSAMH overseeing substance use disorder programs, prevention, and recovery. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Data Hub and Reports", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/prevention-healthy-living/substance-misuse-injury-prevention/prescription-drug-monitoring-program/pdmp-reports-resources/", "description": "Arkansas PDMP data hub with annual reports, quarterly reports, county maps, mortality reports, and statewide evaluation data. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Opioid Dashboard", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/news/new-public-opioid-dashboard-serves-as-tool-to-shine-light-on-epidemic/", "description": "Arkansas DHS public opioid dashboard providing data on opioid trends in the state. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Annual Report 2022", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/wp-content/uploads/PDMP_Annual_Report_2022_FINAL.pdf", "description": "2022 PDMP annual report with data on prescriber types, opioid dispensing trends, and resident data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP 2023 Annual Report", "url": "https://www.arorp.org/prescription-drug-monitoring-program-2023-annual-report/", "description": "Arkansas Opioid Recovery Partnership summary of the 2023 PDMP annual report, noting that scheduled drug prescriptions decreased sharply between 2019 and 2021."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Substance Misuse Data", "url": "https://healthy.arkansas.gov/programs-services/prevention-healthy-living/substance-misuse-education-and-prevention/", "description": "ADH page with nonfatal overdose data, EMS naloxone administrations, and other surveillance information. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Response Grant Data", "url": "https://humanservices.arkansas.gov/divisions-shared-services/shared-services/office-of-substance-abuse-and-mental-health/substance-abuse-prevention/substance-abuse-prevention-grants/state-opioid-response-grant-ii/", "description": "DHS State Opioid Response Grant II page with information on funded programs and the Narcansas app. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Opioid Recovery Partnership", "url": "https://www.arorp.org/", "description": "Statewide coalition committed to abating opioid misuse and addiction in Arkansas. Provides data, resources, and the ReviveAR app."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://arrx.org/", "description": "Arkansas Pharmacists Association advocacy page for state legislative priorities and pharmacy profession advancement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Arkansas State Legislature", "url": "https://www.arkleg.state.ar.us/", "description": "Arkansas General Assembly website for tracking current legislation related to pharmacy practice and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Your Arkansas Legislator", "url": "https://www.arkleg.state.ar.us/Legislators/List", "description": "Find and contact your Arkansas state legislators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations model legislation and policy resources. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Legislation: Act 593 (2019) naloxone standing order authority. Arkansas Pharmacy Practice Act (Section 17-92-101 et seq.) including collaborative practice provisions. The Uniform Controlled Substances Act governs controlled substance scheduling and paraphernalia definitions. Note: fentanyl test strips remain classified as paraphernalia under current law - check for any recent legislative updates."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Arkansas Drug Director: The Arkansas Drug Director (housed within DHS) coordinates statewide substance abuse initiatives and opioid response efforts."}]}]}, "california": {"name": "California", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nCalifornia law governing the scope of practice of a pharmacist does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a) (West 2024).\nHowever, the definition of the word “prescription” in California pharmacy law provides that a prescription can be issued by a pharmacist “pursuant to Section 4052.1, 4052.2, or 4052.6.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4040(a)(2) (West 2024).\nThe three referenced sections address pharmacist authority:\n(1) pursuant to the protocols of a healthcare facility; (2) pursuant to certain protocols of a facility, clinic with physician oversight, or for care provided by a physician; or (3) as an “advanced practice pharmacist” (APP). CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 4052.1, 4052.2, 4052.6 (West 2024).\nThe law governing the scope of pharmacist practice expressly authorizes pharmacists to act pursuant to each of these three sections. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(4), (5), (6) (West 2024).\nAn APP may “initiate, adjust, or discontinue drug therapy” with no reference to needing a CPA or physician protocol for such actions. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052.6(a)(5) (West 2024). Although this provision does not expressly refer to prescribing, the definition of “prescription” makes clear an APP can prescribe.\nMoreover, the law governing APP practice notes that prior to initiating or adjusting a controlled substance therapy, the APP must “personally register with the federal Drug Enforcement Administration.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052.6(d) (West 2024). This is a reference to obtaining the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances. In addition, California law describing the general scope of pharmacist practice also provides that a pharmacist authorized by any part of the scope of practice to issue an order to initiate or adjust a controlled substance therapy must “personally register” with DEA. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(b) (West 2024). It is unclear if this provision authorizes any additional prescribing authority for a pharmacist independent of a CPA or established protocol by a health care facility or physician, other than what an APP can perform.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in California can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Prescribe Only.”", "1B": "Apply for and obtain recognition from the California State Board of Pharmacy (Board) as an APP. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 4210 to 4211 (West 2024); CAL. CODE. REGS., tit. 16, §§ 1730 to 1731 (2024).\nObtain the DEA mid-level practitioner registration.\nAdhere to California laws regarding APP practice, including informing the patient’s primary provider or diagnosing provider upon initiating drug therapy. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052.6 (West 2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "1C": null, "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nCalifornia law governing the scope of practice of a pharmacist expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “administer drugs and biological products that have been ordered by a prescriber.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(3) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the types of drugs or medications that a pharmacist can administer and is separate from another express provision related to administering vaccinations.The scope of practice law also expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “provide medication-assisted treatment pursuant to a state protocol, to the extent authorized by federal law.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(14) (West 2024). However, no such protocol appears in California regulations as of November 2024, although the Board considered such a protocol in early 2023 that expressly includes administering MAT.\nMoreover, California law expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “administer a narcotic controlled substance in the treatment of a person with substance use disorder for addiction to a controlled substance” so long as the pharmacist is “acting under the direction of a physician and surgeon.” CAL. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE § 11215(b)(3) (West 2024).\nAlthough the Health & Safety code provision described above directly authorizes pharmacist administration of certain medications for SUD treatment such as buprenorphine, it does make it unclear if an APP, who can initiate, adjust, or discontinue drug therapy with no reference to needing a CPA or physician protocol (see the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, may only administer buprenorphine under the direction of a physician or surgeon.", "2B": "Obtain the order of a prescriber or the direction of a physician and surgeon.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below the authorization could be limited slightly for certain pharmacists.\nCalifornia law governing the scope of practice of a pharmacist expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “order and interpret tests for the purpose of monitoring and managing the efficacy and toxicity of drug therapies.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(12) (West 2024).\nIn addition, an APP is authorized to “order and interpret drug therapy-related tests” without reference to needing a CPA or physician protocol for such actions. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052.6(a)(2) (West 2024).\nThe language difference between the APP provision and the general pharmacist provision may mean that an APP has broader authority to order and interpret the results of lab tests.", "3B": "Order the tests in coordination with the patient’s primary care provider or diagnosing prescriber and provide the information required by California law. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 4052(a)(12), 4052.6(e) (West 2024).\nIf not an APP, confirm that the test ordered is “for the purposes of monitoring and managing the efficacy and toxicity of drug therapies.”\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "3C": "Revise California law and/or regulations to define or explain the phrase “for the purposes of monitoring and managing the efficacy and toxicity of drug therapies.”\nIf necessary, expand the California scope of pharmacy practice to expressly allow pharmacists other than APPs to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "As described in the information below, California laws do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes” at least for some pharmacists.\nCalifornia law governing the scope of practice of a pharmacist expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “initiate, adjust, or discontinue drug therapy for a patient under a collaborative practice agreement with any health care provider with prescriptive authority.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(13) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “initiate” and “adjust” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nCalifornia pharmacy laws and regulations contain no other information about the extent of pharmacy practice under a CPA.\nHowever, the scope of pharmacist practice law provides that a pharmacist authorized by any part of that law to issue an order to initiate or adjust a controlled substance therapy must “personally register” with DEA. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(b) (West 2024). This is a reference to obtaining the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances and may indicate that a CPA can authorize pharmacist prescribing of controlled substances.\nHowever, the definition of the word “prescription” in California pharmacy law provides that a prescription can be issued by a pharmacist “pursuant to Section 4052.1, 4052.2, or 4052.6.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4040(a)(2) (West 2024).\nThe three referenced sections address pharmacist authority:\n(1) pursuant to the protocols of a healthcare facility; (2) pursuant to certain protocols of a facility, clinic with physician oversight, or for care provided by a physician; or (3) as an APP. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 4052.1, 4052.2, 4052.6 (West 2024). None of these sections expressly pertain to pharmacist practice under a CPA.\nNevertheless, § 4052.2 addresses pharmacist practice performed in accord with certain policies, procedures, or protocols, including those of a patient’s treating physician. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052.2 (West 2024). It is possible that prescribing authority granted by a CPA could fall under this provision.Finally, in 2020, the Board published a sample CPA entitled “Pharmacist Protocol for Management of Opioid Use Disorders.” The publicly available version of this CPA was last revised in April 2023. This CPA expressly allows a pharmacist to “initiate, modify, discontinue, and administer formulations of buprenorphine indicated for OUD,” but does not expressly refer to prescribing buprenorphine or the need to obtain a DEA mid-level practitioner registration to do so.\nIn summary, California pharmacy laws and regulations do not clearly authorize or prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances under a CPA. However, based on the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, an APP has such authority outside of a CPA and it is logical to conclude that such APP would have the same authority under a CPA.", "4B": "If necessary, apply for and obtain recognition from the California State Board of Pharmacy (Board) as an APP. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 4210 to 4211 (West 2024); CAL. CODE. REGS., tit. 16, §§ 1730 to 1731 (2024).\nObtain the DEA mid-level practitioner registration.\nEnter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": "Revise California laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPAs.\nExpressly specify in California laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.", "5A": "As described in the information below, California laws do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" sectionand other available Board information, the answer is likely “yes.”\nCalifornia law governing the scope of practice of a pharmacist expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “initiate, adjust, or discontinue drug therapy for a patient under a [CPA] with any health care provider with prescriptive authority.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(13) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “initiate” and “adjust,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nCalifornia pharmacy laws and regulations contain no other information about the extent of pharmacy practice under a CPA.\nBased on the above, California laws do not provide a clear answer to this question. However, the sample CPA entitled “Pharmacist Protocol for Management of Opioid Use Disorders” published by the Board and last revised in April 2023 expressly provides that a pharmacist can “administer formulations of buprenorphine indicated for OUD” under a CPA. Moreover, the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section indicates that pharmacists have the general authority to administer drugs and biological products that have been ordered by a prescriber.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in California laws and/or regulations that as part of providing drug therapy under a CPA, a pharmacist can order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "6A": "As described in the information below, California laws do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" sectionand other available Board information, the answer is likely “yes.”\nCalifornia law governing the scope of practice of a pharmacist expressly authorizes a pharmacist to “initiate, adjust, or discontinue drug therapy for a patient under a [CPA] with any health care provider with prescriptive authority.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(13) (West 2024).\nCalifornia pharmacy laws and regulations contain no other information about the extent of pharmacy practice under a CPA and whether it includes ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests.\nBased on the above, California laws do not provide a clear answer to this question. However, the sample CPA entitled “Pharmacist Protocol for Management of Opioid Use Disorders” published by the Board and last revised in April 2023 expressly provides that one of a pharmacist’s authorized functions under a CPA is “assessment of opioid use disorder including physical and laboratory examination for signs and symptoms of opioid use and opioid use disorder sequalae.” The reference to “laboratory examination” may indicate that a pharmacist can order and evaluate the results of lab tests under a CPA.\nIn addition, the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section indicates that California pharmacists have the general authority to order and interpret laboratory tests outside of CPAs. As a result, the most logical conclusion is that pharmacists have the same authority within them.", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in California laws and/or regulations that as part of providing drug therapy under a CPA, a pharmacist can administer drugs and medications, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "7": "A California pharmacist can initiate, adjust, or discontinue drug therapy for a patient under a CPA with “any health care provider with prescriptive authority.” The CPA can involve multiple pharmacists and/or multiple health care providers. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 4052(a)(13) (West 2024).\nBesides the provision noted above, there is no information in California laws or regulations about the requirements for entering CPAs or required elements of CPAs.\nIn 2020, the Board published a sample CPA entitled “Pharmacist Protocol for Management of Opioid Use Disorders.” The current version of this CPA was revised in April 2023.", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nCalifornia law contains general telehealth/telemedicine practice acts in two places. One law provides that a “health care practitioner licensed under Division 2” of the business and professions code (“healing arts”) providing services via telehealth “shall be subject to the requirements and definitions set forth in Section 2290.5, to the practice act relating to his or her licensed profession, and to the regulations adopted by a board pursuant to that practice act.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 686 (West 2024).\nPharmacists are licensed under Division 2.\nThe other law, the above-referenced § 2290.5, provides guidelines and restrictions about the way a “health care provider” provides telehealth services. The term “health care provider” includes “a person licensed under this division,” which refers to Division 2 of the business and professions code and includes pharmacists. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 2290.5 (West 2024).\nCalifornia pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "California law prohibits the “prescribing, dispensing, or furnishing” of prescription drugs (called “dangerous drugs”) without an appropriate examination and medical indication. However, the examination can occur through telehealth, so long as the provider follows the appropriate standard of care. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 2242 (West 2024).\nCalifornia laws governing telehealth include – CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 686, 2290.5 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 4044.7, 4130 to 4135 (West 2024) (telepharmacy); CAL. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE §§ 1374.13 to 1374.14 (West 2024) (health care service plans); CAL. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE § 123149.5 (West 2024) (information transmitted during telehealth); CAL. INS. CODE §§ 10123.85 to 10123.855 (West 2024)\n(health insurers); CAL. WELF. & INST. CODE §§ 14132.72 to 14132.725 (Medicaid).", "9A": "California law requires health care services plans and certain disability insurers that cover a service that is within the scope of practice of a pharmacist to pay or reimburse the cost of the service when performed by a pharmacist (assuming provided at an in-network pharmacy or if there are out-of-network benefits) so long as “the coverage otherwise provides reimbursement for identical services performed by other licensed health care providers.” CAL. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE § 1368.5 (West 2024); CAL. INS.\nCODE § 10125.1 (West 2024). These provisions do not apply to the California Medicaid program, however.\nUnder the California Medicaid program, pharmacists can bill for furnishing naloxone, self-administered hormonal contraception, vaccinations, nicotine replacement, human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) or post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP), travel medications and medication therapy management services.79", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the California Medicaid program.\nExpressly specify in California laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CPA are covered under the California Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "California law provides that a minor aged 16 or older can consent to OUD treatment “that uses buprenorphine at a physician's office, clinic, or health facility, by a licensed physician and surgeon or other health care provider acting within the scope of their practice, whether or not the minor also has the consent of their parent or guardian.” CAL. FAM. CODE § 6929.1 (West 2024).\nAs described in the the \"laws and regulations applying to non-pharmacists\" section, California has a series of laws governing the prescribing, dispensing, or administration of controlled substances to persons with SUD, including for purposes of treatment. These laws contain an express authorization for a pharmacist to administer a controlled substance to a person with SUD so long as the pharmacist is “acting under the direction of a physician and surgeon.” CAL. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE § 11215(b)(3) (West 2024). However, neither the California pharmacy laws addressing the scope of practice of pharmacists generally/APPs specifically nor the sample CPA for MOUD treatment drafted by the Board, expressly refer to the provisions described in the \"laws and regulations applying to non-pharmacists\" section. As a result, it is unclear how these provisions affect, or could affect, a pharmacist prescribing, administering, or otherwise providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "10B": "“A physician and surgeon may prescribe, dispense, or administer prescription drugs or prescription controlled substances to a person with substance use disorder for purposes of maintenance on, or detoxification from, prescription drugs or controlled substances only as set forth in subdivision (c) or in Sections 11215, 11217, 11217.5, 11218, 11219, and 11220 of the Health and Safety Code.” CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 2241(b) (West 2024).\nSubdivision (c) of § 2241 authorizes administration of controlled substances to a person with SUD “by a physician and surgeon, or by a registered nurse acting under their instruction and supervision” if it is done in accordance with § 11217.5. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE § 2241(c) (West 2024).\nSections 11215, 11217, 11217.5, 11218, 11219, and 11220 of the Health and Safety Code are found within California’s controlled substances act, in an article entitled “Treatment of Addicts for Addiction.” This article addresses who can administer a “narcotic controlled substance” to an individual with SUD, where such treatment may occur, and the amounts of certain controlled substances (not including buprenorphine) that can be prescribed or furnished. CAL. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE §§ 11215 to 11223 (West 2024).\nThere are California laws allowing physician assistants and nurse practitioners to administer, provide, and order buprenorphine so long as they do so in compliance with the Comprehensive Addiction Recovery Act (Public Law 114-198) enacted in 2016. CAL. BUS. & PROF. CODE §§ 2836.4, 3502.1.5 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (CURES)", "url": "https://oag.ca.gov/cures", "description": "The Controlled Substance Utilization Review and Evaluation System (CURES) is California's PDMP, operated by the Department of Justice. It tracks Schedule II-V controlled substance prescriptions dispensed in California."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CURES Registration and FAQs", "url": "https://oag.ca.gov/cures/faqs", "description": "Information on how pharmacists, prescribers, and other authorized users can register for CURES. Applicants must complete the online registration form and provide a valid email address, license number, and DEA registration number (when applicable)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://oag.ca.gov/cures", "description": "California Health and Safety Code Section 11165.4 sets forth requirements for mandatory consultation of CURES. Pharmacists and prescribers are required to consult CURES before dispensing or prescribing Schedule II-IV controlled substances, with limited exemptions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "California has restricted PMP InterConnect participation. As of 2023, California shares interstate data only with Oregon and the Veterans Health Administration. California's data sharing is more limited than most states due to state privacy law restrictions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://oag.ca.gov/cures/faqs", "description": "The DOJ has created a Quick Reference Guide detailing how to establish and activate a Delegate in CURES. Delegate eligibility and agreement requirements are described in DOJ's October 2022 bulletin on Expanded Delegate Access. See the FAQs page for detailed instructions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DCA CURES Update Page", "url": "https://www.dca.ca.gov/licensees/cures_update.shtml", "description": "The Department of Consumer Affairs page with the latest CURES updates, user guides for prescribers, pharmacists, and delegates, and contact information for the CURES helpdesk at CURES@doj.ca.gov or (916) 210-3187."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/", "description": "The California State Board of Pharmacy, under the Department of Consumer Affairs, protects and promotes public health through licensing, regulation, and enforcement of pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Law and Regulations", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/laws_regs/index.shtml", "description": "The Board of Pharmacy's laws and regulations page, with links to the California Pharmacy Practice Act (Business and Professions Code), California Code of Regulations Title 16, and related statutes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Lawbook (Full Text)", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/laws_regs/lawbook.pdf", "description": "The complete 2026 Lawbook for Pharmacy, containing excerpts from the Business and Professions Code and California Code of Regulations relevant to pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement (OUD Template)", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/licensees/collaborative_practice.pdf", "description": "Sample Collaborative Practice Agreement for pharmacist protocol for management of opioid use disorders, authorized under California Business and Professions Code Sections 4050-4052.2."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority (SB 493)", "url": "https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201320140SB493", "description": "SB 493 expanded pharmacist scope of practice in California, creating the Advanced Practice Pharmacist (APh) designation and authorizing pharmacists to furnish hormonal contraception, nicotine replacement products, HIV PrEP/PEP, and provide medication-assisted treatment pursuant to state protocol."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "California Opioid Response Treatment Locator", "url": "https://californiaopioidresponse.org/resources/find-treatment-and-services/", "description": "DHCS Opioid Response page with links to find treatment services, including the NTP Provider Directory, SAMHSA Treatment Locator, naloxone distribution resources, and syringe services programs across California."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "The federal Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA) treatment locator to find confidential and anonymous resources for substance use disorder treatment. Can be filtered by state and treatment type."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHCS SUD Directories", "url": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/provgovpart/Pages/sud-directories.aspx", "description": "The California Department of Health Care Services maintains directories of licensed and certified SUD facilities and programs, county alcohol and drug offices, and referral information. Please verify this link before publishing (DHCS site uses Incapsula protection)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prescribing After X-Waiver Removal", "url": "https://californiaopioidresponse.org/removal-of-x-waiver-requirement/", "description": "Information on the removal of the X-waiver requirement. All practitioners with a valid DEA registration including Schedule III authority may now prescribe buprenorphine for OUD, if permitted by applicable state law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing. The DEA's 2025 final rule allows practitioners to initiate buprenorphine prescribing via audio-only telehealth for up to 6 months, after which an audio-video or in-person visit is required."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Telehealth Resource Center - DEA Telehealth Rule", "url": "https://caltrc.org/blog/the-deas-new-telehealth-rule-what-practitioners-should-know/", "description": "California Telehealth Resource Center summary of the DEA's new telehealth rule for practitioners, including specific guidance on buprenorphine prescribing via telehealth."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Medi-Cal Rx Portal (Pharmacy Benefit)", "url": "https://www.medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/home/", "description": "The Medi-Cal Rx portal is California's Medicaid pharmacy benefit program, administered by DHCS. It provides information for providers, pharmacies, and members on prescription drug coverage."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medi-Cal Rx Contract Drug List", "url": "https://medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/home/cdl/", "description": "The Medi-Cal Rx Contract Drug List (CDL) is California's Medicaid preferred drug list. Buprenorphine products are listed. Providers can look up drugs and prior authorization requirements through the CDL portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medi-Cal Rates", "url": "https://mcweb.apps.prd.cammis.medi-cal.ca.gov/rates", "description": "Medi-Cal provider rates and fee schedules, including pharmacy reimbursement rates. Provides basic Medi-Cal rates and conversion factors for various provider types."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AB 1114 - Medi-Cal Pharmacist Services Billing", "url": "https://ncccp.net/advocacy/ab-1114-medi-cal-pharmacist-services/", "description": "Information about AB 1114, which established that the rate of reimbursement for pharmacist services shall be at 85 percent of the fee schedule for physician services under the Medi-Cal program and directed DHCS to establish a fee schedule for pharmacist services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California State Opioid Response (SOR) Grant Funding", "url": "https://www.grants.ca.gov/grants/hub-and-spoke-system-hss-sor-iv-request-for-applications-rfa/", "description": "California's SOR IV grant, funded by SAMHSA, supports DHCS Opioid Response projects including Hub and Spoke System programs, treatment access expansion, and harm reduction services. Applications available through the California Grants Portal."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/licensees/personal/ce.shtml", "description": "California pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE per renewal period (every two years). This must include a Board-provided law webinar, ethics webinar, and cultural competency CE. Advanced Practice Pharmacists must complete 10 additional hours (40 total). Pharmacists who prescribe Schedule II controlled substances must complete at least 1 hour of CE on addiction risks every 4 years."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Pharmacists Association (CPhA) Education", "url": "https://cpha.com/ce-events/on-demand-courses/", "description": "CPhA offers on-demand continuing education courses for pharmacists, including training programs required by the Board for furnishing hormonal contraception and other protocol-based services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/registration-faq.html", "description": "DEA registration information including the Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act requirements. All practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS-MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, podcasts, and clinical tools to enhance provider knowledge in evidence-based OUD treatment, including buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS 8-Hour DEA Training Options", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/medications-for-opioid-use-disorder/8-hour-moud-education-options/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD offers multiple training options that meet the 8-hour DEA MATE Act training requirements for practitioners prescribing controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs Directory", "url": "https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CID/DOA/pages/oa_prev_needle_exchange_syringe.aspx", "description": "California Department of Public Health (CDPH) directory of syringe services programs across California. Harm reduction programs provide essential safety net services including sterile syringes, naloxone, and overdose prevention education. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order and Access", "url": "https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CCDPHP/sapb/Pages/Naloxone-Standing-Order.aspx", "description": "Information on California's naloxone standing order. Over-the-counter naloxone nasal spray (NARCAN) no longer requires a standing order. Other naloxone formulations remain available by prescription or standing order. The standing order provides additional liability protections under CA Civil Code Section 1714.22."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution Project", "url": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/individuals/Pages/Naloxone_Distribution_Project.aspx", "description": "The DHCS Naloxone Distribution Project (NDP) provides free naloxone to organizations and individuals to reduce opioid overdose deaths across California. Please verify this link before publishing (DHCS uses Incapsula protection)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Information", "url": "https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CCDPHP/sapb/CDPH%20Document%20Library/FentanylTestStrips_FAQs.pdf", "description": "CDPH FAQ on fentanyl test strips. Fentanyl test strips are legal in California and available through harm reduction programs. California has made fentanyl test strips free to qualifying organizations through DHCS."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Overdose Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://skylab.cdph.ca.gov/ODdash/", "description": "The California Overdose Surveillance Dashboard provides state and county-level data on drug-related overdose deaths, emergency department visits, hospitalizations, and opioid prescription trends from 2008 to present."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Medi-Cal Peer Support Services", "url": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/services/Pages/Peer-Support-Services.aspx", "description": "DHCS page on Medi-Cal Peer Support Services. California recognizes certified Medi-Cal Peer Support Specialists as a provider type effective July 1, 2022. Contact CalMHSA at PeerCertification@CalMHSA.org for certification questions. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Certification (CalMHSA)", "url": "https://www.calmhsa.org/peer-certification/", "description": "California Mental Health Services Authority (CalMHSA) administers the Medi-Cal Peer Support Specialist certification program, including approved training vendors and the Stakeholder Advisory Council."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Association of Mental Health Peer-Run Organizations", "url": "https://www.californiapeers.org/peercertification", "description": "Information on peer certification requirements, CalMHSA-approved training programs, and resources for peer support specialists in California."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Residence Directory (CCAPP)", "url": "https://ccapprecoveryresidences.org/search/", "description": "The California Consortium of Addiction Programs and Professionals (CCAPP) maintains the state's certified recovery residence directory. CCAPP is the only organization recognized by DHCS for recovery residence certification in California."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHCS Behavioral Health Services", "url": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/services/Pages/Behavioral-Health-Services.aspx", "description": "The California Department of Health Care Services behavioral health division homepage, overseeing mental health and substance use disorder services statewide. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (California)", "url": "https://www.chhs.ca.gov/988california/", "description": "California's 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline page. Call or text 988 for support with suicidal, mental health, and substance use-related crises, available 24/7."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SUD County Access Lines", "url": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/individuals/Pages/sud_county_access_lines.aspx", "description": "DHCS directory of Substance Use Disorder county access lines for treatment referrals across all California counties. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Executive Officer", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/about/executive_staff.shtml", "description": "Anne Sodergren is the Executive Officer of the California State Board of Pharmacy. Main office phone: (916) 518-3100. Address: 2720 Gateway Oaks Drive, Suite 100, Sacramento, CA 95833."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact Page", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ca.gov/about/contact_us.shtml", "description": "Main contact page for the California State Board of Pharmacy. Phone: (916) 518-3100. Fax: (916) 574-8618. Inspectors available Monday-Thursday 9am-1pm for pharmacy law questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHCS Contact Information", "url": "https://www.dhcs.ca.gov/", "description": "The California Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) administers Medi-Cal and behavioral health services. Main phone: (916) 440-7800. DHCS serves as the state Medicaid agency and Single State Agency for substance use disorder services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://cpha.com/", "description": "CPhA is California's state pharmacy association, representing pharmacists across all practice settings. Contact Michelle Rivas, Executive Vice President of Government Relations, at mrivas@cpha.com for advocacy inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Department of Public Health - Opioid Program", "url": "https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CCDPHP/sapb/Pages/Data.aspx", "description": "The CDPH Overdose Prevention Initiative (OPI) tracks and shares data on drug-related overdoses, opioid prescriptions, and substance use behaviors through dashboards and data briefs."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "California Overdose Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://skylab.cdph.ca.gov/ODdash/", "description": "Interactive dashboard providing state, county, and zip code-level data on overdose deaths, emergency department visits, hospitalizations, and opioid prescriptions. Includes time trends, geographic distribution, and demographic breakdowns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDPH Overdose Data and Information", "url": "https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CCDPHP/opioids/Pages/Data.aspx", "description": "CDPH opioid data page reporting that close to 8,000 Californians died from opioid-related overdoses in 2023. Provides links to data briefs, reports, and surveillance tools."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDPH Substance Abuse Prevention Branch Data", "url": "https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CCDPHP/sapb/Pages/Data.aspx", "description": "The CDPH Substance and Addiction Prevention Branch data page, providing overdose prevention data, surveillance reports, and research publications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHCS Opioid Response Data and Reports", "url": "https://californiaopioidresponse.org/", "description": "The DHCS California Opioid Response website with information on current projects, treatment resources, data, and reports related to the state's opioid crisis response including the State Opioid Response (SOR) grant programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Hub and Spoke System", "url": "https://www.cahubandspoke.com/", "description": "Through regional Hub and Spoke Systems, DHCS aims to ensure highest quality evidence-based OUD services are available to Californians. Includes data on treatment access and outcomes across the state."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CPhA Current Legislation Tracker", "url": "https://cpha.com/advocacy/legislation/current-legislation/", "description": "The California Pharmacists Association tracks current legislation affecting pharmacy practice, including PBM reform (SB 41), pharmacist scope of practice bills, and other advocacy priorities. Contact mrivas@cpha.com for legislative questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Legislative Information", "url": "https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/", "description": "Official California Legislative Information website for tracking bills, searching California law codes, and monitoring legislative activity related to pharmacy practice and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Legislature - Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://www.legislature.ca.gov/your-legislators", "description": "Tool to find and contact your California state senators and assembly members by address. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "California Overdose Prevention Network (COPN)", "url": "https://nopn.org/california/about-copn", "description": "COPN is the largest overdose prevention network in the country, with 32 active coalitions representing 85% of California's population. Offers monthly webinars, workshops, and guided discussions on coalition building and overdose prevention strategies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHCS Opioid Response Projects", "url": "https://californiaopioidresponse.org/projects/current-projects/", "description": "Overview of current DHCS opioid response projects, including the Emergency Medical Services Buprenorphine Use Pilot Program (EMSBUP), Hub and Spoke System, California Overdose Prevention Network, and other state-funded initiatives."}]}]}, "colorado": {"name": "Colorado", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Colorado’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA), which is defined in two different ways depending on the type of collaborative practice. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-601 (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAlthough the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Colorado law includes pharmacists “exercising independent prescriptive authority” in certain situations, those situations do not include prescribing controlled substances outside of a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement (CPPA). COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-103(39)(g) (West 2024).\nAdditionally, in Colorado’s pharmacy laws, a “practitioner” is defined as a “person authorized by law to prescribe any drug or device” including pharmacists in some situations. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-103(40) (West 2024). However, these situations do not include prescribing controlled substances outside of a CPPA.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Colorado cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Colorado practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Colorado pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nAs of a new law first effective in August 2024, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Colorado law includes “dispensing or administering any FDA-approved product for opioid use disorder in accordance with federal law and regulations, including medications for opioid use disorder.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-103(39)(l) (West 2024).", "2B": "Colorado law does not expressly describe any requirements or training necessary to administer buprenorphine other than noting that a statewide drug therapy protocol or CPPA is not needed “if the prescribing, dispensing, or administering medication-assisted treatment is otherwise authorized under law.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(3) (West 2024). Presumably, the administration must be pursuant to a valid prescription or physician-approved protocol of some kind, although no such language is used in the new statutory provision.\nUnder the new law, the state medical board, state board of nursing, and state board of pharmacy “shall promulgate rules no later than May 1, 2025, developing a statewide drug therapy protocol for pharmacists to prescribe, dispense, and administer only federal drug enforcement administration schedule III, IV, and V FDA-approved products as medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorder.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(2)(a)\n(West 2024).These boards “shall consider requirements for training” as part of these regulations. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(2)(b) (West 2024). These rules could apply to a pharmacist administering buprenorphine in the absence of a CPPA.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below the authorization could be limited slightly.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Colorado law includes “ordering and evaluating laboratory tests as related to medication therapy.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-103(39)(h) (West 2024). Colorado pharmacy laws and regulations do not define or further explain the phrase “medication therapy.”", "3B": "Confirm that the lab test ordered or evaluated fits within the meaning of “as related to medication therapy.”", "3C": "Revise Colorado law and/or regulations to define or explain the phrase “as related to medication therapy.”\nIf necessary, expand the Colorado practice of pharmacy to expressly allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Based on the information described below, the answer is currently “no.” However, the answer may become “yes” in the future.\nAs of a law first effective in August 2024, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Colorado includes “exercising independent prescriptive authority” for any “FDA-approved product indicated for opioid use disorder in accordance with federal law and regulations, including medications for opioid use disorder, if authorized pursuant to [Colorado law related to CPPAs].” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-103(39)(g)(V) (West 2024). Although this new law theoretically allows a pharmacist to prescribe buprenorphine under a CPPA, there are practical obstacles that currently make the answer “no.”\nThis new law does not expressly authorize a Colorado pharmacist to obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPPA directs.\nHowever, under law this new law, the state medical board, state board of nursing, and state board of pharmacy “shall promulgate rules no later than May 1, 2025, developing a statewide drug therapy protocol for pharmacists to prescribe, dispense, and administer only federal drug enforcement administration schedule III, IV, and V FDA-approved products as medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorder.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(2)(a) (West 2024). Such future regulations could address the issue noted above and provide a mechanism for a pharmacist to obtain state/DEA controlled substances registrations and prescribe controlled substances.", "4B": null, "4C": "Include within the regulations due by May 2025 a process for pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe buprenorphine under a CPPA or statewide protocol.\nExpressly specify in the regulations due by May 2025 how prescriptions for buprenorphine work under CPPAs or a statewide protocol.", "5A": "Based on the information described below, the answer is currently “no,” but will be “yes” once Colorado adopts implementing regulations.\nThere are two types of CPPAs under Colorado law: (1) a “statewide protocol” issued jointly by several regulatory bodies; and (2) a specific agreement between a pharmacist and one or more physicians or advance practice registered nurses. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-601 (West 2024).\nUnder a law first effective in August 2024, the state medical board, state board of nursing, and state board of pharmacy “shall promulgate rules no later than May 1, 2025, developing a statewide drug therapy protocol for pharmacists to prescribe, dispense, and administer only federal drug enforcement administration schedule III, IV, and V FDA-approved products as medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorder.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(2)(a) (West 2024). Therefore, whenever these regulations take effect, the answer will be “yes” with respect to the statewide protocol CPPA option.\nUnder a specific CPPA, a pharmacist can perform “evidence-based healthcare services.” 3 COLO. CODE REGS. § 719-1:17.00.10(c) (2024). The Colorado regulation spells out what such services entail, which include “medication management and monitoring.” However, the regulation does not use the word “administer.” As a result, it is unclear if a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a specific CPPA.", "5B": "Await adoption of regulations describing the process for administering buprenorphine under a statewide protocol.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Adopt regulations describing the process for administering buprenorphine under a statewide protocol.\nExpressly specify in Colorado laws and/or regulations governing specific CPPAs (as opposed to statewide protocols) that “evidence-based healthcare services” includes administering drugs, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below the authorization could be limited slightly There are two types of CPPAs under Colorado law: (1) a “statewide protocol” issued jointly by several regulatory bodies; and (2) a specific agreement between a pharmacist and one or more physicians or advance practice registered nurses. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-601 (West 2024).\nUnder the new law first effective in August 2024, the state medical board, state board of nursing, and state board of pharmacy “shall promulgate rules no later than May 1, 2025, developing a statewide drug therapy protocol for pharmacists to prescribe, dispense, and administer only federal drug enforcement administration schedule III, IV, and V FDA-approved products as medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorder.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(2)(a) (West 2024).\nIn developing this statewide drug therapy protocol, the boards “shall consider . . . lab screening and testing.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-604(2)(b) (West 2024).\nBecause this provision uses the word “consider” and not “include,” it is not completely clear if the final statewide protocol will address lab screening and testing.\nAlternatively, under a specific CPPA, a pharmacist can perform “evidence-based healthcare services.” 3 COLO. CODE REGS. § 719-1:17.00.10(c) (2024). Colorado regulation spells out what such services entail but the language does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. However, Colorado regulations do provide that “collaborative drug therapy management” (CDTM) is a CPPA “involving a higher level of disease complexity and/or decision making,” CDTM may include “ordering and evaluating the results of laboratory tests directly, related to management of the drug therapy.” 3 COLO. CODE REGS. § 719-1:17.00.70(e) (2024).\nSummarizing the four bullet points just above: (1) regulations that may address ordering/evaluating lab tests as part of a statewide protocol for buprenorphine do not exist yet and, when implemented, do not have to address it;\n(2) it is unclear if a pharmacist can order lab tests and/or evaluate the results under all specific CPPAs; but (3) ordering and evaluating lab tests directly related to a CPPA that covers CDTM is allowed.\nMoreover, per the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the practice of pharmacy in general includes “ordering and evaluating laboratory tests as related to medication therapy.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-103(39)(h)\n(West 2024). Colorado pharmacy laws and regulations do not define or further explain the phrase “as related to medication therapy” and thus whether this phrase acts as a limitation is unclear.", "6B": "Confirm that the lab test being ordered or evaluated fits within the meaning of “as related to medication therapy” in the practice of pharmacy or is directly related to a CDTM CPPA.\nEnter into CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "As part of the upcoming regulations covering the process for prescribing and administering buprenorphine under a statewide protocol, expressly include a provision that pharmacists may order lab tests and evaluate the results.\nExpressly specify in Colorado regulations governing specific CPPAs that “evidence-based healthcare services” includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Colorado law defines CPPA two different ways (intentionally).\nFirst, a CPPA can refer to a written and signed agreement entered into voluntarily between one or more pharmacists and one or more physicians or advanced practice registered nurses. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-601(1)(a) (West 2024).\nSecond, a CPPA may also refer to a statewide drug therapy protocol developed by the state board of pharmacy, the state medical board, and the state board of nursing in collaboration with the state department of public health and environment for public health-care service. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-601(1)(b) (West 2024).\nThe following Colorado laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPPAs and required elements of CPPAs – COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 12-280-601 to 12-280-604 (West 2024); 3 COLO. CODE REGS. § 719-1:17.00.00 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nColorado does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, Colorado insurance law provides that “it is the intent of the general assembly to recognize the practice of telehealth as a legitimate means by which an individual may receive health-care services from a provider without in-person contact with the provider.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 10-16-123(1) (West 2024).\n“Provider” mean “any physician, dentist, optometrist, anesthesiologist, hospital, X ray, laboratory and ambulance service, or other person who is licensed or otherwise authorized in this state to furnish health-care service.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 10-16-102(56) (West 2024). The ending clause of this provision covers pharmacists.\n“Health-care services” expressly includes providing services for SUD. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 10-16-102(33) (West 2024).", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Colorado laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Colorado laws and regulations governing telehealth include – COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 10-16-102, 10-16-123 (West 2024) (insurance); COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-30-124 (West 2024) (out of state providers); COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-240-104(6) (West 2024) (physicians); COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 12-280-107 (West 2024) (telepharmacy); COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 25.5-5-414 (West 2024) (Medicaid); 3 COLO. CODE REGS. § 719-1:31.00.00 (2024)\n(telepharmacy).", "9A": "“Medically necessary services authorized in [Colorado collaborative pharmacy practice law] that are not duplicative of other pharmacist services or programs reimbursed under the [Colorado Medicaid] program.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 25.5-5-511(2)(a) (West 2024).\nA pharmacist or pharmacy that dispenses or administers extended-release injectable medications for mental health or SUD treatment may seek reimbursement for those medications under the Colorado Medicaid program “either as a pharmacy benefit or as a medical benefit.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 25.5–5–512(2) (West 2024).\nA pharmacist or pharmacy that dispenses or administers vaccinations to children under age 19 pursuant to CDC guidelines may seek reimbursement for the dispensing or administration of vaccines under the Colorado Medicaid program “either as a pharmacy benefit or as a medical benefit.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 25.5–5–515(2) (West 2024).\nAs of August 2024, a pharmacist is eligible for reimbursement from the Colorado Medicaid program “for prescribing or administering medications for an opioid use disorder, if the pharmacist is authorized pursuant to [Colorado pharmacy law], at a rate equal to the reimbursement provided to a physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse for the same services.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 25.5–5–512.5(2) (West 2024).\nUnder Colorado insurance laws generally, “any health benefit plan, except supplemental policies covering a specified disease or other limited benefit, that provides hospital, surgical, or medical expense insurance may provide coverage for health-care services under a specific treatment protocol provided by a pharmacist” if the pharmacist meets the conditions specified in statute. COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 10-16-144(1) (West 2024).\nMoreover, a health benefit plan that provides coverage for SUD treatment “shall reimburse a licensed pharmacist acting within the licensed pharmacist’s scope of practice, and in accordance with the requirements in [Colorado collaborative practice law], for the provision of medication-assisted treatment services if the health benefit plan provides coverage for the same services provided by a licensed physician or an advanced practice registered nurse.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 10-16-144(3)(a) (West 2024) as enacted by 2024 COLO. LEGIS. CH. 470, § 2 (West).83", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "As of August 2024, pharmacists and pharmacies are eligible to obtain grants from the “medication-assisted treatment expansion pilot program” to obtain “the training and ongoing support required to prescribe medications, such as buprenorphine and all other medications and therapies approved by [FDA] to treat opioid use disorders.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 23-21-802(1)(h)(1) (West 2024).\nAdditional information about the pilot program is located here - COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 23-21-801 to 23-21-809 (West 2024).", "10B": "A physician “upon consultation by a minor as a patient, with the consent of such minor patient, may examine, prescribe for, and treat the minor patient for use of drugs or a substance use disorder without the consent of or notification to the parent, parents, or legal guardian of the minor patient, or to any other person having custody or decision-making responsibility with respect to the medical care of the minor patient.” COLO. REV. STAT. ANN. § 13-22-102 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/PDMP", "description": "The Colorado Prescription Drug Monitoring Program (PDMP), operated by the Division of Professions and Occupations (DPO) under DORA, helps reduce prescription drug misuse, abuse, and diversion. Contact: 303-894-5957 or pdmpinqr@state.co.us."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Login and Registration", "url": "https://colorado.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "The CO PDMP AWARE login portal where pharmacists and prescribers can access the system. New users can create an account. Support: 855-263-6403. Located at 1560 Broadway Ste. 1350, Denver, CO 80202."}, {"type": "link", "title": "About the PDMP", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/PDMP/About", "description": "Overview of the Colorado PDMP, including its role in helping prescribers and dispensers make informed decisions about controlled substances. PDMP enrollment is required for prescribers and dispensers. Data reporting is daily, no later than the next business day, for Schedules II-V."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "Colorado participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing. Colorado is included in the national network of states sharing PDMP data across state lines through the NABP PMP InterConnect system."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/PDMP", "description": "Information about delegate access and registration for the Colorado PDMP is available through the PDMP homepage, including training materials and forms. Contact the PDMP helpdesk at 855-263-6403 for assistance."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy", "description": "The Colorado State Board of Pharmacy, part of the Division of Professions and Occupations under the Department of Regulatory Agencies (DORA). Contact: 303-894-7800, Fax: 303-894-7693, Email: dora_dpo_licensing@state.co.us. Located at 1560 Broadway, Suite 1350, Denver, CO 80202."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Laws", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy/Laws", "description": "Colorado Pharmacy Practice Act (Pharmacists, Pharmacy Businesses, and Pharmaceuticals Practice Act) and Uniform Controlled Substances Act full text."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Laws, Rules, and Policies", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy/LawsRulesPolicies", "description": "Comprehensive page for all pharmacy laws, rules, regulations, and board policies governing pharmacy practice in Colorado."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements and Statewide Protocols", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy/Protocols", "description": "Information about Colorado pharmacy collaborative agreements, found in Pharmacy Rule 17, and statewide drug therapy protocols including the MOUD protocol for opioid use disorder treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority - MOUD Statewide Protocol", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy/PrescriptiveAuthorityTable", "description": "Colorado's Prescriptive/Drug Procurement Authority Table. Pharmacists may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD under the statewide protocol (Appendix G, 3 CCR 719-1). Pharmacists must obtain a Pharmacist MOUD authority credential and a DEA license to prescribe buprenorphine."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statewide MOUD Protocol (Appendix G)", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/colorado/3-CCR-719-1-app-G", "description": "The Colorado State Board of Pharmacy Statewide Protocol for Medications for Opioid Use Disorder, authorized under CRS 12-280-604. Allows qualified, Colorado-licensed pharmacists to assess patients with OUD and prescribe buprenorphine."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Colorado BHA Opioid Treatment Programs", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/behavioral-health/opioid-treatment-programs", "description": "The Colorado Behavioral Health Administration (BHA) page on opioid treatment programs (OTPs) that provide medications for opioid use disorder, including methadone, buprenorphine, and naltrexone. Includes links to SAMHSA's buprenorphine provider locator."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "Federal treatment locator to find substance use disorder treatment providers, filterable by state and treatment type including buprenorphine/medication-assisted treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHA Get Help Page", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/help/get-help-mental-health-drugs-or-alcohol", "description": "Colorado Behavioral Health Administration's resource page for individuals seeking help for mental health, drug, or alcohol concerns, including OUD treatment options and opioid replacement therapies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prescribing (Post X-Waiver)", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA guidance on buprenorphine prescribing after removal of the X-waiver requirement. All DEA-registered practitioners with Schedule III authority can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing, including the DEA's 2025 final rule allowing audio-only telehealth initiation of buprenorphine for up to 6 months."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Health First Colorado Pharmacy Benefits", "url": "https://hcpf.colorado.gov/pharmacy-benefits", "description": "Colorado's Medicaid program (Health First Colorado) pharmacy benefit information. Most drugs in the Preferred column of the Preferred Drug List do not require prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Resources (HCPF)", "url": "https://hcpf.colorado.gov/pharmacy-resources", "description": "Colorado Department of Health Care Policy and Financing pharmacy resources, including the Pharmaceutical Benefit Help Guide and prior authorization requirements for Health First Colorado members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List (January 2026)", "url": "https://hcpf.colorado.gov/sites/hcpf/files/01-01-26%20PDL%20V1.pdf", "description": "Colorado Medicaid (Health First Colorado) Preferred Drug List effective January 1, 2026. Buprenorphine products are included; preferred products generally do not require prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medi-Cal Pharmacist Services Billing Model", "url": "https://hcpf.colorado.gov/pharmacy-resources", "description": "Colorado Medicaid pharmacist services billing information is available through the HCPF pharmacy resources page. Colorado covers buprenorphine as a pharmacy benefit under Medicaid."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grant opportunities for states including Colorado. Funds support FDA-approved MOUD, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery support services."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Pharmacy CE Requirements", "url": "https://cpsconferences.com/", "description": "Colorado requires pharmacists to complete 24 hours of ACPE-approved continuing education every two years. The Colorado Pharmacists Society offers regularly scheduled ACPE-approved CE programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Pharmacists Society Education", "url": "https://copharm.memberclicks.net/education-and-development", "description": "CPS education and development resources for pharmacists. Address: 303 E 17th Ave, Suite 400, Denver, CO 80203. Email: info@copharm.org. Phone: (720) 250-9585."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Pharmacists Society Homepage", "url": "https://www.copharm.org/", "description": "CPS supports professional development of pharmacists, technicians, and student pharmacists through continuing education opportunities including the Annual Meeting, Winter Meeting, and quarterly webinars."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/registration-faq.html", "description": "DEA registration information including the 8-hour MATE Act training requirement for substance use disorders, required for all practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS-MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Free Provider Clinical Support System training on medications for opioid use disorders, including buprenorphine. Offers modules, webinars, podcasts, and clinical tools that meet DEA MATE Act requirements."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Prevention (CDPHE)", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/overdose-prevention", "description": "Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment overdose prevention program page, with links to syringe access programs, naloxone standing orders, overdose data surveillance, and prevention initiatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Orders", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/overdose-prevention/naloxone-standing-orders", "description": "Information on Colorado's naloxone standing orders. Pharmacies, law enforcement, local public health agencies, and harm reduction organizations can establish standing orders to distribute naloxone to those at risk of overdose."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Naloxone Standing Orders", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy/Naloxone", "description": "Colorado Board of Pharmacy page on naloxone standing orders for pharmacists. Allows pharmacists and harm reduction organizations to provide naloxone to family members, friends, and anyone in a position to assist a person at risk of overdose."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stop the Clock Colorado (Naloxone Locator)", "url": "https://www.stoptheclockcolorado.org/", "description": "Colorado's interactive map to find the nearest naloxone in an emergency. Provides harm reduction resources and information about naloxone access, syringe services, and overdose prevention."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/registries-and-vital-statistics/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system-sudors/colorado", "description": "Colorado drug overdose statistics dashboard from CDPHE's State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS), providing data on circumstances of death and substances involved in overdoses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strips", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/overdose-prevention", "description": "Fentanyl test strips are legal in Colorado. They are available through harm reduction programs and syringe access programs. Information on fentanyl test strip access is available through CDPHE's overdose prevention page."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "BHA Recovery Support Services", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/behavioral-health/recovery", "description": "Colorado Behavioral Health Administration recovery support services page, including information on recovery community organizations, peer support, Oxford House sober living environments (100+ in Colorado), and a directory of certified recovery residences. Please verify this link before publishing (BHA may restrict access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Crisis Services", "url": "https://coloradocrisisservices.org/", "description": "Free, confidential, and immediate support for mental health, substance use, and emotional concerns, available 24/7/365. Call 844-493-TALK (8255) or text TALK to 38255."}, {"type": "link", "title": "988 in Colorado", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/988", "description": "Starting July 1, 2025, calls to the Colorado Crisis Services line are connected to the 988 Colorado Mental Health Line. Call or text 988 for support with suicidal, mental health, and substance use-related crises."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health Administration Homepage", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/", "description": "The Colorado BHA is the state administration responsible for ensuring all people in Colorado have access to quality mental health and substance use disorder services, regardless of where they live or ability to pay."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHA Peer Support and Workforce", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/behavioral-health/recovery", "description": "Information on Colorado peer recovery support specialists, certification, and workforce development through the BHA recovery support services program."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/Pharmacy", "description": "Colorado State Board of Pharmacy, Division of Professions and Occupations. Phone: 303-894-7800. Fax: 303-894-7693. Email: dora_dpo_licensing@state.co.us. 1560 Broadway, Suite 1350, Denver, CO 80202."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Contact", "url": "https://dpo.colorado.gov/PDMP", "description": "Colorado PDMP. Phone: 303-894-5957. Fax: 303-894-0133. Email: pdmpinqr@state.co.us. Helpdesk: 855-263-6403."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Pharmacists Society", "url": "https://www.copharm.org/", "description": "CPS is Colorado's state pharmacy association. Address: 303 E 17th Ave, Suite 400, Denver, CO 80203. Email: info@copharm.org. Phone: (720) 250-9585."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health Administration", "url": "https://bha.colorado.gov/", "description": "Colorado BHA oversees mental health and substance use disorder services statewide and serves as the state's behavioral health authority."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDPHE Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/overdose-prevention", "description": "Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment overdose prevention program. Leads surveillance of the drug overdose epidemic and coordinates with DORA on PDMP improvements."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Drug Overdose Statistics Dashboard", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/registries-and-vital-statistics/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system-sudors/colorado", "description": "Interactive dashboard providing drug overdose death data, including circumstances of death and substances involved, from coroner and medical examiner reports. Includes county-level data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS)", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/center-for-health-and-environmental-data/registries-and-vital-statistics/state-unintentional-drug", "description": "SUDORS collects data on unintentional drug overdose deaths and deaths of undetermined intent in Colorado from multiple data sources including death certificates and coroner reports."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Health Institute Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://www.coloradohealthinstitute.org/research/2020overdose_dashboard", "description": "Independent analysis of Colorado overdose data including trends in fentanyl fatalities and year-over-year comparisons of drug overdose deaths."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDPHE Overdose Prevention Data", "url": "https://cdphe.colorado.gov/overdose-prevention", "description": "CDPHE uses existing data to inform evidence-based public health approaches to prevent opioid misuse and overdose, partnering with organizations across the state for local prevention initiatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Consortium Data and Reports", "url": "https://corxconsortium.org/", "description": "The Colorado Consortium for Prescription Drug Abuse Prevention coordinates statewide response data and reports through its 10 workgroups addressing various aspects of the opioid crisis."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Pharmacists Society Advocacy", "url": "https://www.copharm.org/", "description": "CPS advocacy information for pharmacists, including legislative priorities and professional development. CPS works to advance pharmacy practice and advocate for pharmacist scope of practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado General Assembly - Find My Legislator", "url": "https://leg.colorado.gov/find-my-legislator", "description": "Tool to search for and contact Colorado state representatives and senators by district number, name, or address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado Consortium for Prescription Drug Abuse Prevention", "url": "https://corxconsortium.org/", "description": "Statewide coalition coordinating Colorado's response to the opioid crisis. Established in 2013, the Consortium includes federal agencies, state departments (CDPHE, BHA), and dozens of grassroots organizations. Administered by the CU Skaggs School of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colorado General Assembly Opioid Legislation", "url": "https://leg.colorado.gov/", "description": "Colorado General Assembly website for tracking current legislation related to pharmacy practice, opioid treatment, harm reduction, and substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Statute (CRS 12-280-604)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/colorado/title-12/health-care-professions-and-occupations/article-280/part-6/section-12-280-604/", "description": "Colorado statute authorizing collaborative pharmacy practice agreements and statewide drug therapy protocols for medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorder, enabling pharmacist prescribing of buprenorphine."}]}]}, "connecticut": {"name": "Connecticut", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Connecticut uses three terms—\"collaborative drug therapy management agreement,” “collaborative drug therapy management policy,” and “collaborative drug therapy care plan” (collectively, CDTMA/P/CP)—to collectively embody CPA activities. CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631(a) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Connecticut law refers only to “the distributing, dispensing and use of drugs and devices.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-571(30) (West 2024).\nAlthough not in the practice of pharmacy definition, Connecticut pharmacists can prescribe opioid antagonists, epinephrine injectors, and certain HIV prophylaxis medications.\nAlso, pharmacists are ineligible to obtain a state controlled substance registration for prescribing controlled substances, as pharmacists are not included in the definition of “practitioner” under the Connecticut statutory provisions for controlled substance registration. CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 21a-316 (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Connecticut cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Connecticut practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Connecticut pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Connecticut law refers only to “the distributing, dispensing and use of drugs and devices.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-571(30) (West 2024). The definition does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nAlthough administration is not addressed in the practice of pharmacy definition, Connecticut pharmacists can administer certain vaccines and “epinephrine cartridge injectors.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-633 (West 2024).\nThis is the only express reference to administering drugs or medications in Connecticut pharmacy laws outside of collaborative drug therapy management agreement, collaborative drug therapy management policy, and collaborative drug therapy care plan (collectively, CDTMA/P/CP).", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Connecticut practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Connecticut law refers only to “the distributing, dispensing and use of drugs and devices.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-571(30) (West 2024). The definition does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nHowever, a separate Connecticut law provides that a pharmacist may order and administer COVID-19 related tests, influenza-related tests, and HIV-related tests. CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-633f (West 2024), as enacted by 2024 CONN. ACTS. 24-73, § 10 (West).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Connecticut to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nA pharmacist can “initiate, modify, continue, discontinue or deprescribe a drug therapy” as part of a collaborative drug therapy management agreement, collaborative drug therapy management policy, and collaborative drug therapy care plan (collectively, CDTMA/P/CP). CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631(c) (West 2023). Connecticut regulations make clear that “initiate, modify, continue, discontinue or deprescribe a drug therapy” includes making “prescriptive authority decisions.” CONN. AGENCIES REGS. § 20-631-2(1) (2024).\nHowever, Connecticut law and regulations do not expressly specify whether the pharmacist’s prescriptive authority under a CDTMA/P/CP includes controlled substances.\nMoreover, Connecticut laws and regulations governing CDTMA/P/CP does not account for the fact that a Connecticut pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CDTMA/P/CP directs.\nIn summary, Connecticut laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing drugs under a CDTMA/P/CP. Even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, however, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Connecticut pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Connecticut laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CDTMA/P/CPs.\nExpressly specify in Connecticut laws and regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CDTMA/P/CPs.\nAllow Connecticut pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nA pharmacist can “administer drugs” if it is authorized as part of a CDTMA/P/CP. CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631(c) (West 2024).\nThe only limitation expressly placed on this authorization is that a CDTMA/P/CP cannot authorize a pharmacist “to establish a port to administer parenteral drugs.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631(c) (West 2024).", "5B": "Enter into CDTMA/P/CP (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization only applies to ordering lab tests.\nA CDTMA/P/CP may authorize a pharmacist to “order associated laboratory tests.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631(c) (West 2024).\nHowever, Connecticut laws and regulations governing CDTMA/P/CP do not expressly authorize a pharmacist to evaluate test results.", "6B": "Enter into CDTMA/P/CP (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Connecticut laws and/or regulations that under CDTMA/P/CP, a pharmacist can evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "“One or more” qualified pharmacists can enter into a CDTMA/P/CP with “one or more” prescribing practitioners. CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631(a)(3), (4), (5) (West 2024).\nA prescribing practitioner is “an individual licensed by the state of Connecticut, any other state of the United States, the District of Columbia, the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico or any territory or insular possession subject to the jurisdiction of the United States who is authorized to issue a prescription within the scope of the individual’s practice.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-571(31) (West 2024).\nThe following Connecticut laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CDTMA/P/CPs and required elements of CDTMA/P/CPs – CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 20-631 (West 2024); CONN. AGENCIES REGS. §§ 20-631-1 to 20-631-3 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but note the restriction related to controlled substance prescribing (see the telehealth provisions related to buprenorphine section).\nUnder Connecticut’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law, pharmacists are one of the types of providers expressly authorized to provide “health care or other health services through the use of telehealth within such person’s scope of practice and in accordance with the standard of care applicable to the profession.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 19a-906(12) (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "Generally, “no telehealth provider shall prescribe any schedule I, II or III controlled substance through the use of telehealth.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 19a-906(c) (West 2024).\nHowever, the prohibition just above does not apply to the prescribing of “a schedule II or III controlled substance other than an opioid drug, as defined in section 20-14o, in a manner fully consistent with the Ryan Haight Online Pharmacy Consumer Protection Act, 21 USC 829(e), as amended from time to time, for the treatment of a person with a psychiatric disability or substance use disorder, as defined in section 17a-458, including, but not limited to, medication-assisted treatment.” CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 19a-906(c) (West 2024). Whether this provision allows for prescribing buprenorphine via telehealth is unclear, as Connecticut law defines the word “opioid drug” by referring to federal opioid treatment program regulations, but the 2024 changes to those federal regulations eliminated the defined term “opioid drug.”\nConnecticut laws governing telehealth include – CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 19a-906 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 17b-245g (West 2024) (Medicaid); CONN. GEN. STAT. ANN. §§ 38a-499a, 38a-526a (West 2024) (insurance).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Connecticut Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Connecticut laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CDTMA/P/CPs are covered under the Connecticut Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (CPMRS)", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/prescription-monitoring-program/prescription-monitoring-program", "description": "The Connecticut Prescription Monitoring and Reporting System (CPMRS) collects prescription data for Schedule II-V drugs. Operated by the Department of Consumer Protection (DCP). Connecticut allows interstate data sharing via PMP InterConnect and RxCheck."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CPMRS Login", "url": "https://connecticut.pmpaware.net", "description": "Login portal for the Connecticut Prescription Monitoring and Reporting System. Prescribers and pharmacists can access patient controlled substance prescription histories."}, {"type": "link", "title": "How to Register", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/prescription-monitoring-program/how-to-register", "description": "All prescribers possessing a CT controlled substance registration and pharmacists must register as users with the CPMRS. Registration instructions and requirements are detailed on this page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Information", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/prescription-monitoring-program/pharmacist-information", "description": "CPMRS information specific to pharmacists, including requirements and updates. As of October 1, 2019, a pharmacist's authorized pharmacy technician may register for a CPMRS user account."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate/Designee Registration", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/DCP/drug_control/PMP/pdf/CPMRSRegPolicyandProceduresManual112016pdf.pdf", "description": "CPMRS registration policy and procedures manual with details on delegate account registration and access requirements."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Commission of Pharmacy", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/drug-control-division/commission-of-pharmacy/the-commission-of-pharmacy", "description": "The Connecticut Commission of Pharmacy operates within the Department of Consumer Protection. Consists of seven Governor-appointed members with jurisdiction over pharmacy practice, approving licensure and registration of pharmacies, pharmacists, and interns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Control Division", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/agency-administration/division-home-pages/drug-control-division", "description": "Connecticut DCP Drug Control Division homepage with information on drug scheduling, pharmacy regulations, licensing, and updates including fentanyl test strip exemptions from drug paraphernalia laws."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Chapter 400j)", "url": "https://www.cga.ct.gov/current/pub/chap_400j.htm", "description": "Connecticut General Statutes Chapter 400j governing pharmacy practice, including collaborative drug therapy management agreements between pharmacists and physicians or advanced practice registered nurses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Drug Therapy Management", "url": "https://www.cga.ct.gov/current/pub/chap_400j.htm", "description": "Section 20-631 of the Connecticut General Statutes authorizes collaborative drug management agreements between pharmacists employed by community pharmacies and one or more physicians or advanced practice registered nurses. Section 20-631b addresses agreements entered into prior to October 1, 2010."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/dcp/drug_control/commission/rph-ce-requirement.pdf", "description": "Connecticut requires pharmacists to complete 15 continuing education credits per calendar year (January 1 through December 31). Five of the 15 CE credits must be in a live format and 1 must be in pharmacy law."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Opioid Services", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas/programs-and-services/opioid-treatment/opioid-services", "description": "The Connecticut Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services (DMHAS) opioid services page. The 24/7 Access Line, operated by Wheeler and funded by DMHAS, facilitates access to substance use services for Connecticut residents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Opioid Treatment Programs", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas/programs-and-services/opioid-treatment/opioid-treatment-programs", "description": "List of methadone treatment programs and opioid treatment programs in Connecticut providing medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "Federal treatment locator to find substance use disorder treatment providers including buprenorphine prescribers. Can be filtered by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT Clearinghouse Treatment Facility Locator", "url": "https://www.ctclearinghouse.org/find-help/treatment-facility-locator/", "description": "Links to statewide and national treatment facility locators, hotlines, and warm lines. Call the DMHAS Action Line at 1-800-HOPE-135 (1-800-467-3135) or 211 for referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing, including the DEA's 2025 final rule allowing audio-only telehealth initiation of buprenorphine for up to 6 months."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "HUSKY Health Pharmacy Benefits", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/HUSKY/Pharmacy", "description": "Connecticut Medicaid (HUSKY Health) pharmacy benefit information. HUSKY A, C, and D members do not have to pay for their medications. Provides details on covered and excluded drug types."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.ctdssmap.com/ctportal/portals/0/staticcontent/publications/ct_pdl_medicaid.pdf", "description": "The Connecticut Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL), a listing of prescription products recommended by the Department of Social Services (DSS) Pharmaceutical and Therapeutics Committee as efficacious, safe, and cost effective choices for HUSKY A, C, D, and EMDS patients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT DSS Pharmacy Information Portal", "url": "https://www.ctdssmap.com/CTPortal/PharmacyInformation/tabid/65/Default.aspx", "description": "Connecticut Medicaid pharmacy information portal with preferred drug lists, prior authorization requirements, and formulary details. Most FDA-approved drugs not on the PDL are available with prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "HUSKY Health Medical Management", "url": "https://www.huskyhealthct.org/providers/medical-management.html", "description": "Information on medical management including the Connecticut Medicaid PDL and prior authorization procedures for pharmacy benefits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grant opportunities available to states including Connecticut. Connecticut reimbursement of OUD treatment is supported through Medicaid and DMHAS grants."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CT Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/dcp/drug_control/commission/rph-ce-requirement.pdf", "description": "Connecticut requires 15 CE credits per calendar year. Five credits must be in a live format, and 1 credit must be in pharmacy law. Contact the Commission of Pharmacy at (860) 713-6070 for questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Connecticut Pharmacists Association CE", "url": "https://ctpharmacists.org/events-and-ce/continuing-education/", "description": "CPA continuing education programs and resources. Connecticut requires 15 hours of CE annually, with 5 in live format and 1 in law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/registration-faq.html", "description": "DEA registration information including the 8-hour MATE Act training requirement on substance use disorders for all practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS-MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders. Free training modules, webinars, and clinical tools meeting DEA MATE Act requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS 8-Hour DEA Training Options", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/medications-for-opioid-use-disorder/8-hour-moud-education-options/", "description": "Multiple training options meeting the 8-hour DEA MATE Act education requirements for practitioners prescribing controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Naloxone Information", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/DMHAS/Programs-and-Services/Opioid-Treatment/Naloxone", "description": "Connecticut DMHAS naloxone resources including DPH-supported mobile vans offering Specialized Syringe Programs for needle exchange that also offer naloxone and training. Harm reduction programs may also offer free naloxone and training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/DMHAS/Programs-and-Services/Opioid-Treatment/Naloxone", "description": "Connecticut does not maintain a traditional statewide standing order for naloxone dispensing. Pharmacists can furnish naloxone under specific state laws. Over-the-counter naloxone (NARCAN nasal spray) is available without a prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/agency-administration/division-home-pages/drug-control-division", "description": "Connecticut excludes certain test types and uses from being classified as drug paraphernalia, including fentanyl test strips. This makes fentanyl test strips legal to possess and distribute in the state. Information available through the DCP Drug Control Division."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT DPH Overdose Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dph/health-education-management--surveillance/the-office-of-injury-prevention/opioid-and-drug-overdose-statistics", "description": "Connecticut DPH interactive dashboard showcasing data from the State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS) on drug overdose deaths to increase public awareness."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/DMHAS/Programs-and-Services/Opioid-Treatment/Naloxone", "description": "Connecticut operates DPH-supported mobile vans offering Specialized Syringe Programs for needle exchange. These programs also provide naloxone, fentanyl test strips, and harm reduction education. Contact DMHAS for program locations."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Recovery Community Affairs", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/DMHAS/Divisions/Divisions/Recovery-Community-Affairs", "description": "DMHAS Recovery Community Affairs division provides information on initiatives, services, and resources offered by DMHAS and DMHAS-funded agencies throughout Connecticut."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Peer Support Specialist Information", "url": "https://copelandcenter.com/peer-specialists/connecticut", "description": "Connecticut's DMHAS approves training vendors for peer support specialists. Each approved training site must address core competencies, principles, and code of ethics. Contact Advocacy Unlimited at (860) 505-7581 for information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing and Support", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas", "description": "DMHAS coordinates recovery housing and support services across Connecticut. In January 2025, Connecticut announced a $58.6 million investment to create programs providing stable housing and recovery support for residents with OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Connecticut DMHAS Homepage", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas", "description": "The Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services is Connecticut's state behavioral health agency, overseeing mental health and substance use disorder services. LiveLOUD initiative connects people to treatment and recovery resources. Call 1-800-563-4086 or visit liveloud.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT 211 Resource Line", "url": "https://uwc.211ct.org/", "description": "Connecticut 211 provides referrals to substance use treatment options, including MAT, naloxone access, and recovery support services. Call 211 for immediate assistance."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Commission of Pharmacy", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/drug-control-division/commission-of-pharmacy/the-commission-of-pharmacy", "description": "Connecticut Commission of Pharmacy, Department of Consumer Protection. Phone: (860) 713-6070. Responsible for pharmacy practice regulation, licensure, and enforcement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Contact", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas", "description": "Connecticut Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services. DMHAS Action Line: 1-800-HOPE-135 (1-800-467-3135). DMHAS serves as the State Opioid Treatment Authority."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Connecticut Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://ctpharmacists.org/", "description": "CPA is the primary voice for Connecticut's pharmacy profession, representing pharmacists in all practice settings. Offers advocacy, continuing education, and professional development resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CPA Advocacy", "url": "https://ctpharmacists.org/advocacy/", "description": "CPA advocacy page covering legislative priorities, pharmacist scope of practice expansion, and policy initiatives in Hartford and Washington DC."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT DPH Opioid Data", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dph/health-education-management--surveillance/the-office-of-injury-prevention/opioid-and-drug-overdose-statistics", "description": "Connecticut Department of Public Health Office of Injury Prevention opioid and drug overdose statistics and surveillance data."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CT DPH Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dph/health-education-management--surveillance/the-office-of-injury-prevention/opioid-and-drug-overdose-statistics", "description": "Interactive dashboard from CT DPH showcasing SUDORS data on drug overdose deaths, including demographic breakdowns, geographic distribution, and substances involved."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CPMRS Prescription Data", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dcp/prescription-monitoring-program/prescription-monitoring-program", "description": "The Connecticut Prescription Monitoring and Reporting System provides prescription-level data on controlled substances. CHANGE the SCRxIPT educational campaign provides prescriber and pharmacist data resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Connecticut CORE Initiative", "url": "https://medicine.yale.edu/internal-medicine/genmed/addictionmedicine/policy/connecticut-opioid-response-core-initiative/", "description": "The Connecticut Opioid REsponse (CORE) Initiative at Yale Program in Addiction Medicine issues comprehensive reports advising the Opioid Settlement Advisory Committee on data-informed use of settlement funds."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT Opioid Settlement Allocations Tracker", "url": "https://medicine.yale.edu/internal-medicine/genmed/addictionmedicine/policy/connecticut-opioid-response-core-initiative/allocations-tracker/", "description": "Tracks Connecticut opioid settlement fund allocations across priorities including expanding MAT access, harm reduction, and recovery services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DataHaven Overdose Data", "url": "https://ctdatahaven.org/report/overdose-data-action-2023-update/", "description": "DataHaven's Overdose Data to Action report with Connecticut-specific data on opioid prescriptions, syringe service programs, and fentanyl test strip distribution."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CPA Advocacy Page", "url": "https://ctpharmacists.org/advocacy/", "description": "Connecticut Pharmacists Association advocacy resources covering state legislative priorities, pharmacist scope of practice, and policy engagement opportunities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Connecticut General Assembly - Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://www.cga.ct.gov/asp/menu/cgafindleg.asp", "description": "Tool to find and contact Connecticut state senators and representatives by address or name."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT Opioid Settlement Advisory Committee", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas/newsworthy/news-items/ct-opioid-settlement-advisory-committee", "description": "The CT OSAC consists of state and local government experts, health care professionals, individuals with lived experience, and public health leaders. Advises on allocation of opioid settlement funds."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHAS Legislative Unit", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas/divisions/policy-and-governmental-affairs/legislative-unit", "description": "DMHAS Policy and Governmental Affairs legislative unit, tracking and supporting legislation related to mental health and substance use disorder services in Connecticut."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Connecticut General Assembly - Pharmacy Law", "url": "https://www.cga.ct.gov/current/pub/chap_400j.htm", "description": "Full text of Connecticut General Statutes Chapter 400j governing pharmacy practice, including collaborative drug therapy management agreements and scope of practice provisions."}]}]}, "delaware": {"name": "Delaware", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Delaware’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). DEL. CODE ANN. tit.24, § 2502(5) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Delaware law expressly allows “initiating drug therapy for health conditions in accordance with § 2525 of this title.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(k) (West 2024). SUD is not one of these conditions, however. DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2525 (West 2024).\nOtherwise, the practice of pharmacy definition does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23) (West 2024).\nIn addition, pharmacists are not identified by the state division of professional regulation as eligible to register to prescribe controlled substances.\nThis is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Delaware cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Delaware practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Delaware pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Delaware laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Delaware law includes “administering a drug to a patient.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23) (West 2024). This provision itself does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition further specifies that it includes “administration of injectable medications, biologicals and adult immunizations” and “administering injectable hormonal contraceptives.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(h), (i) (West 2024).\nA separate Delaware law provides that a pharmacist can “initiate, dispense, or administer medications for HIV pre-exposure prophylaxes and for HIV post-exposure prophylaxis.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2525A (West 2024) as enacted by 2024 DEL. LAWS Ch. 424, § 1 (West).\nIf the general “administering a drug to a patient” phrase in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in Delaware may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Delaware practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Delaware law refers to involvement with tests in four ways, but they are all limited in scope.\nThe first is “performing and interpreting capillary blood tests to screen and monitor disease risk factors or facilitate patient education.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(e) (West 2024).\nThe second is “ordering, performing, and interpreting” CLIA-waived tests authorized by FDA. DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(j) (West 2024).\nThe third is administering tests related to HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis and HIV post-exposure prophylaxis. DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(m) (West 2024) as enacted by 2024 DEL. LAWS Ch. 424, § 1 (West).\nFinally, the practice of pharmacy includes “initiating drug therapy for health conditions in accordance with § 2525 of this title.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(k) (West 2024). The referenced section is entitled “testing, screening, and treatment of health conditions,” but the specified health conditions do not include SUD. DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2525 (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in Delaware to expressly allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Delaware law includes “collaborative pharmacy practice in accordance with a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(l) (West 2024).Delaware law provides no additional information about what collaborative pharmacy practice can entail, what constitutes “patient care and drug therapy management,” or whether collaborative pharmacy practice includes prescriptive authority.\nMoreover, Delaware law governing CPPAs does not account for the fact that a Delaware pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPPA directs.\nIn summary, Delaware laws do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing drugs under a CPPA. Even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, however, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Delaware pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Delaware laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPPAs.\nExpressly specify in Delaware laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPPAs.\nAllow Delaware pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Delaware laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Delaware law includes “collaborative pharmacy practice in accordance with a [CPPA].” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(l) (West 2024). Delaware law provides that collaborative pharmacy practice allows a pharmacist to provide “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist” under a CPPA that “defines the nature, scope, conditions, and limitations of the services to be provided by the pharmacist(s).” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(4) (West 2024). This provision could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a CPPA because that practice does not appear to be allowed in general, per the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section.\nHowever, Delaware law provides no additional information about what collaborative pharmacy practice can entail, what constitutes “patient care and drug therapy management,” or whether collaborative pharmacy practice includes administering drugs other than what the law expressly allows outside of CPPA. The lack of specificity in Delaware law (and lack of regulations addressing it) could indicate that the legislature and state board of pharmacy have not considered the scope of a CPPA.\nIn summary, although Delaware pharmacy law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine under a CPPA it also does not clearly authorize it.", "5B": null, "5C": "Expressly specify in Delaware law and/or regulation what “patient care and drug therapy management” includes and that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a CPPA.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Delaware laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes “collaborative pharmacy practice in accordance with a [CPPA].” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(23)(l) (West 2024).\nCollaborative pharmacy practice allows a pharmacist to provide “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist” under a CPPA that “defines the nature, scope, conditions, and limitations of the services to be provided by the pharmacist(s).” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(4) (West 2024). This provision could support a conclusion that a pharmacist can order or evaluate any type of lab tests under a CPPA because that practice is not allowed in general, per the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section.\nHowever, Delaware law provides no additional information about what collaborative pharmacy practice can entail, what constitutes “patient care and drug therapy management,” or whether collaborative pharmacy practice includes ordering lab tests and evaluating the results. The lack of specificity in Delaware law (and lack of regulations addressing it) could indicate that the legislature and state board of pharmacy have considered the scope of a CPPA.\nIn summary, although Delaware pharmacy law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from ordering or administering all types of lab tests under a CPPA it also does not clearly authorize those activities. Given the response in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that Delaware pharmacists have limited authority with respect to ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of a CPPA, the most logical answer to this question is that pharmacists have the same limited authority under a CPPA as they do outside of one.", "6B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Delaware law that under a CPPA, pharmacists can order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "One or more pharmacists can enter a CPPA with one or more “practitioners.”\nFor purposes of Delaware pharmacy law, a “practitioner,” also known as a “prescriber,” is “an individual who is authorized by law to prescribe drugs in the course of professional practice or by collaborative pharmacy practice agreement or research in any state.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(24) (West 2024).\nThere is little Delaware law (and no regulations) providing information about collaborative pharmacy practice and CPPAs. What exists is at DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 2502(4), (5), (23)(l) (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nUnder Delaware’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law, health care providers licensed by specified professional licensing boards are “authorized to deliver health-care services by telehealth and telemedicine.” The Delaware Boad of Pharmacy is one of those boards. DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 6002(a)(8) (West 2024).\n“Health-care providers may not deliver health-care services by telehealth and telemedicine in the absence of a health-care provider-patient relationship.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 6003(a) (West 2024). Moreover, “treatment and consultation recommendations delivered by telehealth and telemedicine shall be subject to the same standards of appropriate practice as those in traditional (in-person encounter) settings.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, § 6003(c) (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "Delaware law and regulations governing telehealth include – DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 24, §§ 6001 to 6005 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 18, §§ 3370, 3571R (West 2024) (health insurance); 18 DEL. ADMIN. CODE §§ 1409-1.0 to 1409-6.0 (2024) (insurance coverage); 24 DEL. ADMIN. CODE §§ 2500-1.1, 2500-5.2.5 (2024)\n(pharmacy); 24 DEL. ADMIN. CODE § 3000-11.0 (2024)\n(chemical dependency counseling).", "9A": "Effective January 1, 2025, “no health insurer, health service corporation, managed care organization, or health maintenance organization may deny benefits for eligible services based on the type of provider performing the service as long as the provider is acting within the provider’s scope of practice.” In addition, “no contract of insurance delivered or issued for delivery in this State by a health insurer, health service corporation, managed care organization, or health maintenance organization may exclude pharmacists as providers of services covered in the contract.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 18, § 2321 (West 2024), as enacted by 2024 DEL. LAWS Ch. 421, §1 (West).\nAs part of this new law, the definition of “medical care” for the Delaware Medicaid program will now include “pharmacist’s services, whether furnished in the office, the patient’s house, a hospital, a skilled nursing facility, an assisted living facility, a pharmacy, a federally qualified health center, a rural health clinic, or elsewhere.” DEL. CODE ANN. tit. 31, § 502(7)(f) (West 2024), as added by 2024 DEL. LAWS Ch. 421, §5 (West).\nIn addition, separate “pharmacist services reimbursement” provisions will be added to Delaware laws governing health insurance contracts, group and blanket health insurance, and public officers and employee’s health care insurance. 2024 DEL. LAWS Ch. 421, §§ 2-4 (West).", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (PMP)", "url": "https://dpr.delaware.gov/boards/pmp/", "description": "The Delaware Prescription Monitoring Program (PMP), operated by the Division of Professional Regulation (DPR), collects information on all controlled substance (Schedules II-V) prescriptions dispensed in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Login", "url": "https://delaware.pmpaware.net", "description": "Login portal for the Delaware PMP AWARxE system powered by Appriss Health. Practitioners and pharmacists can access patient controlled substance prescription histories."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Practitioner, Pharmacist and Delegate Registration", "url": "https://dpr.delaware.gov/boards/pmp/pandp/", "description": "Registration instructions for practitioners and pharmacists. Out-of-state practitioners and pharmacists not licensed in Delaware can request access to the Delaware PMP for patient care purposes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP FAQs", "url": "https://dpr.delaware.gov/boards/pmp/faqs/", "description": "Frequently asked questions about the Delaware PMP, including information about delegate access, OTP physician and pharmacist registration, and data sharing requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "Delaware participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing. The Delaware Office of Controlled Substances partnered with Appriss Health to provide interoperability services enabling providers to access PMP data within their EHR or pharmacy dispensing software."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dpr.delaware.gov/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "The Delaware Board of Pharmacy, within the Division of Professional Regulation, issues licenses to pharmacists and pharmacy interns. Contact: customerservice.dpr@delaware.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Pharmacy Practice Act (Title 24, Chapter 25)", "url": "https://delcode.delaware.gov/title24/c025/sc01/index.html", "description": "Delaware Code Title 24, Chapter 25 governing pharmacy practice, including definitions of collaborative pharmacy practice agreements, pharmacist and practitioner authority, and Board powers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://regulations.delaware.gov/AdminCode/title24/2500.shtml", "description": "Delaware Administrative Code Title 24, Section 2500 containing the Board of Pharmacy rules and regulations governing pharmacy practice, licensure, and operations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Agreement Statute", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/delaware/title-24/chapter-25/subchapter-i/section-2502/", "description": "Delaware Code defines collaborative pharmacy practice agreement as a written and signed agreement between one or more pharmacists and one or more practitioners that provides for collaborative pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "License Renewal and CE Requirements", "url": "https://dpr.delaware.gov/boards/pharmacy/renewal/", "description": "Delaware pharmacists are required to complete 30 hours of continuing education every two years (biennial renewal). A minimum of 2 hours must be in medication safety and errors, and 2 hours must be in controlled substances distribution, dispensing, or delivery. New licensees must complete 1.25 CE hours per month."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Help Is Here DE", "url": "https://www.helpisherede.com/", "description": "Delaware's comprehensive resource portal for addiction prevention, treatment, and recovery. Includes treatment provider search, naloxone and fentanyl test strip mail-order programs, and information on medication for opioid use disorder (MOUD). Helpline: 833-9-HOPEDE."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "Federal treatment locator to find substance use disorder treatment providers including buprenorphine prescribers. Can be filtered by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware SOR Initiative (DSAMH)", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dsamh/startexp/", "description": "Delaware's State Opioid Response initiative through the Division of Substance Abuse and Mental Health (DSAMH), focused on decreasing opioid overdoses through expanded access to treatment and targeted referral systems."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prescribing (Post X-Waiver)", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA guidance on buprenorphine prescribing after removal of the X-waiver requirement. All DEA-registered practitioners with Schedule III authority can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing, including the DEA's 2025 final rule allowing audio-only telehealth initiation for up to 6 months."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Medicaid Pharmacy Corner", "url": "https://medicaid.dhss.delaware.gov/provider/Home/PharmacyCornerLanding/tabid/2096/Default.aspx", "description": "Delaware Medical Assistance Portal pharmacy corner for Medicaid providers, with pharmacy-specific billing information and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.ctdssmap.com/ctportal/portals/0/staticcontent/publications/ct_pdl_medicaid.pdf", "description": "Delaware Medicaid covers buprenorphine products (Suboxone, buprenorphine/naloxone tablets, and buprenorphine tablets) under fee-for-service plans. The PDL is updated twice a year. Please verify this link before publishing - check the DMMA website for the current Delaware-specific PDL."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Policy Billing Reference Guide", "url": "https://medicaidpublications.dhss.delaware.gov/docs/Search?Command=Core_Download&EntryId=893", "description": "Delaware Medicaid pharmacy policy billing reference guide with detailed information on preferred drug list requirements, prior authorization procedures, and billing codes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "AmeriHealth Caritas Delaware Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://www.amerihealthcaritasde.com/provider/pharmacy/index.aspx", "description": "AmeriHealth Caritas (Delaware Medicaid MCO) pharmacy services page with links to the DMAP Preferred Drug List and pharmacy resources for member prescriptions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA SOR grant opportunities. Delaware DSAMH has received over $181 million in SOR funding from FY18-FY23 to support treatment access, harm reduction, and recovery services."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.netce.com/ce-requirements/pharmacist/de/", "description": "Delaware requires 30 hours of CE every two years. Must include 2 hours in medication safety/errors and 2 hours in controlled substances distribution/dispensing. All hours may be completed by home study."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Licensure Requirements", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/delaware/24-Del-Admin-Code-SS-2500-1.0", "description": "Delaware Administrative Code pharmacist licensure requirements including continuing education details. Pharmacists presenting CE programs receive credit for time expended during actual presentation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Pharmacists Society", "url": "https://www.dpsrx.org/", "description": "DPS provides education, advocacy, and resources for Delaware pharmacists. Currently offering a medical billing platform through a McKesson grant to help pharmacists with insurance credentialing and Medicaid billing for clinical services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/registration-faq.html", "description": "DEA registration information including the 8-hour MATE Act training requirement for substance use disorders for all practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS-MOUD Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Free Provider Clinical Support System training on medications for opioid use disorders. Offers modules, webinars, and clinical tools meeting DEA MATE Act requirements."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Help Is Here DE - Harm Reduction", "url": "https://www.helpisherede.com/addiction/harm-reduction/naloxone", "description": "Delaware's Help Is Here portal for naloxone access and harm reduction resources, including information on where to get naloxone, fentanyl test strips, and harm reduction vending machines."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DPH Standing Orders", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dph/standingorders/", "description": "Delaware Division of Public Health standing orders page. Delaware expanded access to naloxone in 2014 through Senate Bill 219, creating Community and First Responder programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Distribution", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/pressreleases/2022/delawareoverdose_052422.html", "description": "Information on Delaware's naloxone distribution efforts. Go to HelpIsHereDE.com and click on the overdose prevention tab to find training/distribution events, participating pharmacies, and Bridge Clinics in each county."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality and Access", "url": "https://legis.delaware.gov/BillDetail?legislationId=48404", "description": "Delaware SB 76 authorized the distribution of fentanyl testing strips as a harm reduction strategy. Fentanyl test strips are legal in Delaware and included in state-distributed Narcan kits. Free 10-pack test strip kits are available by mail through helpisherede.com."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/pressreleases/2022/delawareoverdose_052422.html", "description": "Brandywine Counseling and Community Services operates Delaware's Syringe Services Program, providing outreach and harm reduction services including sterile syringes, naloxone, and fentanyl test strips."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DSAMH Homepage", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dsamh/", "description": "The Delaware Division of Substance Abuse and Mental Health (DSAMH) is the state behavioral health agency providing integrated services for adults with mental illness and substance use disorders. Programs include crisis intervention, treatment access, DUI rehabilitation, and peer services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DSAMH About and Programs", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dsamh/about/", "description": "Overview of DSAMH programs including community support services, continuous treatment teams, group homes, clinic-based services, 24-hour mobile crisis teams, and substance abuse treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DSAMH Contact Information", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dsamh/contact/", "description": "DSAMH contact page with information on 988 crisis intervention, court programs, PROMISE Assessment Center, Delaware Psychiatric Center, eligibility and enrollment, and peer services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.helpisherede.com/", "description": "Delaware's Help Is Here portal connects people to recovery housing and support services. In 2025, Delaware invested in expanded housing and recovery support programs for residents with OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services - 988 and Help Line", "url": "https://www.helpisherede.com/", "description": "Delaware offers 24/7 coaching and support through the Help Is Here DE helpline at 833-9-HOPEDE (833-946-7333). For immediate crisis support, call or text 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://dpr.delaware.gov/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "Delaware Board of Pharmacy, Division of Professional Regulation. Email: customerservice.dpr@delaware.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DSAMH Contact", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dsamh/contact/", "description": "Delaware Division of Substance Abuse and Mental Health. DSAMH serves as the State Opioid Treatment Authority and behavioral health agency."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Pharmacists Society", "url": "https://www.dpsrx.org/", "description": "DPS is Delaware's state pharmacy association, founded in 1886. Provides advocacy, education, and professional development resources for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Division of Public Health", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dph/standingorders/", "description": "DPH oversees standing orders, naloxone distribution, fentanyl test strip programs, and overdose data surveillance. Tracks current year suspected overdose death totals on its website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Help Is Here DE Helpline", "url": "https://www.helpisherede.com/", "description": "Delaware's statewide help portal. Call 833-9-HOPEDE for free 24/7 coaching and support, links to mental health, addiction, and crisis services."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "My Healthy Community - Drug Overdose Deaths", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dph/my-healthy-community/", "description": "Delaware DHSS My Healthy Community platform (transitioning to Delaware Open Data Portal) provides comprehensive data on drug overdose deaths, with state-level and demographic breakdowns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Open Data Portal", "url": "https://data.delaware.gov/", "description": "Delaware Open Data Portal hosting priority datasets from My Healthy Community including drug overdose death data and related health statistics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHSS Overdose Death Tracking", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/", "description": "The Delaware DHSS homepage publishes year-to-date total number of suspected overdose deaths. Current data is also available at HelpIsHereDE.com."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DPH Fentanyl Health Alerts", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/dph/php/alerts/dhan404/", "description": "Delaware DPH health alerts regarding the increased presence of fentanyl in overdose deaths and the illicit drug supply, with recommendations for health care providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DSAMH SOR Data", "url": "https://nasadad.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/Delaware-SOR-Brief-Draft-2024_Final.pdf", "description": "Delaware State Opioid Response initiatives data brief from NASADAD, documenting DSAMH's receipt of over $181 million in SOR funding and program outcomes."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Pharmacists Society", "url": "https://www.dpsrx.org/", "description": "DPS provides advocacy for Delaware pharmacists including supporting Medicaid medical billing for pharmacist clinical services (hormonal contraception, tobacco cessation) and scope of practice expansion."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware General Assembly", "url": "https://legis.delaware.gov/", "description": "Delaware General Assembly website for tracking current legislation, searching bills by number or keyword, and accessing legislative information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware General Assembly - Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://legis.delaware.gov/", "description": "The Delaware General Assembly website provides constituent services and links to contact elected officials. Use the homepage to search bills or find information about your district. Please verify the exact legislator lookup URL before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CT Opioid Settlement Advisory Committee Model", "url": "https://portal.ct.gov/dmhas/newsworthy/news-items/ct-opioid-settlement-advisory-committee", "description": "Delaware participates in national opioid settlement allocation processes. For model approaches to opioid settlement spending, see neighboring state advisory committee frameworks."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delaware Fentanyl Test Strip Legislation (SB 76)", "url": "https://legis.delaware.gov/BillDetail?legislationId=48404", "description": "SB 76 authorized the distribution of fentanyl testing strips in Delaware as a harm reduction strategy. This legislation removed fentanyl test strips from the drug paraphernalia classification, allowing their distribution alongside naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Blueprint for Transforming OUD Treatment", "url": "https://dhss.delaware.gov/wp-content/uploads/dhss/pdf/johnshopkinsrep.pdf", "description": "Johns Hopkins report providing a comprehensive blueprint for transforming opioid use disorder treatment in Delaware, with recommendations on expanding access to methadone, buprenorphine, and naltrexone."}]}]}, "districtofcolumbia": {"name": "District of Columbia", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in District of Columbia law does not expressly refer to prescribing any drug or medication other than “the prescribing and dispensing of self-administered hormonal contraceptives” in accordance with laws and regulations. D.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11)(A) (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in the District of Columbia cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the District of Columbia practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow District of Columbia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in District of Columbia law expressly refers to administering a drug or medication in only three ways: (1) administering immunizations and vaccinations; (2) administering anticoagulation therapy; and (3) “the administration of a prescribed drug, device, and biological in accordance with regulations issued by the Mayor.” D.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11)(A) (West 2024).\nAs of October 2024, the only District of Columbia pharmacy regulation that expressly refers to administering a drug or medication relates to immunizations and vaccinations.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the District of Columbia practice of pharmacy to include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in District of Columbia law expressly refers to pharmacist testing authority in only three ways: (1) “conducting health screenings, including ordering, performing, and interpreting [CLIA]-waived tests”; (2) “point-of-care testing for blood glucose”; and (3) “point-of-care testing and cholesterol monitoring.” D.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11)(A) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the practice of pharmacy in the District of Columbia to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based upon the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in District of Columbia law includes “initiating, modifying, or discontinuing a drug therapy” in accordance with a CPA.\nD.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11)(A) (West 2024).\nAlthough this provision uses the word “initiating,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nIn addition, District of Columbia regulations governing CPAs provide such regulations do not allow a pharmacist “to accept delegation of a physician’s authority outside of or beyond the scope of the pharmacist’s practice.” D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, § 10000.7 (2024). As described in the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, prescribing buprenorphine outside of a CPA is not part of the practice of pharmacy and so this provision may prevent a pharmacist from doing so. Moreover, District of Columbia laws and regulations governing CPAs does not account for the fact that a District of Columbia pharmacist cannot obtain a District controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPA directs.\nIn summary, District of Columbia laws and regulations may expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances under a CPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a District of Columbia pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise District of Columbia laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPAs.\nExpressly specify in District of Columbia laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow District of Columbia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, District of Columbia laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in District of Columbia law includes “initiating, modifying, or discontinuing a drug therapy” in accordance with a CPA.\nD.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11)(A) (West 2024).\nAlthough this provision uses the phrase “initiating, modifying or discontinuing,” there is no express reference to “administering” drugs or medications in this provision or any other laws or regulations governing CPAs.\nDistrict of Columbia laws and regulations do not expressly identify what constitutes “initiating, modifying, or discontinuing a drug therapy.” To the extent that those actions include administering a drug or medication, then this provision could mean a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a CPA.\nHowever, District of Columbia regulations governing CPAs provide such regulations do not allow a pharmacist “to accept delegation of a physician’s authority outside of or beyond the scope of the pharmacist’s practice.” D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, § 10000.7 (2024). As described in the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, administering buprenorphine outside of a CPA is not part of the practice of pharmacy and so this provision may prevent a pharmacist from doing so under a CPA.", "5B": null, "5C": "Expressly specify in District of Columbia laws or regulations what “initiating, modifying, or discontinuing a drug therapy” means and that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a CPA.", "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization only applies to ordering lab tests.\nA CPA “may include treatment protocols that include a physician(s) delegation of authority to the pharmacist(s) to obtain laboratory tests provided the tests relate directly to the drug therapy management under the protocol.” D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, § 10002.7 (2024).\nThere is no express authorization for evaluating test results, however.", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in District of Columbia laws and/or regulations that under CPAs, a pharmacist can evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CPA is a written agreement between a licensed pharmacist and either a licensed physician or “another health practitioner with independent prescriptive authority licensed by a District health occupation board.” D.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11)(B)(i), § 3-1204.12 (West 2024).\nA CPA can cover pharmacists and collaborating physicians or other health practitioners in “institutional facility settings.” D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, § 10009 (2024).\nD.C. regulations provide that “pharmacists engaging in collaborative practice shall not delegate any collaborative practice activities to any other staff.” D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, § 10002.9 (2024).\nThe following District of Columbia laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – D.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.02(11) (West 2024); D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, §§ 10000 to 10099 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nDistrict of Columbia’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that a “health professional licensed, registered, or certified in the District pursuant to this chapter [covering Health Occupation Boards] may provide a telehealth service to a District resident or person located in the District” if doing so is consistent with the professional’s applicable standard of care and scope of practice and it is not otherwise prohibited by regulation.\nD.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.05(a) (West 2024). The District of Columbia Board of Pharmacy is included in the chapter.", "8B": null, "8C": "District of Columbia law and regulations governing telehealth include – D.C. CODE ANN. § 3-1201.05 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); D.C CODE ANN. § 7-3202 (West 2024) (expanding access to OUD treatment); D.C CODE ANN. §§ 31-3861 to 31-3863 (2024) (telehealth reimbursement); D.C. MUN. REGS. tit. 17, § 4618 (2024) (telemedicine); D.C. MUN. REGS tit. 29, § 910 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "“Medicaid reimbursement for pharmacists’ administration services, provided consistent with the requirements set forth in 42 C.F.R. § 440.60(a) and the provisions set forth in this section, is limited to administering Medicaid-covered immunizations, vaccines, and emergency anaphylaxis agents.” D.C. MUN. REGS tit. 29, § 913 (2024).", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the District of Columbia Medicaid program.\nSpecify in District of Columbia laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under CPAs are covered under the District of Columbia Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Page", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/service/prescription-drug-monitoring-program", "description": "DC Health Prescription Drug Monitoring Program (PDMP) page. The PDMP aims to improve the District's ability to identify and reduce diversion of prescription drugs while enhancing patient care. All licensed prescribers and dispensers must register for the DC PDMP."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal Login", "url": "https://districtofcolumbia.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "PMP AWARxE login portal for the DC PDMP. Registered practitioners can query patient prescription histories for controlled substances."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Mandatory PDMP query is in effect in the District of Columbia under DC Law 23-251 (Prescription Drug Monitoring Program Query and Omnibus Health Amendments Act of 2020, effective March 16, 2021). Prescribers and dispensers must query the PDMP prior to prescribing or dispensing an opioid or benzodiazepine for more than seven consecutive days, and every ninety days thereafter. Gabapentin has been a covered substance since June 7, 2019. DC participates in PMP InterConnect (PMPi) for interstate data sharing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Gateway Integration", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/node/1388911", "description": "DC PDMP Gateway integration page. DC Health covers the licensing fees for EHR/PMS integration through Bamboo Health's PMP Gateway service for all healthcare entities in the District."}, {"type": "note", "text": "PDMP Training: DC Health provides training webinars on using the DC PDMP, including patient queries, PDMP reports, bulk patient searches, and the NarxCare analytics feature. Access webinar recordings through the PDMP program page."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the PMP AWARxE system by prescribers and pharmacists to query the PDMP on their behalf."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/service/board-pharmacy", "description": "District of Columbia Board of Pharmacy, under DC Health. The Board consists of seven DC residents: five licensed pharmacists and two consumers, appointed by the Mayor. Processing Center hours: Mon, Tue, Thu, Fri 9am-1pm; Wed 9am-3:30pm. Phone: (202) 442-5955."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Laws and Regulations", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/service/pharmacy-laws-and-regulations", "description": "Comprehensive page listing all DC pharmacy laws and regulations organized by section, including pharmacy licensing (DC Code Title 47, 48), pharmacist licensure (DC Code Title 3, Chapter 12), controlled substances (DCMR Title 22), pharmacy technician regulations (Chapter 99), and collaborative practice agreements (Chapter 100)."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacy Practice Act: DC Code Title 3, Chapter 12, Subchapter II establishes the Board of Pharmacy at DC Code Section 3-1202.08. The full DC Code is available at https://code.dccouncil.gov/"}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Regulations: DCMR Title 17, Chapter 65 (Pharmacists) contains the administrative rules governing pharmacist practice in the District. Available through the Pharmacy Laws and Regulations page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements", "url": "https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/sections/3-1202.08", "description": "DC Code Section 3-1202.08 authorizes licensed pharmacists to initiate, modify, or discontinue a drug therapy regimen pursuant to a collaborative practice agreement with a licensed physician. DCMR Title 17, Chapter 100 contains the rules for Collaborative Practice Agreements Between Physicians and Pharmacists."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: DC pharmacists may initiate, modify, or discontinue drug therapy under a collaborative practice agreement. DC also has provisions for pharmacist prescribing of naloxone and other authorized medications."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "LIVE.LONG.DC Resources", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/page/resources-LLDC", "description": "LIVE.LONG.DC resources page - the District's comprehensive plan to reduce opioid use, misuse, and related deaths. Includes links to treatment, prevention, harm reduction, naloxone, and recovery resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "LIVE.LONG.DC Provider Resources", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/page/providers-0", "description": "Provider-focused resources including the BUP-DAP (Buprenorphine Drug Assistance Plan) for uninsured and underinsured individuals needing OUD treatment. BUP-DAP covers buprenorphine/naloxone, Vivitrol injection, Suboxone, and Narcan nasal spray."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in the District of Columbia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MyRecoveryDC Services Map", "url": "https://myrecoverydc.org/services-in-dc/", "description": "Interactive map of treatment and recovery services in DC, including substance use treatment, mental health, housing resources, naloxone access, and overdose prevention education. Part of the LIVE.LONG.DC initiative."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DBH Substance Use Disorder Services", "url": "https://dbh.dc.gov/page/substance-use-disorder-services", "description": "Department of Behavioral Health (DBH) page listing certified community-based SUD treatment providers across the District, including detoxification, residential, and outpatient services. To enroll, call the DBH Access HelpLine at 1-888-793-4357."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DBH Assessment and Referral Center (ARC)", "url": "https://dbh.dc.gov/service/treatment-services", "description": "DBH Assessment and Referral Center for connecting individuals to substance use disorder services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Crisis Work", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/page/our-work-opioid-crisis", "description": "LIVE.LONG.DC page on the District's opioid crisis work, including MAT programs, OTP locations, naloxone distribution, syringe services, and the DBH Mobile Van that provides buprenorphine initiation at community hotspots."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), healthcare providers no longer need an X-waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of DEA registration or renewal. DC does not impose additional requirements beyond federal law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine: DC follows federal DEA telehealth regulations for prescribing buprenorphine. The District has supported expanded telehealth access for OUD treatment."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DBH Access HelpLine: 1-888-793-4357 (1-888-7WE-HELP). Available 24/7, staffed by behavioral health professionals who can refer callers to immediate help or ongoing care."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DC Medicaid (DHCF)", "url": "https://dhcf.dc.gov/", "description": "Department of Health Care Finance (DHCF) homepage, the agency that administers the District's Medicaid program. Phone: (202) 442-5988. Address: 441 4th Street NW, 900S, Washington, DC 20001."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Right Rx Initiative", "url": "https://dhcf.dc.gov/service/right-rx-initiative", "description": "DHCF Right Rx Initiative providing decision and administrative support to clinicians for appropriate medication use by Medicaid beneficiaries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://dc.fhsc.com/providers/PDL.asp", "description": "District of Columbia Medicaid Preferred Drug List page on the First Health Services Corporation website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDL Document", "url": "https://fm.formularynavigator.com/FBO/4/DC_PDL.pdf", "description": "District of Columbia Medicaid-Approved Preferred Drug List (effective February 1, 2026). Lists preferred and non-preferred drugs by therapeutic class."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Provider Manual", "url": "https://www.dc-pbm.com/provider/external/medicaid/dc/doc/en-us/District_FFS_Provider_Manual.pdf", "description": "District of Columbia Fee-for-Service Pharmacy Provider Manual. Includes information on buprenorphine, naltrexone, and other SUD medications. Notes that DHCF requires prior authorization for opioid prescriptions greater than 90 MME and/or a 7-day supply."}, {"type": "note", "text": "BUP-DAP (Buprenorphine Drug Assistance Plan): Available through LIVE.LONG.DC at https://livelong.dc.gov/page/providers-0. Covers buprenorphine/naloxone, Vivitrol injection, Suboxone, and Narcan for uninsured and underinsured individuals."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State-Specific Pharmacist Billing Codes: DC Medicaid does not have a comprehensive set of billing codes specific to pharmacist-provided clinical services beyond dispensing. Contact DHCF for pharmacist service billing guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: DC receives State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA (DCOR3 - District of Columbia Opioid Response 3). The District has invested in buprenorphine expansion at community clinics, naloxone distribution, syringe services, and supported employment for individuals with OUD."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/service/pharmacist-continuing-education-requirements-and-resources", "description": "DC Health pharmacist continuing education requirements and resources page. Includes links to DCRx (The DC Center for Rational Prescribing), NABP CPE Monitor Program, and the Board's public health priorities for CE. Phone: (877) 672-2174."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Public Health CE Priorities", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/doh/service_content/attachments/2025-02-13%20Directors%20Public%20Health%20Priorities%20for%20CE%20Final_1.pdf", "description": "2025 DC Health Director's Public Notice Identifying Public Health Issues for Continuing Education (effective October 1, 2025). Pharmacists may be required to complete CE on identified public health priorities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Washington DC Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://wdcpha.org/", "description": "Washington DC Pharmacy Association (WDCPhA), celebrating its 50th anniversary in 2025. WDCPhA provides pharmacy leadership, advocacy, and educational resources for pharmacists in the District."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS provides free training on medications for opioid use disorder, including training options that meet the DEA 8-hour MATE Act education requirement. Funded by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division website for DEA registration, practitioner resources, and controlled substance regulations relevant to buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Learning Institute", "url": "https://dbhtraininginstitute.networkofcare4elearning.org/", "description": "DBH Opioid Learning Institute offering online training modules on naloxone and overdose prevention, available for free. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: The District of Columbia operates licensed syringe service programs (SSPs). DC Health supports comprehensive harm reduction programs at four licensed syringe service programs to prevent the spread of HIV/AIDS and Hepatitis C, provide wound care, and connect individuals to health services. Authorized under DC Code Section 48-1103.01."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access", "url": "https://dbh.dc.gov/page/where-can-i-get-naloxone-dc", "description": "DBH page on where to get naloxone in DC. Naloxone is available at no cost, without a prescription or ID, in every ward. Text LiveLongDC to 888-811 for naloxone delivery within two business days to any DC address. Extensive list of pharmacies, community health centers, and vending machines across all eight wards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone and Harm Reduction Resources", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/page/resources-LLDC", "description": "LIVE.LONG.DC resources page with free education materials on naloxone use, fentanyl test strips, and DC's Good Samaritan Laws. Includes video tutorials in English and Spanish."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: Free fentanyl test strip education materials are available through LIVE.LONG.DC. DC distributes fentanyl test strips as part of its harm reduction strategy. The District's Good Samaritan Laws (DC Code) protect individuals seeking help during an overdose from drug paraphernalia and possession charges."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips are legal in the District of Columbia. They are distributed as part of the District's comprehensive harm reduction strategy through LIVE.LONG.DC and community organizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://dataviz1.dc.gov/t/OCTO/views/DCHealthLiveLongDCDashboardFinal/OpioidLandingPage?%3AshowAppBanner=false&%3Adisplay_count=n&%3AshowVizHome=n&%3Aorigin=viz_share_link&%3Aembed=yes&%3Atoolbar=no", "description": "DC Health / Live Long DC interactive dashboard showing fatal and non-fatal overdose data, naloxone distribution, harm reduction efforts, and used syringe testing results. A collaborative effort between DC Health, OCME, DBH, and DFS. Data aggregated at neighborhood and ward levels."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OCME Epidemiology Reports", "url": "http://ocme.dc.gov/publication/epidemiology-and-surveillance-reports", "description": "Office of the Chief Medical Examiner (OCME) epidemiology and surveillance reports on fatal opioid overdoses in the District."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MyRecoveryDC", "url": "https://myrecoverydc.org/", "description": "MyRecoveryDC, a program of DC Health, features stories of recovery and connects individuals to DBH-certified peers. Includes a treatment services map, peer directory, and resources for recovery from opioid and substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find a Peer", "url": "https://myrecoverydc.org/find-a-peer/", "description": "DC has nearly 100 Certified Peers who provide support and encouragement along the recovery path. Connect with a peer to find the services that are right for you."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DBH Substance Use Disorder Services", "url": "https://dbh.dc.gov/page/substance-use-disorder-services", "description": "DBH-certified community-based SUD treatment providers including detoxification, residential, and outpatient services. Call the Access HelpLine at 1-888-793-4357 for referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://dbh.dc.gov/", "description": "DC Department of Behavioral Health (DBH) homepage. DBH is the District's primary behavioral health authority. Phone: (202) 673-2200. Address: 64 New York Avenue NE, 3rd Floor, Washington, DC 20002."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Residences: DC supports recovery residences through the DCOR3 (District of Columbia Opioid Response 3) initiative, which funds recovery residences with intensive case management for individuals with opioid and/or stimulant use disorder."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: DBH Access HelpLine: 1-888-793-4357 (1-888-7WE-HELP) available 24/7. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is also available 24/7. Text LiveLongDC to 888-811 for naloxone delivery and outreach worker connection."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DC Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/service/board-pharmacy", "description": "DC Board of Pharmacy, DC Health. Processing Center at 899 North Capitol Street NE, Washington, DC 20002. Phone: (202) 442-5955. Office Hours: Mon-Fri 8:15am-4:45pm."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DC Medicaid (DHCF)", "url": "https://dhcf.dc.gov/", "description": "Department of Health Care Finance (DHCF). 441 4th Street NW, 900S, Washington, DC 20001. Phone: (202) 442-5988. Director: Wayne Turnage, M.P.A."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Behavioral Health (SOTA equivalent)", "url": "https://dbh.dc.gov/", "description": "DC Department of Behavioral Health. 64 New York Avenue NE, 3rd Floor, Washington, DC 20002. Phone: (202) 673-2200. Fax: (202) 673-3433. Director: Barbara J. Bazron, PhD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Washington DC Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://wdcpha.org/", "description": "WDCPhA provides pharmacy leadership, advocacy, and education in the District."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DC Health Opioid Program", "url": "https://dchealth.dc.gov/opioids", "description": "DC Health opioid awareness campaign bringing attention to the dangers and risks of opioid misuse and abuse."}, {"type": "link", "title": "LIVE.LONG.DC", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/", "description": "The District's comprehensive opioid strategy website coordinating across multiple agencies (DC Health, DBH, DHCF, OCME, DFS) to address the opioid epidemic."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Live Long DC Data Page", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/page/data-0", "description": "LIVE.LONG.DC data page with multiple data sources including DC Health overdose dashboard, OCME fatality data, DBH program outputs, and ward-level reports on suspected non-fatal and fatal overdoses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DC Health Live Long DC Dashboard", "url": "https://dataviz1.dc.gov/t/OCTO/views/DCHealthLiveLongDCDashboardFinal/OpioidLandingPage?%3AshowAppBanner=false&%3Adisplay_count=n&%3AshowVizHome=n&%3Aorigin=viz_share_link&%3Aembed=yes&%3Atoolbar=no", "description": "Interactive Tableau dashboard showing comprehensive opioid data including ambulance transports for overdoses, fatalities, naloxone distribution, harm reduction efforts, and syringe testing results. Data aggregated by neighborhood and ward."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OCME Reports", "url": "http://ocme.dc.gov/publication/epidemiology-and-surveillance-reports", "description": "Office of the Chief Medical Examiner epidemiology and surveillance reports on fatal overdoses. OCME peer reviews each case monthly."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Ward-Level Data Reports: Available through the Live Long DC data page. Ward meetings are held every other month with government partners, SOR grantees, SUD providers, and community stakeholders to review overdose trends and plan targeted outreach."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DBH Monthly Reporting: The Department of Behavioral Health collects monthly reporting data from providers (subrecipients, contractors) evaluating progress on DCOR initiatives. Annual opioid reports are published at https://livelong.dc.gov/page/data-0."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Data Point: Overdose deaths in the District of Columbia dropped by 33 percent in 2024 according to the Bowser Administration."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Washington DC Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://wdcpha.org/", "description": "WDCPhA provides advocacy, leadership, and professional development for pharmacy professionals in the District. Celebrating 50th anniversary in 2025."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DC Council", "url": "https://dccouncil.gov/", "description": "Council of the District of Columbia website for tracking current legislation. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DC Code (Law Library)", "url": "https://code.dccouncil.gov/", "description": "District of Columbia Law Library with searchable DC Code, including pharmacy practice statutes and regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "LIVE.LONG.DC Strategic Plan", "url": "https://livelong.dc.gov/page/strategic-plan-0", "description": "LIVE.LONG.DC strategic plan outlining the District's comprehensive strategies to address the opioid epidemic, including prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery goals and achievements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy templates. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Legislation and Initiatives: DC Law 23-251 (PDMP Query and Omnibus Health Amendments Act of 2020) established mandatory PDMP querying. DC Code Section 3-1202.08 authorizes pharmacist collaborative practice agreements. DC Code Section 48-1103.01 authorizes the Needle Exchange Program. Good Samaritan Laws protect individuals seeking help during overdoses. The BUP-DAP program provides medication access for uninsured individuals with OUD."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DC Opioid Response (DCOR3): The District of Columbia Opioid Response 3 (DCOR3), funded through SAMHSA's State Opioid Response grant and administered by DBH, supports comprehensive prevention, treatment, harm reduction, and recovery services across the District."}]}]}, "florida": {"name": "Florida", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Florida’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1865(1)(a) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of the profession of pharmacy” in Florida law does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.003(22) (West 2024).\nFlorida law specifies those professions authorized to prescribe medication, which includes only a “prescribing health care provider” as licensed under chapter 458 (medical practice), chapter 459 (osteopathic medicine), chapter 461 (podiatric medicine), or chapter 466 (dentistry). FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.003(22) (West 2024).\nMoreover, under a provision related to pharmacist “testing or screening for and treatment of minor, non-chronic health conditions” pursuant to a written protocol with a physician, Florida law provides that the formulary of medicinal drugs that a pharmacist can prescribe for such minor conditions (established by the state board of pharmacy) “may not include any controlled substance.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1895(3) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Florida cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Florida practice of the profession of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Florida pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of the profession of pharmacy” in Florida law expressly refers to administering a drug or medication in only two circumstances: (1) administering vaccines; and (2) “administering medicinal drugs pursuant to [§] 465.0125 by a consultant pharmacist.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.003(22) (West 2024).\nThe consultant pharmacist provision referred to above applies to such a pharmacist (a defined term) providing “medication management services in a health care facility within the framework of a written collaborative pharmacy practice agreement [CPPA]” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.0125(1)(a) (West 2024). Accordingly, it does not authorize administering drugs or medications outside of a CPPA.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Florida practice of the profession of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment outside of a consultant pharmacist providing medication management services in a health care facility under a CPPA.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of the profession of pharmacy” in Florida law expressly includes “testing or screening for and treatment of minor, nonchronic health conditions pursuant to [§] 465.1895.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.003(22) (West 2024). The referenced section provides that a pharmacist acting under a written protocol with a supervising Florida physician may use any tests that may guide diagnosis or clinical decision making that are CLIA-waived. FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1895(4) (West 2024).In addition, the profession of pharmacy definition includes “ordering and evaluating of any laboratory or clinical testing . . . pursuant to [§] 465.0125 by a consultant pharmacist.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.003(22) (West 2024).\nThe consultant pharmacist provision referred to above applies to such a pharmacist (a defined term) providing “medication management services in a health care facility within the framework of a written collaborative pharmacy practice agreement [CPPA]” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.0125(1)(a) (West 2024). Accordingly, it does not authorize ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of a CPPA.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Florida practice of the profession of pharmacy to allow pharmacists, outside of a CPPA, to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nFlorida regulation provides that OUD is one of the “chronic health conditions” for which a pharmacist can provide “specified patient care services” to patients of a collaborating physician under a CPPA. FLA. ADMIN. CODE ANN. r. 64B16-31.007 (2024).\nHowever, Florida law governing collaborative pharmacy practice expressly provides that a “a physician may not delegate the authority to initiate or prescribe a controlled substance” to pharmacist under a CPPA. FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1865(5) (West 2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Florida law and/or regulation to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPPAs.\nExpressly specify in Florida law and/or regulation how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPPAs.\nAllow Florida pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Florida laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nFlorida regulation provides that OUD is one of the “chronic health conditions” for which a pharmacist can provide “specified patient care services” to patients of a collaborating physician under a CPPA. FLA. ADMIN. CODE ANN. r. 64B16-31.007 (2024). Florida law or regulation does not expressly define the phrase “patient care services” and whether those services include administrating drugs or medications.\nFlorida law governing CPPAs requires that that the agreement include “specific medicinal drug or drugs to be managed by the pharmacist for each patient.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1865(3)(a)(3) (West 2024). The law does not define what “managed” means and whether it includes administrating drugs or medications.", "5B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in Florida laws and/or regulations that “patient care services” under a CPPA includes administering drugs, or at least administering buprenorphine.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nFlorida regulation provides that OUD is one of the “chronic health conditions” for which a pharmacist can provide “specified patient care services” to patients of a collaborating physician under a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement (CPPA). FLA. ADMIN. CODE ANN. r. 64B16-31.007 (2024).\nFlorida law governing CPPAs expressly requires that that the agreement include the “circumstances under which the pharmacist may order or perform and evaluate laboratory or clinical tests.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1865(3)(a)(4) (West 2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "A pharmacist who meets the qualifications of FLA. STAT. ANN. § 456.1865 may enter into a CPPA with a physician licensed under either chapter 458 (medical practice) or chapter 459 (osteopathic medicine). FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1865(1)(a) (West 2024).\nThe following Florida statutes and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – FLA. STAT. ANN. § 465.1865 (West 2024); FLA. ADMIN. CODE ANN. r. 64B16-31.001 to 64B16-31.009 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nFlorida’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that a “telehealth provider” is “any individual who provides health care and related services using telehealth and who is licensed or certified under” a variety of Florida laws, including Chapter 465, which covers pharmacy. FLA. STAT. ANN. § 456.47(1)(b) (West 2024).\n“A telehealth provider has the duty to practice in a manner consistent with his or her scope of practice and the prevailing professional standard of practice for a health care professional who provides in-person health care services to patients in this state.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 456.47(2)(a).", "8B": null, "8C": "Florida laws and regulations governing telehealth include – FLA. STAT. ANN. § 456.47 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); FLA. STAT. ANN. § 627.42396 (West 2024)\n(insurance reimbursement); FLA. STAT. ANN. § 641.31(45) (West 2024) (health maintenance contracts); FLA. ADMIN. CODE ANN. r. 59G-1.057 (2024) (Medicaid); FLA. ADMIN.\nCODE ANN. r. 64B-9.008 (2024) (out of state provider registration).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Florida Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Florida laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under CPPAs are covered under the Florida Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Florida law contains a chapter devoted to the licensing and regulation of a “substance abuse service provider.” FLA. STAT. ANN. §§ 397.401 to 397.4873 (West 2024).\nHowever, the law exempts certain service providers from the requirements including hospitals and “a physician or physician assistant licensed under chapter 458 or chapter 459.” FLA. STAT. ANN. § 397.4012(5) (West 2024).\nThere is a regulation pertaining to the “clinical and medical guidelines” for facilities involved in, among other things, “medication-assisted treatment for opioid addiction,” but it is possible that the guidelines apply only to service providers required to be licensed under FLA. STAT. ANN. § 397.401 to 397.4873. Is also possible even though the regulation contains the phrase “medication-assisted treatment for opioid addiction” the regulation actually refers only to methadone for OUD treatment. FLA. ADMIN. CODE ANN. r. 65D-30.0042 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://florida.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "The E-FORCSE (Electronic-Florida Online Reporting of Controlled Substance Evaluation Program) login portal, Florida's PDMP system powered by PMP AWARxE. Healthcare practitioners use this portal to query patient controlled substance dispensing histories."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Information Page", "url": "https://flhealthsource.gov/FloridaTakeControl/pdmp/", "description": "Comprehensive information about the Florida PDMP including registration instructions, mandatory use requirements, FAQs, and statutory exemptions. Prescribers, dispensers, and their designees may register for access at florida.pmpaware.net."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Pharmacist and Prescriber Registration", "url": "https://florida.pmpaware.net", "description": "Registration portal for pharmacists, prescribers, and designees to create an E-FORCSE PDMP account. Florida-licensed practitioners register using their license number for identity verification."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://flhealthsource.gov/FloridaTakeControl/controlled-substances-bill/", "description": "Florida law requires each prescriber and dispenser (or designee) to consult the PDMP system to review a patient's controlled substance dispensing history each time a controlled substance is prescribed or dispensed to a patient age 16 or older, unless a statutory exemption applies. Exemptions include patients under 16, non-opioid Schedule V drugs, system downtime, or technological failure. Failure to consult may result in a non-disciplinary citation for the initial offense and disciplinary action for subsequent offenses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing and PMP InterConnect", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "Florida participates in PMP InterConnect, the NABP-operated interstate data-sharing hub that enables secure transmission of PDMP data across state lines. Florida is among the 51 PMPs that share data through this platform, allowing practitioners to view out-of-state dispensing records."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Designee Registration Instructions", "url": "https://pmpawarxe.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/29549790392339-Florida", "description": "PMP AWARxE support page for Florida with links to quick reference guides for designee registration, designee patient RxSearch, delegate reverification, and other PDMP system functions. Designees must complete an Information Security and Privacy Training course."}, {"type": "link", "title": "E-FORCSE Program Homepage", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/statistics-data/prescription-drug-monitoring-e-forcse-2/", "description": "The Florida Department of Health's main page for E-FORCSE, providing information about EHR integration through PMP Gateway, NarxCare analytics, and program updates."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/", "description": "The official website of the Florida Board of Pharmacy, providing information on licensure, renewal, continuing education, board meetings, and regulatory updates for pharmacists, pharmacies, pharmacy interns, and pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Pharmacy Practice Act (Chapter 465)", "url": "https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2024/Chapter465/All", "description": "Full text of Chapter 465 of the Florida Statutes, the Pharmacy Practice Act, which governs the practice of pharmacy in Florida. Includes definitions, licensure requirements, pharmacy permits, collaborative practice, and disciplinary provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (Chapter 64B16)", "url": "https://flrules.org/gateway/ChapterHome.asp?Chapter=64B16-27", "description": "Chapter 64B16 of the Florida Administrative Code contains the rules promulgated by the Board of Pharmacy, including pharmacy practice standards. The full set of board rules is also available through the Board of Pharmacy resources page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Laws and Rules Booklet", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/Forms/laws-and-rules-booklet.pdf", "description": "Compiled booklet of Florida pharmacy statutes and administrative rules published by the Board of Pharmacy for practitioner reference."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute (Section 465.1865)", "url": "https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2024/465.1865", "description": "Florida statute authorizing collaborative pharmacy practice for chronic health conditions. A collaborative pharmacy practice agreement is a written agreement between a qualified pharmacist and a physician allowing the pharmacist to perform specified patient care functions. A physician may not delegate authority to initiate or prescribe controlled substances to a pharmacist under this provision."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Certification Information", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/pharmacy-collaborative-practice-certification/", "description": "Florida Board of Pharmacy page with information about collaborative pharmacy practice certification, including required CE courses, agreement templates, and scope of delegated services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Links and Resources", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/resources/", "description": "Comprehensive resource page with links to Florida statutes (Chapters 465, 456, 893), administrative rules (Chapter 64B16), federal agency sources, telehealth resources, and pharmacy school information."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator for substance use disorders and mental health, which can be filtered to find buprenorphine treatment providers in Florida. Provides a searchable directory of treatment facilities across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "Directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine. Note that since the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023, all practitioners with DEA Schedules II-V registration can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD, so this list is not fully inclusive."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory (Florida)", "url": "https://dpt2.samhsa.gov/treatment/", "description": "Directory of certified opioid treatment programs (OTPs) including methadone clinics in Florida. Select Florida from the dropdown to view all OTPs in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "The Florida SOTA is Corine M. Stancil, located at 2415 North Monroe Street, Tallahassee, FL 32399. Phone: (850) 717-4653. Email: corine.stancil@myflfamilies.com. The SOTA oversees opioid treatment programs within the state under the Department of Children and Families."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida State Opioid Response (SOR) Project", "url": "https://www.myflfamilies.com/services/samh/samh-treatment-services-and-facilities/fsorp", "description": "The Florida DCF's State Opioid Response Project page, which provides comprehensive information about SOR-funded services including hospital bridge programs for MAT initiation, naloxone distribution, prevention programs, recovery support services, and buprenorphine/methadone treatment access expansion."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Prescribing of Controlled Substances", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS guidance on prescribing controlled substances (including buprenorphine) via telehealth. DEA-registered practitioners can prescribe schedule II-V controlled substances via telemedicine without an in-person evaluation if required conditions are met. Florida practitioners must comply with both federal and state telehealth laws."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Telehealth and Controlled Substances Legal Analysis", "url": "https://www.akerman.com/en/perspectives/hrx-harmonizing-federal-and-florida-laws-on-prescribing-controlled-substances-through-telehealth.html", "description": "Legal analysis of the interplay between federal DEA telehealth rules and Florida state law regarding prescribing controlled substances (including buprenorphine) via telehealth encounters."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Florida Medicaid Preferred Drug Program", "url": "https://ahca.myflorida.com/medicaid/prescribed-drugs/florida-medicaid-preferred-drug-program", "description": "The Agency for Health Care Administration (AHCA) page for Florida Medicaid's Preferred Drug Program, including the Preferred Drug List, pharmacy prior authorization forms, electronic prior authorizations, and drug utilization review information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL)", "url": "https://ahca.myflorida.com/medicaid/prescribed-drugs/medicaid-pharmaceutical-therapeutics-committee/florida-medicaid-preferred-drug-list-pdl", "description": "The Florida Medicaid Preferred Drug List, which includes buprenorphine products. The PDL is reviewed and updated following recommendations by the Pharmaceutical and Therapeutics (P&T) Committee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Medicaid Fee Schedules and Billing Codes", "url": "https://ahca.myflorida.com/medicaid/rules/rule-59g-4.002-provider-reimbursement-schedules-and-billing-codes", "description": "Rule 59G-4.002 provides the Florida Medicaid provider reimbursement schedules and billing codes, including fee schedules for various provider types. Fee schedules are incorporated by reference and available for download."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida State Opioid Response Grant Funding", "url": "https://www.myflfamilies.com/services/samh/samh-treatment-services-and-facilities/fsorp", "description": "Information about Florida's State Opioid Response (SOR) federal grant, administered through the Department of Children and Families, which funds buprenorphine and methadone treatment, naloxone distribution, recovery support services, and prevention programs for uninsured and underinsured individuals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "Federal SAMHSA State Opioid Response grant program information, which provides funding to states including Florida for increasing access to FDA-approved medications for OUD treatment, harm reduction, and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Federal and State Funding Sources for SUD Treatment", "url": "https://nashp.org/funding-options-for-states/", "description": "National Academy for State Health Policy resource outlining federal and state funding options for substance use disorder treatment programs, including the Comprehensive Opioid, Stimulant, and Substance Use Program (COSSUP) and other grants relevant to Florida providers."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Florida CE Requirements for Controlled Substances", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/continuing-education-requirements-update/", "description": "Florida Board of Pharmacy requirement that all licensed pharmacists complete a Board-approved 2-hour continuing education course on the \"Validation and Counseling of Prescriptions for Controlled Substances and Opioids\" during each biennial renewal period, in addition to the standard 30-hour CE requirement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida CE Requirements Summary", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/florida/", "description": "Summary of Florida pharmacist CE requirements: 30 hours per 2-year biennial cycle, including 2 hours on controlled substances, 2 hours on medication errors, and 10 hours of live programming. Consultant pharmacists have additional requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://floridapharmacy.org/on-demand-education/", "description": "On-demand continuing education programs offered by the Florida Pharmacy Association, which is accredited by ACPE as a provider of continuing pharmacy education and approved by the Florida Department of Health."}, {"type": "link", "title": "University of Florida Continuing Pharmacy Education", "url": "https://cpe.pharmacy.ufl.edu/", "description": "University of Florida College of Pharmacy continuing education programs, including Board-approved courses for controlled substance validation, medication errors, and collaborative practice agreement certification."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring for healthcare providers on evidence-based buprenorphine treatment. PCSS also provides one-on-one clinical guidance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/technical-assistance/pcss/pcss-moud", "description": "SAMHSA page on PCSS-MOUD training requirements for DEA registrations. Since the MATE Act (part of the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023), practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations to prescribe Schedule II-V medications must complete required training on substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Society of Health-System Pharmacists CE Information", "url": "https://fshp.org/ce-information/", "description": "CE requirement details and resources from the Florida Society of Health-System Pharmacists, including information about mandatory controlled substance and opioid education requirements and CE Broker tracking."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs in Florida", "url": "https://www.flhrc.org/services/", "description": "The Florida Harm Reduction Collective operates syringe services programs in Gainesville and Saint Petersburg, offering harm reduction services including free rapid HIV and hepatitis C testing. Florida's Infectious Disease Elimination Act (IDEA) allows county commissions to authorize sterile syringe services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IDEA Exchange (University of Miami)", "url": "https://ideaexchangeflorida.org/", "description": "Florida's first public clean syringe program, operated through the University of Miami. The IDEA Exchange Center distributes naloxone and harm reduction supplies in Miami-Dade County."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Harm Reduction Resources Directory", "url": "https://med.ucf.edu/harm-reduction/harm-reduction-resources/", "description": "UCF College of Medicine Harm Reduction Research Initiative resource page listing Florida syringe services programs across multiple counties including IDEA programs in Orlando, Miami, Tampa, Pinellas, and Alachua counties, as well as Rebel Recovery FLASH Exchange in Palm Beach and The SPOT in Broward."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Law (Section 381.887, Florida Statutes)", "url": "https://m.flsenate.gov/statutes/381.887", "description": "Florida statute authorizing pharmacists to dispense emergency opioid antagonists (naloxone) with autoinjection, prefilled injection, or intranasal delivery systems pursuant to a pharmacist's order or a non-patient-specific standing order, without a patient-specific prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.floridabar.org/the-florida-bar-news/legislature-approves-legalization-of-fentanyl-testing-strips/", "description": "The Florida Legislature has approved measures to decriminalize fentanyl test strips. Additional bills (HB 477, SB 646) have been introduced to further decriminalize the possession, distribution, and use of drug-testing products so residents can access life-saving information about controlled substances. Please verify current status of this legislation before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/statistics-data/overdose-reporting/", "description": "Florida Department of Health Drug Overdose Surveillance and Epidemiology page with overdose death data, Medical Examiner Commission annual drug reports, and trend information. According to the 2024 annual report, opioid-related deaths decreased by 26% compared to 2023."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Coalition of Florida", "url": "https://www.peersupportfl.org/", "description": "Statewide organization dedicated to promoting peer support services in Florida, providing training, advocacy, and community for Certified Recovery Peer Specialists. PSCFL offers a model for peer recovery support within the community."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Association of Recovery Residences (FARR)", "url": "https://www.farronline.org/", "description": "FARR is the statewide organization that sets standards and certifies recovery residences in Florida. Founded in 2011 to evaluate and monitor recovery housing, FARR is affiliated with the National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "FARR Certified Recovery Residence Directory", "url": "https://farronline.info/providers", "description": "Searchable directory of FARR-certified recovery residences across Florida, providing verified recovery housing options for individuals in recovery from substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida DCF Recovery Residence Information", "url": "https://www.myflfamilies.com/services/samh/recovery-residence-administrators-and-recovery-residences", "description": "Florida Department of Children and Families page on recovery residence administrators and recovery residences, with links to FARR for certification information and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida DCF Substance Abuse and Mental Health", "url": "https://www.myflfamilies.com/services/substance-abuse-and-mental-health", "description": "The Florida Department of Children and Families Substance Abuse and Mental Health (SAMH) Program, responsible for overseeing the statewide system of care for prevention, treatment, and recovery of children and adults with serious mental illnesses or substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "988 Florida Lifeline", "url": "https://www.myflfamilies.com/988", "description": "Florida's 988 Lifeline, managed by the Department of Children and Families, is a free behavioral health support service available 24/7 connecting Floridians experiencing suicidal thoughts, substance use disorder, mental health crises, or emotional distress to trained counselors. Call or text 988."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Florida Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/the-board/", "description": "The Florida Board of Pharmacy executive director is Traci Zeh, located at the Bureau of Health Care Practitioner Regulation, 4052 Bald Cypress Way, Bin C-04, Tallahassee, FL 32399-3254. Contact the Board directly through the helpful contacts page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Board of Pharmacy Contact Information", "url": "https://floridaspharmacy.gov/helpful-emails-numbers-addresses/", "description": "Complete contact directory for the Florida Board of Pharmacy including phone numbers, email addresses, and mailing addresses for licensing, renewals, and general inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida State Opioid Treatment Authority Contact", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "The Florida SOTA is Corine M. Stancil, Department of Children and Families, 2415 North Monroe Street, Tallahassee, FL 32399. Phone: (850) 717-4653. Email: corine.stancil@myflfamilies.com."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida DCF Substance Abuse and Mental Health Program Office", "url": "https://www.myflfamilies.com/services/samh/treatment", "description": "The DCF Substance Abuse and Mental Health Program Office is located at 2415 North Monroe Street, Suite 400, Tallahassee, FL 32303-4190. Phone: (850) 717-4427."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Pharmacy Association Contact", "url": "https://floridapharmacy.org/about-fpa/", "description": "The Florida Pharmacy Association (FPA) is the state's professional pharmacy organization providing advocacy, education, and member services. Contact through the website or the advocacy and legislation page for policy-related inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Department of Health Opioid Response", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/programs-and-services/opioid-response/index.html", "description": "Overview of the Florida Department of Health overdose response activities including the Overdose Data to Action in States (OD2A-S) program, which coordinates data surveillance and prevention strategies."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Florida Overdose Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/statistics-data/overdose-reporting/", "description": "Florida Department of Health page providing drug overdose surveillance and epidemiology data, including the Medical Examiner Commission's annual Drugs Identified and Deceased Persons reports, trend data, and county-level overdose statistics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "FL-DOSE (Florida Drug Overdose Surveillance and Epidemiology)", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/programs-and-services/opioid-response/fl-dose/index.html", "description": "The FL-DOSE program monitors non-fatal drug overdose visits at Florida emergency departments and hospitals, and collects fatal overdose data from death certificates and medical examiner reports for CDC's SUDORS system."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Medical Examiner Commission Annual Drug Reports", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/statistics-and-data/e-forcse/news-reports/index.html", "description": "News and reports from Florida's E-FORCSE program, including links to the Medical Examiner Commission's annual drug reports that provide detailed opioid-related death data by county and drug type."}, {"type": "link", "title": "E-FORCSE Prescription Drug Monitoring Reports", "url": "https://www.floridahealth.gov/statistics-data/prescription-drug-monitoring-e-forcse-2/", "description": "E-FORCSE program data on controlled substance prescribing patterns, which can be used to track prescribing trends and identify areas of concern for opioid diversion or misuse."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Opioid Settlement Information", "url": "https://floridaopioidsettlement.com/overview/", "description": "Overview of Florida's opioid settlement funds, which will be appropriated by the Legislature and Governor. The Department of Children and Families' Office of Substance Abuse and Mental Health, as the State Opioid Treatment Authority, oversees statewide prevention, treatment, and recovery efforts funded by settlement proceeds."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Florida Pharmacy Association Advocacy and Legislation", "url": "https://floridapharmacy.org/advocacy-legislation/", "description": "FPA's advocacy page tracking current legislation affecting pharmacy practice in Florida, including bill tracking documents, action alerts, and information about the Governmental Affairs Committee's lobbying efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Pharmacy Association Advocacy Issues", "url": "https://floridapharmacy.org/advocacy-issues/", "description": "Detailed page on specific advocacy issues being monitored by FPA, with information about proposed legislation, potential impacts on pharmacy practice, and ways for pharmacists to get involved."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Florida Legislators", "url": "https://www.flsenate.gov/Senators/Find", "description": "Florida Senate tool allowing residents to find their state senator, state representative, and congressional representative by entering their address. Links to legislator contact information and district details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Florida House Representative", "url": "https://www.flhouse.gov/FindYourRepresentative", "description": "Florida House of Representatives tool for identifying and contacting your state representative based on your address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Statewide Task Force on Opioid Abuse", "url": "https://doseofrealityfl.com/opioid-task-force.html", "description": "The 21-member Statewide Task Force on Opioid Abuse, chaired by the Florida Attorney General, was created by Executive Order 19-97 in 2019 to develop a coordinated and comprehensive statewide drug control and substance abuse prevention strategy covering education, prevention, treatment, recovery, and law enforcement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Florida Take Control of Controlled Substances Initiative", "url": "https://flhealthsource.gov/FloridaTakeControl/", "description": "State initiative providing comprehensive information about Florida's controlled substance laws affecting prescribers, dispensers, and pharmacists, including PDMP requirements and prescribing limitations."}]}]}, "georgia": {"name": "Georgia", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Georgia law does not expressly include the ability to prescribe medications. GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-4 (West 2024).\nAdditionally, the definition of “prescriber” within Georgia’s controlled substance laws includes only a physician, dentist or other person licensed in the state to prescribe a controlled substance. GA. CODE ANN. § 16-13-21(23.1) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Georgia cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Georgia practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Georgia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Georgia law includes “participation in . . . drug administration.” GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-4 (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nThe definition of “pharmacy care” in Georgia law also includes “participation in . . . drug administration” without caveat. GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-5(31)(A) (West 2024).Unlike the laws and regulations of several other states with general language about administration in the practice of pharmacy definition, there are no other Georgia laws or regulations that address administration of a small subset of drugs or medications (such as immunizations) that would give the impression that the legislature does not view the “drug administration” language as a broad authorization.\nUnder Georgia pharmacy law, “administer” means “the provision of a unit dose of medication to an individual patient as a result of the order of an authorized practitioner of the healing arts.” GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-5(1) (West 2024).", "2B": "A pharmacist must have a valid order from an authorized practitioner of the healing arts, which includes a physician, dentist, podiatrist, optometrist, or veterinarian. GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-5(33) (West 2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe statutory definition of “pharmacy care” includes “[o]rdering and administering . . . [t]ests that have been cleared or approved for home use by the [FDA] and interpreting the results as a means to screen for or monitor disease, disease risk factors, or drug use and to facilitate patient education.” GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-5(31) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Georgia practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nUnder Georgia medical practice law, “a physician may delegate to a pharmacist the authority to modify drug therapy as part of drug therapy management.” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024). Delegation of the authority, however, can be made only pursuant to “the physician’s diagnosis, written order, and drug therapy protocol.” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024).\n“Unless a drug therapy modification is a substitution of a generic drug which is pharmaceutically and therapeutically equivalent to the patient’s initial prescription drug order . .\n. [the] protocol shall meet the applicable requirements for issuance of prescriptions provided in [Georgia law].” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024). This suggests that the written order/drug therapy protocol (DTP) from the physician may serve as the prescription, as thus the pharmacist does not prescribe drugs as part of drug therapy management.\nMoreover, Georgia laws and regulations governing DTPs does not account for the fact that a Georgia pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the DTP directs.\nIn summary, Georgia laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances under a DTP. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Georgia pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Georgia law and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under DTPs.\nExpressly specify in Georgia law and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under DTPs.\nAllow Georgia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Georgia laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nUnder Georgia medical practice law, “a physician may delegate to a pharmacist the authority to modify drug therapy as part of drug therapy management.” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024). Delegation of the authority, however, can be made only pursuant to “the physician’s diagnosis, written order, and drug therapy protocol.” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024).\nGeorgia laws and regulations governing DTPs do not use the term “administer” nor do they expressly state what “modify drug therapy” means.\nIn summary, even though Georgia laws and regulations governing drug therapy management do not expressly provide what “modify drug therapy” means, given that Georgia pharmacists can administer drugs generally, a logical conclusion is that this includes administering buprenorphine under a DTP.", "5B": "Enter into a DTP (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in Georgia law and regulation that “to modify drug therapy as part of drug therapy management” includes administering drugs.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Georgia laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nUnder Georgia medical practice law, “a physician may delegate to a pharmacist the authority to modify drug therapy as part of drug therapy management.” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024). Delegation of the authority, however, can be made only pursuant to “the physician’s diagnosis, written order, and drug therapy protocol.” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024).\nGeorgia laws and regulations governing DTP do not expressly state what “modify drug therapy” means and there is no reference to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results.\nIn summary, although Georgia laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from ordering or administering all types of lab tests under a DTP they also do not clearly authorize those activities. Given the response in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that Georgia pharmacists have limited authority with respect to ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of a DTP, the most likely answer to this question is that pharmacists have the same limited authority under a DTP as they do outside of one.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Georgia law that under a DTP pharmacists can order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Under Georgia medical practice law, a physician may delegate to a pharmacist the authority to modify drug therapy as part of drug therapy management. GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(b) (West 2024).\n“Physician” means “a person licensed to practice medicine under [Title 43, Chapter 24, Article 2 of the Georgia statutes].” GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-21(2) (West 2024).\n“Pharmacist” means a person meeting the requirements of GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-50, which requires obtaining a certification from the state board of pharmacy. GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24(a) (West 2024).\nThe following Georgia laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering DTPs and required elements of DTPs – GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-24 (West 2024); GA. CODE ANN. § 26-4-50 (West 2024); GA. COMP. R. & REGS. 480-35-.01 to 480.35.08 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nGeorgia does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, Georgia insurance law provides that “it is the intent of the General Assembly to mitigate geographic discrimination in the delivery of health care by recognizing the application of and payment for covered medical care provided by means of telehealth, provided that such services are provided by a physician or by another health care practitioner or professional acting within the scope of practice of such health care practitioner.” GA. CODE ANN. § 33-24-56.4(c) (West 2024).\nThis provision does not define “health care practitioner” or “health care professional,” but it is worded broadly enough to include pharmacists and there is no indication that the legislature intends a more restrictive meaning.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Georgia laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Georgia laws and regulations governing telehealth include – GA. CODE ANN. § 33-24-56.4 (West 2024) (insurance coverage); GA. CODE ANN. § 43-34-31.1 (West 2024)\n(licensing for telemedicine physicians); GA. COMP. R. & REGS. 360-2-.17 (2024) (telemedicine licensure requirements – physicians); GA. COMP. R. & REGS. 360-3-.07 (2024)\n(medical practice through electronic means).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Georgia Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Georgia law or regulation that pharmacist services provided under DTPs are covered under the Georgia Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://georgia.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Georgia's PDMP (GA PMP AWARxE) login portal for prescribers, pharmacists, and delegates to query patient controlled substance dispensing histories. Each individual must register as a separate user with a unique email address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Information", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/pdmp", "description": "Georgia Department of Public Health PDMP information page. Effective July 1, 2017, dispensers must report Schedule II-V controlled substance prescriptions within 24 hours. All prescribers with a DEA number were required to register by January 1, 2018. Beginning July 1, 2018, prescribers must check the PDMP before prescribing opiates, cocaine derivatives (Schedule II), or benzodiazepines."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration Instructions", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/pdmp", "description": "To register, visit georgia.pmpaware.net/login. Prescribers and dispensers need their name, employment information, last 4 digits of SSN, GA professional license number, DEA number, and NPI number. Delegates must also upload a signed Delegate's Responsibility form."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Secretary of State PDMP Information", "url": "https://sos.ga.gov/how-to-guide/prescription-drug-monitoring-program", "description": "Secretary of State's guide on PDMP requirements including the mandatory check requirement for prescribers before prescribing certain controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "Georgia participates in PMP InterConnect, enabling interstate sharing of prescription drug monitoring data across state lines for authorized users."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://rules.sos.ga.gov/gac/511-7-2", "description": "Georgia Administrative Code Subject 511-7-2 containing the Prescription Drug Monitoring Program rules, including data submission requirements, access provisions, and de-identification of older records."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/", "description": "The Georgia State Board of Pharmacy is an eight-member board appointed by the Governor to protect, promote, and preserve the public health and safety through regulation of pharmacists, pharmacies, pharmacy interns, and pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/laws-policies-rules", "description": "Full document of the Georgia Pharmacy Practice Act including Title 16, Chapter 13 (Controlled Substances); Title 26, Chapter 4 (Pharmacists and Pharmacies); and Title 43, Chapter 1 (General Provisions). Also includes links to the Board Policy Manual."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://rules.sos.ga.gov/gac/480", "description": "Searchable directory of Georgia Board of Pharmacy Rules and Regulations (Chapter 480), covering licensure, renewals, continuing education, pharmacy practice, and controlled substance requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/about-us/contact-us", "description": "Contact information for the Georgia Board of Pharmacy for inquiries about licensure, regulations, and practice questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements", "url": "https://nastad.org/resources/pharmacists-authority-engage-collaborative-practice-agreements-and-initiate-prep-pep-and", "description": "Georgia authorizes collaborative practice agreements (CPAs) between pharmacists and physicians. The CPA must identify the scope of services covered, but Georgia statute explicitly prohibits a CPA from giving a pharmacist authority to prescribe a controlled substance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy and Pharmacist FAQs", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/faqs-other-information/pharmacy-and-pharmacist-faqs", "description": "Frequently asked questions from the Georgia Board of Pharmacy covering licensure renewal, continuing education requirements (see Board Rule 480-4-.06), pharmacy permits, and practice questions."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator for substance use disorders, searchable by location to find buprenorphine treatment providers and OUD treatment programs in Georgia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "Directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine in Georgia. Since the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023, all practitioners with DEA Schedules II-V registration can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://dpt2.samhsa.gov/treatment/", "description": "Directory of certified opioid treatment programs (OTPs) in Georgia, including methadone clinics and other medication-assisted treatment facilities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "The Georgia SOTA is Vonshurii S. Wrighten, Division of Addictive Diseases, Georgia Department of Behavioral Health, 2 Peachtree Street NW, Suite 22-283, Atlanta, GA 30303. Phone: (404) 416-5225. Email: vonshurii.wrighten@dbhdd.ga.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Prescribing of Controlled Substances", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS guidance on prescribing controlled substances including buprenorphine via telehealth. Practitioners must comply with both federal DEA rules and Georgia state telehealth regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stop Opioid Addiction Resources (Georgia DPH)", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/stopopioidaddiction/what-you-need-know-about-opioids/naloxone", "description": "Georgia Department of Public Health page on opioid addiction with links to naloxone information, treatment resources, and prevention programs."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Medicaid Preferred Drug Lists", "url": "https://dch.georgia.gov/providers/provider-types/pharmacy/preferred-drug-lists", "description": "Georgia Department of Community Health (DCH) page listing the Medicaid Fee-for-Service Outpatient Pharmacy Program preferred and non-preferred drug products, including drugs requiring prior approval, quantity limits, and therapy limits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Medicaid Prior Authorization Process", "url": "https://dch.georgia.gov/providers/provider-types/pharmacy/prior-authorization-process-and-criteria", "description": "The DCH page describing guidelines for drugs requiring Prior Authorization (PA) in the Georgia Medicaid Fee-for-Service/PeachCare for Kids Outpatient Pharmacy Program, including criteria for buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Medicaid Preferred Drug List (Current PDF)", "url": "https://fm.formularynavigator.com/FBO/4/Georgia_PDL_English.pdf", "description": "Current Georgia Medicaid-Approved Preferred Drug List in PDF format showing preferred and non-preferred medications and prior authorization requirements. Please verify this link before publishing as the URL may update with each revision."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "Federal SAMHSA State Opioid Response grant program providing funding to states including Georgia for increasing access to OUD medications, harm reduction, and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "GASPS Data Warehouse", "url": "https://gaspsdata.dbhdd.ga.gov/", "description": "Georgia's Substance Prevention System data warehouse operated by DBHDD, containing treatment data, funding information, and resources for OUD treatment programs in the state."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/faqs-other-information/pharmacy-and-pharmacist-faqs", "description": "Georgia pharmacists must complete continuing education hours as specified in Board Rule 480-4-.06 for biennial license renewal. Specific requirements for controlled substance education are outlined in the Board rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Board of Pharmacy CE Rules", "url": "https://rules.sos.ga.gov/gac/480-3", "description": "Chapter 480-3 of the Georgia Administrative Code covering renewals, inactive licenses, and continuing education requirements for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://www.gpha.org/", "description": "The Georgia Pharmacy Association (GPhA) provides continuing education programs, conferences, and educational resources for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians. GPhA has been the voice of pharmacy in Georgia for 150 years."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, mentoring, and clinical tools for healthcare providers on evidence-based buprenorphine treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/technical-assistance/pcss/pcss-moud", "description": "SAMHSA page on training requirements for DEA registrations under the MATE Act. Practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations must complete required training on substance use disorders."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://georgiaoverdoseprevention.org/", "description": "Georgia Overdose Prevention provides free naloxone kits, overdose reversal reporting, and education on overdose recognition and response. Offers online naloxone kit request form."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Information (Georgia DPH)", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/stopopioidaddiction/what-you-need-know-about-opioids/naloxone", "description": "Georgia Department of Public Health naloxone information page. Naloxone is available as an over-the-counter medication at most major pharmacies in Georgia. Georgia law allows pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a patient-specific prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro - Georgia Naloxone by Mail", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/georgia", "description": "Free naloxone-by-mail program for Georgia residents in partnership with Georgia Harm Reduction Coalition. Available to people who use drugs, those recently released from incarceration, or anyone likely to be a first responder to an opioid overdose."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: As of July 1, 2023, fentanyl test strips are legal in Georgia. They were previously classified as drug paraphernalia but have been exempted by state legislation. Source: Georgia Public Broadcasting and academic research from Georgia Southern University."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Surveillance Data and Dashboard", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/epidemiology/drug-surveillance", "description": "Georgia DPH Drug Surveillance Unit page providing opioid overdose surveillance data, annual surveillance reports, stimulant overdose data, PDMP surveillance reports, and drug-related health alerts. Includes county-level data and OASIS customizable data tools."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Association of Recovery Residences (GARR)", "url": "https://www.garronline.org/", "description": "GARR was founded in 1987 to evaluate and monitor quality of care in addiction recovery services in Georgia. GARR is an affiliate of the National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) and certifies recovery residences throughout the state. Phone: (404) 719-1218."}, {"type": "link", "title": "GARR Network Member Directory", "url": "https://www.thegarrnetwork.org/", "description": "Directory of GARR-certified recovery residences and programs in Georgia, providing a list of certified recovery housing options."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia DBHDD (Behavioral Health Agency)", "url": "https://dbhdd.georgia.gov/", "description": "The Georgia Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities is the state's behavioral health agency overseeing mental health, substance use disorder, and developmental disability services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Certified Peer Specialists (DBHDD)", "url": "https://dbhdd.georgia.gov/recovery-transformation/cps", "description": "DBHDD's Certified Peer Specialist program, including the Certified Peer Specialist - Addictive Disease (CPS-AD) credential for individuals with lived experience in addiction recovery. Training information available through the Georgia Mental Health Consumer Network."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Crisis and Access Line (GCAL)", "url": "https://dbhdd.georgia.gov/be-dbhdd/crisis-system-georgia", "description": "GCAL is Georgia's 24/7/365 crisis line at 1-800-715-4225 for mental health and substance use emergencies. GCAL is a nationally accredited crisis center and partner to the 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Operated by Carelon, a private-sector partner of DBHDD. Call or text 988 or 1-800-715-4225."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/about-us/contact-us", "description": "Contact the Georgia Board of Pharmacy for licensing, regulatory, and practice inquiries. The Board consists of eight members appointed by the Governor."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Vonshurii S. Wrighten, Division of Addictive Diseases, Georgia DBHDD, 2 Peachtree Street NW, Suite 22-283, Atlanta, GA 30303. Phone: (404) 416-5225. Email: vonshurii.wrighten@dbhdd.ga.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Drugs and Narcotics Agency (GDNA)", "url": "https://gdna.georgia.gov/", "description": "GDNA oversees controlled substance regulation in Georgia, including pharmacy inspections and the PDMP program. Phone: (404) 656-5100. Toll Free: (800) 656-6568. Address: 254 Washington Street SW, Suite G2000, Atlanta, GA 30334."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.gpha.org/", "description": "GPhA is the largest professional association for pharmacists, pharmacy owners, technicians, and students in Georgia. Founded in 1875, GPhA provides advocacy, education, and member services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Department of Public Health - Opioid Response", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/stopopioidaddiction/what-you-need-know-about-opioids/naloxone", "description": "Georgia DPH opioid response page with naloxone information, treatment resources, and overdose prevention programming."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Surveillance Dashboard (Georgia DPH)", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/epidemiology/drug-surveillance", "description": "Georgia DPH Drug Surveillance Unit provides opioid-involved overdose surveillance data including annual reports, county and district-level data, stimulant overdose surveillance, and PDMP annual surveillance reports."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Overdose Surveillance Reports", "url": "https://gaspsdata.dbhdd.ga.gov/data/opioid-overdose-surveillance-report", "description": "GASPS Data Warehouse page with opioid overdose surveillance reports describing fatal and nonfatal opioid-involved overdoses in Georgia, including prescription opioids, heroin, fentanyl, and fentanyl analogs analyzed from hospital discharge and vital records data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "GASPS Data Warehouse", "url": "https://gaspsdata.dbhdd.ga.gov/", "description": "Georgia's comprehensive substance use prevention data warehouse providing treatment data, related links, prevention resources, and overdose surveillance information aggregated from multiple state data sources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Annual Surveillance Reports", "url": "https://dph.georgia.gov/epidemiology/drug-surveillance", "description": "Annual PDMP surveillance reports available through the Drug Surveillance page, providing data on controlled substance prescribing patterns across Georgia."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Georgia Opioid Settlement Information: The Georgia Opioid Settlement funds are overseen through the state legislature and the Attorney General's office for distribution to opioid prevention, treatment, and recovery programs."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.gpha.org/", "description": "GPhA provides state and local-level advocacy for pharmacists. The association actively monitors legislation such as SB 195 and other bills affecting pharmacy practice and OUD treatment in Georgia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Georgia Legislator", "url": "https://www.legis.ga.gov/find-my-legislator", "description": "Georgia General Assembly tool to find your state senator and representative by entering your address. Provides direct links to legislator contact information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact State Legislators (Georgia.gov)", "url": "https://georgia.gov/contact-state-legislators", "description": "Georgia.gov resource for contacting elected officials by phone, email, mail, or social media with information on how to reach state legislators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Board of Pharmacy Laws and Policies", "url": "https://gbp.georgia.gov/laws-policies-rules", "description": "Access to current Georgia pharmacy law, Board rules, and policy manual for monitoring legislative and regulatory changes affecting pharmacist prescribing and practice scope."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Statewide Task Force on Opioid Abuse", "url": "https://doseofrealityfl.com/opioid-task-force.html", "description": "Note: Georgia does not have a single centralized opioid task force website. Multiple county-level task forces exist (e.g., Pinellas County). The Georgia DBHDD and DPH coordinate statewide opioid response efforts. For the latest Georgia-specific opioid coalition information, contact DBHDD directly. Please verify this link before publishing as it references the Florida Dose of Reality initiative."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Georgia Recovery Community Organizations Legislation", "url": "https://www.gpb.org/news/2026/03/10/how-georgia-might-legislate-nonprofit-recovery-community-organizations-and-define", "description": "Recent coverage of Georgia General Assembly efforts to define and regulate Recovery Community Organizations and certified peer support specialists through legislation."}]}]}, "hawaii": {"name": "Hawaii", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Hawaii law does not expressly include prescribing any drugs or medications except for “prescribing and dispensing an opioid antagonist” and “prescribing and dispensing contraceptive supplies.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” items (2)(I) and (4)).\nMoreover, the application instructions for a practitioner’s Hawaii controlled substance registration provides that a practitioner with “a DO, DOS, DT, DTT, MD, PO, or VE medical license may apply with this application.”\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Hawaii cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Hawaii practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Hawaii pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Hawaii law expressly includes “administering drugs orally, topically, by intranasal delivery, or by injection pursuant to the order of the patient’s licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024)\n(“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(D)).\nHawaii law defines “drug” broadly and the pharmacy laws do not otherwise limit the administering drugs provision described above.", "2B": "Obtain authorization via the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes “ordering, performing, and reporting the results of the following [eight listed] CLIA-waived tests.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (5)).\nIn addition, the practice of pharmacy includes “ordering drug therapy related laboratory tests.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2(B)). Hawaii law does not provide additional explanation for what this provision covers, however.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Hawaii practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe practice of pharmacy includes “initiating emergency contraception oral drug therapy in accordance with a written collaborative agreement.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(C)). Hawaii pharmacy law does not mention collaborative practice or CPAs in any other context. Accordingly, a pharmacist may be limited to participating in collaborative practice only with respect to emergency contraception.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy allows for “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient” so long as it is “authorized by the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority” and “pursuant to an order or authorization” by such individual. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(F)).\nHawaii law does not expressly identify what constitutes “initiating . . . the drug regimen of a patient” and Hawaii law does not expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe drugs or medications other than opioid antagonists or contraceptives.\nMoreover, Hawaii law governing the initiation or adjustment of a drug regimen does not account for the fact that a Hawaii pharmacist cannot obtain a state controlled substance registration (if any) or a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the instructions from the healthcare provider direct.\nIn summary, Hawaii law governing the initiation or adjustment of a drug regimen does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Hawaii pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Hawaii law and/or regulation to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under the law allowing pharmacists to initiate or adjust the drug regimen of a patient.\nExpressly specify in Hawaii laws or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under the law allowing pharmacists to initiate or adjust the drug regimen of a patient.\nAllow Hawaii pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Hawaii laws do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Hawaii law includes “initiating emergency contraception oral drug therapy in accordance with a written collaborative agreement.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024)\n(“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(C)). Hawaii pharmacy law does not mention collaborative practice or CPAs in any other context. Accordingly, a pharmacist may be limited to participating in collaborative practice only with respect to emergency contraception.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy allows for “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient” so long as it is “authorized by the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority” and “pursuant to an order or authorization” by such individual. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(F)). Hawaii law does not expressly identify what constitutes “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient.”\nAs a result, Hawaii law governing the initiation or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient does not expressly provide for pharmacist administration of drugs. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that the practice of pharmacy generally includes administering drugs or medications pursuant to the order of certain healthcare providers, the logical conclusion is that the same authority applies as part of initiating or adjusting a drug regimen.", "5B": "Obtain the authorization via the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "As described in the information below, Hawaii laws do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Hawaii law includes “initiating emergency contraception oral drug therapy in accordance with a written collaborative agreement.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024)\n(“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(C)). Hawaii pharmacy law does not mention collaborative practice or CPAs in any other context. Accordingly, a pharmacist may be limited to participating in collaborative practice only with respect to emergency contraception.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy allows for “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient” so long as it is “authorized by the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority” and “pursuant to an order or authorization” by such individual. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(F)).\nHawaii law does not expressly identify what constitutes “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient” or whether it includes ordering or evaluating lab tests. Nevertheless, as described in the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the practice of pharmacy includes “ordering, performing, and reporting the results of the following [eight listed] CLIA-waived tests.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (5)).\nFinally, the practice of pharmacy expressly includes “ordering drug therapy related laboratory tests.” HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2(B)). Hawaii law does not provide additional explanation for this provision, however, and it is possible it only relates to initiating emergency contraception oral drug therapy in accordance with a written collaborative agreement.", "6B": "Obtain the authorization via the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Hawaii law and/or regulation what “ordering drug therapy related laboratory tests” means.\nExpressly specify in Hawaii law and/or regulation that under their authority for “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient,” pharmacists can order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Hawaii pharmacy law does not mention collaborative practice or CPAs in any other context besides initiating emergency contraception oral drug therapy. Accordingly, a pharmacist may be limited to participating in such practice only with respect to emergency contraception.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy allows for “initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient” so long as it is “authorized by the written instructions of a licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority” and “pursuant to an order or authorization” by such individual. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(F)).\nTo initiate or adjust a drug regimen, the pharmacist must have a valid order from the patient’s licensed physician, physician assistant, or advanced practice registered nurse with prescriptive authority. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(D)).\nThe pharmacist must also satisfy the training and education requirements specified in Hawaii law. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy,” item (2)(D)).\nThe only Hawaii law/regulation pertaining to initiating or adjusting a drug regimen is HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 461-1 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy”).", "8A": "As described in the information below, Hawaii laws do not clearly answer this question.\nHawaii does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. While Hawaii law contains general health insurance provisions related to telehealth, the definition of “health care provider” in those laws are complicated and do not clearly indicate that pharmacists fall under it. HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 431:10A-116.3(g), 432D-23.5(g) (West 2024).\nMoreover, other than insurance laws, Hawaii laws and regulations reference “telehealth” and/or “telemedicine” only with respect to physicians, dentists, nurses, licensed marriage therapists, mental health counselors, psychologists, radiologic technicians, social workers and veterinarians.", "8B": "Expressly provide in Hawaii laws and regulations that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "Hawaii law and regulations governing telehealth include – HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 346.59.1 (West 2024) (insurance coverage – Medicaid); HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 431:10A-116.3 (West 2024) (insurance coverage); HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 432D-23.5 (West 2024) (insurance coverage – HMO); HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 453-1.3 (West 2024)\n(physicians); HAW. REV. STAT. ANN. § 671-7 (West 2024) (professional liability insurance); HAW. CODE REG. § 17-1737-51.1 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Hawaii Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Hawaii law or regulation that pharmacist services provided for initiating or adjusting the drug regimen of a patient pursuant to written instructions of certain healthcare providers are covered under the Hawaii Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://hawaii.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Hawaii's PDMP (HI PMP AWARxE) login portal for prescribers and pharmacists to query patient controlled substance dispensing histories. Located at 3375 Koapaka Street, Suite D100, Honolulu, HI 96819. Support: 844-544-4767."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Information", "url": "https://law.hawaii.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/HAWAII-PDMP-FREQUENTLY-ASKED-QUESTIONS_updated-2018-FOR-WEB.pdf", "description": "Hawaii PDMP Frequently Asked Questions document explaining the program's scope, registration requirements, and data access. The PDMP monitors Schedule II-IV controlled substance prescriptions to help prevent prescription drug misuse and improve quality of care."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://hawaii.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "New users can create an account at the HI PMP AWARxE portal. Contact the Hawaii PDMP at (808) 837-8470 or hawaiicsreg@hawaii.gov for registration assistance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Data Submission Guide", "url": "https://law.hawaii.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/HI-PDMP-Data-Submission-Dispenser-Guide_v3.0.pdf", "description": "Dispenser guide for submitting controlled substance prescription data to the Hawaii PDMP through the PMP Clearinghouse system."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "Hawaii participates in PMP InterConnect, enabling interstate sharing of prescription drug monitoring data across state lines for authorized users."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Hawaii law requires prescribers to check the PDMP before prescribing controlled substances. Dispensers must submit prescription data for Schedule II-IV controlled substances. For specific statutory requirements, see HRS Chapter 329, Part IX."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://cca.hawaii.gov/pvl/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "The Hawaii Board of Pharmacy, under the Department of Commerce and Consumer Affairs (DCCA) Professional and Vocational Licensing Division, regulates pharmacists, pharmacies, and pharmacy interns in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Pharmacy Practice Act (HRS Chapter 461)", "url": "https://files.hawaii.gov/dcca/pvl/pvl/hrs/hrs_pvl_461.pdf", "description": "Full text of HRS Chapter 461, the Hawaii Pharmacy Practice Act governing the practice of pharmacy, including definitions, licensure requirements, and pharmacy operations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statutes and Rules", "url": "https://cca.hawaii.gov/pvl/boards/pharmacy/statute_rules/", "description": "Links to all relevant Hawaii statutes and rules for pharmacy practice: HAR Chapter 95 (Pharmacists and Pharmacies), HRS Chapter 461 (Pharmacists and Pharmacy), HRS Chapter 436B (Uniform Professional and Vocational Licensing Act), and HRS Chapter 329 (Uniform Controlled Substances Act)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (HAR Chapter 95)", "url": "https://files.hawaii.gov/dcca/pvl/pvl/har/har_95-c.pdf", "description": "Hawaii Administrative Rules Title 16, Chapter 95 governing pharmacists and pharmacies, including practice standards, continuing education, and compounding requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Applications and Forms", "url": "https://cca.hawaii.gov/pvl/boards/pharmacy/application_publications/", "description": "Licensure applications, forms, and publication information for Hawaii pharmacists, pharmacy interns, and pharmacies."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice: Hawaii does not have a comprehensive collaborative practice agreement statute comparable to some other states. Pharmacist prescriptive authority is limited. For the most current information on pharmacist prescribing scope, consult HRS Chapter 461 and HAR Chapter 95."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator for substance use disorders, searchable by location to find buprenorphine treatment providers and OUD treatment programs in Hawaii."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "Directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine in Hawaii. Since the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023, all practitioners with DEA Schedules II-V registration can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://dpt2.samhsa.gov/treatment/", "description": "Directory of certified opioid treatment programs in Hawaii, including methadone clinics and medication-assisted treatment facilities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "The Hawaii SOTA is Kathi Fujii, State of Hawaii Department of Health, Alcohol and Drug Abuse Division, 601 Kamokila Boulevard, Room 360, Kapolei, HI 96707. Phone: (808) 692-7523. Email: kathi.fujii@doh.hawaii.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii CARES Crisis Line", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/substance-abuse/", "description": "For substance use treatment services, contact Hawaii CARES at (808) 832-3100 or toll-free 1(800) 753-6879. The Alcohol and Drug Abuse Division (ADAD) is the primary source of public funds for substance abuse treatment in Hawaii."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Prescribing of Controlled Substances", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS guidance on prescribing controlled substances including buprenorphine via telehealth. Practitioners must comply with both federal DEA rules and Hawaii state telehealth regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Medicaid (MedQUEST) Drug Coverage", "url": "https://medquest.hawaii.gov/en/plans-providers/pharmacy/drug-coverage.html", "description": "Hawaii Medicaid drug coverage information through the MedQUEST Division, detailing covered products, coverage restrictions, plan limits, and clinical criteria for the fee-for-service pharmacy program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Medicaid MCO Formulary Search", "url": "https://medquest.hawaii.gov/en/plans-providers/pharmacy/drug-coverage/mco-formulary-search.html", "description": "Formulary search tools for Hawaii Medicaid managed care organizations including AlohaCare, HMSA, Kaiser Permanente, Ohana, and UnitedHealthCare, allowing providers to check medication coverage including buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Medicaid Pharmacy Provider Memos", "url": "https://medquest.hawaii.gov/en/plans-providers/pharmacy/communications/provider-memos.html", "description": "Archive of provider communications from MedQUEST regarding pharmacy benefits, drug list updates, and coverage changes for the Medicaid program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "Federal SAMHSA State Opioid Response grant program providing funding to states including Hawaii for increasing access to OUD medications, harm reduction, and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Federal and State Funding Sources", "url": "https://nashp.org/funding-options-for-states/", "description": "NASHP resource outlining federal and state funding options for substance use disorder treatment programs, including grants relevant to Hawaii OUD treatment providers."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Board of Pharmacy CE Information", "url": "https://cca.hawaii.gov/pvl/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "Hawaii Board of Pharmacy page with information about continuing education requirements for pharmacist license renewal. Specific CE requirements are outlined in HAR Chapter 95."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.hipharm.org/", "description": "The Hawaii Pharmacists Association (HPhA) provides continuing education, legislative updates, and professional development resources for pharmacists in Hawaii."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, mentoring, and clinical tools for healthcare providers on evidence-based buprenorphine treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/technical-assistance/pcss/pcss-moud", "description": "SAMHSA page on training requirements for DEA registrations under the MATE Act. Practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registrations must complete required training on substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "University of Hawaii OD2A-C3 Training Resources", "url": "https://manoa.hawaii.edu/c3od2a/hawaii-programs/", "description": "Hawaii State resources from the Overdose Data to Action (OD2A) Care Coordination and Capacity Building project, including the Hawaii Opioid Initiative collaboration of public health, public safety, healthcare professionals, and community partners."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Services Branch", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/harmreduction/for-providers/overdose-prevention-and-naloxone/", "description": "Hawaii Department of Health Harm Reduction Services Branch page for providers with information on overdose prevention and naloxone. Please verify this link before publishing as the site may block automated access."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Health and Harm Reduction Center (HHHRC)", "url": "https://nasen.org/sep/hawaii-health-and-harm-reduction-center", "description": "Hawaii Health and Harm Reduction Center operates syringe exchange services available on 4 Hawaiian Islands. NASEN directory listing with contact information and service hours. Website: https://www.hhhrc.org/"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Laws", "url": "https://www.safeproject.us/naloxone/state-rules/", "description": "Hawaii law allows healthcare providers (including pharmacists) to make naloxone available to anyone at risk of overdose, anyone in a position to assist someone at risk, or to harm reduction organizations. Hawaii permits standing orders for naloxone distribution."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.civilbeat.org/2023/05/hawaii-is-set-to-decriminalize-fentanyl-test-strips-as-drug-overdoses-reach-record-highs/", "description": "Hawaii has moved to decriminalize fentanyl test strips. Legislation has been passed to remove fentanyl test strips from the definition of drug paraphernalia to support overdose prevention and harm reduction efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Behavioral Health Data Dashboard", "url": "https://bh808.hawaii.gov/", "description": "State of Hawaii Department of Health Behavioral Health Dashboard providing substance use data including hospitalizations, overdose deaths, mental health crisis data, and co-occurring substance use and mental health indicators. Includes interactive dashboards for statewide and county-level data."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Alcohol and Drug Abuse Division (ADAD)", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/substance-abuse/", "description": "The Hawaii Department of Health Alcohol and Drug Abuse Division is the primary and often sole source of public funds for substance abuse treatment. ADAD promotes a statewide, culturally appropriate, comprehensive system of services for treatment and recovery. Located at 601 Kamokila Blvd, Room 360, Kapolei, HI 96707. Phone: (808) 692-7506."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Hawaii CARES Crisis Line: Contact Hawaii CARES at (808) 832-3100 or toll-free 1(800) 753-6879 for substance use treatment services referrals and crisis assistance.", "description": "Hawaii CARES provides 24/7 crisis intervention, referral, and access to substance use and mental health treatment services statewide."}, {"type": "note", "text": "988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline: Call or text 988 for immediate crisis support including substance use-related emergencies. Available 24/7/365.", "description": "The national 988 Lifeline is available in Hawaii for suicidal thoughts, substance use crises, and emotional distress. Connected to local crisis centers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Opioid Initiative", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/substance-abuse/files/2019/06/THE-HAWAII-OPIOID-INITIATIVE-1.0-A-Statewide-Response-to-Opioid-Use-and-Other-Substance-Misuse.pdf", "description": "The Hawaii Opioid Initiative (HOI) is a collaboration of public health, public safety, healthcare professionals, and community partners working to address opioid and substance misuse, including recovery support services. PDF document outlining the statewide response."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Hawaii does not have a state-specific recovery residence certification organization affiliated with NARR at the same scale as some other states. For recovery housing resources, contact ADAD at (808) 692-7506 or the Hawaii CARES line."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://cca.hawaii.gov/pvl/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "Contact the Hawaii Board of Pharmacy through the DCCA Professional and Vocational Licensing Division for licensing, regulatory, and practice inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Kathi Fujii, Hawaii Department of Health, Alcohol and Drug Abuse Division, 601 Kamokila Boulevard, Room 360, Kapolei, HI 96707. Phone: (808) 692-7523. Email: kathi.fujii@doh.hawaii.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Alcohol and Drug Abuse Division (ADAD)", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/substance-abuse/", "description": "ADAD, Department of Health, 601 Kamokila Blvd, Room 360, Kapolei, HI 96707. Phone: (808) 692-7506. Primary state agency for substance abuse prevention, treatment, and recovery coordination."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.hipharm.org/", "description": "HPhA provides advocacy, education, legislative updates, and professional support for pharmacists in Hawaii. Email: info@hipharm.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Department of Health", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/", "description": "The Hawaii Department of Health oversees public health programs including the Harm Reduction Services Branch, ADAD, and behavioral health initiatives related to opioid use disorder."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Behavioral Health Dashboard", "url": "https://bh808.hawaii.gov/", "description": "State of Hawaii Behavioral Health Dashboard with interactive data visualizations covering substance use hospitalizations, overdose deaths, mental health indicators, co-occurring conditions, and crisis data. Provides statewide and county-level trend analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Surveillance (Hawaii DOH)", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/substance-abuse/", "description": "The ADAD collects and reports on substance use data including treatment admissions, program outcomes, and epidemiological surveillance. Contact ADAD for specific data requests."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Opioid Settlement Website", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/news/newsroom/doh-launches-hawai%CA%BBi-opioid-settlement-website/", "description": "Hawaii DOH launched an opioid settlement website with three primary data dashboards including the Opioid Overdose Data Dashboard tracking overdose deaths and emergency department visits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OD2A-C3 Project Resources", "url": "https://manoa.hawaii.edu/c3od2a/hawaii-programs/", "description": "Hawaii State resources from the CDC-funded Overdose Data to Action, Care Coordination and Capacity Building project, providing data on overdose trends and program outcomes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Opioid Initiative Report", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/substance-abuse/files/2019/06/THE-HAWAII-OPIOID-INITIATIVE-1.0-A-Statewide-Response-to-Opioid-Use-and-Other-Substance-Misuse.pdf", "description": "Comprehensive report on Hawaii's statewide response to opioid use and substance misuse, including data on the scope of the crisis, treatment capacity, and strategic initiatives."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Pharmacists Association Legislative Updates", "url": "https://www.hipharm.org/news", "description": "HPhA news page featuring legislative updates and advocacy information affecting pharmacy practice in Hawaii."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Hawaii Legislator", "url": "https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/legislature/findleg.aspx", "description": "Hawaii State Legislature tool to find your state senator and representative by entering your street or road name. Provides direct links to legislator contact information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Legislature Website", "url": "https://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/", "description": "Official Hawaii State Legislature website for tracking bills, accessing committee information, and following legislation related to pharmacy practice and opioid treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Opioid Initiative", "url": "https://manoa.hawaii.edu/c3od2a/hawaii-programs/", "description": "The Hawaii Opioid Initiative (HOI) is a collaboration of public health, public safety, healthcare professionals, and community partners working to address opioid misuse and promote evidence-based treatment approaches."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Hawaii Harm Reduction Services Branch", "url": "https://health.hawaii.gov/harmreduction/", "description": "Hawaii DOH Harm Reduction Services Branch coordinating statewide harm reduction efforts including syringe services, naloxone distribution, and overdose prevention education. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}]}, "idaho": {"name": "Idaho", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Idaho’s term for a CPA appears to be a “protocol” or “agreement” for collaborative practice. IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024); IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.351 (2024).", "1A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Idaho law includes both the “provision of pharmaceutical care services” and the “prescribing of drugs and devices.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “pharmaceutical care services” in Idaho regulation includes “prescribing drugs and devices as provided in these rules.” IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.010(19)(f) (2024).\nMoreover, Idaho regulation expressly provides that “a pharmacist may independently prescribe” any drug or medication, if the pharmacist complies with the requirements provided in regulation which include maintaining appropriate educational levels, establishing a patient relationship, and only practicing within the scope of learning. IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.350 (2024).\nGeneral pharmacist prescribing authority results from an Idaho law that took effect in July 2023. However, DEA’s latest published information (dated November 2024) continues to indicate—as it did in the prior version of DEA’s information (dated December 2022)—that registered pharmacists in Idaho can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Administer, Prescribe, & Dispense” controlled substances, only “pursuant to a collaborative agreement with prescriber.” Based on the information above, this is not correct.", "1B": "Any practitioner “who intends to prescribe, administer, dispense, or conduct research with a controlled substance” must first obtain: (1) an Idaho controlled substance registration for practitioners; (2) a valid license or registration to prescribe medications from an Idaho licensing entity; and (3) a DEA registration. IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.224 (2024). Pharmacists wishing to prescribe drugs or medications must comply with the requirements specified in regulation including maintaining the proper education for the drugs being dispensed, establishing a patient-prescriber relationship, obtaining adequate information regarding a patient’s health to make decisions on standard of care, recognizing the limits of the pharmacist’s own knowledge, collaborating with other health care professionals when necessary, and maintaining documentation as necessary. IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.350 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "1C": null, "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Idaho law expressly includes both the “provision of pharmaceutical care services” and “administration . . . of prescription drug orders.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “pharmaceutical care services” in Idaho regulation includes “medication administration . . . as provided in these rules.” IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.010(19)(e) (2024).\nIdaho regulation also makes clear that a pharmacist’s authority includes “direct administration of a medication.” IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.350.06 (2024).", "2B": "Any practitioner “who intends to prescribe, administer, dispense, or conduct research with a controlled substance” must first obtain: (1) an Idaho controlled substance registration for practitioners; (2) a valid license or registration to prescribe medications from an Idaho licensing entity; and (3) a DEA registration. IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.224 (2024).Idaho regulation provides that it is not necessary for a pharmacist to comply with the “pharmacist prescribing” requirements in IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.350 to directly administer medications to a patient. IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.350.06 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes the “provision of pharmaceutical care services.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “pharmaceutical care services” includes “ordering and interpreting laboratory tests and imaging.” IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.010(19)(d) (2024).", "3B": "Understand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "3C": null, "4A": "As described in the information below, Idaho laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes “collaborative pharmacy practice.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024). “Collaborative pharmacy practice” means a pharmacy practice where one or more pharmacists or pharmacies jointly agree to work under a protocol authorized by one or more prescribers to provide “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist under specified conditions.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024). Idaho laws and regulations do not provide additional explanation about allowed or disallowed collaborative pharmacy practice activities.\nAlthough Idaho laws and regulations are unclear about the scope of collaborative practice, given the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has the independent authority to prescribe controlled substances, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "4B": "Enter into a collaborative practice protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent prescribing, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": "Although not completely necessary, revise Idaho laws and/or regulations to expressly provide that a pharmacist can prescribe controlled substances under a collaborative practice protocol.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Idaho laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes “collaborative pharmacy practice.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024).\n“Collaborative pharmacy practice” means a pharmacy practice where one or more pharmacists or pharmacies jointly agree to work under a protocol authorized by one or more prescribers to provide “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist under specified conditions.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024). Idaho laws and regulations do not provide additional explanation about allowed or disallowed collaborative pharmacy practice activities. Although Idaho laws and regulations are unclear about the scope of collaborative practice, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has the independent authority to administer drugs and medications generally, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a collaborative practice protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, revise Idaho laws and/or regulations to expressly provide that a pharmacist can administer controlled substances under a collaborative practice protocol.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Idaho laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes “collaborative pharmacy practice.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024).\n“Collaborative pharmacy practice” means a pharmacy practice where one or more pharmacists or pharmacies jointly agree to work under a protocol authorized by one or more prescribers to provide “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist under specified conditions.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024). Idaho laws and regulations do not provide additional explanation about allowed or disallowed collaborative pharmacy practice activities.\nAlthough Idaho laws and regulations are unclear about the scope of collaborative practice, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has the independent authority to order and interpret laboratory tests and imaging, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "6B": "Enter into a collaborative practice protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Although not completely necessary, revise Idaho laws and/or regulations to expressly provide that under a collaborative practice protocol, a pharmacist can order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Collaborative pharmacy practice involves one or more pharmacists or pharmacies jointly agreeing to work under a protocol authorized by one or more prescribers. IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(46) (West 2024).\n“Prescriber” means “an individual currently licensed, registered or otherwise authorized to prescribe and administer drugs in the course of professional practice.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704(51) (West 2024).\nThe following Idaho laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering collaborative practice protocols or agreements – IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-1704 (West 2024); IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 24.36.01.351 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nUnder Idaho’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law, a “provider” is defined as “any health care provider who is licensed or required to be licensed under this title [Title 54 of the Idaho Code]” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-5703(2) (West 2024). Pharmacists are included in this definition.\n“Health care services” includes the “assessment, diagnosis, consultation, treatment, and remote monitoring of a patient.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-5703(1) (West 2024).\n“A provider delivering health care services via virtual care must at all times act within the scope of the provider’s license.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-5704 (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "Controlled substances may be prescribed via telehealth. IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-5707(1) (West 2024).\nIdaho law and regulations governing telehealth include – IDAHO CODE ANN. § 54-5701 to 54-5714 (West 2024)\n(virtual care access act); IDAHO ADMIN. CODE R. 16.03.09.210 (09) (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "Pharmacists appear to be full providers under the Idaho Medicaid program if the pharmacist chooses to become enrolled.", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Idaho law covering “narcotic drugs – treatment of addicts” provides that “a person seeking treatment or rehabilitation for drug addiction or dependency shall first be examined and evaluated by a physician” who “shall prescribe a proper course of treatment and medication, if needed.” IDAHO CODE ANN. § 37-3103 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://idaho.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Idaho Prescription Monitoring Program (IPMP) login portal powered by PMP AWARxE. For assistance, contact the Idaho Board of Pharmacy at 208-334-3233. Support line: 855-543-4767."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Information", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/", "description": "The Idaho PDMP is administered by the Idaho Board of Pharmacy (now under the Division of Occupational and Professional Licenses - DOPL). The Board requires pharmacists and prescribers (except veterinarians) to annually register with the Board to obtain online access to the controlled substances prescriptions database."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://idaho.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "New users can create an account at the Idaho PMP AWARxE portal. Click \"Create an Account\" on the login page. Pharmacists and prescribers must register annually as required by Idaho law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Statutes and Rules", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/bop-statutes-rules-and-guidance/", "description": "Idaho Board of Pharmacy statutes, rules, and guidance including IDAPA 24.36.01 (Rules of the Idaho State Board of Pharmacy) and relevant sections of the Idaho Code governing the PDMP."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "Idaho participates in PMP InterConnect, enabling interstate sharing of prescription drug monitoring data across state lines for authorized users."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Idaho law requires prescribers to check the PDMP before prescribing controlled substances. Pharmacists and prescribers must register annually for PDMP access. For specific requirements, see Idaho Code sections referenced on the Board of Pharmacy PDMP page."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/", "description": "The Idaho State Board of Pharmacy operates under the Division of Occupational and Professional Licenses (DOPL). The Board regulates pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, and pharmacies in Idaho. Contact: HP-Licensing@dopl.idaho.gov or 208-334-3233. Mailing address: DOPL, 550 W. State St., Boise, ID 83702."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Pharmacy Practice Act and Rules", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/bop-statutes-rules-and-guidance/", "description": "Idaho Board of Pharmacy statutes, rules, and guidance page with links to IDAPA 24.36.01 (Rules of the Idaho State Board of Pharmacy) and proposed rule changes. The pharmacy practice act is contained in Idaho Code Title 54, Chapter 17."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Licensing", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/bop-licensing/", "description": "Application and renewal information for Idaho pharmacy licenses and registrations through the DOPL Online Services page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Meetings", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/mec-category/board-of-pharmacy/", "description": "Schedule and information for Idaho Board of Pharmacy meetings, including agendas and minutes."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice: Idaho law permits pharmacist collaborative practice under certain conditions. For current statutes on pharmacist prescriptive authority and collaborative practice arrangements, consult Idaho Code Title 54, Chapter 17 and IDAPA 24.36.01 through the statutes and rules page."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator for substance use disorders, searchable by location to find buprenorphine treatment providers and OUD treatment programs in Idaho."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "Directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine in Idaho. Since the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023, all practitioners with DEA Schedules II-V registration can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://dpt2.samhsa.gov/treatment/", "description": "Directory of certified opioid treatment programs in Idaho, including methadone clinics and medication-assisted treatment facilities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "The Idaho SOTA is Brandi Clark, Idaho Department of Health and Welfare, Division of Behavioral Health, 450 W. State St., 3rd Floor, Boise, ID 83702. Phone: (208) 512-5895. Email: brandi.clark@dhw.idaho.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho State Opioid Response (ISOR) Project", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/behavioral-health-providers/idahos-state-opioid-response", "description": "Idaho's State Opioid Response project page describing SAMHSA-funded efforts to expand MAT access, increase naloxone distribution, support peer recovery services, law enforcement diversion programs, and emergency department warm handoff programs. For help with opioid use, call 1-855-202-0973 Monday through Friday 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. MT."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Prescribing of Controlled Substances", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS guidance on prescribing controlled substances including buprenorphine via telehealth. Practitioners must comply with both federal DEA rules and Idaho state telehealth regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Medicaid Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/pharmacy-providers/idaho-medicaid-pharmacy-program", "description": "Idaho Medicaid Pharmacy Program page with information on the Preferred Drug List, prior authorization requirements, claims processing, and pharmacy benefit administration through Prime Therapeutics. Idaho Medicaid Pharmacy call center: 208-364-1829 or toll free 866-827-9967. Prior authorization fax: 800-327-5541."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://publicdocuments.dhw.idaho.gov/WebLink/DocView.aspx?id=702&dbid=0&repo=PUBLIC-DOCUMENTS&cr=1", "description": "Idaho Medicaid Preferred Drug List with prior authorization criteria. The list includes coverage information for buprenorphine products and other OUD medications. Please verify this link before publishing as document links may change."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prime Therapeutics (Idaho Medicaid PBA)", "url": "https://idaho.fhsc.com/", "description": "Prime Therapeutics is the Idaho Medicaid Pharmacy Benefit Administrator. Provider support: 800-922-3987 (available 24/7). Member line: 888-773-9466."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "Federal SAMHSA State Opioid Response grant program providing funding to states including Idaho for increasing access to OUD medications, harm reduction, and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Federal and State Funding Sources", "url": "https://nashp.org/funding-options-for-states/", "description": "NASHP resource outlining federal and state funding options for substance use disorder treatment programs, including grants relevant to Idaho OUD treatment providers."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Board of Pharmacy CE Information", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/bop-licensing/", "description": "Idaho Board of Pharmacy licensing page with information about continuing education requirements for pharmacist license renewal. Idaho has moved to a 2-year renewal cycle."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho State Pharmacy Association (ISPA)", "url": "https://idahopharmacy.weebly.com/", "description": "ISPA provides education, advocacy, and professional support for pharmacists in Idaho. ISPA lobbies for pharmacy-related legislation and facilitates Pharmacy Day at the Capitol."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Society of Health-System Pharmacy (ISHP)", "url": "https://ishp.wildapricot.org/", "description": "ISHP provides continuing education, networking, and professional development for health-system pharmacists in Idaho."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, mentoring, and clinical tools for healthcare providers on evidence-based buprenorphine treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Project ECHO Idaho", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/behavioral-health-providers/idahos-state-opioid-response", "description": "Idaho's State Opioid Response program funds Project ECHO Idaho sessions, a virtual educational resource that empowers healthcare professionals in the treatment of OUD. Project ECHO provides telementoring and case-based learning for providers."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Naloxone Access Information", "url": "https://eiph.id.gov/healthy-living/drug-alcohol-prevention/drug-overdose-prevention/what-is-naloxone-and-a-where-can-i-get-it/", "description": "Eastern Idaho Public Health information on naloxone access. In Idaho, anyone with a valid reason can ask for a prescription for naloxone from a physician, PA, nurse practitioner, or pharmacist. Those who administer naloxone during an overdose are protected by Idaho's Naloxone Access Law and Good Samaritan Law (Idaho Code 54-1733B)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Naloxone Distribution (State Opioid Response)", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/behavioral-health-providers/idahos-state-opioid-response", "description": "The Idaho Office of Drug Policy uses State Opioid Response funds to provide naloxone kits to first responders and other agencies working with individuals with OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Laws in Idaho", "url": "https://www.networkforphl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Idaho-Harm-Reduction-Laws_FINAL.pdf", "description": "Network for Public Health Law fact sheet on harm reduction and overdose prevention laws in Idaho, including naloxone access provisions under Idaho Code 54-1733B."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips are legal in Idaho. The Idaho Legislature legalized access to fentanyl testing strips in 2024, passing the House unanimously. However, the Legislature simultaneously repealed the Safe Syringe and Needle Exchange Act, eliminating the state syringe services program."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services: Idaho repealed its Safe Syringe and Needle Exchange Act in 2024. As a result, syringe services programs are no longer authorized under state law. For current harm reduction resources, contact the Idaho Office of Drug Policy or local health districts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Prevention Program", "url": "https://cdh.idaho.gov/hl-rx-drugs.php", "description": "Central District Health Drug Overdose Prevention Program improving access to and education on naloxone as a harm reduction tool to prevent overdose."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Division of Behavioral Health - SUD Services", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/behavioral-health-providers/behavioral-health-service-providers", "description": "The Division of Behavioral Health's SUD Services Program contracts with Magellan of Idaho to provide statewide treatment and recovery support services funded through the SAMHSA SUPTRS Block Grant. Services available for qualifying individuals and families."}, {"type": "link", "title": "About Substance Use Disorder (Idaho HW)", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health/about-substance-use-disorder", "description": "Idaho Department of Health and Welfare page on substance use disorder resources. For help quitting opioids, call 1-855-202-0973, Monday through Friday 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. MT for a confidential screening."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Behavioral Health Resources", "url": "https://www.empoweridaho.org/idaho-behavioral-health-resources/", "description": "Empower Idaho compiles behavioral health resources including Recovery Idaho (peer support and recovery tools) and the Idaho Office of Drug Policy Prevention Resources Dashboard."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Health, Behavioral Health and SUD Services", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/services-programs/health-behavioral-health-and-substance-use-disorder", "description": "Idaho Department of Health and Welfare portal for health, behavioral health, and substance use disorder services with an online database for locating free, low-cost, or sliding scale resources in your area."}, {"type": "note", "text": "988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline: Call or text 988 for immediate crisis support including substance use-related emergencies in Idaho. Available 24/7/365.", "description": "The national 988 Lifeline is available in Idaho for suicidal thoughts, substance use crises, and emotional distress."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Idaho does not have a state-specific recovery residence certification organization affiliated with NARR at the same scale as some other states. The State Opioid Response program supports community-based peer support and sober living activities. For housing resources, contact Idaho CARES or the Division of Behavioral Health."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Board of Pharmacy (DOPL)", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/", "description": "Idaho State Board of Pharmacy under the Division of Occupational and Professional Licenses. Contact: HP-Licensing@dopl.idaho.gov or 208-334-3233. Headquarters: 11341 W. Chinden Blvd., Boise, ID 83714. Mailing: DOPL, 550 W. State St., Boise, ID 83702."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Brandi Clark, Idaho Department of Health and Welfare, Division of Behavioral Health, 450 W. State St., 3rd Floor, Boise, ID 83702. Phone: (208) 512-5895. Email: brandi.clark@dhw.idaho.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Office of Drug Policy", "url": "https://odp.idaho.gov/", "description": "The Idaho Office of Drug Policy coordinates statewide drug prevention efforts, prescription drug take-back programs, naloxone distribution, and youth substance use prevention. Contact: https://odp.idaho.gov/contact-us/"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Department of Health and Welfare", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/", "description": "The Idaho Department of Health and Welfare oversees Medicaid, behavioral health services, substance use disorder programs, and the Division of Behavioral Health."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Medicaid Pharmacy Program Contact", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/pharmacy-providers/idaho-medicaid-pharmacy-program", "description": "Idaho Medicaid Pharmacy call center: 208-364-1829 or toll free 866-827-9967. Prime Therapeutics Provider Support: 800-922-3987. Myers and Stauffer: 800-591-1183."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Drug Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://prevention.odp.idaho.gov/data-sources/", "description": "Idaho Office of Drug Policy publications and data sources page with links to the IDHW Drug Overdose Prevention Program (DOPP) Idaho Drug Overdose Data Dashboard and other surveillance data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Office of Drug Policy - Issues and Trends", "url": "https://odp.idaho.gov/issues-trends/", "description": "Idaho Office of Drug Policy page tracking current issues and trends including opioids, stimulants, marijuana, alcohol, vaping, and other substance use data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho State Opioid Response Data", "url": "https://healthandwelfare.idaho.gov/providers/behavioral-health-providers/idahos-state-opioid-response", "description": "The Idaho State Opioid Response project tracks OUD treatment outcomes, naloxone distribution data, and overdose reduction metrics as part of SAMHSA grant requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Substance Misuse Prevention Data", "url": "https://prevention.odp.idaho.gov/data-sources/", "description": "Comprehensive list of publications and data sources for substance misuse prevention in Idaho, including state and national surveys, treatment data, and overdose surveillance reports."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho PDMP Surveillance", "url": "https://dopl.idaho.gov/bop/", "description": "The Idaho Board of Pharmacy administers the PDMP, which collects data on controlled substance and opioid antagonist prescriptions dispensed in Idaho. PDMP data is used for surveillance of prescribing trends."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Idaho State Pharmacy Association (ISPA)", "url": "https://idahopharmacy.weebly.com/", "description": "ISPA advocates for pharmacy-related legislation in Idaho and facilitates Pharmacy Day at the Capitol, connecting pharmacists with their legislators on key issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Idaho Legislator", "url": "https://legislature.idaho.gov/legislators/whosmylegislator/", "description": "Idaho Legislature's \"Who's My Legislator?\" tool allowing residents to find their state senator and house representatives by entering their street address and zip code."}, {"type": "link", "title": "How to Contact Your Legislators", "url": "https://odp.idaho.gov/contact-legislators/", "description": "Idaho Office of Drug Policy resource for contacting legislators, with instructions on finding your representatives through the Idaho Legislature website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Legislature Homepage", "url": "https://legislature.idaho.gov/", "description": "Official Idaho State Legislature website for tracking bills, accessing committee information, and following legislation related to pharmacy practice and opioid treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Fentanyl Test Strip Legalization", "url": "https://legislature.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/sessioninfo/2024/legislation/H0441.pdf", "description": "Idaho House Bill 441 (2024) legalizing access to fentanyl testing strips. The bill passed the House unanimously and the Senate with minimal opposition. Note: the Legislature simultaneously repealed the Safe Syringe and Needle Exchange Act in the same session."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Idaho Office of Drug Policy", "url": "https://odp.idaho.gov/", "description": "The Idaho Office of Drug Policy coordinates statewide drug prevention, provides grants to prevention organizations, and partners with state and federal agencies on substance use prevention strategies. The ODP oversees prescription drug take-back programs and naloxone distribution efforts."}]}]}, "illinois": {"name": "Illinois", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Illinois law comprises 17 identified activities, but none of those expressly involve prescribing drugs or medications. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d) (West 2024).\nAdditionally, a prescription may only be issued by a physician (which includes dentist, veterinarian, podiatric physician or optometrist), physician assistant, or advance practice nurse. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(e) (West 2024).\n The above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Illinois cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Illinois practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Illinois pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine. The authorization broadens (slightly) once new legislation takes effect January 1, 2025.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Illinois law includes “drug administration limited to the administration of oral, topical, injectable, and inhalation” as further specified in the law. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4) (West 2024).As of October 2024, a pharmacist may administer “injections of long-acting or extended-release form opioid antagonists for the treatment of substance use disorder, pursuant to a valid prescription by a physician licensed to practice medicine in all its branches.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(B-5) (West 2024).This authorization, however, applies only “following the initial administration” of it by a physician. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(B-5) (West 2024).\n However, as of January 1, 2025, a pharmacist can administer “long-acting injectables for mental health or substance use disorders pursuant to a valid prescription by the patient’s physician licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, advanced practice registered nurse, or physician assistant.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(D) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 ILL. LEGIS. SERV. 103-612 (West). The new language covers the initial administration of the medication.\nThere does not appear to be authority in Illinois law or regulation for a pharmacist to administer any form of buprenorphine other than a long-acting injectable.", "2B": "The answer to this question prior to January 1, 2025 differs somewhat from the answer on or after January 1, 2025.\nBefore January 1, 2025, the pharmacist: (1) needs a valid prescription by a physician licensed to practice medicine; and (2) must wait for the physician to perform the initial administration. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(B-5) (West 2024).\nOn or after January 1, 2025, the pharmacist needs a valid prescription from the patient’s physician, advanced practice registered nurse, or physician assistant. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(D) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 ILL. LEGIS. SERV. 103-612 (West).\nBefore January 1, 2025, the authorization applies after “completion of appropriate training, including how to address contraindications and adverse reactions, including, but not limited to, respiratory depression and the performance of cardiopulmonary resuscitation.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(B-5) (West 2024).On or after January 1, 2025, the pharmacist must complete “appropriate training conducted by an Accreditation Council of Pharmaceutical Education accredited provider, including how to address contraindications and adverse reactions set forth by rule.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(4)(D) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 ILL. LEGIS. SERV. 103-612 (West).\nBoth before and after January 1, 2025, the pharmacist must notify the patient’s physician and keep appropriate records.", "2C": "Expand the Illinois practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering additional forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment in addition to long-acting injectable forms.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Illinois law includes “the initiation, dispensing, or administration of drugs, laboratory tests, assessments, referrals, and consultations for human immunodeficiency virus pre-exposure prophylaxis and human immunodeficiency virus post-exposure prophylaxis under Section 43.5.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(14) (West 2024).\nAlso, the practice of pharmacy includes “ordering and administration of point of care tests, screenings, and treatments for (i) influenza, (ii) SARS-CoV-2, (iii) Group A Streptococcus, (iv) respiratory syncytial virus, (v) adult-stage head louse, and (vi) health conditions identified by a statewide public health emergency.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(17) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Illinois practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Illinois law includes “medication therapy management.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(11) (West 2024).\n“Medication therapy management services” (MTMS) means “a distinct service or group of services offered by licensed pharmacists, physicians licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, advanced practice registered nurses authorized in a written agreement with a physician licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, or physician assistants authorized in guidelines by a supervising physician that optimize therapeutic outcomes for individual patients through improved medication use.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024).\nIllinois law further specifies that in “a retail or other non-hospital pharmacy,” MTMS consists of “the evaluation of prescription drug orders and patient medication records to resolve conflicts” with 12 specified things (e.g., allergies, contraindications, adverse drug reactions, etc.). ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024). This provision does not cover pharmacist prescribing.\nMTMS “may also include patient care functions authorized by a physician . . . for his or her identified patient or groups of patients under specified conditions or limitations in a standing order from the physician.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024). Illinois law does not provide additional explanation about the extent of “patient care functions” a physician can authorize and whether it includes prescribing.\nHowever, Illinois law governing MTMS does not account for the fact that an Illinois pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the written agreement or standing order provides.\nIn summary, Illinois law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of MTMS. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Illinois pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Illinois law to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under a written agreement or standing order for MTMS.\nExpressly specify in Illinois law how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under written agreements or standing orders for MTMS.\nAllow Illinois pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Illinois law does not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” at least to the same extent.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Illinois includes “medication therapy management.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(11) (West 2024).\n“Medication therapy management services” (MTMS) means “a distinct service or group of services offered by licensed pharmacists, physicians licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, advanced practice registered nurses authorized in a written agreement with a physician licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, or physician assistants authorized in guidelines by a supervising physician that optimize therapeutic outcomes for individual patients through improved medication use.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024).\nIllinois law further specifies that in “a retail or other non-hospital pharmacy,” MTMS consists of “the evaluation of prescription drug orders and patient medication records to resolve conflicts” with 12 specified things (e.g., allergies, contraindications, adverse drug reactions, etc.). ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024). This provision does not expressly cover pharmacist administration of drugs or medications. MTMS “may also include patient care functions authorized by a physician . . . for his or her identified patient or groups of patients under specified conditions or limitations in a standing order from the physician.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024). Illinois law does not provide additional explanation about the extent of “patient care functions” a physician can authorize and whether or not it includes administration.\nAlthough Illinois MTMS law is unclear on administering buprenorphine, given the the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer certain forms of buprenorphine, the logical answer is to this question is “yes,” at least to that same limited extent described in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section. The authorization broadens (slightly) once new legislation takes effect January 1, 2025.", "5B": "The answer until January 1, 2025 differs somewhat from the answer on or after January 1, 2025.see the independent administration of buprenorphine sectionand (2B) for more information.\nEnter into a written agreement or standing order covering MTMS (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in Illinois law that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a written agreement or standing order for MTMS.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Illinois law does not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Illinois includes “medication therapy management.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d)(11) (West 2024). “Medication therapy management services” (MTMS) means “a distinct service or group of services offered by licensed pharmacists, physicians licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, advanced practice registered nurses authorized in a written agreement with a physician licensed to practice medicine in all its branches, or physician assistants authorized in guidelines by a supervising physician that optimize therapeutic outcomes for individual patients through improved medication use.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024).\nIllinois law further specifies that in “a retail or other non-hospital pharmacy,” MTMS consists of “the evaluation of prescription drug orders and patient medication records to resolve conflicts” with 12 specified things (e.g., allergies, contraindications, adverse drug reactions, etc.). ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024). This provision does not expressly cover pharmacist ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nMTMS “may also include patient care functions authorized by a physician . . . for his or her identified patient or groups of patients under specified conditions or limitations in a standing order from the physician.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024). Illinois law does not provide additional explanation about the extent of “patient care functions” a physician can authorize and whether it includes ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nAlthough Illinois MTMS law is unclear on ordering or evaluating lab tests, given the response in (3A) above that a pharmacist has limited authority to order or evaluate lab tests outside of MTMS, the logical conclusion is that the same limited authority applies.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Illinois law that a pharmacist’s authority as part of MTMS includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "MTMS involves a written agreement or standing order between one or more pharmacists, physicians, advanced practice registered nurses authorized in a written agreement with a physician, or physician assistants authorized in guidelines by a supervising physician. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(aa) (West 2024).\nThe only Illinois law or regulation pertaining to MTMS is 225 ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 85/3(d), (aa) (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nUnder Illinois’ general telehealth/telemedicine law, “a health care professional may engage in the practice of telehealth services in Illinois to the extent of his or her scope of practice as established in his or her respective licensing Act consistent with the standards of care for in-person services.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 150/15(a) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “health care profession” includes pharmacists. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 150/5 (West 2024).\n“Telehealth services” includes “mental health treatment and substance use disorder treatment.” ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 150/5 (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "Illinois laws and regulations governing telehealth include – 225 ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 150/1 to 150/15 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); 215 ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 5/356z.22 (West 2024) (insurance coverage); 225 ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 60/49.5 (West 2024) (physicians); 305 ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN. 5/5-50 (West 2024) (Medicaid coverage for SUD telehealth services); ILL. ADMIN. CODE tit. 89, § 140.403 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "A group or individual policy of accident and health insurance or a managed care plan must cover health care or patient care services provided by a pharmacist relating to hormonal contraceptives or HIV prophylaxis if the health plan provides coverage for the same service provided by a licensed physician, an advanced practice registered nurse, or a physician assistant. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN 5/356z.45 (West 2024).\nAs of January 1, 2025, a group or individual policy of accident and health insurance or a managed care plan must cover health care or patient care services provided by a pharmacist relating to vaccinations and COVID/influenza testing and treatment in the health plan provides coverage for the same service provided by a licensed physician, an advanced practice registered nurse, or a physician assistant. ILL. COMP. STAT. ANN 5/356z.63 (West 2024).112", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Illinois Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Illinois laws and/or regulations that pharmacist health care or patient care services performed as part of MTMS are covered under the Illinois Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://idfpr.illinois.gov/profs/boards/pharmacy.html", "description": "The Illinois State Board of Pharmacy operates under the Department of Financial and Professional Regulation (IDFPR). The Board is composed of eleven members including eight licensed pharmacists, two public members, and one pharmacy technician, all appointed by the Governor."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Full Text)", "url": "https://ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/ilcs3.asp?ActID=1318&ChapterID=24", "description": "The Illinois Pharmacy Practice Act (225 ILCS 85), full text available through the Illinois General Assembly website. Covers the definition of pharmacy practice, licensure requirements, scope of practice, and regulatory provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://www.ilga.gov/agencies/JCAR/EntirePart?titlepart=06801330", "description": "Title 68, Part 1330 of the Illinois Administrative Code contains the administrative rules implementing the Pharmacy Practice Act, including regulations on continuing education, licensing, and practice standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements", "url": "https://ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/ilcs3.asp?ActID=1318&ChapterID=24", "description": "Illinois authorizes collaborative pharmacy practice agreements under the Pharmacy Practice Act (225 ILCS 85). Section 4.5 establishes the Collaborative Pharmaceutical Task Force. Pharmacists may enter into collaborative practice agreements with physicians for expanded clinical services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing and Clinical Authority", "url": "https://idfpr.illinois.gov/profs/pharm.html", "description": "Illinois pharmacists have authority to administer vaccinations, prescribe and dispense naloxone under standing orders, and engage in certain clinical services. The IDFPR pharmacy profession page provides current information on scope of practice updates and licensure requirements."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "State Treatment and Recovery Resources", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/treatment.html", "description": "The Illinois Department of Public Health provides comprehensive information on OUD treatment including medication-assisted treatment (MAT) with buprenorphine, counseling, and recovery support services. Includes the Illinois Helpline at 1-833-2FINDHELP."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Treatment Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's Buprenorphine Treatment Locator allows users to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine. Can be filtered by state (Illinois) to find local providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Illinois SOTA contact is Richard Weisskopf, IDHS Division of Substance Use Prevention and Recovery, 401 S. Clinton St, 2nd Floor, Chicago, IL 60607. Phone: (312) 814-6380. Email: richard.weisskopf@illinois.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IDHS Division of Substance Use Prevention and Recovery (SUPR)", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=29759", "description": "IDHS/SUPR is the state's lead agency for addressing substance use disorders, providing a recovery-oriented system of care including prevention, intervention, treatment, and recovery support services for individuals with SUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=171182", "description": "IDHS information on the DEA/HHS final rule (January 2025) permitting DEA-registered prescribers to prescribe Schedule III-V controlled substances including buprenorphine via telemedicine for OUD treatment. Illinois Telehealth Act is at 225 ILCS 60/49.5."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Pharmacy Benefit Homepage", "url": "https://hfs.illinois.gov/medicalproviders/pharmacy.html", "description": "The Illinois Department of Healthcare and Family Services (HFS) Medicaid pharmacy program covers prescription drugs and some OTC products from manufacturers with signed rebate agreements with CMS. Some drugs require prior approval."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://hfs.illinois.gov/medicalproviders/pharmacy/preferred.html", "description": "The Illinois Medicaid Preferred Drug List includes buprenorphine products. Users can search for prior approval status by drug or view the complete preferred drug list. Email notification is available when new lists are posted."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Preferred Drug List Search", "url": "https://hfs.illinois.gov/medicalproviders/pharmacy/medicaid-preferred-drug-list.html", "description": "Additional Medicaid PDL resources including drug prior approval information, pharmaceutical labeler rebate agreements, and the Drugs and Therapeutics Advisory Board agenda."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Fee Schedule", "url": "https://hfs.illinois.gov/medicalproviders/medicaidreimbursement/pharmacist-fee-schedule.html", "description": "Illinois Medicaid pharmacist fee schedule listing reimbursement rates for pharmacist-provided services. The fee schedule is updated periodically (most recent effective 04/01/2024)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities (Opioid Settlement)", "url": "https://www.ilopioidsettlements.com/", "description": "The Illinois Opioid Settlements Initiative provides information on opioid settlement funding, approved uses, and application opportunities (NOFOs) for OUD treatment programs and community-based services. Additional SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grant information is available through IDHS/SUPR."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Safe Opioid Prescribing CE Requirements", "url": "https://idfpr.illinois.gov/content/dam/soi/en/web/idfpr/faq/dpr/safe-opioid-rx-ce-faq.pdf", "description": "Illinois requires prescribers licensed to prescribe controlled substances to complete continuing education on safe opioid prescribing practices. This FAQ document details the CE requirements, including a minimum of 1 hour of opioid-specific training per renewal cycle."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IPhA Certificate Training Programs", "url": "https://www.ipha.org/certificate-training-programs/", "description": "The Illinois Pharmacists Association (IPhA) offers APhA Certificate and Advanced Training Programs including immunization delivery, diabetes care, MTM services, and other pharmacy practice training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IPhA Continuing Education Programs", "url": "https://www.ipha.org/webinars-and-cpe-programs/", "description": "IPhA webinars and CPE programs including required CE courses for pharmacists and technicians. Topics include HIV prevention, pharmacist-prescribed PrEP/PEP for Illinois pharmacists, and other clinical education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA resources for the Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act, which requires practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registration with Schedule II-V authority to complete substance use disorder training, including buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD (Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders) offers modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring resources to enhance provider knowledge in evidence-based buprenorphine treatment practices."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.illinoisharmreduction.org/syringe-access", "description": "The Illinois Harm Reduction and Recovery Coalition provides a directory of syringe service programs (SSPs) in Illinois, resources for safer injection, and information on registering as an SSP under the Overdose Prevention and Harm Reduction Act (Public Act 101-0356)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order and Access", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/overdose-reversal.html", "description": "Illinois offers a statewide standing order allowing pharmacists and opioid overdose education and naloxone distribution (OEND) programs to provide naloxone without a direct individual prescription. The page includes the standing order and educational resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standardized Procedure", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/overdose-reversal/standardized-procedure.html", "description": "The updated Naloxone Standardized Procedure outlines how entities may become authorized to obtain, dispense, and administer naloxone for reversing opioid overdoses, including educational requirements and administration techniques."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Prevention Program (DOPP) - Free Naloxone", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=58142", "description": "IDHS/DBHR manages the Drug Overdose Prevention Program (DOPP), which allows organizations to order free Narcan through the Access Narcan program to distribute within their communities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality and Overdose Surveillance", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/prevention.html", "description": "Fentanyl test strips are legal in Illinois. The state was included in legislation explicitly removing drug checking equipment from paraphernalia laws. The IDPH Prevention and Harm Reduction page includes information on substance testing and overdose prevention resources."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Support Services", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=36696", "description": "IDHS provides information on Certified Recovery Support Specialist (CRSS) and Certified Peer Recovery Specialist (CPRS) programs, training requirements, and certification processes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Specialist Training", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=143289", "description": "The CRSS Success Program supports students with lived experience of mental health or substance use recovery to complete requirements for CRSS or CPRS certification. Administered by IDHS."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Residence Registry", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=115597", "description": "The IDHS Recovery Residence Registry connects individuals to safe, healthy living environments that promote recovery from alcohol and other drug use. Recovery residences are defined as sober, safe housing that supports recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IDHS Division of Substance Use Prevention and Recovery", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=29759", "description": "IDHS/SUPR serves as the state behavioral health agency for substance use disorders, overseeing community-based treatment programs and providing a recovery-oriented system of care."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis and Warmline Contacts", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=123539", "description": "Illinois Helpline for Opioids and Other Substances: 1-833-2FINDHELP (available 24/7). Illinois Warm Line: 866-359-7953 for non-crisis mental health and substance use support. The Warm Line is staffed by Wellness Support Specialists with lived experience in recovery."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://idfpr.illinois.gov/profs/boards/pharmacy.html", "description": "Illinois State Board of Pharmacy is housed within the Department of Financial and Professional Regulation (IDFPR). Board liaison: Diane Casas, 312-814-5325, Diane.Casas@illinois.gov. Board Chair: Tomson George, RPh."}, {"type": "link", "title": "HFS Medicaid Director Contact", "url": "https://hfs.illinois.gov/about/phonedirectory.html", "description": "Illinois Department of Healthcare and Family Services (HFS), Director: Elizabeth M. Whitehorn. Director's Office: 217-782-1200 or 312-793-4792. HFS manages the state Medicaid program including pharmacy benefits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Richard Weisskopf, IDHS Division of Substance Use Prevention and Recovery, 401 S. Clinton St, 2nd Floor, Chicago, IL 60607. Phone: (312) 814-6380. Email: richard.weisskopf@illinois.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Illinois Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.ipha.org/", "description": "The Illinois Pharmacists Association (IPhA) is the state's professional pharmacy organization dedicated to advancing pharmacy practice, providing CE, and leading public policy efforts. Contact via website or 217-522-7300."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IDPH Opioid Program", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids.html", "description": "The Illinois Department of Public Health (IDPH) manages the state's opioid response program including data surveillance, naloxone distribution, harm reduction, and treatment resources. Contact IDPH for opioid-related public health inquiries."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Data Dashboard", "url": "https://idph.illinois.gov/OpioidDataDashboard/", "description": "The IDPH interactive Opioid Data Dashboard provides mortality and morbidity data including overdose rates per 10,000 population, cause of overdose breakdowns (heroin vs. other opioids), and demographic details for geographical areas across Illinois."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Data and Reporting Overview", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/idph-data-dashboard.html", "description": "IDPH opioid data reporting page with summary statistics on opioid overdose deaths (3,261 in 2022, an 8.2% increase from 2021), trends in synthetic opioid deaths, and comparisons to other causes of death."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Semiannual Overdose Reports", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/idph-data-dashboard/semiannual-opioid-reports/opioid-report-may-2022.html", "description": "Statewide Semiannual Opioid Reports provide detailed analysis of opioid overdose trends, county-level fatality rates, monthly patterns, and demographic breakdowns. Reports are published twice yearly by IDPH."}, {"type": "link", "title": "County-Level Data", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/content/dam/soi/en/web/idph/publications/idph/topics-and-services/opioids/idph-data-dashboard/semiannual-overdose-report_102023.pdf", "description": "The Statewide Semiannual Overdose Report includes county-level opioid fatality rates per 100,000 capita, provisional county-level data, and detailed geographic analysis. Available as PDF download."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Dashboard Detail", "url": "https://dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/opioids/idph-data-dashboard/overdoses.html", "description": "Detailed overdose data dashboard from IDPH providing information on opioid-related emergency department visits, hospitalizations, and fatalities across Illinois, with interactive filtering capabilities."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "IPhA Advocacy Center", "url": "https://www.ipha.org/advocacy-center/", "description": "The Illinois Pharmacists Association Advocacy Center provides resources on current legislation affecting pharmacy including PBM reform (HB1697), how-to guides for filing witness slips with the Illinois General Assembly, and advocacy tools for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IPhA Pharmacy Protection Fund", "url": "https://www.ipha.org/pharmacy-protection-fund/", "description": "IPhA's Pharmacy Protection Fund provides resources to defend pharmacy legislation, support rulemaking, and ensure that legislative initiatives deliver results for the profession and patients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Illinois Legislators", "url": "https://www.ilga.gov/", "description": "The Illinois General Assembly website provides tools to find state legislators by district. For direct contact, call 217-782-2000 or 312-814-3500. The MyILGA account system enables users to manage witness slips and track legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Illinois Opioid Settlements Initiative", "url": "https://www.ilopioidsettlements.com/", "description": "Comprehensive resource for Illinois opioid settlement funding and programs. Provides information on approved uses of opioid settlement funds, NOFOs for community organizations, and resources on implementing the State of Illinois Overdose Action Plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Illinois Opioid Remediation Advisory Board", "url": "https://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=146327", "description": "The IDHS Opioid Remediation Advisory Board oversees the distribution and use of opioid settlement funds. Contact: DHS.OpioidSettlementFunds@Illinois.gov. The board advises on funding priorities and community-based opioid response strategies."}]}]}, "indiana": {"name": "Indiana", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Indiana laws/regulations do not refer to collaborative pharmacy practice. The statutory definition of the practice of pharmacy references “medication therapy management” (MTM), although Indiana’s definition for MTM does not seem to match up with collaborative pharmacy practice. IND. CODE § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy”; “medication therapy management”). Another Indiana law provides that a pharmacist has the power to “perform . . . drug regimen review.” IND. CODE § 25-26-13-31(a)(2) (West 2024). Again, the term “drug regimen review” does not seem to match up with collaborative pharmacy practice. IND. CODE § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024) (“drug regimen review”). Nevertheless, a separate chapter of Indiana law provides that pharmacists can adjust a patient’s “drug regimen,” under a “protocol.” IND. CODE §§ 25-26-16-1 to 25-26-16-12 (West 2024). Therefore, Indiana’s term for a CPA is a “protocol” that adjusts a patient’s drug regimen.", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Indiana does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024).\nAlthough not contained within the definition of the practice of pharmacy, a pharmacist can prescribe certain specified FDA-approved “devices or supplies.” IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-31(a)(5) (West 2024). This prescribing authorization does not include buprenorphine.\nAlso, while a pharmacy is part of the definition of “practitioner,” pharmacists are not one of the types of practitioners eligible for the state’s “practitioner” controlled substance registration that allows the prescribing of controlled substances.115 IND. CODE ANN. § 35-48-1-24 (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Indiana cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Indiana practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Indiana pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Indiana laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Indiana law includes “the . . . administering . . . of drugs and devices . . . whether dispensed under a practitioner’s prescription or drug order or sold or given directly to the ultimate consumer.” IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024)\n(“practice of pharmacy”). This provision does not limit the drugs for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, while there are Indiana laws and regulations expressly covering the administration of immunizations, including training necessary to do it, there are no provisions expressly addressing administration of any other kinds of drugs, including controlled substances.\n If the general “administering . . . drugs and devices” phrase in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions in law or regulation. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in Indiana may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.", "2B": "Obtain a practitioner’s prescription or drug order.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the Indiana practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Indiana law does not expressly include ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024).\nIn addition, ordering lab tests and/or evaluating the results is not in the statutory list of “powers and duties of pharmacists.” IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-31 (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Indiana practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nIndiana law provides that pharmacists can “adjust” a patient’s “drug regimen,” under a “protocol.” IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-26-16-1 to 25-26-16-12 (West 2024).\nThere are several ways a pharmacist may adjust a drug regimen including: (1) changing the duration of treatment for a current drug therapy; (2) adjusting the strength, dosage form, route of administration, or strength of a drug;\n(3) adding a drug; or (4) “issu[ing] a new prescription” for one of the above purposes. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-16-2 (West 2024).\nMoreover, “a pharmacist may adjust the drug therapy regimen of the patient or group of patients under the authorization of the physician, including issuing new prescriptions in writing, by electronic transmission, or by other means allowed by law.” IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-16-3.5(b)(2) (West 2024).This suggests that, at least in theory, an Indiana pharmacist can prescribe buprenorphine under a drug regimen protocol.\nHowever, Indiana law governing these protocols does not account for the fact that an Indiana pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what of what the agreement or protocol provides.\nIn summary, Indiana law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine under a protocol to adjust a patient’s drug regimen. However, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Indiana pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Indiana law to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under protocols to adjust patient drug regimens.\nExpressly specify in Indiana law how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under protocols to adjust patient drug regimens.\nAllow Indiana pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Indiana laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nIndiana law provides that pharmacists can “adjust” a patient’s “drug regimen,” under a “protocol.” IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-26-16-1 to 25-26-16-12 (West 2024).\nThere are several ways a pharmacist may adjust a drug regimen including: (1) changing the duration of treatment for a current drug therapy; (2) adjusting the strength, dosage form, route of administration, or strength of a drug; or (3) adding a drug; and (4) “issu[ing] a new prescription” for one of the above purposes. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-16-2 (West 2024). This provision may mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a protocol. If not, Indiana laws and regulations governing drug regimen protocols do not directly address administering drugs or medications.\nIn summary, although Indiana pharmacy law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine under a protocol it also does not clearly authorize it, and a pharmacist’s general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a protocol is also unclear.", "5B": "Enter into a written drug regimen protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Indiana laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under protocols to adjust patient drug regimens includes administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "No, based on the information described below.\nIndiana law provides that pharmacists can “adjust” a patient’s “drug regimen,” under a “protocol.” IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-26-16-1 to 25-26-16-12 (West 2024).\nIndiana law identifies six ways in which a pharmacist adjusts a drug regimen. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-16-2 (West 2024). None of the six ways reference ordering laboratory tests or evaluating the results.\nMoreover, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, an Indiana pharmacist does not have the authority to order tests or evaluate results as a matter of general practice.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Indiana laws or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under protocols to adjust patient drug regimens includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Indiana laws/regulations do not refer to collaborative pharmacy practice. The statutory definition of the “practice of pharmacy” references “medication therapy management” (MTM), although Indiana’s definition for MTM does not seem to match up with collaborative pharmacy practice. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024) (“practice of pharmacy”; “medication therapy management”).\nAnother Indiana law provides that a pharmacist has the power to “perform . . . drug regimen review.” IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-31(a)(2) (West 2024). Again, the term “drug regimen review” does not seem to match up with collaborative pharmacy practice. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-13-2 (West 2024) (“drug regimen review”).\nNevertheless, a separate chapter of Indiana law provides that pharmacists can “adjust” a patient’s “drug regimen,” under a “protocol.” IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-26-16-1 to 25-26-16-12 (West 2024).\nA “protocol” means the policies, procedures, and protocols of a hospital, physician, or “physician group practice” concerning activities delegated to a pharmacist. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-16-1 (West 2024).\nThe individuals who can provide “direct supervision” of a pharmacist operating under a protocol are a physician, an advanced practice registered nurse, or a physician assistant. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-16-4.5 (West 2024).\nThe following Indiana laws provide more information on requirements for entering drug regimen protocols and required elements of protocols other than protocols in hospitals – IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-26-16-1 to 25-26-16-12 (West 2024).\nThe following Indiana laws provide more information on requirements for entering drug regimen protocols and required elements of protocols in hospitals – IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-26-16.5-1 to 25-26-16.5-18 (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nIndiana’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law expressly identifies a pharmacist as one of the “practitioners” who can provide “health care services” via telehealth. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-1-9.5-3.5(a)(13) (West 2024).\n“Health care services” include the following concerning a patient to the extent it is part of the practitioner’s underlying scope of practice: (1) assessment; (2) diagnosis;\n(3) evaluation; (4) consultation; (5) treatment; and (6) monitoring. IND. CODE ANN. § 25-1-9.5-2.5(a)(1) (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "The general rule is that prescriptions issued through telehealth do not require in-person visit if certain criteria are met. Opioids are specifically excluded from the general rule and are not allowed to be prescribed via telehealth, except that “an opioid may be prescribed [via telehealth] if the opioid is a partial agonist that is used to treat or manage opioid dependence.” IND. CODE ANN. § 25-1-9.5-8(a)(3)(B) (West 2024).\nIndiana laws and regulations governing telehealth include - IND. CODE ANN. §§ 25-1-9.5-0.5 to 25-1-9.5-15 (West 2024); 405 IND. ADMIN. CODE 5-38-1 to 5-38-4 (2024).", "9A": "Services and prescriptions provided under IND. CODE ANN. § 25-26-25 (hormonal contraceptives) to an eligible Medicaid recipient. IND. CODE ANN. § 12-15-1.3-6.5 (West 2024).\nTobacco dependence counseling services. 405 IND. ADMIN. CODE 5-37-3(c)(6) (2024).\nDiabetes self-management training services.117,118", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Indiana Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Indiana law or regulation that pharmacist services provided under a protocol to adjust a patient’s drug regimen are covered under the Indiana Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Indiana law directs the state division of mental health and addiction to “develop a treatment protocol containing best practice guidelines for the treatment of opiate dependent patients” by “an office based opioid treatment provider.” IND. CODE ANN. § 12-23-20-1 (West 2024). The statute expressly includes, among other things, the following requirements for that protocol: o Regular/random drug testing for certain substances; o Review of/changes to treatment plan for certain positive drug tests; and o Clinical standards for medication taper, relapse, and overdose prevention.\nIn addition, for “office based opioid treatment,” there is a law providing the duties of a supervising physician and prescriber and requirements for the treatment plan, including contents of health care agreements, informed consent, and toxicology screening. IND. CODE ANN. § 12-23-20-2 (West 2024).\nA law enacted in 2017 and amended in 2022 provides for a “physician medication assisted treatment training reimbursement program.” IND. CODE ANN. § 12-23-21-1 to 12-23-21-4 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.in.gov/pla/professions/pharmacy-home/", "description": "The Indiana Board of Pharmacy operates under the Professional Licensing Agency (PLA). The page provides information on licensure, renewals, CE requirements (30 hours per biennium), and pharmacy practice regulation under IC 25-26."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Pharmacy Practice Act (IC 25-26)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/indiana/title-25/article-26/chapter-13/", "description": "Indiana Code Title 25, Article 26 governs the regulation of pharmacists and pharmacies, including licensure, scope of practice, and the creation of the Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (856 IAC)", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/indiana/title-856", "description": "Title 856 of the Indiana Administrative Code contains the Board of Pharmacy's administrative rules covering pharmacies, pharmacists, controlled substances, and practice standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements (IC 25-26-16-4.5)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/indiana/title-25/article-26/chapter-16/section-25-26-16-4-5/", "description": "Indiana Code 25-26-16-4.5 authorizes pharmacist protocols (collaborative practice agreements) allowing pharmacists to provide clinical services under the direct supervision of a prescriber with prescriptive authority. The Council on Pharmacy Standards provides an Indiana CPA roadmap."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://www.in.gov/pla/professions/pharmacy-home/", "description": "Indiana pharmacists have authority under IC 25-26-13-4.1 for certain prescribing functions. The Indiana Pharmacy Association was awarded grants for pharmacist contraception prescribing and \"test and treat\" authority initiatives. Check the PLA pharmacy page for current scope of practice updates."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DMHA Opioid Treatment Program", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/dmha/addiction-services/opioid-treatment-program/", "description": "The Indiana FSSA Division of Mental Health and Addiction (DMHA) oversees opioid treatment programs offering medication-assisted treatment for OUD. Includes a downloadable directory of OTP facilities. Contact: OTP.FSSA@fssa.in.gov, (317) 232-7800."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Treatment Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's Buprenorphine Treatment Locator allows users to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine. Can be filtered by state (Indiana)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Indiana SOTA contact is Tony Toomer, Division of Mental Health and Addiction, Office of Addiction Services, 402 W. Washington Street, W353, Indianapolis, IN 46204. Phone: (317) 232-7835. Email: tony.toomer@fssa.in.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHA Find a Local Service Provider", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/dmha/find-a-local-service-provider/", "description": "DMHA's provider locator helps individuals find addiction treatment service providers, recovery residences, and opioid treatment programs throughout Indiana. Also accessible by dialing 2-1-1."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "Federal DEA/HHS rules permit buprenorphine prescribing via telemedicine for OUD treatment. Indiana follows federal telehealth guidelines for buprenorphine prescribing. The SAMHSA page provides comprehensive Q&A on telemedicine prescribing of buprenorphine."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Pharmacy Benefits", "url": "https://www.in.gov/medicaid/providers/clinical-services/pharmacy-benefits/", "description": "The Indiana Health Coverage Programs (IHCP) pharmacy benefits page provides information on pharmacy claims processing, preferred drug lists, and pharmacy benefit managers. Managed care entities use designated PBMs; Optum Rx manages Traditional Medicaid and fee-for-service pharmacy benefits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statewide Uniform Preferred Drug List (SUPDL)", "url": "https://www.in.gov/medicaid/providers/clinical-services/pharmacy-benefits/", "description": "Indiana Medicaid uses a Statewide Uniform Preferred Drug List (SUPDL) that includes buprenorphine products. The SUPDL and related prior authorization criteria are available through the IHCP Pharmacy Services page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Addiction Treatment Finder", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/addiction/", "description": "The FSSA Division of Mental Health and Addiction certifies all addiction treatment providers in Indiana. Users can find treatment providers or dial 2-1-1 for connections to available treatment and community resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Commission to Combat Substance Use Disorder - Resources", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/about/resources/", "description": "The Commission provides resources on OUD treatment funding, data, and programs. Includes links to the Department of Child Services drug endangered children program, DMHA, and Indiana Criminal Justice Institute substance abuse resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/prevention/", "description": "Indiana has invested nearly $4 million in statewide naloxone distribution through SAMHSA State Opioid Response Grant funding. The Indiana Commission to Combat Substance Use Disorder coordinates opioid settlement fund spending recommendations."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.in.gov/pla/professions/pharmacy-home/", "description": "Indiana pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE per biennium (IC 25-1-4; 856 IAC 1-26). A minimum of 24 hours must be pharmacy-related, with at least 15 hours ACPE-accredited. Note: The previous 2-hour opioid prescribing CE requirement for controlled substance registrants expired 7/1/2025."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://indianapharmacy.org/", "description": "The Indiana Pharmacy Association (IPA) provides continuing education programs, residency showcases, and professional development resources for Indiana pharmacists. Founded in 1882 as the voice for Indiana pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA resources for the MATE Act requirement that practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registration with Schedule II-V authority complete substance use disorder training including buprenorphine prescribing education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD provides modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring to enhance provider knowledge in evidence-based buprenorphine treatment practices for opioid use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHA Certified Peer Support Professional Certification", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/dmha/Recovery/peer-support/certified-peer-support-professional-certification/", "description": "DMHA offers Certified Peer Support Professional training at Ivy Tech locations statewide. Training and initial exam costs are currently covered by DMHA. Contact: peersupport@fssa.in.gov."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.in.gov/health/overdose-prevention/files/Guidance-Document-2017-Update-9-12-17-EC.pdf", "description": "Indiana State Department of Health Syringe Service and Harm Reduction Program Guidance document. Indiana allows syringe services programs with state approval. Programs must comply with state law regarding participant confidentiality."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access (Aaron's Law) and Standing Order", "url": "https://www.safeproject.us/naloxone/state-rules/", "description": "Under Aaron's Law (effective 2015, amended 2016), a statewide standing order from the Indiana State Health Officer allows pharmacists and registered entities to dispense naloxone to anyone who requests it without an individual prescription. Indiana Medicaid reimburses for naloxone dispensed under the standing order."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution Programs", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/prevention/", "description": "Indiana has invested nearly $4 million in statewide naloxone distribution, including NaloxBox units and naloxone vending machines, funded through SAMHSA's State Opioid Response Grant."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.wfyi.org/news/articles/indiana-senate-passes-bill-to-decriminalize-fentanyl-test-strips-eliminate-legal-gray-area", "description": "Indiana law historically classified drug purity testing tools as paraphernalia, creating a legal gray area for fentanyl test strips. As of early 2025, the Indiana Senate passed legislation (SB0098) to clarify that test strips checking for the presence of a substance are not paraphernalia. Please verify current status of this legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.in.gov/health/overdose-prevention/overdose-surveillance/indiana/", "description": "The Indiana Drug Overdose Dashboard presents information on drug overdose injuries, opioid prescriptions, and prevention efforts at county and state levels with interactive visualizations."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Certified Peer Support Professionals", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/dmha/Recovery/peer-support/", "description": "DMHA's Recovery Support Services team has authority and oversight over all Peer Certification programs in Indiana, including Certified Peer Support Professionals (CPSPs)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Regional Recovery Hubs", "url": "https://secure.in.gov/fssa/dmha/Recovery/regional-recovery-hubs/", "description": "Indiana's Regional Recovery Hubs provide access to Certified Peer Support Professionals. A directory and map of Hubs is available. For 24/7 peer support, dial 2-1-1."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://inarr.org/resources/recovery-residence-certification/", "description": "The Indiana Association of Recovery Residences (INARR) coordinates DMHA designation for recovery residences. DMHA is the authority for Indiana recovery residence designation covering Levels II, III, and IV."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMHA Homepage", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/dmha/home/", "description": "The Indiana FSSA Division of Mental Health and Addiction (DMHA) is the state behavioral health agency for mental health and addiction services. Provides treatment finder, peer support information, and email subscription for updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Contacts", "url": "https://www.in.gov/fssa/dmha/home/", "description": "Indiana crisis and substance use support: Dial 2-1-1 for 24/7 connection to treatment providers, peer support, and community resources throughout Indiana. Never Use Alone Hotline: 877-696-1996."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.in.gov/pla/professions/pharmacy-home/", "description": "Indiana Board of Pharmacy is housed under the Professional Licensing Agency (PLA). Contact PLA at (317) 232-2960. Address: 402 W. Washington Street, Room W072, Indianapolis, IN 46204."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Pharmacy Director Contact", "url": "https://www.in.gov/medicaid/providers/clinical-services/pharmacy-benefits/", "description": "Indiana Health Coverage Programs (IHCP) manages Medicaid pharmacy benefits through the Family and Social Services Administration (FSSA). Contact IHCP for pharmacy benefit inquiries through the provider portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Tony Toomer, Division of Mental Health and Addiction, Office of Addiction Services, 402 W. Washington Street, W353, Indianapolis, IN 46204. Phone: (317) 232-7835. Email: tony.toomer@fssa.in.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://indianapharmacy.org/", "description": "The Indiana Pharmacy Association (IPA) is the state's professional pharmacy organization. Since 1882, IPA has been advocating for and advancing the profession of pharmacy in Indiana."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Department of Health Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://www.in.gov/health/overdose-prevention/", "description": "The Indiana Department of Health manages overdose prevention efforts including surveillance, naloxone distribution, and public health education. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://www.in.gov/health/overdose-prevention/overdose-surveillance/indiana/", "description": "The Indiana Drug Overdose Dashboard presents data on drug overdose injuries, opioid prescriptions, and prevention efforts at county and state levels. Updated as new data becomes available."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Commission to Combat Substance Use Disorder - Data", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/data/", "description": "Data dashboards from the Indiana Commission including naloxone events reported by EMS providers, refreshed daily from 2014 to present. Provides insight into statewide naloxone distribution and use."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Prevention Webcasts", "url": "https://secure.in.gov/health/overdose-prevention/overdose-prevention-webcasts/", "description": "The Indiana Department of Health hosts webcasts on drug overdose data, including county-level programs, opioid prescriptions, hospital discharges, and death data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Commission Resources and Reports", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/about/resources/", "description": "Resources include the Commission's Final Report (Sep. 2018), BitterPill IN, county-level task force reports, and links to DCS, DMHA, and ICJI substance abuse data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Settlement Fund Recommendations", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/about/commission/", "description": "The Indiana Commission to Combat Substance Use Disorder adopted recommendations for spending national opioid settlement funds (November 2024). Includes data on fund allocation and priority areas."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "IPA Legislative News", "url": "https://indianapharmacy.org/", "description": "The Indiana Pharmacy Association provides legislative updates, advocacy alerts, and information on pharmacy-related bills. Recent victories include passage of SB 293 (MPJE bill) and PBM reform advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Indiana Legislators", "url": "https://iga.in.gov/", "description": "The Indiana General Assembly website at iga.in.gov provides tools to find state legislators, track legislation, and access bill information. Contact your representatives regarding pharmacy and OUD-related policy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Commission to Combat Substance Use Disorder", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/", "description": "The Indiana Commission serves as the state's primary coalition for addressing substance use disorders, coordinating prevention, treatment, and recovery efforts across state agencies and community partners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Indiana Commission Treatment Resources", "url": "https://www.in.gov/recovery/treatment/", "description": "Treatment-related policy resources including the Recovery Works program focusing on pre-incarceration diversion and post-incarceration re-entry services, and Know Your Rights resources for individuals seeking treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA State Association Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/blog/member/indiana-pharmacists-alliance/", "description": "The National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA) page for Indiana provides access to model legislation, state association management resources, and pharmacy policy tools relevant to Indiana."}]}]}, "iowa": {"name": "Iowa", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Iowa’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.48 (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nIowa law first effective July 1, 2024 provides that a pharmacist “may dispense, administer, monitor, and issue prescription drugs . . . commensurate with the pharmacist’s training and education and in accordance with the appropriate standard of care.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.8(2) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 IOWA H.F. 555 § 5 (West). This language does not include the word “prescribing.”\nMoreover, in Iowa regulations governing “pharmaceutical care,” which appears different from collaborative pharmacy practice, the regulation provides that “pharmaceutical care does not include the prescribing of drugs without the consent of the prescriber.” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. § 657-39.4 (2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Iowa cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.\nNote that, effective July 1, 2024, Iowa amended its pharmacy law to add “pharmacist” into the definition of “practitioner,” who is a someone who can legally “prescribe, distribute, or dispense a prescription drug or device in the course of professional practice in this state.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.3(39) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 IOWA H.F. 555 § 1 (West). This change does not appear to be an intent to grant pharmacists broad authority to prescribe drugs.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Iowa practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Iowa pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nIowa law first effective July 1, 2024 provides that a pharmacist “may dispense, administer, monitor, and issue prescription drugs . . . commensurate with the pharmacist’s training and education and in accordance with the appropriate standard of care.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.8(2) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 IOWA H.F. 555 § 5 (West).\nIn addition, pursuant to a new provision added effective July 1, 2024, a pharmacist “may, pursuant to statewide protocols developed and approved by the [state board of pharmacy] . . . order and administer prescription drugs, products, tests, or treatments.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.46(01) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 IOWA H.F. 555 § 23 (West).\nIowa regulation provides that “a pharmacist may administer . . . any medication pursuant to a prescription or medication order for an individual patient.” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.8(2) (2024).", "2B": "Obtain a prescription or medication order for the individual patient.\nReport any adverse reactions from the administration of the medication to the FDA’s Adverse Event Reporting System. IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.8(2) (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nIowa law first effective July 1, 2024, provides that a pharmacist “may dispense, administer, monitor, and issue prescription drugs . . . commensurate with the pharmacist’s training and education and in accordance with the appropriate standard of care.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.8(2) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 IOWA H.F. 555 § 5 (West). This provision does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nHowever, in a new provision added effective July 1, 2024, a pharmacist “may, pursuant to statewide protocols developed and approved by the [state board of pharmacy] .\n. . order and administer prescription drugs, products, tests, or treatments.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.46(01) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 IOWA H.F. 555 § 23 (West).\nAs a result, Iowa pharmacists are limited in what lab tests can be ordered (or possibly evaluated) by what statewide protocols are put in place.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Iowa practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAn Iowa pharmacist can participate in “collaborative pharmacy practice,” which involves providing “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist to patients under a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement [CPPA] with another pharmacist or practitioner.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.48(1)(a) (West 2024). Iowa regulation provides that a CPPA must include “the protocol, formulary, or clinical guidelines that describe or limit the pharmacist’s authority to perform the patient care or drug therapy management services and, as applicable, the drug name, class or category provided under drug therapy management.” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.13(2)(b)(3) (2024).There is no additional information about the scope of a pharmacist’s authorized activities under a CPPA and whether it includes prescribing drugs or medications.\nMoreover, Iowa law and regulation governing collaborative pharmacy practice and CPPAs does not account for the fact that an Iowa pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPPA provides.\nIn summary, Iowa laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CPPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Iowa pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Iowa laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPPAs.\nExpressly specify in Iowa laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPPAs.\nAllow Iowa pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Iowa laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nAn Iowa pharmacist can participate in “collaborative pharmacy practice,” which involves providing “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist to patients under a [CPPA] with another pharmacist or practitioner.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.48(1)(a) (West 2024).\nThe CPPA must include “establishment of the delegating practitioner’s scope of practice authorized in the agreement and a description of the permitted activities and decisions to be performed by the pharmacist(s).” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.13(2)(b)(2) (2024). This provision does not expressly address administering drugs or medications, and Iowa laws and regulations do not provide additional information about the scope of a pharmacist’s authorized activities under a CPPA Although Iowa laws and regulations are unclear about administering buprenorphine, given the the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer all medications, the most logical answer is to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in Iowa laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment under a CPPA.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Iowa laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nAn Iowa pharmacist can participate in “collaborative pharmacy practice,” which involves providing “patient care and drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist to patients under a [CPPA] with another pharmacist or practitioner.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.48(1)(a) (West 2024).\nThe CPPA must include “establishment of the delegating practitioner’s scope of practice authorized in the agreement and a description of the permitted activities and decisions to be performed by the pharmacist(s).” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.13(2)(b)(2) (2024). There is no additional information about the scope of a pharmacist’s authorized activities under a CPPA and whether that includes ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nAlthough Iowa collaborative pharmacy practice law is unclear on ordering or evaluating lab tests, given the response in (3A) above that a pharmacist has limited authority to order or evaluate lab tests outside of a CPPA, the most logical answer is that the same limited authority applies within one.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Iowa laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority as part of a CPPA includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "“A pharmacist or pharmacy may engage in collaborative pharmacy practice under a [CPPA] agreement with one or more practitioners, or as established by a health system pharmacy and therapeutics committee, to provide patient care and drug therapy management services to one or more patients.” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.13(1) (2024).\n“Practitioner” means “a physician, dentist, podiatric physician, veterinarian, optometrist, or advanced registered nurse practitioner who holds an active license to practice in Iowa.” IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.13(1) (2024).\nThe following Iowa laws and regulations provides more information on collaborative pharmacy practice, entering CPPAs, and required elements of CPPAs – IOWA CODE ANN. § 155A.48 (West 2024); IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-39.13 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nIowa does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, under Iowa insurance laws, a “health care professional” authorized to provide “health care services” includes “a physician or other health care practitioner licensed, accredited, registered, or certified to perform specified health care services consistent with state law.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 514C.34(1) (West 2024) (citing to IOWA CODE ANN. § 514J.102(21) for the definition). This is a broad definition that appears to cover pharmacists.\n“Health care services” means “services for the diagnosis, prevention, treatment, cure, or relief of a health condition, illness, injury, or disease.” IOWA CODE ANN. § 514J.102(23) (West 2024).\nIowa pharmacy regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Iowa laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Iowa laws and regulations governing telehealth include – IOWA CODE ANN. § 514C.34 (West 2024) (insurance coverage); IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 441-78.55 (2024) (Medicaid); IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 441-79.1 (2024) (Medicaid); IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 653-13.11 (2024)\n(physician standards of practice); IOWA ADMIN. CODE r. 657-13.1 to 657-13.23 (2024) (telephamacy).", "9A": "Pharmacists providing covered vaccines. IOWA ADMIN CODE r. 441-78.42 (2024).\n“Pharmaceutical case management services provided by an eligible physician and pharmacist for Medicaid members determined to be at high risk for medication-related problems.” IOWA ADMIN CODE r. 441-78.47 (2024).123\nServices for ordering and dispensing naloxone and nicotine replacement therapy tobacco cessation products, as well as to ordering and administering vaccines to Medicaid members.124,125", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Iowa Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Iowa laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under collaborative pharmacy practice CPPAs are covered under the Iowa Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dial.iowa.gov/about-dial/boards/pharmacy/about", "description": "The Iowa Board of Pharmacy operates under the Department of Inspections, Appeals, and Licensing (DIAL). The page provides links to statutes and administrative rules pertaining to pharmacy practice, pharmaceuticals, distribution, and prescribing in Iowa."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Pharmacy Practice Act and Rules", "url": "https://pharmacy.iowa.gov/ruleslaws", "description": "The complete Iowa Board of Pharmacy rules are contained in 657 Iowa Administrative Code. The Iowa Code contains permanent laws enacted by the Iowa General Assembly. Links to planned rule making are also provided."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (657 IAC)", "url": "https://rules.iowa.gov/Notice/Details/6174C", "description": "Iowa Administrative Rules relating to pharmacy practice, including amendments to collaborative pharmacy practice agreement rules between pharmacists and Iowa-licensed prescribers with independent prescribing authority."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreements", "url": "https://rules.iowa.gov/Notice/Details/6012C", "description": "Iowa authorizes collaborative pharmacy practice agreements. A CPA must identify the parties, the pharmacist(s) and practitioner(s) involved, and delegated activities. Rules are found in 657 IAC and were updated pursuant to 2021 Iowa Acts, Senate File 296."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://pharmacy.iowa.gov/prescription-monitoring-program", "description": "Iowa pharmacists have authority for certain clinical activities including immunization administration, naloxone dispensing under standing orders, and collaborative practice activities. Check the Board of Pharmacy website for current scope of practice information."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Opioid Help Treatment Locator", "url": "https://opioidhelp.iowa.gov/", "description": "Iowa's opioid treatment resources page with an interactive map of MAT and OUD clinics by area. Includes links to additional treatment options at yourlifeiowa.org/facility-locator."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Treatment Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's Buprenorphine Treatment Locator allows users to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, filterable by state (Iowa)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Iowa SOTA contact is Kevin Gabbert, Iowa Department of Health and Human Services, 321 East 12th Street, Des Moines, IA 50319. Phone: (515) 305-0396. Email: kevin.gabbert@hhs.iowa.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa HHS Addiction and Substance Use Disorders", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders", "description": "Iowa HHS Division of Behavioral Health is the lead agency for substance use disorder services. The page includes the Opioid Update newsletter, client data collection information, and links to treatment and prevention resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medications for Addiction Treatment (MAT)", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders/medications-addiction-treatment", "description": "Iowa HHS page on medication-assisted treatment for opioid use disorders, including information on buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone. References SAMHSA guidance on MAT effectiveness."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Pharmacy Benefits", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/programs/welcome-iowa-medicaid/provider-services/medicaid-pharmacy", "description": "Iowa Medicaid pharmacy information including links to the Preferred Drug List, P&T Committee, and pharmacy benefit administration. Iowa uses managed care entities for Medicaid pharmacy benefits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.iowamedicaidpdl.com/pa-pdl/preferred-drug-lists.html", "description": "The Iowa Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) contains comprehensive listings of preferred and nonpreferred drugs including buprenorphine products, prior authorization requirements, and mandatory 90-day supply prescription information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Your Life Iowa Treatment Finder", "url": "https://yourlifeiowa.org/", "description": "Your Life Iowa connects people struggling with substance use to experts in recovery. Includes a treatment facility locator with options for outpatient, residential, gender-specific, OTP (methadone), and fee assistance programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa HHS Substance Use Data", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders", "description": "Iowa HHS Division of Behavioral Health collects client data from licensed SUD treatment agencies to meet state and federal reporting requirements (TEDS). Includes information on treatment funding and programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders", "description": "Iowa HHS coordinates federal and state opioid response funding including SAMHSA State Opioid Response grants. Information on funding opportunities and opioid settlement funds is available through the Iowa HHS addiction and substance use disorders page."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://dial.iowa.gov/about-dial/boards/pharmacy/about", "description": "Iowa pharmacists must complete continuing pharmacy education for license renewal. Requirements are detailed in 657 Iowa Administrative Code. The Board of Pharmacy operates under the Department of Inspections, Appeals, and Licensing (DIAL). Contact the Iowa Board of Pharmacy for specific CE requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://www.iarx.org/", "description": "The Iowa Pharmacy Association (IPA) provides continuing education through 2/2/2 Webinars, the Standard of Care Symposium, Annual Meeting, and the Insight to Advocacy Pharmacy Law Series. IPA also offers the Decker-Temple Leadership Pharmacy program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA resources for the MATE Act requirement that practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registration with Schedule II-V authority complete substance use disorder training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD provides training modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring to enhance provider knowledge in evidence-based buprenorphine treatment practices."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Board of Pharmacy CE and Licensing", "url": "https://dial.iowa.gov/licenses/health-professions/pharmacy/prescription-monitoring-program-pmp", "description": "The DIAL Board of Pharmacy manages pharmacist licensing and CE tracking. Pharma Phacts newsletter provides updates on new code chapters, PMP delegate limits, inspection guidance, and compliance tips."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Harm Reduction Coalition - Syringe Services", "url": "https://www.iowaharmreductioncoalition.org/services/", "description": "The Iowa Harm Reduction Coalition (IHRC) provides overdose prevention training, naloxone distribution, fentanyl test strips, patient navigation for linkage to care, and peer recovery support services. Note: Iowa does not currently have a state law explicitly authorizing syringe services programs, though advocacy efforts are ongoing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://pharmacy.iowa.gov/naloxone-standing-order", "description": "Iowa has a statewide naloxone standing order from the State Medical Director allowing pharmacists to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription. Anyone can obtain naloxone under this standing order."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution (IHRC)", "url": "https://www.iowaharmreductioncoalition.org/overdose-education-naloxone-distribution/", "description": "The Iowa Harm Reduction Coalition provides overdose education and naloxone distribution. Under the standing order, anyone can obtain naloxone without a prescription from participating pharmacies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access", "url": "https://www.iowaharmreductioncoalition.org/services/", "description": "IHRC provides fentanyl test strips that allow individuals to test their drugs for the presence of fentanyl. Note: Iowa's legal status on fentanyl test strips has been in a gray area. Advocacy efforts have sought to clarify their legality. Please verify current legal status before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data (IASUDORS)", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/about/data-reports/health-disease/substance-use/drug-overdose/drug-overdose-sudors-data", "description": "The Iowa State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (IASUDORS) provides drug overdose death data for surveillance and public health response. Managed by Iowa HHS."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Your Life Iowa Treatment Finder", "url": "https://yourlifeiowa.org/", "description": "Your Life Iowa is the state's primary resource for connecting individuals to substance use treatment and recovery services. Includes a facility locator, live chat, and helpline services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa HHS Addiction and Substance Use Disorders", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders", "description": "Iowa HHS Division of Behavioral Health serves as the state behavioral health agency, overseeing licensed substance use disorder treatment agencies and coordinating prevention, treatment, and recovery services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Harm Reduction Coalition", "url": "https://www.iowaharmreductioncoalition.org/", "description": "IHRC is a statewide coalition providing harm reduction services including naloxone distribution, fentanyl test strips, linkage to housing and homelessness services, and peer recovery support. The primary harm reduction organization in Iowa."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://yourlifeiowa.org/finder", "description": "The Your Life Iowa facility finder includes options for residential treatment programs. Iowa does not currently have a comprehensive state-managed recovery residence registry comparable to some other states. Please verify current recovery housing resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis and Helpline Contacts", "url": "https://yourlifeiowa.org/", "description": "Your Life Iowa Helpline: Call or text 855-581-8111 (24/7) for substance use and mental health support. Live chat available at yourlifeiowa.org. Iowa Warm Line and crisis resources are also accessible through Iowa HHS."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://dial.iowa.gov/about-dial/boards/pharmacy/about", "description": "Iowa Board of Pharmacy, Department of Inspections, Appeals, and Licensing (DIAL). Contact information available through the DIAL website. Address: 321 E. 12th Street, Des Moines, IA 50319."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Medicaid Contact", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/programs/welcome-iowa-medicaid/provider-services/medicaid-pharmacy", "description": "Iowa Medicaid pharmacy services are managed by Iowa HHS. Iowa Medicaid address: 1305 E. Walnut St., Des Moines, IA 50319. Contact through the HHS Medicaid provider services page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Kevin Gabbert, Iowa Department of Health and Human Services, 321 East 12th Street, Des Moines, IA 50319. Phone: (515) 305-0396. Email: kevin.gabbert@hhs.iowa.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.iarx.org/", "description": "The Iowa Pharmacy Association (IPA) has been the voice for Iowa pharmacy since its founding. IPA provides advocacy, education, and professional resources. Contact via iarx.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa HHS Opioid Program", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders", "description": "Iowa Department of Health and Human Services manages opioid response programs including the Opioid Update newsletter, data collection, and coordination of prevention and treatment services."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose SUDORS Data", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/about/data-reports/health-disease/substance-use/drug-overdose/drug-overdose-sudors-data", "description": "The Iowa State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (IASUDORS) provides drug overdose death data for surveillance purposes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Monitoring Program Data", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/about/data-reports/health-disease/substance-use/prescription-monitoring-program", "description": "PMP data and reporting from the Iowa Public Health Tracking Portal, including information on controlled substance prescribing patterns and trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa HHS Substance Use Data Reports", "url": "https://hhs.iowa.gov/health-prevention/addiction-substance-use-disorders", "description": "Iowa HHS Division of Behavioral Health collects and publishes client data from licensed SUD treatment agencies. The Opioid Update newsletter shares information about opioid use trends and Iowa's response efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Harm Reduction Coalition Reports", "url": "https://www.iowaharmreductioncoalition.org/reports/", "description": "IHRC publishes reports on harm reduction activities including fentanyl testing results, naloxone distribution data, and syringe services utilization statistics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Opioid Help Resources", "url": "https://opioidhelp.iowa.gov/", "description": "Iowa Opioid Help provides a directory of MAT and OUD clinics by region, serving as a resource for understanding treatment access across the state."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "IPA Legislative Resources", "url": "https://www.iarx.org/", "description": "The Iowa Pharmacy Association provides legislative resources including \"Contact Your Legislators\" tools, \"Host a Legislator\" program, Iowa Pharmacists Political Action Committee (IPPAC), Legislative Defense Fund, and \"Become a Champion Advocate\" resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Iowa Legislators", "url": "https://www.legis.iowa.gov/legislators/find", "description": "The Iowa Legislature's official tool to find state legislators by entering an address, city, or zip code. Provides contact information for state senators and representatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Pharmacy Day on the Hill", "url": "https://www.iarx.org/", "description": "IPA hosts annual Pharmacy Day on the Hill event for pharmacists to engage directly with legislators on pharmacy policy issues including OUD treatment and pharmacist scope of practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Harm Reduction Coalition Advocacy", "url": "https://www.iowaharmreductioncoalition.org/2020-legislative-priorities/community-access-to-naloxone/", "description": "IHRC advocacy priorities include expanding community access to naloxone through standing orders, authorizing syringe services programs, and decriminalizing fentanyl test strips."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Iowa Opioid Help", "url": "https://opioidhelp.iowa.gov/", "description": "Iowa's comprehensive opioid response resource page providing treatment locator, prevention information, and links to state and federal OUD treatment resources."}]}]}, "kansas": {"name": "Kansas", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kansas law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1) (West 2024).\nThe definition does include “initiation of therapy for the conditions specified in [§] 65-16,131.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1)(I) (West 2024). However, the referenced provision does not include SUD as one of the conditions. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-16,131(a) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Kansas cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Kansas practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Kansas pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below, unless the form of buprenorphine is one that a prescriber considers to be safely self-administered by a patient (if such form exists).\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Kansas law does not expressly include administering any drugs or medications other than a “vaccine pursuant to a vaccination protocol.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1)(C) (West 2024).Although it is not in the definition of the practice of pharmacy, a pharmacist “may administer a drug by injection that, in the judgment of the prescriber, may be safely self-administered by a patient, to a patient pursuant to a prescription order, unless the prescription order includes the words ‘not to be administered by a pharmacist,’ or words of like effect.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-16,129(a)(1) (West 2024).", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Kansas practice of pharmacy to include administering all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kansas law does not expressly include ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Kansas pharmacy laws and regulations expressly refer to ordering or evaluating any type of lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Kansas practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kansas law includes the “performance of collaborative drug therapy management” (CDTM) pursuant to a collaborative practice agreement (CPA). KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1)(G) (West 2024). However, Kansas law governing CDTM expressly provides that it “shall not be construed to permit a pharmacist to alter a physician’s orders or directions, diagnose or treat any disease, [or] independently prescribe drugs.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(2) (West 2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Kansas laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CDTM CPAs.\nExpressly specify in Kansas laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow Kansas pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Kansas laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kansas law includes performing CDTM pursuant to a CPA. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1)(G) (West 2024).\nKansas law provides that a CPA must contain “certain specified conditions or limitations pursuant to the collaborating physician’s order, standing order, delegation or protocol” and must be “appropriate to the pharmacist’s training and experience.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(3) (West 2024). This provision does not expressly address whether a CPA can authorize the administration of buprenorphine.\nHowever, Kansas laws and regulations governing CDTM indicate that a CPA cannot encompass certain things, which include altering a physician’s order, diagnosing a patient, independently prescribing, or administering a flu vaccine in a manner not authorized by law. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(2) (West 2024); KAN. ADMIN. REGS. § 68-7-22(c)(1) (2024). This is the only express reference to the word “administer” in these laws and regulations. It is possible, although not clear, that the provision that a CPA cannot authorize a pharmacist to administer a vaccine except pursuant to a certain Kansas law means that a CPA can authorize a pharmacist to generally administer drugs or medications, including buprenorphine.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Kansas laws and/or regulations what duties pharmacists can perform under a CPA and that it includes administering controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Kansas laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kansas law includes performing CDTM pursuant to a CPA. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1)(G) (West 2024).\nKansas law provides that a CPA must contain “certain specified conditions or limitations pursuant to the collaborating physician’s order, standing order, delegation or protocol” and must be “appropriate to the pharmacist’s training and experience.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(3) (West 2024). This provision does not expressly address whether a CPA can authorize ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nKansas law and regulation governing CDTM do not specify what types of activities a pharmacist can or cannot perform under a CPA, other than prohibiting altering the physician’s order, diagnosing, independently prescribing, or administering a flu vaccine in a manner not authorized by law. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(2) (West 2024); KAN. ADMIN. REGS. § 68-7-22(c)(1) (2024). However, this provision does not clearly prohibit ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Kansas law and/ot regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a CPA includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A pharmacist may perform CDTM “pursuant to a written [CPA] with one or more physicians who have an established physician-patient relationship.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b)(1)(G) (West 2024).\nThe following Kansas regulations provide more information on requirements for participating in CDTM and required elements of CPAs. – KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-1626a(b) (West 2024); KAN. ADMIN. REGS. § 68-7-22 (2024).", "8A": "No, based on the information described below, except for telepharmacy.\nKansas does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law except within its insurance code. Under the insurance law, “for purposes of Kansas telemedicine act,” a “healthcare provider” is a “a physician, licensed physician assistant, licensed advanced practice registered nurse or person licensed, registered, certified or otherwise authorized to practice by the behavioral sciences regulatory board.” KAN. STAT. ANN. § 40-2,211(a)(2) (West 2024).\nThis does not include a pharmacist.\nKansas pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy, however.", "8B": "Expressly provide in Kansas laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "The same laws and regulations that apply to a healthcare provider prescribing drugs, including controlled substances in person also apply to prescribing them by telemedicine. KAN. ADMIN. REGS. § 100-77-3 (2024).\nKansas laws and regulations governing telehealth include – KAN. STAT. ANN. §§ 40-2,210 to 40-2,216 (West 2024)\n(telemedicine act – within insurance law); KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-16,130 (West 2024) (telepharmacy); KAN. ADMIN. REGS. §§ 100-77-1 to 100-77-3 (2024)\n(telemedicine).", "9A": "Point-of-care testing and CLIA-waived testing as specified in an August 2023 bulletin to pharmacists.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Kansas Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Kansas laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under CDTM CPAs are covered under the Kansas Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Kansas law provides that minors may consent to an examination and/or treatment for SUD without parent or guardian consent and grants minors the right to give such consent. KAN. STAT. ANN. § 65-2892a (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ks.gov/", "description": "The Kansas Board of Pharmacy regulates pharmacists, pharmacies, and controlled substances in Kansas. The Board oversees licensing, inspections, K-TRACS, collaborative practice, and naloxone dispensing programs. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statutes and Regulations", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ks.gov/legal/statutes-regs", "description": "Complete Kansas Pharmacy Statutes and Regulations available for download in PDF and Word formats (updated August 2024). Contains the Kansas Pharmacy Act and all related rules under 657 Kansas Administrative Regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Pharmacy Act (KSA 65-16)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/kansas/chapter-65/article-16/", "description": "Kansas Statutes Chapter 65, Article 16, governing the regulation of pharmacists. Includes provisions for telepharmacy (65-16,130) and pharmacist-initiated therapy for certain health conditions (65-16,131)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice and Protocols", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ks.gov/programs/collaborative-practice-and-protocols", "description": "The Kansas Board of Pharmacy's Collaborative Drug Therapy Management Committee oversees collaborative practice agreements and adopted protocols for pharmacist testing and initiation of therapy. Pharmacists must maintain copies of protocols at each practice location for 10 years."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority (KSA 65-1626a)", "url": "https://ksrevisor.gov/statutes/chapters/ch65/065_016_0026a.html", "description": "Kansas statute governing collaborative drug therapy management agreements between physicians and pharmacists. Pharmacists may not independently prescribe drugs or practice medicine but may manage drug therapy under physician-pharmacist agreements."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "KDADS Substance Use Disorder Treatment Services", "url": "https://www.kdads.ks.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health/services-and-programs/substance-use-disorder-treatment-services", "description": "The Kansas Department for Aging and Disability Services (KDADS) licenses treatment providers and substance abuse counselors. For treatment assessment or to find providers, call Carelon Behavioral Health of Kansas at 1-866-645-8216 (select option 2)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Treatment Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's Buprenorphine Treatment Locator allows users to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, filterable by state (Kansas)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Kansas SOTA contact is Paul Hunt, Kansas Department of Aging and Disability Services, 503 South Kansas Avenue, Topeka, KS 66603. Phone: (785) 296-7022. Fax: (785) 296-0256. Email: paul.hunt@ks.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KDHE Substance Use Disorder and Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1298/Substance-Use-Disorder-Overdose-Preventi", "description": "Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE) resources on substance use disorder and overdose prevention, including information on opioid withdrawal, treatment options, and links to the overdose data dashboard."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "Federal DEA/HHS rules permit buprenorphine prescribing via telemedicine for OUD treatment. Kansas follows federal telehealth guidelines. The SAMHSA page provides comprehensive Q&A on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Preferred Drug List Program", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/212/Preferred-Drug-List-Program", "description": "Kansas Medicaid uses a Preferred Drug List (PDL) managed by KDHE. A PDL Advisory Committee of practicing physicians and pharmacists ensures clinical review. Drugs without significant therapeutic advantage may require prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/211/Preferred-Drug-List", "description": "The current Kansas Medicaid PDL is available for download as PDF, including prior authorization criteria and non-preferred drug PA forms."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Medicaid Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/212/Preferred-Drug-List-Program", "description": "KDHE Health Care Finance manages Kansas Medicaid pharmacy benefits. The PDL applies to drugs billed on both the medical and pharmacy benefits. Generic drugs are required when available."}, {"type": "link", "title": "211 Kansas Resource Directory", "url": "https://211kansas.myresourcedirectory.com/", "description": "211 Kansas connects individuals to community resources including substance use disorder treatment, naloxone access, and social services. Dial 2-1-1 for assistance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Fights Addiction Grant", "url": "https://www.ag.ks.gov/Home/Components/News/News/139/1292", "description": "The Kansas Fights Addiction Grant Review Board awards funding for opioid treatment and prevention programs. Recent awards provided approximately 12,000 fentanyl test strips and funded treatment services. The Kansas Fights Addiction Act was enacted in 2021."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Board of Pharmacy CE Information", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ks.gov/legal/statutes-regs", "description": "Kansas pharmacist CE requirements are detailed in the Kansas Pharmacy Statutes and Regulations. Pharmacists must complete required continuing education hours for license renewal. Contact the Board of Pharmacy at (785) 296-4056 for specific CE questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.ksrx.org/", "description": "KPhA offers continuing education, annual conferences, technician vaccination training, and professional development resources. Founded in 1880, KPhA represents pharmacists, technicians, and students of all practice settings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA resources for the MATE Act requirement that practitioners applying for or renewing DEA registration with Schedule II-V authority complete substance use disorder training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD provides training modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring to enhance provider knowledge in evidence-based buprenorphine treatment practices."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Pharmacists Recovery Network", "url": "https://www.ksrx.org/about/kansas-pharmacists-recovery-network", "description": "KPhA's Kansas Pharmacists Recovery Network (KsPRN) provides support for pharmacy professionals in recovery from substance use disorders. Monthly administrative fee of $45 charged by KPhA/KsPRN."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1298/Substance-Use-Disorder-Overdose-Preventi", "description": "Kansas does not currently have a statewide law authorizing syringe services programs. KDHE provides overdose prevention information and harm reduction resources. Contact KDHE for current information on harm reduction programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Dispensing by Pharmacists", "url": "https://www.ktracs.ks.gov/pharmacists/naloxone-dispensing", "description": "Naloxone and other emergency opioid antagonists can be dispensed by Kansas pharmacists according to the statewide protocol. The Kansas Board of Pharmacy K-TRACS page provides guidelines for pharmacist naloxone dispensing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Naloxone Program (Free Narcan)", "url": "https://www.kdads.ks.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health/kansas-naloxone-program", "description": "DCCCA provides free Naloxone (Narcan) nasal spray, fentanyl test strips, and training to community organizations and any Kansas resident. Funded by KDADS through the SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grant and Healthy Blue of Kansas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Naloxone Program (DCCCA)", "url": "https://www.dccca.org/program/kansas-naloxone-program/", "description": "DCCCA distributes free naloxone and fentanyl test strips statewide. Available to any Kansas resident or organization upon request. Contact DCCCA for ordering and training information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1309/Data-Dashboard", "description": "The KDHE Overdose Data Dashboard displays Kansas overdose data including drug category, geographical location, and demographic factors. In 2022, 497 Kansas residents died from opioid overdose."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "KDADS Behavioral Health", "url": "https://www.kdads.ks.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health", "description": "KDADS is responsible by statute for coordinating and providing substance abuse and mental health services in Kansas. The behavioral health division oversees licensed treatment providers and recovery support programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use Disorder Treatment Services", "url": "https://www.kdads.ks.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health/services-and-programs/substance-use-disorder-treatment-services", "description": "KDADS licenses treatment providers and substance abuse counselors in Kansas. For assessment or to find treatment providers, call Carelon Behavioral Health of Kansas at 1-866-645-8216 (select option 2)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.kdads.ks.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health", "description": "KDADS oversees behavioral health services including recovery housing in Kansas. Contact KDADS for information on certified recovery residences and sober living environments. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Prescription Drug and Opioid Advisory Committee", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1305/Kansas-Prescription-Drug-Opioid-Advisory", "description": "The Advisory Committee works to increase K-TRACS registration, develop prescriber toolkits, implement opioid prescribing policies, and expand peer support services to support a comprehensive treatment and recovery-oriented system of care."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis and Helpline Contacts", "url": "https://www.kdads.ks.gov/services-programs/behavioral-health", "description": "Kansas SUD crisis support: Call Carelon Behavioral Health of Kansas at 1-866-645-8216. Dial 2-1-1 for community resource connections. 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline available 24/7."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ks.gov/", "description": "Kansas Board of Pharmacy, 800 SW Jackson Street, Suite 1414, Topeka, KS 66612-1244. Phone: (785) 296-4056. The Board regulates pharmacy practice, K-TRACS, and controlled substances. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KDHE Medicaid Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/212/Preferred-Drug-List-Program", "description": "Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE), Health Care Finance division manages Kansas Medicaid pharmacy benefits including the Preferred Drug List."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Paul Hunt, Kansas Department of Aging and Disability Services, 503 South Kansas Avenue, Topeka, KS 66603. Phone: (785) 296-7022. Fax: (785) 296-0256. Email: paul.hunt@ks.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.ksrx.org/", "description": "Kansas Pharmacists Association (KPhA), founded 1880. Represents pharmacists of all practice settings. Provides advocacy, education, and professional development. Contact via ksrx.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KDHE Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1298/Substance-Use-Disorder-Overdose-Preventi", "description": "KDHE manages overdose prevention efforts including data surveillance, the Overdose Data 2 Action program, and coordination with the Kansas Board of Pharmacy on K-TRACS prescription monitoring."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1309/Data-Dashboard", "description": "The KDHE Overdose Data Dashboard displays Kansas overdose data by drug category, geographical location, and demographic factors with interactive visualizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data 2 Action (OD2A)", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/2344/Overdose-Data-2-Action", "description": "KDHE's Overdose Data 2 Action program partners with the Kansas Board of Pharmacy to support K-TRACS. Healthcare providers and pharmacists can access patients' opioid prescription history for safer prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Prescription Drug and Opioid Advisory Committee", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1305/Kansas-Prescription-Drug-Opioid-Advisory", "description": "The Advisory Committee provides data-driven recommendations including provider education, opioid prescribing policies, and K-TRACS utilization. Meeting minutes and the Provider Education Appendix are available."}, {"type": "link", "title": "K-TRACS Data Reports", "url": "https://www.ktracs.ks.gov/", "description": "K-TRACS provides data on controlled substance prescribing patterns in Kansas. The OJP state profile notes that K-TRACS website includes statistics and an opioid dashboard."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use Disorder Overdose Prevention Toolkit", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1298/Substance-Use-Disorder-Overdose-Preventi", "description": "KDHE regularly monitors syndromic surveillance data and publishes overdose spike alert community response toolkits. Controlled substances are tracked through the Kansas Board of Pharmacy K-TRACS system."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "KPhA Advocacy", "url": "https://www.ksrx.org/", "description": "Kansas Pharmacists Association represents the pharmacy profession on local, state, and federal levels to influence positive change and advance pharmacy practice. Advocacy resources and KPhA PAC available through the website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Kansas Legislators", "url": "https://www.kslegislature.gov/li/b2025_26/members/", "description": "The Kansas State Legislature website provides a roster of all legislators with contact information. A spreadsheet-compatible file of legislator information is available for download."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Fights Addiction Act", "url": "https://www.ag.ks.gov/Home/Components/News/News/139/1292", "description": "The Kansas Fights Addiction Act (enacted 2021) created a grant review board that awards funding for opioid treatment and prevention programs. The Attorney General's office coordinates funding from opioid settlement and litigation proceeds."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Prescription Drug and Opioid Advisory Committee", "url": "https://www.kdhe.ks.gov/1305/Kansas-Prescription-Drug-Opioid-Advisory", "description": "The statewide Advisory Committee serves as Kansas' primary opioid response coalition, working to increase K-TRACS use, develop prescriber toolkits, implement prescribing policies, and expand peer support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kansas Legislature Homepage", "url": "https://www.kslegislature.gov/", "description": "The Kansas State Legislature consists of a 125-member House of Representatives and a 40-member Senate. The website provides bill tracking, committee information, and legislative calendars. Contact: 785-296-2391."}]}]}, "kentucky": {"name": "Kentucky", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Kentucky’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative care agreement” (CCA). KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kentucky law does not expressly include prescribing drugs. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(22) (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Kentucky cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.\nIn 2018, Kentucky enacted legislation related to a “pilot program” for “community pharmacy care for medication-assisted substance abuse therapy.” However, by the express statutory language, this program only applies to “noncontrolled medication-assisted therapy” for SUD and so it does not include buprenorphine. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 194A.800(4) (West 2024).", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Kentucky practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Kentucky pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kentucky law expressly includes the “administration of medications or biologics in the course of dispensing or maintaining a prescription drug order.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(22) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.The practice of pharmacy definition also contains more specific provisions tied to administering vaccines to children and adults. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(22) (West 2024). There are also Kentucky regulations governing vaccine administration, including the training required to do so, while there are no such regulations for administering other drugs or medications.\nHowever, unlike other states where the conclusion to this question is that the state’s laws and/or regulations are unclear, the fact that Kentucky law expressly ties the general administration language to dispensing or maintaining a prescription drug order indicates the legislature’s intent to broadly authorize administration.", "2B": "Obtain a prescription drug order from a prescriber.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kentucky law does not expressly reference ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(22) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Kentucky pharmacy laws and regulations expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests by pharmacists outside of a collaborative care agreement (CCA).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Kentucky practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAlthough not specified within the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kentucky law, a pharmacist may enter a “collaborative care agreement” (CCA) “that outlines a plan of cooperative management of patients’ drug-related health care needs.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5) (West 2024). The law does not expressly describe what “a plan of cooperative care management” includes.\nKentucky law does provide that the CCA must “specif[y] the drug-related regimen to be provided, and how drug therapy is to be monitored” and must “stipulate[s] the conditions for initiating, continuing, or discontinuing drug therapy and conditions which warrant modifications to dose, dosage regimen, dosage form, or route of administration.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5)(c) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the word “initiate,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nKentucky regulation governing CCAs provides only that the CCA must contain “protocol, criteria, standing orders, or other method by which services are authorized.” KY. ADMIN. REGS. 2:220, § 4 (2024). There is no further description of what that can or cannot include.\nMoreover, Kentucky laws and regulations governing CCAs do not account for the fact that a Kentucky pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CCA provides.\nIn summary, Kentucky laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CCA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Kentucky pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Kentucky law and regulation to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CCAs.\nExpressly specify in Kentucky law or regulation how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CCAs.\nAllow Kentucky pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Kentucky laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nAlthough not specified within the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Kentucky law, a pharmacist may enter a CCA “that outlines a plan of cooperative management of patients’ drug-related health care needs.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5) (West 2024). The law does not expressly describe what “a plan of cooperative care management” includes.\nKentucky law provides that the CCA must “specif[y] the drug-related regimen to be provided, and how drug therapy is to be monitored” and must “stipulate[s] the conditions for initiating, continuing, or discontinuing drug therapy and conditions which warrant modifications to dose, dosage regimen, dosage form, or route of administration.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5)(c) (West 2024). This provision may mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a CCA. If not, Kentucky laws and regulations governing CCAs do not directly address administering drugs or medications.\nAlthough Kentucky CCA laws and regulations are unclear on administering buprenorphine, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer drugs or medications outside of a CCA, the most logical answer is to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a CCA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Kentucky laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a CCA.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests.\nKentucky regulation provides that a CCA must contain the “[l]ab tests that may be ordered.” KY. ADMIN. REGS. 2:220, § 4 (2024). The regulation does not expressly address evaluating the results of those tests.", "6B": "Enter into a CCA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Kentucky law and regulation that a pharmacist’s authority under a CCA includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CCA is a written agreement between a pharmacist or pharmacists and “a practitioner or practitioners” that outlines a plan of cooperative management of patients’ drug-related health care need KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “practitioner” in Kentucky pharmacy laws is tied to the definition used in the state’s food, drug, and cosmetic’s act. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(23) (West 2024) (citing to KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 217.015(35)).\n“Practitioners” include medical or osteopathic physicians, dentists, chiropodists, veterinarians, optometrists, advanced practice registered nurses, and physician assistants. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 217.015(35) (West 2024).\nThe following Kentucky regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CCAs and required elements of CCAs – KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.010(5) (West 2024); 201 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 2:220 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nKentucky’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law certain state agencies to “provide guidance and direction to providers delivering health care services using telehealth or digital health” via regulation. KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 211.334(1) (West 2024).\nThe regulations developed to “establish a telehealth terminology glossary to provide standard definitions for all health care providers who deliver health care services via telehealth” define a “health care provider” to include pharmacists. 900 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 12:005, §1(2) (2024)\n(citing to KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 304.17A-005(23) for the source of the definition).", "8B": null, "8C": "There is a Kentucky law specific to the “duty of treating pharmacist utilizing telehealth to ensure patient’s informed consent and maintain confidentiality.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 315.310 (West 2024).\nKentucky laws and regulations governing telehealth include – KY. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 211.332 to 211.388\n(West 2024) (telehealth generally); KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 304.17A-138 (West 2024) (insurance); KY. REV. STAT.\nANN. § 315.310 (West 2024) (pharmacist’s duty); 900 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 12:005 (telehealth generally); 806 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 17:270 (insurance); 907 KY. ADMIN. REGS.\n3:010 (Medicaid – physicians); 907 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 3:170 (Medicaid).", "9A": "None for Medicaid. 907 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 1:672, §1(4) (2024) (pharmacist not a “credentialed provider”).\nHowever, Kentucky insurance law provides that an insurer must reimburse any service provided by any pharmacist within their scope of practice that would otherwise be covered when provided by a physician, advanced practice registered nurse, or physician’s assistant. KEN. REV. STAT. ANN. § 304.12-237 (West 2024). The definition of “insurer” does not include the Kentucky Medicaid program.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Kentucky Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Kentucky laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under CCAs are covered under the Kentucky Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Prior to the discharge of a patient that has received “medication for addiction-treatment,” the treating facility must submit a written discharge plan to the patient, and the patient’s third-party payor (if any), which “shall describe arrangements for additional services needed following discharge.” KY. REV. STAT. ANN. § 222.422 (West 2024).\nKentucky regulation provides professional standards for physicians and advance practice registered nurses prescribing buprenorphine. KY. ADMIN. REGS. 9:270 (2024) (physicians); 201 KY. ADMIN. REGS. 20:065 (2024)\n(nurses)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (KASPER)", "url": "https://ekasper.chfs.ky.gov", "description": "Kentucky All Schedule Prescription Electronic Reporting (KASPER) is the state's PDMP system. Access requires creating a Kentucky Online Gateway (KOG) account first, then linking to a KASPER account."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KASPER Information and Registration", "url": "https://pharmacy.ky.gov/professionals/Pages/KASPER-Information.aspx", "description": "Kentucky Board of Pharmacy page with KASPER registration instructions. Per KRS 218A.202(2), all pharmacists authorized to dispense controlled substances must register and maintain a KASPER account."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KASPER Main Page (Cabinet for Health and Family Services)", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/os/oig/dai/deppb/Pages/kasper.aspx", "description": "Official KASPER homepage with overview of the system, access rules, and reporting requirements. KASPER collects data on Schedule II-V controlled substances dispensed in Kentucky."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory vs. Voluntary Use", "url": "https://pharmacy.ky.gov/Frequently-Asked-Questions/Pages/KASPER-FAQ.aspx", "description": "KASPER FAQ page. Kentucky pharmacy law does not require mandatory use of KASPER by pharmacists for checking. However, all pharmacists authorized to dispense controlled substances must register and maintain an account. Prescribers have mandatory checking requirements under KRS 218A.205."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Kentucky participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate PDMP data sharing. Information on this is available through the KASPER main page and through the PDMP TTAC at https://www.pdmpassist.org"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/os/oig/dai/deppb/Documents/KASPERKOGIntegrationUserGuide.pdf", "description": "KASPER-KOG Integration User Guide with instructions for delegate management. Practitioners and pharmacists can authorize delegates to run KASPER reports under their account. Contact the KASPER Help Desk at 502-564-2703 or eKASPERHelp@ky.gov for assistance."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://pharmacy.ky.gov/", "description": "Official website of the Kentucky Board of Pharmacy. Provides information on licensure, regulations, continuing education, and board news."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Pharmacy Practice Act (KRS Chapter 315)", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/chapter.aspx?id=38825", "description": "Full text of Kentucky Revised Statutes Chapter 315, the Pharmacists and Pharmacies statute, hosted on the Kentucky Legislative Research Commission website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statutes and Regulations Page", "url": "https://pharmacy.ky.gov/statutesandregulations/Pages/default.aspx", "description": "Kentucky Board of Pharmacy page with links to all relevant statutes (KRS 315, KRS 217, KRS 218A) and administrative regulations (201 KAR Chapter 2, 902 KAR 55)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Regulations (201 KAR Chapter 2)", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/kar/TITLE201.HTM", "description": "Kentucky Administrative Regulations Title 201, which includes Chapter 2 covering Board of Pharmacy regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Care Agreements (201 KAR 2:220)", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/statute.aspx?id=54762", "description": "KRS 315.010 defines collaborative care agreements as written agreements between pharmacists and practitioners for cooperative management of patients' drug-related healthcare needs. The regulation 201 KAR 2:220 provides the administrative framework."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board Authorized Protocols (201 KAR 2:380)", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/kar/titles/201/002/380/", "description": "Regulation authorizing the Kentucky Board of Pharmacy to review and approve advanced practice protocols for pharmacist use, enabling pharmacists to provide protocol-driven care. KPhA provides protocol support at https://www.kphanet.org/board%20authorized%20protocols"}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Opioid Response Effort (KORE)", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dbhdid/Pages/kore.aspx", "description": "KORE is Kentucky's comprehensive state response effort to reduce overdose deaths by expanding access to prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery support services. Links to multiple treatment and support resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to Kentucky to find substance use disorder treatment facilities, including those providing buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "A listing of practitioners by state who previously held a DATA-2000 waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD treatment, now searchable for Kentucky providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA)", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA directory listing each state's Opioid Treatment Authority contact. Kentucky's SOTA is housed within the Cabinet for Health and Family Services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Buprenorphine Prescribing Standards", "url": "https://kbml.ky.gov/prescribing-substance-abuse/Pages/default.aspx", "description": "Kentucky Board of Medical Licensure page covering prescribing and substance abuse resources. Includes links to 201 KAR 9:270, the professional standards for prescribing buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA guidance on buprenorphine prescribing, including telemedicine provisions. Federal rules now allow practitioners with DEA registration to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD via telemedicine under certain conditions. Kentucky follows federal telehealth regulations for controlled substance prescribing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Medicaid Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dms/dpo/ppb/Pages/default.aspx", "description": "Welcome page for the Kentucky Medicaid Pharmacy Program, managed by the Department for Medicaid Services Pharmacy Policy Branch. Includes links to the pharmacy benefit manager, billing information, and program updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://kyportal.medimpact.com/sites/default/files/2023-12/kentucky-medicaid-pdl.pdf", "description": "Current Kentucky Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) maintained by MedImpact, the state's fee-for-service pharmacy benefit manager. Lists preferred medications by therapeutic class."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MedImpact Kentucky Provider Portal", "url": "https://kyportal.medimpact.com/", "description": "Kentucky Medicaid FFS pharmacy portal managed by MedImpact, providing drug coverage information, prior authorization criteria, pharmacy locator, and benefit plan details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Medicaid Fee Schedules", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dms/Pages/feesrates.aspx", "description": "Department for Medicaid Services page with links to current fee schedules for provider services, including pharmacy services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Medicaid FFS Pharmacy Billing Manual", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dms/dpo/ppb/Documents/Provider%20Billing%20Manual%20(Fee%20For%20Service).pdf", "description": "Provider billing manual for Kentucky Medicaid fee-for-service pharmacy benefit, including pricing, payment information, and billing procedures."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OUD Treatment Funding (KORE/SOR Grants)", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dbhdid/Pages/kore.aspx", "description": "The Kentucky Opioid Response Effort administers federal State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funds for expanding access to treatment, prevention, and recovery services. For FY 2023-2024, Kentucky received $35.9 million in SOR funding."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://pharmacy.ky.gov/professionals/Pages/Continuing-Education.aspx", "description": "Board of Pharmacy page on CE requirements. Kentucky pharmacists must complete 15 hours of CE annually (March 1 through February 28). For licensing years 2023-2028, one hour must be on the opioid epidemic or opioid use disorder per 201 KAR 2:015."}, {"type": "link", "title": "University of Kentucky HEALing Communities Study CE", "url": "https://healky.learningexpressce.com/", "description": "UK College of Pharmacy continuing education platform with courses on overdose education, naloxone distribution, and medication for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.kphanet.org/education", "description": "KPhA's education page with links to online CE opportunities through the Kentucky Pharmacy Education and Research Foundation (KPERF) and live CE events."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA page on Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act requirements. All DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of training on opioid or substance use disorder treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD offers free training that satisfies DEA MATE Act requirements for 8-hour opioid use disorder education. Includes buprenorphine-specific training modules and clinical mentoring."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Harm Reduction Branch (KDPH)", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dph/Pages/harmreduction.aspx", "description": "Kentucky Department for Public Health Harm Reduction Branch homepage. Includes information on syringe services programs, naloxone distribution, fentanyl/xylazine test strips, and overdose prevention resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dph/dehp/hab/Documents/HRSEPGuidLV.pdf", "description": "Kentucky Harm Reduction and Syringe Exchange Program (HRSEP) guidelines document. Kentucky authorizes local health departments to operate syringe services programs. Contact the KDPH Harm Reduction Branch for the current directory of active programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Law (KRS 217.186)", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/law/statutes/statute.aspx?id=52963", "description": "Kentucky statute authorizing licensed healthcare providers to prescribe or dispense opioid antagonists (naloxone) directly or by standing order to any person or agency. Provides civil and criminal immunity for good faith prescribing, dispensing, and administration."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KORE Naloxone Distribution Program", "url": "https://www.kphanet.org/kore", "description": "The KORE Overdose Education and Naloxone Distribution (OEND) program, administered through the Kentucky Pharmacists Association, provides naloxone at no cost to eligible Kentucky agencies serving individuals at risk for opioid overdose."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: As of June 29, 2023, fentanyl test strips are legal to possess in Kentucky per HB353, which amended KRS 218A.500 to exclude devices used to detect synthetic opioids from the definition of drug paraphernalia. Information available at https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dph/Pages/harmreduction.aspx"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://kiprc.uky.edu/injury-focus-areas/drug-overdose-prevention", "description": "Kentucky Injury Prevention and Research Center (KIPRC) at the University of Kentucky serves as a bona fide agent for KDPH. Provides timely reports on drug overdose morbidity and mortality, including county-level profiles and the Drug Overdose Fatality Surveillance System (DOFSS)."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Peer Specialist Training and Certification", "url": "https://dbhdid.ky.gov/sud/ebpi-recovery", "description": "DBHDID page on evidence-based practices in recovery, including Kentucky Peer Specialist (KPS) certification. Peer specialists must complete 30 hours of approved training and pass written and oral exams."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Recovery Housing Network", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dbhdid/Pages/krhn.aspx", "description": "State-administered recovery housing network. Per KRS 222.502, recovery residences must be certified by an approved certifying organization. Contact Jonathan Philpot at 502-782-8478 for information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Alliance of Recovery Residences (KYARR)", "url": "https://kyarr.org/", "description": "One of three Cabinet-approved certifying organizations for recovery residences in Kentucky. Provides a directory of certified recovery homes across the Commonwealth using NARR standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department for Behavioral Health, Developmental and Intellectual Disabilities (DBHDID)", "url": "https://dbhdid.ky.gov/", "description": "State behavioral health agency responsible for administering mental health, substance use disorder, developmental, and intellectual disability programs throughout Kentucky."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline", "url": "https://988.ky.gov/", "description": "Call or text 988 to connect with suicide prevention, mental health, and substance abuse counselors. Available 24/7/365 to all Kentuckians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KY HELP Call Center (Operation UNITE)", "url": "https://operationunite.org/programs/kyhelp-call-center/", "description": "Statewide call center for substance use disorder assistance. Call 1-833-8KY-HELP (1-833-859-4357) for treatment referral and recovery support. Funded by the Kentucky Justice and Public Safety Cabinet."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://pharmacy.ky.gov/", "description": "Executive Director: Christopher P. Harlow. Phone: 502-564-7910. Fax: 502-696-3806. Email: pharmacy.board@ky.gov. Address: State Office Building Annex, Suite 300, 125 Holmes Street, Frankfort, KY 40601."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Department for Medicaid Services", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dms/Pages/default.aspx", "description": "Kentucky Medicaid agency. For public records requests, email DMS.Records@ky.gov. The Pharmacy Policy Branch manages the pharmacy benefit."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Kentucky's SOTA is located within the Cabinet for Health and Family Services. Contact SAMHSA's SOTA directory for the current Kentucky SOTA contact person."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Pharmacists Association (KPhA)", "url": "https://www.kphanet.org/", "description": "The largest professional organization representing pharmacists in Kentucky since 1879. KPhA serves as the voice of pharmacy for education, policy, legislative, and regulatory matters."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Office of Drug Control Policy (ODCP)", "url": "https://odcp.ky.gov/Pages/index.aspx", "description": "The ODCP is tasked with coordinating Kentucky's response to substance abuse, bringing together prevention/education, treatment, and law enforcement efforts. Located within the Justice and Public Safety Cabinet."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "KIPRC Drug Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://kiprc.uky.edu/injury-focus-areas/drug-overdose-prevention", "description": "Kentucky Injury Prevention and Research Center drug overdose surveillance program. Provides timely reports on drug overdose morbidity and mortality in the Commonwealth."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Overdose Data to Action Surveillance", "url": "https://kiprc.uky.edu/programs/kentucky-overdose-data-action-surveillance-programs", "description": "CDC-funded OD2A surveillance programs that monitor fatal and nonfatal drug overdose data using multiple data sets including EMS data, emergency department encounters, and medical examiner/coroner data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KIPRC Drug Overdose Surveillance", "url": "https://kiprc.uky.edu/programs/drug-overdose-surveillance", "description": "Drug Overdose Technical Assistance Core (DOTAC) maintains multiple databases on injury patterns in Kentucky, including emergency department visits, inpatient hospitalizations, death certificates, and prescription drug monitoring data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Drug Overdose Fatality Report", "url": "https://governor.ky.gov/attachments/2023-Drug-Overdose-Fatality-Report.pdf", "description": "Annual Drug Overdose Fatality Report compiled using data from the Office of the State Medical Examiner, KIPRC, and the Kentucky Office of Vital Statistics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Overdose Response Effort Data", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dbhdid/Pages/kore.aspx", "description": "KORE page includes data on treatment utilization, naloxone distribution, and prevention services funded through the State Opioid Response grant program."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Legislature Bill Search", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/record/25rs/record.html", "description": "Kentucky Legislative Research Commission bill search tool for tracking current legislation, including bills related to pharmacy practice, opioid treatment, and substance use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Kentucky Legislator", "url": "https://apps.legislature.ky.gov/findyourlegislator/findyourlegislator.html", "description": "Tool to find your Kentucky state representative and senator by entering your home address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Pharmacists Association (KPhA) Advocacy", "url": "https://www.kphanet.org/", "description": "KPhA is the voice of pharmacy concerning legislative and regulatory matters in the Commonwealth. The association advocates on behalf of pharmacists from all practice settings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "KPhA Board Authorized Protocols", "url": "https://www.kphanet.org/board%20authorized%20protocols", "description": "Information on 201 KAR 2:380 board authorized protocols, which allow pharmacists to provide protocol-driven care. KPhA assists pharmacists with protocol implementation and connecting with signing providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Kentucky Overdose Response Effort (KORE) Coalition", "url": "https://www.chfs.ky.gov/agencies/dbhdid/Pages/kore.aspx", "description": "KORE serves as the primary OUD-related coalition in Kentucky, coordinating prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery support services across the Commonwealth with over $35 million in annual federal funding."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Operation UNITE", "url": "https://operationunite.org/", "description": "Multi-county initiative serving 32 counties in Southeastern Kentucky through education, community coalitions, treatment entry assistance, and drug investigations. Also operates the statewide KY HELP Call Center."}]}]}, "louisiana": {"name": "Louisiana", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Louisiana’s term for a CPA is a written “protocol” under “pharmacy collaborative drug therapy management” (PCDTM). LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(39)(a) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Louisiana law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(44) (West 2024).\nMoreover, the definition provides that drugs and medications must be dispensed “pursuant to prescriptions or orders of physicians, dentists, veterinarians, or other licensed practitioners.” LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(44) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Louisiana cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Louisiana practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Louisiana pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Louisiana laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, the answer is likely “no.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Louisiana law does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(44) (West 2024).\nDespite this, Louisiana regulation provides education, training, and reporting requirements for “pharmacists who intend to administer medications to their patients.” LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 521 (2024). This regulation does not expressly limit the type of drugs and medications that a pharmacist can administer and may mean a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine.The complicating factor, however, is that as described in the answer to the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, Louisiana pharmacy regulations prohibit pharmacist collaborative drug therapy management (PCDTM) from involving controlled substances. Given this limitation, it seems unlikely that a Louisiana pharmacist would have more authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a PCDTM protocol than within one.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Louisiana practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Louisiana law does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(44) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Louisiana pharmacy laws and regulations expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of a protocol for pharmacy collaborative drug therapy management (PCDTM).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Louisiana practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAlthough not in the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Louisiana law, pharmacists may take part in PCDTM. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(39)(a) (West 2024).\nHowever, Louisiana regulation prohibits the scope of PCDTM from including “the management of controlled substances or drugs of concern.” LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523(D)(1)(e) (2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Louisiana laws and/or regulations to allow PCDTM to manage controlled substances.\nRevise Louisiana laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under written protocols for PCDTM.\nExpressly specify in Louisiana laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under written protocols for PCDTM.\nAllow Louisiana pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAlthough not in the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Louisiana law, pharmacists may take part in PCDTM. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(39)(a) (West 2024).\nHowever, Louisiana regulation prohibits the scope of PCDTM from including “the management of controlled substances or drugs of concern.” LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523(D)(1)(e) (2024).", "5B": null, "5C": "Revise Louisiana laws and/or regulations to allow PCDTM to manage controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Louisiana laws or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a written protocol for PCDTM.", "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nAlthough not in the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Louisiana law, pharmacists may take part in PCDTM “under a written protocol.” LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(39)(a) (West 2024).\nLouisiana regulation provides that the PCDTM protocol must identify “the specific laboratory test or tests, if any, directly related to drug therapy management the physician authorizes the pharmacist to order and evaluate.” LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523(D)(3)(b)(viii)) (2024).\nAlthough pharmacists can order and evaluate lab tests under written protocols for PCDTM generally, the regulation prohibits the scope of PCDTM from including “the management of controlled substances or drugs of concern.” LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523(D)(1)(e) (2024).", "6B": "N/A, because a written protocol for PCDTM cannot manage controlled substances.", "6C": "Revise Louisiana laws and/or regulations to allow PCDTM to manage controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Louisiana laws and/or regulations that pharmacist authority under a written protocol for PCDTM includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "PCDTM is a practice in which a pharmacist “voluntarily agrees with a physician to manage the disease specific drug therapy of one or more patients of such physician, within a predetermined range of medication selected by the physician and set forth in a patient specific written order set.” LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523(A) (2024)\n(definitions).\nThe term “physician” means a person with an unrestricted license to practice medicine issued by the Louisiana State Board of Medical Examiners. LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523(A) (2024) (definitions).\nThe following Louisiana laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering PCDTM and required elements of written protocols for PCDTM – LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1164(39) (West 2024); LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, § 523 (2024).", "8A": "As described in the information below, Louisiana laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. Also, note that there are limitations related to controlled substances (see the telehealth provisions related to buprenorphine section).\nFor purposes of Louisiana’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law, a “healthcare provider” includes any person “licensed or certified by this state to practice medicine or provide health care or healthcare professional services.” LA. STAT. ANN. § 40:1223.3(3) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.\nLouisiana’s general telehealth/telemedicine law provides that “each state agency or professional or occupational licensing board or commission that regulates the practice of a healthcare provider . . . shall promulgate . . . , any rules necessary to provide for, promote, and regulate the use of telehealth in the delivery of healthcare services within the scope of practice regulated by the licensing entity.” LA. STAT. ANN. § 40:1223.4(A) (West 2024). Prior to a January 2024 law change, the promulgation of regulations was voluntary, not required.\nHowever, there are no telehealth or telemedicine specific laws or regulations for pharmacists in Louisiana, only regulations related to telepharmacy. This makes it unclear if pharmacists actually can provide telehealth/telemedicine services beyond telepharmacy.", "8B": "Adopt regulations to expressly provide that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "The general rule is that, unless allowed by regulation or state board protocol, a healthcare provider cannot prescribe controlled substances “prior to conducting an appropriate in-person patient history or physical examination of the patient.” LA. STAT. ANN. § 40:1223.4(6) (West 2024).\nLouisiana physician regulations provide that controlled substances can be prescribed via telemedicine only if the physician can sufficiently examine a patient via that method and meets other requirements stated in regulation. LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:XLV, § 7513 (2024).\nLouisiana laws and regulations governing telehealth include – LA. STAT. ANN. §§ 40:1223.1 to 40:1223.5 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); LA. STAT. ANN. §§ 40:1255.1 to 40:1255.2 (West 2024) (Medicaid); LA. STAT. ANN. § 46:460.54 (West 2024) (Medicaid managed care); LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:XLV, §§ 7501 to 7521 (2024)\n(physicians); LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 46:LIII, §§ 2421 to 2425 (2024) (telepharmacy); LA. ADMIN CODE. tit. 50:I, §§ 501 to 503 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "Administering immunizations such as influenza, hepatitis, HPV, etc., and family planning items/services.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Louisiana Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Louisiana laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a written protocol for PCDTM are covered under the Louisiana Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Advanced practice registered nursing “may include the provision of medication-assisted treatment (MAT)” pursuant to an agreement with a collaborating physician. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:913(3)(c) (West 2024). “MAT” means “the use of medications with counseling and behavioral therapies to treat substance use disorders and prevent opioid overdose.”\nA physician assistant “may provide medication-assisted treatment (MAT)” pursuant to an agreement with a supervising physician. LA. STAT. ANN. § 37:1360.31(C)(4) (West 2024). “MAT” means “medications with counseling and behavioral therapies to treat substance use disorders and prevent opioid overdose.”"}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PMP Portal", "url": "https://louisiana.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Louisiana PMP AWARxE web portal operated by Bamboo Health on behalf of the Louisiana Board of Pharmacy. Pharmacists and prescribers log in here to access patient prescription monitoring data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Information Page", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/page/prescription-monitoring-program-pmp-information", "description": "Louisiana Board of Pharmacy PMP information page with links to the web portal, general information, annual program reports, and the PMP Advisory Council. Also covers the EHR/pharmacy management system integration platform."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Registration", "url": "https://louisiana.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "To register for PMP access, visit the portal and select \"Create an Account.\" An Individual Access Code provided by the Board is required for immediate access. Contact the Board at 225-925-6496 for assistance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Louisiana has a PMP mandatory use law under RS 40:978. Prescribers or their delegates must access and review the PMP before initially prescribing any opioid to a patient. Pharmacists licensed by the Louisiana Board of Pharmacy are automatically registered as PMP participants."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Louisiana participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate PDMP data sharing through the Bamboo Health platform. Details available at https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/page/prescription-monitoring-program-pmp-information"}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: The PMP system allows prescribers to designate delegates to access PMP data on their behalf. Delegate registration is managed through the PMP AWARxE portal at https://louisiana.pmpaware.net/login"}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/", "description": "Official website of the Louisiana Board of Pharmacy. Created by the Louisiana Legislature in 1888, the Board regulates and controls the practice of pharmacy in Louisiana."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Laws and Regulations", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/page/876", "description": "Louisiana Board of Pharmacy laws and regulations page, updated through the 2024 Regular Legislative Session. Includes links to all pharmacy-related statutes and administrative rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/page/877", "description": "Board page with links to all laws affecting pharmacy practice in Louisiana, including the Pharmacy Practice Act (Chapter 14 of Title 37), Uniform Controlled Dangerous Substances Law, and related health provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/page/807", "description": "Board page covering Louisiana Administrative Code provisions affecting pharmacy, including emergency rules and final rules adopted by the Board."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice and Prescriptive Authority", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/assets/docs/Public_Library/2020_ES-2_SR-39_BoardRptPkg.pdf", "description": "Board report on collaborative practice and limited prescriptive authority for pharmacists under proposed R.S. 37:1220. Louisiana has explored pharmacist collaborative practice authority but specific statutes are evolving. Check the Board's laws page for current status."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Louisiana pharmacists do not have broad independent prescribing authority. However, pharmacists can dispense naloxone under a statewide standing order and provide certain protocol-based services. Check https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/page/876 for current legislation."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Help Louisiana", "url": "https://opioidhelpla.org/", "description": "State-supported website connecting individuals to help for opioid use disorder, including local recovery resources, information on safe disposal and storage of drugs, and guides to opioid alternatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "LDH Opioid Resources Page", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/opioids", "description": "Louisiana Department of Health opioid information page covering the scope of the opioid crisis in Louisiana, with links to treatment resources, the HOPE Council, and surveillance data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Treatment Programs and Office-Based Providers", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/directory/category/opioid-treatment-office-based-providers", "description": "LDH directory of opioid treatment programs and office-based providers in Louisiana, including methadone clinics and buprenorphine prescribers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to Louisiana to find substance use disorder treatment facilities, including those offering medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA directory listing each state's Opioid Treatment Authority. Louisiana's SOTA is housed within the Louisiana Department of Health."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine: Louisiana follows federal telehealth regulations for buprenorphine prescribing under the Louisiana Telehealth Access Act. The DEA now allows prescribing buprenorphine for OUD via telemedicine. See https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html for current federal guidance."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Medicaid Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://www.lamedicaid.com/provweb1/pharmacy/pharmacyindex.htm", "description": "Louisiana Medicaid pharmacy program index page with links to provider information, billing guidance, and program updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/assets/healthyla/pharmacy/pdl.pdf", "description": "Current Louisiana Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) and Non-Preferred Drug List (NPDL). Non-preferred medications are available through the prior authorization process."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Healthy Louisiana Pharmacy Information", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/behavioral-health", "description": "Louisiana Department of Health Healthy Louisiana managed care program information. Medicaid pharmacy benefits in Louisiana are administered through managed care organizations."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Louisiana Medicaid Fee Schedules: Contact the Louisiana Department of Health for current Medicaid fee schedules for pharmacist services. General Medicaid information is available at https://www.lamedicaid.com"}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Funding: Louisiana receives federal State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA. The Office of Behavioral Health administers these grants for expanding treatment, prevention, and recovery services. Information at https://ldh.la.gov/office-of-behavioral-health"}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/", "description": "Louisiana pharmacists must complete either 15 hours of CE annually (3 must be live) or 20 hours (if no live). Pharmacist clinicians with controlled substance registration must complete 2 hours on responsible opioid prescribing practices. Check the Board website for current requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.louisianapharmacists.com/", "description": "The Louisiana Pharmacists Association (LPA) offers continuing education programs and training for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians. ACPE-accredited provider since 1892."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "All DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorder treatment per the MATE Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD offers free training satisfying DEA MATE Act requirements for 8-hour opioid use disorder education, including buprenorphine-specific training modules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA MATE Act Resources", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/mate-act", "description": "SAMHSA resources for MATE Act training requirements, with links to approved training programs for practitioners who prescribe controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Overdose Prevention and Response Hub", "url": "https://louisianahealthhub.org/oprh/", "description": "LDH Overdose Prevention and Response Hub providing Narcan and fentanyl test strip distribution, training for participating institutions, and overdose prevention resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/assets/HealthyLa/Pharmacy/NaloxoneStandingOrder.pdf", "description": "Louisiana statewide standing order for naloxone distribution, authorizing pharmacists to dispense naloxone or other opioid antagonists without an individual prescription."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Louisiana Syringe Services: Louisiana has authorized syringe services programs. The STI/HIV/Hepatitis Program within the Office of Public Health manages these services. Information at https://louisianahealthhub.org/oprh/"}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips are legal in Louisiana. In 2022, Gabby's Law (HB 212 / Act 137) excluded rapid fentanyl test strips from the definition of drug paraphernalia. Test strips are distributed through the Overdose Prevention and Response Hub."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Opioid Data and Surveillance System (LODSS)", "url": "https://lodss.ldh.la.gov/", "description": "Interactive dashboard for Louisiana opioid and drug overdose surveillance data, including fatal and nonfatal overdose data, emergency department visits, and fact sheets. Maintained by the Louisiana Department of Health."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Specialist Program", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/page/2578", "description": "Louisiana Office of Behavioral Health peer support specialist information page. OBH recognizes peer support specialists in the recovery process. Certification requires 76 hours of training and continuing education of 10 hours per year (3 in ethics)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prevention, Treatment, and Recovery Services", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/office-of-behavioral-health/substance-use-and-gambling-disorders", "description": "LDH page on substance use and gambling disorder services, including links to Oxford House recovery housing and treatment provider directories."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Office of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/office-of-behavioral-health", "description": "Louisiana's state behavioral health agency managing mental health and addiction services. Phone: 225-342-2540. For substance use support, call 877-664-2248."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Louisiana 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline: Call or text 988 for suicide prevention, mental health, and substance use crisis support. Available 24/7."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Louisiana Addiction Helpline: Call 877-664-2248 for resources and support for alcohol and drug addiction. For non-emergency behavioral health resources, call 211."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.la.gov/", "description": "Executive Director: M. Joseph Fontenot. Address: 3388 Brentwood Drive, Baton Rouge, LA 70809-1700. Phone: 225-925-6496."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Department of Health - Medicaid", "url": "https://www.lamedicaid.com", "description": "Louisiana Medicaid program. Customer service: 1-888-342-6207. Healthy Louisiana: 1-855-229-6848."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Louisiana's SOTA contact is available through the SAMHSA directory."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.louisianapharmacists.com/", "description": "Professional association serving pharmacists and pharmacy technicians in Louisiana since 1892. Address: 620 Florida St., Suite 210, Baton Rouge, LA 70801. Phone: 225-346-6883."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Department of Health Opioid Programs", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/opioids", "description": "LDH opioid crisis response page with links to the HOPE Council, treatment resources, and state opioid data."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Opioid Data and Surveillance System (LODSS)", "url": "https://lodss.ldh.la.gov/", "description": "Interactive dashboard with data on drug overdose deaths, emergency department visits, and other surveillance metrics. Includes fact sheets and HOPE Council surveillance updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Surveillance Program", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/bureau-of-health-informatics/opioidsurveillance", "description": "LDH Bureau of Health Informatics opioid surveillance program that assembles and analyzes data on the opioid epidemic in Louisiana to support education, prevention, intervention, and treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Annual Drug Death Reports", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/assets/opioid/2021_Annual_Drug_Death_Report.pdf", "description": "Annual drug death report analyzing opioid and drug poisoning death data in Louisiana. Reports are published periodically by the LDH."}, {"type": "link", "title": "HOPE Council Reports", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/page/2970", "description": "HOPE (Heroin and Opioid Prevention and Education) Council page with links to annual reports, surveillance updates, and the Interagency Heroin and Opioid Coordination Plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Help Louisiana Data", "url": "https://opioidhelpla.org/", "description": "State-supported website with data on opioid deaths, treatment resources, and community-level information."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Legislature Bill Search", "url": "https://www.legis.la.gov/", "description": "Louisiana State Legislature homepage with bill search and tracking tools for monitoring current legislation related to pharmacy practice, opioid treatment, and substance use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find My Legislators", "url": "https://www.legis.la.gov/legis/FindMyLegislators.aspx", "description": "Tool to find your Louisiana state representative and senator by entering your address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Louisiana Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.louisianapharmacists.com/", "description": "LPA serves as the collaborative Voice of Pharmacy in Louisiana for legislative and regulatory advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "HOPE Council (Opioid Task Force)", "url": "https://ldh.la.gov/page/2970", "description": "Advisory Council on Heroin and Opioid Prevention and Education (HOPE Council), established by Act 88 of the Louisiana Legislature. Coordinates the state's opioid response, parish-level data, and makes policy recommendations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Governor's Drug Policy Page", "url": "https://gov.louisiana.gov/page/drug-policy", "description": "Louisiana Governor's Office drug policy page with links to the HOPE Council and state drug policy initiatives."}]}]}, "maine": {"name": "Maine", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maine law does not include prescribing drugs or medications other than “ordering and dispensing of over-the-counter nicotine replacement products” and “prescribing, dispensing and administering of an HIV prevention drug” pursuant to protocol. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(28) (West 2024).\nIn addition, although not in the practice of pharmacy definition, there are other Maine pharmacy laws pertaining to prescribing insulin, overdose reversal agents, and contraceptives. There are no laws or regulations that address prescribing controlled substances.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Maine cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Maine practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Maine pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maine law includes “the administration to adults by intramuscular and subcutaneous injection of drugs approved by [FDA].” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(28) (West 2024).\nFurther, beyond the practice of pharmacy definition, there is a “subchapter” of Maine pharmacy laws that address “administration of drugs and vaccines.” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, §§ 13831 to 13835 (West 2024). This law specifies the circumstances under which a pharmacist may administer drugs and vaccines. The only listed circumstance potentially applicable to administering buprenorphine is for the “administration of injectable drugs.” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13831(5) (West 2024).\nThere does not appear to be authority in Maine law or regulation for a pharmacist to administer any form of buprenorphine other than an injectable.", "2B": "Obtain an order by a practitioner to dispense and administer the drug, and the practitioner must be notified after administration is complete. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13831(5)(A) (West 2024).\nAdhere to the training, educational, and recordkeeping requirements in Maine laws. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, §§ 13831 to 13835 (West 2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maine law does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(28) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Maine pharmacy laws and regulations expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests by pharmacists outside of a collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM) in accordance with a CPA.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Maine practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maine law includes performing CDTM. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(28) (West 2024).\nMaine law defines CDTM as “the initiating, administering, monitoring, modifying and discontinuing of a patient’s drug therapy by a pharmacist as authorized by a practitioner in accordance with a [CPA].” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(2-A) (West 2024). Although the provision uses the words “initiating” and “modifying” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. It is possible that these words could encompass prescribing buprenorphine.\nHowever, Maine laws and regulations governing CDTM and CPAs do not account for the fact that a Maine pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPA provides.\nIn summary, Maine laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Maine pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Maine laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPAs.\nExpressly specify in Maine laws and/ or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs for CDTM.\nAllow Maine pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Yes, based on the information below, if the term “qualifying condition” encompasses SUD.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maine law includes performing CDTM. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(28) (West 2024).\nMaine law defines CDTM as “the initiating, administering, monitoring, modifying and discontinuing of a patient’s drug therapy by a pharmacist as authorized by a practitioner in accordance with a [CPA].” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(2-A) (West 2024). This language expressly authorizes administering drugs or medications in general.\nHowever, Maine regulation provides that a CPA “may authorize collaborative drug therapy management only for qualifying conditions.” 02-392-39 ME. CODE R. § 3 (2024).\nA “qualifying condition” is a “condition or disease with generally accepted standards of care.” 02-392-39 ME. CODE R. § 1(5) (2024). Maine regulation provides a list of eight examples, none of which are SUD. However, the regulation expressly notes that the list is non-exhaustive.\nSo long as SUD is considered a “qualifying condition,” a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a CPA. If SUD is not such a condition, however, then the answer would be “no.” Moreover, if this answer becomes “no,” that calls into question whether the answer to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section can remain “yes,” as it seems unlikely a pharmacist would have authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CPA but not within one.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, revise Maine laws and/or regulations to expressly provide that SUD is a “qualifying condition” for CDTM under a CPA.", "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the evaluation cannot include a diagnostic component, and “qualifying condition” must encompasses SUD.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maine law includes performing CDTM. ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(28) (West 2024).\nAs part of CPA for CDTM, a pharmacist may “order and evaluate the results of laboratory tests directly related to drug therapy under the supervision of, or in direct consultation with, a practitioner . . . when the evaluation does not include a diagnostic component.” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13841(2)(C) (West 2024). This language expressly authorizes ordering and evaluating the results of lab tests except as limited.\nHowever, Maine regulation provides that a CPA “may authorize collaborative drug therapy management only for qualifying conditions.” 02-392-39 ME. CODE R. § 3 (2024).\nA “qualifying condition” is a “condition or disease with generally accepted standards of care.” 02-392-39 ME. CODE R. § 1(5) (2024). Maine regulation provides a list of eight examples, none of which are SUD. However, the regulation expressly notes that the list is non-exhaustive.\nSo long as SUD is considered a “qualifying condition,” under a CPA, a pharmacist can order and evaluate the results of lab tests directly related to drug therapy when the evaluation does not include a diagnostic component. If SUD is not such a condition, however, then the answer would be “no.”", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Although not completely necessary, revise Maine laws and/or regulations to expressly provide that SUD is a “qualifying condition” for CDTM under a CPA.", "7": "Maine law provides that a CPA means “a written and signed agreement between one or more pharmacists with training and experience relevant to the scope of the collaborative practice and a practitioner that supervises or provides direct consultation to the pharmacist or pharmacists.” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(2-B) (West 2024).\n“Practitioner” means an “individual who is licensed, registered or otherwise authorized in the appropriate jurisdiction to prescribe and administer drugs in the course of professional practice.” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13702-A(29) (West 2024).\nMaine pharmacy regulations contain two separate sections pertaining to CDTM, one issued in conjunction with the Maine Board of Licensing in Medicine, and one issued in conjunction with the Maine Board of Nursing.\nThe following Maine laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, §§ 13841 to 13847 (West 2024); 02-392-39 ME. CODE R. §§ 1-8 (2024) (issued jointly with Maine Board of Licensing in Medicine); 02-392-39-A ME. CODE R. §§ 1-8 (2024) (issued jointly with Maine Board of Nursing).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMaine pharmacy law expressly provides that a pharmacist “may provide telehealth services as long as the licensee [pharmacist] acts within the scope of practice of the licensee’s license, in accordance with any requirements and restrictions imposed by this subchapter and in accordance with standards of practice.” ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, § 13849 (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "There are Maine laws specific to pharmacy provision of telehealth. Although the laws suggest that regulations governing the standards of pharmacy telehealth practice must be adopted, none appear adopted to date.\nMaine has a specific regulations for physicians and nurses related to telehealth practice for office based opioid treatment (OBOT). 02-373-12 ME. CODE R. § 6 (2024); 02-380-12 ME. CODE R. § 6 (2024).\nMaine laws and regulations governing telehealth include – ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, §§ 13848 to 13849-C (West 2024) \n(pharmacists); ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 24-A,§ 4316 (West 2024) \n(health plan requirements); ME. REV. STAT. ANN. tit. 32, §§ 3300-AA to 3300-EE (West 2024)\n(physicians); 02-373-11 ME. CODE R. §§ 1-3 (guidelines for medical practice); 02-373-12 ME. CODE R. § 6 (2024) (OBOT); 02-380-12 ME. CODE R. § 6 (2024) (OBOT).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Maine Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Maine laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CPA for CDTM are covered under the Maine Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "There is a joint rule of the Maine Board of Licensure in Medicine, the Maine Board of Nursing, and the Maine Board of Osteopathic Licensure “to ensure safe and adequate treatment of [OUD] with Approved Medications in an outpatient medical setting that is not a certified Opioid Treatment Program.” 02-373-12 ME. CODE R. §§ 1-6 (2024). The regulations include prescription requirements, qualifications, “principles of proper OBOT,” and telehealth."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PMP Portal", "url": "https://maine.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Maine PMP AWARxE web portal. Login page for prescribers and pharmacists to access patient prescription monitoring data. For password resets or login questions, call 207-287-2595."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Information Page", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/providers/prescription-drug-monitoring-program", "description": "Maine DHHS Office of Behavioral Health PMP information page. The PMP is a secure database used to improve public health by providing controlled substance drug use information prior to prescribing or dispensing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "PMP Registration: To create a PMP account, visit https://maine.pmpaware.net/login and select \"Create an Account.\" Technical support is available at 844-463-4767."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP FAQ", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/providers/pmp-faq", "description": "Frequently asked questions about the Maine Prescription Monitoring Program, including registration, access requirements, and use guidelines."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Maine requires prescribers to check the PMP before initially prescribing opioids and at defined intervals. Pharmacists are registered participants in the PMP system."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Maine participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing through the Bamboo Health/AWARxE platform."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Regulatory Information", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/sos/cec/rules/14/118/118c011.docx", "description": "Chapter 11 Rule document with regulatory and statutory information governing the Maine PMP."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/pfr/professionallicensing/professions/board-pharmacy", "description": "Maine Board of Pharmacy, housed within the Office of Professional and Occupational Regulation. Regulates pharmacist licensure, pharmacy permits, and the practice of pharmacy in Maine."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Laws and Rules", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/pfr/professionallicensing/professions/board-pharmacy/home/laws-rules", "description": "Board of Pharmacy laws and rules page with links to applicable statutes and administrative regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Pharmacy Act (Title 32, Chapter 117)", "url": "https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/32/title32ch117sec0.html", "description": "Full text of the Maine Pharmacy Act, Title 32, Chapter 117 of the Maine Revised Statutes. Covers pharmacist licensure, pharmacy operations, collaborative practice, and related provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Pharmacy Act (PDF)", "url": "https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/32/title32ch117.pdf", "description": "Downloadable PDF of the complete Maine Pharmacy Act including provisions on collaborative practice agreements, drug administration, and pharmacist authority."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice Agreements: Under Title 32, Section 13702-A, Maine pharmacists may enter into collaborative practice agreements with supervising practitioners. The agreement must define the collaborative practice scope, dates, and be within the practitioner's practice area. Pharmacists in collaborative practice must complete 5 of their 15 annual CE hours in the practice areas covered by the agreement."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Maine pharmacists have certain prescribing and dispensing authorities including naloxone dispensing, HIV prevention drug prescribing (effective 2025), and vaccine administration. Check the Board website for current authorities."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Substance Use Disorder Treatment Services", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/support-services/substance-use-disorder-services/treatment-services", "description": "DHHS Office of Behavioral Health treatment services page. Covers medication-assisted treatment (MAT) using methadone, Suboxone (buprenorphine), and naltrexone for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Drug Data Hub - Treatment", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/maine-drug-data-hub/maine-drug-data/treatment/", "description": "Data and resources on substance use disorder treatment trends in Maine, including buprenorphine prescribing data, treatment capacity, and outcome metrics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "SAMHSA national treatment locator, filterable to Maine, for finding substance use disorder treatment facilities including those providing medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "Directory of practitioners authorized to treat OUD with buprenorphine, searchable by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA directory of State Opioid Treatment Authorities. Maine's SOTA is within the Department of Health and Human Services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine: Maine follows federal telehealth regulations for buprenorphine prescribing. The DEA allows prescribing buprenorphine for OUD via telemedicine. See https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html for federal guidance."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MaineCare Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.mainecarepdl.org/", "description": "MaineCare (Maine Medicaid) Preferred Drug List portal. Provides drug coverage information, policy updates, and resources for members, pharmacies, and healthcare providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MaineCare Buprenorphine Coverage", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/oms/providers/provider-bulletins/extended-release-buprenorphine-clinical-use-criteria-2023-06-23", "description": "MaineCare clinical use criteria for extended-release buprenorphine. Preferred cost-effective options include buprenorphine/naloxone films and oral tablets."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MaineCare OTC Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/oms/providers/provider-bulletins/over-counter-otc-naloxone-standing-order-mainecare-members-2024-02-20", "description": "MaineCare standing order for OTC naloxone billing. Authorizes pharmacists to create a single-use prescription for naloxone for MaineCare members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine DHHS Office of MaineCare Services", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/oms", "description": "MaineCare (Maine Medicaid) program homepage with links to provider bulletins, fee schedules, and benefit information."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Funding: Maine receives federal State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA for expanding OUD treatment and prevention services. The Office of Behavioral Health administers these programs."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.mainelegislature.org/legis/statutes/32/title32sec13735.html", "description": "Title 32, Section 13735 of the Maine Revised Statutes outlines CE requirements. Pharmacists must complete 15 hours of continuing education annually. Those authorized to administer drugs must complete at least 2 hours in board-approved drug administration courses."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice CE: Pharmacists entering into collaborative practice agreements must complete 5 of 15 annual CE hours in practice areas covered by the agreement per Title 32, Section 13735."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maine Pharmacy Association Education: The Maine Pharmacy Association offers continuing education programs. Contact: 207-772-7235. The association partners with the University of New England for specialty CE including naloxone training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "All DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorder treatment per the MATE Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System offers free training satisfying DEA requirements for 8-hour opioid use disorder education."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Access Points (MAP)", "url": "https://www.maineaccesspoints.org/", "description": "Harm reduction organization providing syringe access services, overdose prevention education, naloxone distribution, peer support, and advocacy throughout rural Maine. Call or text 207-319-8284 for free naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Drug Data Hub - Harm Reduction", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/maine-drug-data-hub/maine-drug-data/harm-reduction/", "description": "Data and resources on harm reduction strategies in Maine, including syringe access programs, naloxone distribution, and overdose prevention."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MAP Naloxone and Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://www.maineaccesspoints.org/naloxone", "description": "Free naloxone and overdose prevention education available anywhere in Maine. Orders available online in English and Spanish."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order for MaineCare", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/oms/providers/provider-bulletins/over-counter-otc-naloxone-standing-order-mainecare-members-2024-02-20", "description": "Standing order authorizing licensed pharmacists to dispense naloxone to MaineCare members."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strips: Fentanyl test strips are legal and available in Maine through syringe access programs and harm reduction organizations. They are distributed through Maine Access Points, Health Equity Alliance, and other organizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Drug Death Dashboard", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/fatal-overdose-dashboard/", "description": "Interactive dashboard showing drug-related fatalities in Maine, filterable by substance (fentanyl, heroin/morphine, pharmaceutical opioids, cocaine, methamphetamine, benzodiazepines, xylazine)."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Association of Recovery Residences (MARR)", "url": "https://www.mainerecoveryresidences.com/", "description": "MARR is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit that manages ethical and safety standards for recovery residences in Maine and certifies residences based on NARR standards. Provides a directory of certified recovery homes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Office of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh", "description": "State behavioral health agency within the Department of Health and Human Services. Provides substance use disorder services, mental health services, and crisis support."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use Disorder Services", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/support-services/substance-use-disorder-services", "description": "DHHS OBH page covering substance use disorder services including treatment, recovery supports, and related services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SUD Recovery Supports", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/support-services/substance-use-disorder-services", "description": "OBH page with links to substance use disorder treatment and recovery support services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maine Crisis Services: Call 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (24/7). Call 211 or visit 211maine.org for general behavioral health and social service resources."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/pfr/professionallicensing/professions/board-pharmacy", "description": "Located within the Office of Professional and Occupational Regulation. Contact via the website for licensing and regulatory inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine DHHS Office of MaineCare Services", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/oms", "description": "Maine Medicaid program administration."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Maine's SOTA is within the Department of Health and Human Services. Contact through SAMHSA's SOTA directory."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maine Pharmacy Association: Contact phone 207-772-7235. Address: 725 Main Street, South Portland, ME 04106. The association advocates for the profession and provides education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Office of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/about", "description": "Oversees behavioral health programs including substance use disorder services. Works with the Governor's Director of Opioid Response on policy."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Drug Data Hub", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/", "description": "Comprehensive hub with nearly 300 data metrics, 200 reports and resources, dashboards, maps, and data products related to substance use in Maine. Supports the state's Opioid Response Strategic Action Plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Drug Death Dashboard", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/fatal-overdose-dashboard/", "description": "Interactive fatal overdose dashboard with data filterable by substance type, location, and time period."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Drug Data Index", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/maine-drug-data-hub/data-index/", "description": "Comprehensive index of available data sources including Maine CDC syndromic surveillance, drug overdose morbidity and mortality dashboards, and opioid prescribing trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Annual Reports", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/PMP-Annual-Report-2023-Final.pdf", "description": "PMP annual report for calendar year 2023, including data on opioid dispensing quantities and prescribing trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Treatment Data", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/maine-drug-data-hub/maine-drug-data/treatment/", "description": "Treatment trend data including buprenorphine prescribing volumes, unique patient counts, and treatment capacity metrics."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maine Legislature Bill Search", "url": "https://legislature.maine.gov/", "description": "Maine Legislature homepage with access to bill tracking, session information, and legislative documents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Your Legislator", "url": "https://legislature.maine.gov/house/MemberProfiles/ContactYourLegislator", "description": "Tool to find and contact your Maine state representative and senator."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maine Pharmacy Association: Contact phone 207-772-7235. The association advocates for pharmacy practice and public health through legislative and regulatory engagement. Member of NASPA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maine Opioid Response Strategic Action Plan", "url": "https://mainedrugdata.org/", "description": "The Maine Drug Data Hub tracks progress toward goals outlined in Maine's Opioid Response 2023-2025 Strategic Action Plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Governor's Director of Opioid Response", "url": "https://www.maine.gov/dhhs/obh/about", "description": "Maine has a Governor's Director of Opioid Response who works with the Office of Behavioral Health to oversee programs and set public policy regarding behavioral health and opioid response."}]}]}, "maryland": {"name": "Maryland", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Maryland’s term for a CPA is a “prescriber-pharmacist agreement” (P-PA) for “drug therapy management” (DTM). MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-01(f) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maryland law does not expressly reference prescribing drugs or medications other than those for contraceptive and nicotine replacement therapies. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-101(x)(1) (West 2024).\nThe definition of an “authorized prescriber” in Maryland pharmacy law does not include pharmacist. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-101(b) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Maryland cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Maryland practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Maryland pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maryland law includes “administering . . . maintenance injectable medications in accordance with § 12-509 of this title.” MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-101(x)(1)(viii) (West 2024).“Maintenance injectable medication” means a medication that is “administered by injection other than intravenously” and “treats a chronic need, condition, or disorder.” Such medication expressly includes a medication for SUD treatment. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-101(o-1) (West 2024).\nThere does not appear to be authority in Maryland law or regulation for a pharmacist to administer any form of buprenorphine other than a maintenance injectable.", "2B": "Obtain written authorization from a licensed prescriber prior to administering the first dose. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-509(b) (West 2024).\nAdhere to the administration, recordkeeping, and training requirements contained in Maryland law and regulations. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-509 (West 2024); MD. CODE REGS. 10.34.41.00 to 10.34.41.07 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the Maryland practice of pharmacy to include administering all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Maryland does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-101(x)(1) (West 2024).\nHowever, Maryland regulation governing medical laboratories does allow a pharmacist to obtain a “letter of exception” to become a “point-of-care laboratory” to independently perform 37 specified types of CLIA-waived tests. MD. CODE REGS. 10.10.03.02 (2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Maryland practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nMaryland law allows a pharmacist to enter into a “prescriber-pharmacist agreement” (P-PA) for drug therapy management (DTM) with an “authorized prescriber.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-01(f) (West 2024).\nThe term “authorized prescriber” in Maryland pharmacy law generally, and law specific to DTM as well, does not include pharmacists. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. §§ 12-101(b), 12-6A-01(b) (West 2024).\nWhat a protocol in a P-PA can authorize depends in part on what prescriber is involved. Protocols in P-PAs between a pharmacist and a physician may authorize “the initiation of drug therapy under written, disease-state specific protocols.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-06(a)(1)(i) (West 2024); MD. CODE REGS. 10-34.29.02(B)(4) (2024). Although this provision uses the term “initiation,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. It is possible that “initiation” could encompass prescribing buprenorphine.\nIn contrast, protocols in P-PAs between a pharmacist and a non-physician may not authorize the initiation of drug therapy. MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-06(a)(1)(i) (West 2024).\nMoreover, Maryland laws and regulations governing DTM and P-PAs do not account for the fact that a Maryland pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the P-PA provides.\nIn summary, Maryland laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a P-PA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Maryland pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Maryland laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under P-PAs.\nExpressly specify in Maryland laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under P-PAs for DTM.\nAllow Maryland pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Maryland laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” at least to the same extent.\nMaryland law allows a pharmacist to enter into a P-PA for DTM with an “authorized prescriber.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-01(f) (West 2024).\nWhat a protocol in a P-PA can authorize depends in part on what prescriber is involved. Protocols in P-PAs between a pharmacist and a physician may authorize “the initiation of drug therapy under written, disease-state specific protocols.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-06(a)(1)(i) (West 2024); MD. CODE REGS. 10-34.29.02(B)(4) (2024). Although this provision uses the term “initiation,” it does not expressly refer to administration. It is possible that the term could encompass administering buprenorphine.\nMoreover, a P-PA between a pharmacist and any prescriber (not just physicians) can authorize “modification, continuation, and discontinuation of drug therapy under written, disease–state specific protocols.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-06(a)(1)(ii) (West 2024); MD. CODE REGS. 10-34.29.02(B)(1) (2024).\nAlthough this provision uses the phrase “modification, continuation, and discontinuation,” it does not expressly refer to administration. It is possible that the phrase could encompass administering buprenorphine. Although Maryland laws and regulations are unclear about administering buprenorphine under P-PAs, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that Maryland pharmacists have the authority to administer a “maintenance injectable medication”—which includes injectable medications for SUD treatment—the logical answer to this question is yes, at least to the same extent.", "5B": "Enter into a P-PA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Maryland laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under all P-PAs for DTM.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests.\nMaryland law allows a pharmacist to enter into a P-PA for DTM with an “authorized prescriber.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-01(f) (West 2024).\nThe protocols under a P-PA between a pharmacist and any authorized prescriber can include “the ordering of laboratory tests.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-06(a)(1)(iii) (West 2024); MD. CODE REGS. 10-34.29.02(B)(2) (2024).\nMaryland laws and regulations governing P-PAs do not expressly refer to evaluating lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a P-PA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Maryland laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a P-PA includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A P-PA is an agreement between “an authorized prescriber and a licensed pharmacist that is disease-state specific and specifies the protocols that may be used.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-01(f) (West 2024).\n“Authorized prescriber” means “a licensed physician, licensed podiatrist, or certified advanced practice nurse with prescriptive authority.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 12-6A-01(b) (West 2024).\nThe following Maryland laws and regulations provide more information on drug therapy management, entering P-PAs, and required elements of P-PAs – MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. §§ 12-6A-01 to 12-6A-10 (West 2024); MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH-GEN. § 19-713.6 (West 2024) (P-PAs in health maintenance organization); MD. CODE REGS. 10.34.29.01 to 10.34.29.07 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMaryland’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that a “health care practitioner” can provide health care services via telehealth within the individual’s scope of practice. MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 1-1003 (West 2024).\nA “health care practitioner” means “an individual who is licensed, certified, or otherwise authorized by law to provide health care services.” MD. CODE. ANN., HEALTH OCC. § 1-1001(c) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "Maryland laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH OCC. §§ 1-1001 to 1-1006 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH-GEN. § 15-141.2 (West 2024) (Medicaid); MD. CODE ANN., INS. § 15-139 (West 2024) (insurance); MD. CODE REGS. 10.09.49.01 to 10.09.49.12 (2024) (Medicaid); MD. CODE REGS. 10.32.05.01 to 10.32.05.07 (2024) (physicians).", "9A": "The Maryland Medicaid program and all commercial insurers must reimburse all services rendered by a licensed pharmacist within the pharmacist’s scope of practice, to the same extent as services rendered by any other health care practitioner. MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH-GEN. § 15-152 (West 2024); MD. CODE ANN., INS. § 15-716 (West 2024).", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Each health care facility not part of a health care system and each health care system must “make available to patients the services of health care providers who are trained and authorized under federal law to prescribe opioid addiction treatment medications, including buprenorphine-containing formulations.” MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH-GEN. § 8-1101(b) (West 2024).\n“Health care facility” means a: (1) hospital; (2) federally qualified health center; (3) outpatient mental health clinic;\n(4) outpatient or residential addiction treatment provider; and (5) local health department. MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH-GEN. § 8-1101(a)(2) (West 2024).\nMaryland law directs the Maryland Department of Health to adopt a reporting system to monitor the prescribing of MOUD and conduct outreach to MOUD prescribers. MD. CODE ANN., HEALTH-GEN. § 8-1102 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (CRISP)", "url": "https://www.crisphealth.org/pdmp/", "description": "Maryland's PDMP is run through CRISP (Chesapeake Regional Information System for our Patients). Clinical users access PDMP data through the CRISP portal. The PDMP displays Morphine Milligram Equivalents (MME) for opioid dispenses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Homepage (Maryland Department of Health)", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pdmp/pages/home.aspx", "description": "Official Maryland PDMP page with program information, reporting requirements, and resources for prescribers and dispensers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://www.crisphealth.org/register/", "description": "Registration page for PDMP access through CRISP. Clinical users register for access to Maryland PDMP data exclusively through CRISP. Users must provide licensure information during registration."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Maryland requires prescribers to check the PDMP before prescribing opioids and benzodiazepines. Dispensers must report controlled dangerous substances (CDS) to CRISP. Non-CDS reporting required per COMAR 10.25.18.13 effective September 2025."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Maryland participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing through the CRISP platform."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: The CRISP PDMP system allows practitioners to designate delegates to access PDMP data. Registration and delegate management is handled through the CRISP portal at https://www.crisphealth.org/register/"}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pharmacy/pages/index.aspx", "description": "Maryland Board of Pharmacy, within the Maryland Department of Health. Protects consumers and promotes quality healthcare through licensing pharmacists, registering pharmacy technicians, and setting practice standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "About the Board", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pharmacy/Pages/about-the-board.aspx", "description": "Information about the Board's mission to protect Maryland consumers through effective regulation, legislation development, and public education. Phone: 410-764-4755."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Health Occupations Article, Title 12 (Pharmacy Practice Act)", "url": "https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gho&section=12-101&enactments=false", "description": "Maryland Health Occupations Article, Title 12 covering Pharmacists and Pharmacies. Includes definitions, licensure, authorized activities, therapy management contracts, and delegated pharmacy acts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Information", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pharmacy/Pages/pharmacists.aspx", "description": "Board page for pharmacists and pharmacy interns covering new licensure, renewal, reinstatement, vaccination authorization, and related correspondence."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Therapy Management Contracts: Under Title 12, Subtitle 6A of the Health Occupations Article, Maryland pharmacists may enter into therapy management contracts with prescribers. These are collaborative practice agreements that allow pharmacists to manage drug therapy within defined parameters."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Maryland pharmacists can dispense naloxone under the statewide standing order, administer vaccinations with authorization, and provide therapy management services under collaborative practice agreements. Check the Board website for current authorized activities."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Stop Overdose Website", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/", "description": "Maryland's Office of Overdose Response website with resources for overdose prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery. Includes information on opioid settlement funds and the overdose data dashboard."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov", "description": "SAMHSA national treatment locator filterable to Maryland for finding substance use disorder treatment facilities including those providing medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "Directory of practitioners authorized to treat OUD with buprenorphine, searchable by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA directory of State Opioid Treatment Authorities. Maryland's SOTA is within the Behavioral Health Administration of the Maryland Department of Health."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Behavioral Health Administration OUD Resources", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/bha/Pages/Overdose-Data-.aspx", "description": "BHA overdose data page with links to the Overdose Data Dashboard, emerging drug trends, and treatment reports."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine: Maryland follows federal telehealth regulations for buprenorphine prescribing. See https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html for current DEA guidance on telemedicine prescribing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/mmcp/pap/pages/Preferred-Drug-List.aspx", "description": "Maryland Medicaid PDL page with current preferred and non-preferred drug listings, including OUD treatment medications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Medicaid Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://www.mmppi.com/", "description": "Maryland Medicaid Pharmacy Program Information website with resources for providers, including formulary information, billing guidance, and prior authorization procedures."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Medicaid Program", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/mmcp", "description": "Maryland Medical Care Programs (Medicaid) main page. Maryland Medicaid operates through HealthChoice managed care organizations."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Funding: Maryland receives federal State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding and opioid settlement funds. The Behavioral Health Administration administers these programs. Information at https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Restitution Fund", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/", "description": "Visit the Stop Overdose website to learn how Maryland is using prescription opioid settlement funds across the state for prevention, treatment, and recovery services."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/regs/Pages/10-34-18-Continuing-Education-for-Pharmacists-(BOARD-OF-PHARMACY)----.aspx", "description": "COMAR 10.34.18 CE requirements. Maryland pharmacists must earn 30 hours of approved CE within each 2-year renewal period, including 1 hour on preventing medication errors, 2 hours live, and a minimum of 3 hours related to opioids."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice CE: Pharmacists engaged in collaborative drug therapy management must complete 10 hours in each disease state of the collaborative practice agreement every two years."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://marylandpharmacist.org/", "description": "MPhA provides continuing education, networking, and professional development opportunities for Maryland pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "All DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorder treatment per the MATE Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System offers free training satisfying DEA MATE Act requirements for opioid use disorder education."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Office of Harm Reduction", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pha/NALOXONE/Pages/accessharmreduction.aspx", "description": "Office of Harm Reduction (OHR) within the BHA Prevention and Promotion Division. Oversees the Overdose Response Program, Syringe Services Program, naloxone distribution, harm reduction grants, and workforce development."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statewide Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pha/NALOXONE/Pages/Statewide-Standing-Order.aspx", "description": "The statewide standing order issued by the Maryland Department of Health allows all Maryland licensed pharmacists to dispense naloxone, including necessary administration supplies, to any individual."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order Document", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pha/NALOXONE/Documents/Pharmacy-Naloxone-Standing-Order-and-Guidance.pdf", "description": "Current standing order document for pharmacy naloxone dispensing in Maryland, issued August 28, 2025."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Resources", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/harm-reduction/", "description": "Maryland's Office of Overdose Response harm reduction page with information on naloxone, fentanyl test strips, syringe services, and overdose prevention education."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strips: Fentanyl test strips are legal in Maryland and can be used to check for the presence of fentanyl in drugs. Available through harm reduction programs and the Office of Harm Reduction. Information at https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/harm-reduction/"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Overdose Data", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pha/NALOXONE/Pages/ORP-program-Reports.aspx", "description": "Maryland overdose data page with links to the Maryland Overdose Data Dashboard, which combines data on fatal overdoses, non-fatal emergency department visits, and EMS naloxone administrations."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Certified Peer Recovery Specialist (CPRS)", "url": "https://www.mabpcb.com/certified-peer-recovery-specialist-cprs", "description": "Maryland Addiction and Behavioral-health Professionals Certification Board page on CPRS certification. Validates individuals in long-term recovery who have completed formal training in peer support."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CPRS Requirements Guide", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/bha/documents/cprs%20requirements%20guide_comms_030518.pdf", "description": "Maryland BHA guide to the Certified Peer Recovery Specialist certification process and requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Certification of Recovery Residences (MCORR)", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/bha/Pages/Maryland-Certification-of-Recovery-Residence-License-.aspx", "description": "BHA office providing statewide certification of recovery residences. Certified residences provide substance-free, peer-supportive living environments."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Certified Recovery Residence Directory", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/bha/documents/certified%20rr.pdf", "description": "PDF listing of certified recovery residences in Maryland with owner names and contact information."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maryland 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline: Call or text 988 to connect with someone who can help with substance use or mental health crises. Learn more at https://988.maryland.gov/"}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maryland Crisis Hotline: Call 211 for non-emergency behavioral health resources and referrals."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pharmacy/pages/index.aspx", "description": "Phone: 410-764-4755. Part of the Maryland Department of Health."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Medicaid", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/mmcp", "description": "Maryland Medical Care Programs (Medicaid). Contact for pharmacy benefit and coverage questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "Maryland's SOTA is within the Behavioral Health Administration. Contact through SAMHSA's SOTA directory."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Pharmacists Association (MPhA)", "url": "https://marylandpharmacist.org/", "description": "Professional society representing all practicing pharmacists in Maryland since 1882. Provides advocacy, continuing education, and legislative representation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Office of Overdose Response", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/", "description": "State office coordinating Maryland's comprehensive overdose response across prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/bha/Pages/Overdose-Data-.aspx", "description": "BHA overdose data page with links to the interactive Overdose Data Dashboard, emerging drug trends, and reports. Dashboard combines data on fatal overdoses, non-fatal ED visits, and EMS naloxone administrations by jurisdiction and zip code."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Overdose Data Reports", "url": "https://health.maryland.gov/pha/NALOXONE/Pages/ORP-program-Reports.aspx", "description": "Overdose Response Program reports and data, including CDC Behavioral Risk Factor data and the publicly available Overdose Data Dashboard."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Stop Overdose Data", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/", "description": "Office of Overdose Response website with the most recent data on overdose trends, opioid settlement fund allocation, and program outcomes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CRISP PDMP Data", "url": "https://www.crisphealth.org/pdmp/", "description": "CRISP provides PDMP data analytics including opioid prescribing trends and MME calculations for clinical use."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Maryland Opioid Operational Command Center: The Governor established the Opioid Operational Command Center to coordinate the state's response. Current activities are managed through the Office of Overdose Response at https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/"}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Maryland General Assembly Bill Search", "url": "https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/", "description": "Maryland General Assembly website with legislative search tools, bill tracking, and session information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find My Representatives", "url": "https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Members/District", "description": "Interactive tool to find your Maryland state delegate and senator by district or address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://marylandpharmacist.org/", "description": "MPhA advocates for all Maryland pharmacists through legislative representation and regulatory engagement. Mission is to strengthen the profession and promote excellence in pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Maryland Office of Overdose Response", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/", "description": "Coordinates Maryland's statewide overdose response efforts including prevention, harm reduction, treatment, recovery, and data surveillance. Manages opioid settlement fund distribution."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Restitution Fund Advisory Council", "url": "https://stopoverdose.maryland.gov/", "description": "Visit the Stop Overdose website for information on how Maryland's Opioid Restitution Fund Advisory Council allocates opioid settlement funds across the state for evidence-based programs."}]}]}, "massachusetts": {"name": "Massachusetts", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nMassachusetts pharmacy laws and regulations do not clearly define the “practice of pharmacy.”\nHowever, in the Massachusetts regulation governing controlled substance registration requirements, the only reference to a pharmacist prescribing drugs or medications is to “prescribe and dispense hormonal contraceptive patches and self-administered oral hormonal contraceptives.” MASS. CODE REGS. 700.004(B)(15) (2024).\nMoreover, according to a scope of practice policy issued by the Massachusetts Board of Registration in Pharmacy (Board), “in order for a pharmacist to . . . prescribe medications, a CDTM [collaborative drug therapy management] agreement with a physician is required.”\nDEA information last updated in November 2024 indicates that registered pharmacists in Massachusetts can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration, but subject to the limitations of “Prescribe only[,] Institutional pharmacist only, [and] No Retail.” However, as described above and in the response to the \"prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, this authority applies only to pharmacists acting under CDTM agreements, called CPAs in regulation, even though that limitation is not specified by DEA.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Massachusetts to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Massachusetts pharmacists not operating under CDTMAs to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nMassachusetts regulation expressly authorizes a pharmacist “to dispense by administration FDA approved mental health or substance use disorder treatment drugs to persons 18 years of age or older.” MASS. CODE REGS. 700.004(B)(9) (2024).\nHowever, this activity must be conducted in accordance with guidelines adopted by the Massachusetts Department of Public Health (Department), “which shall include, but not be limited to, requirements for . . . specific drugs permitted to be administered.” MASS. CODE REGS. 700.004(B)(9)(d)(1) (2024).\nAccording to a circular letter issued by the Department in April 2023, the only drug or medication for SUD that a pharmacist can administer currently is naltrexone.", "2B": null, "2C": "Revise Massachusetts regulations to allow for pharmacist administration of buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nMassachusetts pharmacy laws and regulations do not clearly define the “practice of pharmacy.”\nAccording to a scope of practice policy issued by the Board, a pharmacist can “administer, process, read, and report the results” of two types of tests, but in neither case may the pharmacist interpret test results. The two types of tests are Health Promotion Screening tests and COVID-19 tests. Otherwise, the Board policy notes that “in order for a pharmacist to order drug-related laboratory tests . . . a CDTM agreement with a physician is required.”", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Massachusetts to include ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Based on the information described below, the answer is “no” if the CDTM practice setting is within a community/retail pharmacy, but “yes” if the practice setting is within one of the other allowed types.\nMassachusetts law provides that CDTM is “the initiating, monitoring, modifying and discontinuing of a patient's drug therapy by a pharmacist in accordance with a [CPA].” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(a) (West 2024).\nMassachusetts laws and regulations authorize CDTM in five types of settings: (1) hospitals; (2) long-term care facilities; (3) inpatient or outpatient hospice settings; (4) ambulatory care clinics; and (5) community/retail pharmacies. MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(c) (West 2024); 247 MASS. CODE REGS. 16.03 (2024).\nIn general, a CPA can grant prescriptive authority to a pharmacist that includes prescribing controlled substances. Massachusetts regulation provides that if a CPA grants prescriptive authority, the pharmacist must “maintain a current controlled substance registration issued by the Department during the term of the agreement.” MASS. CODE REGS. 16.02(1)(f) (2024). However, “no [CPA] in the retail drug business setting may permit the prescribing of schedule II through V controlled substances.” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(c) (West 2024); 247 MASS. CODE REGS.\n16.03(5)(e)(3) (2024). Along with prohibiting pharmacists from prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA in a community pharmacy setting, the implication of this provision is that pharmacists can prescribe buprenorphine under a CPA in the other allowed CDTM settings.", "4B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": "Revise Massachusetts laws and/or regulations governing CPAs to allow pharmacists to prescribe schedule II to V controlled substances in community pharmacies.\nExpressly specify in Massachusetts laws or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow all Massachusetts pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Based on the information described below, the answer is “no” if the CDTM practice setting is within a community/retail pharmacy, and “unclear” if the practice setting is within one of the other allowed types.\nMassachusetts law provides that CDTM is “the initiating, monitoring, modifying and discontinuing of a patient’s drug therapy by a pharmacist in accordance with a [CPA].” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(a) (West 2024).\nAlthough this provision uses the phrase “initiating, monitoring, [and] modifying,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications. However, the phrase could be interpreted to include administration of drugs and medications generally.\nMassachusetts laws and regulations authorize CDTM in five types of settings: (1) hospitals; (2) long-term care facilities; (3) inpatient or outpatient hospice settings; (4) ambulatory care clinics; and (5) community/retail pharmacies. MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(c) (West 2024); 247 MASS. CODE REGS. 16.03 (2024). Massachusetts laws and regulations governing CPAs place more restrictions on CPAs in community/retail pharmacies than in the other allowed settings. A pharmacist operating under a CPA in a community/retail pharmacy may administer vaccines, but can only “initiate, modify, or discontinue dosages of medications prescribed by the supervising physician” for eight identified conditions, none of which is SUD. MASS. CODE REGS. 16.03(e)(1)(b) (2024). This provision appears to prevent community pharmacists from administering buprenorphine under a CPA.\nMassachusetts laws and regulations governing CPAs do not expressly address administering drugs or medications under a CPA in the four other types of practice settings besides a community/retail pharmacy.\nThe scope of practice policy issued by the Board expressly notes that a pharmacist can administer vaccines as part of CDTM but does not indicate if CDTM can involve administration of any other type of drug or medication beyond that allowed outside of a CPA.150", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Revise Massachusetts laws and/or regulations governing CPAs to allow SUD to be treated in a community pharmacy setting.\nExpressly specify in Massachusetts laws or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a CPA.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMassachusetts law expressly provides that CDTM performed pursuant to a CPA may include “ordering and evaluating the results of laboratory tests directly related to drug therapy.” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(a) (West 2024).\nThe actions must be performed “under the supervision of, or in direct consultation with, a physician,” in accordance with approved protocols applicable to the practice setting, and “the evaluation shall not include a diagnostic component.” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(a) (West 2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "A CPA is a written and signed agreement between a pharmacist with training and experience relevant to the scope of the collaborative practice and a “supervising physician.” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(a) (West 2024).\nMassachusetts laws and regulations authorize CDTM under CPAs in five types of settings: (1) hospitals; (2) long-term care facilities; (3) inpatient or outpatient hospice settings; (4) ambulatory care clinics; and (5) community/retail pharmacies. MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½(c) (West 2024); 247 MASS. CODE REGS.\n16.03 (2024).\nA CPA must specify those duties of the authorized pharmacist that may be delegated to other trained and authorized staff and those duties under a CPA that cannot be delegated. MASS. CODE REGS. 16.04(3) (2024).\nThe following Massachusetts laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 24B ½, 24B ¾ (West 2024); 243 MASS. CODE REGS. 2.12 (2024); 247 MASS. CODE REGS. 16.01 to 16.05 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMassachusetts does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act. However, the telehealth provision for physicians requires the state board of medicine to “allow a physician licensed by the board to obtain proxy credentialing and privileging for telehealth services with other health care providers, as defined in section 1 of chapter 111.” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 5O(b) (West 2024). The referenced definition of health care providers expressly includes pharmacists. MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.111, § 1 (West 2024).\nMoreover, Massachusetts insurance laws and Medicaid program laws, require coverage for health care services delivered by telehealth by a “health care provider.” MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.118E, § 79 (West 2024); MASS. GEN.\nLAWS ANN. ch.175, § 47MM (West 2024). The health care insurance provisions do not define “health care provider,” but as noted above, public health law does define the term to include pharmacists.\nThe definition of “telehealth” expressly includes services for a patient’s mental health or SUD condition. MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.118E, § 79(a) (West 2024); MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.175, § 47MM(a) (West 2024).\nThe scope of pharmacist practice policy issued by the Board, however, notes that “in Massachusetts, the scope of telepharmacy is limited to remote pharmacist clinical activities and verification of final patient-specific products.”", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Massachusetts laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Massachusetts laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.112, § 5O) (West 2024) (physicians); MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.118E, § 79 (West 2024) (Medicaid); MASS. GEN. LAWS ANN. ch.175, § 47MM (West 2024) (health insurance generally).", "9A": "Certain medication therapy management services provided by clinical pharmacists in community health centers.\nVaccine administration.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Massachusetts Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Massachusetts laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CPA are covered under the Massachusetts Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Massachusetts SUD treatment provider regulations define both “office-based addiction treatment” (OBAT) and “office-based opioid treatment” (OBOT). MASS. CODE REGS. 164.005 (2024).\nOBAT is “a type of outpatient service not subject to 105 CMR 164.000 providing medication for addiction that is provided outside of licensed or approved SUD treatment programs by appropriately licensed clinicians to patients with addiction. Includes, but is not limited to, MAT in a primary care office, MAT in a hospital clinic setting, and office based opioid treatment serving under 300 patients.” MASS. CODE REGS. 164.005 (2024).\nOBOT is “a type of [OBAT] provided by a corporate entity, other than a hospital or clinic licensed under M.G.L. c. 111, § 51, or an opioid treatment program licensed under M.G.L. c. 111E, doing business in the Commonwealth, which has more than 300 patients . . . in a health care professional's office setting or in a primary care center, and is associated with the corporate entity by contract, fee for service, or other arrangement other than as members of the practice.” MASS. CODE REGS. 164.005 (2024).\nMassachusetts regulation provides that “provisions of 105 CMR 164.250 through 164.260 in addition to provisions of 105 CMR 164.000: Part One and 105 CMR 164.201 through 105 CMR 164.205, apply to all licensed or approved for Office-based Opioid Treatment.” MASS. CODE REGS. 164.250 (2024). 105 MASS. CODE REGS. 164.251 to 164.260 address, among other things, admission, patient assessment, drug screening, and diversion control."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (MassPAT)", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/guides/massachusetts-prescription-awareness-tool-masspat", "description": "Massachusetts Prescription Awareness Tool (MassPAT) is the state's online PDMP system. Prescribers and pharmacists use MassPAT to check patient prescription histories for Schedule II through V controlled substances. Login at https://massachusetts.pmpaware.net/login."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/guides/register-for-massachusetts-prescription-awareness-tool-masspat", "description": "Registration page for prescribers, pharmacists, and delegates to create a MassPAT account. Pharmacists need a professional email, license number, and DEA number. Registration takes approximately 5-10 minutes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://malegislature.gov/Laws/GeneralLaws/PartI/TitleXV/Chapter94C/Section24A", "description": "Massachusetts General Laws Ch. 94C, Sec. 24A requires practitioners to query MassPAT each time they issue a prescription for any narcotic drug in Schedule II or III or a benzodiazepine. This is mandatory for prescribers. Pharmacists are encouraged but not mandated to check."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/interstate-prescription-data-sharing", "description": "Massachusetts participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate prescription data sharing. This page details which states share data with Massachusetts and access limitations by practitioner type. Note: This page may require direct browser access. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/guides/register-for-massachusetts-prescription-awareness-tool-masspat", "description": "Delegates authorized by a prescriber or pharmacist can register for MassPAT. Delegates need the email address of the MassPAT account of the authorizing prescriber or pharmacist, their employer name and address, and a professional email. All delegates must create their own account."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/orgs/board-of-registration-in-pharmacy", "description": "The Massachusetts Board of Registration in Pharmacy promotes, preserves, and protects public health through regulation of pharmacy practice, pharmacy operations, and prescription drug distribution. Phone: (617) 973-0960. Email: pharmacy.admin@mass.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://malegislature.gov/Laws/GeneralLaws/PartI/TitleXVI/Chapter112", "description": "Massachusetts General Laws Chapter 112 contains the pharmacy practice provisions. Sections 24 to 42A specifically govern the practice of pharmacy, pharmacist licensure, and pharmacy operations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/law-library/247-cmr", "description": "247 CMR contains the Board of Registration in Pharmacy regulations, including definitions, code of professional conduct, professional standards for pharmacists and pharmacies, and operational requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute", "url": "https://malegislature.gov/laws/generallaws/parti/titlexvi/chapter112/section24b1~2", "description": "M.G.L. Chapter 112, Section 24B1/2 authorizes pharmacist collaborative practice agreements and collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM). Agreements must include individually developed prescriptive practice guidelines and are subject to biennial review and renewal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Drug Therapy Management Regulation", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/doc/247-cmr-16-collaborative-drug-therapy-management/download", "description": "247 CMR 16 provides detailed regulations for collaborative drug therapy management, including pharmacist qualifications, practice setting requirements, and required agreement terms. Massachusetts does not have independent pharmacist prescribing authority outside of CDTM agreements."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator (Massachusetts)", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to find buprenorphine treatment providers and opioid treatment programs in Massachusetts. Replaces the previous buprenorphine practitioner locator following elimination of the X-waiver requirement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Can be filtered by state, city, or zip code for Massachusetts providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/information-on-opioid-treatment-services", "description": "Massachusetts State Opioid Treatment Authority is Jen Babich (Jennifer.Babich@mass.gov), housed within the Bureau of Substance Addiction Services (BSAS). This page provides information on opioid treatment services and licensing requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Bureau of Substance Addiction Services (BSAS)", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/orgs/bureau-of-substance-addiction-services", "description": "BSAS oversees the statewide system of prevention, intervention, treatment, and recovery support services for substance addiction. Contact: questions.bsas@state.ma.us."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Regulations", "url": "https://www.cchpca.org/massachusetts/", "description": "The Center for Connected Health Policy provides a comprehensive overview of Massachusetts telehealth laws, including those applicable to buprenorphine prescribing. Federal DEA and HHS final rules allow buprenorphine initiation via audio-only telehealth for up to a 6-month supply."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MassHealth Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/masshealth-pharmacy-program", "description": "Homepage for the MassHealth (Massachusetts Medicaid) Pharmacy Program. Contains information about drugs and services related to pharmacies, including prior authorization requirements and the MassHealth Drug List."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MassHealth Drug List and Prior Authorization", "url": "https://mhdl.pharmacy.services.conduent.com/MHDL/", "description": "The MassHealth Drug List (MHDL) provides the complete list of covered drugs, preferred drug designations, and links to prior authorization forms. Buprenorphine/naloxone (Suboxone) film is on the preferred drug list. Prior authorization is required for buprenorphine doses exceeding 32mg/day."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prior Authorization Forms for Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://mhdl.pharmacy.services.conduent.com/MHDL/pubpa.do", "description": "Searchable directory of MassHealth prior authorization forms for pharmacy services. Users can search by drug name or browse alphabetically to find the appropriate PA form."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MassHealth Pharmacy Contact and Fee Information", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/contact-information-for-pharmacy-services", "description": "Contact information for MassHealth Pharmacy Services. Drug Utilization Review Program: (800) 745-7318. Email: masshealthdruglist@state.ma.us. Fee schedule information is available through provider payment rates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants provide funding to states for OUD treatment, including increasing access to medications for opioid use disorder (MOUD). Massachusetts-specific funding may also be available through RIZE Massachusetts (https://mosaic.rizema.org/grantmaking/overview/) which awarded $3.75 million to 18 organizations through its CORE Grant program."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "State CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/doc/2021-04-continuing-education-ce-requirements-pdf/download", "description": "Massachusetts Board of Pharmacy CE policy document. Pharmacists must complete 20 hours of CE per biennial renewal period, including 2 hours on validation and counseling of prescriptions for controlled substances and opioids. Pharmacists with CDTM prescriptive authority must complete 1 hour biennially on pain management and opioid addiction risks."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board-Approved Training Programs", "url": "https://www.masspharmacists.org", "description": "The Massachusetts Pharmacists Association (MPhA) offers continuing education programs including immunization training and other pharmacy practice topics. Phone: 781-933-1107. Email: info@masspharmacists.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "Beginning June 27, 2023, all DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders, including opioid use disorder treatment, when renewing or obtaining initial DEA registration. This federal requirement applies to Massachusetts practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA MATE Act Resources", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/mate-act", "description": "SAMHSA's resource page for MATE Act training requirements. All licensed practitioners with DEA Schedule II-V authority can now prescribe buprenorphine where state law allows."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training, mentoring, and clinical guidance on evidence-based OUD treatment. Includes 8-hour DEA training options and buprenorphine-specific modules."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Program Locator", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/syringe-service-program-locator", "description": "Interactive locator for syringe service programs (SSPs) across Massachusetts, operated by the Department of Public Health. SSPs provide sterile needles, syringes, naloxone, and referrals to treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Service Programs Overview", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/syringe-service-programs", "description": "Overview of Massachusetts Department of Public Health supported syringe services programs, including program descriptions, locations, and how to access services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/getting-naloxone-from-a-pharmacy-or-store", "description": "The Massachusetts DPH has issued a statewide standing order allowing retail pharmacies to dispense naloxone without a prescription. All Massachusetts retail pharmacies must maintain a continuous, sufficient supply of naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution Programs", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/where-to-get-naloxone-in-massachusetts", "description": "Information on where to get naloxone in Massachusetts, including state-funded programs, the Community Naloxone Program (CNP), and a naloxone distribution program locator. Free naloxone kits are available by mail to Massachusetts residents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Community Naloxone Program", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/community-naloxone-program-cnp", "description": "The CNP allows eligible programs to obtain Narcan brand naloxone through the State Office of Pharmacy for free distribution to community bystanders. Goal is to prevent opioid overdose deaths statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://malegislature.gov/PressRoom/Detail?pressReleaseId=245", "description": "Massachusetts legalized the sale, possession, and distribution of fentanyl test strips in 2024. Legislation built upon protections established that year to remove barriers to drug testing equipment used to identify fentanyl and other synthetic opioids."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/lists/substance-use-and-overdose-data", "description": "Comprehensive listing of Massachusetts substance use and overdose data resources, including the BSAS Dashboard with city/town level data on substance-related deaths, emergency events, and substance use services."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Support Centers Directory", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/peer-recovery-support-centers", "description": "Directory of Peer Recovery Support Centers (PRSCs) across Massachusetts. PRSCs provide individuals in recovery from substance use disorder, as well as families and loved ones, an opportunity to offer and receive support."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Support Specialist Training", "url": "https://copelandcenter.com/peer-specialists/massachusetts", "description": "Information on becoming a Certified Peer Specialist (CPS) in Massachusetts. Training is provided by the Transformation Center (https://transformation-center.org/) and Kiva Centers. Training is free and requires lived experience with mental health recovery for at least 1 year."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://mashsoberhousing.org/certified-residences/", "description": "Massachusetts Alliance for Sober Housing (MASH) directory of certified sober homes. All MASH-certified sober homes follow National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) standards and have been independently inspected."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/orgs/bureau-of-substance-addiction-services", "description": "The Bureau of Substance Addiction Services (BSAS) within the Massachusetts Department of Public Health oversees prevention, intervention, treatment, and recovery support services for substance addiction statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health Help Line", "url": "https://www.masshelpline.com/", "description": "The Massachusetts Behavioral Health Help Line (BHHL) connects individuals and families to mental health and substance use treatment. Available 24/7, 365 days per year. Call or text 833-773-2445. Online chat also available."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/orgs/board-of-registration-in-pharmacy", "description": "Michael Godek, Executive Director, Massachusetts Board of Registration in Pharmacy. Address: 250 Washington Street, Boston, MA 02108. Phone: (617) 973-0960. Email: pharmacy.admin@mass.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MassHealth Pharmacy Director Contact", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/contact-information-for-pharmacy-services", "description": "MassHealth Pharmacy Services contact. Drug Utilization Review Program: (800) 745-7318. Email: masshealthdruglist@state.ma.us. Senior Pharmacy Director in the Office of Clinical Affairs: Kimberly Lenz."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/information-for-licensed-substance-use-disorder-treatment-programs", "description": "Jen Babich, State Opioid Treatment Authority. Email: Jennifer.Babich@mass.gov. Located within the Bureau of Substance Addiction Services (BSAS). General BSAS contact: questions.bsas@state.ma.us."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.masspharmacists.org", "description": "Massachusetts Pharmacists Association (MPhA). PO Box 374, Boxford, MA 01921. Phone: 781-933-1107. Fax: 781-933-1109. Email: info@masspharmacists.org. MPhA represents pharmacists in all practice settings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Health Department OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/massachusetts-responds-to-the-opioid-epidemic", "description": "Massachusetts Department of Public Health opioid response page. Provides links to naloxone information, overdose data, prescriber education, opioid settlement fund guidance, and DPH public information campaigns about opioids."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Death Dashboard", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/bureau-of-substance-addiction-services-bsas-dashboard", "description": "The BSAS Dashboard reports on substance-related deaths, emergency events, and substance use services at city/town, county, and state levels. Deaths data updated through December 31, 2024."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use and Overdose Data Reports", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/lists/substance-use-and-overdose-data", "description": "Comprehensive page listing all Massachusetts substance use and overdose data resources, including the BSAS Dashboard, Prescription Monitoring Program data, and historical overdose reports."}, {"type": "link", "title": "County-Level Opioid Data", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/bureau-of-substance-addiction-services-bsas-dashboard", "description": "The BSAS Dashboard provides city/town and county-level breakdowns of substance-related deaths and emergency events, allowing county-level analysis of the opioid crisis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system", "description": "Massachusetts participates in the CDC-funded OD2A project (Overdose Data to Action), providing detailed circumstances data on overdose deaths. Massachusetts was one of the first 12 states funded for enhanced opioid overdose surveillance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Monitoring Program Data", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/info-details/prescription-monitoring-program-data-in-massachusetts", "description": "Dashboard sharing selected data collected from pharmacies in Massachusetts, including opioid agonists, benzodiazepines, stimulants, and opioid partial agonists prescription data."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Current State Legislation Search", "url": "https://malegislature.gov/bills/search", "description": "Search tool for current Massachusetts legislation. Search for bills related to pharmacist prescribing, OUD treatment, buprenorphine, or other pharmacy topics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Massachusetts Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.masspharmacists.org/content.aspx?page_id=22&club_id=131603&module_id=472259", "description": "MPhA advocacy page where pharmacists can track pending legislation, identify state representatives, and send crafted messages about important pharmacy bills. MPhA has supported bills like S1425 allowing pharmacists to test and treat for certain conditions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Massachusetts Legislator", "url": "https://malegislature.gov/Search/FindMyLegislator", "description": "Official Massachusetts legislature tool to find your state senator and representative by address. Enables direct contact with legislators on pharmacy and OUD-related policy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Pharmacist Prescribing Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/resource/pharmacist-prescribing/", "description": "The National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy resources for pharmacist prescribing authority. Relevant to Massachusetts efforts to expand pharmacist scope of practice. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Massachusetts Opioid Response and Settlement Fund", "url": "https://www.mass.gov/massachusetts-responds-to-the-opioid-epidemic", "description": "Massachusetts maintains an Opioid Recovery and Remediation Fund Advisory Council and provides guidance for municipalities on utilizing opioid settlement abatement payments. Multiple coalitions and task forces operate across the state, including the Opioid Task Force of Franklin County and the North Quabbin Region."}]}]}, "michigan": {"name": "Michigan", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Michigan pharmacy law does not expressly address collaborative practice or drug therapy management. As a result, the law neither uses the phrase CPA nor clearly uses any other phrase in its place. Based on online sources, it may be that something akin to a written “delegation agreement” between a physician and a pharmacist acts as a CPA.", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Michigan law identifies certain “professional functions” associated with it. These professional functions do not expressly include prescribing any drugs or medications. MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.17707(8) (West 2024).\nThe definition expressly references “ordering,” but only with respect to “qualified immunizing agents” and “qualified laboratory tests.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.17707(8) (West 2024).\nIn addition, the definition of “prescriber” in Michigan pharmacy law does not include a pharmacist. MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.177078(2) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Michigan cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.156", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Michigan practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Michigan pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Michigan law identifies certain “professional functions” associated with it. These professional functions do not include administering drugs and medications other than “ordering and administering qualified immunizing agents in accordance with section 17724.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.17707(8) (West 2024).\nMoreover, although not contained within the practice of pharmacy definition, additional Michigan pharmacy laws related to administering drugs or medications relate only to administering epinephrine and overdose reversal agents.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Michigan practice of pharmacy to include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Michigan law identifies certain “professional functions” associated with it. These professional functions expressly include “ordering and administering qualified laboratory tests in accordance with section 17724a.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.17707(8)(g) (West 2024).\nThe lab tests that Michigan law authorizes pharmacist “ordering and administering” are: (1) CLIA-waived tests;\n(2) tests where the specimen is collected via nasal swab or finger prick; and (3) tests to detect COVID-19, influenza, or a respiratory infection. MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.17724a (West 2024).\nMichigan law does not expressly refer to evaluating any types of lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Michigan practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nMichigan pharmacy law does not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Michigan pursuant to the authority Michigan gives to licensed healthcare providers to delegate healthcare acts or tasks.\nMichigan health occupation law provides that “a licensee who holds a license other than a health profession subfield license may delegate to a licensed or unlicensed individual who is otherwise qualified by education, training, or experience the performance of selected acts, tasks, or functions where the acts, tasks, or functions fall within the scope of practice of the licensee’s profession and will be performed under the licensee’s supervision.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024).\nHowever, the healthcare provider cannot delegate an act that “requires the level of education, skill, and judgment required of the [delegating] licensee.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024). This language seems quite limiting in what can be delegated. In September 2022, the Michigan Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs (LARA) issued an “interpretive statement” entitled “Delegation of Prescriptive Authority to Pharmacists,” which was specific to delegating prescriptive authority for certain contraceptives. LARA concluded that a physician may delegate such prescriptive authority to a pharmacist but limited its conclusion such that “only the authority to prescribe self-administered, hormonal contraceptives may be delegated.” LARA’s analysis suggests that a pharmacist cannot prescribe any other type of drug or medication in the absence of specific LARA interpretive statement or an express provision in law.\nMoreover, Michigan pharmacy laws do not account for the fact that a Michigan pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what a healthcare provider delegates.\nIn summary, Michigan law does not address collaborative practice and does not clearly address the scope of health care provider delegation to pharmacists. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Michigan pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Michigan laws and/or regulations to expressly address collaborative pharmacy practice.\nRevise Michigan laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances pursuant to physician delegation. Expressly specify in Michigan law or regulation how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under physician delegation.\nAllow Michigan pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Michigan laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nMichigan pharmacy law does not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Michigan pursuant to the authority Michigan gives to licensed healthcare providers to delegate healthcare acts or tasks.\nMichigan health occupation law provides that “a licensee who holds a license other than a health profession subfield license may delegate to a licensed or unlicensed individual who is otherwise qualified by education, training, or experience the performance of selected acts, tasks, or functions where the acts, tasks, or functions fall within the scope of practice of the licensee’s profession and will be performed under the licensee’s supervision.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024). This provision could mean that a healthcare provider could delegate the authority to administer buprenorphine to a pharmacist.\nHowever, the healthcare provider cannot delegate an act that “requires the level of education, skill, and judgment required of the [delegating] licensee.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024). This provision seems quite limiting to what can be delegated and may prohibit delegating the ability to administer buprenorphine.\nAs described in the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, a pharmacist does not have the general authority to administer buprenorphine.", "5B": null, "5C": "Revise Michigan laws and/or regulations to expressly address collaborative pharmacy practice.\nExpressly specify, either in new Michigan laws and/or regulations about collaborative practice or current law governing delegation, what duties can be delegated to a pharmacist and that those duties include administering controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Michigan laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nMichigan pharmacy law does not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Michigan pursuant to the authority Michigan gives to licensed healthcare providers to delegate healthcare acts or tasks.\nMichigan health occupation law provides that “a licensee who holds a license other than a health profession subfield license may delegate to a licensed or unlicensed individual who is otherwise qualified by education, training, or experience the performance of selected acts, tasks, or functions where the acts, tasks, or functions fall within the scope of practice of the licensee’s profession and will be performed under the licensee’s supervision.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024). This provision could mean that a healthcare provider could delegate the authority to order and evaluation lab tests of any kind. However, the healthcare provider cannot delegate an act that “requires the level of education, skill, and judgment required of the [delegating] licensee.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024). This provision seems quite limiting to what can be delegated and may prohibit delegating the ability to order and evaluate lab tests outside of a pharmacist’s general practice.\nIn summary, Michigan law does not address collaborative practice and does not clearly address the scope of health care provider delegation to pharmacists and whether it can include ordering or administering lab tests. However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has limited authority to order lab tests in general, the most logical answer is that the same limited authority applies pursuant to healthcare provider delegation.", "6B": null, "6C": "Revise Michigan laws and/or regulations to expressly address collaborative pharmacy practice.\nExpressly specify, either in new Michigan laws and/or regulations about collaborative practice or current law governing delegation, what duties can be delegated to a pharmacist and that those duties ordering evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Michigan pharmacy law does not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Michigan pursuant to the authority Michigan gives to licensed healthcare providers to delegate healthcare acts or tasks.\nMichigan health occupation law provides that “a licensee who holds a license other than a health profession subfield license may delegate to a licensed or unlicensed individual who is otherwise qualified by education, training, or experience the performance of selected acts, tasks, or functions where the acts, tasks, or functions fall within the scope of practice of the licensee’s profession and will be performed under the licensee’s supervision.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16215(1) (West 2024).\nThere is little information in Michigan law about healthcare provider delegations. What information exists is located at MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. §§ 333.16215(1) and 333.17708(2) (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nUnder Michigan’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law, a “health professional” can provide telehealth, so long as the professional acts within the applicable scope of practice. MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. §§ 333.16283 to 333.16288 (West 2024).\nA “health professional” is “an individual who is engaging in the practice of a health profession.” MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16283(a) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "There is no prohibition on prescribing controlled substances if the prescriber acts within the scope of practice and adheres to all telehealth laws and regulations. MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 333.16285 (West 2024).\nMichigan laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. §§ 333.16283 to 333.16288 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 400.105h (West 2024) (Medicaid); MICH. COMP. LAWS ANN. § 500.3476 (West 2024) (insurance); MICH. ADMIN. CODE r. 338.2407 (2024)\n(physicians).", "9A": "Pharmacists can be reimbursed for certain services provided as part of medication therapy management services.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Michigan Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Michigan laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under delegation from a healthcare provider are covered under the Michigan Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No. Michigan regulators rescinded a regulation entitled “Individual with substance use disorder; prescribing, dispensing, and administering controlled substance” effective May 28, 2024 (formerly MICH. ADMIN. CODE. r. 338.3163) that was tangentially relevant to the question."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (MAPS)", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/maps", "description": "Michigan Automated Prescription System (MAPS) is the state's PDMP. MAPS tracks Schedule 2-5 controlled substance prescriptions dispensed in or into Michigan. It is used by prescribers and dispensers to assess patient risk. Contact: BPL-MAPS@Michigan.gov, Phone: (517) 241-0166."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MAPS Login and Registration", "url": "https://michigan.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "MAPS login portal powered by PMP AWARxE (Bamboo Health). Click \"Create an Account\" to register. Support: (844) 364-4767."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MAPS User Registration Guide", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/-/media/Project/Websites/lara/bpl/Folder14/2a-Michigan_PMP_AWARxE_Registration_Support_Manual.pdf", "description": "Detailed registration support manual for MAPS users. Covers prescriber, pharmacist, and delegate registration processes. Every individual must register as a separate user using their email address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/maps", "description": "Michigan law requires prescribers to check MAPS prior to prescribing or dispensing a controlled substance in a quantity that exceeds a 3-day supply. Pharmacists are also authorized to query MAPS."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing (PMP InterConnect)", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/maps", "description": "Michigan participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing. Users can access prescription data from participating states through the MAPS portal. Details available on the MAPS main page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/-/media/Project/Websites/lara/bpl/Folder14/2a-Michigan_PMP_AWARxE_Registration_Support_Manual.pdf", "description": "Prescribers and pharmacists can designate delegates to access MAPS on their behalf. Delegates must create their own accounts in PMP AWARxE. The registration manual provides step-by-step instructions."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/hp-lic-health-prof/pharmacy", "description": "Michigan Board of Pharmacy website within the Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs (LARA), Bureau of Professional Licensing. Phone: (517) 373-8068. Email: BPL-BoardSupport@michigan.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/michigan/chapter-333/statute-act-368-of-1978/article-15/division-368-1978-15-177/", "description": "Michigan Public Health Code, Act 368 of 1978, Part 177 - Pharmacy Practice and Drug Control (MCL 333.17701 through 333.17780). Contains the full text of pharmacy practice statutes including definitions, licensing, scope of practice, and drug control provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://ars.apps.lara.state.mi.us/AdminCode/DeptBureauAdminCode?Department=Licensing+and+Regulatory+Affairs&Bureau=Bureau+of+Professional+Licensing", "description": "Michigan Administrative Rules for the Bureau of Professional Licensing, which includes pharmacy rules governing controlled substances (R 338.3101 through R 338.3199q), continuing education, and professional standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegation of Prescriptive Authority to Pharmacists", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/delegation-of-prescriptive-authority-to-pharmacists", "description": "LARA interpretive statement on delegation of prescriptive authority to pharmacists. Michigan law allows physicians to delegate authority to pharmacists to prescribe certain medications (e.g., hormonal contraceptives) through delegation agreements. However, CPAs explicitly prohibit delegating authority to prescribe controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/hp-lic-health-prof/pharmacy", "description": "Michigan does not have independent pharmacist prescribing authority. Pharmacist prescribing is limited to delegation agreements under the Public Health Code. Controlled substance prescribing cannot be delegated to pharmacists."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Opioid Resources - Find Help", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/opioids/find-help", "description": "MDHHS opioid resources page with information on medications for opioid use disorder (MOUD), treatment locators, naloxone access, and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to find buprenorphine treatment providers and opioid treatment programs in Michigan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Can be filtered by state, city, or zip code for Michigan providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/drugcontrol", "description": "The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (MDHHS) Drug Control section oversees opioid treatment services and the State Opioid Treatment Authority. Contact MDHHS for specific OTA information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Regulations", "url": "https://www.cchpca.org/michigan/", "description": "The Center for Connected Health Policy provides a comprehensive overview of Michigan telehealth laws. Michigan Medicaid reimburses for all four telehealth modalities (live video, store-and-forward, remote patient monitoring, and audio-only). Federal DEA rules allow buprenorphine initiation via telehealth. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Medicaid Pharmacy Benefit", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/assistance-programs/medicaid/portalhome/beneficiaries/resources/medicaid-health-plan-pharmacy-benefit", "description": "Member and provider access to information on drugs and supplies covered by Michigan Medicaid Health Plans, including pharmacy benefit details and formulary information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://mi.primetherapeutics.com/provider/external/medicaid/mi/doc/en-us/MIRx_PDL.pdf", "description": "Michigan Single Preferred Drug List (PDL) effective 01/01/2026. Contains the list of preferred medications including buprenorphine products covered under Michigan Medicaid."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MassHealth Pharmacy Prior Authorization", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/assistance-programs/medicaid/portalhome/beneficiaries/resources/medicaid-health-plan-pharmacy-benefit", "description": "Prior authorization requirements for Michigan Medicaid pharmacy benefits are available through the Medicaid Health Plan pharmacy benefit page and individual health plan formularies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Medicaid Fee Information", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/assistance-programs/medicaid", "description": "Michigan Medicaid (MDHHS) main page with links to provider information, fee schedules, and billing resources. Pharmacist-specific service billing codes and fee schedules may vary by Medicaid health plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants provide funding to states including Michigan for OUD treatment expansion, including increasing access to MOUD. Michigan MDHHS administers SOR funding through Prepaid Inpatient Health Plans (PIHPs)."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "State CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.michiganpharmacists.org/ce-requirements", "description": "Michigan pharmacists must complete 30 hours of continuing education per biennial renewal period. A one-time training in opioids and controlled substances awareness is required for pharmacists with a controlled substance license (Administrative Rule R 338.3135)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Controlled Substance Awareness Training", "url": "https://www.michiganpharmacists.org/education-controlled-substance-awareness-pharmacists", "description": "Michigan Pharmacists Association offers the required one-time controlled substance awareness training for pharmacists. This satisfies the LARA requirement for controlled substance license holders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.michiganpharmacists.org/", "description": "Michigan Pharmacists Association (MPA) offers continuing education programs, practice resources, and advocacy support. Phone: 517-484-1466."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "All DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders when renewing or obtaining initial DEA registration. This applies to Michigan practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free buprenorphine training, mentoring, and clinical guidance including 8-hour DEA training options."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Program Directory", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/drugcontrol/syringe-service-programs", "description": "MDHHS page on Harm Reduction and Syringe Service Programs in Michigan. Includes program information, registration requirements, and links to the statewide SSP directory."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SSP Directory PDF", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/-/media/Project/Websites/mdhhs/SSP/SSP-Directory_new---9-29-25.pdf", "description": "Downloadable PDF directory of syringe service programs across Michigan with locations, hours, phone numbers, and websites for each program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/drugcontrol/naloxoneform/naloxone-standing-order-for-pharmacist-use-only", "description": "Michigan's statewide naloxone standing order issued by the Chief Medical Executive. Allows pharmacists to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription to anyone at risk of an opioid overdose or in a position to help someone at risk."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Information", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/opioids/find-help/naloxone-page", "description": "Comprehensive naloxone information page including the standing order, how to obtain naloxone from pharmacies, free naloxone programs, and training resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strips", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/drugcontrol/syringe-service-programs/resources/resources", "description": "Michigan MDHHS provides information on fentanyl testing strips as a harm reduction tool. As of 2024, legislation was introduced (HB 5178) to explicitly exempt drug testing equipment from paraphernalia laws. Fentanyl test strips are available through syringe service programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/safety-injury-prev/injuryprevention/moda", "description": "Michigan Overdose Data to Action (MODA) program page with links to the MODA dashboard displaying the most recent overdose data at state, county, and zip code levels, including trends, disparities, and harm reduction service utilization."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Information", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/drugcontrol/peer-recovery-information", "description": "MDHHS peer recovery information page with resources on peer recovery support services, certified peer support specialists, and links to recovery services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Services and Supports", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/0,5885,7-339-71550_2941_4871_4877_48561-84396--,00.html", "description": "MDHHS page on certified peer support specialist program, training application, and Medicaid provider manual for peer-delivered support services. Includes application and approval process information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://michiganarr.com/", "description": "Michigan Association of Recovery Residences (MARR) is the sole NARR affiliate in Michigan. Certifies recovery residences to national standards and publishes a directory of certified recovery homes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MARR Certified Operator List", "url": "https://michiganarr.com/full-operator-list", "description": "Full list of MARR-certified recovery residence operators across Michigan, used by hospitals, treatment programs, and courts for making trusted referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health Crisis Services", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/mi-behavioral-health-crisis-services", "description": "Michigan behavioral health crisis services page with crisis contacts. Michigan Peer Warmline: 1-888-PEER-753 (1-888-733-7753), available 7 days a week, 10 a.m. to 2 a.m. for peer support with mental health and substance use conditions."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/hp-lic-health-prof/pharmacy", "description": "Michigan Board of Pharmacy, Bureau of Professional Licensing, LARA. Phone: (517) 373-8068. Fax: (517) 241-2389. Email: BPL-BoardSupport@michigan.gov. Website: www.michigan.gov/bpl."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Medicaid Contact", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/assistance-programs/medicaid", "description": "Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (MDHHS) Medicaid program. For pharmacy-specific questions, contact the Medicaid Health Plan pharmacy benefit section."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/keep-mi-healthy/mentalhealth/drugcontrol", "description": "MDHHS Drug Control section houses the State Opioid Treatment Authority. Contact MDHHS for OTA-specific inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.michiganpharmacists.org/", "description": "Michigan Pharmacists Association (MPA). Phone: 517-484-1466. MPA offers advocacy, education, and practice resources for pharmacy professionals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Opioid Response", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/opioids", "description": "Michigan's comprehensive SUD resources website. Provides information on prevention, treatment, harm reduction, data, and the Michigan Opioids Task Force for residents and health professionals."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MODA Dashboard", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/mdhhs/safety-injury-prev/injuryprevention/moda", "description": "The Michigan Overdose Data to Action (MODA) program brings surveillance and prevention efforts together. The MODA dashboard displays overdose data at state, county, and zip code levels, including current trends, disparities, and harm reduction service utilization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Opioid Data Page", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/opioids/0,9238,7-377-94655---,00.html", "description": "Michigan opioids data page with links to the monthly SUD report, Opioid Task Force summary reports, opioid strategy progress metrics dashboard, and harm reduction data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Overdose Fatality Review", "url": "https://michiganofr.org/data/", "description": "Michigan Overdose Fatality Review (MiOFR) data page with links to the MODA dashboard, overdose data reports, and county-level analysis resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan SUD Data Repository", "url": "https://mi-suddr.com/resources-2/", "description": "Michigan Substance Use Disorder Data Repository with data resources, the MODA dashboard, and related surveillance tools for substance use trends analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Monitoring Program Data", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/lara/bureau-list/bpl/health/maps", "description": "MAPS data on prescribing patterns for Schedule 2-5 controlled substances in Michigan, including reporting and analytics on prescription trends."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MPA Advocacy Action Center", "url": "https://www.michiganpharmacists.org/advocacy-action-center", "description": "Michigan Pharmacists Association advocacy page where members can track legislation, find their legislators, and take action on pharmacy-related issues. MPA monitors issues affecting pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Legislature Homepage", "url": "https://legislature.mi.gov/", "description": "Michigan Legislature website with links to find your senator and representative, search bills, and track legislative activity related to pharmacy and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://www.michiganvotes.org/legislators", "description": "Tool to find Michigan state legislators by name or location. Enables direct contact with representatives and senators on pharmacy and OUD policy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Michigan Opioids Task Force", "url": "https://www.michigan.gov/opioids/crisis-response", "description": "Governor Whitmer's Michigan Opioids Task Force (Executive Order 2022-12) brings together departments from across state government to fight the opioid crisis. The task force catalyzes action on prevention, treatment access, and harm reduction."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Pharmacist Prescribing Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/resource/pharmacist-prescribing/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy resources for pharmacist prescribing authority relevant to Michigan advocacy efforts. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}]}, "minnesota": {"name": "Minnesota", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Minnesota law does not expressly provide for prescribing drugs or medications except for self-administered hormonal contraceptives, nicotine replacement medications, opioid antagonists, and, as of January 1, 2026, “prescribing . .\n.drugs for preventing the acquisition of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West); MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.37(14-17) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nAdditionally, a pharmacist is not included in the definition of “practitioner” except for purposes of prescribing hormonal contraceptives, nicotine replacement therapy or opiate antagonists. MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(23) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Minnesota cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Minnesota practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Minnesota pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Minnesota law expressly includes both “intramuscular and subcutaneous drug administration under a prescription drug order”; and “drug administration, through intramuscular and subcutaneous administration used to treat mental illnesses” subject to specified conditions. MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(4), (5) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).", "2B": "Obtain a “prescription drug order” or “the order of a prescriber” and notify the prescriber after completing administration. MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(4), (5) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Minnesota law expressly includes, as part of the monitoring of drug therapy, “ordering and performing tests that are [CLIA-waived],” and, starting January 1, 2026, “ordering, conducting, and interpreting laboratory tests necessary for therapies that use drugs for preventing the acquisition of HIV.” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(3)(, (15) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nHowever, Minnesota law specifies that “a pharmacist may collect specimens, interpret results, notify the patient of results, and refer the patient to other health care providers for follow-up care . . . only pursuant to a protocol or collaborative practice agreement” (CPA). MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(3) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Minnesota practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nUnder Minnesota law, “collaborative practice” means “patient care activities . . . to initiate, manage, and modify drug therapy under specified conditions mutually agreed” by the pharmacist and collaborating practitioner(s). MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27b) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West). Although this provision uses the term “initiate,” it does not expressly use the term “prescribe.”\nMinnesota law contains little additional explanation about what collaborative practice may entail or what can or cannot be included in CPAs.\nIn addition, Minnesota law governing collaborative practice does not account for the fact that a Minnesota pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPA provides.\nIn summary, Minnesota law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Minnesota pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Minnesota laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPAs.\nExpressly specify in Minnesota laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under physician delegation.\nAllow Minnesota pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it may only apply to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nUnder Minnesota law, “collaborative practice” means “patient care activities . . . to initiate, manage, and modify drug therapy under specified conditions mutually agreed” by the pharmacist and collaborating practitioner(s). MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27b) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiate, manage, and modify,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nHowever, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Minnesota law includes “drug administration, through intramuscular and subcutaneous administration used to treat mental illnesses” if it is done “pursuant to a protocol or [CPA].” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(5)(ii) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West). This appears to expressly allow pharmacists to administer injectable forms of drug for SUD treatment as part of a CPA.\nBesides the practice of pharmacy definition, Minnesota law contains little additional explanation about what collaborative practice may entail or what can or cannot be included in CPAs. As a result, it is unclear if a pharmacist can administer any forms of buprenorphine beyond injectable forms.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Minnesota laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, including non-injectable forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under CPAs.", "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the extent of the authorization is unclear and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nUnder Minnesota law, “collaborative practice” means “patient care activities . . . to initiate, manage, and modify drug therapy under specified conditions mutually agreed” by the pharmacist and collaborating practitioner(s). MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27b) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West). This portion of the law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests.\nMinnesota law contains little additional explanation about what collaborative practice may entail or what can or cannot be included in CPAs However, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Minnesota law expressly includes, as part of the monitoring of drug therapy, “ordering and performing tests that are [CLIA-waived],” and, starting January 1, 2026, “ordering, conducting, and interpreting laboratory tests necessary for therapies that use drugs for preventing the acquisition of HIV.” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(3) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nFurther, the practice of pharmacy definition provides that “a pharmacist may collect specimens, interpret results, notify the patient of results, and refer the patient to other health care providers for follow-up care” pursuant to a CPA. MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(3) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West). It is unclear, however, if this authorization allowing pharmacists to “interpret results” under a CPA applies to any test or only those tests for the pharmacist otherwise has authority to order and administer.", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Minnesota law that a pharmacist’s authority under a CPA includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Minnesota law provides that “collaborative practice” means “patient care activities, consistent with subdivision 27 [the practice of pharmacy], engaged in by one or more pharmacists who have agreed to work in collaboration with one or more practitioners to initiate, manage, and modify drug therapy under specified conditions mutually agreed to by the pharmacists and practitioners.” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27b) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nCPAs can be entered into by “one or more pharmacists” and “one or more practitioners.” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27c) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Minnesota law indicates that the following practitioners can enter into a CPA with a pharmacist: dentists, optometrists, physicians, physician assistants, podiatrists, veterinarians, and advanced practice registered nurses. MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01(27)(5)(ii) (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nThe only Minnesota law that provides information about collaborative practice and CPAs is MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.01 (West 2024) as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMinnesota does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, Minnesota law requires health insurers to cover services provided through telehealth.\nFor purposes of the telehealth coverage law, a “health care provider” means “a health care professional who is licensed or registered by the state to perform health care services within the provider’s scope of practice.” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 62A.673(2)(c) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Minnesota laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "The general rule is that there must be an in-person exam before prescribing controlled substances. However, a prescription for “substance use disorder treatment with medications for opioid use disorder” can be issued if “the prescribing practitioner has completed an examination of the patient via telehealth.” MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.37(2)(e)(2) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West).\nMinnesota laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MINN. STAT. ANN. § 62A.673(2)(c) (West 2024)\n(health insurance); MINN. STAT. ANN. § 147.033 (West 2024) (physicians); MINN. STAT. ANN. § 151.37 (West 2024), as amended by 2024 MINN. SESS. LAWS Ch. (West) (controlled substances); MINN. STAT. ANN. § 256B.0625 (West 2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "Pharmacists can be reimbursed for providing family planning services and supplies, administering vaccines, and providing medication therapy management services. MINN. STAT. ANN.§ 256B.0625(13h) (West 2024).", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Minnesota Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Minnesota laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under CPAs are covered under the Minnesota Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "A comprehensive assessment of a patient for OUD must include providing educational material to the patient about:\n(1) risks for opioid use disorder and opioid dependence; (2) treatment options, including the use of a medication for OUD; (3) the risk and recognition of opioid overdose; and (4) the use, availability, and administration of an opiate antagonist to respond to opioid overdose. MINN. STAT. ANN. § 254A.19(3) (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (MN PMP)", "url": "https://mn.gov/boards/pharmacy-pmp/", "description": "Minnesota Prescription Monitoring Program (PMP) portal, administered by the Minnesota Board of Pharmacy. The PMP contains controlled substance prescription data (Schedules 2-5) provided by Minnesota licensed pharmacies and prescriber dispensers. Login at https://minnesota.pmpaware.net/login. Email: Minnesota.pmp@state.mn.us."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Registration", "url": "https://minnesota.pmpaware.net/identities/new", "description": "Registration page for new PMP AWARxE accounts. Minnesota licensed prescribers and pharmacists can register to access the PMP database. Each individual must create a separate account."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/opioids/mnresponse/pmp.html", "description": "The Minnesota PMP was established under Minnesota Statutes Section 152.126 to promote public health by detecting diversion and misuse of controlled substance prescriptions. Prescribers are required to check the PMP under certain circumstances as defined in state law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://mn.gov/boards/pharmacy-pmp/", "description": "Minnesota participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing, allowing authorized users to access prescription data from other participating states through the PMP AWARxE platform."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://minnesota.pmpaware.net/identities/new", "description": "Delegates can register for PMP access on behalf of authorized prescribers or pharmacists. The delegate must create their own account in PMP AWARxE and be approved by the supervising prescriber or pharmacist."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://mn.gov/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "Minnesota Board of Pharmacy homepage. The Board regulates pharmacists, pharmacies, pharmacy technicians, controlled substance researchers, drug wholesalers, and drug manufacturers. Consists of nine Governor-appointed members (six pharmacists, three public members)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/151", "description": "Minnesota Statutes Chapter 151 - Pharmacy Practice and Wholesale Distribution Act. Contains the full text of the pharmacy practice statutes including definitions, Board powers and duties, licensing, scope of practice, collaborative practice agreements, and drug control."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules", "url": "https://mn.gov/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "Minnesota Board of Pharmacy administrative rules are available through the Board website and the Minnesota Revisor of Statutes. Rules cover pharmacy operations, continuing education, and controlled substance requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute", "url": "https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/151.01", "description": "Minnesota Statutes Section 151.01 defines collaborative practice agreements as written plans between pharmacists and authorized prescribers (physicians, physician assistants, APRNs, dentists, etc.) for initiation, management, modification, and discontinuation of drug therapy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/151", "description": "Minnesota allows pharmacists to participate in collaborative practice agreements for drug therapy management. Pharmacists can also prescribe certain items such as naloxone and HIV prevention medications (PrEP) under specific statutory authority (Section 151.37). Independent pharmacist prescribing of controlled substances is not authorized."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Opioid Response", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/opioids/", "description": "Minnesota Department of Health opioid response page with resources on prescribing practices, overdose prevention, treatment resources, and harm reduction for opioid use disorder. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to find buprenorphine treatment providers and opioid treatment programs in Minnesota."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine. Can be filtered for Minnesota providers by city, state, or zip code."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHS Alcohol, Drugs and Addictions Programs", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/people-we-serve/children-and-families/health-care/alcohol-drugs-addictions/programs-and-services/", "description": "Minnesota Department of Human Services programs and services for substance use disorders, including treatment resources, peer-based recovery support, and medication-assisted treatment information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Regulations", "url": "https://www.cchpca.org/minnesota/", "description": "Center for Connected Health Policy overview of Minnesota telehealth laws. Minnesota allows audio-only communication for SUD treatment and mental health services through July 1, 2027. Federal DEA rules allow buprenorphine initiation via telehealth."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota DHS Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/assets/preferred-drug-list-2025-01-01_tcm1053-662387.pdf", "description": "Minnesota Uniform Preferred Drug List (PDL) effective January 1, 2025. All Managed Care Organizations offering drug benefits for Minnesota Health Care Programs (MHCP) members must use the DHS PDL, which includes buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Medicaid Drug Search", "url": "https://minnesota.magellanmedicaid.com/drug_search.asp", "description": "Minnesota Medicaid PDL drug search tool. For the most up-to-date information, DHS recommends using the DHS NDC Search for coverage and prior authorization details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHS Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/people-we-serve/children-and-families/health-care/alcohol-drugs-addictions/programs-and-services/", "description": "Minnesota DHS programs and services page with links to pharmacy benefits, treatment coverage, and medication information for Minnesota Health Care Programs members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Medicaid", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/", "description": "Minnesota Department of Human Services homepage with access to Medicaid program information, provider resources, fee schedules, and pharmacy benefit details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/opioids/", "description": "Minnesota's Opioid Epidemic Response Advisory Council oversees funding from the opiate epidemic response bill signed in 2019. Funds are raised from drug manufacturers and wholesalers. The Minnesota Opioid Epidemic Response Spending Dashboard tracks investments statewide."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "State CE Requirements", "url": "https://mn.gov/boards/pharmacy/education/pharmacistcontinuingeducation.jsp", "description": "Minnesota Board of Pharmacy CE requirements. Minnesota requires 30 hours of continuing pharmacy education per biennial renewal. The Board does not require state-specific CE topics at this time, though prescribers with controlled substance authority must complete at least 2 hours on best practices in prescribing opioids and controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.mpha.org/", "description": "Minnesota Pharmacists Association (MPhA) offers continuing education programs, annual conference, and advocacy resources. Phone: 651-697-1771. Email: info@mpha.org. Address: 1000 Westgate Drive, Suite 252, St. Paul, MN 55114."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "All DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of substance use disorder training when renewing or obtaining initial DEA registration. This applies to Minnesota practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA MATE Act Resources", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/mate-act", "description": "SAMHSA resource page for MATE Act training requirements. All licensed practitioners with DEA Schedule II-V authority can now prescribe buprenorphine where state law allows."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free buprenorphine training, mentoring, and clinical guidance including 8-hour DEA training options."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/people/syringe/ssp.html", "description": "Minnesota Department of Health page on Syringe Services Programs (SSPs) with resources on reducing harms associated with substance use disorder, including SBIRT guidance, overdose prevention, and harm reduction assessments."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Service Program Calendar", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/people/syringe/calendar.html", "description": "Directory and calendar of syringe service programs across Minnesota with locations, hours, and contact information for each program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/partners-and-providers/news-initiatives-reports-workgroups/alcohol-drug-other-addictions/minnesota-naloxone-portal/naloxone-standing-order.jsp", "description": "Minnesota Naloxone Standing Order managed by the Department of Human Services. The 2023 legislature mandated naloxone carrying for select groups. Under Minnesota Statutes 604A.04, all licensed health care professionals may prescribe, dispense, or distribute naloxone by standing order."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Information", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/opioids/basics/naloxone.html", "description": "Minnesota Department of Health naloxone information page with details on how to obtain naloxone, syringe exchange resources, and overdose reversal guidance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/opioids/documents/ftsforph.pdf", "description": "Minnesota legalized fentanyl test strips as of July 2021, removing them from the definition of drug paraphernalia. Minnesota limits allowed testing equipment to that which can detect fentanyl, fentanyl analogues, or other synthetic opioids. Minnesota was among the first states to take this step."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.health.mn.gov/communities/opioids/opioid-dashboard", "description": "Minnesota Department of Health drug overdose dashboards with interactive data on overdose deaths, trends, and county-level breakdowns. Includes data on opioid, stimulant, and other drug-involved overdoses."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DHS Peer-Based Recovery Support", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/people-we-serve/children-and-families/health-care/alcohol-drugs-addictions/programs-and-services/", "description": "Minnesota DHS peer-based recovery support services include recovery coaching, phone support, support groups, social activities, and assistance with housing, transportation, vocational training, and employment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Association of Sober Homes (MASH)", "url": "https://mnsoberhomes.org/", "description": "Minnesota Association of Sober Homes directory of certified sober homes across the state. MASH provides standards and oversight for recovery housing in Minnesota. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Alliance of Recovery Community Organizations (MARCO)", "url": "https://www.twincitiesrecoveryproject.org/resources", "description": "MARCO works to build an ecosystem of recovery in Minnesota. The Twin Cities Recovery Project resources page provides links to MARCO, treatment options, peer support, and recovery housing resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/people-we-serve/children-and-families/health-care/alcohol-drugs-addictions/", "description": "Minnesota Department of Human Services - Alcohol, Drugs and Addictions section. DHS oversees substance use disorder treatment, prevention, and recovery support services statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis and Helpline Contacts", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/", "description": "Minnesota DHS provides crisis and helpline resources for substance use disorders. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is available 24/7 (call or text 988). Minnesota also supports local crisis teams through community mental health centers."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://mn.gov/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "Aaron Patterson, PharmD, Interim Executive Director, Minnesota Board of Pharmacy. Address: 335 Randolph Avenue, Suite 230, St. Paul, MN 55102. Email: Minnesota.pmp@state.mn.us."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Medicaid/DHS Contact", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/", "description": "Minnesota Department of Human Services administers Medicaid (Minnesota Health Care Programs). Contact DHS for pharmacy benefit, preferred drug list, and billing inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/opioids/", "description": "Minnesota Opioid Epidemic Response Advisory Council (OERAC) oversees opioid response funding and policy. Created under the 2019 Opiate Epidemic Response bill signed by Governor Walz."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.mpha.org/", "description": "Minnesota Pharmacists Association (MPhA). Phone: 651-697-1771. Email: info@mpha.org. Address: 1000 Westgate Drive, Suite 252, St. Paul, MN 55114. Offers advocacy, education, and legislative resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Health Department OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/opioids/", "description": "Minnesota Department of Health opioid response programs including overdose prevention, prescribing practices, naloxone access, and surveillance data. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Dashboards", "url": "https://www.health.mn.gov/communities/opioids/opioid-dashboard", "description": "Minnesota Department of Health interactive drug overdose dashboards with data on overdose deaths by substance type, demographics, and geography."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/overdose/data/index.html", "description": "Comprehensive drug overdose data page with county-level data on overdose deaths by substance type, including county data tables for detailed local analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Epidemic Response Spending Dashboard", "url": "https://mn.gov/mmb/impact-evaluation/projects/opioid-epidemic-response/spending-dashboard/", "description": "Minnesota Management and Budget dashboard providing transparency on Minnesota's investments to mitigate the opioid epidemic, helping policymakers identify needs across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OERAC Reports and Documents", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/opioids/documents/", "description": "Legislative reports and documents from the Opioid Epidemic Response Advisory Council (OERAC), including council charter, bylaws, and annual reports on opioid response funding and outcomes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Monitoring Program Data", "url": "https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/opioids/mnresponse/pmp.html", "description": "Information on the Minnesota PMP including its role in detecting prescription drug diversion, misuse data, and its contribution to opioid prescribing oversight."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MPhA Advocacy and Legislative Action", "url": "https://www.mpha.org/news/", "description": "Minnesota Pharmacists Association advocacy resources including Legislative Day, legislative action alerts, support for pharmacy advocacy fund, and tools to email your legislator about pharmacy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Minnesota Legislator", "url": "https://www.leg.mn.gov/leg/legislators", "description": "Minnesota Legislature page to find your state senator and representative. The \"Who Represents Me?\" tool on the legislature homepage (https://www.leg.mn.gov/) allows address-based legislator lookup."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Minnesota Legislature Bill Search", "url": "https://www.leg.mn.gov/", "description": "Minnesota Legislature homepage with tools to search current legislation, track bills related to pharmacist prescribing and OUD treatment, and access legislative information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Epidemic Response Advisory Council", "url": "https://mn.gov/dhs/opioids/", "description": "OERAC oversees funding from the 2019 opiate epidemic response bill. The council includes representatives from various stakeholder groups and oversees grants for prevention, treatment, and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Pharmacist Prescribing Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/resource/pharmacist-prescribing/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy resources for pharmacist prescribing authority and statewide protocols relevant to Minnesota advocacy. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}]}, "mississippi": {"name": "Mississippi", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Mississippi’s term for CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA) or “protocol” for drug therapy. 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, DEFINITIONS (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Mississippi law does not expressly include prescribing drugs. MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(dd) (West 2024).\nIn addition, under Mississippi pharmacy law a “prescription” means “a written, verbal or electronically transmitted order issued by a practitioner.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(ff) (West 2024). A “practitioner” includes only a “physician, dentist, veterinarian, or other health care provider authorized by law to diagnose and prescribe drugs.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(ee) (West 2024). (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Mississippi cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Mississippi practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Mississippi pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Mississippi laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Mississippi law includes “administering and distributing drugs and devices.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(dd) (West 2024).\nThis provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.Moreover, the laws and regulations of many other states with general language about administration in the practice of pharmacy definition, there are no other Mississippi laws or regulations that address administration of a small subset of drugs or medications (such as immunizations) that would give the impression that the legislature does not view the “drug administration” language as a broad authorization.\nHowever, the response to the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section presents a confounding factor. Mississippi pharmacy regulation expressly limits drug therapy protocols to “non-scheduled drugs.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, Art. XXXVI(4) (2024).\nWith such limitation in place, it is unclear if a pharmacist would have authority to administer a controlled substance outside of a drug therapy protocol when the pharmacist does not have the authority under such protocol.\nUnder Mississippi pharmacy law, “administer” means “the direct application of a prescription drug pursuant to a lawful order of a practitioner to the body of a patient by injection, inhalation, ingestion or any other means.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(a) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain an order from a practitioner.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the Mississippi practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Mississippi expressly refers to lab tests only as to “ordering lab work in accordance with written guidelines or protocols as defined by paragraph (nn) of this section.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(dd) (West 2024). According to the referenced subsection, however, “written guideline or protocol” essentially means collaborative practice, it is “an agreement in which any practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs delegates to a pharmacist authority to conduct specific prescribing functions in an institutional setting, or with the practitioner’s individual patients.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(nn) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Mississippi practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Mississippi law includes “initiating or modifying of drug therapy in accordance with written guidelines or protocols previously established and approved by the [Mississippi Board of Pharmacy].” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(dd) (West 2024).\nThere are two different sets of Mississippi regulations that apply to initiating or modifying drug therapy, perhaps in slightly different contexts. One set is from the Mississippi Board of Pharmacy and one set is from the Mississippi Board of Medical Licensure.\nUnder Mississippi pharmacy regulations, pharmacists may provide “pharmaceutical health care” to patients by “initiating, discontinuing or modifying prescription drug therapy” upon entering into “an active protocol agreement with a licensed prescribing practitioner.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, Art. XXXVI(1) (2024). However, this regulation further provides that the protocol “shall be limited to non-scheduled drugs.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, Art. XXXVI(4) (2024). Under the medical licensure regulations governing collaboration between a physician and pharmacist, there can be a written guideline or protocol whereby “a physician authorized to prescribe drugs delegates to a pharmacist authority to consult with a patient or to conduct specific prescribing functions in an institutional setting, or with individual patients.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 2630, r. 2.3(D) (2024). It is unclear what “conduct specific prescribing functions” means.\nAlthough the medical licensure regulations may allow for pharmacist prescribing under a drug therapy protocol, these regulations do not account for the fact that a Mississippi pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol provides.\nIn summary, Mississippi pharmacy regulation expressly prohibits a drug therapy protocol from managing controlled substances. Additionally, even if pharmacist prescribing of buprenorphine is theoretically allowed under the medical licensure regulations governing a collaborative protocol between a physician and pharmacist, as a practical matter there is no way to do it because a Mississippi pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Mississippi pharmacy laws and/or regulations to allow drug therapy agreements and protocols to manage controlled substances.\nRevise Mississippi laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under collaborative written guidelines or protocols with physicians.\nExpressly specify in Mississippi laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under drug therapy protocols.\nAllow Mississippi pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Mississippi laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Mississippi law includes “initiating or modifying of drug therapy in accordance with written guidelines or protocols previously established and approved by the [Mississippi Board of Pharmacy].” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(dd) (West 2024).\nThere are two different sets of Mississippi regulations that apply to initiating or modifying drug therapy, perhaps in slightly different contexts. One set is from the Mississippi Board of Pharmacy and one set is from the Mississippi Board of Medical Licensure.\nUnder pharmacy regulations, pharmacists may provide “pharmaceutical health care” to patients by “initiating, discontinuing or modifying prescription drug therapy” upon entering into “an active protocol agreement with a licensed prescribing practitioner.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, Art. XXXVI(1) (2024). However, this regulation further provides that the protocol “shall be limited to non-scheduled drugs.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, Art. XXXVI(4) (2024). This appears to prevent a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine under a protocol falling under this regulation.\nUnder the medical licensure regulations governing collaboration between a physician and pharmacist, there can be a written guideline or protocol whereby “a physician authorized to prescribe drugs delegates to a pharmacist authority to consult with a patient or to conduct specific prescribing functions in an institutional setting, or with individual patients.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 2630, r. 2.3(D) (2024).\nThe protocol must include “a statement of the medication categories and the type of initiation and modification of drug therapy that the supervising physician authorizes the pharmacist to perform.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 2630, r. 2.4(B)(6) (2024). Although the provision uses the phrase “initiation and modification,” it does not expressly refer to “administer.” This provision may allow a pharmacist to administer buprenorphine, so long as the pharmacy regulation described above does not prevent it.", "5B": "Enter into a written guideline or protocol with a physician (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Revise Mississippi pharmacy laws and/or regulations to allow an active protocol agreement with a licensed prescribing practitioner for pharmaceutical health care to include controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Mississippi law includes “ordering lab work in accordance with written guidelines or protocols as defined by paragraph (nn) of this section.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(dd) (West 2024).\n“Written guideline or protocol” is “an agreement in which any practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs delegates to a pharmacist authority to conduct specific prescribing functions in an institutional setting, or with the practitioner’s individual patients.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(nn) (West 2024).\nUnder the medical licensure regulations governing collaboration between a physician and pharmacist, there can be a written guideline or protocol whereby “a physician authorized to prescribe drugs delegates to a pharmacist authority to consult with a patient or to conduct specific prescribing functions in an institutional setting, or with individual patients.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 2630, r. 2.3(D) (2024).\nIf this protocol includes the ordering of lab tests, the protocol must describe “the specific responsibilities authorized by the supervising physician, including the type of lab tests the supervising physician authorizes the pharmacist to order.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 2630, r. 2.4(C)(2) (2024). A separate pharmacy regulation governs the provision of “pharmaceutical health care” to patients by “initiating, discontinuing or modifying prescription drug therapy” upon entering into “an active protocol agreement with a licensed prescribing practitioner.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, Art. XXXVI(1) (2024). This regulation does not expressly address ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a written guideline or protocol with a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Mississippi laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a written guideline or protocol includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "“Written guideline or protocol” means “an agreement in which any practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs delegates to a pharmacist authority to conduct specific prescribing functions in an institutional setting, or with the practitioner’s individual patients” so long as the agreement is signed a filed as required by law or regulation. MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73(nn) (West 2024).\n“Collaborative pharmacy practice” (CPP) is where “one or more pharmacists have jointly agreed, on a voluntary basis, to work in conjunction with one or more practitioners under protocol whereby the pharmacist may perform certain patient care functions authorized by the practitioner or practitioners under certain specified conditions and or limitations.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, DEFINITIONS(12) (2024).\n“Collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA) is a written and signed agreement between one or more pharmacists and one or more practitioners that provides for CPP for the purpose of drug therapy management. 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, DEFINITIONS(13) (2024). \n“Practitioner” means “a physician, dentist, veterinarian, or other health care provider authorized by law to diagnose and prescribe drugs.” 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, DEFINITIONS(62) (2024).\nThe following Mississippi laws and regulations provide more information on collaboration, CPPAs, and written guidelines and protocols for drug therapy management – MISS. CODE ANN. § 73-21-73 (West 2024); 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 2630, r. 2.1 to 2.8 (2024); 30 MISS. CODE R. pt.\n3001, DEFINITIONS, Art. XXXVI (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMississippi’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that a “health care practitioner licensed in [Mississippi]” may “prescribe, dispense, or administer drugs . . . or otherwise provide treatment recommendations to a patient” after examining the patient in-person or via telemedicine. The practice is “subject to the limitations of the license under which the individual is practicing.” MISS. CODE ANN. § 41-127-1 (West 2024).\nAlthough not in telehealth/telemedicine law, Mississippi public health laws define “health care practitioner” to include pharmacists. MISS. CODE ANN. § 41-121-5(c)(viii) (West 2024).\nMississippi pharmacy practice regulations define the term “telemedicine” but do not otherwise use the term.", "8B": null, "8C": "Mississippi laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MISS. CODE ANN. § 41-127-1 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); MISS. CODE ANN. § 83-9-351 to 83-8-353 (West 2024) (insurance coverage); 23 MISS. CODE R. pt. 225, r. 1.1 to 4.6 (2024) (Medicaid); 30 MISS. CODE R. pt.\n2635, r. 5.1 to 5.9 (physicians); 30 MISS. CODE R. pt. 3001, DEFINITIONS(89) (2024) (pharmacists).", "9A": "Pharmacists can be reimbursed for disease state management services, including patient evaluation and education, drug therapy review, and other disease state management. 23 MISS. CODE R. pt. 214 (2024).\nEffective January 2024, the Mississippi Medicaid program added coverage for medication management services to the Elderly and Disabled (E&D) waiver, a program, which provides services to beneficiaries who, but for the provision of such services, would require the level of care provided in a nursing facility.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Mississippi Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Mississippi laws and/or regulations that collaborative pharmacist services provided under a written guideline or protocol are covered under the Mississippi Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (MS PMP)", "url": "https://pmp.mbp.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi Prescription Monitoring Program (MS PMP) homepage, managed by the Mississippi Board of Pharmacy. The PMP is an electronic tracking program to aid practitioners and dispensers in providing proper pharmaceutical care relating to controlled substances. Contact: mspmpassist@mbp.ms.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Login and Registration", "url": "https://mississippi.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Mississippi PMP AWARxE login portal (Bamboo Health). Click \"Create an Account\" to register. PDMP account enrollment is automatic with license renewal or application. Address: 6311 Ridgewood Road, Suite E401, Jackson, MS 39211. Support: mspmpassist@mbp.ms.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://pmp.mbp.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi requires prescribers and dispensers to query the PMP for controlled substance prescribing. Specific requirements and exemptions are detailed on the PMP website and in the Mississippi Controlled Substances statutes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://pmp.mbp.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi participates in PMP InterConnect through NABP for interstate data sharing. Mississippi was one of the pilot states for PMP AWARxE software. Interstate data sharing allows authorized users to access prescription data from other participating states."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://mississippi.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Delegates can be registered by authorized prescribers or pharmacists to access the PMP on their behalf. Delegate accounts are created through the PMP AWARxE system. Contact the PMP help desk for delegate registration assistance."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi Board of Pharmacy homepage. The Board protects and promotes the health of Mississippi citizens by regulating pharmacy practice and prescription drug distribution. Phone: (601) 899-8880. Fax: (601) 899-8851. Seven pharmacist members appointed by the Governor."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/compliance/mississippi-pharmacy-practice-act", "description": "Complete Mississippi Pharmacy Practice Act (Title 73, Chapter 21). Contains statutes governing pharmacy practice, pharmacist licensure, and drug control in Mississippi."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act Statutes", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/title-73/chapter-21/mississippi-pharmacy-practice-act/", "description": "Full text of the Mississippi Pharmacy Practice Act (Mississippi Code Title 73, Chapter 21) including all sections governing pharmacy practice, Board powers, licensing, and enforcement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Regulations", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/compliance/regulations", "description": "Mississippi Board of Pharmacy regulations page with links to administrative rules governing pharmacy operations, controlled substances, and professional standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (Cornell)", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/mississippi/title-30/part-3001", "description": "Mississippi Pharmacy Practice Regulations (Title 30, Part 3001) including controlled substance inventory, reporting requirements, and operational standards for pharmacies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi has limited pharmacist prescribing authority. The 2025 Legislative Updates to the Pharmacy Practice Act may expand certain pharmacist services. Check the Board website for current collaborative practice and prescribing provisions."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MSDH Opioid Treatment Program", "url": "https://msdh.ms.gov/page/44,0,382,1065.html", "description": "Mississippi State Department of Health (MSDH) treatment page for opioid use disorder. Anyone aged 15 or older is eligible for medication-assisted treatment. Services are available at no out-of-pocket cost regardless of insurance status. No doctor referral needed."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MSDH OSUD Program", "url": "https://msdh.ms.gov/page/44,25061,382,61.html", "description": "Mississippi OSUD Program Outline including medication-assisted treatment, biospatial surveillance platform for tracking overdoses, naloxone distribution, and program details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to find buprenorphine treatment providers and opioid treatment programs in Mississippi."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine. Can be filtered for Mississippi providers by city or zip code."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Regulations", "url": "https://www.cchpca.org/mississippi/", "description": "Center for Connected Health Policy overview of Mississippi telehealth laws. Federal DEA rules allow buprenorphine initiation via telehealth including audio-only for up to a 6-month supply. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Division of Medicaid", "url": "https://medicaid.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi Division of Medicaid (DOM) homepage. P.O. Box 2222, Jackson, MS 39225. Toll-free: (800) 421-2408. Phone: (601) 359-6050. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://medicaid.ms.gov/preferred-drug-list/", "description": "Mississippi Division of Medicaid Universal Preferred Drug List (PDL). Drugs designated as preferred are selected for efficaciousness, clinical significance, cost effectiveness, and safety for Medicaid beneficiaries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Resources and Buprenorphine Guidance", "url": "https://medicaid.ms.gov/pharmacy/pharmacy-resources/", "description": "Mississippi Medicaid pharmacy resources including Buprenorphine/Naloxone and Buprenorphine Therapy Guidance (revised July 2025), pharmacy billing contact information (PCN/BIN), and ICD-10 codes for POS claims and Smart PAs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fee Schedules and Rates", "url": "https://medicaid.ms.gov/providers/fee-schedules-and-rates/", "description": "Comprehensive fee schedules for Mississippi Medicaid providers, including the MAT for opioid treatment services physician fee schedule. OTP reimbursement is based on 90% of the Medicare fee schedule."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MAT Fee Schedule", "url": "https://medicaid.ms.gov/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/MEDICATION-ASSISTED-TREATMENT-FOR-OPIOID-TREATMENT-SERVICES-PHYSICAN-FEE-SCHEDULE-Print-Date-04-01-2021.pdf", "description": "Specific fee schedule for Medication-Assisted Treatment for Opioid Treatment Services under Mississippi Medicaid. Includes procedure codes and maximum fee amounts."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "State CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/licensing/pharmacists", "description": "Mississippi pharmacists must complete 15 hours of CE per renewal period, including at least 2 hours related to opioid abuse or other addiction-related issues and at least 2 hours obtained via a live seminar."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Board of Pharmacy Naloxone Training", "url": "https://etraining.mbp.ms.gov/trainings/naloxone-training/naloxone-legislation/", "description": "Board of Pharmacy e-training module on naloxone legislation and dispensing requirements. Pharmacists must complete approved training prior to dispensing naloxone under the standing order."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.mspharm.org/", "description": "Mississippi Pharmacists Association (MPhA) offers continuing education programs (quarterly journal with 2 hours CE), networking, and legislative advocacy for pharmacy professionals in Mississippi."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "All DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of substance use disorder training when renewing or obtaining initial DEA registration. This applies to Mississippi practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free buprenorphine training, mentoring, and clinical guidance including 8-hour DEA training options."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://safermississippi.org/key-data/", "description": "A Safer Mississippi provides information on harm reduction including syringe services. Mississippi has limited syringe services programs. Community organizations rooted in communities of color could have significant impact given health disparities in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/news/naloxone", "description": "Mississippi Board of Pharmacy naloxone page. Mississippi Code Section 41-29-319 authorizes pharmacists to dispense an opioid antagonist under a standing order. Pharmacists must complete approved training and provide counseling on medication use."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stand Up Mississippi - Naloxone Policy", "url": "https://standupms.org/policy/", "description": "Stand Up Mississippi page on naloxone policy. HB 996 (2017) authorized health care practitioners to issue standing orders allowing pharmacies to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription. HB 1137 (2024) expanded access by allowing community organizations to store and distribute naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://oxfordtreatment.com/blog/news/fentanyl-test-strips-legalized/", "description": "As of July 1, 2023, fentanyl test strips are legal in Mississippi. The governor signed legislation decriminalizing fentanyl test strips, removing them from the drug paraphernalia classification as a harm reduction measure to reduce opioid-related deaths."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data", "url": "https://odfree.org/", "description": "ODFree.org - Make Mississippi OD Free. Provides Mississippi overdose data, prevention information, and treatment resources. The Mississippi Opioid and Heroin Data Collaborative disseminates data on nonfatal and fatal overdoses, prescribing patterns, and naloxone administrations."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Department of Mental Health - SUD Services", "url": "https://www.dmh.ms.gov/service-options/alcohol-and-drug-services/", "description": "The Mississippi Department of Mental Health (DMH) administers the public system of substance use assessment, referral, prevention, treatment, and recovery support services. Providers include state programs, regional Community Mental Health Centers, and nonprofit community-based programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://soberhousedirectory.com/homes/mississippi/", "description": "Sober House Directory listing recovery homes across Mississippi with information on services, accreditations, and admission processes. Mississippi does not currently require state licensing for recovery housing operations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data to Action", "url": "https://odfree.org/od2a/", "description": "Mississippi's CDC-funded Overdose Data to Action (OD2A) program. The Mississippi Opioid and Heroin Data Collaborative provides provisional data on overdoses, prescribing patterns, drug-related criminal activity, and EMS naloxone administrations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://www.dmh.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi Department of Mental Health homepage. DMH oversees behavioral health and substance use services statewide through state facilities, Community Mental Health Centers, and community-based programs. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Contacts", "url": "https://www.dmh.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi crisis and helpline contacts for substance use disorders. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is available 24/7 (call or text 988). Mississippi DMH also coordinates crisis services through regional Community Mental Health Centers."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/bop_members/mississippi/", "description": "Susan B. McCoy, Executive Director, Mississippi Board of Pharmacy. Address: 6311 Ridgewood Road, Suite E401, Jackson, MS 39211. Phone: (601) 899-8880. Fax: (601) 899-8851. Email: smccoy@mbp.ms.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Division of Medicaid", "url": "https://medicaid.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi Division of Medicaid. P.O. Box 2222, Jackson, MS 39225. Toll-free: (800) 421-2408. Phone: (601) 359-6050. Contact for pharmacy benefit, PDL, and billing inquiries. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://msdh.ms.gov/page/44,25061,382,61.html", "description": "Mississippi State Department of Health (MSDH) oversees opioid treatment services including the OSUD Program. Contact MSDH for State Opioid Treatment Authority information and MAT program referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.mspharm.org/", "description": "Mississippi Pharmacists Association (MPhA). MPhA provides advocacy, continuing education, and professional support for pharmacy professionals in the Magnolia State."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Health Department OUD Programs", "url": "https://msdh.ms.gov/page/44,0,382,1065.html", "description": "Mississippi State Department of Health opioid treatment programs providing medication-assisted treatment at no cost. Available to anyone aged 15 or older without a doctor referral."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PMP Overdose Data Reports", "url": "https://pmp.mbp.ms.gov/node/13", "description": "Mississippi PMP suspected overdose death data, including quarterly reports on opioid-related deaths. In Q2 2024, 73% of suspected overdose deaths reported to the Mississippi Bureau of Narcotics were opioid-related."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODFree Data Dashboard", "url": "https://odfree.org/", "description": "ODFree.org provides Mississippi overdose data including nonfatal and fatal overdose statistics, prescribing patterns, drug-related criminal activity, and naloxone administration data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OD2A Program Data", "url": "https://odfree.org/od2a/", "description": "Mississippi's Overdose Data to Action (OD2A) program, funded by CDC. Provides comprehensive data on overdose trends, using both ED and EMS syndromic surveillance data to track overdose occurrences."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MSDH OSUD Program Data", "url": "https://msdh.ms.gov/page/44,25061,382,61.html", "description": "Mississippi OSUD program outline including biospatial platform data integration for tracking overdoses at the community level, aiding in planning and response efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC WONDER Mississippi Data", "url": "https://wonder.cdc.gov/", "description": "CDC WONDER database provides national and state-level drug overdose death data. Can be filtered for Mississippi-specific mortality data by drug type, county, year, and demographics. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.mspharm.org/", "description": "Mississippi Pharmacists Association provides legislative advocacy on behalf of pharmacy professionals. MPhA tracks and supports legislation affecting pharmacy practice, including recent efforts like HB 733 on pharmacy reimbursement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Legislature", "url": "https://www.legislature.ms.gov/", "description": "Mississippi Legislature homepage with tools to search legislation, access live webcasts, and find representatives and senators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Legislation Search", "url": "https://legislature.ms.gov/legislation-search/", "description": "Mississippi Legislature measure search tool. Search for current bills related to pharmacist prescribing, OUD treatment, buprenorphine, or other pharmacy topics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Mississippi Legislators", "url": "https://www.legislature.ms.gov/legislators/", "description": "Directory of Mississippi state legislators including House Representatives and Senators with contact information and committee assignments."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stand Up Mississippi", "url": "https://standupms.org/", "description": "Stand Up Mississippi is an OUD-related coalition focused on opioid harm reduction policy in Mississippi. Active in advocating for naloxone access, fentanyl test strip legalization, and other harm reduction measures. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mississippi Board of Pharmacy Legislative Updates", "url": "https://www.mbp.ms.gov/", "description": "The Board of Pharmacy posts 2025 Legislative Updates for the Mississippi Pharmacy Practice Act on its homepage. Provides information on recent changes to pharmacy law and regulation."}]}]}, "missouri": {"name": "Missouri", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Missouri’s term for a CPA is a “protocol” for “medication therapy services” (MTS). MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(5) (West. 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Missouri law does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications other than a nicotine replacement therapy product. MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(1) (West 2024).\nFurther, Missouri law specifying the practice of pharmacy expressly provides that “[t]his section shall not be construed to allow a pharmacist to diagnose or independently prescribe pharmaceuticals.” MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(9) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Missouri cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Missouri practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Missouri pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Missouri law expressly includes the “administration of drugs and devices pursuant to medical prescription orders.” MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(1)(3) (West 2024).\nMoreover, the Missouri regulations described in the \"steps for independent administration\" sectionmake clear that the intent of this provision is to broadly authorize pharmacist administration of drugs and medications.", "2B": "File a “Notification of Intent” to administer drugs by medical prescription order with the Missouri Board of Pharmacy. MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2220-6.040(3) (2024).Obtain a medical prescription order for administration from the prescriber. MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2220-6.040(5) (2024).\nAdhere to the administration, recordkeeping, and training requirements contained in Missouri regulation. MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2220-6.040 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Missouri law identifies 10 categories of activities that a pharmacist may perform. This list of activities does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(1) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Missouri pharmacy laws and regulations address ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of a protocol for either medication therapy management or HIV post-exposure prophylaxis.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Missouri practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nUnder Missouri law, a pharmacist may provide “medication therapy services” pursuant to a “written protocol” from a licensed physician. MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(5) (West 2024). However, as part of MTS, a pharmacist “shall not modify any controlled substance prescription” and therefore, a “prescription from the authorizing physician shall be required to modify a controlled substance.” MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(6)(B) (2024).\nMoreover, as part of medication therapy services, a pharmacist may not “adjust, change, or modify any controlled substance prescribed for a patient, except as authorized by state or federal law.” MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(4)(F) (2024).\nThe above two points seem to impliedly prohibit pharmacists from prescribing controlled substances under a MTS protocol.\nMoreover, Missouri laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a MissouriMissouri pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist issuing a prescription for buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol provides.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Missouri laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe (and adjust, change, or modify) controlled substances under MTS protocols with physicians.\nExpressly specify in Missouri laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under MTS protocols.\nAllow Missouri pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Missouri laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nUnder Missouri law, a pharmacist may provide MTS pursuant to a “written protocol” from a licensed physician. MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(5) (West 2024). Such services may include “initiation of drug therapy, as authorized by protocol.” MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(4)(C)(12) (2024). Although this provision uses the word “initiation,” it does not expressly refer to “administration.”\nAs part of MTS, a pharmacist may not “adjust, change, or modify any controlled substance prescribed for a patient, except as authorized by state or federal law.” MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(4)(F) (2024).\nAlthough Missouri laws and regulations are unclear about administering buprenorphine under MTS protocols, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a Missouri pharmacist has the general authority to administer drugs and devices pursuant to medical prescription orders, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a written protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly provide in Missouri laws and/or regulations that “initiation of drug therapy” under MTS protocols includes administering drugs and medications, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nUnder Missouri laws, a pharmacist may provide MTS pursuant to a “written protocol” from a licensed physician. MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(5) (West 2024).\nThe MTS protocol may include a “description of drug therapy related patient assessment procedures or testing that may be ordered or performed by the pharmacist, including any authority to order or perform routine or other laboratory testing.” MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(4)(B)(9) (2024).\nIn addition, the services provided by a pharmacist as part of medication therapy may include “interpreting, monitoring, and assessing patient test results.” MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(4)(C)(11) (2024).", "6B": "Enter into a written protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "A pharmacist may provide MTS pursuant to a written protocol from a licensed physician. MO. ANN. STAT. § 338.010(5) (West 2024).\nMoreover, to participate in MTS, the pharmacist must obtain a “a certificate of medication therapeutic plan authority” from the Missouri State Board of Pharmacy. MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028(1) (2024).\nThe following Missouri laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering into MTS protocols – MO. ANN. STAT. §§ 338.010(5), 338.012 (West 2024); MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2150-5.028 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMissouri’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that “any licensed health care provider shall be authorized to provide telehealth services if such services are within the scope of practice for which the health care provider is licensed and are provided with the same standard of care as services provided in person.” MO. ANN. STAT. § 191.1145(2) (West 2024).\nThe definition for “health care provider” used above comes from Missouri health insurance law. It means the same thing as a “health care professional,” which is defined as a “physician or other health care practitioner licensed, accredited or certified by the state of Missouri to perform specified health services consistent with state law.” MO. ANN. STAT. § 376.1350(19), (20) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "Missouri laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MO. ANN. STAT. §§ 191.1145 to 191.1146 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); MO. ANN. STAT. §§ 208.670 to 208.686 (West 2024) (Medicaid); MO. ANN. STAT. § 334.108\n(West 2024) (physicians); MO. ANN. STAT. § 376.1900 (West 2024) (insurance); MO. CODE REGS. ANN., tit. 13 § 70-3.330 (2024) (Medicaid); MO. CODE REGS. ANN., tit. 20 §§ 2150-2.240, 2150-7.135 (2024) (CPAs with physician assistants);\nMO. CODE REGS. ANN, tit. 20 §§ 2150-5.100, 2200-4.200 (2024) (CPAs with nurses).", "9A": "As of April 2023, the Missouri HealthNet Division (MHD) added additional “pharmacist provider services” (PPS) to Missouri Medicaid coverage. “PPS allows pharmacist providers to receive reimbursement for services that fall within their scope of practice as defined by the Missouri Board of Pharmacy.”", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "The Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services (Department), either through the Department’s director or an employed/contracted physician, “may issue a statewide standing order for . . . an addiction mitigation medication.” MO. ANN. STAT. § 195.206(2) (West 2024). “Addiction mitigation medication” means naltrexone. MO. ANN. STAT. § 195.206(1)(1) (West 2024).", "10B": "Physicians may enter into CPAs with physician assistants allowing the physician assistants to prescribe up to 30 days’ worth of buprenorphine at a time. MO. ANN. STAT. §§ 334.037(12), 334.747(1) (West 2024).\nAdvance practice registered nurses may prescribe up to 30 days’ worth of buprenorphine at a time under collaborating physician oversight. MO. ANN. STAT. § 334.104(2)(4) (West 2024); MO. CODE REGS. ANN. tit. 20, § 2200-4.200 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://pr.mo.gov/pharmacists.asp", "description": "Official homepage of the Missouri Board of Pharmacy, which regulates pharmacists, pharmacies, and pharmacy technicians in Missouri. Includes links to licensing, compliance, and regulatory information. Please verify this link before publishing (site may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/missouri/title-xxii/chapter-338/", "description": "Full text of Missouri Revised Statutes Chapter 338, Pharmacists and Pharmacies, which constitutes the Missouri Pharmacy Practice Act. Includes definitions of practice of pharmacy, licensing requirements, and scope of practice provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rules and Statutes Page", "url": "https://pr.mo.gov/pharmacists-rules-statutes.asp", "description": "Missouri Board of Pharmacy page providing access to the Missouri Lawbook, proposed rules, Federal Controlled Substances Act references, and Missouri Controlled Substance Statutes and Rules. Please verify this link before publishing (site may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Regulations", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/missouri/20-CSR-2200-4-200", "description": "Missouri administrative rule 20 CSR 2200-4.200 governing collaborative practice arrangements. Defines written agreements, jointly agreed upon protocols, or standing orders for the delivery of health care services between physicians and pharmacists, including provisions for controlled substance prescriptive authority."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=338.010", "description": "Missouri Revised Statutes Section 338.010 defines the practice of pharmacy and includes provisions for pharmacist prescribing under written physician protocols. Missouri also enacted Section 338.665 allowing pharmacist prescribing of nicotine replacement therapy products. Missouri does not currently authorize independent pharmacist prescribing of buprenorphine for OUD."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator (FindTreatment.gov) that can be filtered to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in Missouri, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA listing of practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, searchable by state, city, or zip code. Can be filtered to find Missouri-based practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Opioid Crisis Response (DMH)", "url": "https://dmh.mo.gov/opioid-crisis-response", "description": "Missouri Department of Mental Health opioid crisis response page. Details federal grants (State Opioid Response, State Targeted Response) and statewide initiatives to increase access to OUD treatment, reduce unmet treatment need, and reduce opioid overdose deaths."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Time 2 Act Missouri (State Opioid Resource Hub)", "url": "https://time2actmissouri.com/", "description": "Missouri's centralized opioid resource website (formerly opioids.mo.gov), providing information about overdose prevention, treatment options, naloxone access, and recovery support. Includes links to find treatment and get naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Telehealth Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on federal buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing rules. Under the finalized HHS/DEA rule, patients can start and receive up to a 6-month supply of buprenorphine through telephone or audio-visual telehealth consultations. Missouri follows federal telehealth regulations for controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "MO HealthNet Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://mydss.mo.gov/mhd/pharmacy", "description": "Homepage for the Missouri Medicaid (MO HealthNet) Pharmacy Program, which oversees reimbursement for outpatient, fee-for-service prescription drugs, over-the-counter products, and devices. Contact Pharmacy Administration at MHD.PharmacyAdmin@dss.mo.gov or (573) 751-6963."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List and Clinical Edits", "url": "https://mydss.mo.gov/mhd/pharmacy-clinical-edits-pdl", "description": "MO HealthNet preferred drug list and utilization management clinical edits. Buprenorphine sublingual tablets are listed as preferred agents. Includes information on prior authorization requirements for non-preferred buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MO HealthNet Fee Schedules", "url": "https://mydss.mo.gov/mhd/fee-schedules-rate-lists", "description": "MO HealthNet fee schedules updated monthly. Includes reimbursement rates for pharmacy and other provider types. Fee schedule download tools available at apps.dss.mo.gov/fmsFeeSchedules/."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fee Schedule Download Tool", "url": "https://apps.dss.mo.gov/fmsFeeSchedules/DLFiles.aspx", "description": "Interactive tool for downloading MO HealthNet fee schedules by provider type, including pharmacy fee schedules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Opioid Settlement Funds", "url": "https://moopioidsettlements.dmh.mo.gov/", "description": "Missouri opioid settlement fund tracking and reporting site managed by the Department of Mental Health. Under Section 196.1050, RSMo, settlement proceeds are deposited into the Opioid Addiction Treatment and Recovery Fund for treatment, prevention, and related services. Potential funding source for OUD treatment programs."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/missouri/", "description": "Overview of Missouri pharmacist continuing education requirements. Missouri requires a minimum of 30 CE hours every 2 years. Pharmacists with a DEA registration number or pending DEA application must complete 2 hours related to controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Pharmacy Association CE Portal", "url": "https://education.morx.com/?pg=semwebCatalog", "description": "Missouri Pharmacy Association (MPA) continuing education catalog offering online webinars and programs for pharmacist professional development. MPA members can access the latest CE programs on subjects important to their career."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MPA Continuing Education Page", "url": "https://www.morx.com/Web/Web/Education/Continuing-Education.aspx", "description": "Missouri Pharmacy Association continuing education page describing available formats including the online Learning Center with 80+ CE programs and live continuing education events."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA page on Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act requirements. All medical registrants submitting new or renewing DEA registrations must attest to completing an 8-hour training on treating patients with opioid and other substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training Resources", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free buprenorphine training, modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring for healthcare practitioners on evidence-based OUD treatment practices."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://nasen.org/", "description": "North American Syringe Exchange Network (NASEN) directory of harm reduction programs. Note: Under Missouri's drug paraphernalia law, syringe service programs face legal barriers to operation. Some local programs such as the Missouri Safe Project have operated in limited areas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order and Access", "url": "https://pr.mo.gov/pharmacists-naloxone.asp", "description": "Missouri Board of Pharmacy naloxone page. Missouri law authorizes pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a prescription under a statewide Standing Order issued by the Missouri DHSS or by protocol with a licensed physician. Please verify this link before publishing (site may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://health.mo.gov/data/opioids/pdf/naloxone-standing-order.pdf", "description": "The official Missouri statewide standing order for naloxone, issued by the Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services, authorizing pharmacists to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Information", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/missouri", "description": "NEXT Distro Missouri page providing naloxone access resources, information about Missouri's Good Samaritan protections, and Medicaid copay information for naloxone (between $0.50 and $2.00)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://recoveryfriendlymo.com/missouri-joins-over-20-other-states-in-legalizing-fentanyl-test-strips/", "description": "On August 28, 2023, Missouri legalized fentanyl test strips, joining over 20 other states. The law exempts objects used to test for fentanyl or fentanyl analogues from drug paraphernalia statutes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://health.mo.gov/data/opioids/", "description": "Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services interactive Drug Overdose Dashboard displaying fatal and nonfatal overdose data, trends, demographics, and geographic breakdowns. Maintained through the CDC Overdose Data to Action in States (OD2A-S) grant."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Support Services (DMH)", "url": "https://dmh.mo.gov/behavioral-health/treatment-services/specialized-programs/recovery-support-services", "description": "Missouri Department of Mental Health recovery support services page. DMH contracts with recovery support providers to deliver statewide services including care coordination, recovery coaching, spiritual counseling, group support, recovery housing, and transportation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Specialist Certification", "url": "https://missouricb.com/peer-support-specialist/", "description": "Missouri Credentialing Board (MCB) peer support specialist certification page. MCB is recognized by DMH as the sole source for certified peer credentials including Certified Peer Specialist, Family Support Provider, Youth Peer Specialist, and Certified Reciprocal Peer Recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Services (DMH)", "url": "https://dmh.mo.gov/behavioral-health/treatment-services/specialized-programs/peer-support-services", "description": "Missouri Department of Mental Health peer support services page with information on certified peer specialist trainings, resources, and the role of peer support in recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Behavioral Health Division", "url": "https://dmh.mo.gov/behavioral-health", "description": "Missouri Department of Mental Health, Division of Behavioral Health homepage. Manages programs and services for individuals with mental illness and/or substance use disorders, including prevention, education, intervention, treatment, and rehabilitation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services - 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline", "url": "https://missouri988.org/", "description": "Missouri 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline page. Call or text 988 or chat online at 988lifeline.org/chat for free 24/7 support for mental health, suicide, or substance use crises."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://pr.mo.gov/pharmacists-board-members.asp", "description": "Missouri Board of Pharmacy contact page. Executive Director: Kimberly Grinston, J.D. Mailing address: PO Box 625, Jefferson City, MO 65102. Phone: 573-751-0091. Fax: 573-526-3464. Email: MissouriBOP@pr.mo.gov. Please verify this link before publishing (site may block automated access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "MO HealthNet Division (Medicaid)", "url": "https://mydss.mo.gov/mhd/pharmacy", "description": "MO HealthNet Pharmacy Program contact. Director of MO HealthNet Division: Josh Moore, Pharm.D. (appointed December 2025). Pharmacy Administration: MHD.PharmacyAdmin@dss.mo.gov or (573) 751-6963."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://dmh.mo.gov/opioid-crisis-response", "description": "Missouri Department of Mental Health serves as the state authority for substance use disorder treatment and opioid crisis response. DMH coordinates state and federal opioid treatment funding."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.morx.com/", "description": "Missouri Pharmacy Association (MPA), the state professional association for pharmacists. CEO: Ron Fitzwater. MPA provides advocacy, education, and resources for Missouri pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri DHSS Opioid Program", "url": "https://health.mo.gov/data/opioids/", "description": "Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services opioid data and program page. DHSS manages the drug overdose surveillance dashboard and leads public health opioid response initiatives including the OD2A-S grant program."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://health.mo.gov/data/opioids/", "description": "Missouri DHSS interactive Drug Overdose Dashboard showing trends in fatal and nonfatal overdoses, including breakdowns by drug type, demographics, and geography. Over 70% of drug overdose deaths in Missouri involve opioids."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Time 2 Act Missouri Data and Resources", "url": "https://time2actmissouri.com/", "description": "Missouri's centralized opioid information site providing up-to-date data, trends, and resources on substance misuse, overdose, and the state's response. Includes links to overdose statistics and prevention resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Settlement Expenditure Reports", "url": "https://moopioidsettlements.dmh.mo.gov/", "description": "Public reporting site for Missouri opioid settlement fund expenditures, including annual reports to the General Assembly categorizing spending into treatment, prevention, recovery, harm reduction, and law enforcement categories."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri PDMP Data Resources", "url": "https://pdmp.mo.gov/", "description": "The Missouri PDMP collects dispensation data for Schedule II, III, and IV controlled substances. Data from the PDMP can inform surveillance of prescribing trends, though the PDMP is relatively new (launched December 2023)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC SUDORS and OD2A Missouri Data", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11827646/", "description": "Published research article describing Missouri's participation in the CDC Overdose Data to Action in States (OD2A-S) program, including biosurveillance activities, SUDORS data collection, and ESSENCE monitoring for nonfatal overdoses. Missouri was one of 20 states to receive OD2A-S funding for non-fatal overdose biosurveillance."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.morx.com/Web/Web/Membership/Member-Benefits.aspx", "description": "MPA member benefits page describing legislative and regulatory advocacy efforts. MPA represents pharmacists at the Capitol to protect and advance the practice of pharmacy through proactive legislative and regulatory efforts, including the Pharmacy Political Action Committee (PPAC)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Legislator Lookup", "url": "https://www.senate.mo.gov/legislookup/default", "description": "Missouri General Assembly Legislator Lookup tool. Enter a valid Missouri mailing address to find your state senator and representative with contact information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Elected Officials", "url": "https://www.mo.gov/government/elected-officials/", "description": "Missouri state government page for finding information about statewide elected officials and links to the House of Representatives and Senate."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Friendly Missouri", "url": "https://recoveryfriendlymo.com/", "description": "Recovery Friendly Missouri initiative empowering workplaces to support people affected by substance use disorders and those in recovery. Includes resources, education, and links to the Missouri Coalition of Recovery Support Providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Missouri Opioid Settlement Oversight", "url": "https://moopioidsettlements.dmh.mo.gov/", "description": "Missouri opioid settlement public reporting site. The Department of Mental Health is the lead agency for opioid settlement expenditures under Section 196.1050, RSMo. Settlement funds must be used for opioid addiction treatment, prevention, and related health care and law enforcement costs."}]}]}, "montana": {"name": "Montana", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Montana uses both CPA, an undefined term, and the defined term “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(7) (West 2023).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Montana law expressly includes “prescribing drugs and devices in accordance with [§] 37-7-106.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38)(d) (West 2023).\nHowever, the prescribing authority granted by the referenced Montana law provides that a pharmacist “may not prescribe a controlled substance.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-106(5) (West 2023). This law does further note that § 37-7-106 “does not apply to a pharmacist who is operating within a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-106(7) (West 2023).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Montana can only obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Administer, Procure, Dispense & Prescribe” controlled substances as part of a “Pharmacy Practice Agreement.”", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Montana practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Montana pharmacists not operating under a CPPA to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Montana law expressly includes administering drugs or medications in two ways: (1) “pursuant to a [CPA]”; or (2) “as provided in [§] 37-7-105.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38)(b) (West 2023).\nThe referenced Montana law pertains to the administration of immunizations. MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-105 (West 2023).", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Montana practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Montana law does not expressly provide for ordering or evaluating lab tests. MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38) (West 2023).\nMoreover, no other Montana pharmacy laws or regulations address ordering or evaluating lab tests except for testing performed by a “clinical pharmacist practitioner” who must be acting pursuant to a CPPA. MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-306 (West 2023).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Montana practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Montana law includes both “administering drugs and devices pursuant to a [CPA]” and “initiating or modifying drug therapy in accordance with [CPPAs]” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38)(b), (f) (West 2023).\nAlthough the provisions described above do not expressly refer to prescribing, the practice of pharmacy also allows “prescribing drugs and devices in accordance with [§] 37-7-106.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38)(d) (West 2023). The referenced section allows pharmacists to prescribe any drug or device except for controlled substances and abortion-inducing drugs. MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-106(5) (West 2023). Although § 37-7-106 would appear to prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances, that law expressly notes it “does not apply to a pharmacist who is operating within a [CPPA].” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-106(7) (West 2023). This suggests that a pharmacist can prescribe controlled substances under a CPPA because the limitations of § 37-7-106 do not apply.\nMoreover, under Montana pharmacy law, a “prescriber” is defined as a “medical practitioner.” MONT. CODE ANN. §§ 37-7-101(41), 37-7-502(10) (West 2023).\nMontana law applicable to all healthcare practitioners defines “medical practitioner” to include a licensed pharmacist who is “authorized to . . . (ii) prescribe drugs pursuant to [§] 37-7-106 or in accordance with a [CPPA].” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-2-101(8)(b)(ii) (West 2023). This further supports the conclusion that a CPPA can authorize a pharmacist to prescribe additional drugs (i.e., controlled substances) or in different ways beyond the pharmacist’s general authority under § 37-7-106.\nDEA information as of November 2024 indicates that registered pharmacists in Montana may obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Administer, Procure, Dispense & Prescribe” controlled substances under what it calls a “Pharmacy Practice Agreement.”", "4B": "Obtain a DEA mid-level practitioner registration.\nEnter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in Montana laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist can prescribe controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a CPPA.", "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Montana law expressly includes “administering drugs and devices pursuant to a [CPA].” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38)(b) (West 2023).\nMontana laws and regulations governing CPPA do not place any express limitation on this authority.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests and only by certain pharmacists.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Montana law includes both “administering drugs and devices pursuant to a [CPA]” and “initiating or modifying drug therapy in accordance with [CPPAs]” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(38)(b), (f) (West 2023).Neither of these provisions about CPPAs references ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nMontana regulation governing CPPAs also does not expressly address ordering or evaluating lab tests. MONT. ADMIN. R. 24.174.524 (2024).\nHowever, Montana law provides that the state board of pharmacy may certify a pharmacist as a “clinical pharmacist practitioner” to “provide drug therapy management including . . . ordering tests under the direction or supervision of a practitioner.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-306(a) (West 2023). Such clinical pharmacist practitioner must have “in place a [CPPA].” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-306(c) (West 2023).", "6B": "Obtain certification as a CPP.\nEnter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Montana laws and/or regulations that all pharmacists’ authority under a CPPA includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CPPA is a written and signed agreement “between one or more pharmacists and one or more prescribers that provides for collaborative pharmacy practice for the purpose of drug therapy management of patients.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(6) (West 2023).\nUnder Montana pharmacy law, a “prescriber” is a “medical practitioner.” MONT. CODE ANN. §§ 37-7-101(41), 37-7-502(10) (West 2023).\nA “medical practitioner” includes any person licensed in Montana to engage in “the practice of medicine, dentistry, osteopathy, podiatry, or optometry” and “a nursing specialty” with “the licensed practice to administer or prescribe drugs.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-2-101(8) (West 2023).\nNote that Montana law provides that the state board of pharmacy may certify a pharmacist as a clinical pharmacist practitioner to “provide drug therapy management” and such practitioner must have “in place a [CPPA].” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-306 (West 2023). It does not appear that a pharmacist has to be certified as a clinical pharmacist practitioner in order to participate in a CPPA, but the only express reference to ordering lab tests under a CPPA is in the law governing qualifications of clinical pharmacist practitioners.\nThe following Montana laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPPAs, required elements of CPAs, and clinical pharmacist practitioners – MONT. CODE ANN. §§ 37-7-101(5), (6), 37-7-306 (West 2023); MONT. ADMIN. R. 24.174.524 , 24.174.526 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nMontana’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that a “person licensed under this title [Title 37] to provide health care in the ordinary course of business or practice of a profession” may provide services by telehealth so long as the provider meets the standard of care and adheres to administrative regulations. MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-2-305(1) (West 2023). This includes pharmacists.\nMoreover, Montana pharmacy law expressly defines the phrase “practice of pharmacy by means of telehealth,” which is “to provide pharmaceutical care through the use of information technology to patients at a distance.” MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-7-101(39) (West 2023).\nMontana pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "Montana laws and regulations governing telehealth include – MONT. CODE ANN. § 37-2-305 (West 2023) (generally); MONT. CODE ANN. § 33-22-138 (West 2023) (insurance); MONT. CODE ANN. § 53-6-122 (West 2023) (Medicaid); MONT. ADMIN. R. 24.156.813 (2024) (physicians); MONT. ADMIN. R. 24.174.1302 to 24.174.1303 (2024)\n(telepharmacy).", "9A": "Clinical pharmacist practitioners can be reimbursed for drug therapy management services. There are several requirements a pharmacist must meet to qualify as a CPP. Among other things, the pharmacist must have a CPPA with a medical practitioner.179\nOtherwise, Montana pharmacists are eligible Medicaid providers generally, but there is no requirement for payment for professional services.", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://boards.bsd.dli.mt.gov/pharmacy/", "description": "Official homepage of the Montana Board of Pharmacy, administered under the Department of Labor and Industry, Business Standards Division. Contact: (406) 841-2371 or dlibsdpha@mt.gov. Address: 301 S. Park Avenue, 4th Floor, Helena, MT 59620."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statute and Rule Information", "url": "https://boards.bsd.dli.mt.gov/pharmacy/regulations/", "description": "Montana Board of Pharmacy statute and rule information page. Administrative Rules pertaining to pharmacy (Chapter 24.174) are written and adopted by the Board of Pharmacy. Includes links to Montana Code Annotated and administrative rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules of Montana - Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://rules.mt.gov/gateway/ChapterHome.asp?Chapter=24.174", "description": "Full text of Montana Administrative Rules Chapter 24.174, Board of Pharmacy. Includes subchapters on organizational rules, licensing, internship, pharmacy technicians, drug distribution, collaborative practice, and the prescription drug registry."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Requirements", "url": "https://rules.mt.gov/gateway/ruleno.asp?RN=24.174.524", "description": "Montana Administrative Rule 24.174.524 governing collaborative practice agreement requirements. Montana allows pharmacists to engage in collaborative pharmacy practice through written agreements with prescribers for drug therapy management."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://archive.legmt.gov/bills/2023/billhtml/SB0112.htm", "description": "Montana Senate Bill 112 (2023 session) addressing collaborative pharmacy practice. Montana allows pharmacist prescribing under collaborative practice agreements with prescribers. Montana does not currently authorize independent pharmacist prescribing of buprenorphine for OUD, though collaborative arrangements may facilitate pharmacist involvement."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Montana Opioid Resource Hub (DPHHS)", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/opioid/", "description": "Montana DPHHS centralized opioid information page. Includes links to the Montana Substance Use Disorder Task Force (with 2024-2028 Strategic Plan), treatment resources, prevention, harm reduction, and recovery resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Get Help Page", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/opioid/gethelp", "description": "Montana DPHHS page on getting help for opioid use disorder. Includes information on medication-assisted treatment (MAT) resources, partnership with Montana PBS for public service announcements, and links to find treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator that can be filtered to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in Montana, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana SUD Services (State Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/BHDD/SubstanceAbuse/", "description": "Montana DPHHS Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities Division, Bureau of Substance Use Disorder Services. Oversees implementation of federal guidance related to Medication for Opioid Use Disorder (MOUD) and provides direction on compliance with 42 CFR Part 2 and other confidentiality requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Telehealth Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on federal buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing rules. Under the finalized HHS/DEA rule, patients can start and receive up to a 6-month supply of buprenorphine through telephone or audio-visual telehealth consultations. Montana follows federal telehealth regulations for controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Montana Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/montanahealthcareprograms/medicaid/pharmacy", "description": "Montana DPHHS Medicaid pharmacy services page. Not all drugs are covered even with a prescription. Patients must use a pharmacy that is a Montana Healthcare Programs provider."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://medicaidprovider.mt.gov/docs/pharmacy/2025pharm/PreferredDrugListMay2025.pdf", "description": "Montana Healthcare Programs Preferred Drug List (PDL), revised May 2025. Includes coverage information for buprenorphine products. For prior authorization, contact Mountain Pacific Quality Health Clinical Call Center."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Prior Authorization (Mountain Pacific)", "url": "https://mpqhf.org/resources/pharmacy-resources/", "description": "Mountain Pacific Quality Health pharmacy resources page managing prior authorization for Montana Medicaid. Includes clinical criteria for medications including Brixadi (buprenorphine extended release injection) and other buprenorphine products. PA line: 1-800-219-7035."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Medicaid Fee Schedules", "url": "https://medicaidprovider.mt.gov/providertype", "description": "Montana Medicaid provider type page listing available resources by provider type, including fee schedules, provider notices, and manuals. Fee schedules for pharmacy and other provider types are available for download."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Drug Program Manual", "url": "https://medicaidprovider.mt.gov/manuals/prescriptiondrugprogrammanual", "description": "Montana Healthcare Programs Prescription Drug Program Manual. Contains detailed information on pharmacy billing procedures, reimbursement policies, and covered services under Montana Medicaid."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Montana Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/montana/", "description": "Overview of Montana pharmacist continuing education requirements. Pharmacists must complete 1.5 CEU (15 hours) per fiscal year if taking at least 0.5 CEU (5 hours) in approved group programs, or 2.0 CEU (20 hours) per year without group programs. Two hours on controlled substances and opioids are required every two years."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana CE Administrative Rule", "url": "https://rules.mt.gov/gateway/ruleno.asp?RN=24.174.2104", "description": "Montana Administrative Rule 24.174.2104 governing registered pharmacist continuing education requirements. Specifies annual CE requirements and approved program formats."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://rxmt.org/", "description": "Montana Pharmacy Association (MPA) homepage. MPA provides continuing education programs, professional development, and advocacy resources for Montana pharmacists, technicians, and students."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA page on Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act requirements. All medical registrants must attest to completing an 8-hour training on treating patients with opioid and other substance use disorders when applying for new or renewing DEA registrations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training Resources", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free buprenorphine training, modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring for healthcare practitioners on evidence-based OUD treatment practices."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Montana Harm Reduction - Get in Front of It", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/opioid/getinfrontoit", "description": "Montana DPHHS harm reduction page including information on medication storage and disposal, syringe services programs, naloxone access, and partnerships with the Montana Public Health Institute (MTPHI) for opioid prevention and harm reduction resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/assets/publichealth/EMSTS/opioids/MontanaStandingOrderforNaloxoneOpioidAntagonists.pdf", "description": "Montana statewide standing order for naloxone opioid antagonists. Authorizes pharmacists to dispense naloxone to eligible recipients without an individual prescription. Required by HB 333."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Implementation Guide", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/assets/publichealth/EMSTS/opioids/MontanaImplementationGuideforIncreasedNaloxoneUpdatedMay2019.pdf", "description": "Montana implementation guide for increased access to naloxone. Includes details on the statewide standing order, pharmacist responsibilities, and distribution requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Status", "url": "https://legislativeanalysis.org/knowledge-lab-state-maps/fentanyl-tests-strips/", "description": "Legislative Analysis and Public Policy Association (LAPPA) map of fentanyl test strip legality by state. Montana has legalized drug checking equipment generally (not limited to just fentanyl test strips), making distribution and possession legal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Reports", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/publichealth/EMSTS/data", "description": "Montana DPHHS data reports and analytics page. Includes Drug Overdose Deaths in Montana 2014-2023 report, PDMP Report on Montana Prescribing Trends 2021-2023, SUDORS Infographic 2019-2023, and fact sheets on opioid, fentanyl, and methamphetamine use."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Access Montana (RAM)", "url": "https://www.rammontana.org/", "description": "Recovery Access Montana (RAM) certifies recovery homes, connects peer support, and builds recovery systems across Montana. Serves rural, tribal, and justice-involved communities. Montana's primary recovery community organization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities Division", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/bhdd/", "description": "Montana DPHHS Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities Division (BHDD) homepage. Implements and improves statewide prevention, treatment, care, and rehabilitation for Montanans with mental disorders or substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/BHDD/crisissystemsinformationandresources/CrisisServices", "description": "Montana DPHHS crisis services page. Includes information on the 988 Suicide and Mental Health Crisis Lifeline and mobile crisis response services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana 988 Crisis Lifeline", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/suicideprevention/988", "description": "Montana's dedicated 988 crisis lifeline page. Call or text 988 for 24/7 crisis support with trained professionals. Connected to the national 988 Lifeline. Montana 211 provides mental health referral services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana SUD Services", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/BHDD/SubstanceAbuse/", "description": "Montana DPHHS Bureau of Substance Use Disorder Services. Oversees SUD treatment services, MOUD implementation, and federal compliance for substance use treatment programs statewide."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Montana Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://boards.bsd.dli.mt.gov/pharmacy/", "description": "Executive Officer: Marcie Bough, PharmD. Address: 301 S. Park Avenue, 4th Floor, PO Box 200513, Helena, MT 59620-0513. Phone: (406) 841-2371. Fax: (406) 841-2355. Email: dlibsdpha@mt.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Medicaid Provider Resources", "url": "https://medicaidprovider.mt.gov/", "description": "Montana Medicaid provider information portal. For pharmacy-specific questions, see the Prescription Drug Program Manual and pharmacy provider type resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana SUD Treatment Authority", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/BHDD/SubstanceAbuse/", "description": "Montana Department of Public Health and Human Services, Behavioral Health and Developmental Disabilities Division, Bureau of Substance Use Disorder Services. Oversees medication for opioid use disorder (MOUD) implementation and federal compliance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://rxmt.org/", "description": "Montana Pharmacy Association (MPA), the state professional association for pharmacists. Provides advocacy, education, and resources. Established in 1890 as the leading advocate for Montana pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana DPHHS Opioid Program", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/opioid/", "description": "Montana DPHHS centralized opioid response page. Coordinates the Montana SUD Task Force, opioid prevention initiatives, and statewide substance use disorder services. Contact for SUDs Task Force meetings: Emma Perry."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Deaths Report", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/assets/publichealth/EMSTS/Data/DrugOverdoseDeaths_2014-2023.pdf", "description": "Comprehensive report on drug overdose deaths in Montana from 2014-2023, including age-adjusted death rates compared to national rates, trends by substance type, and demographic breakdowns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Data Reports and Analytics Page", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/publichealth/EMSTS/data", "description": "Montana DPHHS data reports hub with multiple opioid-related publications including drug overdose deaths reports, PDMP prescribing trends, SUDORS infographics, and substance-specific fact sheets."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Prescribing Trends Report", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/publichealth/EMSTS/data", "description": "Montana PDMP Report on Prescribing Trends 2021-2023 available through the DPHHS data reports page. Shows controlled substance prescribing patterns analyzed from MPDR data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana SUD Task Force Strategic Plan", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/assets/publichealth/EMSTS/opioids/MontanaSubstanceUseDisordersTaskForceStrategicPlan.pdf", "description": "2024-2028 Montana Substance Use Disorder Task Force Strategic Plan. Includes data on opioid overdose rates, treatment gaps, and strategic goals for prevention, treatment, harm reduction, and recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana SOR Initiatives", "url": "https://nasadad.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/Montana-SOR-Brief-2024_Final.pdf", "description": "National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors (NASADAD) brief on Montana's State Opioid Response (SOR) grant initiatives, including treatment, recovery housing, and prevention programs."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Montana Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://rxmt.org/", "description": "Montana Pharmacy Association website with information on advocacy efforts, legislative priorities, and professional development for pharmacists. MPA advocates for the advancement of pharmacy practice in Montana."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Legislator Lookup", "url": "https://archive.legmt.gov/legislator-lookup/", "description": "Montana State Legislature legislator lookup tool. Find your state legislators by entering your address. County election offices can help determine legislative districts and representatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Legislature Roster", "url": "https://archive.legmt.gov/legislator-information/", "description": "Montana State Legislature legislator roster. Find legislators by year or search. General legislative questions: 406-444-3064. Montana State Legislature, State Capitol, PO Box 201706, Helena, MT 59620-1706."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana SUD Task Force", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/opioid/", "description": "Montana Substance Use Disorder Task Force, a statewide coalition that meets regularly to coordinate opioid and substance use disorder prevention, treatment, harm reduction, and recovery efforts. The 2024-2028 Strategic Plan guides activities. Contact Emma Perry for meeting information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Montana Opioid Settlement Information", "url": "https://dphhs.mt.gov/opioid/", "description": "Information about Montana's opioid settlement funds and their allocation to prevention, treatment, harm reduction, and recovery services. Montana uses settlement funds to support SOR initiatives and related programs coordinated through DPHHS."}]}]}, "nebraska": {"name": "Nebraska", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Nebraska’s term for a CPA is a “practice agreement” (PA). NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2867.03 (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nebraska law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2837(1) (West 2024).\nMoreover, under Nebraska pharmacy law, a prescription is issued by a “practitioner,” and the definition of “practitioner” does not include pharmacists. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2838 (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Nebraska cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Nebraska practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Nebraska pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nebraska expressly includes “the administration of drugs or devices.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2837(1) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.Unlike the laws and regulations of several other states with general language about administration in the practice of pharmacy definition, there are no other Nebraska laws or regulations that address administration of a small subset of drugs or medications (such as immunizations) that would give the impression that the legislature does not view the “administration of drugs or devices” language as a broad authorization.", "2B": "Understand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nebraska law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2837(1) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Nebraska pharmacy laws or regulations address ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Nebraska practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nebraska law allows for “the provision of pharmaceutical care.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2837(1) (West 2024).\nA pharmacist may enter into a practice agreement (PA) with a health care practitioner to provide “pharmaceutical care according to written protocols” to patients. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2867.03(1) (West 2024).\n“Pharmaceutical care” is the process by which a pharmacist works with the patient and other health care professionals “in designing, implementing, and monitoring a therapeutic plan.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2831 (West 2024). This provision does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs and medications.\nNebraska laws and regulations contain little additional explanation about what collaborative practice may entail or what can or cannot be included in PAs.\nIn addition, Nebraska law governing PAs does not account for the fact that a Nebraska pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the PA provides.\nIn summary, Nebraska law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a PA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Nebraska pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Nebraska laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under PAs with practitioners.\nExpressly specify in Nebraska laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under PAs.\nAllow Nebraska pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Nebraska laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nebraska law allows for “the provision of pharmaceutical care.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2837(1) (West 2024).\nA pharmacist may enter into a PA with a health care practitioner to provide “pharmaceutical care according to written protocols” to patients. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2867.03(1) (West 2024).\n“Pharmaceutical care” is the process by which a pharmacist works with the patient and other health care professionals “in designing, implementing, and monitoring a therapeutic plan.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2831 (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase implementing and monitoring,” it does not expressly refer to “administration.”\nNebraska laws and regulations contain little additional explanation about what collaborative practice may entail or what can or cannot be included in PAs.\nAlthough Nebraska laws and regulations are unclear about administering buprenorphine under PAs, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a Nebraska pharmacist has the general authority to administer “drugs and devices,” the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a PA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in Nebraska laws and/or regulations that “pharmaceutical care” includes administering drugs, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Nebraska laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nebraska law allows for “the provision of pharmaceutical care.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2837(1) (West 2024).\nA pharmacist may enter into a PA with a health care practitioner to provide “pharmaceutical care according to written protocols” to patients. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2867.03(1) (West 2024).\n“Pharmaceutical care” is the process by which a pharmacist works with the patient and other health care professionals “in designing, implementing, and monitoring a therapeutic plan.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2831 (West 2024). This provision does not expressly address whether a pharmacist can order or evaluate the results of lab tests under a PA.\nMoreover, Nebraska laws and regulations contain little additional explanation about what collaborative practice may entail, what can or cannot be included in PAs, and whether that can include ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Nebraska laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a PA includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Nebraska law provides that a pharmacist may enter into a PA with “a licensed health care practitioner authorized to prescribe independently” to provide “pharmaceutical care according to written protocols” to patients. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2867.03(1) (West 2024).\nUnder Nebraska pharmacy law, a “practitioner” means “a certified registered nurse anesthetist, a certified nurse midwife, a dentist, an optometrist, a nurse practitioner, a physician assistant, a physician, a podiatrist, or a veterinarian.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2838 (West 2024).\nThe only Nebraska law or regulation pertaining to PAs is – NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2867.03 (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nNebraska’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that any “credential holder under the Uniform Credentialing Act may establish a provider-patient relationship through telehealth.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-1,143(1) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists. NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-121(1)(hh) (West 2024).\nNebraska pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "Nebraska laws and regulations governing telehealth include – NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-1,143 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 38-2845.01 (West 2024)\n(telepharmacy); NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 44-312 (West 2024) (insurance); NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 71-8501 to 71-8512 (West 2024) (Medicaid); 471 NEB. ADMIN. CODE § 1.004 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "Although not specific to Medicaid, Nebraska insurer law provides that “an insurer may contract with a licensed pharmacist for pharmacist professional services.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 44-313 (West 2024).\nHowever, as of 2024, tobacco cessation counseling is the only clinical service for which Medicaid may reimburse pharmacists. 471 NEB. ADMIN. CODE § 16.006 (2024).", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Nebraska Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Nebraska laws and/or regulations that pharmaceutical care services provided under a PA are covered under the Nebraska Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Buprenorphine is expressly excepted from the Nebraska criminal statute governing the administration of controlled “narcotic drugs” to a “narcotic-dependent person.” NEB. REV. STAT. ANN. § 28-412 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy / Pharmacist Licensure", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/licensure/pages/pharmacist.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS pharmacist licensure page serving as the functional Board of Pharmacy homepage. Nebraska State Office Building, 301 Centennial Mall South, 14th and M Streets, 3rd Floor, Lincoln, NE 68508. Hours: Monday-Friday 8am-5pm. Note: Nebraska does not have a standalone Board of Pharmacy; pharmacy regulation is under the DHHS Licensure Unit."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://regulations.justia.com/states/nebraska/health-and-human-services-system/title-172/chapter-128/", "description": "Nebraska Administrative Code Title 172, Chapter 128 - Practice of Pharmacy by Credentialed Pharmacy Personnel. References the Nebraska Pharmacy Practice Act (Neb. Rev. Stat. Sections 38-2801 to 38-28,116) and the Uniform Controlled Substances Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Administrative Rules", "url": "http://govdocs.nebraska.gov/epubs/H8310/R172.0128-2020.pdf", "description": "Full text of Nebraska Administrative Code Title 172, Chapter 128 governing pharmacy practice. Includes definitions, licensing requirements, pharmacy standards, and controlled substance regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice", "url": "https://regulations.justia.com/states/nebraska/health-and-human-services-system/title-172/chapter-128/", "description": "Nebraska permits collaborative drug therapy management through the Pharmacy Practice Act. Pharmacists may enter into collaborative practice arrangements with prescribers under Nebraska statutes. Details are within 172 NAC 128."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/licensure/pages/pharmacist.aspx", "description": "Nebraska does not currently authorize independent pharmacist prescribing of buprenorphine for OUD. Pharmacist scope of practice is defined in the Pharmacy Practice Act (Neb. Rev. Stat. Sections 38-2801 et seq.). Pharmacists may perform certain clinical services under collaborative practice agreements with prescribers."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska State Opioid Response", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/State-Opioid-Response.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS Division of Behavioral Health state opioid response page. Since 2017, DBH has received federal grants to focus on opioid addiction prevention, treatment, and recovery. Includes information on local buprenorphine providers and medication-assisted treatment resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator that can be filtered to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in Nebraska, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Coalition to Prevent Opioid Abuse", "url": "https://ago.nebraska.gov/nebraska-coalition-prevent-opioid-abuse-strategic-initiative-report", "description": "Nebraska Attorney General's office page on the Nebraska Coalition to Prevent Opioid Abuse, a statewide multi-agency coalition. Includes strategic initiative reports detailing progress on treatment access, provider training, and PDMP development."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/behavioral-health.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS Division of Behavioral Health serves as the state's designated single state authority for mental health and substance use disorders. DBH oversees substance use disorder treatment services, MOUD implementation, and federal opioid grant programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Telehealth Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on federal buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing rules. Under the finalized HHS/DEA rule, patients can start and receive up to a 6-month supply of buprenorphine through telephone or audio-visual telehealth consultations. Nebraska follows federal telehealth regulations for controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Medicaid Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://nebraska.fhsc.com/PDL/PDLlistings.asp", "description": "Nebraska Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) listings page. Includes current PDL and claim limitations documents. Managed by First Health Services Corporation (FHSC) on behalf of Nebraska Medicaid."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://nebraska.fhsc.com/PDL/PDLlistings.asp", "description": "Current Nebraska Medicaid PDL with prior authorization criteria. Buprenorphine products are included. The Pharmaceutical and Therapeutics (P&T) Committee reviews and approves drug classes on the PDL. All Medicaid managed care plans must use the Nebraska Medicaid state PDL."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Medicaid Provider Site", "url": "https://nebraska.fhsc.com/", "description": "Nebraska Medicaid provider website with prescription drug program information, billing guides, and pharmacy resources. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Provider Bulletins", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Medicaid%20Provider%20Bulletins/Provider%20Bulletin%2024-28.pdf", "description": "Example Nebraska Medicaid provider bulletin announcing changes to the Preferred Drug List. Provider bulletins include updates on PDL changes, prior authorization criteria, and billing guidance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Opioid Settlement Funds", "url": "https://ago.nebraska.gov/nebraska-opioid-settlement-remediation-advisory-committee", "description": "Nebraska Opioid Settlement Remediation Advisory Committee page. In 2020, the Nebraska Legislature passed LB1124, the Opioid Prevention and Treatment Act, establishing the Opioid Recovery Fund for dedicated opioid treatment and prevention revenue from settlement proceeds."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/nebraska/", "description": "Overview of Nebraska pharmacist continuing education requirements. During the 24 months prior to license renewal, pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE from an approved provider. The Board of Pharmacy has approved ACPE and the Nebraska Council on Continuing Pharmaceutical Education as CE providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska DHHS Pharmacist Licensure CE Information", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/licensure/pages/pharmacist.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS pharmacist page with information on approved continuing education providers, including ACPE and the Nebraska Council on Continuing Pharmaceutical Education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.npharm.org/", "description": "Nebraska Pharmacists Association (NPA) website. NPA provides advocacy, education, and networking opportunities for pharmacy professionals. ACPE-approved CE provider (Provider #0128). CEO: Haley Pertzborn. Phone: (402) 420-1500. Address: 6221 S 58th Street, Suite A, Lincoln, NE 68516."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA page on Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act requirements. All medical registrants must attest to completing an 8-hour training on treating patients with opioid and other substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training Resources", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free buprenorphine training, modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring for healthcare practitioners on evidence-based OUD treatment practices."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://nasen.org/", "description": "North American Syringe Exchange Network (NASEN) directory. Nebraska has been advancing legislation (LB307) to allow local jurisdictions to permit syringe services programs by exempting staff and participants from drug paraphernalia prosecution. Check current status of Nebraska syringe services legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/DOP%20document%20library/Naloxone%20standing%20order.pdf", "description": "Nebraska DHHS statewide standing order for naloxone. Nebraska law and the standing order allow pharmacists to dispense naloxone to anyone at risk of opioid overdose or in a position to help someone at risk, without a prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access Information", "url": "https://www.safeproject.us/naloxone/state-rules/", "description": "SAFE Project state naloxone access rules page. Nebraska allows third-party access to naloxone. Pharmacists can dispense naloxone without a prescription under the statewide standing order (effective since September 6, 2017)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access", "url": "https://nebraskalegislature.gov/FloorDocs/108/PDF/CS/LB1355.pdf", "description": "Nebraska LB1325 allows pharmacists to sell fentanyl test strips for testing. Nebraska has legalized the distribution and possession of fentanyl test strips, with pharmacies and local public health departments authorized to distribute them."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboards", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Public-Data-Dashboards.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS public data dashboards page. Includes overdose prevention and treatment resource mapping across all 93 counties, showing no-cost naloxone availability, drug take-back sites, MOUD providers, and treatment or recovery services."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Response Recovery Services", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/State-Opioid-Response.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS State Opioid Response page. The Division of Behavioral Health is working to increase peer support education and training for those working with people with addiction in treatment and recovery. DBH supports medication-assisted treatment and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Division of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/behavioral-health.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS Division of Behavioral Health homepage. Designated single state mental health and substance use disorder authority. Manages prevention, treatment, care, and rehabilitation programs. Nebraska behavioral health resources are organized into six regional units."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Behavioral Health Regions", "url": "https://www.nebraskahospitals.org/quality_and_safety/nha-opioid-toolkit/nebraska-substance-abuse-continuum/ndhhs-division-of-behavioral-health.html", "description": "Nebraska Hospital Association page with map of Nebraska's six Behavioral Health Regions and contact information for each region. Regions provide comprehensive mental health and substance use prevention, treatment, rehabilitation, and recovery services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHHS Behavioral Health Trainings", "url": "https://dhhs-dbhtraining.unl.edu/", "description": "Nebraska DHHS behavioral health trainings portal produced in partnership with the University of Nebraska Public Policy Center. Includes training resources for peer support specialists and behavioral health professionals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services - 988 Lifeline", "url": "https://988lifeline.org/", "description": "Call or text 988 for 24/7 crisis support. Nebraska has seen steady increases in calls to 988, connecting people to counselors for mental health, substance use, and other crises. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline serves Nebraska residents."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Board of Pharmacy (DHHS Licensure)", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/licensure/pages/pharmacist.aspx", "description": "Nebraska does not have a standalone Board of Pharmacy. Pharmacy regulation is handled by the DHHS Licensure Unit. Address: Nebraska State Office Building, 301 Centennial Mall South, 3rd Floor, Lincoln, NE 68508. NABP contact: https://nabp.pharmacy/bop_members/nebraska/"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Medicaid Pharmacy", "url": "https://nebraska.fhsc.com/PDL/PDLlistings.asp", "description": "Nebraska Medicaid pharmacy program managed through First Health Services Corporation. For pharmacy prior authorization and PDL questions, contact the program through the Medicaid provider website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Division of Behavioral Health (State Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/behavioral-health.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS Division of Behavioral Health serves as the state opioid treatment authority. Oversees substance use disorder treatment services, state opioid response grants, and behavioral health regional system."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.npharm.org/", "description": "Nebraska Pharmacists Association (NPA). CEO: Haley Pertzborn. Phone: (402) 420-1500. Address: 6221 S 58th Street, Suite A, Lincoln, NE 68516. Provides advocacy, education, and professional support for Nebraska pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska DHHS Opioid Program", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/State-Opioid-Response.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS State Opioid Response program. The Division of Behavioral Health has received federal opioid grants since 2017 to support prevention, treatment, and recovery programs statewide."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DHHS Public Data Dashboards", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Public-Data-Dashboards.aspx", "description": "Nebraska DHHS public data dashboards including the overdose prevention and treatment resources dashboard, which maps naloxone availability, drug take-back sites, MOUD providers, and treatment services across all 93 Nebraska counties."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nonfatal Opioid Overdose Surveillance Report", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Reports/Nonfatal%20Opioid-Involved%20Overdose%20Five-Year%20Surveillance%20Report%20-%202019-2023.pdf", "description": "Nebraska DHHS Nonfatal Opioid-Involved Overdose Five-Year Surveillance Report (2019-2023). Includes EMS data on suspected nonfatal opioid overdoses, trend analysis, and demographic breakdowns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "EMS Opioid Overdose Surveillance", "url": "https://dhhs.ne.gov/Reports/EMS%20Opioid%20Overdose%20Five-Year%20Surveillance%20Report%202017-2022.pdf", "description": "Nebraska DHHS EMS Opioid Overdose Five-Year Surveillance Report (2017-2022). Includes nonfatal opioid-involved overdose rates by race, county-level data, and trend analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Coalition Strategic Initiative Reports", "url": "https://ago.nebraska.gov/sites/default/files/doc/Strategic%20Initiatives%20Update%202020.pdf", "description": "Nebraska Coalition to Prevent Opioid Abuse Strategic Initiatives Update (2020). Comprehensive report covering treatment access, buprenorphine prescriber training, PDMP utilization, and opioid data trends in Nebraska."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Opioid Settlement Reporting", "url": "https://ago.nebraska.gov/nebraska-opioid-settlement-remediation-advisory-committee", "description": "Nebraska Attorney General's Opioid Settlement Remediation Advisory Committee page. Tracks settlement fund allocation and expenditures under the Opioid Prevention and Treatment Act (LB1124). Includes ongoing reporting on how settlement funds are being used for treatment and prevention."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.npharm.org/", "description": "Nebraska Pharmacists Association website. NPA advocates for pharmacy issues at the Nebraska Legislature, provides education, and connects pharmacy professionals. Every dollar of membership supports advocacy efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Legislature Website", "url": "https://nebraskalegislature.gov/", "description": "Nebraska Legislature (Unicameral) official website. Nebraska has a unique unicameral (single-chamber) legislature. Find current bills, legislative documents, and senator information. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Legislator Lookup", "url": "https://nebraskalegislature.gov/", "description": "Use the Nebraska Legislature website to find your state senator. Nebraska's unicameral legislature has 49 senators. Contact information and district maps are available through the official website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Coalition to Prevent Opioid Misuse", "url": "https://ago.nebraska.gov/nebraska-coalition-prevent-opioid-abuse-strategic-initiative-report", "description": "The Nebraska Coalition to Prevent Opioid Abuse (now Opioid Misuse) is a multi-agency coalition led by the Nebraska Attorney General's office. Partners include DHHS, UNMC, law enforcement, and other stakeholders. The coalition coordinates statewide opioid prevention, treatment, and education efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nebraska Opioid Prevention and Treatment Act", "url": "https://ago.nebraska.gov/nebraska-opioid-settlement-remediation-advisory-committee", "description": "Information on Nebraska's Opioid Prevention and Treatment Act (LB1124, passed 2020), which established the Opioid Recovery Fund for dedicated opioid treatment and prevention revenue. The Attorney General's office administers settlement fund distribution through the Opioid Settlement Remediation Advisory Committee."}]}]}, "nevada": {"name": "Nevada", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nAs of January 1, 2024, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nevada law includes “assessing a patient and prescribing and dispensing a drug for medication-assisted treatment in accordance with NRS [§] 639.28079.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(l) (West 2024).\nThe referenced Nevada law defined “medication-assisted treatment” (MAT) as “treatment for an [OUD] using medication approved by [FDA] for that purpose.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079(3) (West 2024).\nUnder Nevada’s controlled substances statutes, as of January 1, 2024, a “practitioner” includes “pharmacist who is registered pursuant to [§] 639.28079 to prescribe and dispense drugs for medication-assisted treatment.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 453.126(9) (West 2024). This allows the registered pharmacist to obtain a state controlled substance registration, and thus a DEA mid-level practitioner registration.\nAlthough the 2024 law change pre-dates DEA’s latest published information (dated November 2024) about mid-level practitioner registration, DEA’s information continues to indicate that a registered pharmacist in Nevada cannot obtain that registration.", "1B": "Register with the Nevada Board of Pharmacy to prescribe and dispense an MAT drug. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079(1) (West 2024).\nAssess the patient to determine if the patient has OUD and if MAT is appropriate. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079(1)(a) (West 2024).\nAdhere to additional requirements specified in both law and regulation. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079 (West 2024); NEV. ADMIN. CODE Ch. 639, R059-23, §§ 2 to 7 (2024).187", "1C": null, "2A": "As described in the information below, Nevada laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nAs of January 1, 2024, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nevada law includes “assessing a patient and prescribing and dispensing a drug for [MAT] in accordance with NRS [§] 639.28079.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(l) (West 2024). Although this provision expressly provides for “prescribing” and “dispensing” MAT drugs, it does not expressly refer to “administering.”\nThe referenced section also does not expressly refer to “administering,” only that a pharmacist can “prescribe and dispense a drug for [MAT].” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079 (West 2024).\nMoreover, other aspects of the definition of the practice of pharmacy use the word “administering” in addition to prescribing and dispensing, such as the authorization for pharmacist “prescribing, dispensing and administering” HIV prevention drugs and medication. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(j) (West 2024). Given this, the fact that “administering” does not appear in the provision related to pharmacist prescribing MAT may be an intentional omission by the legislature.\nIn contrast, however, the definition of “dispense” in Nevada pharmacy law means “to deliver a controlled substance or dangerous drug to an ultimate user, patient or subject of research by or pursuant to the lawful order of a practitioner, including the . . . administering . . .necessary to prepare the substance for that delivery.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0065(1) (West 2024). This suggests that dispensing an MAT drug may include administering it.", "2B": "Register with the Nevada Board of Pharmacy to prescribe and dispense an MAT drug. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079(1) (West 2024).\nAssess the patient to determine if the patient has OUD and if MAT is appropriate. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079(1)(a) (West 2024).Adhere to additional requirements specified in both law and regulation. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079 (West 2024); NEV. ADMIN. CODE Ch. 639, R059-23, §§ 2 to 7 (2024).188", "2C": "Expand the Nevada practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nevada law expressly authorizes “ordering and conducting laboratory tests necessary for therapy that uses [HIV prevention] drugs.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(j) (West 2024).\nOtherwise, the only other express provision in Nevada pharmacy laws related to lab tests is that a pharmacist can order lab tests pursuant to a CPA. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(i) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Nevada practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "As described in the information below, Nevada laws do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nevada law expressly authorizes “implementation and modification of drug therapy . . . in accordance with a [CPA].” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(i) (West 2024).\nA CPA is an agreement that allows a pharmacist “to engage in the collaborative practice of pharmacy or collaborative drug therapy management [CDTM]” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0052 (West 2024).\nCDTM means “initiating, monitoring, modifying or discontinuing” a patient’s drug therapy in accordance with a CPA. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0051 (West 2024).\nAlthough this provision uses the phrase “initiating, monitoring, modifying” it does not expressly refer to “prescribing.”\nNevada law governing the scope of CPAs does not expressly address whether the types of decisions a pharmacist can make as part of CDTM include prescribing.\nHowever, a CPA “must not grant a pharmacist the authority to engage in an activity that is outside the scope of the current practice of the practitioner concerning the management of drug therapy.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.2623(5) (West 2024). The implication of this provision is that a CPA may authorize a pharmacist to perform an activity within the pharmacist’s scope of practice.\nAs a result, Nevada law does not expressly provide that a pharmacist can prescribe drugs or medications under a CPA. However, given the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section that pharmacists who register with the Nevada Board of Pharmacy (and adhere to other requirements) can prescribe MAT, the most logical answer to this question is that the same authority applies under a CPA.", "4B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": null, "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nevada law expressly includes “administering drugs . . . in accordance with a [CPA]” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(i) (West 2024).\nNevada pharmacy law governing CPAs do not place any express limitations on the types of drugs or medications that a pharmacist can administer under a CPA.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Nevada law expressly includes “ordering and performing tests in accordance with a [CPA]” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0124(1)(i) (West 2024). This provision does not expressly refer to evaluating lab tests.\nNevada laws governing CPAs do not expressly refer to evaluating the results of tests only the administering tests and notifying patients of the results of the test. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.2623(6)(e)(1) (West 2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Nevada laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a CPA includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Under Nevada law, a CPA is “an agreement that meets the requirements of [§] 639.2627 between one or more pharmacists and one or more practitioners which authorizes a pharmacist to engage in the collaborative practice of pharmacy or [CDTM].” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0052 (West 2024).\n“Practitioner” includes a physician, dentist, veterinarian, podiatric physician, advanced practice registered nurse with prescribing authority, physician assistant with prescribing authority, optometrist, dental hygienist with prescribing authority, certified registered nurse anesthetist with prescribing authority, hospital, and pharmacy. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.0125 (West 2024).\nThe following Nevada laws provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 639.2623 to 639.2629 (West 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nNevada’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law authorizes a licensed “provider of health care” to provide telehealth with the provider’s scope of practice and standard of care. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 629.515 (West 2024).\n“Provider of health care” means an individual “licensed, certified or otherwise authorized by the laws of [Nevada] to administer health care in the ordinary course of the business or practice of a profession.” NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 439.820 (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.\nNevada pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "Nevada laws and regulations governing telehealth include – NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 629.510 to 629.515 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 422.2721 (West 2024) (Medicaid); NEV. REV. STAT. ANN §§ 639.01535 to 639.0154 (West 2024) (definitions - pharmacy); NEV. REV. STAT. ANN § 639.0727 (West 2024)\n(telepharmacy); NEV. REV. STAT. ANN §§ 689A.0463, 689B.0369, 689C.195, 695A.265, 695B.1904, 695C.1708\n(West 2024) (health insurance); NEV. ADMIN. CODE § 458.267 (2024) (SUD treatment providers); NEV. ADMIN. CODE §§ 639.391 to 639.399 (2024) (telepharmacy).", "9A": "As of January 1, 2024 all public and private health plans, Medicaid and Medicaid managed care organizations, and health plans for state and local government employees must reimburse a pharmacist or pharmacy for the services allowed in NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079 (West 2024)—assessing and counseling patients / prescribing and dispensing MAT drugs—at a rate equal to the rate of reimbursement provided to a physician, physician assistant or advanced practice registered nurse for similar services. This directive appears in the various sections of the code related to each type of health insurance coverage. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 422.27237, 689A.0459, 689B.0319, 689C.1665, 695A.1874, 695B.19197, 695C.1699, 695G.1719 (West 2024).\nIn addition, there is a Medicaid “provider type” code for pharmacists in Nevada. As of 2024, there are over 40 approved billing procedure codes for pharmacist services.", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "In order to “prescribe and dispense a drug for [MAT],” a pharmacist must register with the Nevada Board of Pharmacy and adhere to additional requirements specified in both law and regulation. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. § 639.28079 (West 2024); NEV. ADMIN. CODE Ch. 639, R059-23, §§ 2 to 7 (2024).191\nA practitioner working in hospital or emergency department, including a pharmacist, may dispense an FDA-approved drug for OUD without registering at each site of practice as long as the practitioner has a controlled substances certificate. NEV. ADMIN. CODE § 639.7421 (2024).", "10B": "Nevada law establishes certain duties and obligations related to MAT that physicians, physician assistants, osteopathic physicians, osteopathic assistants, and advanced practice registered nurses must meet/adhere to when diagnosing a patient with OUD. NEV. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 630.3737, 632.2383, 633.6947 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://bop.nv.gov/", "description": "Nevada State Board of Pharmacy official website. Provides information on licensing, applications, regulations, PMP, and board meetings. Note: The site may block some automated access; if the main URL does not load, try https://bop.nv.gov/Board/BoardMtgs/ for board information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Pharmacy Practice Act (NRS Chapter 639)", "url": "https://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-639.html", "description": "Full text of Nevada Revised Statutes Chapter 639, Pharmacists and Pharmacy. Includes definitions, licensing requirements, Board composition, disciplinary actions, collaborative practice provisions, and controlled substance regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NRS Chapter 639 on Justia", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/nevada/chapter-639/", "description": "Searchable version of Nevada Revised Statutes Chapter 639 covering all sections of the pharmacy practice act, including recent amendments. Includes pharmacist registration, scope of practice, and prescription drug provisions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Requirements", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/nevada/chapter-639/statute-639-2627/", "description": "NRS 639.2627 governing collaborative practice agreement requirements. A collaborative practice agreement must include a description of drug therapy management decisions the pharmacist is authorized to make, diseases and drugs covered, and conditions and limitations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Authority", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/nevada/chapter-639/statute-639-2623/", "description": "NRS 639.2623 governing authority and requirements to enter into collaborative practice agreements. Nevada allows pharmacists to engage in collaborative pharmacy practice and collaborative drug therapy management with prescribers. Patients are not required to obtain a referral before a pharmacist may engage in collaborative practice."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Opioid Response", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Nevada State Opioid Response comprehensive resource hub. Includes maps for naloxone dispensing locations, fentanyl test strip distribution locations, behavioral health provider directories, and crisis support information. Tracks naloxone kits dispensed and reported overdose reversals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Opioid Center of Excellence (NOCE)", "url": "https://nvopioidcoe.org/resources/practitioners/", "description": "Nevada Opioid Center of Excellence practitioner resources page. Provides evidence-informed training and resources for practitioners treating opioid use disorder, including MOUD basics, video testimonials, and clinical guidance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator that can be filtered to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in Nevada, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada DPBH State Opioid Response Program", "url": "https://www.dpbh.nv.gov/programs/bh-wellness-and-prevention-bbhwp/sor/", "description": "Nevada Division of Public and Behavioral Health State Opioid Response (SOR) program page. SOR funds prevention, treatment, and recovery efforts across Nevada to expand access to treatment for OUD and prevent opioid misuse and overdose."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Telehealth Prescribing", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on federal buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing rules. Under the finalized HHS/DEA rule, patients can start and receive up to a 6-month supply of buprenorphine through telephone or audio-visual telehealth consultations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Medicaid Pharmacy Page (DHCFP)", "url": "https://dhcfp.nv.gov/Pgms/CPT/Pharmacy/", "description": "Nevada Division of Health Care Financing and Policy (DHCFP) Medicaid pharmacy page. Nevada Medicaid reimburses pharmacies and practitioners for FDA-approved prescriptions and certain OTC drugs dispensed to Medicaid recipients. Some drugs may require prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.medicaid.nv.gov/Downloads/provider/NV_PDL_20220103.pdf", "description": "Nevada Medicaid and Nevada Check Up Preferred Drug List (PDL). Includes coverage information for buprenorphine products. For the most current PDL, check the Nevada Medicaid provider portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Medicaid Provider Portal", "url": "https://www.medicaid.nv.gov/", "description": "Nevada Medicaid and Nevada Check Up Provider Web Portal. Healthcare providers can access information on enrollment, recipient eligibility, prior authorization, billing instructions, pharmacy news, and training opportunities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Medicaid Pharmacy Manual", "url": "https://www.medicaid.nv.gov/Downloads/provider/NV_Pharmacy_Manual.pdf", "description": "Nevada Medicaid and Nevada Check Up Pharmacy Manual with detailed billing procedures, reimbursement policies, and covered pharmacy services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Opioid Settlement Spending", "url": "https://nashp.org/state-tracker/state-opioid-settlement-spending-decisions/nevada/", "description": "National Academy for State Health Policy (NASHP) tracker for Nevada opioid settlement spending decisions. The Advisory Committee for a Resilient Nevada publishes biennial reports on strategically awarding settlement funding across gaps in substance use services."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/nevada/", "description": "Overview of Nevada pharmacist continuing education requirements. Pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE every two years to maintain licensure. One hour of approved Nevada pharmacy law CE is required per renewal cycle."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Board of Pharmacy Controlled Substance Registration", "url": "https://bop.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/bopnvgov/content/Services/newapps/Pharmacist%20CS%20Application%2004.24.2024.pdf", "description": "Nevada Board of Pharmacy pharmacist controlled substance registration application. Includes requirements related to OUD assessment and medication-assisted treatment prescribing obligations for prescribers with DEA registration."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Opioid Center of Excellence Training", "url": "https://nvopioidcoe.org/resources/practitioners/", "description": "Nevada Opioid Center of Excellence practitioner resources. Provides evidence-informed training on MOUD, including buprenorphine prescribing, rural implementation, and co-occurring mental health conditions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirements", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/pubs/docs/mate_training.html", "description": "DEA page on Medication Access and Training Expansion (MATE) Act requirements. All medical registrants must attest to completing an 8-hour training on treating patients with opioid and other substance use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training Resources", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free buprenorphine training, modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring for healthcare practitioners on evidence-based OUD treatment practices."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Opioid Response Harm Reduction Resources", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Nevada State Opioid Response website with maps showing naloxone dispensing locations, fentanyl test strip distribution locations, and behavioral health providers across the state. Includes information on syringe services programs (Trac B in Southern Nevada provides SSP and fentanyl test strip distribution)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Naloxone Access", "url": "https://www.safeproject.us/naloxone/state-rules/", "description": "SAFE Project naloxone state rules page. Nevada law allows any individual pharmacist or chain pharmacy with a standing order from the Department of Health to dispense naloxone to anyone without a prescription. Education training is required for dispensing pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Good Samaritan Drug Overdose Act", "url": "https://www.leg.state.nv.us/nrs/NRS-453C.html", "description": "Nevada NRS Chapter 453C, Good Samaritan Drug Overdose Act. Provides legal protections for those who assist in drug overdose emergencies. Also authorizes dispensing of opioid antagonists without charge under certain conditions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Nevada supports fentanyl test strip distribution. The Nevada State Opioid Response website includes a map of fentanyl test strip distribution locations. Nevada has legalized fentanyl test strips through harm reduction legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NV Opioid Dashboard", "url": "https://opioid.snhd.org/", "description": "Southern Nevada Health District (SNHD) opioid surveillance dashboard. Provides data on emergency department visits, inpatient discharges, prescription drug trends (from PDMP data), and overdose death statistics for Southern Nevada (Clark County). In 2023, 692 drug overdose deaths were reported in Clark County, with opioids accounting for 68.1%."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Opioid Response Recovery Services", "url": "https://nvopioidcoe.org/opioid-response-framework/sor/", "description": "Nevada Opioid Center of Excellence SOR page. Includes information on recovery housing (a housing model providing substance use specific services, peer support, and design features supporting recovery), peer support services, and treatment resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health Provider Directory", "url": "https://behavioralhealthnv.org/", "description": "Behavioral Health NV, a database of behavioral health providers specializing in substance use disorder and co-occurring mental health disorder treatment services. All listed agencies are certified by the Division of Public and Behavioral Health (BHCEN certified)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Division of Public and Behavioral Health", "url": "https://www.dpbh.nv.gov/", "description": "Nevada Division of Public and Behavioral Health (DPBH) homepage. Mission is to protect, promote, and improve physical and behavioral health of Nevadans. Main office: 4150 Technology Way, Carson City. Hours: 8am-5pm, Monday-Friday."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DPBH Programs Directory", "url": "https://www.dpbh.nv.gov/programs/", "description": "Nevada DPBH programs directory listing all division programs dedicated to improving health and wellness, including behavioral health, substance use, prevention, and treatment programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services - 988 Lifeline", "url": "https://988lifeline.org/", "description": "Call or text 988 for 24/7 crisis support for mental health, substance use, or suicidal crises. Nevada residents are connected to trained crisis counselors through the national 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://bop.nv.gov/", "description": "Nevada State Board of Pharmacy. NABP page: https://nabp.pharmacy/bop_members/nevada/. PMP contact: PMPAdmin@pharmacy.nv.gov. The Board regulates pharmacists, pharmacies, and controlled substances in Nevada."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Medicaid (DHCFP)", "url": "https://dhcfp.nv.gov/Pgms/CPT/Pharmacy/", "description": "Nevada Division of Health Care Financing and Policy (DHCFP) Medicaid pharmacy program. Administers pharmacy benefit reimbursement for Medicaid recipients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada DPBH (State Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://www.dpbh.nv.gov/", "description": "Nevada Division of Public and Behavioral Health serves as the state authority for substance use disorder treatment and behavioral health services. Main office: 4150 Technology Way, Carson City, NV."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Pharmacy Alliance", "url": "https://nevadapharmacyalliance.com/", "description": "Nevada Pharmacy Alliance, an APhA affiliate and Nevada's pharmacist association. Provides advocacy and resources for Nevada pharmacy professionals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Opioid Response", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Nevada State Opioid Response website managed by CASAT (Center for the Application of Substance Abuse Technologies) at the University of Nevada, Reno, on behalf of DPBH. Central hub for opioid prevention, treatment, and recovery resources."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NV Opioid Dashboard (Southern Nevada)", "url": "https://opioid.snhd.org/", "description": "Southern Nevada Health District interactive opioid surveillance dashboard. Monitors short and long-term goals of Nevada's Prescription Drug Overdose Prevention program. Includes data on deaths, ED visits, hospitalizations, and PDMP prescription trends with crude and age-adjusted rates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data to Action Program", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/initiatives/od2a/", "description": "Nevada's Overdose Data to Action (OD2A) program page. Supports the state in getting high-quality, comprehensive, and timelier data on opioid prescribing and mortality to inform prevention and intervention efforts. Now located on the Nevada Opioid Center of Excellence website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Opioid Crisis Needs Assessment", "url": "https://www.nvopioidresponse.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/nevada-opioid-crisis-needs-assessment-3.21.19.pdf", "description": "Nevada Opioid Crisis Needs Assessment (2018) including data on opioid prescribing trends, overdose deaths, treatment access gaps, and key legislation. Provides baseline data for state opioid response planning."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Opioid Response Data", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Nevada State Opioid Response homepage tracks naloxone kits dispensed, reported overdose reversals using naloxone, and kits distributed to first responders. Provides real-time metrics on harm reduction activities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Opioid Settlement Reporting", "url": "https://nashp.org/state-tracker/state-opioid-settlement-spending-decisions/nevada/", "description": "NASHP tracker for Nevada opioid settlement spending decisions. The Advisory Committee for a Resilient Nevada publishes biennial reports on settlement fund allocation aligned with the Nevada DHHS Opioid Needs Assessment and Statewide Plan."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Pharmacy Alliance", "url": "https://nevadapharmacyalliance.com/", "description": "Nevada Pharmacy Alliance website, the state's pharmacist association and APhA affiliate. Provides advocacy resources and information on pharmacy practice issues in Nevada."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Pharmacist Association (NvPha)", "url": "https://nvpha.com/", "description": "Nevada Pharmacist Association website with updates on state and national pharmacy issues, legislation, and professional resources for Nevada pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Legislature - Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://www.leg.state.nv.us/whosmylegislator/", "description": "Nevada State Legislature \"Who's My Legislator\" tool with interactive district maps to find your state senator and assembly member by address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada Legislature Research Library", "url": "https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Division/Research/Library/FAQ/WhichLegislatorRepresents.html", "description": "Nevada Legislature Research Library page with options to find legislators by address, city, or district. Includes links to the legislator database and district information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Nevada State Opioid Response Initiatives", "url": "https://nvopioidresponse.org/initiatives/opioid-response/", "description": "Nevada State Opioid Response initiatives page describing state-funded treatment and recovery centers, prevention programs, and recovery support services. Includes information on the Advisory Committee for a Resilient Nevada and how opioid settlement funds are being directed to address service gaps."}]}]}, "newhampshire": {"name": "New Hampshire", "q": {"CPA_Term": "New Hampshire’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXVII) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Hampshire law does not expressly include prescribing any drugs or medications. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XIV) (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in New Hampshire cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the New Hampshire practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow New Hampshire pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, New Hampshire laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Hampshire law includes “the administration . . . of drugs and devices.” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XIV) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, while there are New Hampshire laws and regulations expressly covering the administration of vaccines, including training necessary to do it, there are no provisions expressly addressing administration of other kinds of drugs or medications, including controlled substances. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:16-b (West 2024).If the general “administration . . . of drugs and devices” phrase in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions in law or regulation. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in New Hampshire may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.", "2B": "Understand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the New Hampshire practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Hampshire law expressly includes “the initiating, ordering, administering, and analyzing of FDA approved Emergency Use Authorization SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) point-of-care diagnostic kits (COVID-19 tests or test kits) to detect SARS-CoV-2 or its antibodies.” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XIV) (West 2024).\nNew Hampshire pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address ordering or evaluating any other types of lab tests outside of a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement (CPPA).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the New Hampshire practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Hampshire law includes “medication therapy management in accordance with collaborative pharmacy practice agreements” (CPPAs). N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XIV) (West 2024).\n“Medication therapy management” includes “implementing, modifying, and managing medication therapy” pursuant to a CPPA. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXVIII)(a) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “implementing, modifying, and managing,” it does not expressly refer to “prescribing.”\nIn addition, New Hampshire laws and regulations governing CPPAs do not account for the fact that a New Hampshire pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPPA provides.\nIn summary, New Hampshire laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CPPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a New Hampshire pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise New Hampshire laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPAs with practitioners.\nExpressly specify in New Hampshire laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow New Hampshire pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, New Hampshire laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Hampshire law includes “medication therapy management in accordance with [CPPAs].” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XIV) (West 2024).\n“Medication therapy management” includes “implementing, modifying, and managing medication therapy” pursuant to a CPA. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXVIII)(a) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “implementing, modifying, and managing,” it does not expressly refer to “administering.”\nNeither the definition of medication therapy management nor New Hampshire regulations governing CPPAs expressly address whether a pharmacist’s authority under a CPPA can include administering drugs or medications.\nIn summary, although New Hampshire pharmacy law does not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine under a CPPA it also does not clearly authorize it, and a pharmacist’s general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CPPA is also unclear.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly provide in New Hampshire law and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authorized activities under a CPPA include administering drugs and medications, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering lab tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Hampshire law includes “medication therapy management in accordance with [CPPAs].” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XIV) (West 2024). “Medication therapy management” expressly includes “ordering laboratory tests as specifically set out in the [CPA] that are specific to the medication or protocol-driven.” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXVIII)(d) (West 2024).\nNew Hampshire laws and regulations governing CPPAs do not expressly address evaluating lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in New Hampshire laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a CPPA includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "“Collaborative pharmacy practice” means the practice of pharmacy whereby “one or more pharmacists jointly agree, on a voluntary basis, to work in conjunction with one or more attending practitioners” under a CPPA. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXVI) (West 2024).\nA CPPA is “a written and signed specific agreement between a pharmacist and an attending practitioner, that provides for collaborative pharmacy practice for the purpose of medication therapy management.” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXVII) (West 2024).\n“Attending practitioner” means a physician or advanced practice registered nurse with the primary responsibility for the treatment and care of the patient. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. § 318:1(XXV) (West 2024).\nDespite the definition of “attending practitioner,” New Hampshire law specific to CPPAs provides that “any practitioner with prescriptive authority who holds an active, unrestricted license in the state of New Hampshire” may enter into a CPPA. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 318:16-a(II) (West 2024).\nPharmacists cannot delegate activities under a CPA. N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Ph. 1105.02(a) (2024).\nThe following New Hampshire laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPPAs and required elements of CPPAs – N.H. REV. STAT. ANN. §§ 318:1(XXVIII)(a), 318:16-a (West 2024);\nN.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Ph. 1101.01 to 1105.04 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nNew Hampshire’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that “individuals licensed, certified, or registered pursuant to [specific New Hampshire code sections] may provide services through telemedicine or telehealth, provided the services rendered are authorized by scope of practice.” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 310:7(II) (West 2024).\nOne of the 23 code sections specified is “RSA 318,” which is the code section covering pharmacy and pharmacists.\nN.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 310:7(II) (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "The general rule is that controlled substances cannot be prescribed via telehealth. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 318-B:2(XII-f) (West 2024). However, there are exceptions for physicians and certain licensed nurses. N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 318-B:2(XVI) (West 2024).\nNew Hampshire laws and regulations governing telehealth include – N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 310-7 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 167:4-d (West 2024) (Medicaid); N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 318:47-j (West 2024) (Medicaid - pharmacy); N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 318-B:2(XII-f), (XVI) (West 2024) (controlled substances); N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 329:1-d (West 2024) (physicians); N.H. REV. STAT. ANN §§ 415-J:1 to 415-J:3\n(West 2024) (insurance); N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. He-C 5004.01 to 5004.13 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "New Hampshire law governing Medicaid provides that “pharmacists shall be considered providers under RSA 126-A:3, III [provider billing] for the purpose of billing for providing services performed within the scope of a person’s license when said service would have been covered under this section if furnished by a physician or as an incident to a physician’s service, or furnished by a physician assistant or an advanced registered nurse practitioner.” N.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 126-A:3(III-a)(a) (West 2024).\nHowever, in terms of actual billable services, researchers conclude that “pharmacist reimbursement is specific to nicotine cessation therapy services and level 1 evaluation/management (E/M) codes for billing services under a standing order or CPA” and that the “Medicaid program currently covers tobacco cessation counseling services exclusively for pregnant women.”", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status, in terms of actual billable services, under the New Hampshire Medicaid program.\nSpecify in New Hampshire laws and/or regulations that all collaborative pharmacy practice services provided under a CPPA are covered under the New Hampshire Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Any minor 12 years of age or older may voluntarily submit to SUD treatment by different types of service providers, including “any licensed physician or advanced practice registered nurse practicing within such nurse practitioner’s specialty” without the consent of a parent or guardian.\nN.H. REV. STAT. ANN § 318-B:12-a (West 2024).\nSeveral New Hampshire regulations direct that “licensees who prescribe medication assisted treatment shall adhere to the principles outlined in the American Society of Addiction Medicine’s National Practice Guideline For the Use of Medications in the Treatment of Addiction Involving Opioid Use (2015) found at http://www.asam.org/quality-practice/guidelines-and-consensus-documents/npg/complete-guideline as cited in Appendix II.” N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Den 503.07 (2024) (dentists); N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Med 502.07 (2024) (physicians); N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Nat 501.07 (2024)\n(naturopathic treatment); N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Nur 502.07 (2024) (nursing); N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Opt 504.07 (2024) (optometry); N.H. CODE ADMIN. R. Pod 502.07 (2024) (podiatry)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.oplc.nh.gov/board-pharmacy", "description": "New Hampshire Board of Pharmacy, under the Office of Professional Licensure and Certification (OPLC). The Board monitors the practice of pharmacy through inspections, investigations, licensure, and regulation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (RSA 318)", "url": "https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/NHTOC/NHTOC-XXX-318.htm", "description": "Table of contents for RSA Chapter 318, Pharmacists and Pharmacies, the New Hampshire Pharmacy Practice Act. Full text of all sections is accessible from this page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act Full Text", "url": "https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/xxx/318/318-mrg.htm", "description": "Merged full text of RSA Chapter 318, covering all sections of the New Hampshire Pharmacy Practice Act, including collaborative practice standards at Section 318:16-a."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://www.oplc.nh.gov/board-pharmacy-laws-and-rules", "description": "Board of Pharmacy laws and rules page, including RSA 318 (Pharmacists and Pharmacies), RSA 318-B (Controlled Drug Act), and Chapters Ph 100-2600 administrative rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute (RSA 318:16-a)", "url": "https://gc.nh.gov/rsa/html/xxx/318/318-mrg.htm", "description": "RSA 318:16-a establishes standards for collaborative pharmacy practice in New Hampshire. A pharmacist must hold an unrestricted and current license, and any practitioner with prescriptive authority may enter into a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement. Note: CPAs explicitly prohibit giving a pharmacist authority to prescribe a controlled substance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: New Hampshire does not grant independent prescribing authority to pharmacists for controlled substances. Pharmacists may practice under collaborative practice agreements (RSA 318:16-a), but these agreements cannot authorize controlled substance prescribing."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NH Substance Misuse Treatment Services", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/health-care/substance-misuse-treatment-services", "description": "NH DHHS page covering the treatment system in New Hampshire, including information on buprenorphine, methadone, naltrexone, and links to medication-assisted treatment resources. Includes standing orders for dispensing opioid antagonist agents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator, which can be filtered by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in New Hampshire."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA tool to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, searchable by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Opioid Treatment Program Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/locators/opioid-treatment-program-directory", "description": "Directory of certified opioid treatment programs (OTPs), searchable by state. Also contains information on state opioid treatment authorities."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023 (MATE Act), all practitioners with a current DEA registration including Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD if permitted by applicable state law. New Hampshire follows these federal requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS resource on prescribing controlled substances via telehealth. A DEA-registered practitioner can prescribe Schedule II-V controlled substances, including buprenorphine, via telemedicine if required conditions are met. New Hampshire follows federal telehealth prescribing guidelines."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NH Medicaid Pharmacy Benefit Management", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/medicaid/medicaid-pharmacy-benefit-management", "description": "NH DHHS Medicaid pharmacy benefit program page. Prime Therapeutics serves as the Pharmacy Benefit Administrator for NH Medicaid. The Preferred Drug List (PDL) is available on the Prime website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Medicaid Fee for Service", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/medicaid/medicaid-fee-service", "description": "Information on Medicaid Fee for Service, a benefits pathway for individuals not enrolled in Medicaid Care Management, with provider enrollment details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH MMIS Provider Portal (Fee Schedules)", "url": "https://nhmmis.nh.gov/portals/wps/portal/DocumentsandForms", "description": "New Hampshire Medicaid Management Information System portal with documents, forms, fee schedules, and provider manuals."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Medicaid Preferred Drug List and Prior Authorization: The NH Medicaid Preferred Drug List is maintained by Prime Therapeutics. NH Healthy Families and WellSense Health Plan are managed care organizations administering Medicaid benefits, each with their own PDL guidance. Some buprenorphine products may require prior authorization depending on the plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants provide resources to states for increasing access to medications for OUD, supporting prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery support services. New Hampshire has received SOR grant funding."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Education and Training", "url": "https://www.oplc.nh.gov/board-pharmacy-education-and-training", "description": "NH Board of Pharmacy education and training resources, including study materials for NAPLEX and New Hampshire MPJE exams."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CE Requirements for Controlled Substances", "url": "https://www.oplc.nh.gov/board-medicine-opioid-prescribing", "description": "Pursuant to RSA 126-A:97, all practitioners with a DEA license number must complete 3 contact hours of board-approved online continuing education in opioid prescribing. For immediate assistance with addiction, call the NH Statewide Addiction Crisis Line at 1-844-711-HELP (4357)."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirement: Under the Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023 (MATE Act), all DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of their DEA registration or renewal. This applies to all practitioners in New Hampshire."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free training modules, webinars, and clinical tools on buprenorphine and OUD treatment, including MATE Act-compliant training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "New Hampshire Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.nhpharmacists.net/", "description": "NH Pharmacists Association (NHPA) website with events, continuing education opportunities, and news for New Hampshire pharmacy professionals."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs Directory", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/disease-prevention/infectious-disease-control/syringe-services-programs-new", "description": "NH DHHS page listing syringe services programs (SSPs) across the state. SSPs provide sterile supplies, safe syringe disposal, naloxone, support, and referrals to treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Harm Reduction Coalition SSP Directory", "url": "https://www.nhhrc.org/nhssps", "description": "New Hampshire Harm Reduction Coalition directory of the 13 registered syringe service programs in the state. These programs provide sterile supplies, safe syringe disposal, naloxone, and referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/sites/g/files/ehbemt476/files/documents2/standing-order-opioid-antagonist.pdf", "description": "The NH DHHS standing order authorizing any licensed pharmacist in New Hampshire to dispense naloxone or nalmefene to any person at risk of opioid overdose or their family members, friends, or others who may assist at-risk individuals."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips are legal in New Hampshire. In 2023, NH Laws Ch. 186 (H.B. 287) exempted fentanyl test strips, xylazine test strips, and other drug-checking materials from the drug paraphernalia definition. Additional legislation (HB 226/HB 470) has been pursued to further expand drug-checking equipment access."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/health-care/substance-misuse-data-page", "description": "NH DHHS substance misuse data page, including the NH Drug Monitoring Initiative (DMI) with month-to-month trend analysis of drug overdose deaths using data from various sources."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Support Services", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/health-care/recovery-support-services", "description": "NH DHHS page on peer recovery support services and recovery community organizations (RCOs), which are peer-led and peer-run agencies offering services to support people in recovery from substance misuse."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Agencies", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/mental-health/peer-support-agencies", "description": "Directory of peer support agencies in New Hampshire providing face-to-face and telephone peer support, outreach, daily programming, support groups, wellness training, warm line services, and crisis respite."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/health-care/recovery-housing", "description": "NH DHHS page with resources for individuals seeking recovery houses, information for operators on certification and registration, and complaint filing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Coalition of Recovery Residences (NHCORR)", "url": "https://www.nhcorr.org/", "description": "NHCORR is committed to building strong recovery communities, eliminating barriers to recovery-supportive housing, and promoting best practice standards for New Hampshire's alcohol and drug-free homes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Division for Behavioral Health", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/about-dhhs/dhhs-organization", "description": "NH DHHS organizational page showing the Division for Behavioral Health, which includes the Bureau for Children's Behavioral Health, Bureau of Drug and Alcohol Services (BDAS), Bureau of Mental Health Services, and Bureau of Homeless Services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis and Warmline Contacts: NH Statewide Addiction Crisis Line: 1-844-711-HELP (4357). Also available via email at hope@keystonehall.org. The NH Rapid Response Access Point (NHRRAP) at https://nh988.com/ provides 24/7 access to mental health and substance use crisis support via telephone, text, and chat services. National 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is also available by dialing 988."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NH Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.oplc.nh.gov/board-pharmacy", "description": "NH Board of Pharmacy, Office of Professional Licensure and Certification, 7 Eagle Square, Concord, NH 03301. Contact the OPLC for Board of Pharmacy inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH DHHS Medicaid", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/medicaid", "description": "NH DHHS Medicaid Division, overseeing Medicaid pharmacy benefits and managed care organizations including NH Healthy Families and WellSense Health Plan."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/locators/opioid-treatment-program-directory", "description": "The NH state opioid treatment authority is within the NH DHHS Division for Behavioral Health, Bureau of Drug and Alcohol Services (BDAS). Contact DHHS for specific OTA inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.nhpharmacists.net/", "description": "New Hampshire Pharmacists Association (NHPA), 373 South Willow Street D1-1, Suite 165, Manchester, NH. NHPA advocates for pharmacy practice in New Hampshire."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH DHHS Health Department OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/health-care/substance-misuse-treatment-services", "description": "NH DHHS substance misuse treatment services page, the primary state health department resource for OUD programs, treatment system information, and standing orders for opioid antagonist agents."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Substance Misuse Data Page", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/programs-services/health-care/substance-misuse-data-page", "description": "NH DHHS substance misuse data page containing the Drug Monitoring Initiative (DMI) with month-to-month trend analysis of drug overdose deaths and related data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Fatality Review Commission Report", "url": "https://www.dhhs.nh.gov/sites/g/files/ehbemt476/files/documents2/overdose-fatality-review-commission-annual-report-2024.pdf", "description": "Annual report of the New Hampshire Drug Overdose Fatality Review Commission with demographic data on overdose deaths and drug overdose information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC Provisional Drug Overdose Data", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nvss/vsrr/drug-overdose-data.htm", "description": "CDC provisional drug overdose death counts, updated monthly, with state-level data including New Hampshire. Shows trends and percent changes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Center for Excellence on Addiction", "url": "https://nhcenterforexcellence.org/", "description": "The Center for Excellence on Addiction at JSI Research and Training Institute provides data, technical assistance, and support to communities addressing addiction in New Hampshire. Supports the Governor's Commission on Alcohol and Other Drugs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "County-Level and Treatment Data: Treatment gap analyses and county-level data for New Hampshire are available through the NH DHHS substance misuse data page and the Center for Excellence on Addiction resources. SAMHSA's National Survey on Drug Use and Health (NSDUH) also provides state-level estimates."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NH General Court (Legislature)", "url": "https://gencourt.state.nh.us/", "description": "The New Hampshire General Court website. Use the \"Who's My Legislator\" tool to find and contact your state representatives and senators. Quick links include Contact a Representative and Contact a Senator."}, {"type": "link", "title": "New Futures (OUD Advocacy)", "url": "https://new-futures.org/Drug-Checking-Equipment", "description": "New Futures is a New Hampshire advocacy organization working on health-related policy including substance use disorder. They track and advocate for legislation related to drug-checking equipment, OUD treatment access, and harm reduction."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NH Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.nhpharmacists.net/", "description": "NHPA, through its membership with NASPA (National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations), participates in national advocacy efforts. The association advocates for pharmacist professional interests and public health in New Hampshire."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Governor's Commission on Addiction, Treatment, and Prevention", "url": "https://nhcenterforexcellence.org/governors-commission/", "description": "The NH Governor's Commission on Addiction, Treatment, and Prevention serves in an advisory capacity to the governor and general court on prevention, treatment, and recovery services. It includes task forces on opioids, prevention, treatment, recovery, healthcare, and data."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA Model Legislation: The National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA), ASHP, and NCPA provide model legislation and policy templates that may be relevant to New Hampshire pharmacy practice expansion. Contact NHPA for state-specific advocacy priorities and model legislation resources."}]}]}, "newjersey": {"name": "New Jersey", "q": {"CPA_Term": "New Jersey’s term for a CPA is a “protocol” for collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM). N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Jersey law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in New Jersey cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the New Jersey practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow New Jersey pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Jersey law expressly refers to “administering and distributing drugs.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).\nHowever, the definition of “administer” in New Jersey law specifies that it is done “by a pharmacist engaged in collaborative practice or in accordance with regulations jointly promulgated by” the New Jersey Board of Pharmacy and New Jersey State Board of Medical Examiners.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).\nFurther, New Jersey law governing pharmacist administration indicates that the only administrations pharmacists can perform outside of a protocol or collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM) are for “vaccinations and related emergency medications” and immunizations. N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-63 (West 2024).", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the New Jersey practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Jersey law includes “ordering clinical tests, excluding laboratory tests, unless those tests are part of collaborative drug therapy management.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).\nNew Jersey pharmacy law does not define the term “clinical test,” but based on context such tests are something other than laboratory tests and based on part of the definition of CDTM, the term may refer to CLIA-waived tests. N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the New Jersey practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Jersey law expressly allows for CDTM “including modifying, continuing or discontinuing drug or device therapy.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “modifying” and “continuing,” it does not expressly refer to “prescribing.”\nNew Jersey laws and regulations governing CDTM also do not expressly authorize prescribing drugs or medications. Moreover, New Jersey laws and regulations governing CDTM do not account for the fact that a New Jersey pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol for CDTM provides.\nIn summary, New Jersey laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CDTM protocol. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a New Jersey pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise New Jersey laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CDTM protocols.\nExpressly specify in New Jersey laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under protocols.\nAllow New Jersey pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Jersey law expressly allows for CDTM “including modifying, continuing or discontinuing drug or device therapy.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “modifying” and “continuing,” it does not expressly refer to “administering.”\nNew Jersey laws and regulations governing CDTM also do not expressly authorize administering drugs or medications.\nHowever, the definition of the word “administer” in New Jersey pharmacy law provides that administration can occur “by a pharmacist engaged in collaborative practice.”\nN.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024). Moreover, New Jersey law governing pharmacist administration indicates that the administration can occur “for the treatment of that disease for which the medication is prescribed or indicated or for which the collaborative drug therapy management permits.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-63(a) (West 2024).", "5B": "Enter into a CDTM protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly provide in New Jersey laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authorized activities under a CDTM protocol include administering drugs and medications, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the extent of the authorization is unclear and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Jersey law allows for CDTM, which includes both the “ordering or performing of laboratory tests based on the standing orders of a physician as set forth in the written protocol” and the “ordering of clinical tests based on the standing orders of a physician as set forth in the written protocol, provided those laboratory tests are [CLIA-waived].” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).\nNew Jersey regulation governing CDTM further notes that the ordering or performing of laboratory tests based on the standing orders of a physician as set forth in written collaborative practice protocols only allows the pharmacist to perform CLIA-waived tests. N.J. ADMIN. CODE § 13:39-13.7(b)-(c) (2024).\nMoreover, “the interpretation of clinical or laboratory tests under a written collaborative practice protocol shall be performed by a pharmacist only in direct consultation with a physician.” N.J. ADMIN. CODE § 13:39-13.7(d) (2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CDTM protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in New Jersey laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a protocol for CDTM includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine", "7": "CDTM involves a “written protocol directed on a voluntary basis” that is “between a patient’s physician who is treating the patient for a specific disease and a pharmacist.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:14-41 (West 2024).\nThe following New Jersey laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CDTM and required elements of CDTM protocols – N.J. STAT. ANN. §§ 45:14-61 to 45:14-62 (West 2024); N.J. ADMIN. CODE §§ 13:39-13.1 to 13:39-13.9 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nNew Jersey’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law allows a “health care provider” to provide health care services via telehealth. N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:1-62 (West 2024).\nThe definition of “health care provider” includes any “health care professional acting within the scope of a valid license or certification issued pursuant to Title 45 of the Revised Statutes.” N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:1-61 (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "Prescriptions for schedule II controlled substances through telemedicine or telehealth are only allowed after an initial in-person exam, except in certain specified situations. N.J. STAT. ANN. § 45:1-62(e) (West 2024).\nNew Jersey laws and regulations governing telehealth include – N.J. STAT. ANN. §§ 45:1-61 to 45:1-66 (West 2024) (telemedicine generally); N.J. STAT. ANN. § 30:4D-6k (West 2024) (Medicaid); N.J. STAT. ANN §§ 52:14-17.29w, 52:14-17.46.6h (West 2024) (health insurance);\nN.J. ADMIN. CODE §§ 8:53–1.1 to 8:53-3.2 (2024)\n(registration); N.J. ADMIN. CODE §§ 13:35–6b.1 to 13:35-6b.9 (2024) (physicians); N.J. ADMIN. CODE §§ 13:37–8a.1 to 13:37-8a.9 (2024) (nursing).", "9A": "New Jersey Medicaid program information indicates that “effective for claims with service dates on or after July 1, 2024, the NJ FamilyCare FFS Program will reimburse pharmacies an additional administration fee . . . for providing education and consultation related self-administered hormonal contraceptives.”", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the New Jersey Medicaid program.\nSpecify in New Jersey laws and/or regulations that all CDTM services provided under a protocol are covered under the New Jersey Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "New Jersey law allows a “mobile intensive care paramedic” (a defined profession) to administer buprenorphine following “emergency administration of an opioid antidote” (i.e., an overdose reversal agent) if certain conditions are met. N.J. STAT. ANN. § 26:2K-71 (West 2024).\nNew Jersey regulations contain “buprenorphine guidelines” as part of the standards for licensure of outpatient SUD treatment facilities. N.J. ADMIN. CODE. § 10:161b App. B (2024). Similar guidelines exist for inpatient SUD treatment facilities, too."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.njconsumeraffairs.gov/phar", "description": "New Jersey Board of Pharmacy, under the Division of Consumer Affairs. Anthony Rubinaccio serves as Executive Director. P.O. Box 45013, Newark, NJ 07101. The Board was established in 1877 to protect the public by regulating the dispensing of prescription medications. Please verify this link before publishing (site uses WAF protection)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (N.J.S.A. 45:14-40 et seq.)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/new-jersey/title-45/section-45-14-40/", "description": "New Jersey Pharmacy Practice Act beginning at N.J.S.A. 45:14-40, declaring the practice of pharmacy a matter of public interest and requiring that only qualified persons practice pharmacy in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/providers/rulefees/regs/rulesfiles/NJAC%2010_51%20PHARMACEUTICAL%20SERVICES%20MANUAL.PDF", "description": "N.J.A.C. 10:51 Pharmaceutical Services Manual, covering New Jersey administrative rules for pharmaceutical services including Medicaid provider requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement", "url": "https://www.njconsumeraffairs.gov/phar/Applications/Collaborative-Practice-Pre-Approval-Application.pdf", "description": "NJ Board of Pharmacy collaborative practice pre-approval application. Pharmacists must be approved by the Board to enter into collaborative practice agreements with physicians for patient drug therapy management. N.J.A.C. 13:35-6.27 establishes standards for collaborative practice. Please verify this link before publishing (site uses WAF protection)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Regulation", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/new-jersey/N-J-A-C-13-35-6-27", "description": "N.J.A.C. 13:35-6.27, Standards for collaborative practice for drug therapy management with licensed pharmacists. Requires informed patient consent and defines scope of pharmacist drug therapy management under a collaborative agreement."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: New Jersey does not currently grant independent prescribing authority to pharmacists for controlled substances. Pharmacists may participate in collaborative drug therapy management agreements with physicians under N.J.A.C. 13:35-6.27."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator, which can be filtered by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in New Jersey."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA tool to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, searchable by state including New Jersey."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ DMHAS (State Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/dmhas/home/", "description": "New Jersey Division of Mental Health and Addiction Services (DMHAS) serves as the Single State Agency (SSA) for Substance Use and the State Mental Health Authority. DMHAS oversees opioid treatment programs in New Jersey."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ReachNJ Treatment Helpline", "url": "https://reachnj.gov/", "description": "ReachNJ (1-844-ReachNJ / 1-844-732-2465) is a central call-in line for New Jersey residents seeking help with substance use disorders. Calls are answered by live trained staff who screen callers, provide referrals, and connect to local treatment providers regardless of insurance status."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (Consolidated Appropriations Act of 2023), all practitioners with a current DEA registration including Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. New Jersey follows federal requirements. NJ also has specific opioid prescribing guidance through the Division of Consumer Affairs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS resource on prescribing controlled substances via telehealth. New Jersey allows telehealth prescribing of buprenorphine consistent with federal guidelines and state telemedicine regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NJ FamilyCare Medicaid Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://fm.formularynavigator.com/FBO/4/New_Jersey_PDL_English.pdf", "description": "New Jersey Medicaid-approved Preferred Drug List (PDL), effective January 1, 2026. Lists preferred medications by therapeutic class including buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Medicaid Pharmaceutical Services Manual", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/providers/rulefees/regs/rulesfiles/NJAC%2010_51%20PHARMACEUTICAL%20SERVICES%20MANUAL.PDF", "description": "N.J.A.C. 10:51 Pharmaceutical Services Manual covering basis of payment for prescription drugs, provider requirements, and Medicaid pharmacy benefit rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ MMIS Provider Portal", "url": "https://www.njmmis.com/", "description": "New Jersey Medicaid Management Information System portal for providers, including enrollment, claims, and fee schedule information."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Medicaid Managed Care Pharmacy Benefits: NJ FamilyCare Medicaid is administered through managed care organizations including Aetna Better Health, Wellpoint (formerly Amerigroup), UnitedHealthcare Community Plan, and Fidelis Care. Each MCO maintains its own formulary based on the state PDL. Buprenorphine products are generally covered with some requiring prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants provide resources to states including New Jersey for increasing access to medications for OUD, supporting prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery support services."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NJ Opioid Prescribing Requirements", "url": "https://www.njconsumeraffairs.gov/dcu/Documents/Prescribing-Opioids-in-NJ.pdf", "description": "NJ Division of Consumer Affairs guide on prescribing opioids in New Jersey, including PDMP query requirements, prescription limitations, and continuing education requirements. Please verify this link before publishing (site uses WAF protection)."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DEA MATE Act Training Requirement: Under the MATE Act, all DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of their DEA registration or renewal. This applies to all practitioners in New Jersey."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free training modules, webinars, and clinical tools on buprenorphine and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://njpharmacists.org/", "description": "New Jersey Pharmacists Association (NJPhA) website. Established in 1870, NJPhA advances the profession of pharmacy and provides continuing education opportunities for New Jersey pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Addiction Professionals Certification Board", "url": "https://certbd.org/applications/certified-peer-recovery-specialist/", "description": "The Addiction Professionals Certification Board of New Jersey offers certification for peer recovery specialists and other addiction professionals, including substance use disorder training programs."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Access Programs", "url": "https://njharmreduction.org/syringe-access/", "description": "NJ Harm Reduction Coalition directory of syringe access programs (called Harm Reduction Centers in NJ). These programs provide sterile syringes, naloxone, connections to SUD treatment, healthcare services, and community care for people who use drugs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://njharmreduction.org/naloxone-access/", "description": "NJ Harm Reduction Coalition page on naloxone access. Governor Murphy signed legislation in July 2021 (P.L.2021, c.152, Overdose Prevention Act) expanding the naloxone standing order, enabling licensed pharmacists to dispense any FDA-approved form of naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Naloxone Direct Program", "url": "https://dmhas.dhs.state.nj.us/NDP", "description": "NJ Department of Human Services naloxone distribution program providing eligible agencies in New Jersey a means to obtain and distribute naloxone (nasal Narcan) under the standing order issued by the Deputy Commissioner for Public Health Services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips are legal in New Jersey. Legislation excludes fentanyl test strips (FTS) from the definition of drug paraphernalia under N.J.S.2C:36-1. In January 2024, Governor Murphy signed additional legislation to further expand access to harm reduction supplies including fentanyl test strips."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/health/populationhealth/opioid/", "description": "NJ Department of Health overdose data dashboard, including near real-time unconfirmed overdose deaths from the Office of the Chief State Medical Examiner, naloxone administrations, drug-related hospital visits, prescription data, and treatment data."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NJ DMHAS Peer Recovery Services", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/dmhas/resources/services/recovery/peer_recovery.html", "description": "NJ Division of Mental Health and Addiction Services peer recovery support services page. Peer recovery support services are designed and provided by individuals with practical experience in the recovery process."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Peer Network (NJPN)", "url": "https://www.njpn.org/peer-recovery", "description": "NJ Peer Network provides peer recovery support services including certifications, trainings, and programs for peer recovery specialists in New Jersey."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: New Jersey recovery housing is overseen by the Division of Mental Health and Addiction Services (DMHAS). For recovery housing resources, contact DMHAS or search through the SAMHSA treatment locator at https://findtreatment.gov/locator."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ DMHAS (Behavioral Health Agency)", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/dmhas/", "description": "NJ Division of Mental Health and Addiction Services serves as the Single State Agency for Substance Use and the State Mental Health Authority. DMHAS provides crisis services, treatment, and recovery support."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis and Warmline Contacts: ReachNJ: 1-844-ReachNJ (1-844-732-2465) for substance use disorder treatment referrals. NJ 988 Mobile Crisis Outreach Response Team provides 24/7 response for mental health and substance use crises. MHANJ Peer Recovery Warmline: 1-877-292-5588 (Mon-Fri 8am-10pm, Sat-Sun 5pm-10pm, Holidays 3pm-10pm)."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NJ Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.njconsumeraffairs.gov/phar", "description": "New Jersey Board of Pharmacy, Division of Consumer Affairs. Executive Director: Anthony Rubinaccio. P.O. Box 45013, Newark, NJ 07101, 124 Halsey Street, Newark, NJ."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Medicaid/NJ FamilyCare", "url": "https://www.njmmis.com/", "description": "NJ Medicaid Management Information System (NJMMIS) provider portal. NJ FamilyCare is the state's Medicaid program, managed through the Division of Medical Assistance and Health Services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (DMHAS)", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/dmhas/home/about/", "description": "NJ DMHAS serves as the Single State Agency for Substance Abuse and the State Mental Health Authority as designated by SAMHSA. Contact DMHAS for opioid treatment authority inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://njpharmacists.org/advocacy/advocacy-and-legislation/", "description": "NJPhA advocacy and legislation page. NJPhA maintains an active political presence in the state capitol to represent pharmacists in New Jersey."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Department of Health OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/health/populationhealth/opioid/", "description": "NJ Department of Health population health opioid resources including the overdose data dashboard, SUDORS data, and substance use treatment information."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/health/populationhealth/opioid/", "description": "NJ Department of Health overdose data dashboard with near real-time unconfirmed overdose deaths, naloxone administrations, drug-related hospital visits, prescription monitoring data, and treatment utilization data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SUDORS Overdose Mortality Data Explorer", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/health/populationhealth/opioid/sudors.shtml", "description": "NJ State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS) data explorer dashboard displaying drug overdose data with county-level detail."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Monitoring Program Data", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/health/populationhealth/opioid/opioid_pmp.shtml", "description": "NJ Department of Health page with prescription monitoring data visualizations from the NJPMP."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use Treatment Data", "url": "https://www.nj.gov/health/populationhealth/opioid/opioid_njsams.shtml", "description": "NJ Department of Health substance use treatment data, including treatment admissions and utilization statistics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC Provisional Drug Overdose Data", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nvss/vsrr/drug-overdose-data.htm", "description": "CDC provisional drug overdose death counts with state-level data including New Jersey, updated monthly."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NJ Legislature - Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://www.njleg.state.nj.us/members/legsearch.asp", "description": "New Jersey Legislature tool to find your state legislators by district, with contact information for senators and assembly members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJ Legislature Homepage", "url": "https://njleg.state.nj.us/", "description": "NJ Legislature homepage with access to bills, legislative schedules, and legislative roster. Toll-free: 800-792-8630."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NJPhA Advocacy", "url": "https://njpharmacists.org/advocacy/advocacy-and-legislation/", "description": "NJ Pharmacists Association advocacy and legislation page. NJPhA monitors legislative discussions and represents pharmacists' interests in the state capitol."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SaveNJRx Coalition", "url": "https://savenjrx.org/", "description": "SaveNJRx is a joint advocacy effort among multiple pharmacy organizations in New Jersey including NJPhA, Garden State Pharmacy Owners, IAPS, IPA, and others, advocating for pharmacy-related policy."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NJ Governor's Commission / Facing Addiction Task Force: The NJ Facing Addiction Task Force works to address substance use disorder in New Jersey. For task force information, contact the Division of Mental Health and Addiction Services (DMHAS) at https://www.nj.gov/humanservices/dmhas/."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA Model Legislation: The National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA), ASHP, and NCPA provide model legislation and policy templates that may be relevant to New Jersey pharmacy practice. Contact NJPhA for state-specific advocacy priorities."}]}]}, "newmexico": {"name": "New Mexico", "q": {"CPA_Term": "New Mexico’s term for a CPA is a written “guideline” or “protocol” for dangerous drug therapy (DDT). N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11B-2(D) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Mexico law expressly includes “the administering or prescribing of dangerous drug therapy, devices or supplies for prescribed drug therapy for health conditions, including diabetes.” N.M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(CC) (West 2024).\nHowever, the prescriptive authority granted to a pharmacist with respect to dangerous drug therapy (DDT) requires that the pharmacist obtain special training, to become what is termed a “pharmacist clinician,” as well as enter into a written protocol with a physician authorized to prescribe controlled substances. N. M. STAT. ANN. §§ 61-11B-2 to 61-11B-3 (West 2024). As a result, a pharmacist cannot prescribe buprenorphine without such DDT protocol in place.\nDEA information last updated in November 2024 indicates that registered pharmacists in New Mexico can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Administer & Prescribe” controlled substances. However, based on a review of New Mexico pharmacy laws and regulations, this appears to only apply to pharmacist clinicians operating under a DDT protocol.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the New Mexico practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment, outside of a written protocol with a physician. \nAllow all pharmacists, and not just pharmacists operating under a protocol with a physician, to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below The definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Mexico law expressly includes “the administering or prescribing of [DDT], devices or supplies for prescribed drug therapy for health conditions, including diabetes.” N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(CC) (West 2024).\nUnder New Mexico law, a “dangerous drug” means a prescription drug. N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(G) (West 2024).\nThere are no additional New Mexico laws or regulations directly addressing the administration of any drugs or medications by pharmacists.\nThe definition of “administer” in New Mexico law expressly states the administration must be “as a result of an order of a licensed practitioner.” N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(A) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain the order of a licensed practitioner.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Mexico law expressly includes “the ordering, performing and interpreting” of CLIA-waived tests. N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(CC) (West 2024).\nIn addition, although not part of the practice of pharmacy definition, a pharmacist may “order, test, screen, treat and provide preventative services” for certain specified health conditions including influenza, group A streptococcus pharyngitis, SARS-COV-2, “uncomplicated urinary tract infection,” and HIV. N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-30 (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the New Mexico practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the pharmacist must be a pharmacist clinician.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Mexico law expressly includes “the administering or prescribing of [DDT], devices or supplies for prescribed drug therapy for health conditions, including diabetes.” N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(CC) (West 2024).\nFor purposes of DDT, New Mexico law grants “prescriptive authority” to a “pharmacist clinician” acting pursuant to written guidelines or a protocol that are established and approved by a practitioner. N. M. STAT. ANN. §§ 61-11B-1 to 61-11B-3 (West 2024).\n“Prescriptive authority” means “the authority to prescribe, administer, monitor or modify [DDT].” N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.7(Y) (2024).\nNew Mexico regulation provides that a pharmacist clinician may prescribe controlled substances provided that the pharmacist clinician: (1) obtains a New Mexico controlled substances registration; (2) obtains a DEA registration; and (3) prescribes controlled substances within the parameters of written guidelines or protocols established under New Mexico’s pharmacist prescriptive authority act. N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.17(E) (2024).", "4B": "Obtain certification as a pharmacist clinician from the New Mexico Board of Pharmacy (see the CPA procedures and requirements section). \nEnter into a guideline or protocol for DDT (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": null, "5A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the pharmacist must be a pharmacist clinician.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New Mexico law expressly includes “the administering or prescribing of [DDT], devices or supplies for prescribed drug therapy for health conditions, including diabetes.” N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(CC) (West 2024).\nFor purposes of DDT, New Mexico law grants “prescriptive authority” to a pharmacist clinician acting pursuant to written guidelines or a protocol that are established and approved by a practitioner. N. M. STAT. ANN. §§ 61-11B-1 to 61-11B-3 (West 2024).\n“Prescriptive authority” means “the authority to prescribe, administer, monitor or modify [DDT].” N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.7(Y) (2024).\nUnder New Mexico laws and regulations, a “dangerous drug” means a prescription drug. N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(G) (West 2024).", "5B": "Obtain certification as a pharmacist clinician from the New Mexico Board of Pharmacy (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nEnter into a guideline or protocol for DDT (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the pharmacist must be a pharmacist clinician.\nNew Mexico regulation defines the “practice of pharmacy” to include “monitoring dangerous drug therapy.” N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.7(W)(6) (2024).\n“Monitoring dangerous drug therapy,” which is done by a pharmacist clinician, includes “ordering and evaluating the results of laboratory tests relating to dangerous drug therapy, including blood chemistries and cell counts, controlled substance therapy levels, blood, urine, tissue or other body fluids, culture and sensitivity tests when performed in accordance with guidelines or protocols applicable to the practice setting.” N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.7(P)(3) (2024). \nUnder New Mexico laws and regulations, a “dangerous drug” means a prescription drug. N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-11-2(G) (West 2024).\"", "6B": "Obtain certification as a pharmacist clinician from the New Mexico Board of Pharmacy (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nEnter into a guideline or protocol for DDT (see the CPA procedures and requirements section). \nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "Under New Mexico prescriptive authority laws and regulations, “guidelines or protocol” means a written agreement between a pharmacist clinician or group of pharmacist clinicians and a physician or group of physicians that delegates prescriptive authority. N.M. CODE R.§ 16.19.4.7(M) (2024).\n“Pharmacist clinician” means “a pharmacist with additional training required by regulations adopted by the [pharmacy] board in consultation with the New Mexico medical board and the New Mexico academy of physician assistants, who exercises prescriptive authority in accordance with guidelines or protocol.” N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.7(U) (2024). Additional information about how to become a pharmacist clinician is found in regulation. N.M. CODE R. § 16.19.4.17(B) (2024).\nThe following New Mexico laws and regulations provide more information about DDT, requirements for entering DDT protocols, and required elements of protocols – N. M. STAT. ANN. §§ 61-11B-1 to 61-11B-3 (West 2024); N.M. CODE R. §§ 16.19.4.7, 16.19.4.17 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nNew Mexico’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that the delivery of health care via telehealth is “recognized and encouraged” and “no health care provider or operator of an originating site shall be disciplined for or discouraged from participating in telehealth.” N. M. STAT. ANN. § 24-25-4 (West 2024).\n“Health care provider,” for purposes of the general telehealth/telemedicine law, expressly includes pharmacists. N. M. STAT. ANN. § 24-25-3(A)(19) (West 2024).\nNew Mexico pharmacy laws and regulation do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "New Mexico laws and regulations governing telehealth include – N. M. STAT. ANN. §§ 24-25-1 to 24-25-5 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 13-7-14 (West 2024) (health care purchasing); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 59A-22-49.3 (West 2024) (health insurance contracts); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 59A-23-7.12 (West 2024) (group and blanket insurance contracts); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 59A-46-50.3 (West 2024) (health maintenance organizations); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 59A-47-45.3 (West 2024) (non-profit health care plans); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 61-6-11.1 (West 2024) (telemedicine license – physicians); N.M. CODE R. §§ 8.308.9.18, 8.310.2.12(M), 8.310.3.9 to 8.310.3.11 (2024) (Medicaid); N.M. CODE R. § 16.10.2.11 (2024) (telemedicine license – physicians); N.M. CODE R. §§ 16.19.33.1 to 16.19.33.9 (2024) (telepharmacy).", "9A": "All types of health insurers, including the New Mexico Medicaid program, must reimburse pharmacist clinicians and other pharmacists with prescriptive authority at an equivalent rate as other health care providers, such as physicians, physician assistants, and nurse practitioners, when the same clinical services are provided within the pharmacist’s scope of practice. The relevant statutory provisions are: N. M. STAT. ANN. § 13-7-23 (West 2024) (health care purchasing); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 27-2-12.30 (West 2024) (Medicaid); N. M. STAT.ANN § 59A-22-53.2 (West 2024) (health insurance contracts); N. M. STAT. ANN. § 59A-23-12.2 (West 2024)\n(group and blanket health insurance contracts); N. M. STAT. ANN § 59A-46-52.2 (West 2024) (health maintenance organizations); N. M. STAT. ANN § 59A-47-47.2 (West 2024) (non-profit health care plans).\nThe statutory provisions also apply to mandate reimbursement to pharmacists who are not pharmacist clinicians, at least as to the much more limited prescriptive and testing services such pharmacists can provide (e.g., hormonal contraception, tobacco cessation, immunizations, naloxone, tuberculosis testing, HIV PrEP/PEP, and testing and treating for influenza, group A streptococcus, COVID-19, urinary tract infections).", "9B": "Allow all pharmacists, and not just pharmacist clinicians to have “full provider” status under the New Mexico Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.rld.nm.gov/boards-and-commissions/individual-boards-and-commissions/pharmacy/", "description": "New Mexico Board of Pharmacy, under the Regulation and Licensing Department (RLD). Address: 5500 San Antonio Dr. NE Suite C, Albuquerque, NM 87109. Business hours: Mon-Fri 8am-5pm MST. The Board regulates pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, pharmacist interns, pharmacies, hospitals, and other facilities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Rules and Laws", "url": "https://www.rld.nm.gov/boards-and-commissions/individual-boards-and-commissions/pharmacy/pharmacy-rules-and-laws/", "description": "NM Board of Pharmacy rules and laws page, including the Pharmacy Act (NMSA Chapter 61, Article 11), Drug Device and Cosmetic Act, Controlled Substance Act, Drug Precursor Act, and Drug Product Selection Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (NMSA Chapter 61, Article 11)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/new-mexico/chapter-61/article-11/section-61-11-6/", "description": "NMSA Section 61-11-6, Powers and duties of the Board of Pharmacy, including authority to promulgate rules for pharmaceutical care, drug regimen review, patient counseling, and collaborative practice protocols."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority (Article 11B): New Mexico has pharmacist prescriptive authority statutes under NMSA Chapter 61, Article 11B. This allows pharmacists to prescribe certain medications under protocols approved by the Board of Pharmacy, the Medical Board, and the Board of Nursing. New Mexico pharmacists have prescriptive authority for contraception, naloxone, and other dangerous drugs under approved protocols. However, controlled substance prescribing (such as buprenorphine) is not included in pharmacist prescriptive authority."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice: Under NMSA 61-11-6, the Board may promulgate rules and protocols for prescribing of dangerous drug therapy after approval by the NM Medical Board and Board of Nursing. Collaborative practice agreements enable pharmacists to manage drug therapy in partnership with physicians."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM Buprenorphine Treatment Guidelines", "url": "https://www.rld.nm.gov/uploads/FileLinks/a5bdc4c0017d4bf294dd2cbfea6f294e/NM_Buprenorphine_Guidelines_2012.pdf", "description": "New Mexico treatment guidelines for medical providers who treat opioid addiction using buprenorphine-containing medications, including guidance for nurses, recovery coaches, counselors, pharmacists, and administrators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator, filterable by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in New Mexico."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA tool to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, searchable by state including New Mexico."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Health Care Authority BHSD", "url": "https://www.hca.nm.gov/about_the_department/behavioral_health_services_division/", "description": "New Mexico Health Care Authority, Behavioral Health Services Division (BHSD), directed by Nick Boukas. BHSD oversees the state's behavioral health system including substance use disorder treatment. Contact: P.O. Box 2348, Santa Fe, NM 87504, (505) 476-9266."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act, all practitioners with a current DEA registration including Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. New Mexico follows these federal requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS resource on prescribing controlled substances via telehealth. New Mexico allows telehealth prescribing consistent with federal guidelines."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM Medicaid Buprenorphine Coverage", "url": "https://www.asam.org/docs/default-source/advocacy/state-medicaid-reports/state-medicaid-reports_nm.pdf?sfvrsn=6", "description": "ASAM report on New Mexico Medicaid coverage of medications for OUD. NM Medicaid covers Suboxone, buprenorphine/naloxone tablets, and buprenorphine tablets under both fee-for-service and managed care plans, on the preferred drug list, and covered for use in accredited outpatient narcotic treatment programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NM Centennial Care (Medicaid Managed Care): New Mexico's Medicaid program (Centennial Care) is administered through managed care organizations including Blue Cross Blue Shield of New Mexico and Western Sky Community Care. Each MCO maintains a preferred drug list. Buprenorphine products are generally covered."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Medicaid Drug Lists", "url": "https://www.bcbsnm.com/provider/pharmacy/pharmacy-program/medicaid", "description": "Blue Cross Blue Shield of New Mexico Medicaid drug list page, including information about generics, preauthorization, specialty pharmacy, step therapy, OTC products, and dispensing limits."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Medicaid Fee Schedules and Provider Information: Fee schedules and provider manuals for NM Medicaid are available through the state's Medicaid portal. Contact the NM Health Care Authority for pharmacist-specific billing codes and fee schedules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants available to states including New Mexico for OUD treatment, prevention, harm reduction, and recovery support services. NM also receives funding through the NM Prevention program and CDC Overdose Data to Action grants."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM Board of Pharmacy Education", "url": "https://www.rld.nm.gov/boards-and-commissions/individual-boards-and-commissions/pharmacy/", "description": "NM Board of Pharmacy homepage with information on licensure requirements, continuing education, and training for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Pharmacists Association Training", "url": "https://www.nmpharmacy.org/", "description": "New Mexico Pharmacists Association (NMPhA) website offering continuing education events including pharmacist prescriptive authority training courses (Test-to-Treat, contraception, UTI certification), Mid-Winter meetings, and naloxone resources."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DEA MATE Act Training: Under the MATE Act, all DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders for DEA registration or renewal. This applies to all practitioners in New Mexico."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free training modules, webinars, and clinical tools on buprenorphine and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Safety and Prescribing", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/about/erd/ibeb/pos/ospr/", "description": "NM Department of Health opioid safety resources, including information on naloxone dispensing by pharmacists. Pharmacist prescriptive authority is not needed to dispense naloxone under the statewide standing order."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Program", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/about/phd/idb/hrp/", "description": "NM Department of Health Harm Reduction Program providing syringe services, naloxone distribution, fentanyl and xylazine test strip distribution, home delivery supply services, overdose prevention training, community health referrals, and assistance with food, treatment, clothing, and housing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/publication/view/regulation/2126/", "description": "New Mexico statewide standing order for registered pharmacists authorizing dispensing of naloxone products to individuals at risk of opioid overdose. Multiple naloxone formulations may be dispensed based on availability."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: NM Department of Health operates syringe services programs through the Hepatitis and Harm Reduction Program. For SSP locations and services, visit https://www.nmhealth.org/about/phd/idb/hrp/"}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Fentanyl test strips are legal in New Mexico. The Legislature amended the Harm Reduction Act in 2022, modifying the drug paraphernalia exemption to include \"drug testing strips,\" expanding the definition to cover fentanyl and xylazine testing and adding civil protections for distribution of testing strips."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/about/erd/ibeb/sap/", "description": "NM Department of Health Substance Use Epidemiology Section (SUES), which collects and analyzes data on substance use including alcohol-related deaths, drug overdose deaths, and naloxone distribution. Results are shared with community groups, policy makers, and stakeholders."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM BHSD (Behavioral Health Services Division)", "url": "https://www.hca.nm.gov/about_the_department/behavioral_health_services_division/", "description": "NM Health Care Authority Behavioral Health Services Division (BHSD) oversees the state's behavioral health system including peer support, recovery services, and housing programs. Includes Certified Peer Support Worker (CPSW) training and Supportive Housing Endorsement programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Peer Recovery Support Workers: New Mexico certifies Peer Support Workers (PSWs) who are individuals successful in their own SUD recovery who help others through shared understanding and mutual empowerment. BHSD coordinates CPSW training programs and specialized training tracks (Forensic Peer Recovery, Pregnancy/Post-Partum)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "New Mexico Recovery Coalition", "url": "https://sharenm.org/new-mexico-recovery-coalition/support-linkages-program", "description": "NM Recovery Coalition Support Linkages Program providing case management, crisis intervention, skill-building, therapy, medication management, peer support, housing assistance, and advocacy."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Recovery housing resources in New Mexico are coordinated through the BHSD and local community organizations. Contact BHSD at (505) 476-9266 for recovery housing referrals and information."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis and Warmline Contacts: 988 New Mexico (call, text, or chat 988) provides 24/7 free and confidential support for emotional, mental, or substance use concerns through the BHSD. More information at https://988nm.org/. National SAMHSA Helpline: 1-800-662-4357."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.rld.nm.gov/boards-and-commissions/individual-boards-and-commissions/pharmacy/", "description": "New Mexico Board of Pharmacy, Regulation and Licensing Department. 5500 San Antonio Dr. NE Suite C, Albuquerque, NM 87109. Phone: Contact through RLD website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Health Care Authority (Medicaid)", "url": "https://www.hca.nm.gov/", "description": "New Mexico Health Care Authority oversees Medicaid (Centennial Care), including pharmacy benefits and behavioral health services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM BHSD (Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://www.hca.nm.gov/about_the_department/behavioral_health_services_division/", "description": "NM Behavioral Health Services Division, Director Nick Boukas. P.O. Box 2348, Santa Fe, NM 87504. Phone: (505) 476-9266. BHSD serves as the state authority for substance use disorder treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.nmpharmacy.org/", "description": "New Mexico Pharmacists Association (NMPhA), committed to serving pharmacists and patients in New Mexico. Offers advocacy, education, and networking resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Department of Health OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/about/erd/ibeb/pos/ospr/", "description": "NM Department of Health opioid safety and overdose prevention resources, including standing orders for naloxone and harm reduction program information."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM-IBIS Substance Use Data", "url": "https://ibis.doh.nm.gov/topic/healthstatus/SubstanceUse.html", "description": "New Mexico Indicator-Based Information System (NM-IBIS) substance use data page with mortality data on alcohol- and drug-induced deaths, drug overdoses, and related health indicators. Includes county-level data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use Epidemiology", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/about/erd/ibeb/sap/", "description": "NM Department of Health Substance Use Epidemiology Section (SUES) collects and analyzes substance use data including alcohol-related deaths, drug overdose deaths, and naloxone distribution data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use and Mental Health Epidemiology Dashboard", "url": "https://www.nmhealth.org/publication/view/general/9364/", "description": "NM Department of Health substance use and mental health epidemiology profile dashboard introduction, funded through SAMHSA and CDC grants including Overdose Data to Action (OD2A)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Prevention (OSAP)", "url": "https://nmprevention.org/", "description": "New Mexico Office of Substance Abuse Prevention, providing ongoing public health surveillance data and overdose prevention through naloxone distribution and training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC Provisional Drug Overdose Data", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nvss/vsrr/drug-overdose-data.htm", "description": "CDC provisional drug overdose death counts with state-level data including New Mexico, updated monthly."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NM Legislature", "url": "https://www.nmlegis.gov/", "description": "New Mexico Legislature website with access to bills, committee information, and legislator contact information. Use the \"Find My Legislator\" feature to contact state representatives and senators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.nmpharmacy.org/", "description": "NMPhA provides advocacy resources for New Mexico pharmacists. The association tracks legislation affecting pharmacy practice and advocates for expanded pharmacist roles."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Behavioral Health Providers Association", "url": "https://www.nmbhpa.org/", "description": "New Mexico Behavioral Health Providers Association (NMBHPA), uniting over 70 behavioral healthcare providers and organizations. Engages with state departments and agencies on behavioral health policy including substance use disorder services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NM Legislative Reports on Substance Use", "url": "https://www.nmlegis.gov/Entity/LFC/Documents/Program_Evaluation_Reports/Progress%20Report%20-%20Addressing%20Substance%20Use%20Disorders.pdf", "description": "NM Legislative Finance Committee progress report on addressing substance use disorders, including data on treatment gaps, overdose trends, Medicaid spending, and system performance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA Model Legislation: The National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA), ASHP, and NCPA provide model legislation and policy templates that may be relevant to New Mexico pharmacy practice. NMPhA participates in national advocacy through NASPA membership. Contact NMPhA for state-specific advocacy priorities."}]}]}, "newyork": {"name": "New York", "q": {"CPA_Term": "New York’s term for a CPA is a written “agreement” or “protocol” for collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM). N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c), (f) (McKinney 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New York law does not expressly include prescribing drugs and medications. N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(1) (McKinney 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in New York cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the New York practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow pharmacists to register to prescribe controlled substances in New York which would then allow them to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New York law includes “administering . . . drugs, medicines and therapeutic devices . . . on the basis of prescriptions or other legal authority.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(1) (McKinney 2024). Within this provision, New York law does not expressly mention what drugs a pharmacist can (or cannot) administer.However, New York law also provides that “a licensed pharmacist within their lawful scope of practice may administer injectable medications . . . for the treatment of mental health and substance use disorder” when prescribed or ordered by a licensed prescriber. N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(8) (McKinney 2024). This provision, which expressly grants authority to administer injectable forms of medication for SUD, may limit a pharmacist from administering any other form of medication for SUD.", "2B": "Obtain a prescription or order from a licensed prescriber.\nAdhere to the administration, recordkeeping, and training requirements contained in New York laws and regulations.\nN.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(3) (McKinney 2024); N.Y. COMP. CODES R. & REGS. tit. 8, § 63.17 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the New York practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment and not just injectable forms.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New York law provides that, at least until July 1, 2026, a pharmacist is a “qualified health care professional” under N.Y. PUB. HEALTH § 571(6), who can “direct[] a limited service laboratory and order[] and administer[] COVID-19 and influenza tests” that are CLIA-waived. N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(7) (McKinney 2024).\nNew York pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address ordering or evaluating any other types of lab tests outside of an agreement or protocol for collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the New York practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New York law includes “collaborative drug therapy management [CDTM] in accordance with the provisions of [§ 6801-a] of this article.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(1) (McKinney 2024).\nThe referenced law defines CDTM as “the performance of clinical services by a pharmacist… in accordance with a written agreement or protocol” and is limited to certain specified aspects, which includes “adjusting or managing a drug regimen of a patient.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c) (McKinney 2024). Although the provision uses the phrase “adjusting or managing,” it does not expressly refer to “prescribing.”\nMoreover, New York laws and regulations governing CDTM do not account for the fact that a New York pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol for CDTM provides.\nIn summary, New York laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CDTM agreement or protocol. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a New York pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise New York laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CDTM protocols or agreements.\nExpressly specify in New York laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CDTM protocols or agreements.\nAllow New York pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, New York laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” at least to the same extent.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New York law includes CDTM “in accordance with the provisions of [§ 6801-a] of this article.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(1) (McKinney 2024).\nThe referenced law defines CDTM as “the performance of clinical services by a pharmacist… in accordance with a written agreement or protocol” and is limited to certain specified aspects, which includes “adjusting or managing a drug regimen of a patient.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c) (McKinney 2024).\nAdjusting or managing a drug regimen “may include adjusting drug strength, frequency of administration or route of administration.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c)(i) (McKinney 2024). This provision may mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a CDTM protocol or agreement. If not, New York laws and regulations governing CDTM do not directly address administering drugs or medications.\nAlthough New York CDTM law is unclear on administering buprenorphine, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer injectable forms of medications for SUD, a logical answer is to this question is “yes,” at least to that same extent.", "5B": "Enter into a CDTM agreement or protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in New York laws and/or regulations that “adjusting or managing a drug regimen of a patient” includes administering drugs, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in New York law includes CDTM “in accordance with the provisions of [§ 6801-a] of this article.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801(1) (McKinney 2024).\nThe referenced law defines CDTM as “the performance of clinical services by a pharmacist… in accordance with a written agreement or protocol” and is limited to certain specified aspects. N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c) (McKinney 2024).\nA CDTM agreement or protocol may include “evaluating and . . . ordering disease state laboratory tests related to the drug therapy management for the specific disease or disease state specified.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c)(ii) (McKinney 2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CDTM agreement or protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "A CDTM agreement or protocol is a written document between one or more pharmacists and a “voluntary participating physician.” N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a(c), (f) (McKinney 2024).\nThe following New York laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CDTM agreements and protocols and required elements of CDTM agreements and protocols – N.Y. EDUC. LAW § 6801-a (McKinney 2024) and N.Y. COMP. CODES R. & REGS. tit. 8, § 63.10 (2024).", "8A": "No, based on the information described below.\nNew York’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law defines “telehealth provider” using a list of professions. Pharmacists are not included within that list. N.Y PUB. HEALTH § 2999-CC (West 2024).\nNew York pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address telehealth, telemedicine, or telepharmacy.", "8B": "Expressly provide in New York laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "The New York Office of Addiction Services and Supports (OASAS) publishes a guidance document on the standards for providing SUD treatment via telehealth.\nNew York laws and regulations governing telehealth include – N.Y PUB. HEALTH §§ 2999-CC to 2999-EE (McKinney 2024) (telehealth generally); N.Y INS. §§ 3216, 3217-h, 3221 (West 2024) (insurance); N.Y PUB. HEALTH § 4406-g (West 2024) (HMOs); N.Y. COMP. CODES R. & REGS. tit. 14, §§ 596.1 to 596.8 (2024) (mental health);\nN.Y. COMP. CODES R. & REGS. tit. 14, § 830.5 (2024)\n(OASAS designated providers); N.Y. COMP. CODES R. & REGS. tit. 18, §§ 538.1 to 538.2 (2024) (Medicaid).", "9A": "Pharmacists are reimbursed for clinical decision-making associated with prescribing Paxlovid or Lagevrio for COVID-19.42.\nPharmacists can order and dispense self-administered hormonal contraceptives after completing training pursuant to a non-patient specific order.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the New York Medicaid program.\nSpecify in New York laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a written agreement or protocol for CDTM are covered under the New York Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "New York law prohibits prescribing, dispensing, or administering controlled substances “to addicts or habitual users of controlled substances” except in specified situations. N.Y PUB. HEALTH § 3350 (McKinney 2024).\nHowever, “methadone, or such other controlled substance designated by the commissioner [of health] as appropriate for such use, may be administered to an addict by a practitioner . . . as part of a substance abuse or chemical dependence program.” N.Y PUB. HEALTH § 3351(5) (McKinney 2024). Buprenorphine is an approved drug for this purpose. N.Y. COMP. CODES R. & REGS. tit. 10, §§ 80.84 to 80.86 (2024).", "10B": "Individual physicians or groups of physicians “who have obtained authorization from the federal government to administer buprenorphine to addicts” may do so without obtaining an operating certificate from the commissioner of mental health. N.Y MENTAL HYG. § 32.05(b) (McKinney 2024).\nHospitals must have a policy and procedure in place for initiating “medication assisted treatment,” including buprenorphine. N.Y PUB. HEALTH § 2803-u (McKinney 2024).\nCrisis stabilization centers, as defined, must offer “medication assisted treatment” or contract with an organization to offer it. N.Y MENTAL HYG. § 36.01(2) (McKinney 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/professions-index/pharmacy", "description": "New York State Board of Pharmacy, under the NYS Education Department, Office of the Professions. The Board regulates pharmacy practice through Education Law Title VIII, Article 137."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/professions/pharmacist/contact-information", "description": "NYS Board of Pharmacy contact information. Address: 89 Washington Avenue, Albany, NY 12234-1000. Phone: 518-474-3817, ext. 130. Email: pharmbd@nysed.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Education Law Article 137)", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/title8/education-law/article-137", "description": "NYS Education Law Title VIII, Article 137, governing the practice of pharmacy in New York, including licensure requirements, scope of practice, and continuing education mandates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Full Text)", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/professions/pharmacist/laws-rules-regulations/article-137", "description": "Full text of Article 137 with all sections of the pharmacy practice law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Commissioner's Regulations Part 63 (Pharmacy)", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/title8/regulations-commissioner-education/part-63", "description": "Part 63 of the Commissioner's Regulations governing pharmacy practice, including pharmacy technician duties, CDTM, and other regulatory requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Drug Therapy Management (CDTM)", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/professions/pharmacist/collaborative-drug-therapy-management", "description": "CDTM allows pharmacists in facilities regulated under Article 28 of the Public Health Law to enter into written agreements with physicians for collaborative drug therapy management, including initiating or adjusting medications, ordering immunizations, obtaining labs, and managing drug toxicities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDTM Regulations", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/new-york/8-NYCRR-63.10", "description": "8 NYCRR 63.10, Commissioner's Regulations on collaborative drug therapy management. Pharmacists meeting requirements and employed by or affiliated with qualifying facilities may enter into CDTM agreements with physicians."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: New York does not grant independent prescribing authority to pharmacists for controlled substances. Pharmacists may participate in CDTM in qualifying facilities, and may administer immunizations and dispense naloxone under standing orders."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NYS OASAS Medications for OUD", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/providers/medications-treatment-opioid-use-disorder", "description": "OASAS information on medications for treatment of opioid use disorder including buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone. Provides regulatory context for federal and state agencies involved in OUD medication management."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Assistance Program (Bupe-AP)", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/news/nys-office-addiction-services-and-supports-and-nys-department-health-launch-buprenorphine", "description": "NYS OASAS and DOH launched the Buprenorphine Assistance Program (Bupe-AP) to help manage OUD by reducing cost barriers. Buprenorphine decreases the risk for opioid-related mortality."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator, filterable by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in New York."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA tool to find practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine, searchable by state including New York."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYS OASAS (State Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/", "description": "New York State Office of Addiction Services and Supports (OASAS) serves as the state authority for addiction services. OASAS certifies treatment programs, operates 12 Addiction Treatment Centers, and oversees 1,700+ addiction treatment programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act, all practitioners with a current DEA registration including Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. New York follows federal requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://telehealth.hhs.gov/providers/telehealth-policy/prescribing-controlled-substances-via-telehealth", "description": "Federal HHS resource on prescribing controlled substances via telehealth. New York allows telehealth prescribing of buprenorphine consistent with federal guidelines and NYS telemedicine regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NYRx Medicaid Pharmacy Program PDL", "url": "https://newyork.fhsc.com/providers/pdp_about.asp", "description": "NYRx, the New York State Medicaid Pharmacy Program Preferred Drug Program (PDP), managed by Prime Therapeutics State Government Solutions. All drugs currently covered by Medicaid remain available under the PDP."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYRx Preferred Drug List (PDF)", "url": "https://newyork.fhsc.com/downloads/providers/nyrx_pdp_pdl.pdf", "description": "New York Medicaid preferred drug list (revised February 2026), listing preferred and non-preferred drugs. Includes buprenorphine products and OUD treatment medications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Statewide Formulary for OUD Medications", "url": "https://newyork.fhsc.com/providers/mat.asp", "description": "Under Social Services Law 367-a(7)(e), NYS enacted a statewide formulary for opioid antagonists and opioid dependence agents for both Medicaid Managed Care and Fee-for-Service, ensuring consistent coverage across the Medicaid program. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "eMedNY Reimbursable Drug List", "url": "https://www.emedny.org/info/formfile.aspx", "description": "Medicaid pharmacy list of reimbursable drugs. Only drugs appearing on this list are reimbursable under fee-for-service Medicaid."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants provide resources to states including New York for OUD treatment, prevention, harm reduction, and recovery support services."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NYS Pharmacy Continuing Education", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/professions/pharmacist/continuing-education", "description": "NYS Board of Pharmacy continuing education requirements for pharmacist license renewal, including mandatory CE topics. Contact: 89 Washington Avenue, Albany, NY 12234-1000, 518-474-3817, ext. 130."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Continuing Education (Education Law 6827)", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/title8/education-law/article-137/6827", "description": "Education Law Section 6827 establishing mandatory continuing education requirements for pharmacists. Pharmacists who do not satisfy CE requirements shall not practice until they have met such requirements and received a registration certificate."}, {"type": "note", "text": "DEA MATE Act Training: Under the MATE Act, all DEA-registered practitioners must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders for DEA registration or renewal. This applies to all practitioners in New York."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free training modules, webinars, and clinical tools on buprenorphine and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PSSNY Education", "url": "https://www.pssny.org/", "description": "Pharmacists Society of the State of New York (PSSNY), 230 Washington Ave Ext., Suite 101, Albany, NY 12203. Phone: 518-869-6595. PSSNY provides continuing education, advocacy, and professional development resources for New York pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OASAS Training Resources", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/projectcope", "description": "OASAS Community Overdose Prevention Education (Project COPE) provides training resources and tools including the Treatment Availability Dashboard to search for certified programs."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Exchange Programs (SEPs)", "url": "https://www.health.state.ny.us/diseases/aids/consumers/prevention/syringe_access.htm", "description": "NYS Department of Health syringe access programs and Drug User Health Hub directory. Services include syringe exchange, office-based and street-based harm reduction, mobile van services, peer-delivered exchange, and Drug User Health Hubs delivering buprenorphine, primary care, wound care, and mental health services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order for Pharmacies", "url": "https://www.health.ny.gov/diseases/aids/general/opioid_overdose_prevention/pharmacy_standing_order.htm", "description": "All pharmacies in NYS may dispense naloxone through a statewide standing order (non-patient specific prescription). No personal prescription is needed. The Naloxone Co-payment Assistance Program (N-CAP) covers co-payments up to $40."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OASAS Harm Reduction Delivered", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/harm-reduction-delivered", "description": "OASAS online ordering portal where NYS residents can order fentanyl test strips, xylazine test strips, and naloxone kits delivered free to any valid New York State address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Overdose Prevention Programs", "url": "https://www.health.ny.gov/diseases/aids/general/opioid_overdose_prevention/", "description": "NYS Statewide Opioid Overdose Prevention Program, including toolkits and guidance for registered opioid overdose prevention programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality and Access: Fentanyl test strips are legal and widely distributed in New York State. OASAS has partnered with NY MATTERS to supply fentanyl test strips to OASAS and OMH providers. OASAS has distributed over 20 million test strips. Individuals can order free fentanyl and xylazine test strips through the OASAS Harm Reduction Delivered portal at https://oasas.ny.gov/harm-reduction-delivered."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://apps.health.ny.gov/public/tabvis/PHIG_Public/opioid/", "description": "NYS Opioid Data Dashboard providing comprehensive data on opioid use and misuse with 104 opioid-related indicators. Includes state and county-level data, historical trends, overdose deaths, ED visits, and treatment admissions."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "OASAS Recovery Services", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/recovery", "description": "OASAS recovery services page with information on certified recovery residences, housing, recovery and peer support, self-help groups, and family support resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Housing, Recovery and Peer Support", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/housing-recovery-and-peer-support", "description": "OASAS peer-based services offering non-clinical drug-free environments for recreation, skill-building, and recovery supports including emotional, informational, and concrete support. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Residences: Recovery Residences in NYS are certified by OASAS. They are community-based shared living environments for individuals maintaining recovery from substance use disorder. Information available at https://oasas.ny.gov/recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OASAS Treatment and Recovery", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/treatment", "description": "OASAS treatment page listing certified addiction treatment programs at various levels of care, from outpatient counseling to residential care. OASAS operates 12 Addiction Treatment Centers and oversees 1,700+ programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis and Warmline Contacts: NYS HOPEline: 1-877-8-HOPENY (1-877-846-7369) or text HOPENY to 467369. Available 24/7 for New Yorkers struggling with addiction. National 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is also available by dialing 988."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NYS Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.op.nysed.gov/professions/pharmacist/contact-information", "description": "NYS Board of Pharmacy, Office of the Professions, NYS Education Department. 89 Washington Avenue, Albany, NY 12234-1000. Phone: 518-474-3817, ext. 130. Email: pharmbd@nysed.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYS Medicaid (eMedNY)", "url": "https://www.emedny.org/", "description": "eMedNY is New York's Medicaid Management Information System providing claims processing, provider enrollment, and drug information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYS OASAS (State Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://oasas.ny.gov/", "description": "New York State Office of Addiction Services and Supports, the state authority for addiction services, treatment certification, and recovery support."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PSSNY (Pharmacists Society of the State of New York)", "url": "https://www.pssny.org/", "description": "PSSNY, 230 Washington Ave Ext., Suite 101, Albany, NY 12203. Phone: 518-869-6595. Email: staff@pssny.org. PSSNY's mission is to unite and empower the profession of pharmacy through advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYS Department of Health OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.health.ny.gov/diseases/aids/general/opioid_overdose_prevention/", "description": "NYS DOH opioid overdose prevention resources, including standing orders, pharmacy naloxone programs, and opioid data reporting."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NYS Opioid Data Dashboard", "url": "https://apps.health.ny.gov/public/tabvis/PHIG_Public/opioid/", "description": "NYS DOH Opioid Data Dashboard with 104 opioid-related indicators, state and county-level data, historical trends, overdose deaths, ED visits, naloxone administrations, and treatment admissions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYS DOH Opioid Statistics", "url": "https://www.health.ny.gov/statistics/opioid/", "description": "NYS Department of Health opioid-related statistics page. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC Provisional Drug Overdose Data", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nvss/vsrr/drug-overdose-data.htm", "description": "CDC provisional drug overdose death counts with state-level data including New York, updated monthly."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OASAS Treatment Availability Dashboard: Available through the OASAS Project COPE page at https://oasas.ny.gov/projectcope, this dashboard allows searching for state-certified outpatient or bedded programs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "County-Level Data: The NYS Opioid Data Dashboard at https://apps.health.ny.gov/public/tabvis/PHIG_Public/opioid/ provides county-level opioid data for all 62 counties in New York State."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NYS Senate - Find Your Senator", "url": "https://www.nysenate.gov/", "description": "New York State Senate website with legislator search, bill tracking, and contact information for senators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NYS Assembly - Find Your Assembly Member", "url": "https://nyassembly.gov/mem/search/", "description": "New York State Assembly member search to find and contact your assembly representative."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Joint Senate Task Force on Opioids, Addiction and Overdose Prevention", "url": "https://www.nysenate.gov/committees/joint-senate-task-force-opioids-addiction-overdose-prevention", "description": "NYS Senate Joint Task Force on Opioids, Addiction and Overdose Prevention. Contact: nysoverdosetaskforce@nysenate.gov. The task force focuses on legislative recommendations to address the opioid crisis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PSSNY Advocacy", "url": "https://www.pssny.org/", "description": "PSSNY advocates for pharmacists in New York State on legislative and regulatory issues. Contact for state-specific pharmacy advocacy priorities."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA Model Legislation: The National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA), ASHP, and NCPA provide model legislation and policy templates that may be relevant to New York pharmacy practice. PSSNY participates in national advocacy through NASPA membership. Contact PSSNY for state-specific advocacy priorities and model legislation resources."}]}]}, "northcarolina": {"name": "North Carolina", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Carolina law does not expressly include prescribing drugs and medications. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A (West 2024).\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition does provide that a “clinical pharmacist practitioner” (CPP) may collaborate with physicians to determine the appropriate health care for a patient. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A(d) (West 2024). This collaboration may include some prescribing authority. However, the collaboration requires a drug therapy management (DTM) agreement between the clinical pharmacist practitioner and a physician.\nDEA information last updated in November 2024 indicates that registered pharmacists in North Carolina can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Prescribe Only.” However, based on the information in North Carolina laws and regulations described in the response to the \"prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, this authority appears to apply only to CPPs operating under DTM agreements, even though that limitation is not specified by DEA.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the North Carolina practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment outside of a DTM agreement.\nAllow all North Carolina pharmacists, and not just CPPs, to register obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Carolina law provides that an “immunizing pharmacist” is “authorized and permitted to administer drugs as provided in [§] 90-85.15B.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A(c)\n(West 2024). This is the only express reference to administering drugs and medications in the definition.\nThe referenced North Carolina law contains a list of drugs and medications that an immunizing pharmacist may administer. The only item within the list potentially applicable to treating SUD is administering “a long-acting injectable medication . . . to persons at least 18 years of age pursuant to a specific prescription order initiated by a prescriber.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.15B(c1) (West 2024). Mot North Carolina regulation governing the administration of long-acting injectable medications defines them as a “drug product formulated to produce sustained release and gradual absorption of the active pharmaceutical ingredient over an extended period of time after administration by subcutaneous or intramuscular injection.” 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 46.2514(a) (2024). The regulation does not limit what drugs or medications may or may not qualify as a long-acting injectable.\nHowever, unlike several other states that allow pharmacists to administer injectable medications, North Carolina laws and regulations to not expressly specify that long-acting injectables include medications for mental illness or SUD.", "2B": "Satisfy the requirements for becoming an “immunizing pharmacist” that are contained in that term’s definition.\nN.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3(i1) (West 2024).\nObtain a specific prescription order initiated by a prescriber.\nAdminister the long-acting injectable medication in accordance with the requirements of North Carolina law and regulation. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.15B (West 2024); 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 46.2514 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the North Carolina practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment and not just injectable forms.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Carolina law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A (West 2024). In addition, no other North Carolina pharmacy law or regulation expressly refers to ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of a CPP operating under a DTM agreement.\nHowever, the North Carolina Association of Pharmacists’ (NCAP) website indicates that “in North Carolina, pharmacists are permitted to perform CLIA waived tests by the Board of Pharmacy” although the post does not provide a link or citation to what provides that authority.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the North Carolina practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Carolina law provides that a CPP may collaborate with physicians to determine the appropriate health care for a patient. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A(d) (West 2024). A CPP is a licensed pharmacist who “meets the guidelines and criteria . . . established by the joint subcommittee of the North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy” and is authorized to enter into DTM agreements “in accordance with the provisions of [§] 90-18.4.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3(b2) (West 2024).\nThe referenced North Carolina law provides that CPPs are authorized to “implement predetermined drug therapy” and “modify prescribed drug dosages, dosage forms, and dosage schedules.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-18.4(b) (West 2024).\nNorth Carolina regulation further specifies that a CPP is “approved to provide drug therapy management, including controlled substances, under the direction or supervision of a Supervising Physician pursuant to a CPP Agreement.” 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 46.3101(a)(3) (2024). This provision could mean that a CPP can prescribe controlled substances, but it is not clear.\nHowever, a North Carolina regulation governing physician authority to prescribe controlled substances does make it clearer. This regulation provides that a physician must have a valid DEA registration “in order for the physician to supervise any other health professional (physician assistant, nurse practitioner, clinical pharmacist practitioner) with prescriptive authority for controlled substances.” 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 32B.1001(b) (2024).\nThis regulation, combined with the DEA information described in the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, supports the conclusion that a CPP can prescribe controlled substances.", "4B": "Obtain certification as a CPP (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nEnter into a DTM agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": null, "5A": "As described in the information below, North Carolina laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” at least to the same extent.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Carolina law provides that a CPP may collaborate with physicians to determine the appropriate health care for a patient. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A(d) (West 2024).\nA CPP is a licensed pharmacist who “meets the guidelines and criteria . . . established by the joint subcommittee of the North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy” and is authorized to enter into DTM agreements “in accordance with the provisions of [§] 90-18.4.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3(b2) (West 2024).\nThe referenced North Carolina law provides that CPPs are authorized to “implement predetermined drug therapy” and “modify prescribed drug dosages, dosage forms, and dosage schedules.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-18.4(b) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “implement” and “modify,” it does not expressly refer to “administering.”\nNorth Carolina regulation further specifies that a CPP is “approved to provide drug therapy management, including controlled substances, under the direction or supervision of a Supervising Physician pursuant to a CPP Agreement.” 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 46.3101(a)(3) (2024). Although this provision refers to controlled substances, it does not expressly provide that a CPP can administer them.\nHowever, as part of the process of becoming a CPP, a pharmacist must complete one or more “certificate programs” that cover several topics. One of these topics is administering medications. 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 46.3101(b)(2)(F) (2024). This fact could indicate that a CPP has broad authority to administer drugs and medications, including controlled substances, under a DTM agreement. In summary, North Carolina laws and regulations do not expressly provide that a CPP can administer controlled substances under a DTM agreement. However, given the answer to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that an immunizing pharmacist has the general authority to administer long-acting injectable medications outside of DTM agreements, the most logical answer to this question is a pharmacist has at least the same authority under a DTM agreement", "5B": "Obtain certification as a CPP (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nEnter into a DTM agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in North Carolina laws and/or regulations that the activities a CPP can perform under a DTM agreement include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Carolina law provides that a CPP may collaborate with physicians to determine the appropriate health care for a patient. N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3A(d) (West 2024).\nA CPP is a licensed pharmacist who “meets the guidelines and criteria . . . established by the joint subcommittee of the North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy” and is authorized to enter into DTM agreements “in accordance with the provisions of [§] 90-18.4.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3(b2) (West 2024).\nAs part of DTM, CPPs are authorized “to order laboratory tests.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-18.4(b) (West 2024).\nNorth Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations governing DTM do not expressly address evaluating results.", "6B": "Obtain certification as a CPP (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nEnter into a DTM agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in North Carolina laws and/or regulations that the activities a CPP can perform under a DTM agreement include evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CPP is a licensed pharmacist who “meets the guidelines and criteria . . . established by the joint subcommittee of the North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy” and is authorized to enter into DTM agreements “in accordance with the provisions of [§] 90-18.4.” N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. § 90-85.3(b2) (West 2024).\nNorth Carolina regulations call a DTM agreement a CPP agreement. Regulations provide that a CPP agreement is a written agreement between the CPP, a “Primary Supervising Physician,” and “any Back-Up Supervising Physician” covering the DTM arrangement. 21 N.C. ADMIN. CODE 46.3101(a)(10) (2024).\nThe following North Carolina laws and regulations provide more information on CPP certification, requirements for entering DTM (CPP) agreements, and required elements of DTM (CPP) agreements – N.C. GEN. STAT. ANN. §§ 90-85.3A, 90-18(c)(3a), 90-18.4 (West 2024); 21 N.C. ADMIN.\nCODE 46.3101 (2024).", "8A": "No, based on the information described below.\nNorth Carolina does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. North Carolina also does not have a Medicaid or other health insurance law addressing telemedicine/telehealth.\nNorth Carolina’s laws and regulations address telehealth or telemedicine only with respect to veterinarians, involuntary commitment, opioid treatment programs, maternal and child health screening, and several professions in which North Carolina is a part of interstate compacts (audiologists/speech pathologists, professional counselors, and occupational therapists).\nNorth Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address telehealth, telemedicine, or telepharmacy.", "8B": "Expressly provide in North Carolina laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "There are no North Carolina laws or regulations of the type that are identified in responding to the \"telehealth provisions related to buprenorphine\" sectionin other states. However, the North Carolina Medical Board has a position statement about it215 and some Medicaid resources are available online.", "9A": "Designation as a CPP is required in most cases for Medicaid reimbursement to occur and the reimbursement rates applicable to pharmacists may differ from physicians and other health care professionals.\nNorth Carolina Medicaid recently authorized non-CPP immunizing pharmacists to enroll as providers, but only as to reimbursement for services related to self-administered contraceptives according to a pre-defined protocol.", "9B": "Allow all pharmacists, and not just CPPs, to have “full provider” status under the North Carolina Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (NC CSRS)", "url": "https://northcarolina.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "The North Carolina Controlled Substances Reporting System (CSRS) is the state's PDMP, operated through the PMP AWARxE platform by Bamboo Health. It collects information on dispensed controlled substance prescriptions (Schedules II-V) and makes this information available to prescribers and dispensers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSRS Information Page (NCDHHS)", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mental-health-developmental-disabilities-and-substance-use-services/north-carolina-drug-control-unit/nc-controlled-substances-reporting-system", "description": "The NC DHHS page providing information about the CSRS, including registration instructions, FAQs, and contact information for technical support."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSRS Pharmacist Registration", "url": "https://northcarolina.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "All prescribers, pharmacists, and delegates may apply through the NC CSRS website by selecting \"Create an Account\" and following the provided instructions. Under NC law (GS 90-113.74A), pharmacists must register with the CSRS within 30 days of obtaining an initial or renewal pharmacy license."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mental-health-developmental-disabilities-and-substance-use-services/north-carolina-drug-control-unit/nc-controlled-substances-reporting-system/nc-controlled-substances-reporting-system-prescriber-and-dispenser-resources", "description": "North Carolina requires mandatory CSRS enrollment and use for prescribers and dispensers of controlled substances under the NC STOP Act. Prescribers must check the CSRS before prescribing certain controlled substances, and pharmacists must be registered as a condition of licensure."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing (PMP InterConnect)", "url": "https://www.nctracks.nc.gov/content/public/es/providers/pharmacy/pharmacy-announcements/2018-Pharmacy-Announcements/Update-to-Controlled-Substance-Reporting-System.html", "description": "North Carolina participates in PMP InterConnect, the National Association of Boards of Pharmacy's interstate data sharing network. This allows providers to obtain multi-state information about patients' controlled substance prescriptions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://northcarolina.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Delegates may register through the NC CSRS website (PMP AWARxE). Each delegate applies online and is given their own individual username and password. Prescribers and dispensers should never share their login credentials. Delegate reverification is required periodically."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/", "description": "The North Carolina Board of Pharmacy (NCBOP) is responsible for the licensure and regulation of pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, and pharmacies in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Full Text)", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/downloads/Statutes.pdf", "description": "North Carolina's Pharmacy Practice Act (N.C. Gen. Stat. 90-85.2 to 90-85.44) is available as a PDF download from the Board of Pharmacy website. This document includes all relevant statutes governing pharmacy practice in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "http://reports.oah.state.nc.us/ncac/title%2021%20-%20occupational%20licensing%20boards%20and%20commissions/chapter%2046%20-%20pharmacy/chapter%2046%20rules.html", "description": "Title 21, Chapter 46 of the North Carolina Administrative Code contains the Board of Pharmacy's administrative rules and regulations governing pharmacy practice, including rules on dispensing, compounding, continuing education, and pharmacy permits."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement (Clinical Pharmacist Practitioner)", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/clinical-pharmacist-practitioner.html", "description": "North Carolina authorizes Clinical Pharmacist Practitioners (CPPs) to enter into drug therapy management agreements with supervising physicians, as authorized by GS 90-85.3(b2) and GS 90-18.4. CPPs can provide health care services including prescribing, with joint approval from the NC Board of Pharmacy and Medical Board."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority (Immunizing Pharmacists)", "url": "https://www.ncleg.gov/EnactedLegislation/Statutes/PDF/BySection/Chapter_90/GS_90-85.15B.pdf", "description": "Under GS 90-85.15B and Session Law 2021-110, immunizing pharmacists in North Carolina have authority to administer vaccines, dispense hormonal contraceptives, and administer long-acting injectable medications. Session Law 2025-37 also authorized pharmacists to test and treat for influenza."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator (North Carolina)", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in North Carolina, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/medication-assisted-treatment/find-treatment/treatment-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Can be filtered to show North Carolina practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC DHHS Substance Use Disorders Page", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mental-health-developmental-disabilities-and-substance-use-services/substance-use-disorders", "description": "The NCDHHS Division of Mental Health, Developmental Disabilities, and Substance Use Services page on substance use disorders, covering prescription drug misuse, recovery-oriented systems of care, and opioid treatment programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority and OTP Resources", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/state-operated-healthcare-facilities/facilities/alcohol-and-drug-abuse-treatment-centers", "description": "North Carolina's Opioid Treatment Programs (OTPs) are certified by SAMHSA/CSAT, The Joint Commission, and the NC State Opioid Treatment Authority. The State Opioid Treatment Authority is housed within the NCDHHS Division of Mental Health, Developmental Disabilities, and Substance Use Services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NCDHHS Buprenorphine Guidance", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/buprenorphineguidance/download", "description": "North Carolina DHHS guidance document on the treatment of opioid use disorder with buprenorphine and buprenorphine/naloxone, including state-specific requirements and best practices."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://ncmedsoc.org/dea-hhs-publish-final-rule-on-telemedicine-prescribing-for-oud/", "description": "The DEA and HHS finalized telemedicine flexibility regulations for buprenorphine prescribing in January 2025. North Carolina providers must comply with both federal rules and state Board of Medicine and Board of Pharmacy regulations governing telehealth prescribing, including checking the CSRS before prescribing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NC Medicaid Pharmacy Services Homepage", "url": "https://medicaid.ncdhhs.gov/providers/programs-and-services/prescription-drugs/pharmacy-services", "description": "The NC Medicaid Outpatient Pharmacy Services page, providing information about the comprehensive prescription drug benefit, clinical coverage policies, and pharmacy program management."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Tracks Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://www.nctracks.nc.gov/content/public/providers/pharmacy.html", "description": "The NC Tracks pharmacy portal for providers and pharmacists, with information about prior authorization requirements, pharmacy announcements, and claims processing for NC Medicaid and Health Choice recipients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://medicaid.ncdhhs.gov/preferred-drug-list", "description": "North Carolina Medicaid's Preferred Drug List (PDL) page. Buprenorphine products are included on the PDL. The PDL specifies preferred and non-preferred medications and prior authorization requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fee Schedule and Covered Codes Portal", "url": "https://ncdhhs.servicenowservices.com/fee_schedules", "description": "The NC DHHS Fee Schedule and Covered Code Portal provides searchable fee schedules for NC Medicaid, including pharmacy-related billing codes and reimbursement rates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Medicaid Contacts", "url": "https://medicaid.ncdhhs.gov/contacts", "description": "NC Medicaid Contact Center information. Phone: 888-245-0179, Monday through Friday. Provider and beneficiary information on Medicaid policies and procedures."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Settlement Funding", "url": "https://ncopioidsettlement.org/", "description": "North Carolina is receiving approximately $1.4 billion in national opioid settlement funds. Information on state and local spending of settlement funds to support treatment, recovery, harm reduction, and other life-saving programs is available on this website."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Continuing Education Requirements", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/continuing-education.html", "description": "North Carolina Board of Pharmacy CE requirements. The Board accepts ACPE-accredited CE, NCAP-accredited CE, and preceptor credit. Detailed requirements are in 21 NCAC 46 .2201."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Board of Pharmacy - Controlled Substance Dispensing Requirements", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/renewal.html", "description": "Pharmacists working in a pharmacy that dispenses controlled substances must be registered with the CSRS as a condition of licensure. The renewal page includes information about CE and CSRS registration requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "North Carolina Association of Pharmacists (NCAP) Education", "url": "https://www.ncpharmacists.org/", "description": "NCAP provides quality continuing education programming, annual conventions, webinars, and specialty training including hormonal contraception dispensing training. NCAP is recognized by the Board as an approved CE provider."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA online forms and applications for practitioner registration. Since the removal of the X-waiver requirement in December 2022, all practitioners with a current DEA registration that includes Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD if permitted by applicable state law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System (PCSS) offers free training, guidance, and mentoring on the prevention, diagnosis, and treatment of opioid use disorder, including buprenorphine prescribing education modules, webinars, and clinical tools."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs Directory", "url": "https://www.dph.ncdhhs.gov/programs/chronic-disease-and-injury/injury-and-violence-prevention-branch/north-carolina-safer-syringe-initiative/syringe-services-programs-north-carolina", "description": "The NC Division of Public Health's directory of syringe services programs in North Carolina. As of July 2016 (GS 90-113.27), North Carolina allows legal establishment of syringe services programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Safer Syringe Initiative", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/public-health/north-carolina-safer-syringe-initiative", "description": "The NCDHHS page for the North Carolina Safer Syringe Initiative, including a list of active syringe services programs, annual reports, and information about the limited immunity provided under the syringe exchange law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/about/department-initiatives/overdose-epidemic/syringe-and-naloxone-access", "description": "North Carolina's statewide standing order for naloxone, signed by the State Health Director, authorizes any pharmacist licensed by the NC Board of Pharmacy to dispense naloxone to any person who meets set criteria without a patient-specific prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution (NCHRC and NEXT Distro)", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/northcarolina", "description": "North Carolina Harm Reduction Coalition (NCHRC) partners with NEXT Distro to provide free naloxone kits by mail. Residents can also access naloxone through local syringe services programs at no cost."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://nccriminallaw.sog.unc.edu/drug-testing-equipment-isnt-drug-paraphernalia-anymore/", "description": "North Carolina legalized fentanyl test strips and other drug testing equipment in 2019 by amending the paraphernalia laws. Drug users and harm reduction organizations can possess drug testing equipment without violating paraphernalia laws."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.dph.ncdhhs.gov/programs/chronic-disease-and-injury/injury-and-violence-prevention-branch/north-carolina-overdose-epidemic-data", "description": "The NC Division of Public Health's overdose epidemic data page, including monthly overdose surveillance updates, statewide summary data, and interactive visuals of state, regional, and county-level metrics."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Communities of North Carolina (RCNC)", "url": "https://www.rcnc.org/", "description": "Recovery Communities of North Carolina is a nonprofit organization promoting addiction recovery, wellness, and citizenship through advocacy, education, and support. RCNC serves as the statewide recovery community organization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Community Impact NC - RCCs and RCOs Directory", "url": "https://impactcarolina.org/rcc-list/", "description": "A directory of Recovery Community Centers (RCCs) and Recovery Community Organizations (RCOs) across North Carolina, listing locations, contact information, and service areas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Specialist Certification", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mental-health-developmental-disabilities-and-substance-use-services/certified-peer-support-specialists/information-peer-support-specialists", "description": "Information about North Carolina's Certified Peer Support Specialist Program (NCCPSSP), which certifies individuals in recovery from mental illness or substance use disorder to provide peer support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing (Oxford Houses of NC)", "url": "https://oxfordhousenc.com/", "description": "Oxford House of North Carolina, established in 1991, is a statewide network of peer-driven, democratically run, self-supported recovery residences chartered by Oxford House, Inc."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC DHHS Behavioral Health Division", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mhddsus", "description": "The Division of Mental Health, Developmental Disabilities, and Substance Use Services (DMH/DD/SUS) within NCDHHS works to achieve a better quality of life and well-being for North Carolinians through behavioral health services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis and Warmline Services", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mental-health-developmental-disabilities-and-substance-use-services/crisis-services", "description": "NC DHHS crisis services page. The NC Peer Warmline (855-PEERS-NC or 855-733-7762) is staffed by certified peer support specialists with personal experience with mental health or substance use issues. Also includes information about Hope4NC and the 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NC Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/meet-our-board.html", "description": "Jay Campbell, Executive Director. NC Board of Pharmacy, 6015 Farrington Rd, Suite 201, Chapel Hill, NC 27517. Phone: (919) 246-1050. Email: jcampbell@ncbop.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Medicaid / Division of Health Benefits", "url": "https://medicaid.ncdhhs.gov/contacts", "description": "NC Medicaid Contact Center: 888-245-0179 (Monday-Friday, 8 a.m. to 5 p.m.). Division of Health Benefits, NC DHHS. Website: https://medicaid.ncdhhs.gov/agencydepartment/division-health-benefits"}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/divisions/mental-health-developmental-disabilities-and-substance-use-services/north-carolina-drug-control-unit/north-carolina-controlled-substances-act", "description": "The NC State Opioid Treatment Authority is within the NCDHHS Division of Mental Health, Developmental Disabilities, and Substance Use Services. Drug Control Unit phone: 919-733-1765. Location: 695 Palmer Drive, Anderson Building, Raleigh, NC 27603. Mailing: 3001 Mail Service Center, Raleigh, NC 27699-3001."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Association of Pharmacists (NCAP)", "url": "https://www.ncpharmacists.org/", "description": "North Carolina Association of Pharmacists. PO Box 58, 36 Court Square, SW, Graham, NC 27253. Phone: (984) 439-1646."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC DHHS Contact", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/contact", "description": "NC Department of Health and Human Services. Mailing: 2001 Mail Service Center, Raleigh, NC 27699-2000. Physical: 1915 Health Drive, Raleigh, NC."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Death Dashboard", "url": "https://www.dph.ncdhhs.gov/programs/chronic-disease-and-injury/injury-and-violence-prevention-branch/north-carolina-overdose-epidemic-data", "description": "North Carolina's overdose epidemic data page from the Division of Public Health. From 2000-2023, more than 41,500 North Carolinians lost their lives to drug overdose. The site includes monthly surveillance updates, statewide summary data, and interactive county-level visualizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid and Substance Use Action Plan Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/opioid-and-substance-use-action-plan-data-dashboard", "description": "An interactive dashboard providing integration and visualization of state, regional, and county-level metrics tracking progress toward the NC Opioid and Substance Use Action Plan. Includes 15 public health indicators and 16 local actions across 8 strategies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "County-Level Opioid Data", "url": "https://www.sog.unc.edu/resources/microsites/opioid-response-project/online-resource-library/data-sources", "description": "UNC School of Government's Opioid Response Project maintains an online resource library of North Carolina opioid data sources, including links to the NC Opioid Data Dashboard with county-level metrics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Opioid and Substance Use Action Plan", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/about/department-initiatives/overdose-epidemic/north-carolinas-opioid-and-substance-use-action-plan", "description": "North Carolina's Opioid and Substance Use Action Plan (now in its third iteration) addresses overdose prevention through a comprehensive strategy framework. The associated data dashboard provides county-level tracking."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Settlement Spending and Data", "url": "https://ncopioidsettlement.org/about/state-spending/", "description": "Data on North Carolina's opioid settlement fund spending, including details on NCDHHS grants awarded to agencies across the state for treatment services, harm reduction, and prevention."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "NCAP Government Affairs", "url": "https://ncap.memberclicks.net/government-affairs", "description": "The North Carolina Association of Pharmacists advocacy page, including priority legislative issues and information about NCAP's work to expand scope of practice for pharmacists in North Carolina."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NCAP Advocacy Issues", "url": "https://ncappolicyadvocacy.wixsite.com/mysite", "description": "NCAP's advocacy site covering priority issues including PBM reform, provider status for pharmacists, and other legislative priorities for the current session."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Clinical Pharmacist Practitioner Expansion", "url": "https://www.ncbop.org/downloads/Guidance%20on%20New%20CPP%20Authority%2025%20AUG%202025.pdf", "description": "August 2025 guidance from the NC Board of Pharmacy on expanded Clinical Pharmacist Practitioner authority under updated collaborative practice statutes (GS 90-18(c)(3a) and GS 90-18.4)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your NC Legislators", "url": "https://www.ncleg.gov/findyourlegislators", "description": "The North Carolina General Assembly's tool for finding state representatives and senators by address. Useful for contacting legislators about pharmacy practice or OUD treatment legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NC Opioid Action Plan and Coalition", "url": "https://www.ncdhhs.gov/about/department-initiatives/overdose-epidemic/north-carolinas-opioid-and-substance-use-action-plan", "description": "North Carolina's comprehensive Opioid and Substance Use Action Plan developed by NCDHHS with community partners. The plan addresses equity, prevention, harm reduction, treatment access, and recovery support across the state."}]}]}, "northdakota": {"name": "North Dakota", "q": {"CPA_Term": "North Dakota’s term for a CPA is either a “written protocol” or a “collaborative agreement,” depending on context. N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4 (West 2023).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Dakota law expressly authorizes “prescriptive practices as limited under this chapter.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-01(24) (West 2023).\nUnder the chapter of North Dakota law governing pharmacy practice (Chapter 43-15), pharmacists have “limited prescriptive practices,” but only pursuant to a collaborative agreement. N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4 (West 2023).\nUnder North Dakota regulations, a pharmacist’s limited prescriptive practices relate to opioid antagonists, immunizations, and tobacco cessation therapies. N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-12-01 to 61-04-12-02, 61-04-14-01 to 61-04-14-02, 61-04-15-01 to 61-04-15-02 (2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in North Dakota cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the North Dakota practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow North Dakota pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Dakota law expressly includes “participation in . . . drug administration.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-01(24) (West 2023). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer.Moreover, North Dakota law expressly directs the state board of pharmacy to develop rules for “educational and operational requirements for a pharmacist to obtain and maintain authority to administer drugs.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.5 (West 2023). The regulations developed refer to administering “medications and immunizations” and do not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer.\nThe definition of “administration” in North Dakota law includes “provision of other drugs to an individual who is at least three years of age upon the order of a practitioner authorized to prescribe such a drug.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-01(1)(c) (West 2023).", "2B": "Obtain the order of a practitioner authorized to prescribe the drug or medication.\nObtain administering authority from the North Dakota Board of Pharmacy and adhere to the laws and regulations governing authorized pharmacist administration of drugs.\nN.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.5 (West 2023); N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-11-01 to 61-04-11-09 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Dakota law expressly includes “the performance of laboratory tests . . . which are [CLIA] waived.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-01(24) (West 2023).\nNorth Dakota law also identifies the following “approved” tests for pharmacists: “glucose monitoring devices (FDA cleared/home use) 9221, cholesterol 1020, HDL cholesterol 2550, triglyceride 6118, glycosylated hemoglobin (Hgb A1C) 2204, and SARS-CoV-2.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-25.3 (West 2023).", "3B": "Adhere to the education and training requirements contained in North Dakota regulation for pharmacist use of CLIA-waived tests. N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-10-01 to 61-04-10-07 (2024).", "3C": "Expand the North Dakota practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Dakota law expressly authorizes “prescriptive practices as limited under this chapter.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-01(24) (West 2023).\nNorth Dakota law grants pharmacists “limited prescriptive practices to initiate or modify drug therapy following diagnosis or established protocols by a licensed physician or an advanced practice registered nurse.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(1) (West 2023).\nThe pharmacist and collaborative practitioner “shall prepare a collaborative agreement concerning the scope of the pharmacist’s prescriptive practices.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(2) (West 2023).\nHowever, there is no further explanation in North Dakota law or regulation about the extent of these prescriptive practices and whether they include prescribing controlled substances.\nMoreover, North Dakota laws and regulations governing pharmacist prescriptive authority and collaborative agreements do not account for the fact that a North Dakota pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what collaborative agreement provides.\nIn summary, North Dakota laws and regulations allow pharmacist prescribing generally and do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a collaborative agreement. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a North Dakota pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise North Dakota laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under collaborative agreements.\nExpressly specify in North Dakota laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under collaborative agreements.\nAllow North Dakota pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, North Dakota laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in North Dakota law expressly authorizes “prescriptive practices as limited under this chapter.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-01(24) (West 2023).\nNorth Dakota law grants pharmacists “limited prescriptive practices to initiate or modify drug therapy following diagnosis or established protocols by a licensed physician or an advanced practice registered nurse.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(1) (West 2023).\nThe pharmacist and collaborative practitioner “shall prepare a collaborative agreement concerning the scope of the pharmacist’s prescriptive practices.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(2) (West 2023).\nThere is no further explanation in North Dakota law or regulation about the extent of these prescriptive practices and whether they include administering controlled substances. Although not in the context of a collaborative agreement for limited prescribing practices, North Dakota regulation provides that “a practitioner may prepare a written protocol governing the administration of medications with an authorized pharmacist for a specific period of time or purpose.” N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-11-05 (2024). This provision does not expressly limit the types of drugs or medications that a pharmacist could administer under such protocol.\nIn summary, although North Dakota law and regulations are unclear about administering drugs or medications under a collaborative agreement, given the pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs under a written protocol as well as the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a collaborative agreement or written protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in North Dakota law and/or regulation that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a written protocol or collaborative agreement include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, North Dakota laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine North Dakota law grants pharmacists “limited prescriptive practices to initiate or modify drug therapy following diagnosis or established protocols by a licensed physician or an advanced practice registered nurse.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(1) (West 2023).\nThe pharmacist and collaborative practitioner “shall prepare a collaborative agreement concerning the scope of the pharmacist’s prescriptive practices.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(2) (West 2023). There is no further explanation in North Dakota law or regulation about the extent of the collaborative agreement and whether it may include ordering or evaluating lab tests Although not in the context of a collaborative agreement for limited prescribing practices, North Dakota regulation provides that “a practitioner may prepare a written protocol governing the administration of medications with an authorized pharmacist for a specific period of time or purpose.” N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-11-05 (2024). This provision also does not expressly address ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nAs a result, North Dakota laws and regulations governing collaborative agreements and written protocols for drug administration are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist may order or evaluate lab tests However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has limited authority to order lab tests in general, the most logical answer is that the same limited authority applies under a collaborative agreement or written protocol.", "6B": "Enter into a collaborative agreement or written protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent lab testing, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in North Dakota law and/or regulation that a pharmacist’s authority under a collaborative agreement or written protocol includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A licensed physician or advanced practice registered nurse, and the pharmacist may enter into a collaborative agreement concerning the scope of the pharmacist’s prescriptive practices to initiate or modify drug therapy N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-15-31.4(2) (West 2023).\nSeparately, a “practitioner” may prepare a written protocol governing the administration of medications with an authorized pharmacist for a specific period of time or purpose. N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-11-05 (2024). The regulation does not define “practitioner,” however.\nThe following North Dakota laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering written protocols or collaborative agreements and required elements of written protocols or collaborative agreements – N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. §§ 43-15-31.4 to 43-15-31.5 (West 2023); N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-11-01 to 61-04-11-09 (2024).\nNote that North Dakota repealed its general regulations governing limited pharmacist prescriptive practice in 2020. However, there remain specific regulations dedicated to the prescribing authority (granted via statewide protocol) for opioid antagonists, immunizations, and tobacco cessation. N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-04-12-01 to 61-04-12-02, 61-04-14-01 to 61-04-14-02, 61-04-15-01 to 61-04-15-02 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nNorth Dakota does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, North Dakota law requires health insurers to cover services provided through telehealth.\nUnder North Dakota insurance law related to the coverage of telehealth services, a “health care provider” authorized to provide telehealth includes an individual licensed under Chapter 43-15, which is the statutory chapter related to pharmacy. N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 26.1-36-09.15(1)(d) (West 2023).\nNorth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise North Dakota laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Although most controlled substances can be prescribed via telemedicine, opioids generally cannot be so prescribed. However, an opioid can be prescribed via telemedicine “if prescribed as an [FDA-] approved medication assisted treatment for opioid use disorder.” N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 43-17-45(1) (West 2023).\nNorth Dakota laws and regulations governing telehealth include – N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 26.1-36-09.15 (West 2023) (health insurance); N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 26.1-36.11-02 (West 2023) (comprehensive medication management); N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. §§ 43-17-44 to 43-17-45 (West 2023) (physicians); N.D. ADMIN. CODE 50-02-15-01 to 50-02-15-02 (2024) (physicians); N.D. ADMIN. CODE 61-02-08-01 to 61-02-08-09 (2024) (telepharmacy).", "9A": "“Any physicians, pharmacists, and other health professionals who provide face-to-face or telephonic medication therapy management [MTM] services to covered individuals in the identified health population are entitled to reimbursement” from the North Dakota Medicaid program. N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 50-06-40(b) (West 2023).\nIn addition to MTM services, pharmacists may bill North Dakota Medicaid for anticoagulation management, continuous glucose monitoring, and tobacco cessation codes.\nNorth Dakota law also requires health insurers to provide coverage for licensed pharmacists to provide comprehensive medication management to participating enrollees. N.D. CENT. CODE ANN. § 26.1-36.11-02 (West 2023).", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the North Dakota Medicaid program.\nSpecify in North Dakota laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a collaborative agreement or protocol are covered under the North Dakota Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "The formulary of drugs that a naturopath with prescribing authority can prescribe includes naltrexone. N.D. ADMIN. CODE 50-06-02-08 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://northdakota.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "The North Dakota Prescription Drug Monitoring Program (PDMP) is operated by the North Dakota Board of Pharmacy through the PMP AWARxE platform by Bamboo Health. The PDMP collects and monitors data on dispensed controlled substance prescriptions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Information Page", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/PDMP-index.asp", "description": "The North Dakota Board of Pharmacy's PDMP information page, including forms for law enforcement, out-of-state practitioners, and patient self-requests."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://northdakota.pmpaware.net/identities/new", "description": "Account creation page for the ND PDMP. Pharmacists and prescribers need their NPI number, DEA number (if applicable), and ND Board license number to register. Contact PDMP questions at 701-877-2410 or pdmp@ndboard.pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/PDMP-faq.asp", "description": "North Dakota PDMP FAQ page covering mandatory use requirements, reporting obligations, and usage guidelines. Providers who prescribe controlled substances must participate in the PDMP."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing (PMP InterConnect)", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/PDMP-faq.asp", "description": "North Dakota's PDMP integrates with PMP InterConnect (PMPi) for interstate data sharing. PMP AWARxE is configured to allow searches across participating states. Users can configure default states for interstate patient request searches."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://northdakota.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Delegates may create accounts through the PMP AWARxE system. Shared email addresses and creating accounts on behalf of others are not permitted. Each user must have their own individual account."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/", "description": "The North Dakota State Board of Pharmacy protects, preserves, and promotes public health and welfare by assuring quality pharmaceutical care. Located at 1838 E Interstate Ave, Suite D, Bismarck, ND 58503. Phone: 701-877-2404."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Full Text)", "url": "https://ndlegis.gov/cencode/t43c15.pdf", "description": "North Dakota Century Code Chapter 43-15 (Pharmacists) contains the state's pharmacy practice legislation, first enacted in 1890 and codified as NDCC 43-15."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Law Book (Statutes and Rules)", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/pdfs/lawbooknew.pdf", "description": "Comprehensive law book containing both the North Dakota Century Code pharmacy statutes (Chapter 43-15) and the Administrative Code pharmacy rules (Title 61), compiled by the Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules", "url": "https://ndlegis.gov/prod/acdata/pdf/61-03-04.pdf", "description": "North Dakota Administrative Code Title 61 contains the Board of Pharmacy's administrative rules. The full set of rules covers pharmacist licensure, pharmacy technicians, professional practice, and continuing education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Limited Prescriptive Authority", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/authority.asp", "description": "North Dakota grants pharmacists limited prescriptive authority through statewide protocols. Senate Bill 2221 (67th session) authorized independent authority to prescribe immunizations and tobacco cessation therapies. Administrative rules, statewide protocols, and implementation resources are available on this page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice", "url": "https://nastad.org/resources/pharmacists-authority-engage-collaborative-practice-agreements-and-initiate-prep-pep-and", "description": "North Dakota allows pharmacists to engage in collaborative practice agreements with specific prescribing authority. Agreements must include specific disease states, pharmacist prescribing authority, detailed practice protocols, and risk management activities."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ND HHS Addiction Resources", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/addiction", "description": "North Dakota Health and Human Services addiction resource hub providing information on opioid treatment programs, substance use disorder services, and treatment locators for the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND Substance Abuse Treatment Programs", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-treatment-programs", "description": "Directory of substance abuse treatment programs across North Dakota, including regional Human Service Centers and the North Dakota State Hospital."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in North Dakota, including those offering buprenorphine and medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/medication-assisted-treatment/find-treatment/treatment-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who can prescribe buprenorphine for OUD treatment, filterable by state to show North Dakota providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://ndlegis.gov/information/acdata/pdf/50-02-15.pdf", "description": "North Dakota Administrative Code Chapter 50-02-15 governs telemedicine practice. Practitioners prescribing controlled substances via telehealth must participate in the PDMP. Federal rules (effective January 2025) allow buprenorphine prescribing via telemedicine with specific requirements."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ND Medicaid Pharmacy Providers", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/healthcare/medicaid/provider/pharmacy", "description": "North Dakota Medicaid pharmacy provider page with information on pharmacy billing, 340B requirements, and contact information (medicaidrx@nd.gov)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://ndmedicaid.acentra.com/preferred-drug-list-pdl/", "description": "North Dakota Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL), developed in conjunction with the Drug Use Review Board (DUR Board). The PDL identifies preferred and non-preferred drugs with clinical prior authorization criteria."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Use Review Board", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/healthcare/medicaid/providers/pharmacy/drug-use-review-board", "description": "North Dakota Medicaid DUR Board page with the PDL, academic detailing handouts, newsletters, and pharmacy communication archives. Contact: Brendan Joyce, PharmD, Administrator, Pharmacy and Clinical Services (bjoyce@nd.gov)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rates and Fee Schedules", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/healthcare/medicaid/provider/fee-schedules", "description": "North Dakota Medicaid rate and fee schedules. These serve as informational resources for providers. ND Medicaid requires all providers to bill their usual and customary charges."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Provider Manual", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/sites/www/files/documents/pharmacy-provider-manual.pdf", "description": "The complete North Dakota Medicaid Pharmacy Provider Manual with billing procedures, eligibility verification, dispensing rules, and reimbursement guidelines."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Settlement Fund Grants", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/opioids/settlement", "description": "North Dakota's Opioid Settlement Fund provides grant funding for prevention, treatment, and recovery programs. Over $7 million has been awarded to more than a dozen agencies statewide."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Continuing Education Requirements", "url": "https://ndlegis.gov/prod/acdata/pdf/61-03-04.pdf", "description": "North Dakota Administrative Code 61-03-04 governs continuing pharmaceutical education. Pharmacists must complete a minimum of 15 continuing education hours per year."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Prescriptive Authority Training", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/naloxone.asp", "description": "North Dakota Board of Pharmacy naloxone prescribing page. Pharmacists must review rule 61-04-12, complete approved naloxone training (SAMHSA, CDC, or equivalent), and register as a trained pharmacist to prescribe opioid antagonists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "North Dakota Pharmacists Association (NDPhA)", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.net/", "description": "The North Dakota Pharmacists Association promotes safe, rational use of cost-effective medications and provides continuing education and professional development resources for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA online registration forms and applications. Since the removal of the X-waiver requirement in December 2022, all practitioners with a current DEA registration that includes Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Provider Clinical Support System offers free training and mentoring on OUD prevention, diagnosis, and treatment, including buprenorphine prescribing education."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Service Programs", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/health/diseases-conditions-and-immunization/syringe-service-programs", "description": "There are seven authorized syringe service programs (SSPs) in North Dakota, listed on this page. The HHS Public Health Division and Behavioral Health Division developed guidance for establishing and operating SSPs in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Prescriptive Authority (Pharmacist)", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/naloxone.asp", "description": "North Dakota allows pharmacists to prescribe opioid antagonists (naloxone) to patients at risk of overdose, their friends and family members, or other individuals in a position to assist. Governed by Administrative Rule 61-04-12."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Rule (61-04-12)", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/pdfs/Limited_Rx_authority_opioid_antagonist_61-04-12.pdf", "description": "Full text of Administrative Rule 61-04-12 governing pharmacist limited prescriptive authority for opioid antagonists, including documentation, training, and record-keeping requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/health/diseases-conditions-and-immunization/syringe-service-programs", "description": "In North Dakota, syringe exchange programs are permitted to provide \"supplies,\" which include test strips, to program participants. These are not considered drug paraphernalia under state law when provided through authorized SSPs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/overdose-prevention/data-research/facts-stats/sudors-dashboard-fatal-overdose-data.html", "description": "CDC's State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS) dashboard includes North Dakota data on fatal drug overdoses. State-specific overdose death data is also available through the North Dakota Violent Death Reporting System."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ND HHS Behavioral Health Division", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health", "description": "The North Dakota Health and Human Services Behavioral Health Division oversees addiction services, mental health programs, and recovery support across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Specialist Certification", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/peer-support/certification/apply", "description": "North Dakota offers two levels of peer support certification: Certified Peer Support Specialist I (PRSS I) and Certified Peer Support Specialist II (PRSS II) for individuals with lived experience in recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Training", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/peer-support/trainings", "description": "Peer support trainings approved by the Behavioral Health Division. Each training is approved for CEUs by the ND Board of Addiction Counseling Examiners, Board of Social Work Examiners, and for Certified Peer Support Specialists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Assistance Provider List", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/recovery-housing/provider-list", "description": "North Dakota HHS Recovery Housing Assistance Program provider list, showing approved recovery housing options across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health", "description": "North Dakota crisis services are accessible through the Behavioral Health Division. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline provides 24/7 support for mental health and substance use crises. North Dakota also has regional Human Service Centers providing crisis intervention."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ND Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/contact.asp", "description": "Mark J. Hardy, Executive Director. North Dakota Board of Pharmacy, 1838 E Interstate Ave, Suite D, Bismarck, ND 58503. Phone: 701-877-2404. Email: mhardy@ndboard.pharmacy. PDMP Line: 701-877-2410."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND Medicaid Pharmacy Director", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/healthcare/medicaid/providers/pharmacy/drug-use-review-board", "description": "Brendan Joyce, PharmD, Administrator, Pharmacy and Clinical Services. Email: bjoyce@nd.gov. North Dakota Medicaid, Health and Human Services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA)", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/licensing", "description": "The State Opioid Treatment Authority is within the ND HHS Behavioral Health Division. Contact: dhsbhd@nd.gov or 701-328-8920. OTP licensing and Certificate of Need must be submitted to SOTA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "North Dakota Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.net/", "description": "The North Dakota Pharmacists Association promotes and advises the safe, rational use of cost-effective medications. Contact through their website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND HHS Contact", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/", "description": "North Dakota Health and Human Services. Main office in Bismarck. The Behavioral Health Division manages substance use and mental health programs statewide."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CDC SUDORS Dashboard (North Dakota)", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/overdose-prevention/data-research/facts-stats/sudors-dashboard-fatal-overdose-data.html", "description": "CDC's SUDORS dashboard provides state-level data on unintentional and undetermined drug overdose deaths, including North Dakota. Data is drawn from death investigations and toxicology reports."}, {"type": "link", "title": "North Dakota Violent Death Reporting System", "url": "https://ndlegis.gov/sites/default/files/pdf/committees/68-2023/25.5120.03000appendixd.pdf", "description": "The North Dakota Violent Death Reporting System (NDVDRS) collects and investigates overdose death information. Reports are presented to the Health Services Interim Committee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND Opioid Settlement Data and Reports", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/opioids/settlement", "description": "North Dakota's opioid settlement page includes data on funded strategies, settlement spending, and the impact of prevention, treatment, and recovery programs supported by settlement funds."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND HHS Addiction Data", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/addiction", "description": "North Dakota HHS addiction page including data on opioid treatment programs, treatment utilization, and community-based behavioral health services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ONDCP Drug Overdose Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://nemsis.org/drug-overdose-surveillance-dashboard/", "description": "The Office of National Drug Control Policy Drug Overdose Surveillance Dashboard tracks fatal and nonfatal drug overdoses by state, including North Dakota provisional data."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ND Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.net/", "description": "The North Dakota Pharmacists Association advocates for the pharmacist's role as a vital healthcare provider and supports professional development and expanded scope of practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND Board of Pharmacy - Prescriptive Authority Resources", "url": "https://www.nodakpharmacy.com/authority.asp", "description": "Resources related to pharmacist limited prescriptive authority in North Dakota, including immunization protocols, tobacco cessation, and implementation materials from the Center for Collaboration and Advancement in Pharmacy (CAP Center)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact My Legislators", "url": "https://ndlegis.gov/contact-my-legislators", "description": "North Dakota Legislative Branch tool for contacting state legislators. During session, legislators can be reached at the State Capitol through Constituent Views. Legislative Council phone: 701-328-2916."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND Opioid Settlement and Policy", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/opioids/settlement", "description": "Information on North Dakota's opioid settlement funds, including grant opportunities for prevention, treatment, and recovery programs. The settlement supports programs addressing OUD across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ND HHS Opioid Initiatives", "url": "https://www.hhs.nd.gov/behavioral-health/addiction", "description": "North Dakota HHS addiction services page covering opioid treatment programs, community behavioral health services, and state initiatives addressing opioid use disorder."}]}]}, "ohio": {"name": "Ohio", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Ohio’s term for a CPA is a “consult agreement” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(D) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Ohio law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(B) (West 2024).\nIn addition, the definition of “licensed health professional authorized to prescribe drugs” (aka “prescriber”) in Ohio law does not include a pharmacist. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(I) (West 2024).\nDEA information indicates that registered pharmacists in Ohio can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Administer, Prescribe, and Dispense” controlled substances without condition.\nHowever, Ohio Board of Pharmacy information makes clear that an Ohio “controlled substance prescriber registration is deemed void if the pharmacist no longer has a valid consult agreement authorizing the prescribing of a controlled substance. Failure to obtain or maintain a valid controlled substance prescriber registration prohibits a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances.” See the response to the \"prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA\" section.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Ohio practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications outside of a consult agreement, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Ohio pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances outside of a consult agreement.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Ohio law expressly includes “engaging in the administration of drugs to the extent authorized by section 4729.45.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(B)(10) (West 2024).\nIn the referenced law, among the list of authorized drugs is “an addiction treatment drug administered in a long-acting or extended-release form.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.45(B)(1)(a) (West 2024).\nNote that a pharmacist may not delegate to any person the pharmacist’s authority to administer drugs or medications under OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.45. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.45(G)(2) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain a prescription from a physician with an ongoing physician-patient relationship with patient. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.45(B)(1) (West 2024); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-3-03(A) (2024).\nAdhere to the administration, recordkeeping, and training requirements specified in both Ohio law and regulations. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.45 (West 2024); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-3-03 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the Ohio practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment and not just injectable forms.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Ohio law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(B) (West 2024).\nHowever, Ohio regulation authorizes a pharmacist to administer CLIA-waved ”diagnostic laboratory testing,” and evaluate the results of such tests, subject to certain specified conditions. OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-3-01 (2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Ohio practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Ohio law expressly includes “acting pursuant to a consult agreement.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(B)(8) (West 2024).\nUnder a consult agreement a pharmacist may “add[] a drug to the patient’s drug therapy.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39(D)(1)(a)(v) (West 2024). This provision does not expressly refer to “prescribing.”\nHowever, Ohio regulations make clear that a consult agreement can authorize a pharmacist to prescribe controlled drugs. OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-6-02(C) (2024).\nTo prescribe controlled substances under a consult agreement, a pharmacist must both: (1) maintain a valid controlled substance prescriber registration issued by Ohio’s Board of Pharmacy; and (2) prescribe using a valid DEA registration. OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-6-02(C)(6) (2024).\nUnder a consult agreement, a pharmacist “shall comply with the same requirements for the prescribing dangerous drugs [sic] pursuant to Chapter 4731 of the Administrative Code.” OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-6-03(C) (2024). A “dangerous drug” includes all prescription drugs. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(F) (West 2024).\nChapter 4731 is the administrative code section for the state medical board. This appears to be an express provision that Ohio pharmacists prescribing under a consult agreement are subject to the same restrictions that apply to Ohio physician prescribers.", "4B": "Enter into consult agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nAdhere to Ohio laws and regulations governing the process for pharmacist prescribing drugs under a consult agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": null, "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Ohio law expressly includes “acting pursuant to a consult agreement.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(B)(8) (West 2024).\nOhio law governing consult agreements provides that a pharmacist can “manage drug therapy for treatment of specified diagnoses or diseases.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39(D)(1)(a) (West 2024).\nThe phrase “manage drug therapy” expressly includes “administering a drug.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39(D)(1)(a)(iv) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the types of drugs or medications a pharmacist can administer.", "5B": "Enter into a consult agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Ohio law expressly includes “acting pursuant to a consult agreement.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.01(B)(8) (West 2024).\nOhio law governing consult agreements provides that a pharmacist can “order laboratory and diagnostic tests, including blood and urine tests, that are related to the drug therapy being managed, and evaluate the results of the tests that are ordered.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39(D)(1)(b) (West 2024).\nHowever, a pharmacist’s authority to evaluate test results under a consult agreement “does not authorize the pharmacist to make a diagnosis.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39(D)(1)(b)(ii) (West 2024).", "6B": "Enter into consult agreement (see (7A) and (7B) below).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "“One or more” pharmacists may enter into a consult agreement with “one or more” practitioners. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39 (West 2024)\n“Practitioner,” for purposes of consult agreements, means a physician, physician assistant, clinical nurse specialist, certified nurse-midwife, or certified nurse practitioner. OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-6-01 (2024). If the agreement is with a physician assistant, one or more supervising physicians must authorize the agreement. If the agreement is with a clinical nurse specialist, certified nurse-midwife, or certified nurse practitioner, one or more collaborating physicians must authorize the agreement.\nThe following Ohio laws and regulations provide detailed information on requirements for entering consult agreements and required elements of consult agreements – OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.39 (West 2024); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4729:1-6-01 to 1-6-03 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nOhio pharmacy law provides that “a pharmacist may provide telehealth services in accordance with section 4743.09 of the Revised Code.” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.285 (West 2024).\nThe referenced Ohio law contains the general telehealth standards for all medical occupations and professions. OHIO REV. CODE ANN § 4743.09 (West 2024).", "8B": null, "8C": "In the case of dispensing a dangerous drug, a pharmacist may not use telehealth mechanisms or other virtual means to perform any of the actions involved in dispensing the dangerous drug unless the action is authorized by the state board of pharmacy through rules it adopts. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.285 (West 2024).\nNo state regulatory board may require an initial in-person visit for a new patient whose medical record indicates that the patient is receiving, among other things, “medication-assisted treatment [MAT] or any other medication for opioid-use disorder [MOUD].” OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4743.09(B)(2)(c)(i) (West 2024).\nOhio laws and regulations governing telehealth include – OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4729.285 (West 2024)\n(pharmacists); OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4743.09 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 3902.30 (West 2024) (insurance); OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 4731.741 (West 2024) (physicians); OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 5164.95 (West 2024) (Medicaid); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4731-11-09 (2024) (prescribing controlled substances); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4731-37-01 (2024)\n(physicians); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 5160-1-18 (2024)\n(Medicaid); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 5160-8-52 (2024)\n(Medicaid - pharmacist services).", "9A": "Managing drug therapy under a consult agreement pursuant to OHIO CODE ANN. § 4729.39. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 5164.14(A) (West 2024).\nAdministering immunizations in accordance with OHIO CODE ANN. § 4729.41. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 5164.14(B) (West 2024).\nAdministering drugs and medications in accordance with OHIO CODE ANN. § 4729.45. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 5164.14(C) (West 2024).\nIn addition, Ohio regulations do not preclude a Medicaid managed care organization (as defined in Ohio law) from paying pharmacists for additional purposes, within scope of practice, including care management services that are rendered by a pharmacist without a consult agreement. OHIO ADMIN. CODE 5160-8-52 (2024).", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Ohio law and regulations set forth four types of medical providers who can provide MOUD: (1) physicians; (2) physician assistants; (3) advanced practice registered nurses designated as a clinical nurse specialist or certified nurse practitioner; and (4) certified nurse midwifes. There are separate sets of regulations for each type of provider, although the content is largely consistent among the types. OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4731-33-01 to 4731-33-04 (2024) (physicians); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4730-4-01 to 4730-4-04 (2024) (physician assistants); OHIO ADMIN. CODE 4723-9-13 (2024) (nurses and nurse midwifes).\nThe regulations referenced above cover the following topics, among other things: educational requirements, patient assessment, drug testing, patient counseling, medication form/dosage, and provider visit requirements.\nBefore initiating MOUD, a prescriber must give the patient (or patient’s representative) information about all drugs approved by FDA for MAT both orally and in writing. The prescriber must note in the patient’s medical record when this information was provided and make the record available for state board inspection. OHIO REV. CODE ANN. § 3719.064 (West 2024). Prescriber means the four types of providers identified above."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (OARRS)", "url": "https://www.ohiopmp.gov/", "description": "The Ohio Automated Rx Reporting System (OARRS) is Ohio's Prescription Drug Monitoring Program, created by the Ohio Board of Pharmacy. Established in 2006, OARRS collects information on all outpatient prescriptions for controlled substances (Schedules II-V), gabapentin, and naltrexone dispensed to Ohio patients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OARRS Information Page", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/oarrs/default", "description": "Ohio Board of Pharmacy's main OARRS page with information about the PDMP, registration, reporting requirements, and data access resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OARRS Pharmacist Registration and Mandatory Use", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/Documents/Pubs/Special/OARRS/Mandatory%20OARRS%20Registration%20and%20Requests.pdf", "description": "Information on mandatory OARRS registration and request requirements. Only pharmacists who dispense controlled substances to Ohio residents are required to register. Pharmacy interns may obtain delegate access."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OARRS Fact Sheet for Pharmacists", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/documents/pubs/special/oarrs/oarrs%20fact%20sheet%20for%20pharmacists.pdf", "description": "Fact sheet covering OARRS access, authorized users, delegate accounts, and usage guidelines. Account passwords cannot be shared, and delegate accounts are available for staff to use on behalf of a prescriber or pharmacist."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Interactive Data Tool", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/oarrs/stats", "description": "The Ohio Board of Pharmacy's PDMP Interactive Data Tool provides visualizations of controlled substance dispensing data to assist state and local partners in understanding medication distribution in their communities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing (PMP InterConnect)", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/oarrs/default", "description": "Ohio participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate PDMP data sharing. OARRS users can query prescription data from participating states through the integrated system."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/", "description": "The Ohio Board of Pharmacy is the single state agency responsible for administering and enforcing laws governing the practice of pharmacy and the legal distribution of drugs in Ohio."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Revised Code - Pharmacy Laws", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/LawsRules/ORC.aspx", "description": "Ohio Revised Code Chapter 4729 contains the state's pharmacy practice statutes, including pharmacist licensure, unauthorized practice, prescription requirements, and Board authority."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (Ohio Administrative Code)", "url": "https://codes.ohio.gov/ohio-administrative-code/rule-4729:1-5-02", "description": "Ohio Administrative Code Chapter 4729 contains the Board of Pharmacy's administrative rules governing pharmacist practice, continuing education, dispensing requirements, and licensing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Dispensing Protocol (Collaborative Practice)", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/pubs/naloxoneresources", "description": "Ohio Board of Pharmacy naloxone resources page. Under Ohio Revised Code Section 3715.502 and OAC Rules 4729:1-3-04 and 4729:2-3-04, pharmacists may dispense naloxone without a prescription in accordance with a physician-approved protocol."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Pharmacists Association Protocol Packages", "url": "https://www.ohiopharmacists.org/aws/OPA/pt/sp/protocol-packages", "description": "OPA provides protocol packages including naloxone dispensing protocols. Section 4729.44 of the ORC authorizes pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a prescription per physician-approved protocols."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Sample Naloxone Protocol", "url": "http://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/sample", "description": "Ohio Board of Pharmacy sample naloxone dispensing protocol for pharmacies, updated March 2022, including clinical criteria, assessment, and follow-up actions."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in Ohio, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for opioid use disorder."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/medication-assisted-treatment/find-treatment/treatment-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for buprenorphine treatment practitioners, filterable by state to show Ohio providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio State Opioid Response", "url": "https://medicine.wright.edu/sardi/state-opioid-response", "description": "Ohio's State Opioid Response (SOR) program, funded by SAMHSA, provides treatment and recovery services for Ohioans with opioid use disorder and stimulant use disorder through the Ohio Department of Behavioral Health (formerly OhioMHAS)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Department of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://dbh.ohio.gov/Default.aspx?tabid=315", "description": "Ohio's Department of Behavioral Health (formerly the Ohio Department of Mental Health and Addiction Services/OhioMHAS) oversees behavioral health services, treatment programs, and substance use disorder initiatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing (Federal Rule)", "url": "https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2025/01/17/2025-01049/expansion-of-buprenorphine-treatment-via-telemedicine-encounter", "description": "The DEA/HHS final rule (January 2025) governing telemedicine prescribing of buprenorphine for OUD. Ohio providers must also comply with state Board of Medicine rules regarding telehealth practice."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Medicaid Single Pharmacy Benefit Manager (SPBM)", "url": "https://spbm.medicaid.ohio.gov/", "description": "Gainwell Technologies serves as Ohio Medicaid's Single Pharmacy Benefit Manager for both Managed Care and Fee for Service. The SPBM portal provides access to pharmacy claims processing, the Unified Preferred Drug List, and reference materials."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Unified Preferred Drug List (UPDL)", "url": "https://dam.assets.ohio.gov/image/upload/medicaid.ohio.gov/PHM/unified-pdl/20260101_UPDL_v1_CLEAN.pdf", "description": "Ohio Medicaid's Unified Preferred Drug List identifies preferred medications, non-preferred medications, prior authorization requirements, and other coverage limits. Buprenorphine products are addressed within the UPDL."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODM Fee Schedule", "url": "https://ohpnm.omes.maximus.com/OH_PNM_PROD/Process/FeeScheduleContact.aspx", "description": "Access to Ohio Department of Medicaid (ODM) fee schedules for provider reimbursement. Pharmacy dispensing fees received a 5.7% rate increase under HB 33."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Medicaid Pharmacy Pricing (Myers and Stauffer)", "url": "https://myersandstauffer.com/client-portal/ohio/", "description": "Myers and Stauffer LC is the Pharmacy Pricing and Audit Consultant (PPAC) for the Ohio Department of Medicaid, handling pharmacy reimbursement rate analysis and auditing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Opioid Settlement Funds", "url": "https://recoveryohio.gov/about/overview", "description": "The RecoveryOhio initiative coordinates state resources and settlement funds for opioid response, including treatment expansion, recovery services, and prevention programs."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CE Requirements for Pharmacists", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/Documents/Licensing/CE/General/Pharmacist%20CE%20Reporting%20Requirements.pdf", "description": "Ohio pharmacists must complete 30 continuing education hours every two years (renewal cycle). At least 2 hours must be in pharmacy jurisprudence/law and 2 hours in patient/medication safety."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CE Requirements (Administrative Code)", "url": "https://codes.ohio.gov/ohio-administrative-code/rule-4729:1-5-02", "description": "Ohio Administrative Code Rule 4729:1-5-02 governing pharmacist continuing education requirements, including topic-specific requirements and acceptable CE providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://ohiopharmacists.org/", "description": "The Ohio Pharmacists Association (OPA) provides continuing education, annual meetings, and specialty programming for Ohio pharmacists, including topics related to controlled substances and patient safety."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA online registration forms. Since December 2022, all practitioners with Schedule III DEA registration authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD without an additional waiver."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS offers free training and mentoring on OUD prevention, diagnosis, and treatment, including buprenorphine prescribing education modules and clinical tools."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs Directory", "url": "https://www.harmreductionohio.org/list-of-all-ohio-syringe-service-programs/", "description": "Harm Reduction Ohio maintains a comprehensive, regularly updated list of all syringe service programs in Ohio, currently covering 25 counties. Includes locations, hours, and services offered (syringe exchange, naloxone distribution, HIV/HCV testing)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Dispensing Resources", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/pubs/naloxoneresources", "description": "Ohio Board of Pharmacy naloxone resources page. Ohio law allows pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a prescription under physician-approved protocols. The Board provides sample protocols and training resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Dispensing Rule", "url": "https://codes.ohio.gov/ohio-administrative-code/rule-4729:1-3-04", "description": "Ohio Administrative Code Rule 4729:1-3-04 governing pharmacist dispensing of naloxone under physician-established protocols, including clinical pharmacology requirements and documentation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.healthpolicyohio.org/health-policy-news/2025/10/03/ohio-decriminalizes-fentanyl-test-strips-in-effort-to-curb-overdoses", "description": "In October 2025, Governor DeWine signed an executive order allowing the Ohio Board of Pharmacy to exempt fentanyl test strips and reagent kits from the drug paraphernalia definition. The emergency rule covers test strips detecting fentanyl, xylazine, medetomidine, nitazenes, and benzodiazepines."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data", "url": "https://dbh.ohio.gov/Default.aspx?tabid=315", "description": "The Ohio Department of Behavioral Health launched the State of Ohio Integrated Behavioral Health Dashboard providing county- and state-level data on opioid use disorder, overdoses, and treatment across all 88 Ohio counties."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "RecoveryOhio", "url": "https://recoveryohio.gov/about/overview", "description": "Governor DeWine's RecoveryOhio initiative coordinates work across state departments, boards, and commissions to leverage resources for addiction prevention, treatment, and recovery. The initiative engages local governments, coalitions, and task forces."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.ohiorecoveryhousing.org/copy-of-recovery-housing-in-ohio", "description": "Ohio Recovery Housing (ORH) provides information about recovery housing in Ohio, defined by Ohio Revised Code Section 340.01 as housing providing an alcohol/drug-free environment, peer support, and assistance with addiction services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Peer Recovery Support", "url": "https://socohio.org/ohio-peer-recovery-support/", "description": "Ohio Systems of Care page on peer recovery support, including information on the Ohio Department of Behavioral Health's peer support programs and webinars on employing peer providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Department of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://dbh.ohio.gov/Default.aspx?tabid=315", "description": "The Ohio Department of Behavioral Health (formerly OhioMHAS) provides statewide leadership for mental health and addiction prevention, treatment, and recovery services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services (988 Lifeline)", "url": "https://recoveryohio.gov/about/overview", "description": "Ohio residents can access crisis support through the 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (call or text 988) for mental health and substance use emergencies. RecoveryOhio also coordinates crisis response resources."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/about/board", "description": "Steven W. Schierholt, Esq., Executive Director. Ohio Board of Pharmacy, 77 S. High St., Room 1702, Columbus, OH 43215-6126. Phone: (614) 466-4143. Email: contact@pharmacy.ohio.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Medicaid Pharmacy", "url": "https://spbm.medicaid.ohio.gov/", "description": "Ohio Department of Medicaid pharmacy services through the Single Pharmacy Benefit Manager (Gainwell Technologies). For pharmacy billing and PDL questions, access the SPBM provider portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Department of Behavioral Health (SOTA)", "url": "https://dbh.ohio.gov/Default.aspx?tabid=315", "description": "The State Opioid Treatment Authority is within the Ohio Department of Behavioral Health (formerly OhioMHAS). The department oversees OTP licensing and certification."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://ohiopharmacists.org/", "description": "The Ohio Pharmacists Association (OPA) represents pharmacists statewide. OPA provides advocacy, education, and professional development resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Department of Health", "url": "https://odh.ohio.gov/", "description": "The Ohio Department of Health oversees public health programs, including overdose prevention, disease surveillance, and health data reporting."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Integrated Behavioral Health Dashboard", "url": "https://dbh.ohio.gov/Default.aspx?tabid=315", "description": "Ohio's Integrated Behavioral Health Dashboard provides county- and state-level data on long-term trends in opioid use disorder, overdoses, and treatment across all 88 Ohio counties. Launched in 2023."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OARRS PDMP Interactive Data Tool", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.ohio.gov/oarrs/stats", "description": "The Ohio Board of Pharmacy's PDMP Interactive Data Tool provides visualizations of controlled substance prescribing and dispensing patterns across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Health Policy Ohio Data", "url": "https://www.healthpolicyohio.org/", "description": "Health Policy Ohio's Health Value Dashboard provides data on leading causes of death, including overdose, with state-level and county-level analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Opioid Data (RecoveryOhio)", "url": "https://recoveryohio.gov/about/overview", "description": "RecoveryOhio coordinates data sharing across state agencies to track opioid trends, treatment utilization, and recovery outcomes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDC SUDORS Ohio Data", "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/overdose-prevention/data-research/facts-stats/sudors-dashboard-fatal-overdose-data.html", "description": "CDC's SUDORS dashboard provides Ohio-specific data on unintentional and undetermined drug overdose deaths with detailed toxicology information."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "OPA Legislative Priorities", "url": "https://ohiopharmacists.org/aws/OPA/pt/sd/news_article/92887/_PARENT/layout_interior_details/true", "description": "Ohio Pharmacists Association current legislative priorities and successes, including HB 44 (emergency dispensing), HB 394 (immunization expansion), and other pharmacy practice legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OPA Advocacy and Resources", "url": "https://ohiopharmacists.org/aws/OPA/pt/sp/resources_national", "description": "OPA national and state advocacy resources, including Pharmacy PAC information and the OPA Legal Defense Fund supporting pharmacy profession advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Ohio Legislature District Maps", "url": "https://www.legislature.ohio.gov/legislators/district-maps", "description": "Find your Ohio state representative and senator by entering your address. The Ohio Legislature website provides contact information for all House and Senate members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "RecoveryOhio Initiative", "url": "https://recoveryohio.gov/about/overview", "description": "Governor DeWine's RecoveryOhio initiative is the state's primary opioid response coordination body, bringing together state agencies, local governments, and community partners to address addiction."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Ohio Advocacy", "url": "https://www.harmreductionohio.org/", "description": "Harm Reduction Ohio is a statewide organization advocating for evidence-based drug policies, harm reduction programs, and expanded treatment access. They track legislation and provide policy analysis."}]}]}, "oklahoma": {"name": "Oklahoma", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Oklahoma pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly reference collaborative practice, drug therapy management, or agreements/protocols associated with those practices. However, Oklahoma pharmacy laws and regulations do expressly allow “agreements” between pharmacists and physicians, although there is little explanation of what these “agreements” are or what they can or cannot cover.", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oklahoma law does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.1(38) (West 2024).\nAlthough not in the practice of pharmacy definition, Oklahoma law provides that pharmacists “may, in accordance with state and federal laws and rules, prescribe nonprescription drugs for the purposes of extemporaneous compounding or compounding for a known patient need in the practice area.” OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.1c (West 2024). Pharmacists can also prescribe opioid antagonists. OKLA. ADMIN. CODE § 535:10-9-15 (2024).\nThese are the only pharmacy laws or regulations expressly addressing prescribing drugs or medications.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Oklahoma cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Oklahoma practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Oklahoma pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oklahoma law expressly includes “administering . . . drugs and devices.” OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.1(38)(b) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nAlso, under the definition of the practice of pharmacy, a pharmacist may provide “those acts or services that are necessary to provide pharmaceutical care.” OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.1(38)(g) (West 2024). Oklahoma laws and regulations do not define “pharmaceutical care.”\nWithin Oklahoma regulations governing pharmaceutical care, there is a provision that a “pharmacist may administer drugs that have been dispensed on orders from a prescriber.” OKLA. ADMIN. CODE 535:10-9-13(a) (2024).\nThis provision also does not restrict the types of drugs or medications a pharmacist can administer.\nHowever, there are no further Oklahoma laws or regulations related to the administration of drugs and medications other than immunizations, which do contain educational requirements.\nWhenever the general phrase “administering . . . drugs and devices” appears in the practice of pharmacy definition but there are also more specific administration provisions, such as those related to training for administering immunizations, this creates a question as to whether the general language actually serves as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications. However, the existence of the broad Oklahoma regulation regarding administering drugs dispensed on orders from a prescriber indicates the intent for broad administration authority.", "2B": "Obtain an order from a prescriber.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oklahoma law does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.1(38) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Oklahoma pharmacy laws or regulations address ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Oklahoma practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nAs of September 2024, Oklahoma pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly reference collaborative practice, drug therapy management, or agreements/protocols associated with those practices. Indeed, in recent years, legislators introduced (but did not pass) several pieces of legislation to establish collaborative pharmacy practice in Oklahoma for one or more types of drug therapy management.\nHowever, Oklahoma law provides that “the use of agreements in the practice of pharmacy shall be acceptable” pursuant to rules promulgated by the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy, Oklahoma Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision, and the Oklahoma Board of Osteopathic Examiners. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(A) (West 2024).\nBesides indicating that the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy must develop regulations “relating to training requirements and administration of immunizations and therapeutic injections” jointly with the two medical boards, there is no further description in law or regulation about the content or limitations in an agreement. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(B) (West 2024). Even if an agreement could allow an Oklahoma pharmacist to prescribe drugs, Oklahoma laws and regulations governing agreements do not account for the fact that an Oklahoma pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the agreement provides.\nIn summary, Oklahoma laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of an agreement. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Oklahoma pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Oklahoma laws and/or regulations governing agreements to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Oklahoma laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under agreements.\nAllow Oklahoma pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.\nEnact legislation authorizing collaborative practice in Oklahoma that allows pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Oklahoma laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.” As of September 2024, Oklahoma pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly reference collaborative practice, drug therapy management, or agreements/protocols associated with those practices. Indeed, in recent years, legislators introduced (but did not pass) several pieces of legislation to establish collaborative pharmacy practice in Oklahoma for one or more types of drug therapy management.\nHowever, Oklahoma law provides that “the use of agreements in the practice of pharmacy shall be acceptable” pursuant to rules promulgated by the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy, Oklahoma Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision, and the Oklahoma Board of Osteopathic Examiners. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(A) (West 2024).\nBesides indicating that the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy must develop regulations “relating to training requirements and administration of immunizations and therapeutic injections” jointly with the two medical boards, there is no further description in law or regulation about the content or limitations in an agreement. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(B) (West 2024). There is no definition for the term “therapeutic injections.”\nNevertheless, within a section entitled “use of agreements,” Oklahoma law provides that a pharmacist who has completed required training “may administer therapeutic injections on orders from a licensed prescriber.” OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(C) (West 2024). The law does not define “therapeutic injection.”\nAs a result, Oklahoma laws and regulations governing pharmacy agreements are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can administer drugs besides immunizations or therapeutic injections. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has the general authority to administer drugs and medications outside of an agreement, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into an agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in Oklahoma laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under an agreement with a physician include administering drugs and medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Oklahoma laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “no.”\nAs of September 2024, Oklahoma pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly reference collaborative practice, drug therapy management, or agreements/protocols associated with those practices. Indeed, in recent years, legislators introduced (but did not pass) several pieces of legislation to establish collaborative pharmacy practice in Oklahoma for one or more types of drug therapy management.\nHowever, Oklahoma law provides that “the use of agreements in the practice of pharmacy shall be acceptable” pursuant to rules promulgated by the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy, Oklahoma Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision, and the Oklahoma Board of Osteopathic Examiners. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(A) (West 2024).\nBesides indicating that the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy must develop regulations “relating to training requirements and administration of immunizations and therapeutic injections” jointly with the two medical boards, there is no further description in law or regulation about the content or limitations in an agreement. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(B) (West 2024). As a result, Oklahoma laws and regulations governing pharmacy agreements are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can order or evaluate lab tests. However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has no such authority outside of an agreement, the most logical answer to this question is “no.”", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Oklahoma laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under an agreement with a physician includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "As of September 2024, Oklahoma pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly reference collaborative practice, drug therapy management, or agreements/protocols associated with those practices. Indeed, in recent years, legislators introduced (but did not pass) several pieces of legislation to establish collaborative pharmacy practice in Oklahoma for one or more types of drug therapy management.\nHowever, Oklahoma law provides that “the use of agreements in the practice of pharmacy shall be acceptable” pursuant to rules promulgated by the Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy, Oklahoma Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision, and the Oklahoma Board of Osteopathic Examiners. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30(A) (West 2024).\nAgreements are allowed between pharmacists and “physicians licensed by the Oklahoma Board of Medical Licensure or the Oklahoma Board of Osteopathic Examiners.” OKLA. ADMIN. CODE 535:10-9-5 (2024).\nThere is little Oklahoma law or regulation governing agreements, but it includes – OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 353.30 (West 2024); OKLA. ADMIN. CODE 535:10-9-5 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nOklahoma does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, Oklahoma insurance law requires health insurers to cover services provided through telemedicine. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 36, § 6803(C) (West 2024).\nUnder Oklahoma’s insurance law pertaining to telemedicine, a “health care professional” entitled to practice telemedicine is “a physician or other health care practitioner licensed, accredited or certified to perform specified health care services consistent with state law.” OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 36, § 6802(3) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Oklahoma laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Telemedicine encounters cannot be used to establish a physician-patient relationship for the purpose of prescribing opiates, synthetic opiates, semisynthetic opiates, benzodiazepine or carisprodol, unless the encounter is used to prescribe a “Schedule III, IV, or V controlled dangerous substance approved by [FDA] for medication assisted treatment or detoxification treatment” for SUD. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 478.1(C)(2) (West 2024).\nOklahoma laws and regulations governing telehealth include – OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 36, §§ 6801 to 6804 (West 2024) (insurance, including Medicaid); OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 59, § 478.1 (West 2024) (physicians); OKLA. ADMIN.\nCODE 317:30-3-27 (2024) (Medicaid); OKLA. ADMIN.\nCODE 435:10-7-13 (2024) (physicians).", "9A": "Oklahoma law provides that pharmacists and pharmacies may receive direct reimbursement from Oklahoma’s Medicaid programs equal to that of any other billing provider. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 56, § 4002.12(I)(2) (West 2024). As a practical matter, however, researchers found that as of early 2024, many changes authorized by law are not reflected in pharmacist billable codes and there are no adopted regulations.", "9B": "Adopt regulations and billable codes so that reimbursement of SUD treatment-related pharmacist services provided under an agreement with a physician can occur under the Oklahoma Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Every person who owns in whole or in part a public or private medical facility for which a majority of patients are issued on a reoccurring monthly basis a prescription for opioids, benzodiazepines, barbiturates or carisoprodol must obtain a registration issued by the Director of the Oklahoma State Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs Control.\nHowever, prescriptions for “buprenorphine with naloxone or buprenorphine as used for medication-assisted treatment services” do not apply towards this calculation. OKLA. STAT. ANN. tit. 63, § 2-302(C) (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (PMP AWARxE)", "url": "https://oklahoma.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Oklahoma's Prescription Monitoring Program (PMP) is accessed through the PMP AWARxE platform. The PMP is administered by the Oklahoma Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs Control (OBN) and collects data on dispensed controlled dangerous substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OBN Prescription Monitoring Program Page", "url": "https://www.obndd.ok.gov/registration-pmp/pmp", "description": "The Oklahoma Bureau of Narcotics PMP information page, including access to the Oklahoma NPLEx system for pseudoephedrine reporting, and PMP training and information resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OBN Registration and PMP", "url": "https://www.obndd.ok.gov/registration-pmp", "description": "Anyone who conducts business with controlled dangerous substances is required to register with OBN. The Registration and PMP page provides information about both programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mandatory Use Requirements", "url": "https://www.obndd.ok.gov/registration-pmp/pmp/pmp-training-information", "description": "By Oklahoma law (63 O.S. 2-309D), it is mandatory that providers check the PMP prior to prescribing and every 180 days prior to authorizing refills for opiates, synthetic opiates, semi-synthetic opiates, benzodiazepines, or carisoprodol. Exclusions apply for hospice, end-of-life, or inpatient settings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Delegate Access", "url": "https://oklahoma.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Pharmacists may designate delegates with their own PMP system logins to access the system on their behalf. Oklahoma law requires dispensation of Schedule II-IV controlled medications to be recorded within 5 minutes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://www.obndd.ok.gov/registration-pmp/pmp", "description": "Oklahoma participates in interstate PDMP data sharing through PMP InterConnect, allowing providers to query prescription data from participating states through the PMP AWARxE platform."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/pharmacy.html", "description": "The Oklahoma State Board of Pharmacy protects the health, safety, and welfare of citizens by regulating and enforcing laws regarding the practice of pharmacy and the manufacturing, sale, distribution, and storage of drugs, medicines, chemicals, and poisons."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Laws and Rules", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/pharmacy/laws-rules.html", "description": "The permanent rules of the Oklahoma State Board of Pharmacy are codified in Title 535 of the Oklahoma Administrative Code (OAC). The OAC is published by the Office of Administrative Rules under the Secretary of State."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Oklahoma Statutes Title 59)", "url": "https://oksenate.gov/sites/default/files/2019-12/os59.pdf", "description": "Oklahoma Statutes Title 59, Professions and Occupations, contains the pharmacy practice statutes beginning at Section 353, including board powers, pharmacist licensure, and practice requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Law Book", "url": "https://www.ok.gov/pharmacy/Laws_&_Rules/Oklahoma_Pharmacy_Law_Book/index.html", "description": "Oklahoma State Board of Pharmacy law book containing the compiled statutes and administrative rules governing pharmacy practice in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Collaborative Practice", "url": "https://nastad.org/resources/pharmacists-authority-engage-collaborative-practice-agreements-and-initiate-prep-pep-and", "description": "Oklahoma allows pharmacists to enter into collaborative practice agreements (CPAs). The agreement must state procedures, decision criteria, and plans for therapeutic decisions. Oklahoma statute explicitly prohibits CPAs from giving a pharmacist authority to prescribe controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board Staff and Contact", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/pharmacy/about/staff.html", "description": "Oklahoma State Board of Pharmacy staff directory. Board located at 2920 N Lincoln Blvd, Suite A, Oklahoma City, OK 73105."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS Adult and Family Treatment Services", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas/treatment/adult-family-treatment-services.html", "description": "The Oklahoma Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services (ODMHSAS) provides Medications for Opioid Use Disorder (MOUD) services statewide, including Office Based Opioid Treatment (OBOT) and Opioid Treatment Provider (OTP)/methadone clinics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator can be filtered by state to find substance use disorder treatment facilities in Oklahoma, including those offering buprenorphine and medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/medication-assisted-treatment/find-treatment/treatment-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for buprenorphine treatment practitioners, filterable by state to show Oklahoma providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS Homepage", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas.html", "description": "The Oklahoma Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services is the state agency overseeing all prevention, treatment, and education related to mental health and substance abuse. ODMHSAS has expanded access to medication-assisted treatment statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing (Federal Rule)", "url": "https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2025/01/17/2025-01049/expansion-of-buprenorphine-treatment-via-telemedicine-encounter", "description": "The DEA/HHS final rule (January 2025) governing telemedicine prescribing of buprenorphine for OUD. Oklahoma providers must comply with both federal rules and state telehealth regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Medicaid (SoonerCare) Pharmacy", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/ohca/providers/types/pharmacy/pharmacy.html", "description": "Oklahoma Health Care Authority (OHCA) pharmacy provider page for SoonerCare (Oklahoma Medicaid). Pharmacy Management Consultants manages pharmacy services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SoonerCare Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/okhca/docs/providers/types/pharmacy/drug-lists/brand%20name%20preferred.pdf", "description": "SoonerCare Brand Name Preferred Drug List. Buprenorphine products are covered with specific prior authorization criteria. Generic buprenorphine/naloxone is preferred; brand Suboxone films require clinical justification."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SoonerCare Buprenorphine Coverage", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/okhca/documents/a0302/23341.pdf", "description": "SoonerCare pharmacy bulletin regarding buprenorphine coverage. Contact Pharmacy Management Consultants at (800) 522-0114, option 4, or fax (800) 224-4014 for prior authorization questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SoonerCare Naloxone Coverage", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/ohca/about/newsroom/2023/august/ohca-removes-physician-visit-requirement-for-naloxone-hosts-vending-machine-with-odmhsas.html", "description": "SoonerCare covers naloxone products without requiring a physician visit. Members can obtain naloxone from SoonerCare contracted pharmacies with a standing order that allows pharmacies to initiate a prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Abatement Grants", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/oag/resources/grants/opioid-abatement-grant.html", "description": "Oklahoma's Opioid Abatement Grant program uses settlement funds to fund treatment and recovery programs, co-occurring disorder assistance, opioid abuse education and prevention, and strategies to decrease narcotics supply. Over $29 million has been distributed to 85 political subdivisions."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CE Requirements for Pharmacists", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/pharmacy/licensees-applications/education.html", "description": "Oklahoma pharmacists must complete 15 clock hours of continuing education per year through accredited programs as a condition for license renewal. Board-approved or ACPE-approved programs qualify for credit."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OU College of Pharmacy CE", "url": "https://pharmacy.ouhsc.edu/alumni/professional-development", "description": "The University of Oklahoma College of Pharmacy offers continuing pharmacy education programs. Oklahoma requires 15 hours of approved CE annually."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://opha.com/", "description": "The Oklahoma Pharmacists Association (OPhA) provides continuing education, advocacy, and professional development resources for Oklahoma pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA online registration forms. Since December 2022, all practitioners with Schedule III DEA registration authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD without an additional waiver."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS offers free training and mentoring on OUD prevention, diagnosis, and treatment, including buprenorphine prescribing education modules, webinars, and clinical tools."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Programs", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/health/services/personal-health/sexual-health-and-harm-reduction-service/harm-reduction.html", "description": "Oklahoma State Department of Health harm reduction page. Harm reduction sites must register with OSDH annually and comply with quarterly reporting. Authorized under SB 511. Contact: harmreduction@health.ok.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/health/services/personal-health/sexual-health-and-harm-reduction-service/harm-reduction.html", "description": "Oklahoma legalized syringe service programs. The OSDH Public Health Division provides guidance and registration requirements for establishing and operating harm reduction sites, including syringe exchange services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/ohca/about/newsroom/2023/august/ohca-removes-physician-visit-requirement-for-naloxone-hosts-vending-machine-with-odmhsas.html", "description": "In Oklahoma, pharmacists can dispense naloxone without a prescription. SoonerCare covers naloxone without requiring a physician visit. ODMHSAS also distributes naloxone through vending machines and community programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.kosu.org/show/stateimpact-oklahoma/2023-05-18/new-law-clarifies-fentanyl-test-strips-are-legal-in-oklahoma", "description": "Oklahoma passed a law in 2023 clarifying that fentanyl test strips are not considered drug paraphernalia. The law was enacted to help curtail the spike in fentanyl-related deaths."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/health/health-education/injury-prevention-service/drug-overdose/data/drug-overdose-data-dashboard.html", "description": "The Oklahoma State Department of Health Drug Overdose Data Dashboard displays the most recent information on fatal and nonfatal drug overdoses in Oklahoma, including counts, rates, proportions, trends, and demographic information at state and county levels."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS Recovery Services", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas/recovery/prss.html", "description": "ODMHSAS Peer Recovery Support Specialists (PRSS) page. Oklahoma has more than 1,000 actively certified peer support specialists providing recovery support services statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS Peer Recovery Support Specialist Certification", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas/trainings/workforce-certification/certified-peer-recovery-support-specialist.html", "description": "ODMHSAS administers the Certified Peer Recovery Support Specialist program. Training, testing, and certification are under the Mental Health Recovery Division. Applicants must complete training and pass a competency exam."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OCARTA Wellness Hub", "url": "https://www.ocartaoklahoma.org/", "description": "The Oklahoma C.A.R.T. Association (OCARTA) is a nonprofit providing peer support services to people in recovery throughout Oklahoma since 2002. OCARTA provides recovery housing, mentoring, PRSS supports, and case management."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery-Based Housing", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas/recovery/housing/recovery-based-housing.html", "description": "ODMHSAS recovery-based housing page listing certified recovery housing programs in Oklahoma. Programs are certified by OKARR (Oklahoma Alliance for Recovery Resources) following NARR national standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OKARR (Oklahoma Alliance for Recovery Resources)", "url": "https://okarr.org/projects/", "description": "OKARR partners with state agencies and recovery community organizations to advocate for high-quality housing standards. Projects include opioid recovery coordination in multiple counties."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS (Behavioral Health Agency)", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas.html", "description": "The Oklahoma Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services is the state's behavioral health agency overseeing prevention, treatment, and recovery from mental illness and substance abuse."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Services", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas.html", "description": "Oklahoma crisis services include the 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (call or text 988) and ODMHSAS crisis services. ODMHSAS coordinates behavioral health crisis response across the state."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Board of Pharmacy Executive Director", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/bop_members/oklahoma/", "description": "Marty Lee Hendrick, Executive Director. Oklahoma State Board of Pharmacy, 2920 N Lincoln Blvd, Suite A, Oklahoma City, OK 73105-4212."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Staff", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/pharmacy/about/staff.html", "description": "Oklahoma State Board of Pharmacy staff directory with current contact information for all board staff members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Health Care Authority (SoonerCare)", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/ohca/providers/types/pharmacy/pharmacy.html", "description": "Oklahoma Health Care Authority administers SoonerCare (Oklahoma Medicaid). Pharmacy Management Consultants: (800) 522-0114, option 4. Located in Oklahoma City, OK 73105."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS (State Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas.html", "description": "The Oklahoma Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services serves as the State Opioid Treatment Authority, overseeing OTP licensing and substance use disorder treatment services statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://opha.com/", "description": "The Oklahoma Pharmacists Association (OPhA) is the leading voice for pharmacy in Oklahoma. OPhA advocates for the profession through public policy, scope of practice advancement, and education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma State Department of Health", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/health.html", "description": "The Oklahoma State Department of Health oversees public health programs, including the Injury Prevention Service which manages drug overdose surveillance and harm reduction programs."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/health/health-education/injury-prevention-service/drug-overdose/data/drug-overdose-data-dashboard.html", "description": "The OSDH Drug Overdose Data Dashboard displays information on fatal and nonfatal drug overdoses in Oklahoma, including counts, rates, trends, and demographics. Death data include unintentional fatal drug overdoses by county of residence."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data Reports", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/health/health-education/injury-prevention-service/drug-overdose/data.html", "description": "The OSDH Injury Prevention Service monitors overdose trends using multiple data sources including SUDORS, hospitalization data, ED discharge data, PDMP dispensation data, and surveys."}, {"type": "link", "title": "County-Level Opioid Data", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/health/health2/documents/opioid-county-fact-sheet-oklahoma-county.pdf", "description": "Example of county-level opioid fact sheets from OSDH showing unintentional overdose deaths by substance type, with data available for all Oklahoma counties."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data Graphs and Maps", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/content/dam/ok/en/health/health2/aem-documents/prevention-and-preparedness/injury-prevention/drug-overdose/Drug%20Overdose%20Data%20Graphs%20and%20Maps.pdf", "description": "OSDH drug overdose data graphs and maps showing unintentional drug overdose death rates by county of residence and trends over time, including substance-specific breakdowns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS Prevalence Data", "url": "http://www.odmhsas.org/eda/prevalence.htm", "description": "ODMHSAS substance use prevalence data for Oklahoma based on NSDUH survey data. Oklahoma ranks approximately 12th nationally for rates of any mental illness, with an 8.21% rate for any substance abuse disorders."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://opha.com/", "description": "OPhA unites and promotes the profession of pharmacy through advocacy, communication, and education. OPhA aggressively advocates by shaping public policy and scope of practice to enhance the value of pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Abatement Board", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/oag/resources/meetings/opioid-abatement-board.html", "description": "Oklahoma's Opioid Abatement Board reviews and approves grant applications for opioid settlement funding. Created under Title 74, sections 30.3-30.8, the board oversees grants for treatment, recovery, education, and prevention programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oklahoma Opioid Settlement Spending (NASHP Tracker)", "url": "https://nashp.org/state-tracker/state-opioid-settlement-spending-decisions/oklahoma/", "description": "NASHP's tracker of Oklahoma's opioid settlement spending decisions, including state-level funding allocations, laws, and processes for distributing settlement funds."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find My Oklahoma Legislator", "url": "https://www.oklegislature.gov/findmylegislature.aspx", "description": "The Oklahoma Legislature's tool for finding state representatives and senators by address. Useful for contacting legislators about pharmacy practice or OUD treatment legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODMHSAS Comprehensive Opioid Initiatives", "url": "https://oklahoma.gov/odmhsas/treatment/adult-family-treatment-services.html", "description": "ODMHSAS comprehensive opioid prevention and treatment initiatives, including the statewide network of community-based treatment providers that has expanded access to medication-assisted treatment for opioid addiction."}]}]}, "oregon": {"name": "Oregon", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Oregon’s term for a CPA is an “agreement” for “collaborative drug therapy management” (CDTM). OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315(1) (2024).", "1A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it is only in limited cases.\nAs of April 2024, the definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oregon law expressly includes “the prescribing and dispensing of early refills of medication for the treatment of opioid use disorder pursuant to section 7 of [2024 OR. LEGIS. SERV. Ch. 70].” OR. REV. STAT.\nANN. § 689.005(29)(p) (West 2024), as amended by 2024 OR. LEGIS. SERV. Ch. 70, § 9 (West).\nAn “early refill” means “up to three refills of a current prescription for a medication that a patient has lost or that has been stolen or destroyed” or “one refill in a 12-month period of a medication for which the previous prescription expired in the prior 12 month period.” 2024 OR. LEGIS. SERV. Ch. 70, § 7 (West).\nThe new law directs the Oregon Board of Pharmacy to adopt rules to carry out this provision including rules allowing a pharmacist to apply for and obtain a DEA registration as a mid-level practitioner. 2024 OR. LEGIS. SERV. Ch. 70, § 7 (West).\nAlthough the April 2024 law change pre-dates DEA’s latest published information (dated November 2024), DEA information still indicates that registered pharmacists in Oregon cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.”", "1B": "Await adoption of regulations describing the process for obtaining a DEA mid-level practitioner registration and prescribing early refills of buprenorphine.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "1C": "Expand the Oregon practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment, beyond the limited early refill authorization granted by the 2024 law.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oregon law expressly includes “administering of drugs and devices to the extent permitted under ORS 689.655.” OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.005(29)(d) (West 2024).\nThe referenced Oregon law permits pharmacists to administer a drug or device so long as the pharmacist acts both “under the direction of or pursuant to a prescription or order of a licensed practitioner” and in accordance with Oregon Board of Pharmacy rules. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.655 (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain the direction of, prescription of, or order of a licensed practitioner.\nAdhere to the educational, training, and recordkeeping requirements specified in Oregon law and regulation. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.655 (West 2024); OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0305 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oregon law does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.005(29) (West 2024).\nAlthough not in the definition of the practice of pharmacy, another Oregon law provides that “a pharmacy” can perform CLIA-waived tests. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.661 (West 2024).\nMoreover, “a pharmacist may perform an HIV test or may order an HIV test performed by a laboratory.” OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.704(3) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Oregon practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "As described in the information below, Oregon laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” but only to a very limited extent.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oregon law does not expressly refer to collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM). OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.005(29) (West 2024).\nHowever, Oregon regulation provides that CDTM means the participation by a practitioner and a pharmacist in the management of drug therapy “pursuant to a written agreement that includes information on the dosage, frequency, duration and route of administration of the drug, authorized by a practitioner and initiated upon a prescription order for an individual patient.” OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315(1) (2024). Although this provision uses the word “initiated,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nMoreover, the CDTM agreement must include the “circumstances which will cause the pharmacist to initiate communication with the practitioner, including but not limited to the need for a new prescription order.” OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315(2)(d)(D) (2024). This provision may mean that a pharmacist is not authorized to prescribe and drug or medication under a CDTM agreement.\nEven if a CDTM agreement could allow an Oregon pharmacist to prescribe, the Oregon regulation governing such agreements does not expressly address obtaining a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes is necessary before a pharmacist can prescribe buprenorphine regardless of what the CDTM agreement provides. However, the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section indicates that, once the Oregon Board of Pharmacy adopts regulations, a pharmacist will be able to obtain a DEA registration to prescribe and dispense “early refills” of MOUD.\nIn summary, Oregon laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CDTM agreement. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because an Oregon pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary except in the very limited situation described in the response to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Oregon laws and/or regulations governing CDTM agreements to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Oregon laws or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CDTM agreements.\nAllow Oregon pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances in more situations than just prescribing “early refills.”", "5A": "As described in the information below, Oregon laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oregon law does not expressly refer to CDTM. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.005(29) (West 2024). Oregon regulation provides that CDTM means the participation by a practitioner and a pharmacist in the management of drug therapy “pursuant to a written agreement that includes information on the dosage, frequency, duration and route of administration of the drug, authorized by a practitioner and initiated upon a prescription order for an individual patient.” OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315(1) (2024). This provision may mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine under a CDTM agreement. If not, Oregon regulation governing CDTM does not directly address administering drugs or medications. OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315 (2024).\nAs a result, Oregon laws and regulations governing CDTM agreements are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can administer drugs or medications. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has the general authority to administer drugs outside of a CDTM agreement, the logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a CDTM agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in Oregon law or regulation that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CDTM agreement include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Oregon law does not expressly refer to CDTM. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.005(29) (West 2024).\nHowever, Oregon regulation governing CDTM provides that a pharmacist may “order and receive” laboratory tests as part of “managing drug therapy pursuant to the terms of a . . . [CDTM] agreement.” OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0310(1)(a) (2024).\nOregon pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly reference evaluating tests under a CDTM agreement.", "6B": "Enter into a CDTM agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Oregon law and regulation that a pharmacist’s authority under a CDTM agreement includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Oregon law provides that CDTM means the participation by a practitioner and a pharmacist in the management of drug therapy “pursuant to a written agreement that includes information on the dosage, frequency, duration and route of administration of the drug, authorized by a practitioner and initiated upon a prescription order for an individual patient.” OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315(1) (2024).\nA CDTM agreement may be between “one practitioner and one pharmacist,” or “one or more practitioners in a single organized medical group . . . and one or more pharmacists.” OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315(1) (2024).\n“Practitioner” means “a person licensed and operating within the scope of such license to prescribe, dispense, conduct research with respect to or administer drugs in the course of professional practice or research” in Oregon or another state. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.005(30) (West 2024).\nThe following Oregon regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CDTM agreements and required elements of CDTM agreements – OR. ADMIN. R. 855-115-0315 and 855-115-0310 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nOregon does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, Oregon health insurance law provides that a health benefit plan must provide coverage of a health service that is provided using telemedicine if, among other things, “the plan provides coverage of the health service when provided in person by a health professional.” OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 743A.058(2) (West 2024).\nA “health professional” is “a person licensed, certified or registered in this state to provide health care services or supplies.” O.R.S. § 743A.058(1)(c) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.\nOregon pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Oregon laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Oregon laws and regulations governing telehealth include – OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 414.723 (West 2024) (Medicaid); OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 442.015(26) (West 2024) (health planning); OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 677.494 (West 2024) (physicians); OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 689.700 (West 2024)\n(telepharmacy); OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 743A.058 (West 2024) (health insurance); OR. ADMIN. R. 409-045-0115 to 409-045-0135 (2024) (health care practitioner credentialing); OR. ADMIN. R. 410-120-1990 and 410-141-3566 (Medicaid); OR. ADMIN. R. 855-139-0001 to 855-139-0730 (telepharmacy).", "9A": "Whenever a health benefit plan provides for payment or reimbursement for a service that is within the lawful scope of practice of a pharmacist, the insurer “may provide payment or reimbursement for services when the service is provided by a pharmacist.” OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 743A.051(1)(a) (West 2024).244\nHowever, under the same provision, the insurer “shall provide, in the same manner as would be provided for any other health care provider, payment or reimbursement” to a pharmacist for: (1) prescription of emergency refills of insulin and associated insulin-related devices; (2) prescription, dispensation and administration of preexposure and post-exposure prophylactic antiretroviral therapies; (3) testing for severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) and the prescribing, dispensing and administering of treatment for SARS-CoV-2 (until June 29, 2026); and (4) prescription and dispensation of other prescription drugs by a licensed pharmacist if the Oregon Board of Pharmacy or any state law authorizes the drug to be prescribed and dispensed. OR. REV. STAT. ANN. § 743A.051(1)(b) (West 2024).\nIn addition, pharmacists are reimbursed for prescribing hormonal contraception, prescribing smoking cessation products, initiating vaccination, administering immunizations, providing medication therapy management, and preventive medicine counseling.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Oregon Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Oregon law or regulation that pharmacist services provided under a under a CDTM agreement are covered under the Oregon Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "There are several patient rights’ provisions in Oregon regulations that require that a patient receive medications specific to individual needs, including MOUD. OR. ADMIN. R. 309-018-0115 (2024) (residential SUD treatment); OR. ADMIN. R. 309-019-0115 (2024)\n(outpatient behavioral health); OR. ADMIN. R. 309-022-0115 (2024) (children and adolescent treatment); OR. ADMIN. R 415-050-0120 (2024) (alcohol detoxification centers).\nSeveral types of treatment facilities must allow patients to continue MOUD during their stay and/or are prohibited from “titration” of the MOUD of a patient as a condition to receiving or continuing treatment. OR. ADMIN. R. 309-018-0110 (2024) (residential SUD treatment); OR. ADMIN. R. 309-019-0110 (2024) (outpatient behavioral health); Or.\nAdmin. R. 415-050-0115 and 415-050-0140 (2024)\n(alcohol detoxification centers)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/pharmacy/pages/index.aspx", "description": "The Oregon Board of Pharmacy homepage. The Board promotes and protects public health, safety, and welfare by ensuring high standards in the practice of pharmacy and regulating the manufacture and distribution of drugs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Pharmacy Practice Act (ORS Chapter 689)", "url": "https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/bills_laws/ors/ors689.html", "description": "Full text of Oregon Revised Statutes Chapter 689, Pharmacists; Drug Outlets; Drug Sales, which constitutes the Oregon Pharmacy Practice Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (OAR Chapter 855)", "url": "https://secure.sos.state.or.us/oard/displayChapterRules.action?selectedChapter=19", "description": "Oregon Administrative Rules Chapter 855, Board of Pharmacy, containing all divisions of administrative rules governing pharmacy practice in Oregon."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Drug Therapy Management", "url": "https://oregon.public.law/rules/oar_855-019-0200", "description": "OAR 855-019-0200 outlines the general responsibilities of a pharmacist, including collaborative drug therapy management (CDTM). Oregon permits pharmacists to engage in CDTM pursuant to a valid written agreement with a practitioner or organized medical group."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescriptive Authority", "url": "https://secure.sos.state.or.us/oard/displayDivisionRules.action?selectedDivision=3968", "description": "OAR Chapter 855, Division 20 covers Pharmacist Prescriptive Authority. Oregon pharmacists licensed and located in the state may prescribe and dispense FDA-approved drugs and devices as authorized by the Board. Oregon has also adopted Division 115 rules expanding pharmacist prescribing. Note: CPAs explicitly prohibit pharmacist authority to prescribe controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon OHA Medication-Assisted Treatment Page", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/HSD/AMH/Pages/MAT.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority's page on Medication-Assisted Treatment for Opioid Use Disorder, including information about Opioid Treatment Programs that dispense and administer medications for OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator (FindTreatment.gov) where users can search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Oregon by location, services offered, and insurance accepted."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine. Can be filtered by state to find Oregon providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA)", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA's listing of State Opioid Treatment Authorities by state. Oregon's SOTA oversees opioid treatment program compliance within the state through the Oregon Health Authority."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon MOUD Fact Sheet", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/PREVENTIONWELLNESS/SUBSTANCEUSE/OPIOIDS/Documents/MOUD-factsheet.pdf", "description": "Oregon Health Authority fact sheet on Medication for Opioid Use Disorder (MOUD), including state-specific prescribing information and the Oregon Opioid Prescribing Guidelines."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.cchpca.org/oregon/", "description": "Center for Connected Health Policy (CCHP) summary of Oregon's telehealth laws and regulations, including Medicaid reimbursement policies. DEA flexibilities for telehealth prescribing of buprenorphine have been extended through 2025. Oregon requires Coordinated Care Organizations and FFS providers to offer patients a choice of telehealth or in-person services."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Health Plan Pharmaceutical Services", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/hsd/ohp/pages/policy-pharmacy.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority's Pharmaceutical Services Program page for the Oregon Health Plan (Medicaid), including NPI lookup, prescription drug coverage information, federal upper limits, and pricing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Preferred Drug List (PDL) and Prior Authorization", "url": "https://www.orpdl.org/drugs/", "description": "Searchable database of Oregon Health Plan fee-for-service Preferred Drug List and drug prior authorization requirements. Includes buprenorphine products and substance use disorder drug class listings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Drug Class Information", "url": "https://www.orpdl.org/drugs/drugclass.php?cid=1004", "description": "Oregon PDL substance use disorder drug class page, including buprenorphine products, prior authorization criteria, and clinical reviews for buprenorphine place in therapy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OHP Fee-for-Service Fee Schedule", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/hsd/ohp/pages/fee-schedule.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Plan fee-for-service fee schedule for provider reimbursement rates, billing tips, general rules, and payment policies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Professional Billing FAQ", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/HSD/OHP/Tools/Pharmacist%20fee-for-service%20community%20pharmacist%20professional%20billing.pdf", "description": "Oregon Health Authority FAQ document on pharmacist professional billing for community pharmacist services under OHP fee-for-service, including HCPCS, CPT, and ICD-10 codes and a pharmacist medical billing toolkit."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/hsd/amhpac/pages/block-grants.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority page on Mental Health and Substance Abuse Prevention and Treatment Block Grants, which provide funding for prevention, treatment, and recovery support services for uninsured or underinsured individuals."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Board of Pharmacy CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/pharmacy/pages/continuing-education-.aspx", "description": "Oregon Board of Pharmacy continuing pharmacy education page. Oregon pharmacists must complete continuing education including a minimum of 2 hours in pharmacy and drug law. Pharmacist clinicians with controlled substance registration to prescribe Schedule II and III substances must complete 2 hours of responsible opioid prescribing practices CE."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Board of Pharmacy CE FAQ", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/pharmacy/Documents/RPHCE_FAQs.pdf", "description": "Frequently asked questions about Oregon pharmacist continuing education requirements, including specific requirements for therapeutics, pharmacy law, and other healthcare topics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon State Pharmacy Association (OSPA) Education", "url": "https://oregonpharmacy.org/", "description": "OSPA provides continuing education opportunities, clinical updates, hands-on training, networking events, and annual conferences for pharmacy professionals across Oregon. Please verify this link before publishing (Cloudflare protection detected during verification)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division online forms and applications page for DEA registration, including registration for buprenorphine prescribing. Since the MATE Act, all DEA registrants must complete required training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "The Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, podcasts, clinical tools, and mentoring for providers treating OUD, including buprenorphine prescribing guidance."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Syringe Services Program Directory", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/DISEASESCONDITIONS/HIVSTDVIRALHEPATITIS/HIVPREVENTION/Pages/ssp.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority's Syringe Services Program page, with information about Oregon law allowing syringe exchange programs and links to directories including NASEN and 211 for finding services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Pharmacist Prescribing", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/pharmacy/pages/naloxone-prescribing.aspx", "description": "Oregon Board of Pharmacy page on short-acting opioid antagonist (naloxone, nalmefene) prescribing. Oregon pharmacists can prescribe, dispense, distribute, and administer naloxone without formal certification or additional training requirements (per HB 3440 of 2017)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Naloxone Distribution and Resources", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ph/preventionwellness/substanceuse/opioids/pages/reverseoverdose.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority page on opioid overdose reversal medications. Pharmacists can prescribe naloxone under OHA standing order or statewide protocol authorized by the Board of Pharmacy. Includes information on naloxone distribution programs and cost assistance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Pharmacy Naloxone Toolkit", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/PREVENTIONWELLNESS/SUBSTANCEUSE/OPIOIDS/Documents/2024%20Pharmacy%20Naloxone%20Toolkit.pdf", "description": "Oregon Health Authority's pharmacy naloxone toolkit with key legal information including HB 3440 (2017) allowing pharmacist naloxone prescribing and HB 4143 (2018) allowing dispensing without direct prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality and Information", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/PREVENTIONWELLNESS/SUBSTANCEUSE/OPIOIDS/Pages/FentanylFacts.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority fentanyl facts page. Fentanyl test strips are legal in Oregon following passage of 2023 legislation that exempted them from drug paraphernalia laws. The page includes harm reduction guidance including testing substances before use."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://oregoninjurydata.shinyapps.io/overdose/", "description": "Oregon Health Authority's interactive drug overdose surveillance dashboard containing death, hospital discharge, and emergency room discharge data for 11 drug categories, with statewide annual trends and county-level and demographic breakdowns."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Recovers (Recovery Community Organization)", "url": "https://oregonrecovers.org/", "description": "Oregon Recovers is a statewide recovery community organization building a movement of people in recovery, families, and healthcare workers to bring prevention, treatment, and recovery support services to all Oregonians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Network of Oregon", "url": "https://recoverynetworkoforegon.org/", "description": "Recovery Network of Oregon is a directory of support services, providers, peers, and meetings designed to assist people with recovery from drugs and alcohol. Includes real recovery stories and community resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Recovery Resources", "url": "https://oregonrecovers.org/resources/", "description": "Oregon Recovers resource page with links to directories, peer support services, community organizing tools, and other recovery support resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://www.transitionalhousing.org/state/oregon", "description": "Directory of transitional and sober housing options in Oregon, including Oxford House locations and other recovery housing programs throughout the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Behavioral Health Division", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/hsd/amh/pages/index.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority Behavioral Health Division homepage. Provides access to health, mental health, and addiction services and supports for Oregon adults and children through collaboration with counties, providers, advocates, and communities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis and Helpline Contacts", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/hsd/amh/pages/get-help.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority Get Help Now page with crisis contacts including 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline (call, text, or chat), Oregon Youthline (877-968-8491), and links to local community mental health programs. Lines for Life (linesforlife.org) is Oregon's home for the 988 Lifeline."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/pharmacy/pages/contact-us.aspx", "description": "Oregon Board of Pharmacy contact page. Main phone: 971-673-0001. Email: pharmacy.board@bop.oregon.gov. Address: 800 NE Oregon Street, Suite 150, Portland, OR 97232. The executive director position was held by Joseph Schnabel until his retirement in November 2023; contact the Board directly for current leadership."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Health Authority Contacts", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/pages/contact-us.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority main contact directory with information for the Director's Office, OHA divisions, and popular services and programs including Medicaid and pharmacy services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Medicaid Policy Contact", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/hsd/medicaid-policy/pages/contact-us.aspx", "description": "Contact information for Oregon Medicaid Waiver and policy staff within the Health Systems Division."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/HSD/AMH/Pages/MAT.aspx", "description": "Oregon's SOTA functions are managed through the Oregon Health Authority under the Behavioral Health Division. Contact OHA for the current SOTA designee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon State Pharmacy Association (OSPA) Contact", "url": "https://oregonpharmacy.org/", "description": "Oregon State Pharmacy Association is the leading professional organization representing pharmacists, student pharmacists, and pharmacy technicians in Oregon. Contact OSPA for executive leadership information. Please verify this link before publishing (Cloudflare protection detected during verification)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Health Authority Opioid Program", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/PREVENTIONWELLNESS/SUBSTANCEUSE/OPIOIDS/Pages/data.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority Public Health Division's opioid data and programs page, with links to overdose data, prescribing data, and prevention initiatives."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Overdose Death Dashboard", "url": "https://oregoninjurydata.shinyapps.io/overdose/", "description": "Interactive dashboard with death, hospital discharge, and ER data for drug overdoses in Oregon across 11 drug categories. Includes statewide annual trends, county-level data, and demographic breakdowns."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Prescribing and Overdose Data Page", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ph/preventionwellness/substanceuse/opioids/pages/data.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority hub for prescribing and overdose data, including links to the interactive dashboard, annual reports, and detailed data breakdowns by drug category."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Opioid Data Report", "url": "https://sharedsystems.dhsoha.state.or.us/dhsforms/served/le2479_22.pdf", "description": "Oregon Health Authority report on opioids and the ongoing drug overdose crisis in Oregon, using death certificates, medical examiner reports, and toxicology data for detailed contextual information about overdose deaths."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Quarterly Reports", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/PREVENTIONWELLNESS/SAFELIVING/PDMP/Documents/4th_Quarter_2024_Report.pdf", "description": "Oregon PDMP quarterly reports with prescriber enrollment and use statistics, special request data, and PDMP activity summary statistics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Publicly Funded SUD Treatment Analysis", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/adpc/MeetingDocuments/SB1041Report.pdf", "description": "Analysis of Oregon's publicly funded substance use disorder treatment data, including counts of members with OUD receiving pharmacotherapy, Medicaid enrollees with active SUD, and treatment utilization data."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Opioid Prescribing Guidelines Task Force", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/ph/preventionwellness/substanceuse/opioids/pages/task-force.aspx", "description": "Oregon Health Authority's Opioid Prescribing Guidelines Task Force page. The task force has approved Oregon-specific opioid prescribing guidelines to address opioid use, misuse, and overdose by optimizing care and improving patient safety."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OSPA Advocacy Page", "url": "https://oregonpharmacy.org/advocacy/", "description": "Oregon State Pharmacy Association advocacy page. OSPA aggressively advocates on behalf of the pharmacy profession before the State Legislature, state agencies, Congress, and other healthcare stakeholders. Please verify this link before publishing (Cloudflare protection detected during verification)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Opioid Settlement Prevention, Treatment and Recovery Board", "url": "https://www.oregon.gov/oha/PH/PREVENTIONWELLNESS/SUBSTANCEUSE/OPIOIDS/Pages/OSPTR-board.aspx", "description": "The OSPTR Board determines how to allocate the state's portion of Oregon's opioid settlement funds for prevention, treatment, and recovery efforts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Oregon Legislator", "url": "https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/FindYourLegislator/districts-initial.html", "description": "Oregon Legislature's tool for finding your state representative and senator by entering your address, enabling direct contact with legislators on pharmacy and OUD-related policy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Oregon Recovers (OUD Coalition)", "url": "https://oregonrecovers.org/", "description": "Oregon Recovers is a broad, inclusive coalition building a statewide movement to implement a comprehensive policy agenda addressing the addiction crisis, working to make Oregon the Recovery State through advocacy and policy change."}]}]}, "pennsylvania": {"name": "Pennsylvania", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Pennsylvania’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative agreement” for drug therapy management (DTM) in a non-institutional setting. 63 PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. § 390-2(14) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Pennsylvania law does not expressly include prescribing. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(11) (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Pennsylvania cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Pennsylvania practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Pennsylvania pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Pennsylvania law expressly includes “drug administration.” PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(11) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the types of drugs or medications that can be administered and may mean a pharmacist has general authority to administer buprenorphine.\n However, Pennsylvania law expressly grants pharmacists the authority to administer “injectable medications” to individuals aged 18 or older. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-9.2 (West 2024).249If the general “drug administration” phrase in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions in law or regulation. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in Pennsylvania may be limited. The provision regarding injectable medications appears to cover certain forms of buprenorphine, however.\n“Drug administration” may occur “only pursuant to a medical order.” PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(16) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain a medical order.\nAdhere to the educational, training, and recordkeeping requirements specified in Pennsylvania laws and regulations. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-9.2 (West 2024);250 49 PA. CODE §§ 27.401 to 27.408 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Pennsylvania law does not expressly include ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(11) (West 2024).\nAlthough not in the definition of the practice of pharmacy, other Pennsylvania law provides that a pharmacy or pharmacist may “order and perform laboratory examinations and procedures” for COVID-19, influenza and streptococcal infections if the pharmacy “holds a valid certificate of waiver issued by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services.” PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-9.5 (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Pennsylvania practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Pennsylvania law expressly includes “drug therapy management” (DTM) PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(11) (West 2024).\nAlthough the definition of DTM mentions “adjusting a drug regimen,” there is no express reference in the definition to prescribing drugs or medications. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(14) (West 2024).\nIn addition, Pennsylvania regulation governing collaborative agreements in non-institutional settings expressly provides that the provisions of the agreement identifying the manner in which a pharmacist can manage drug therapy “does not provide prescriptive authority to a pharmacist.” 49 PA. CODE § 27.302(f)(5) (2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Pennsylvania laws and/or regulations governing collaborative agreements to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Pennsylvania laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under collaborative agreements.\nAllow Pennsylvania pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Pennsylvania law includes DTM. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(11) (West 2024).\nOne of the services that may be performed by a pharmacist as part of DTM is “administration of drugs.” PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(14) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the types of drugs or medications a pharmacist can administer.\nMoreover, Pennsylvania laws and regulations governing DTM do not expressly limit the types of drugs that a pharmacist can administer.", "5B": "Enter into a collaborative agreement for DTM (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": null, "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Pennsylvania law includes DTM. PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(11) (West 2024).\nOne of the services that may be performed by a pharmacist as part of DTM is “ordering laboratory tests and ordering and performing other diagnostic tests necessary in the management of drug therapy.” PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-2(14) (West 2024).\nPennsylvania laws and regulations governing collaborative agreements for DTM do not expressly address evaluating the results of lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a collaborative agreement for DTM (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Pennsylvania law and regulation that a pharmacist’s authority under a collaborative agreement for DTM includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A pharmacist may enter into a collaborative agreement for DTM with a licensed physician for DTM “in a setting other than an institutional setting.” PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-9.3(a) (West 2024). DTM in an institutional setting involves a written protocol, not a collaborative agreement.\nThe following Pennsylvania laws and regulations provides more information on requirements for entering collaborative agreements for DTM and required elements of such agreements – 63 PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 390-9.3 (West 2024); 49 PA. CODE § 27.302 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nPennsylvania does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law. However, as of October 2024, Pennsylvania insurance law provides that a health insurance policy offered, issued or renewed in Pennsylvania “shall provide coverage for medically necessary health care services provided through telemedicine and delivered by a participating network provider who provides a covered health care service through telemedicine consistent with the insurer’s medical policies.” 40 PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 4803(a) (West 2024).\n“Health care provider” includes any individual “that is licensed, certified or otherwise regulated to provide health care services” under Pennsylvania laws or the laws of another state. 40 PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 4802 (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Pennsylvania laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "The lone Pennsylvania laws governing telehealth are the following first effective in October 2024 – 40 PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. §§ 4801 to 4805 (West 2024) (insurance, including Medicaid).", "9A": "Tobacco cessation counseling services.\nAs of March 2024, pharmacists may enroll as individual (mid-level) practitioners and provide services to Medicaid beneficiaries within the scope of the pharmacist’s license. To date, not all types of services may have associated pharmacist billing codes, however.", "9B": "Adopt regulations and billable codes so that reimbursement of SUD treatment-related pharmacist services provided under a collaborative agreement for DTM can occur under the Pennsylvania Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "“A health care practitioner shall refer an individual for treatment if the individual is believed to be at risk for substance abuse while seeking treatment in an emergency department or urgent care center or when in observation status in a health care facility.” 35 PA. STAT. AND CONS. STAT. ANN. § 873.4 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dos/department-and-offices/bpoa/boards-commissions/pharmacy", "description": "The Pennsylvania State Board of Pharmacy regulates the practice of pharmacy through licensure, registration, certification, and discipline of pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, pharmacy technician trainees, pharmacy interns, and pharmacies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Pharmacy Act (Act 699 of 1961)", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/content/dam/copapwp-pagov/en/dos/department-and-offices/bpoa/pharmacy/Law%20-%20Act%20699%20of%201961.pdf", "description": "Full text of the Pennsylvania Pharmacy Act (Act of September 27, 1961, P.L. 1700, No. 699), the primary statute governing pharmacy practice in the Commonwealth."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (49 Pa. Code Chapter 27)", "url": "https://www.pacodeandbulletin.gov/Display/pacode?file=/secure/pacode/data/049/chapter27/chap27toc.html&d=reduce", "description": "Pennsylvania Code Title 49, Chapter 27 - State Board of Pharmacy regulations, containing definitions, pharmacy permits, pharmacist manager requirements, and all administrative rules governing pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Regulations", "url": "https://www.pacodeandbulletin.gov/Display/pacode?file=/secure/pacode/data/049/chapter27/s27.302.html", "description": "49 Pa. Code Section 27.302 governing collaborative agreements for management of drug therapy in non-institutional settings. Pennsylvania allows pharmacists to engage in collaborative drug therapy management with physicians under written agreements that must be approved by the Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CPA and Protocol Toolkit", "url": "https://www.papharmacists.com/page/ToolkitCPAProtocols", "description": "Pennsylvania Pharmacists Association toolkit for collaborative practice agreements and protocols, providing guidance and templates for pharmacists establishing CPAs."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania DDAP Treatment Locator", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap/treatment-and-support/substance-use-disorder-treatment", "description": "Pennsylvania Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs treatment page. Individuals can call the PA Get Help Now helpline at 1-800-662-HELP (4357) for treatment referrals. Includes links to drug and alcohol facility locators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator where users can search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Pennsylvania by location, services, and insurance type."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine, filterable by state to find Pennsylvania providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA's listing of State Opioid Treatment Authorities by state. Pennsylvania's SOTA oversees opioid treatment program compliance through the Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Buprenorphine Prescribing", "url": "https://www.cchpca.org/pennsylvania/", "description": "Center for Connected Health Policy summary of Pennsylvania telehealth laws and policies. DEA telehealth flexibilities for buprenorphine prescribing have been extended through 2025. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dhs/resources/pharmacy-services", "description": "Pennsylvania Department of Human Services Pharmacy Services program, overseeing the outpatient prescription drug benefit for all Medicaid-eligible beneficiaries and administering the pharmacy benefit."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dhs/resources/pharmacy-services/preferred-drug-list", "description": "Pennsylvania's Statewide Preferred Drug List (PDL) maintained by the Department of Human Services for Medical Assistance program beneficiaries in both FFS and managed care."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Covered Drugs Search Tool", "url": "https://www.humanservices.dhs.pa.gov/CoveredDrugs/CoveredDrugs/Index", "description": "DHS Pharmacy Services searchable covered drugs tool, updated weekly, allowing lookup of specific drugs and their PDL class status, including buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Provider Status and Billing", "url": "https://www.papharmacists.com/page/PAProviderStatus_MA", "description": "PPA page on Pennsylvania pharmacist provider status under Medical Assistance. Beginning March 1, 2024, DHS enrolls pharmacists as PT 10 (Mid-Level Practitioner)/Spec 247. Includes links to FFS pharmacist billing procedures and relevant Medical Assistance Bulletins."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OUD Treatment Funding and Grants", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants providing funding for states to increase access to MOUD, support prevention and treatment for OUD and stimulant use disorders. Pennsylvania receives SOR funding through the Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.papharmacists.com/page/CE_Requirements", "description": "All licensed pharmacists in Pennsylvania must complete 30 contact hours of ACPE-approved continuing education during the biennial renewal period (ending September 30 in even-numbered years). Includes 2-3 hours of child abuse recognition and reporting CE, and 4 hours of opioid-related education (2 hours pain management/addiction identification + 2 hours opioid prescribing/dispensing practices)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Licensure Requirements", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dos/department-and-offices/bpoa/boards-commissions/pharmacy/pharmacist-licensure-snapshot", "description": "Pennsylvania Board of Pharmacy licensure snapshot page with information on CE requirements, including the ABC-MAP opioid education requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Pharmacists Association CE", "url": "https://www.papharmacists.com/page/ContinuingEducation", "description": "PPA continuing education page offering CE programs for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians, including accredited courses relevant to substance use disorder treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division online forms and applications for DEA registration, including MATE Act training requirements for controlled substance prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Providers Clinical Support System for Medications for OUD (PCSS-MOUD) offers free training modules, webinars, clinical tools, and mentoring for providers treating OUD with buprenorphine."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PA Harm Reduction Network", "url": "https://www.pahrn.org/", "description": "Pennsylvania Harm Reduction Network provides resources, advocacy, and education for harm reduction services across the state, including syringe services program information and naloxone resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.pahrn.org/ssps", "description": "PAHRN's syringe services program page with information on expanding access to SSPs in Pennsylvania and advocacy materials for harm reduction policy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/health/programs/opioids/naloxone", "description": "Pennsylvania Department of Health naloxone page. Pennsylvania has a statewide standing order authorizing pharmacists to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription. Pharmacists can treat the standing order as a verbal order for Medical Assistance beneficiaries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order Document", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/content/dam/copapwp-pagov/en/health/documents/topics/documents/opioids/General%20Public%20Standing%20Order.pdf", "description": "The actual Pennsylvania General Public Standing Order document authorizing pharmacists to dispense naloxone and devices for their administration. Also enables community-based organizations to distribute naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.billthompsonlaw.com/blog/2023/04/what-to-know-about-pennsylvanias-new-fentanyl-test-strip-law/", "description": "Pennsylvania legalized fentanyl test strips in 2023, removing them from the drug paraphernalia classification. Fentanyl test strips are now legal to possess and use in the Commonwealth."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://data.pa.gov/stories/s/Pennsylvania-Opioids/9q45-nckt/", "description": "Pennsylvania Opioid Data Dashboard on the PA Open Data Portal, providing comprehensive data behind Pennsylvania's response to the opioid crisis including overdose deaths, treatment data, and county-level information."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DDAP Recovery Support", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap/recovery", "description": "Pennsylvania Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs recovery page, including the Recovery Rising initiative to foster a resilient, diverse, and accessible recovery environment in the Commonwealth."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DDAP Support Services Directory", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap/treatment-and-support/support-services", "description": "List of organizations and resources for individuals in recovery and families impacted by substance use disorder, compiled by the Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap/treatment-and-support/housing", "description": "DDAP housing page with links to the Drug and Alcohol Facility Locator for licensed recovery houses. Includes information on halfway houses providing treatment and home-like atmospheres."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Alliance of Recovery Residences (PARR)", "url": "https://www.parronline.org", "description": "PARR is the state affiliate of NARR (National Alliance for Recovery Residences), certifying recovery residences across Pennsylvania."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap", "description": "DDAP is Pennsylvania's single state agency for substance use disorder prevention, intervention, treatment, and recovery services, serving as the state behavioral health agency for SUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Contact - PA Get Help Now", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap/treatment-and-support/substance-use-disorder-treatment", "description": "PA Get Help Now helpline: 1-800-662-HELP (4357). A toll-free helpline for individuals seeking treatment or support for substance use disorders for themselves or a loved one."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dos/department-and-offices/bpoa/boards-commissions/pharmacy", "description": "Pennsylvania State Board of Pharmacy, Bureau of Professional and Occupational Affairs. Phone: 717-783-7156. Address: P.O. Box 2649, Harrisburg, PA 17105-2649."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania DHS Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dhs/resources/pharmacy-services", "description": "Department of Human Services Pharmacy Services division contact for Medicaid pharmacy benefit inquiries, preferred drug list, and prior authorization questions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DDAP Contact", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap", "description": "Pennsylvania Department of Drug and Alcohol Programs, the state's substance use disorder authority. Address: 2601 N. Third Street, Suite 200, Harrisburg, PA 17110."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.papharmacists.com/", "description": "PPA is the leading voice of pharmacy in Pennsylvania, promoting the profession through advocacy, education, and communication. Phone: 717-234-6151. Address: 508 North Third Street, Harrisburg, PA 17101."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Health Opioid Programs", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/health/programs/opioids/naloxone", "description": "Pennsylvania Department of Health opioid programs, including naloxone access, PDMP administration, and overdose surveillance through the Office of Drug Surveillance and Misuse Prevention."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Opioid Data Dashboard", "url": "https://data.pa.gov/stories/s/Pennsylvania-Opioids/9q45-nckt/", "description": "Comprehensive Pennsylvania Opioid Data Dashboard on the Open Data Portal, providing data behind the state's opioid crisis response including overdose deaths, prescribing trends, and county-level data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Opioid Treatment Data", "url": "https://data.pa.gov/stories/s/Pennsylvania-Opioids-Treatment/fvkx-eumb/", "description": "Treatment-specific opioid data dashboard showing efforts to increase access to treatment for OUD, including MAT utilization data across the Commonwealth."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DDAP Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.ddap.pa.gov/Pages/Data-Dashboard.aspx", "description": "DDAP program measures dashboard including SCA-funded treatment admissions, licensed treatment facility capacity, Get Help Now hotline call volume, and links to fatal and non-fatal drug overdose surveillance data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Data Reports", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/health/healthcare-and-public-health-professionals/pdmp/data", "description": "Interactive PDMP and overdose data reports from the Office of Drug Surveillance and Misuse Prevention, including prescribing patterns and controlled substance dispensing data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PA Opioid Settlement Data", "url": "https://www.paopioidsettlementdata.org/programs/", "description": "Pennsylvania opioid settlement data site with information on remediation programs, recovery housing investments, peer support services, and allocation of settlement funds by county."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PPA Advocacy and Legislative Priorities", "url": "https://www.papharmacists.com/", "description": "Pennsylvania Pharmacists Association advocates for the pharmacy profession through legislative initiatives including pharmacist provider status, PharmPAC, Pharmacy Legislative Day, and the Legislative Action Center. Access advocacy resources from the PPA homepage."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pennsylvania Society of Health-System Pharmacists Legislative Updates", "url": "https://www.pshp.org/page/StateUpdates", "description": "PSHP state legislative updates page tracking current legislation related to pharmacy practice in Pennsylvania, including Senate Bill 1133 to expand Board of Pharmacy representation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your PA Legislator", "url": "https://www.palegis.us/find-my-legislator", "description": "Pennsylvania General Assembly's tool for finding your state senator and representative by entering your address, enabling direct contact on pharmacy and OUD-related policy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DDAP Recovery and Policy Initiatives", "url": "https://www.pa.gov/agencies/ddap/recovery", "description": "DDAP's policy initiatives including Recovery Rising, designed to transform the recovery environment in Pennsylvania through evidence-based policy and investment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PA Harm Reduction Network Advocacy", "url": "https://www.pahrn.org/resources", "description": "PAHRN advocacy resources including educational materials for harm reduction policy, syringe services program expansion, naloxone allocation, and outreach materials for community organizations."}]}]}, "puertorico": {"name": "Puerto Rico", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe “functions of the pharmacist” identified in Puerto Rico law do not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407b (2024).\nMoreover, the definition of “prescribing professional” in Puerto Rico pharmacy law contains an identified list of professions that does not include pharmacists. P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407(tt) (2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Puerto Rico cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Puerto Rico to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Puerto Rico pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe “functions of the pharmacist” identified in Puerto Rico law expressly addresses administration only with respect to “administer[ing] vaccines, pursuant to the provisions of subsection (e) of § 410(c) of this title.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407b(i) (2024).\nIn addition, the definition of “administration of drugs” in Puerto Rico law provides that “in the case of vaccination administration to humans, these may be administered by duly certified pharmacists, as provided in this chapter.”\nP.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407(a) (2024). There is no other express reference to pharmacist authority to administer in the definition, which indicates that a pharmacist’s administration authority is limited.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Puerto Rico to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe “functions of the pharmacist” identified in Puerto Rico law do not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407b(i) (2024).\nMoreover, no other Puerto Rico pharmacy laws address ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Puerto Rico to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe “functions of the pharmacist” identified in Puerto Rico law include “manag[ing] the pharmacotherapy of the patient collaboratively with the physician or group of physicians following a protocol, without affecting the patient’s free selection of the pharmacy that will dispense his/her drugs.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407b(e) (2024).\nA “protocol” is a document “authorizing the pharmacist to initiate or modify the pharmacotherapy of the patient to collaboratively manage the same.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407(vv) (2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiate or modify” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nPuerto Rico pharmacy laws contain no further explanation as to what managing the pharmacotherapy of the patient may or may not entail and whether that includes prescribing drugs and medications.\nEven if a protocol could allow a Puerto Rico pharmacist to prescribe drugs, Puerto Rico laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a Puerto Rico pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the protocol provides.\nIn summary, Puerto Rico laws do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a protocol. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Puerto Rico pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Puerto Rico laws and/or regulations governing collaborative protocols to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Puerto Rico laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under collaborative protocols.\nAllow Puerto Rico pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Puerto Rico laws do not clearly answer this question.\nThe “functions of the pharmacist” identified in Puerto Rico law include “manag[ing] the pharmacotherapy of the patient collaboratively with the physician or group of physicians following a protocol, without affecting the patient’s free selection of the pharmacy that will dispense his/her drugs.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407b(e) (2024).\nA “protocol” is a document “authorizing the pharmacist to initiate or modify the pharmacotherapy of the patient to collaboratively manage the same.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407(vv) (2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiate or modify,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications. However, the provision could be interpreted to allow a pharmacist to administer buprenorphine.\nPuerto Rico pharmacy laws contain no further explanation as to what managing the pharmacotherapy of the patient may or may not entail and whether that includes administering drugs and medications.\nIn summary, although Puerto Rico pharmacy laws do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine as part of a collaborative protocol, they also do not clearly authorize it and a pharmacist does not have general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a protocol.", "5B": "Enter into a collaborative protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Puerto Rico laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a collaborative protocol include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Puerto Rico laws do not clearly answer this question.\nThe “functions of the pharmacist” identified in Puerto Rico law include “manag[ing] the pharmacotherapy of the patient collaboratively with the physician or group of physicians following a protocol, without affecting the patient’s free selection of the pharmacy that will dispense his/her drugs.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407b(e) (2024).\nA “protocol” is a document “authorizing the pharmacist to initiate or modify the pharmacotherapy of the patient to collaboratively manage the same.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407(vv) (2024).\nPuerto Rico pharmacy laws contain no further explanation as to what managing the pharmacotherapy of the patient may or may not entail and whether that includes ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests.\nIn summary, although Puerto Rico pharmacy laws do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests as part of a collaborative protocol, they also do not clearly authorize those activities and a pharmacist does not have general authority to perform those activities outside of a protocol.", "6B": "Enter into a collaborative protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Puerto Rico laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a collaborative protocol include ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A protocol is a document to execute the written agreement between “the physician or group of physicians” and a pharmacist to collectively manage the pharmacotherapy of a patient. P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 407(vv) (2024).\nThere little information in Puerto Rico law about the requirements for entering collaborative protocols and required elements of collaborative protocols and what exists is here – P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, §§ 407(vv), 407b(e) (2024).", "8A": "No, based on the information described below.\nPuerto Rico’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice act requires a certification to practice telemedicine. The law expressly provides that the certification “shall only be issued to physicians holding a valid license in the jurisdiction of Puerto Rico or in the federal jurisdiction” although “skilled nursing facilities, physical therapists, occupational therapists, and speech therapists shall be included for telemedicine purposes.” P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, § 6011a (2024).", "8B": "Expressly provide in Puerto Rico laws and/or regulations that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "Puerto Rico laws governing telehealth include – P.R. LAWS ANN. tit. 20, §§ 6011 to 6011k (2024).", "9A": "None. Pharmacists can enroll in the Puerto Rico Medicaid program as an ordering/prescribing/referring provider, but pharmacists may not render or bill for services.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Puerto Rico Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Puerto Rico laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a collaborative protocol are covered under the Puerto Rico Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Page", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/pdmp", "description": "Puerto Rico Prescription Drug Monitoring Program (PDMP) page, administered by the Administracion de Servicios de Salud Mental y Contra la Adiccion (ASSMCA). Established under PR Law 70 of 2017, implemented in May 2018. All pharmacies operating in Puerto Rico must electronically report all controlled substance dispensing within 48 hours."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal Login", "url": "https://puertorico.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "PMP AWARxE login portal for the Puerto Rico PDMP. Healthcare professionals including physicians, pharmacists, psychiatrists, social workers, and psychologists can register for free and access patient controlled substance histories. Contact: pdmp@assmca.pr.gov."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Puerto Rico requires mandatory registration and use of the PDMP by prescribers and dispensers. All pharmacies must report Schedule II-V controlled substance dispensing data within 48 hours. Puerto Rico shares data with 33 U.S. states through PMP InterConnect. The system is provided by Bamboo Health and funded by federal Department of Justice grants."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Data Dashboard", "url": "https://datosopioides.pr.gov/datacardscollection/pdmp", "description": "Puerto Rico Opioids Dashboard PDMP section showing data on most dispensed opioids, distribution by age and sex, opioid use by municipality, and other visualizations based on PDMP data from May 2018 through recent periods."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the PMP AWARxE system by authorized prescribers and pharmacists. Contact pdmp@assmca.pr.gov for registration assistance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Bamboo Health Support: 833-276-0091 for PMP AWARxE technical support."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy (Junta Examinadora de Farmacia)", "url": "https://www.salud.pr.gov/CMS/116", "description": "Puerto Rico Board of Pharmacy (Junta Examinadora de Farmacia) page on the Department of Health website. Contains pharmacy laws, regulations, resolutions, and application forms for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Department of Health", "url": "https://www.salud.pr.gov/", "description": "Puerto Rico Department of Health (Departamento de Salud) homepage. The Junta Examinadora de Farmacia operates under the Department of Health."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacy Laws and Regulations: The Board of Pharmacy page at salud.pr.gov includes links to Reglamento General 8503 and other regulations governing pharmacy practice in Puerto Rico. The Pharmacy Practice Act is found in Puerto Rico law governing professions and occupations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colegio de Farmaceuticos de Puerto Rico (CFPR)", "url": "https://cfpr.org/", "description": "Colegio de Farmaceuticos de Puerto Rico, the professional association for pharmacists in Puerto Rico. ACPE-accredited CE provider (Provider 0151). Phone: (787) 753-7157. Email: educacion@cfpr.org. P.O. Box 360206, San Juan, PR 00936-0206."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice Agreements: Puerto Rico pharmacy law permits collaborative practice between pharmacists and physicians. Contact the Junta Examinadora de Farmacia for specific CPA requirements and templates."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Puerto Rico does not have broad independent pharmacist prescribing authority. Pharmacists may provide services under collaborative agreements and have authority to administer vaccines and certain medications as authorized by the Board."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ASSMCA Treatment Services", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/tratamientos", "description": "ASSMCA treatment services page listing substance use disorder services available across all 78 municipalities of Puerto Rico, including specialized programs (SEVAS), medication-assisted treatment, and residential services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASSMCA Special Projects (PR SOR)", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/proyectos-especiales", "description": "ASSMCA special projects page including the Puerto Rico State Opioid Response (PRSOR) program. Includes harm reduction services, naloxone distribution, fentanyl test strips, peer support, naltrexone and buprenorphine treatment expansion, HIV/hepatitis screening, and new medication-assisted treatment clinics (CTIAM) in Fajardo, Vega Baja, and Arecibo."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Puerto Rico, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grupo Nexos PAICO-PR", "url": "https://www.nexospr.org/en/2025/09/24/transforming-the-response-to-the-opioid-crisis/", "description": "Grupo Nexos leads the Project for the Comprehensive Response to the Opioid Crisis in Puerto Rico (PAICO-PR), funded through the Opioid Recovery and Restitution Fund administered by the Department of Health. A three-year plan (2024-2027) focused on improving treatment access, reviewing treatment standards, and developing public policy recommendations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: ASSMCA serves as the equivalent of the State Opioid Treatment Authority for Puerto Rico. ASSMCA (Administracion de Servicios de Salud Mental y Contra la Adiccion) oversees opioid treatment programs, the PDMP, and the State Opioid Response grant. Website", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/", "description": ""}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), healthcare providers no longer need an X-waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of DEA registration or renewal. Puerto Rico follows federal requirements."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine: Puerto Rico has telesalud regulations (Reglamento 9518 on the Use of Telesalud in Puerto Rico) that apply to healthcare delivery including OUD treatment. Puerto Rico follows federal DEA telehealth regulations for prescribing buprenorphine."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Linea PAS (Crisis Line)", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/linea-pas", "description": "ASSMCA's 24/7 confidential crisis line (Linea PAS) providing mental health and substance use crisis support, referrals to treatment, and coordination of services. Available free of charge."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Medicaid (ASES)", "url": "https://www.medicaid.gov/state-overviews/puerto-rico.html", "description": "CMS overview of Puerto Rico Medicaid program. The PR Medicaid delivery system operates as part of the island's public healthcare system through the PR Health Insurance Administration (ASES - Administracion de Seguros de Salud)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASES Pharmacy Benefit (Abarca Health PBM)", "url": "https://abarcahealth.com/our-clients/ases-english/", "description": "Abarca Health serves as the Pharmacy Benefit Manager (PBM) for the PR Government Health Insurance Plan (PRGHIP), administered by ASES with federal Medicaid and state funds. Covers approximately 1.3 million lives. Includes links to ASES formularies, clinical protocols, and provider manuals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASES Preferred Drug List (PDL)", "url": "https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/12iTCIL8Sfs2uk3Xzz1YzK-JHwS4DYEOW", "description": "Google Drive folder containing ASES Preferred Drug List (PDL) formularies. The PDL guides providers on medication decisions under cost-effective coverage for PRGHIP beneficiaries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASES Clinical Protocols", "url": "https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1aMde_HO_pjOwd2VtBq4k1LPn-I_leawx", "description": "Clinical protocols document repository for ASES pharmacy benefit, including protocols for controlled substances and OUD treatment medications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASES Normative Letters", "url": "https://www.asespr.org/proveedores-2/comunicados/cartas-normativas/", "description": "ASES normative letters and circulars for providers."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State-Specific Pharmacist Billing Codes: Puerto Rico Medicaid (through ASES/Abarca) does not have a comprehensive set of billing codes for pharmacist-provided clinical services beyond dispensing. Contact ASES or Abarca Health for pharmacy service billing guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Puerto Rico receives federal State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA (PRSOR). The Opioid Recovery and Restitution Fund, administered by the Department of Health, supports comprehensive opioid crisis response programs including PAICO-PR. ASSMCA administers multiple grant-funded projects for prevention, treatment, and recovery."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Colegio de Farmaceuticos de Puerto Rico (CE Provider)", "url": "https://cfpr.org/", "description": "CFPR is an ACPE-accredited continuing education provider (Provider 0151) offering CE courses for pharmacists in Puerto Rico. Phone: (787) 753-7157. Email: educacion@cfpr.org. Offers both knowledge-based and application-based CE courses."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Board of Pharmacy CE Requirements: Puerto Rico pharmacists must complete ACPE-accredited continuing education as required by the Junta Examinadora de Farmacia. Check the Board's page at https://www.salud.pr.gov/CMS/116 for current CE requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS provides free training on medications for opioid use disorder, including training options that meet the DEA 8-hour MATE Act education requirement. Available in English. Funded by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division website for DEA registration, practitioner resources, and controlled substance regulations relevant to buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "ASSMCA Training: ASSMCA provides training through its special projects including overdose prevention education, naloxone administration training, and peer support specialist training. Over 227,000 people have been trained in overdose prevention and naloxone administration."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Puerto Rico operates syringe services programs. Iniciativa Comunitaria in San Juan launched the first harm reduction vending machines in the United States in 2009 (Punto Fijo program). SSPs provide sterile syringes, naloxone, and other harm reduction supplies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASSMCA Harm Reduction Programs", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/proyectos-especiales", "description": "ASSMCA harm reduction programs under the PRSOR project. Includes naloxone distribution (over 190,000 kits distributed across Puerto Rico), fentanyl test strip distribution (over 20,000 distributed), community outreach, and overdose prevention training for first responders, municipal officials, community leaders, and families."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro Puerto Rico", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/", "description": "NEXT Distro serves all 50 states and Puerto Rico with confidential online and mail-order distribution of naloxone, syringes, and other harm reduction materials, free of charge."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Naloxone Access: Naloxone is distributed free through ASSMCA programs, community organizations, and at large public events. ASSMCA has trained over 227,000 people in overdose prevention and naloxone administration. Narcan is available over-the-counter at pharmacies across Puerto Rico."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: ASSMCA distributes free fentanyl test strips as part of its PRSOR harm reduction strategy. Over 20,000 test strips have been distributed. Fentanyl contamination in illicit drug markets has significantly increased overdose risk in Puerto Rico."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://datosopioides.pr.gov/", "description": "Puerto Rico Opioids Dashboard (Datos Opioides) providing interactive data and visualizations on opioid-related indicators. Please verify this link before publishing (may require specific browser)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Opioids and Substances Dashboard", "url": "https://prosd-dspr.hub.arcgis.com/", "description": "ArcGIS Hub dashboard integrating interactive tools about opioid and drug-related indicators and key information for Puerto Rico."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ASSMCA Treatment Services", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/tratamientos", "description": "ASSMCA page listing treatment services available across Puerto Rico, including residential treatment, outpatient services, specialized programs, and homelessness intervention services through centers in San Juan, Ponce, Fajardo, Arecibo, Mayaguez, and Moca."}, {"type": "note", "text": "ASSMCA Peer Support Program: ASSMCA's PRSOR includes a Peer Support program that has trained over 40 peer facilitators (facilitadores pares) to support individuals in recovery from opioid and substance use disorders. Peer support groups are available across the island."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASSMCA Homepage (Behavioral Health Authority)", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/", "description": "ASSMCA is Puerto Rico's primary behavioral health authority responsible for mental health, addiction prevention, treatment, and rehabilitation services. ASSMCA evaluates, monitors, and certifies public and private agencies providing mental health and substance use services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: ASSMCA operates residential treatment facilities across Puerto Rico. The PRSOR Offender Reentry program provides specialized treatment and recovery services for incarcerated individuals. Contact ASSMCA for specific recovery housing resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Linea PAS Crisis Line", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/linea-pas", "description": "ASSMCA's 24/7 confidential and free crisis line for mental health and substance use support, referrals, and coordination of services. Available for communities, schools, elderly centers, and agencies across Puerto Rico."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Linea PAS (ASSMCA) available 24/7 for free and confidential support. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is also available in Puerto Rico."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.salud.pr.gov/CMS/116", "description": "Junta Examinadora de Farmacia, Puerto Rico Department of Health. Access through the Department of Health website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Medicaid (ASES)", "url": "https://www.asespr.org/", "description": "Administracion de Seguros de Salud (ASES), the Puerto Rico Health Insurance Administration. Administers the PR Government Health Insurance Plan (PRGHIP) with Abarca Health as PBM. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ASSMCA (State Opioid Treatment Authority)", "url": "https://www.assmca.pr.gov/", "description": "Administracion de Servicios de Salud Mental y Contra la Adiccion. Puerto Rico's behavioral health authority and SOTA equivalent. Oversees PDMP, State Opioid Response programs, naloxone distribution, and treatment services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Colegio de Farmaceuticos de Puerto Rico", "url": "https://cfpr.org/", "description": "Professional pharmacy association for Puerto Rico. P.O. Box 360206, San Juan, PR 00936-0206. Phone: (787) 753-7157. Email: educacion@cfpr.org. ACPE-accredited CE provider."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Health Opioid Program", "url": "https://www.salud.pr.gov/", "description": "Puerto Rico Department of Health (Departamento de Salud). The Division of Public Health for the Prevention of Overdoses from Psychoactive Substances monitors opioid data. The Department also administers the Opioid Recovery and Restitution Fund."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Opioids Dashboard", "url": "https://datosopioides.pr.gov/", "description": "Interactive Puerto Rico Opioids Dashboard with data on PDMP dispensing, overdoses, and opioid-related indicators by municipality. Includes PDMP data from May 2018 onward, provided by ASSMCA in collaboration with the Department of Health. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Opioids and Substances Dashboard", "url": "https://prosd-dspr.hub.arcgis.com/", "description": "ArcGIS-based interactive dashboard integrating tools and data about opioids and other drugs in Puerto Rico."}, {"type": "note", "text": "ASSMCA Overdose Monitoring: ASSMCA's PR PDO (Puerto Rico Prevention of Drug Overdoses) project maintains continuous epidemiological monitoring of overdoses reported to ASSMCA. In 2022, there were 2,140 opioid-related overdoses in Puerto Rico (approximately 6 per day)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Health Statistical Compendium", "url": "https://www.salud.pr.gov/menuInst/download/2030", "description": "Puerto Rico Department of Health Division of Public Health statistical compendium on overdoses from psychoactive substances. The Puerto Rico Institute of Forensic Sciences reported 452 deaths due to substance intoxication, with opioids present in 344 (76.1%) of those deaths. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Dashboard Data", "url": "https://datosopioides.pr.gov/datacardscollection/pdmp", "description": "PDMP section of the Puerto Rico Opioids Dashboard with information on most dispensed opioids, distribution by age, sex, and municipality."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Colegio de Farmaceuticos de Puerto Rico", "url": "https://cfpr.org/", "description": "CFPR serves as the professional association and advocacy organization for pharmacists in Puerto Rico. Provides legislative updates, CE programs, and professional development."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Puerto Rico Legislature", "url": "https://www.oslpr.org/", "description": "Puerto Rico Legislative Assembly (Asamblea Legislativa). Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grupo Nexos PAICO-PR", "url": "https://www.nexospr.org/", "description": "Grupo Nexos leads the Project for the Comprehensive Response to the Opioid Crisis in Puerto Rico (PAICO-PR), focused on reviewing treatment standards, strengthening multisector collaboration, and developing public policy recommendations for improved OUD treatment access."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy templates. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Legislation and Initiatives: PR Law 70 of 2017 established the PDMP. ASSMCA administers the PRSOR (Puerto Rico State Opioid Response) with federal SAMHSA funding. The Opioid Recovery and Restitution Fund (administered by the Department of Health) supports comprehensive crisis response programs. Reglamento 9518 regulates telesalud in Puerto Rico. The PAICO-PR project (2024-2027) is developing policy recommendations for OUD treatment access."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Puerto Rico Opioid Response: The comprehensive opioid response in Puerto Rico is led by ASSMCA through the PRSOR program with federal SOR grant funding. Key achievements include distribution of over 190,000 naloxone kits, training of over 227,000 people in overdose prevention, distribution of over 20,000 fentanyl test strips, expansion of medication-assisted treatment clinics, and peer support programs. The Department of Health administers the Opioid Recovery and Restitution Fund supporting additional initiatives through organizations like Grupo Nexos."}]}]}, "rhodeisland": {"name": "Rhode Island", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Rhode Island law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.1-2 (x) (West 2024).\nAlthough not in the practice of pharmacy definition, Rhode Island law provides that a pharmacist “may prescribe and dispense all short-term, FDA-approved hormonal contraceptives.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.1-36(a) (West 2024). This is the only pharmacy law or regulation expressly addressing prescribing drugs or medications.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Rhode Island cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Rhode Island practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Rhode Island pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Rhode Island law includes “the administration of . . . medications approved by the department of health in consultation with the board of pharmacy for administration by a pharmacist.”\nR.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.1-2 (x) (West 2024).\nRhode Island regulation provides that a pharmacist can administer medications in 25 listed classes to any age group. 216-40 R.I. CODE REG. § 15-1.11.3(B) (2024).\nBuprenorphine is one of the drug classes listed.\nAdministration must be pursuant to a valid prescription or physician-approved protocol, including, but not limited to, a standing order. 216-40 R.I. CODE REG. § 15-1.11.3(A) (2024).", "2B": "Obtain a valid prescription or physician-approved protocol.\nAdhere to the educational, training, and recordkeeping requirements specified in Rhode Island regulations. 216-40 R.I. CODE REG. § 15-1.11.3 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Rhode Island law provides that a pharmacist can perform “clinical laboratory tests provided such testing is limited to limited-function tests as defined in this Part.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.1-2 (x) (West 2024).\nLimited function tests are tests listed in the federal register as CLIA-waived tests. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.1-2 (p) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Rhode Island practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nRhode Island law authorizes a pharmacist to engage in collaborative pharmacy practice (CPP) pursuant to a CPA. \nR.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-3 (West 2024). The purpose of CPP is drug therapy management (DTM) of patients. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(a) (West 2024). DTM may include “initiating, adjusting, monitoring, or discontinuing drug therapy.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(d) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “initiating” and “adjusting,” Rhode Island laws and regulations governing DTM do not expressly refer to “prescribing” drugs or medications.\nEven if a CPA could allow a Rhode Island pharmacist to prescribe drugs, Rhode Island laws and regulations governing CPP do not account for the fact that an Rhode Island pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the agreement provides.\nIn summary, Rhode Island laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Rhode Island pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Rhode Island laws and/or regulations governing CPAs to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Rhode Island laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow Rhode Island pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Rhode Island laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nRhode Island law authorizes a pharmacist to engage in CPP pursuant to a CPA. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-3 (West 2024). The purpose of CPP is DTM of patients. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(a) (West 2024).\nDTM may include “initiating, adjusting, monitoring, or discontinuing drug therapy.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(d) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “initiating” and “adjusting,” Rhode Island laws and regulations governing DTM do not expressly refer to “administering” drugs or medications.\nAs a result, Rhode Island laws and regulations governing CPAs are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can administer drugs. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has the general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CPA, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in Rhode Island laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CPA include administering medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nRhode Island law authorizes a pharmacist to engage in CPP pursuant to a CPA. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-3 (West 2024). The purpose of CPP is DTM of patients. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(a) (West 2024). DTM expressly incudes “ordering and evaluating the results of laboratory tests directly related to drug therapy,” so long as the pharmacist is “under the supervision of, or in direct consultation with, one or more physician(s).” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(d)(4) (West 2024).\nThe authorization to evaluate results, however, “does not include any diagnostic component.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(d)(4) (West 2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "A CPA is a written agreement between one or more pharmacists and “one or more physicians.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(a) (West 2024).\nHowever, despite the initial limitation to physicians, the same Rhode Island law further adds that “a healthcare professional who has prescribing privileges and is employed by a collaborating physician” may be a party to a CPA. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.2-2(a) (West 2024).\nThe following Rhode Island laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – R.I. GEN. LAWS §§ 5-19.2-1 to 5-19.2-5 (West 2024); 216-40 R.I. CODE REG. § 15-1.13 (2024); 216-40 R.I. CODE REG. § 15-1.4.17(A)(2), (3) (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nRhode Island does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act. However, Rhode Island health insurance law provides that health insurers must provide coverage for “covered healthcare services provided through telemedicine.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-81-4(a) (West 2024).\n“Telemedicine” means “the delivery of clinical healthcare services by . . . [technology that] facilitate assessment, diagnosis, counseling and prescribing treatment, and care management of a patient’s health care while such patient is at an originating site and the healthcare provider is at a distant site.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-81-3(15) (West 2024).\n“Healthcare provider” means a “healthcare professional” or a “healthcare facility.” A “healthcare professional” is “a physician or other healthcare practitioner licensed, accredited, or certified to perform specified healthcare services consistent with state law.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-81-3(4) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Rhode Island laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Rhode Island laws and regulations governing telehealth include – R.I. GEN. LAWS §§ 27-81-1 to 27-81-7 (West 2024) (insurance); 210-40 R.I. CODE REG. § 10-1.7.8 (2024)\n(Medicaid).", "9A": "“Any individual health plan or group health plan and any health coverage through any commercial health plan shall cover hormonal contraceptives that are prescribed and dispensed by a pharmacist, including contraceptive counseling, if those contraceptives would otherwise be covered if prescribed by another type of healthcare provider.” R.I. GEN. LAWS § 5-19.1-36(e) (West 2024).255\nEvery group health insurance contract, or every group hospital or medical expense insurance policy, plan, or group policy delivered, issued for delivery, or renewed in Rhode Island beginning January 1, 2024, must provide coverage for treatment of pre-exposure prophylaxis (“PrEP”) for the prevention of HIV and post-exposure prophylaxis (“PEP”) to prevent HIV infection. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-18-91(a) (West 2024) (accident and sickness policies); R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-19-83(a) (West 2024)\n(nonprofit hospital service corporations); R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-20-79(a) (West 2024) (nonprofit medical service corporations); R.I. GEN. LAWS § 27-41-96(a) (West 2024) (health maintenance organizations). For purposes of Rhode Island laws governing the “prevention and suppression” of HIV/AIDS, as of January 2024, a “health care provider” includes a pharmacist. R.I. GEN. LAWS § 23-6.3-2(16) (West 2024).256", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Rhode Island Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Rhode Island laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a CPA are covered under the Rhode Island Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy (RIDOH Pharmacy Licensing)", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/licensing/pharmacy", "description": "Rhode Island Department of Health pharmacy licensing page. Rhode Island does not have a separate Board of Pharmacy; pharmacy regulation is administered through RIDOH's Center for Professional Regulation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Pharmacy Practice Act (RIGL Title 5, Chapter 19.1)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/rhode-island/title-5/chapter-5-19-1/section-5-19-1-5/", "description": "Rhode Island General Laws Title 5, Chapter 5-19.1, Pharmacies, establishing the State Board of Pharmacy's powers and duties, including qualifications for licensure of pharmacists, pharmacy interns, and pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://risos-apa-production-public.s3.amazonaws.com/DOH/6764.pdf", "description": "Rules and Regulations Pertaining to Pharmacists, Pharmacies and Manufacturers, Wholesalers and Distributors published by the Rhode Island Secretary of State, containing all administrative rules governing pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Act (RIGL Chapter 5-19.2)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/rhode-island/title-5/chapter-5-19-2/section-5-19-2-2/", "description": "Rhode Island General Laws Chapter 5-19.2 authorizing collaborative pharmacy practice. Licensed pharmacists with advanced training may work in collaboration with physicians for drug therapy management pursuant to authorized protocols, subject to RIDOH conditions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Statute", "url": "http://webserver.rilin.state.ri.us/Statutes/TITLE5/5-19.2/5-19.2-2.HTM", "description": "Full statutory text of the Rhode Island Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Act definitions, including collaborative pharmacy practice, drug therapy management, and protocol requirements."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Prevent Overdose RI - Get Help", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/get-help/", "description": "Rhode Island's comprehensive overdose prevention resource with a treatment locator map and table of providers, updated using BHDDH data. Includes statewide treatment and recovery resource guides."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Buprenorphine Hotline", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/addiction-overdose", "description": "People with moderate to severe OUD can access telehealth buprenorphine treatment initiation 24/7 through Rhode Island's Buprenorphine Hotline at 401-606-5456. Page also includes addiction and overdose resources from RIDOH."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator where users can search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Rhode Island."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine, filterable by state for Rhode Island."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prevent Overdose RI - Provider Resources", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/providers/", "description": "Resources for healthcare providers including information on the elimination of the DATA waiver requirement, PDMP guidance, naloxone co-prescribing information, and buprenorphine prescribing guidance for Rhode Island."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (BHDDH)", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/mental-health", "description": "BHDDH is recognized as the State Mental Health Authority, Single State Agency for SUD Treatment and Prevention, and the State Opioid Treatment Authority for Rhode Island."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://eohhs.ri.gov/providers-partners/provider-directories/pharmacy", "description": "Rhode Island Executive Office of Health and Human Services (EOHHS) pharmacy provider page with information on Medicaid pharmacy benefit administration, prior authorization policies, and provider enrollment for Fee-for-Service and Managed Care beneficiaries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://eohhs.ri.gov/sites/g/files/xkgbur226/files/2024-01/PDL%2001.17.2024.pdf", "description": "Rhode Island Medicaid Preferred Drug List managed by the Fee-for-Service Pharmacy and Therapeutics Committee. Includes therapeutic classes and associated drugs, prior authorization requirements, and buprenorphine coverage information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Covered Drugs Search", "url": "https://eohhs.ri.gov/providers-partners/provider-directories/pharmacy", "description": "EOHHS pharmacy page includes NDC lookup tools to verify covered medications in the Medicaid Fee-for-Service program, including buprenorphine products."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants providing funding for states including Rhode Island to increase access to MOUD, support prevention and treatment for OUD and stimulant use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHDDH Substance Use Services", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/about-us/whats-new", "description": "BHDDH latest updates on substance use disorder services, funding opportunities, and program developments including the Buprenorphine Hotline and treatment access initiatives."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.netce.com/ce-requirements/pharmacist/ri/", "description": "Rhode Island pharmacists are required to complete 15 hours of continuing education each year, of which 10 may be completed by home study. A minimum of 1 hour must be in specific topics as determined by the Board."}, {"type": "link", "title": "RIDOH Pharmacy Licensing", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/licensing/pharmacy", "description": "RIDOH pharmacy licensing page with information on pharmacist licensure requirements, renewal procedures, and CE compliance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Pharmacists Association (RIPA)", "url": "https://www.ripharmacists.org/", "description": "Established in 1874, RIPA is one of the oldest state pharmacist associations in the country. Provides professional development resources, continuing education, and advocacy for Rhode Island pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division online forms for DEA registration, including MATE Act training requirements applicable to all DEA registrants."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Providers Clinical Support System for MOUD offers free training modules, webinars, clinical tools, and mentoring for providers treating OUD with buprenorphine."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Prevent Overdose RI - Harm Reduction", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/people-who-use-drugs/", "description": "Comprehensive harm reduction resource page for Rhode Island. ENCORE offers free syringe delivery (401-781-0665) and mobile outreach throughout the state. Project Weber/RENEW provides additional syringe exchange and harm reduction services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Get Naloxone in Rhode Island", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/get-naloxone/", "description": "Prevent Overdose RI provides free naloxone by mail to Rhode Island residents. Naloxone is also available over-the-counter at pharmacies. Pharmacists can prescribe naloxone, and providers can co-prescribe to patients on opioids."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Project Weber/RENEW", "url": "https://weberrenew.org/", "description": "Project Weber/RENEW offers free syringe exchange, fentanyl test strips, safer injection and smoking supplies, naloxone distribution, and overdose prevention education throughout Rhode Island."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/people-who-use-drugs/", "description": "Rhode Island was the first state to formally decriminalize fentanyl test strips in 2018, exempting them from drug paraphernalia laws. Test strips are available through harm reduction organizations including ENCORE and Project Weber/RENEW."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/see-the-data/", "description": "Prevent Overdose RI data page with links to overdose data from the 48-hour reporting system, EMS run data, and harm reduction organization data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "RIDOH Opioid and Stimulant Use Data Hub", "url": "https://ridoh-overdose-surveillance-rihealth.hub.arcgis.com/", "description": "Rhode Island Department of Health interactive ArcGIS data hub for opioid and stimulant use surveillance, providing geographic and temporal overdose data."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "BHDDH Recovery Housing", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/substance-useaddiction/recovery-services/recovery-housing-information", "description": "BHDDH recovery housing information page with descriptions of recovery residence levels based on type, intensity, and duration of support, from peer-to-peer recovery support to medical and counseling services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHDDH Peer Recovery and Family Support", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/mental-health/individual-and-family-information", "description": "BHDDH peer support services page. Peer Support Services (PSS) provide specialized therapeutic interactions between current or former behavioral health service consumers and individuals in recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHDDH Homepage", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/", "description": "Rhode Island Department of Behavioral Healthcare, Developmental Disabilities and Hospitals, serving as the state behavioral health agency. Includes information on Certified Community Behavioral Health Clinics and expanded behavioral health services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prevent Overdose RI - Get Help", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/get-help/", "description": "Treatment and recovery resource locator for Rhode Island, including downloadable guides compiled by RIDOH with statewide treatment and recovery support services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Contacts", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/addiction-overdose", "description": "Rhode Island crisis resources including the Buprenorphine Hotline (401-606-5456, 24/7), 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline, and SAMHSA Helpline (1-800-662-4357). RIDOH addiction and overdose resource page."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "RIDOH Pharmacy Licensing Contact", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/licensing/pharmacy", "description": "Rhode Island Department of Health pharmacy licensing. Phone: 401-222-5960. Address: 3 Capitol Hill, Room 104, Providence, RI 02908. Rhode Island pharmacy regulation is administered through RIDOH rather than a separate Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "EOHHS Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://eohhs.ri.gov/providers-partners/provider-directories/pharmacy", "description": "Rhode Island Executive Office of Health and Human Services pharmacy provider contact for Medicaid pharmacy benefit inquiries, PDL information, and prior authorization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHDDH Contact", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/", "description": "Department of Behavioral Healthcare, Developmental Disabilities and Hospitals. Serves as Rhode Island's State Mental Health Authority, Single State Agency for SUD, and State Opioid Treatment Authority. Address: 14 Harrington Road, Cranston, RI 02920."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.ripharmacists.org/", "description": "RIPA is the professional association representing pharmacists in Rhode Island since 1874, providing education, advocacy, and professional development."}, {"type": "link", "title": "RIDOH Addiction and Overdose", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/addiction-overdose", "description": "Rhode Island Department of Health addiction and overdose page with contacts for opioid programs, the Buprenorphine Hotline, and safe opioid prescribing resources."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Prevent Overdose RI Data Hub", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/see-the-data/", "description": "Central data page for Rhode Island's overdose surveillance, with links to 48-hour reporting data, EMS run data, and harm reduction service data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Death Data", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/overdose-deaths/", "description": "Detailed overdose death data from the Office of the State Medical Examiners, with monthly and annual breakdowns, demographic information, and substance-specific data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "RIDOH Opioid and Stimulant Use Data Hub", "url": "https://ridoh-overdose-surveillance-rihealth.hub.arcgis.com/", "description": "Interactive ArcGIS data hub from RIDOH providing geographic, demographic, and temporal opioid and stimulant use surveillance data for Rhode Island."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Safe Opioid Prescribing Data", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/healthcare/medicine/about/safeopioidprescribing/", "description": "RIDOH safe opioid prescribing page with prescribing guidelines, data on opioid prescribing patterns, and clinical resources for providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHDDH Substance Use Data", "url": "https://bhddh.ri.gov/about-us/whats-new", "description": "BHDDH updates including treatment utilization data, program outcome measures, and reports on substance use disorder services in Rhode Island."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Governor's Overdose Prevention and Intervention Task Force", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/the-task-force/", "description": "Established in 2015, the Task Force is a statewide coalition of professionals and community members developing strategy to prevent overdoses and save lives. Co-chaired by RIDOH Director, BHDDH Director, and EOHHS Assistant Secretary. 2023 Strategic Plan Refresh available."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.ripharmacists.org/", "description": "RIPA unites pharmacists across the state for professional development and advocacy, representing pharmacy interests before the state legislature and regulatory bodies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rhode Island General Assembly - Representatives", "url": "https://www.rilegislature.gov/representatives", "description": "Rhode Island General Assembly website for finding and contacting state representatives on pharmacy and OUD-related policy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prevent Overdose RI", "url": "https://preventoverdoseri.org/", "description": "Rhode Island's home for ending the overdose crisis, providing the latest data, resources, and policy information. Serves as the public-facing hub for the Governor's Overdose Task Force work."}, {"type": "link", "title": "RIDOH Addiction and Overdose Policy", "url": "https://health.ri.gov/addiction-overdose", "description": "RIDOH page on addiction and overdose with policy updates, safe prescribing guidelines, and links to legislative resources and public health initiatives addressing OUD in Rhode Island."}]}]}, "southcarolina": {"name": "South Carolina", "q": {"CPA_Term": "South Carolina pharmacy law refers to “drug therapy management” (DTM) in general but does not use a term for the document memorializing the arrangement. S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(19) (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Carolina law does not expressly include prescribing any drugs or medications. S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(50) (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in South Carolina cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the South Carolina practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow South Carolina pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, South Carolina laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Carolina law expressly includes “participation in . . . drug administration.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(50)(b) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, while there are South Carolina laws and regulations expressly covering the administration of vaccines and hormonal contraceptives, including the training necessary to do it, there are no provisions expressly addressing administration of other kinds of drugs or medications, including controlled substances. S.C. CODE ANN. §§ 40-43-190, 40-43-230 (West 2024).If the general “participation in . . . drug administration” phrase in the practice of pharmacy definition acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions in law or regulation. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in South Carolina may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.\n“Administer” means “the direct application of a drug or device pursuant to a lawful order of a practitioner.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(1) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain a lawful order of a practitioner.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the South Carolina practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Carolina law expressly includes “initiation, ordering, and administration of flu and COVID tests.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(50)(e) (West 2024).\nOtherwise, South Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the South Carolina practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Carolina includes “the provision of those acts or services necessary to provide pharmacy care and drug therapy management” (DTM). S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(50)(c) (West 2024).\nDTM is “that practice of pharmacy which involves the expertise of the pharmacist in a collaborative effort with the practitioner and other health care providers to ensure the highest quality health care services for patients.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(19) (West 2024). South Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what DTM may or may not include and whether that includes prescribing drugs and medications.\nEven if a DTM arrangement could allow a South Carolina pharmacist to prescribe drugs and medications, South Carolina laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a South Carolina pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the DTM arrangement provides.\nIn summary, South Carolina laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a DTM arrangement. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a South Carolina pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise South Carolina laws and/or regulations governing DTM to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in South Carolina laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under DTM arrangements.\nAllow South Carolina pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, South Carolina laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Carolina law includes “the provision of those acts or services necessary to provide pharmacy care and [DTM].\nS.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(50)(c) (West 2024).\nDTM is “that practice of pharmacy which involves the expertise of the pharmacist in a collaborative effort with the practitioner and other health care providers to ensure the highest quality health care services for patients.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(19) (West 2024). South Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what DTM may or may not include and whether that includes administering drugs and medications.\nIn summary, although South Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine under a DTM arrangement, they also do not clearly authorize it and a pharmacist’s general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of DTM is also unclear.", "5B": "Enter into a DTM arrangement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly provide in South Carolina laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authorized activities under a DTM arrangement include administering drugs and medications, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, South Carolina laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine The definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Carolina law includes “the provision of those acts or services necessary to provide pharmacy care and [DTM].\nS.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(50)(c) (West 2024). DTM is “that practice of pharmacy which involves the expertise of the pharmacist in a collaborative effort with the practitioner and other health care providers to ensure the highest quality health care services for patients.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(19) (West 2024). South Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what DTM may or may not include and whether that includes ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nAs a result, South Carolina laws and regulations governing DTM arrangements are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist may order or evaluate lab tests However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has limited authority to order lab tests in general, the most logical answer is that the same limited authority applies as part of a DTM arrangement.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in South Carolina laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a DTM arrangement includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "South Carolina law describes DTM as involving “the expertise of the pharmacist in a collaborative effort with the practitioner and other health care providers.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(19) (West 2024).\nA “practitioner” is “a physician, dentist, optometrist, podiatrist, veterinarian, or other health care provider authorized by law to diagnose and prescribe drugs and devices.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-30(51) (West 2024).\nSouth Carolina pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what DTM may or may not include or what must be part of any written agreement.", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nSouth Carolina’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law allows a “licensee” to provide health care via telehealth “within his scope of practice.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-42-20(A)(1) (West 2024).\nA “licensee” is “a professional licensed by a licensing board and authorized to practice health care pursuant to this title [Title 40].” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-42-10(3) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "The general rule for physicians is that “Schedule II-narcotic and Schedule III-narcotic prescriptions are not permitted” via telehealth. S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-47-37(C)(7)(b) (West 2024). However, a prescription via telehealth is allowed for “those Schedule II and Schedule III medications used specifically for patients actively enrolled in a Medication-Assisted Treatment (MAT) program with a provider who has an established physician-patient relationship when buprenorphine is being prescribed as a medication for opioid use disorder.” S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-47-37(C)(7)(b)(ii) (West 2024).\nSouth Carolina laws and regulations governing telehealth include – S.C. CODE ANN. §§ 40-42-10 to 40-42-30 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-33-34 (West 2024) (nurses); S.C. CODE ANN. §§ 40-47-37, 40-47-113 (West 2024) (physicians).", "9A": "Dispensing self-administered hormonal contraceptives, as outlined and authorized in S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-230.\nS.C. CODE ANN. § 44-6-115(B)(1)(a) (West 2024).\nAdministering injectable hormonal contraceptives, as outlined and authorized in in S.C. CODE ANN. § 40-43-230.\nS.C. CODE ANN. § 44-6-115(B)(1)(b) (West 2024).260", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the South Carolina Medicaid program.\nSpecify in South Carolina laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a DTM arrangement are covered under the South Carolina Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://llr.sc.gov/bop/", "description": "South Carolina Board of Pharmacy, part of the Department of Labor, Licensing and Regulation (LLR). The Board regulates the practice of pharmacy, licenses pharmacists, certifies interns, and registers pharmacy technicians."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Carolina Pharmacy Practice Act (Title 40, Chapter 43)", "url": "https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t40c043.php", "description": "Full text of the South Carolina Pharmacy Practice Act, promoting, preserving, and protecting public health, safety, and welfare through effective control and regulation of the practice of pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Laws and Regulations", "url": "https://llr.sc.gov/bop/laws.aspx", "description": "Links to all relevant statutes and regulations including S.C. Code of Laws Title 40 Chapter 43 (Pharmacists), Title 39 Chapter 24 (Drug Product Selection Act), Title 39 Chapter 23 (Adulterated Drugs), and S.C. Code of Regulations Chapter 99 (State Board of Pharmacy)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Regulations (Chapter 99)", "url": "https://www.scstatehouse.gov/coderegs/Chapter%2099.pdf", "description": "South Carolina Code of Regulations Chapter 99, State Board of Pharmacy, containing all administrative rules governing pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Roadmap", "url": "https://pharmacystandards.org/collaborative-practice/south-carolina-collaborative-practice-roadmap/", "description": "Council on Pharmacy Standards roadmap for collaborative practice in South Carolina. State statutes distinguish between pharmacist authority via statewide protocols and collaborative practice agreements. CPAs must be kept on file and reviewed at least annually."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Protocols", "url": "https://llr.sc.gov/bop/Protocols.aspx", "description": "Board of Pharmacy protocols page including naloxone dispensing protocols, immunization protocols, and other statewide pharmacist protocols for clinical services."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DAODAS Local Treatment Providers", "url": "https://www.daodas.sc.gov/services/treatment/local-providers/", "description": "South Carolina Department of Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse Services directory of local treatment providers. Medical practitioners throughout South Carolina are authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Just Plain Killers - Find Help", "url": "https://justplainkillers.com/find-help/", "description": "DAODAS-affiliated resource for finding substance use disorder treatment options in South Carolina through a system of state-licensed and nationally accredited service providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator for searching substance use disorder treatment facilities in South Carolina by location, services, and insurance type."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine, filterable by state for South Carolina."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCDHHS Medicaid OUD Treatment Coverage", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/communications/medicaid-coverage-treatment-opioid-use-disorder", "description": "SCDHHS page on Medicaid coverage for OUD treatment. Since July 2020, SCDHHS reimburses for long-acting injectable medications for OUD including naltrexone and buprenorphine extended-release."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCDHHS Opioid Treatment Programs", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/communications/medicaid-coverage-opioid-treatment-programs-and-scdhhs-efforts-address-opioid-crisis", "description": "SCDHHS efforts to address the opioid crisis including Medicaid coverage of opioid treatment programs, MAT initiation in emergency departments, and partnership with DAODAS."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SCDHHS Pharmacy Page", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/providers/pharmacy", "description": "South Carolina Department of Health and Human Services pharmacy provider page. Effective July 1, 2024, SCDHHS implemented a single state-directed preferred drug list (PDL) for all participating MCOs and the FFS Medicaid program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Carolina Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://southcarolina.fhsc.com/providers/pdl.asp", "description": "South Carolina Pharmacy Services website providing the current Preferred Drug List, searchable by drug name or therapeutic class."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Single PDL Implementation", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/communications/implementation-single-preferred-drug-list", "description": "Information about the implementation of the single Preferred Drug List effective July 1, 2024, based on the existing FFS PDL and applied uniformly across all MCOs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCDHHS Fee Schedules", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/provider/resource/fee-schedules", "description": "Provider fee schedule resources including pharmacy reimbursement rates, physician services, and alcohol and other drug rehabilitation services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/grants/grant-announcements/ti-24-008", "description": "SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grants providing funding for states including South Carolina to increase MOUD access and support prevention and treatment for OUD."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "South Carolina Board of Pharmacy CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.llr.sc.gov/bop/ce.aspx", "description": "South Carolina pharmacists must complete 15 hours (1.5 CEUs) of ACPE or CME Category-1 continuing education each license year for renewal. At least 7.5 hours must be in drug therapy or patient management."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCPhA Educational Resources", "url": "https://scrx.org/resources/popular-resources/", "description": "South Carolina Pharmacy Association resources page with links to collaborative practice agreement toolkits, clinical resources, and educational materials for pharmacy professionals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Carolina Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://scrx.org/", "description": "SCPhA provides advocacy, education, and connectivity for pharmacy professionals in South Carolina, including continuing education opportunities and advanced practice resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/online_forms_apps.html", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division online forms for DEA registration, including MATE Act training requirements for all DEA registrants prescribing controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Providers Clinical Support System for MOUD offers free training modules, webinars, clinical tools, and mentoring for providers treating OUD with buprenorphine."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Saves SC", "url": "http://naloxonesavessc.org/", "description": "South Carolina's naloxone information resource providing guidance on the SC Overdose Prevention Act, which authorizes pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a prescription under the Joint Protocol."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Dispensing Protocol", "url": "http://naloxonesavessc.org/dispensers/", "description": "Information for pharmacist dispensers on the Joint Protocol for dispensing naloxone. The SC Overdose Prevention Act gives pharmacists licensed in South Carolina permission to dispense naloxone to persons meeting the criteria."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Naloxone Protocol", "url": "https://llr.sc.gov/bop/Protocols.aspx", "description": "Board of Pharmacy protocols page with the Joint Protocol for community organizations to distribute naloxone and the Joint Protocol for pharmacist dispensing of naloxone without a prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SC Overdose Prevention Act", "url": "https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t44c130.php", "description": "Full text of the South Carolina Overdose Prevention Act (Title 44, Chapter 130). A pharmacist acting in good faith may dispense an opioid antidote pursuant to a written prescription or standing order by a prescriber."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality", "url": "https://www.scstatehouse.gov/sess125_2023-2024/bills/3503.htm", "description": "South Carolina Bill 3503 (2023) exempted rapid fentanyl test strips from the drug paraphernalia definition. Fentanyl test strips are legal and available through community distributors at no cost."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Just Plain Killers - Fentanyl Information", "url": "https://justplainkillers.com/fentanyl/", "description": "DAODAS-affiliated fentanyl awareness page with information on fentanyl test strips, naloxone, and free community distribution resources across South Carolina."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://justplainkillers.com/data/", "description": "South Carolina opioid epidemic data page with special statistical reports and county-level data tables on drug overdose deaths, EMS naloxone administrations, and treatment services, with detailed dashboards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCRIPTS Prescription Monitoring Data", "url": "https://dph.sc.gov/professionals/healthcare-quality/prescription-monitoring-program-scripts", "description": "DPH SCRIPTS dashboards showing dispensation information by time, place, and drug category for opioids, benzodiazepines, and stimulants with county-level and demographic data."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DAODAS Recovery Services", "url": "https://www.daodas.sc.gov/services/recovery/", "description": "South Carolina Department of Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse Services recovery page with information on collegiate recovery programs and links to Embrace Recovery SC for community resources and support groups."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Embrace Recovery SC", "url": "https://embracerecoverysc.com/", "description": "South Carolina's recovery support platform providing information, resources, and support groups for individuals in recovery and their communities. Affiliated with DAODAS."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SC SHARE (Peer Support Certification)", "url": "https://www.scshare.com/", "description": "SC SHARE is a non-profit recovery-oriented organization offering peer support specialist certification, education, and support for people with mental illness, substance use, and co-occurring issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BHDD Office of Mental Health (SC DMH)", "url": "https://www.scdmh.org/", "description": "South Carolina BHDD Office of Mental Health homepage offering counseling services and programs for anxiety, depression, bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, and other mental health conditions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.daodas.sc.gov/services/recovery/", "description": "DAODAS recovery page includes information on recovery housing resources in South Carolina. For additional recovery housing listings, visit the DAODAS local providers directory."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Contacts", "url": "https://osp.scdmh.org/get-help/", "description": "SC Mobile Crisis Line: 1-833-364-2274 for 24/7/365 community-based mental health crisis response. Also 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline and Crisis Text Line (text HOPE4SC to 741741). SAMHSA National Helpline: 1-800-662-4357."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "South Carolina Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://llr.sc.gov/bop/", "description": "SC Board of Pharmacy, Department of Labor, Licensing and Regulation. Phone: 803-896-4700. Address: P.O. Box 11329, Columbia, SC 29211."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCDHHS Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/providers/pharmacy", "description": "South Carolina Department of Health and Human Services pharmacy provider contact. Provider Service Center: 888-289-0709."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DAODAS Contact", "url": "https://www.daodas.sc.gov/services/treatment/local-providers/", "description": "South Carolina Department of Alcohol and Other Drug Abuse Services, the state's single state agency for substance use disorder prevention and treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Carolina Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://scrx.org/", "description": "SCPhA represents pharmacy professionals across South Carolina through advocacy, education, and connectivity. Address: 1350 Browning Road, Suite 100, Columbia, SC 29210."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DPH Opioid Programs", "url": "https://dph.sc.gov/professionals/healthcare-quality/prescription-monitoring-program-scripts", "description": "South Carolina Department of Public Health prescription monitoring and opioid oversight programs, including SCRIPTS administration and data dashboards."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Just Plain Killers Data Dashboard", "url": "https://justplainkillers.com/data/", "description": "Comprehensive South Carolina opioid epidemic data hub with special statistical reports, county-level data tables on overdose deaths, EMS naloxone administrations, and treatment services with interactive dashboards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCRIPTS Prescription Monitoring Data", "url": "https://dph.sc.gov/professionals/healthcare-quality/prescription-monitoring-program-scripts", "description": "Interactive dashboards showing dispensation information for opioids, benzodiazepines, and stimulants at state and county levels with demographic data for a rolling two-year period."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DPH Overdose Death Statistical Reports", "url": "https://dph.sc.gov/news/state-sees-first-decline-overdose-death-10-years-dph-daodas-continue-focus-prevention", "description": "South Carolina Department of Public Health overdose death data derived from death certificates, with annual Drug Overdose Deaths Statistical Reports and press releases on overdose trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DAODAS Overdose Death Prevention", "url": "https://www.daodas.sc.gov/services/prevention/overdose-death-prevention/", "description": "DAODAS overdose death prevention page with data and resources for prevention efforts statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCDHHS OUD Treatment Data", "url": "https://www.scdhhs.gov/communications/medicaid-coverage-opioid-treatment-programs-and-scdhhs-efforts-address-opioid-crisis", "description": "SCDHHS reporting on Medicaid coverage of opioid treatment programs, MAT access, and treatment utilization data for OUD in South Carolina."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SCPhA Advocacy", "url": "https://scrx.org/", "description": "South Carolina Pharmacy Association provides advocacy on the state level representing pharmacy interests to governmental entities and payers. SCPhA offers collaborative practice agreement toolkits and legislative resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SCPhA Popular Resources", "url": "https://scrx.org/resources/popular-resources/", "description": "SCPhA resources page with links to collaborative practice agreement toolkits, state-by-state CPA comparisons, patient medication safety programs, and advocacy tools."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your South Carolina Legislator", "url": "https://www.scstatehouse.gov/legislatorssearch.php", "description": "South Carolina Legislature Online tool for finding state senators and representatives by address. Also enables direct email contact with legislators on pharmacy and OUD-related policy issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SC Overdose Prevention Act", "url": "https://www.scstatehouse.gov/code/t44c130.php", "description": "Full text of the South Carolina Overdose Prevention Act, key legislation enabling pharmacist naloxone dispensing and community naloxone distribution."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DAODAS Prevention and Advocacy", "url": "https://www.daodas.sc.gov/services/prevention/overdose-death-prevention/", "description": "DAODAS overdose death prevention programs and statewide prevention initiatives addressing opioid use disorder in South Carolina."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Just Plain Killers (DAODAS Campaign)", "url": "https://justplainkillers.com/", "description": "DAODAS public awareness campaign with comprehensive information on the opioid epidemic in South Carolina, including data, treatment resources, naloxone access, and fentanyl test strip distribution."}]}]}, "southdakota": {"name": "South Dakota", "q": {"CPA_Term": "South Dakota’s term for a CPA is a “protocol” for drug therapy. S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(6) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Dakota law expressly provides that it “does not authorize a pharmacist to prescribe drugs as a practitioner.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-2.2 (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in South Dakota cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the South Dakota practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow South Dakota pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, South Dakota laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Dakota law does not expressly address administering drugs or medications. S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-2.2 (West 2024).\nAlthough it is not in the practice of pharmacy definition, a separate law about the “authority of registered pharmacists” provides that such pharmacists may “perform drug administration pursuant to a prescription drug order.”\nS.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(1) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.However, this same law further directs that the “[South Dakota] Board of Pharmacy shall establish standards for drug administration.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(1) (West 2024). While there are South Dakota pharmacy regulations addressing pharmacist administration of immunizations, there are no regulations addressing the administration of any other drug or medication. S.D. ADMIN. R. 20:51:28 (2024).\nThe lack of any standards promulgated through regulation (other than for immunizations) may serve to limit a pharmacist’s authority to administer drugs and medications generally.", "2B": "Obtain a prescription drug order.\n Understand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the South Dakota practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in South Dakota law does not expressly address ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-2.2 (West 2024).\nAlthough it is not in the practice of pharmacy definition, a separate law about the “authority of registered pharmacists” provides that such pharmacists may “interpret and apply pharmacokinetic data and other pertinent laboratory data to design safe and effective drug dosage regimens.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(4) (West 2024).\nSouth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations do not provide additional explanation about what “interpret and apply pharmacokinetic data and other pertinent laboratory data” means.", "3B": "Confirm that the lab test ordered or evaluated fits within the meaning of “interpret and apply pharmacokinetic data and other pertinent laboratory data.”", "3C": "Revise South Dakota laws and/or regulations to define or explain the phrase “pharmacokinetic data and other pertinent laboratory data.”\nIf necessary, expand the South Dakota practice of pharmacy to expressly allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nSouth Dakota law setting forth additional aspects of the “authority of registered pharmacists” beyond the definition of the practice of pharmacy allows pharmacists to “initiate or modify drug therapy by protocol or other legal authority established and approved . . . by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(6) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiate or modify,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nSouth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what drug therapy may or may not entail and whether that includes prescribing drugs and medications.\nEven if a drug therapy protocol could allow a South Dakota pharmacist to prescribe drugs, South Dakota laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a South Dakota pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the drug therapy protocol provides.\nIn summary, South Dakota laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a drug therapy protocol. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a South Dakota pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise South Dakota laws and/or regulations governing drug therapy to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in South Dakota laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under drug therapy protocols.\nAllow South Dakota pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, South Dakota laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nSouth Dakota law setting forth additional aspects of the “authority of registered pharmacists” beyond the definition of the practice of pharmacy allows pharmacists to “initiate or modify drug therapy by protocol or other legal authority established and approved . . . by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(6) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiate or modify,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nSouth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what drug therapy may or may not entail and whether that includes administering drugs and medications.\nIn summary, although South Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine as part of a protocol for drug therapy, they also do not clearly authorize it and a pharmacist’s general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a drug therapy protocol is also unclear.", "5B": "Enter into a drug therapy protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in South Dakota laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a drug therapy protocol include administering drugs and medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, South Dakota laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nSouth Dakota law setting forth additional aspects of the “authority of registered pharmacists” beyond the definition of the practice of pharmacy allows pharmacists to “initiate or modify drug therapy by protocol or other legal authority established and approved . . . by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(6) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the phrase “initiate or modify,” it does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests.\nSouth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what drug therapy may or may not entail and whether that includes administering drugs and medications.\nAs a result, South Dakota laws and regulations governing drug therapy protocols are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can order or evaluate lab tests. However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has limited authority to interpret and apply pharmacokinetic data and other pertinent laboratory data, the most logical answer to this question is that a pharmacist has the same authority under a drug therapy protocol.", "6B": "Confirm that the lab test ordered or evaluated fits within the meaning of “interpret and apply pharmacokinetic data and other pertinent laboratory data.”\nEnter into a drug therapy protocol (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in South Dakota law and regulation that a pharmacist’s authority under a protocol for drug therapy includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Pharmacists may initiate or modify drug therapy “by protocol or other legal authority established and approved within a licensed health care facility or by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-19.1(6) (West 2024).\nUnder South Dakota pharmacy law, “practitioner” means “a person licensed, registered or otherwise authorized by the jurisdiction in which the person is practicing to prescribe drugs in the course of professional practice.”\nS.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 36-11-2(23) (West 2024).\nSouth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation or description about what drug therapy may or may not entail or what must be part of any written protocol for drug therapy.", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nSouth Dakota’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice act authorizes a licensed “health care professional” to treat a patient using telehealth, subject to any rule adopted by the applicable licensing body. S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 34-52-2 (West 2024).\n“Health care professional” means “a physician or other health care practitioner licensed, accredited, or certified to perform specified health services consistent with state law.” S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 34-52-1(1) (West 2024)\n(incorporating the definition from S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 58-17F-1(8) (West 2024)). This includes pharmacists.\nSouth Dakota pharmacy laws and regulations do not address telehealth but do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "Controlled drugs cannot be prescribed without “a proper provider-patient relationship,” but that relationship can be established through telehealth. S.D. CODIFIED LAWS § 34-52-6 (West 2024).\nSouth Dakota laws and regulations governing telehealth include – S.D. CODIFIED LAWS §§ 34-52-1 to 34-52-8 (West 2024) (telehealth generally); S.D. CODIFIED LAWS §§ 36-11-71 to 36-11-72 (West 2024) (telepharmacy); S.D. CODIFIED LAWS §§ 58-17-167 to 58-17-170 (West 2024) (insurance); S.D. ADMIN. R. 20:51:30:01 to 20:51:30:18 (2024) (telepharmacy); S.D. ADMIN. R. 67:16 (2024)\n(Medicaid – spread throughout chapter).", "9A": "None.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the South Dakota Medicaid program.\nSpecify in South Dakota laws and/or regulation that pharmacist services provided under a under a protocol for drug therapy are covered under the South Dakota Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://southdakota.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "South Dakota's PDMP login portal (PMP AWARxE) for prescribers and pharmacists to query controlled substance dispensing records."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Homepage", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/licensing-and-records/boards/pharmacy/prescription-drug-monitoring-program/", "description": "South Dakota Department of Health PDMP homepage with program information, user sign-in links, data submitter resources, and law enforcement access details. The SD PDMP was established by SDCL 34-20E in 2010 and became operational in March 2012."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration and User Support", "url": "https://pmpawarxe.zendesk.com/hc/en-us", "description": "PMP AWARxE User Support Center for account registration, troubleshooting, and access instructions for pharmacists and prescribers."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Reporting to the SD PDMP is required per SDCL 34-20E and ARSD 20:51:32. Dispensers must submit data on all controlled substance prescriptions dispensed to South Dakota patients. Prescribers and pharmacists may be granted online access for query purposes."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Interstate Data Sharing", "url": "https://nabp.pharmacy/members/programs-services/pmp-interconnect/", "description": "South Dakota participates in NABP's PMP InterConnect, enabling interstate sharing of PDMP data with other participating states. SD went live with PMP InterConnect and integrates PDMP data via Bamboo Health's PMP Gateway platform."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the PMP AWARxE system at the PDMP portal. Prescribers and dispensers can designate authorized delegates to query the PDMP on their behalf. See the Quick Reference Guide for making requests linked from the PDMP program homepage."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/licensing-and-records/boards/pharmacy/", "description": "South Dakota Board of Pharmacy homepage, housed within the Department of Health. Provides licensing information, board meeting dates, news, and links to statutes and rules. Executive Director: Tyler Laetsch, PharmD. Phone: 605-362-2737."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (SDCL 36-11)", "url": "https://sdlegislature.gov/Statutes/36-11", "description": "South Dakota Codified Laws Title 36, Chapter 11 - Pharmacies and Pharmacists. Full text of the state Pharmacy Practice Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Justia mirror)", "url": "https://law.justia.com/codes/south-dakota/title-36/chapter-11/", "description": "Alternative access to South Dakota Codified Laws Chapter 36-11 on Justia, in case the SD Legislature website requires a specific browser."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules (ARSD 20:51)", "url": "https://sdlegislature.gov/Rules/Administrative/20:51", "description": "South Dakota Administrative Rules Title 20, Article 51 - Pharmacists. Contains the Board of Pharmacy's administrative rules for pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statutes and Rules Overview", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/news-statutes/statutes-rules/licensing-boards-statutes-rules/", "description": "South Dakota Department of Health page listing all pharmacy-related statutes and administrative rules, including SDCL 34-12B, SDCL 36-11, SDCL 36-11A, and ARSD sections."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice and Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: South Dakota authorizes collaborative drug therapy management by pharmacists under protocol. SDCL 36-11-19.1 outlines the authority of registered pharmacists. Collaborative practice agreements (CPAs) in SD cannot grant a pharmacist authority to prescribe controlled substances independently. South Dakota does not have broad independent pharmacist prescribing authority."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in South Dakota, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory for finding practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine. Can be filtered by state to find South Dakota providers."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Gretchen Stai, Department of Social Services Division of Behavioral Health, 1501 S Highline Ave, Suite 2D, Sioux Falls, SD 57110. Phone: (605) 812-3330. Fax: (605) 367-5239. Email: gretchen.stai@state.sd.us", "description": "South Dakota's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA SOTA Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA's full directory of State Opioid Treatment Authorities by state."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), healthcare providers no longer need an X-waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of DEA registration or renewal. South Dakota does not impose additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law for buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing. South Dakota follows federal DEA telehealth regulations. Under current DEA rules, practitioners may initiate buprenorphine via telehealth with follow-up in-person visits required."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://dss.sd.gov/medicaid/providers/programinfo/pharmacy/", "description": "South Dakota Medicaid pharmacy benefit page. Since November 2017, South Dakota Medicaid utilizes OptumRx to process pharmacy claims and prior authorizations. Help Desk: 855-401-4262. Member questions: 800-452-7691."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Pharmacy Billing Manual", "url": "https://dss.sd.gov/docs/medicaid/providers/billingmanuals/Pharmacy/Pharmacy_Services.pdf", "description": "South Dakota Medicaid Billing and Policy Manual for Pharmacy Services, including information on the preferred drug list, dispensing fees, and prior authorization requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OptumRx Prior Authorization Portal", "url": "https://sdm.pharmacy.optum.com/", "description": "OptumRx website for South Dakota Medicaid pharmacy prior authorization forms and additional information. Prior authorization fax: 800-527-0531."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medicaid Fee Schedules", "url": "https://dss.sd.gov/Medicaid/providers/feeschedules/default.aspx", "description": "South Dakota Medicaid provider fee schedules page. Includes pharmacy dispensing fee schedule and other service rates. Providers must bill their usual and customary charges."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities for OUD Treatment", "url": "https://dss.sd.gov/behavioralhealth/grantinfo.aspx", "description": "South Dakota DSS Behavioral Health funding opportunities page, including the State Opioid Response (SOR) Grant and Opioid Settlement Fund Community Grant Program with three tiers of awards (Resource Grants up to $5,000, Organizational Grants up to $50,000, and Transformative Grants above $50,000)."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Continuing Education Requirements", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/licensing-and-records/boards/pharmacy/continuing-education-requirements/", "description": "South Dakota Board of Pharmacy CE requirements page. Pharmacists must complete 12 hours of approved continuing education for yearly licensure, earned in the two years prior to the license expiration date. South Dakota does not currently require specific controlled substance CE hours."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://www.sdpha.org/member-center", "description": "SDPhA member center providing access to continuing education opportunities, annual convention information, and professional development resources. SDSU College of Pharmacy is accredited by ACPE as a CE provider."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Pharmacists Association Annual Convention", "url": "https://www.sdpha.org/annual-convention", "description": "SDPhA annual convention page with CE programming information. The SDSU College of Pharmacy and Allied Health Professions is the accredited CE provider."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division homepage for DEA registration and controlled substance regulations relevant to buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training (Provider Clinical Support System)", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS-MOUD offers free training modules, webinars, and clinical tools for healthcare providers on evidence-based treatment of opioid use disorder, including buprenorphine prescribing. Satisfies MATE Act training requirements."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/licensing-and-records/boards/pharmacy/naloxone-standing-order/", "description": "South Dakota Board of Pharmacy naloxone standing order page. Through a statewide standing order, pharmacists can dispense naloxone without a prescription to anyone at risk of an opioid overdose or their family members, friends, or close third parties. Pharmacists must complete 1 hour of training and follow six steps outlined on this page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Let's Be Clear Naloxone Distribution", "url": "https://letsbeclearsd.com/providers/pharmacy/standing-order-participation", "description": "Detailed information for pharmacies on participating in the statewide naloxone standing order, including eligibility assessment forms, patient education materials, and how to join the participating pharmacy list. Naloxone cost assistance is available through SD DSS for uninsured individuals."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: South Dakota does not have a statewide syringe services program law. Access to SSPs may be limited. Contact the Division of Behavioral Health at 605-367-5236 for current harm reduction resources."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: South Dakota passed HB 1041 exempting fentanyl test strips from the state drug paraphernalia definition, making them legal to possess and distribute."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://letsbeclearsd.com/key-data", "description": "Let's Be Clear South Dakota dashboard with key substance use and overdose data, intervention metrics, and more. From 2020-2024, there were 357 overdose deaths in South Dakota, with stimulants involved in 51% and opioids in 47%."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SUDORS Reports", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/health-data-reports/substance-use-data-reports/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system-sudors/", "description": "South Dakota State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS) page with annual reports on overdose deaths, including county-level data and substance involvement breakdowns."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Communities of South Dakota", "url": "https://www.recoverycommunitiesofsouthdakota.org/", "description": "A peer-based recovery community organization providing recovery coaching and peer support services in South Dakota. Guided by Lakota cultural values and elders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Services", "url": "https://sdbehavioralhealth.gov/recovery/peer-support", "description": "South Dakota Behavioral Health page on peer support services, including certified peer coaching for individuals with substance use disorders. Participants partner with a certified peer coach with lived experience."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://sdbehavioralhealth.gov/recovery-housing", "description": "South Dakota Behavioral Health recovery housing page with information on sober living and transitional housing options in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Division of Behavioral Health", "url": "https://dss.sd.gov/behavioralhealth/", "description": "South Dakota Department of Social Services Division of Behavioral Health homepage. Provides information on substance use disorder treatment services, prevention, and recovery support. Contact: 605-367-5236. Email: DSSBH@state.sd.us."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Behavioral Health Portal", "url": "https://sdbehavioralhealth.gov/", "description": "South Dakota's public-facing behavioral health website with resources for mental health, substance use, and crisis care. Includes 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline and 211 for local resources."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Call 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Call 211 (Helpline Center) for local resources including housing, food, health care, and behavioral health. South Dakota Division of Behavioral Health: 605-367-5236."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Board of Pharmacy Executive Director: Tyler Laetsch, PharmD, Executive Director, South Dakota Board of Pharmacy, 4001 W. Valhalla Blvd., Suite 106, Sioux Falls, SD 57106. Phone: 605-362-2737. Fax: 605-362-2738. Email: tyler.laetsch@state.sd.us.", "description": "Primary contact for the South Dakota Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact Page", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/licensing-and-records/boards/pharmacy/contact/", "description": "Full staff directory for the South Dakota Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Medicaid Contact", "url": "https://dss.sd.gov/medicaid/contact/PhoneList.aspx", "description": "South Dakota Medicaid phone listing with contacts for claims, eligibility, and pharmacy-related inquiries. Pharmacy claims handled by OptumRx: 855-401-4262."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Gretchen Stai, Department of Social Services Division of Behavioral Health, 1501 S Highline Ave, Suite 2D, Sioux Falls, SD 57110. Phone: (605) 812-3330. Email: gretchen.stai@state.sd.us.", "description": "South Dakota's SOTA contact for opioid treatment program oversight."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://www.sdpha.org/", "description": "SDPhA homepage. The state pharmacy association advocates for the profession and provides CE, legislative advocacy, and resources to members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Department of Health OUD Programs", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/programs/lets-be-clear/", "description": "Let's Be Clear program page, South Dakota's joint initiative between the Department of Health and Department of Social Services to address substance misuse and substance use disorders. Contact the DOH for program lead information."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SUDORS Overdose Death Reports", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/health-data-reports/substance-use-data-reports/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system-sudors/", "description": "South Dakota's SUDORS page with annual reports on unintentional drug overdose deaths. Data sourced from death certificates, coroner reports, and toxicology. From 2020-2024, males made up 59% of overdose deaths, and American Indians died at a rate 4.4 times higher than Whites."}, {"type": "link", "title": "2024 SUDORS Report", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/media/zj2ojicg/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system-sudors-report-2024.pdf", "description": "Most recent SUDORS report with opioid and stimulant involvement data by county of injury."}, {"type": "link", "title": "2023 SUDORS Report", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/media/140dz3hm/state-unintentional-drug-overdose-reporting-system-sudors-report-2023.pdf", "description": "2023 SUDORS report showing that from 2020-2023, 51% of deaths involved a stimulant and 47% involved an opioid."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Use Data Reports", "url": "https://doh.sd.gov/health-data-reports/substance-use-data-reports/", "description": "South Dakota Department of Health substance use data and reports page, including SUDORS, treatment data, and other epidemiological resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Let's Be Clear Data Dashboard", "url": "https://letsbeclearsd.com/key-data", "description": "Interactive reporting dashboard with overdose death trends, intervention metrics, and substance misuse data across South Dakota."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Federal Opioid Funding Annual Report", "url": "https://mylrc.sdlegislature.gov/api/Documents/Attachment/246096.pdf?Year=2023", "description": "2022 Annual Report on federal opioid funding in South Dakota, detailing SOR grant activities, treatment access, and outcomes."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SDPhA Legislative Resources", "url": "https://www.sdpha.org/resources", "description": "South Dakota Pharmacists Association resources page with links to legislation, government relations information, and the SD Board of Pharmacy. SDPhA is committed to creating legislation that benefits pharmacists and their patients."}, {"type": "link", "title": "South Dakota Legislative Sessions", "url": "https://sdlegislature.gov/Session/Bills/44", "description": "Current South Dakota legislative session bills page for tracking pharmacy-related and OUD-related legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your SD Legislator", "url": "https://sdlegislature.gov/legislators/find", "description": "South Dakota Legislature tool to find and contact your state legislators by address."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SDPhA Contact for Advocacy", "url": "https://www.sdpha.org/contact-us", "description": "Contact the South Dakota Pharmacists Association for advocacy talking points and legislative engagement opportunities. SDPhA hosts annual Legislative Days for pharmacists to meet with policymakers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Let's Be Clear Initiative", "url": "https://letsbeclearsd.com/", "description": "South Dakota's statewide opioid response initiative jointly led by the Department of Health and Department of Social Services. Serves as a central hub for opioid prevention, treatment, and recovery resources and serves as the state's main OUD coalition effort."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SDAHO Opioid Resources", "url": "https://sdaho.org/opioids/", "description": "South Dakota Association of Healthcare Organizations opioid resources page, including the ED toolkit for providers on screening, diagnosis, and referral to treatment for OUD. Funded through SAMHSA grant."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA Pharmacy Model Legislation: For national model legislation and policy templates relevant to pharmacist prescribing and OUD treatment, visit the National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA) at https://naspa.us/ and ASHP at https://www.ashp.org/advocacy. These resources can be adapted for South Dakota-specific advocacy efforts."}]}]}, "tennessee": {"name": "Tennessee", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Tennessee’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(5) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Tennessee law expressly provides that it does not authorize pharmacists “to prescribe any prescription drugs except pursuant to a medical order by the attending prescriber for each patient or pursuant to a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(B) (West 2024).\nDespite the general prohibition, the practice of pharmacy does allow Tennessee pharmacists to issue a “prescription or medical order” for certain specified, non-controlled drugs or devices. TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(C) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Tennessee can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Administer, Prescribe & Dispense” controlled substances, but only “pursuant to a collaborative agreement with prescriber.” Note, however, that as described in the answer to the \"prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, CPPAs cannot grant pharmacists the ability to prescribe controlled substances except in certain settings.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Tennessee practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications outside of a CPPA, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Tennessee pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances without needing a CPPA.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Tennessee law expressly includes “participation in drug . . . administration.” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(A)(iii) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.\nUnlike the laws and regulations of several other states with general language about administration in the practice of pharmacy definition, there are no other Tennessee laws or regulations that expressly address administration of a small subset of drugs or medications (such as immunizations) that would give the impression that the legislature or state board of pharmacy does not view the “drug administration” language as a broad authorization.", "2B": "Tennessee laws or regulations do not expressly describe what, if any, requirements must be met before a pharmacist can administer drugs.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Tennessee law expressly provides that “nothing in this chapter authorizes a pharmacist to order laboratory tests . . . except pursuant to a medical order by the attending prescriber for each patient or pursuant to a [CPPA].” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(B) (West 2024).However, pharmacists are authorized “to conduct and assist patients with tests approved for home use.” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(B) (West 2024).\nMoreover, a pharmacist can order lab tests in conjunction with therapy for post-exposure prophylaxis for nonoccupational exposure to HIV infection. TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(C)(iii) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Tennessee practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Based on the information described below, the answer is “yes,” if the CPPA is within “an institutional-based pharmacy setting” and “no” if it is not in such setting.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Tennessee law expressly includes “provision of patient care services and activities pursuant to a [CPPA].” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(A)(vii) (West 2024).\nTennessee law governing CPPAs directs the Tennessee Board of Pharmacy to promulgate rules covering, among other things, the drug categories covered under a CPPA, including controlled substances. TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-217(g) (West 2024).\nTennessee regulation governing CPPAs expressly allows for a pharmacist to hold “a current federal [DEA] license” and requires such holder to obtain continuing education each year related to “controlled substance prescribing.” TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 1140-03-.17(15) (2024).\nHowever, that same Tennessee regulation provides that the scope of a CPPA “shall NOT include . . . the prescribing of controlled substances, except by a pharmacist practicing within an institutional-based pharmacy setting or for hospice patients.” TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 1140-03- .17(6)(b) (2024).", "4B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": "Revise Tennessee laws and/or regulations governing CPPAs to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances outside of institutional-based pharmacy setting.\nExpressly specify in Tennessee laws or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPPAs.\nAllow all Tennessee pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Tennessee laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Tennessee law expressly includes “provision of patient care services and activities pursuant to a [CPPA].” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(A)(vii) (West 2024).\nA CPPA must contain a provision defining the scope of patient care services, including “screening, prevention, assessment, management, and care, authorized or restricted to be provided by the pharmacist(s).” Such services must be “within the routine scope of practice and services” delivered by the collaborating prescriber. TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 1140-03-.17(5)(b) (2024).\nTennessee laws and regulations governing collaborative practice and CPPAs do not expressly address whether administering drugs and medications is one of the authorized patient care services.\nAs a result, Tennessee laws and regulations governing CPPAs are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can administer drugs and medications. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has the general authority to administer drugs outside of a CPPA, the most logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify in Tennessee laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CPPA include administering drugs and medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Tennessee law includes “provision of patient care services and activities pursuant to a [CPPA].” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(A)(vii) (West 2024).\nA CPPA must contain a provision defining the scope of patient care services, including “screening, prevention, assessment, management, and care, authorized or restricted to be provided by the pharmacist(s).” Such services must be “within the routine scope of practice and services” delivered by the collaborating prescriber. TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 1140-03-.17(5)(b) (2024).\nTennessee laws and regulations governing collaborative practice and CPPAs do not expressly address whether ordering or evaluating lab tests is one of the authorized patient care services.\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition also provides that “nothing in this chapter authorizes a pharmacist to order laboratory tests . . . except pursuant to a medical order by the attending prescriber for each patient or pursuant to a [CPPA].” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-204(39)(B) (West 2024). This provision provides implicit authority for a pharmacist to order lab tests under a CPPA even though CPPA-specific laws and regulations do not refer to it.", "6B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Tennessee laws and/or regulations that a pharmacist’s authority under a CPPA includes evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Tennessee law provides that a CPPA is an agreement between one or more pharmacists and either “an individual prescriber” or “one (1) or more prescribers . . . in an organized medical group.” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-217(a) (West 2024).\nTennessee regulation calls the party to a CPPA a “collaborating prescriber,” which includes only physicians, advance practice nurses, or physician assistants. TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 1140-03-.17(1)(d) (2024).\nThe following Tennessee laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPPAs and required elements of CPPAs – TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-10-217 (West 2024); TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 1140-03-.17 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but see the buprenorphine prescribing note in (8C).\nTennessee’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice act provides that a “healthcare provider” delivering services via telehealth is held to the same standard of professional practice as a when providing services through in-person encounters. TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-1-155 (West 2024).\n“Healthcare provider” includes “an individual acting within the scope of a valid license issued pursuant to this title [Title 63].” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-1-155(a)(1)(A)\n(West 2024). This includes pharmacists.", "8B": null, "8C": "A healthcare provider may not prescribe a “buprenorphine product” via telehealth unless the healthcare provider is “employed by or contracted with” one of five types of entities identified in Tennessee telehealth law and telehealth is provided on behalf of the employing or contracting entity. TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-1-155(j) (West 2024).\nTennessee laws and regulations governing telehealth include – TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-1-155 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); TENN. CODE ANN. §§ 56-7-1002 to 56-7-1003, 56-7-1012 (West 2024) (insurance); TENN. CODE ANN. § 71-5-167 (West 2024) (Medicaid); TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 0880-02-.16 (2024) (physicians); TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 0940-05-35-.02 (2024) (OBOT).", "9A": "Tennessee insurance law provides that a “managed health insurance issuer” may not discriminate with respect to “participation, referral, reimbursement of covered services or indemnification” for a defined “class of providers” acting with the provider’s scope of license, solely on the basis of the license or certification. TENN. CODE ANN. § 56-32-129(a) (West 2024). Pharmacists are included in the definition of “class of providers.” TENN. CODE ANN. § 56-32-129(b) (West 2024).\nThe above provision grants Tennessee pharmacists with provider status within managed health insurance plans, which includes Tennessee Medicaid. Although no special designation is necessary, pharmacists may need to be a part of a CPPA to bill for services that would otherwise fall outside of a pharmacist’s scope of practice.", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Tennessee law contains an extensive set of buprenorphine prescribing limitations and restrictions. TENN. CODE ANN. § 53-11-311 (West 2024). These restrictions include limitations on who can prescribe buprenorphine. The general rule is that “a physician licensed under title 63 . . . is the only healthcare provider authorized to prescribe any buprenorphine product” for use in “recovery or medication-assisted treatment.” TENN. CODE ANN. § 53-11-311(c)(1) (West 2024). However, non-physicians otherwise permitted to prescribe schedule III controlled substances who meet the 15 requirements specified in Tennessee law may prescribe buprenorphine for SUD treatment. TENN. CODE ANN. § 53-11-311(c)(2) (West 2024).\nVarious state departments and agencies must collaborate to develop certain educational materials and provide them to “prescribers of medication assisted treatment” and facilities that use such medications to treat SUD. TENN. CODE ANN. § 53-11-312 (West 2024).\nIn addition, there is a law governing the authorized forms of payment for “buprenorphine products” as well as prohibited methods of provider compensation for such products. TENN. CODE ANN. § 53-11-313 (West 2024).Moreover, Tennessee law requires the commissioner of mental health and substance abuse services, in collaboration with the commissioner of health, to develop “recommended nonresidential treatment guidelines for the use of buprenorphine that can be used by prescribers in this state as a guide for caring for patients.” TENN. CODE ANN. § 63-1-403(b)(1) (West 2024).\nAs a result, there are an extensive section of regulations providing “minimum program requirements for nonresidential office-based opiate treatment [OBOT] facilities.” TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 0940-05-35-.01 to 0940-05-35-.20 (2024). These regulations cover, among other things, admission practices, patient records, treatment plans, phases of treatment, counseling, medication management, drug screen, patient rights, and staffing requirements.\nAdditionally, there is a separate set of regulations for “minimum program requirements for nonresidential office-based opiate treatment [OBOT] facilities with dispensing authorization.” TENN. COMP. R. & REGS. 0940-05-36-.01 to 0940-05-36-.11 (2024).\nAll patient charts in which a Tennessee physician assistant (PA) prescribes “any drug containing buprenorphine for use in recovery or medication treatment or a Schedule II controlled drug” must be reviewed by the PA’s collaborating physician within 30 days. TENN. CODE ANN. §§ 63-19-106 to 63-19-107 (West 2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CSMD Portal", "url": "https://www.tncsmd.com/", "description": "Tennessee's Controlled Substance Monitoring Database (CSMD) login portal for practitioners and pharmacists to query controlled substance dispensing records."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSMD Program Homepage", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/health/health-program-areas/health-professional-boards/csmd-board.html", "description": "Tennessee Department of Health CSMD homepage with program information, EHR integration details, and resources. The CSMD was established by the Controlled Substance Monitoring Act of 2002. Data collection began December 1, 2006 for Schedule II-V controlled substances."}, {"type": "note", "text": "CSMD Registration: Registration is available through the CSMD portal at tncsmd.com. Healthcare practitioners (prescribers, pharmacists, and their delegates) must register for an account. Tennessee requires mandatory CSMD checking before prescribing opioids."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Tennessee participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate PDMP data sharing. The state has contracted with Bamboo Health to integrate CSMD data into approved EHR and Pharmacy Management Systems via PMP Gateway."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the CSMD portal. Prescribers and dispensers can designate authorized delegates to query the CSMD on their behalf."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSMD Annual Report", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/health/healthprofboards/csmd/2025CSMDAnnualReportFinal.pdf", "description": "Tennessee CSMD Annual Report with dispensing data and program statistics."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/health/health-program-areas/health-professional-boards/pharmacy-board.html", "description": "Tennessee Board of Pharmacy homepage within the Tennessee Department of Health Health Related Boards. Provides licensing, registration, and regulatory information. Phone: (615) 253-1299. Email: Pharmacy.Health@tn.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy About Page", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/health/health-program-areas/health-professional-boards/pharmacy-board/pharmacy-board/about.html", "description": "About the Tennessee Board of Pharmacy, including mission, contact information, and details on opioid abuse/diversion reporting via the Complaint Intake Hotline: 1-800-852-2187."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Statutes and Rules", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/health/health-program-areas/health-professional-boards/pharmacy-board/pharmacy-board/statutes-and-rules.html", "description": "Links to Tennessee pharmacy statutes (TCA Title 63, Chapter 10) and board rules, including the Pharmacy Practice Act (TCA 63-10-201), Board of Pharmacy (TCA 63-10-301), and related laws."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Administrative Rules", "url": "https://publications.tnsosfiles.com/rules/1140/1140.htm", "description": "Tennessee Board of Pharmacy Rules (Chapter 1140), published by the Tennessee Secretary of State. Includes rules on standards of practice, licensure, and controlled substances."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Rules", "url": "https://publications.tnsosfiles.com/rules/1140/1140-03.20240314.pdf", "description": "Tennessee Rules 1140-03 (Standards of Practice), including Section 1140-03-.17 on Collaborative Pharmacy Practice. Tennessee allows collaborative practice agreements that can grant pharmacists prescriptive authority, including initiation and discontinuance of drug therapy, with specific requirements for listing authorized drugs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice (Cornell Law)", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/tennessee/Tenn-Comp-R-Regs-1140-03-.17", "description": "Tennessee Comp. R. and Regs. 1140-03-.17 on Collaborative Pharmacy Practice, accessible through Cornell Law Institute. Collaborative pharmacists with prescriptive authority are encouraged to complete 10 of 30 biennial CE hours in clinical pharmacy topics."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Tennessee does not have independent pharmacist prescribing authority. However, collaborative pharmacy practice agreements can grant pharmacists prescriptive authority for specific drugs or categories of drugs as outlined in the agreement."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Tennessee, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory for finding practitioners authorized to treat opioid dependency with buprenorphine in Tennessee."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Wes Geminn, TN Dept. of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services, Division of Clinical Leadership, 500 Deaderick St., Nashville, TN 37243. Phone: (615) 532-6736. Email: wesley.geminn@tn.gov", "description": "Tennessee's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TDMHSAS Treatment and Recovery", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-services/treatment.html", "description": "Tennessee Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services treatment and recovery page. Includes information on co-occurring disorders, medication-assisted treatment, and referral to services. Tennessee REDLINE: 800-889-9789."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Guidance", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/mentalhealth/documents/Public_Guidance_DATA_Waiver_Removal_2.27.23.pdf", "description": "TDMHSAS public guidance on removal of the DATA waiver for buprenorphine prescribing. Under the MATE Act (2023), providers no longer need an X-waiver. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of SUD training for DEA registration."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing. Tennessee follows federal DEA telehealth regulations for buprenorphine prescribing."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "TennCare Pharmacy Benefits Manager", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/tenncare/providers/managed-care-contractors/pharmacy-benefits-manager.html", "description": "TennCare (Tennessee Medicaid) pharmacy benefits manager page. OptumRx manages pharmacy claims and prior authorizations for TennCare. Includes links to the Pharmacy Manual, Auto Exempt and Attestation Drug List, PDL, and PA forms."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TennCare Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://contenthub-aem.optumrx.com/content/dam/contenthub/onboarding/assets/Tenncare/Tenncare-PDL.pdf", "description": "TennCare Preferred Drug List (PDL) including buprenorphine and buprenorphine/naloxone products. Generic buprenorphine products are available with Buprenorphine Enhanced Supportive Medication-Assisted Treatment criteria."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TennCare Prior Authorization Criteria", "url": "https://contenthub-aem.optumrx.com/content/dam/contenthub/onboarding/assets/Tenncare/Criteria-PDL.pdf", "description": "TennCare prior authorization criteria document. Buprenorphine products require PA submission using the specific Buprenorphine Products PA Form."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OptumRx TennCare Portal", "url": "https://welcome.optumrx.com/tenncare/landing", "description": "OptumRx TennCare portal for pharmacy providers, including Web PA for prescribers and Web RA for pharmacies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/oac/community.html", "description": "Tennessee Opioid Abatement Council Community Funding page. Funds from opioid settlement agreements are available for prevention, harm reduction, treatment, recovery support, and education/training. The OAC was established by Public Chapter 491 of the Tennessee General Assembly."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CoverRx Program", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/tenncare/coverrx.html", "description": "Tennessee CoverRx prescription assistance program. Buprenorphine/naloxone 8/2 mg sublingual tablets do not count against the monthly 5-script limit."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "CE Requirements: Tennessee pharmacists must complete 30 hours of continuing education per biennial renewal period, with at least 15 hours being live. Pharmacist clinicians with a controlled substance registration to prescribe Schedule II and III controlled substances must complete 2 hours of responsible opioid prescribing practices CE."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CE Requirements Page", "url": "https://www.freece.com/pharmacy-ce-requirements/tennessee/", "description": "Summary of Tennessee pharmacist CE requirements including total hours, live hour requirements, and controlled substance CE information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://tnpharm.org/", "description": "TPA homepage offering continuing education opportunities, advocacy resources, and the Emerging Leaders Academy. The TPA provides CE through webinars, annual meetings, and law series events."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TPA Insight into Advocacy Law Series", "url": "https://tnpharm.org/insight-into-advocacy/", "description": "TPA educational series on pharmacy law, regulations, and advocacy efforts that impact pharmacy practice in Tennessee. Includes CE credit opportunities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division for registration and controlled substance regulatory information. Under the MATE Act, DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of SUD training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System (PCSS-MOUD) free training for healthcare providers on evidence-based treatment of OUD, including buprenorphine prescribing. Satisfies MATE Act training requirements."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://tennesseeharmreduction.com/syringe-exchanges-in-tennessee/", "description": "Tennessee Harm Reduction directory of syringe services programs (SSPs) across Tennessee. SSPs are nonprofits certified by the Department of Health that provide syringe exchange, naloxone, fentanyl test strips, HIV/HCV testing, wound care, and referral services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee Harm Reduction", "url": "https://tennesseeharmreduction.com/", "description": "Tennessee Harm Reduction organization offering a supply-by-mail program for naloxone, syringes, fentanyl test strips, and other harm reduction supplies shipped across Tennessee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access", "url": "https://tennesseeharmreduction.com/how-do-i-get-free-narcan-in-tennessee/", "description": "Guide to obtaining free naloxone in Tennessee, including through SSPs, prevention coalitions, Regional Overdose Prevention Specialists (ROPS), and the supply-by-mail program."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Regional Overdose Prevention Specialists", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-services/prevention/rops.html", "description": "Tennessee ROPS program page. ROPS are state employees who provide overdose response training and distribute naloxone and fentanyl test strips. TDH began providing fentanyl test strips to SSPs and ROPS in November 2022."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Tennessee permits equipment for testing all synthetic substances including fentanyl test strips. FTS are legal and distributed through SSPs and Regional Overdose Prevention Specialists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Developing SSPs in Tennessee Guide", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/health/documents/Developing-SSPs-in-Tennessee-Guide.pdf", "description": "Tennessee Department of Health guide for developing syringe services programs in Tennessee, including requirements and best practices."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/health/health-program-areas/pdo/pdo/data-dashboard.html", "description": "Tennessee Department of Health prescription drug overdose data dashboard with state, regional, and county level data on fatal overdoses, nonfatal overdoses, and drug prescribing. Please verify this link before publishing (may require direct browser access)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TN Overdose Prevention Statistics", "url": "https://www.tnoverdoseprevention.org/statistics", "description": "Tennessee Drug Overdose Dashboard with interactive data from TDH Office of Informatics and Analytics, including state, regional, and county level data."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Certified Peer Recovery Specialist Program", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health/cprs.html", "description": "Tennessee CPRS program page providing state certification for individuals who offer peer-to-peer support for people with mental illness, substance use, or co-occurring disorders. Overseen by TDMHSAS."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CPRS Portal", "url": "https://cprs.tn.gov/", "description": "Tennessee Certified Peer Recovery Specialist online portal for certification applications and management."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee Association of Peer Specialists", "url": "https://tnpeers.org/", "description": "TAPS provides training programs for peer specialists, advocacy efforts, and policy engagement to enhance mental health services in Tennessee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-services/treatment/recovery-housing.html", "description": "TDMHSAS recovery housing page. Recovery Residence Certification Organizations approved by TDMHSAS must meet minimum standards per TCA 33-2-1404. The Tennessee Alliance of Recovery Residences (TN ARR) serves as the state NARR affiliate."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee Alliance of Recovery Residences", "url": "https://www.tnarr.org/", "description": "TN ARR is the state affiliate of the National Alliance for Recovery Residences. Certifies recovery residences at Level I (Peer-Run) and Level II (Monitored)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TDMHSAS Behavioral Health Homepage", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health.html", "description": "Tennessee Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services homepage. Plans, develops, and administers statewide prevention, treatment, and recovery support services. Operates four Regional Mental Health Institutes."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Tennessee REDLINE: 800-889-9789 (24/7/365 substance misuse treatment referrals, call or text). National 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline: call or text 988."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee REDLINE", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-services/prevention/tennessee-redline.html", "description": "The Tennessee REDLINE is the state's 24/7/365 resource for confidential substance misuse treatment referrals."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Board of Pharmacy Contact: Tennessee Department of Health, Health Related Boards, Tennessee Board of Pharmacy, 665 Mainstream Drive, Nashville, TN 37243. Phone: (615) 253-1299. Fax: (615) 741-2722. Email: Pharmacy.Health@tn.gov.", "description": "Primary contact for the Tennessee Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "note", "text": "TennCare Pharmacy Information: OptumRx manages TennCare pharmacy benefits. Pharmacy Help Desk: 855-401-4262. TennCare member eligibility: contact TennCare directly. CoverRx PBM: OptumRx, 800-424-5815."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Wes Geminn, TN Dept. of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services, Division of Clinical Leadership, 500 Deaderick St., Nashville, TN 37243. Phone: (615) 532-6736. Email: wesley.geminn@tn.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://tnpharm.org/", "description": "TPA homepage. Provides advocacy, CE, and professional resources to pharmacy members across Tennessee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TPA Board of Directors", "url": "https://tnpharm.org/about/board-of-directors/", "description": "TPA leadership and board of directors contact information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TDMHSAS OUD Programs", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-services/prevention.html", "description": "TDMHSAS prevention programs page including opioid overdose prevention, Regional Overdose Prevention Specialists, and links to the Tennessee REDLINE."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://healthdata.tn.gov/Behavioral-Health/Drug-Overdose-Data-Dashboard/6phv-jmvk", "description": "Tennessee Department of Health interactive Drug Overdose Data Dashboard hosted on healthdata.tn.gov with state, regional, and county-level data on fatal and nonfatal overdoses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TN Overdose Prevention Dashboard", "url": "https://www.tnoverdoseprevention.org/statistics", "description": "Alternative access to the Tennessee Drug Overdose Dashboard, a collaboration between TDH and the Division of Strategic Technology Solutions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "2023 Drug Overdose Death Report", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/health/documents/pdo/death-report/2023_Tennessee_Drug_Overdose_Death_Report.pdf", "description": "Annual report on Tennessee drug overdose deaths with data by drug type, county, and demographics. Produced by TDH Office of Informatics and Analytics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSMD Annual Report", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/content/dam/tn/health/healthprofboards/csmd/2025CSMDAnnualReportFinal.pdf", "description": "CSMD annual report with controlled substance dispensing data and trends across Tennessee."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Settlement Spending Analysis", "url": "https://sycamoretn.org/opioid-settlement-funds-in-tn/", "description": "The Sycamore Institute's analysis of opioid settlement funds in Tennessee, including TennCare spending on substance abuse treatment and county-level funding data."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "TPA Advocacy and Law Series", "url": "https://tnpharm.org/insight-into-advocacy/", "description": "TPA Insight into Advocacy Pharmacy Law Series helping members understand laws, regulations, and advocacy efforts that shape pharmacy practice in Tennessee. Includes updates from the Tennessee General Assembly, Board of Pharmacy, and Department of Commerce and Insurance."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee General Assembly Legislation", "url": "https://www.capitol.tn.gov/legislators/", "description": "Tennessee General Assembly legislators page with access to current session bills and legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Legislative Updates", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/health/health-program-areas/health-professional-boards/pharmacy-board/pharmacy-board/legislative.html", "description": "Tennessee Board of Pharmacy legislative page with enacted pharmacy-related bills from recent sessions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Tennessee Legislator", "url": "https://wapp.capitol.tn.gov/apps/fml/search", "description": "Interactive map tool to find Tennessee state legislators by address or district."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Tennessee Opioid Abatement Council", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/oac.html", "description": "Tennessee's Opioid Abatement Council, established by Public Chapter 491 of the General Assembly, oversees distribution and use of opioid settlement funds. Provides community grants for prevention, treatment, recovery support, harm reduction, and education."}, {"type": "link", "title": "OAC Community Grants", "url": "https://www.tn.gov/oac/community.html", "description": "Community funding opportunities through the Tennessee Opioid Abatement Council. 35% of settlement proceeds go to counties. Grants are disbursed for opioid remediation activities."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA and National Advocacy Resources: For national model legislation and policy templates relevant to pharmacist prescribing and OUD treatment, visit the National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA) at https://naspa.us/ and ASHP at https://www.ashp.org/advocacy."}]}]}, "texas": {"name": "Texas", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Texas’s term for a CPA is a “protocol” for drug therapy management (DTM). 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295-13 (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Texas law does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs. TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(33) (West 2023).\nIn addition, the definition of “practitioner” in Texas law expressly excludes “a person licensed under this subtitle [Subtitle J].” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(34)(A)\n(West 2023). Subtitle J covers pharmacy and pharmacists.\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Texas cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Texas practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Texas pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Texas law expressly includes “participation in drug administration.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(33)(C) (West 2023).\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition also authorizes “administering an immunization or vaccination under a physician’s written protocol.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(33)(G) (West 2023). The fact that the Texas legislature included this specific provision in the practice of pharmacy definition indicates that the phrase “participation in drug administration” may not grant broad authority to a pharmacist to administer drugs and medications, or else this provision about immunizations/vaccinations might not be necessary.Moreover, the definition of “administer” in Texas law requires that it be done by “a person authorized by law to administer the drug, including a practitioner or an authorized agent under a practitioner’s supervision.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(1)(A) (West 2023). The definition of “practitioner” in Texas law expressly excludes “a person licensed under this subtitle [Subtitle J].” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(34)(A) (West 2023).\nSubtitle J covers pharmacy and pharmacists. This provision could mean that a pharmacist must be under a practitioner’s supervision to administer a drug or medication, unless Texas law or regulation provides express authorization.\nBased on the above points, Texas law would be unclear about a pharmacist administering buprenorphine generally.\nThe deciding factor is that Texas law expressly provides that the Texas Board of Pharmacy (Board) “shall specify conditions under which a pharmacist may administer medication, including an immunization and vaccination.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 554.004(a) (West 2023). The Board instituted conditions “must ensure that: (1) a licensed health care provider authorized to administer the medication is not reasonably available to administer the medication.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 554.004(a)(1) (West 2023). This appears to mean that a pharmacist cannot administer medications absent express Board authorization to do so as the pharmacist would not be a health care provider authorized to administer the medication.\nThe only regulations promulgated by the Board that pertain to pharmacist administration relate to epinephrine, immunizations, and vaccinations.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Texas practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of “practice of pharmacy” in Texas law does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 551.003(33) (West 2023).\nMoreover, within Texas pharmacy laws and regulations, the only express reference to ordering or evaluating lab tests is in the regulation governing drug therapy management (DTM) under a physician’s written protocol. 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(b)(4)(C) (2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Texas practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": null, "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Texas laws and/or regulations governing DTM to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Texas laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under DTM protocols.\nAllow Texas pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Texas laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nTexas pharmacy law grants a physician the ability to delegate to “any qualified and properly trained person acting under the physician’s supervision” the act of “administering or providing dangerous drugs.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 563.051(b) (West 2023). However, under Texas law, a “dangerous drug” is a prescription drug that is not a controlled substance. TEX. HEALTH & SAFETY CODE ANN. § 483.001(2) (West 2023). As a result, this provision does not grant physicians the ability to delegate the administration of controlled substances to pharmacists. Nevertheless, Texas medical practice law authorizes a physician to delegate to a pharmacist “the performance of specific acts of [DTM]” authorized by the physician through an order or protocol. TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 157.101(b) (West 2023).\nTexas regulation provides that DTM may include “implementing or modifying drug therapy” 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(b)(4)(D) (2024). Although this provision contains the phrase “implementing or modifying,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nBut, the same Texas regulation also provides that DTM may include “any other drug therapy related act delegated by a physician.” 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(b)(4)(E) (2024). As a result, to the extent that administering a controlled drug is not covered by “implementing or modifying,” it may be covered by this provision.\nThe Texas DTM regulation notes that it does not “limit, expand, or change any provision of law concerning or relating to . . . administration of medication, including [§ 554.004],” the specific section on pharmacist administration. 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(h)(2). As described in the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, § 554.004 may prevent a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine generally.\nHowever, § 554.004 expressly provides that it “does not prohibit a pharmacist from performing an act delegated by a physician in accordance with Chapter 157.” Such acts are “considered to be performing a medical act and not to be engaging in the practice of pharmacy.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 554.004(c) (West 2023). The fact that performing acts delegated by a physician may be considered “medical acts,” and not the practice of pharmacy, may mean that a physician can delegate the act of administering controlled substances to a pharmacist.", "5B": "Enter into a written protocol for DTM (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Texas laws and/or regulations that the DTM activities a physician may delegate to a pharmacist by protocol include administering controlled substances, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nTexas law authorizes a physician to delegate to a pharmacist “the performance of specific acts of drug therapy management [DTM]” authorized by the physician through an order or protocol. TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 157.101(b) (West 2023).\nTexas regulation provides that DTM may include “ordering drug therapy related laboratory tests.” 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(b)(4)(C) (2024).\nAlthough the same Texas regulation also provides that DTM may include “any other drug therapy related act delegated by a physician,” the fact that the specific provision related to laboratory tests mentions only ordering tests, and not evaluating tests, suggests that this is an intentional omission by regulators.", "6B": "Enter into a written protocol for DTM (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Texas laws and/or regulations that the DTM activities a physician may delegate to a pharmacist by protocol include evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "DTM is “the performance of specific acts by pharmacists as authorized by a physician through written protocol.” 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(b)(4) (2024).\nA “written protocol” is “a physician’s order, standing medical order, standing delegation order, or other order or protocol as defined by rule of the Texas Medical Board under the Medical Practice Act.” 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13(b)(6) (2024).\nThe following Texas laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering protocols for DTM and required elements of such protocols – TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. §§ 157.101, 554.004(c), 563.051 (West 2023);\n22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 295.13 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nTexas general telehealth/telemedicine practice law provides that a “health professional” may provide “telehealth services in accordance with Chapter 111 [general telehealth law] and any requirements imposed by the law and rules governing practice by the health professional.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 51.501(b) (West 2023).\nA “health professional” is anyone “who holds a license issued by the department under Title 3 [the statutory title relating to the licensing of health professionals].” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 51.501(a)(1) (West 2023). This includes pharmacists.\nNote that Texas law defines telehealth separately from telemedicine. A “telehealth service” is a “health service, other than a telemedicine medical service or a teledentistry dental service, delivered by a health professional licensed, certified, or otherwise entitled to practice” in Texas. TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 111.001(3) (West 2023).\n“Telemedicine medical service” means a “health care service delivered by a physician licensed in this state, or a health professional acting under the delegation and supervision of a physician licensed in this state.” TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 111.001(4) (West 2023). This means that telemedicine involves a physician either providing the service or supervising the service.\nTexas pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "Texas laws and regulations governing telehealth include – TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 51.501 (West 2023) (health profession practice); TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. §§ 111.001 to 111.009 (West 2023) (telehealth generally – other than mental health); TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. §§ 113.001 to 113.002 (West 2023) (mental health); TEX. GOVT. CODE ANN. §§ 531.0216 to 531.02174, 531.02253 (West 2023) (Medicaid); TEX. GOVT. CODE ANN. §§ 548.0001 to 548.0401 (Medicaid) (effective April 1, 2025); TEX. INS. CODE ANN. §§ 1455.001 to 1455.006 (West 2023) (insurance); TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 153.004 (West 2023) (physicians); TEX. OCC. CODE ANN. § 562.110 (West 2023) (telepharmacy); 1 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 354.1432 (2024) (Medicaid); 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE §§ 174.1 to 174.12 (2024) (physicians); 22 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 291.121 (2024)\n(telepharmacy).", "9A": "Texas insurance law “authorizes pharmacists to be selected as providers for health plan policies issued or renewed after January 1, 2020.” See also TEX. INS. CODE ANN. § 1451.001(13-a) (West 2023).\nIn addition, Texas insurance law provides that “an insurer or other health benefit plan issuer or a third-party administrator or pharmacy benefit manager of a health benefit plan may not deny reimbursement to a pharmacist for the provision of a service or procedure within the scope of the pharmacist’s license to practice pharmacy . . . that . .\n. would be covered . . . if the service or procedure were provided by: (A) a physician; (B) an advanced practice nurse; or (C) a physician assistant.” TEX. INS. CODE ANN. § 1451.1261(d) (West 2023).\nHowever, the provision above only applies to certain types of insurance policies and expressly does not apply to the Texas Medicaid program. TEX. INS. CODE ANN. § 1451.1261(b) (West 2023).273", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Texas Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Texas laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a protocol for DTM are covered under the Texas Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "Texas law provides information on Medicaid reimbursement provisions for “medication-assisted treatment.” TEX. HUM. RES. CODE ANN. § 32.03115 (West 2023); 1 TEX. ADMIN. CODE § 354.1311 (2024).", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PMP Portal", "url": "https://texas.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Texas Prescription Monitoring Program (PMP) AWARxE login portal for prescribers and pharmacists to query controlled substance dispensing records."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Program Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/pmp/", "description": "Texas State Board of Pharmacy PMP homepage. The Texas PMP collects and monitors data for all Schedule II-V controlled substances dispensed by Texas pharmacies or to Texas residents. Since March 1, 2020, pharmacists and prescribers are required to check PMP history before dispensing or prescribing opioids, benzodiazepines, barbiturates, or carisoprodol."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP AWARxE Registration", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/PMP/aware.asp", "description": "Information and login instructions for provider access to the patient controlled substance history database through AWARxE."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP About Page", "url": "https://txpmp.org/about", "description": "Texas PMP informational website. As the only statewide electronic database storing all controlled substance information, the Texas PMP helps avoid life-threatening drug interactions and supports referrals to treatment."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: The Texas PMP shares prescription data with 30 other states and entities through PMP InterConnect, allowing prescribers and pharmacists to track prescriptions dispensed outside Texas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Resources and Links", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/pmp/PMPResources.asp", "description": "PMP resources page with training materials, reporting guidelines, and links to PMP Clearinghouse for dispensers."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the PMP AWARxE system. Prescribers and pharmacists can designate authorized delegates to query the PMP on their behalf."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Texas State Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/", "description": "Texas State Board of Pharmacy (TSBP) homepage. Responsible for licensing pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, and pharmacies, establishing regulations, and disciplinary actions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/Rules_Pharmacy_Act.asp", "description": "Texas Pharmacy Act (Occupations Code Chapters 551-569). Full text available as HTML or PDF for each chapter, including general provisions, board powers, licensing, and practice standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Rules", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/Rules_Pharmacy_Rules.asp", "description": "Texas Pharmacy Rules page with the Board's administrative rules governing pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Links to Rules and Laws", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/rules/Links_Rules.asp", "description": "Comprehensive links to the Texas Pharmacy Act, Texas Controlled Substances Act (Health and Safety Code Chapter 481), Dangerous Drug Act, Food Drug and Cosmetic Act, DEA Pharmacist Manual, and HIPAA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/page/collaborativepractice", "description": "Texas Pharmacy Association page on collaborative practice. Texas pharmacists can enter into protocol-based agreements with physicians for drug therapy management under specific conditions."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Texas does not have broad independent pharmacist prescribing authority. Pharmacists can provide drug therapy management under physician-delegated protocols. Texas law allows pharmacists to dispense naloxone under standing orders and administer immunizations."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Texas, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory for finding buprenorphine practitioners in Texas."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Laurie DeLong, P.O. Box 149347 Mail Code 1979, Austin, TX 78714-9347. Phone: (512) 834-6700 x2146. Email: laurie.delong@dshs.state.tx.us", "description": "Texas's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Targeted Opioid Response", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/services/mental-health-substance-use/adult-substance-use/texas-targeted-opioid-response", "description": "HHSC's Texas Targeted Opioid Response (TTOR) program, established May 2017 with SAMHSA funding. Mission to save lives by expanding access to prevention, treatment, and recovery support services for opioid and stimulant use disorders."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Opioid Response Website", "url": "https://txopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Public-facing Texas opioid response website with resources on opioid and fentanyl education, naloxone access, prevention, treatment, and recovery."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), providers no longer need an X-waiver. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of SUD training for DEA registration. Texas does not impose additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law for buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing. Texas follows federal DEA telehealth regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Texas Medicaid Vendor Drug Program", "url": "https://www.txvendordrug.com/", "description": "Texas Medicaid Vendor Drug Program homepage. HHSC manages pharmacy benefits for Medicaid, CHIP, and other programs. Includes formulary information, preferred drug list, and prior authorization tools."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.txvendordrug.com/formulary/preferred-drugs", "description": "Texas Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) page. Drugs are recommended by the Texas Drug Utilization Review Board for efficaciousness, clinical significance, cost-effectiveness, and safety."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Current PDL Document", "url": "https://www.txvendordrug.com/sites/default/files/docs/2025-0728-preferred-drug-list.pdf", "description": "Current Texas Medicaid PDL with clinical prior authorization criteria linked for applicable drugs. Updated quarterly following DUR Board meetings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Formulary and Drug Code Index", "url": "https://www.txvendordrug.com/formulary", "description": "Texas Drug Code Index with program-specific formularies for Medicaid, CHIP, CSHCN, Healthy Texas Women, and Kidney Health Care programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Grant and Funding Opportunities", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/services/mental-health-substance-use/adult-substance-use/texas-targeted-opioid-response", "description": "The Texas Targeted Opioid Response (TTOR) program distributes SAMHSA State Opioid Response grant funding for prevention, treatment, and recovery support services. Contact HHSC for current grant opportunities."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Texas Opioid Abatement Fund: Texas receives opioid settlement funds distributed to state and local governments. Contact HHSC or the Texas Attorney General's office for information on fund allocation."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/licensees/ce-pharmacist-faq.asp", "description": "Texas pharmacist CE FAQ page. Pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE per biennial renewal. Minimum 2 hours of prescribing and monitoring controlled substances CE required (within first year of licensure and each renewal). One hour must be Texas-specific pharmacy law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Controlled Substance CE", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/licensees/ce-prescribing-monitoring-cs.asp", "description": "TSBP page on prescribing and monitoring controlled substances CE requirements. Any ACPE or AMA PRA Category 1 course focused on prescribing and monitoring controlled substances qualifies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CE Breakdown Document", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/files_pdf/pharmacist_ce_breakdown.pdf", "description": "Detailed CE requirements breakdown including reference to SAMHSA PCSS free opioid use disorder training for pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/", "description": "TPA homepage with free monthly member CE, Conference and Expo, online CE, and pharmacist CE requirement information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division for registration information. Under the MATE Act, DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of SUD training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System (PCSS-MOUD) free training on evidence-based OUD treatment including buprenorphine prescribing."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://txoti.org/naloxone-standing-order-request", "description": "Texas Overdose Treatment Initiative (TxOTI) naloxone standing order request page. Pharmacies and organizations in Texas can access a standing order to distribute naloxone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TPA Naloxone Standing Order", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/page/TXPHARMNALOX", "description": "Texas Pharmacy Association naloxone standing order application for pharmacists. Pharmacists can dispense naloxone under standing orders from authorizing prescribers after completing a one-hour training."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Texas does not have a statewide syringe services program law. Bexar County has a pilot program authorized by the legislature for needle exchange. Advocacy groups including Texas Criminal Justice Coalition are pushing for expanded SSP access."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: As of the most recent information, fentanyl test strips remain classified as drug paraphernalia in Texas. Multiple bills have been filed in the Texas Legislature to legalize them, but none have passed as of the 2023 session. Check the current legislative session for updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/drug-related-deaths", "description": "Texas Health Data dashboard for drug-related deaths with state and county-level data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution Map", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/naloxone-distribution-interactive-map", "description": "Texas DSHS interactive map of naloxone distribution across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Overdose Data to Action", "url": "https://www.dshs.texas.gov/injury-prevention/texas-overdose-data-action", "description": "DSHS Texas Overdose Data to Action (TODA) program expanding overdose tracking and prevention efforts to reduce fatal and nonfatal drug poisonings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Trends Dashboard", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/fentanyl-trends", "description": "Texas Health Data fentanyl trends dashboard with surveillance data on fentanyl-related incidents."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Support Services", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/services/mental-health-substance-use/adult-substance-use/recovery-support-services", "description": "HHSC recovery support services page. Evidence-based services funded through SAMHSA, provided by peer specialists who help with counseling, sober housing, transportation, and medications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Support Services", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/providers/behavioral-health-services-providers-programs/peer-support-services", "description": "HHSC peer support services page with information on becoming a peer specialist and the PeerForce workforce support hub."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PeerForce Texas", "url": "https://peerforce.org/", "description": "Texas peer specialist workforce support hub. Provides information on Recovery Support Peer Specialist (RSPS) certification through the Texas Certification Board."}, {"type": "link", "title": "HHSC Substance Use Disorder Services", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/providers/behavioral-health-services-providers-programs/substance-use-disorder-services", "description": "HHSC SUD services overview including peer support, case management, therapy, employment assistance, recovery housing, and community navigation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Mental Health and Substance Use", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/services/mental-health-substance-use", "description": "HHSC Mental Health and Substance Use services homepage for families and individuals."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Call 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Texas HHSC helpline resources available at hhs.texas.gov. For immediate medical emergencies, call 911."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Board of Pharmacy Executive Director: Daniel \"Danny\" Carroll, Pharm.D., R.Ph., Executive Director/Secretary, Texas State Board of Pharmacy, 1801 Congress Avenue, Suite 13100, Austin, TX 78701. Email: daniel.carroll@pharmacy.texas.gov. Phone: (512) 305-8000."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Staff", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/staff/", "description": "TSBP staff directory."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://www.pharmacy.texas.gov/consumer/broch9.asp", "description": "General Board of Pharmacy information including governance structure and consumer complaint process."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Laurie DeLong, P.O. Box 149347 Mail Code 1979, Austin, TX 78714-9347. Phone: (512) 834-6700 x2146. Email: laurie.delong@dshs.state.tx.us", "description": "Texas SOTA contact for opioid treatment program oversight."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/", "description": "TPA is the organization representing all Texas pharmacy professionals, providing advocacy, CE, and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TPA Leadership", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/page/MeetOurLeaders", "description": "TPA leadership and executive team contact information."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug-Related Deaths Dashboard", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/drug-related-deaths", "description": "Texas DSHS Health Data dashboard on drug-related deaths with state and county-level data and trend analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Trends", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/fentanyl-trends", "description": "Texas fentanyl trends dashboard with surveillance data on fentanyl-related incidents and deaths."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Non-Fatal Drug Poisoning Data", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/non-fatal-drug-poisoning-hopsital-data", "description": "Texas DSHS dashboard for non-fatal drug poisoning hospital data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Overdose Data to Action", "url": "https://www.dshs.texas.gov/injury-prevention/texas-overdose-data-action", "description": "Federal/state partnership (TODA) to expand overdose surveillance and prevention. Includes TODA reporting documents and program information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Distribution Interactive Map", "url": "https://healthdata.dshs.texas.gov/dashboard/drugs-and-alcohol/all-drugs/naloxone-distribution-interactive-map", "description": "Interactive map showing naloxone distribution across Texas counties."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas PMP Data", "url": "https://txpmp.org/", "description": "Texas PMP website with prescription monitoring data and resources for researchers and practitioners."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Texas Legislature Online", "url": "https://capitol.texas.gov/", "description": "Texas Legislature Online portal for tracking bills, finding legislators, and accessing legislative resources. Enter your address to find who represents you."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Who Represents Me", "url": "https://lrl.texas.gov/genInfo/contactleg.cfm", "description": "Texas Legislative Reference Library tool for contacting your state legislators and finding district information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TPA Advocacy", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/", "description": "Texas Pharmacy Association provides advocacy resources, lobbying, and Political Action Committee support. TPA represents all Texas pharmacy professionals on legislative issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "TPA Collaborative Practice", "url": "https://www.texaspharmacy.org/page/collaborativepractice", "description": "TPA resources on collaborative practice for pharmacists in Texas."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Targeted Opioid Response", "url": "https://www.hhs.texas.gov/services/mental-health-substance-use/adult-substance-use/texas-targeted-opioid-response", "description": "HHSC's TTOR is Texas's primary state-level initiative addressing the opioid crisis through prevention, treatment, and recovery support. Serves as a statewide OUD coalition effort."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Texas Opioid Response", "url": "https://txopioidresponse.org/", "description": "Public-facing Texas opioid response initiative with resources, community leader toolkits, and information on fentanyl awareness."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA and National Advocacy Resources: For national model legislation and policy templates relevant to pharmacist prescribing and OUD treatment, visit the National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA) at https://naspa.us/ and ASHP at https://www.ashp.org/advocacy."}]}]}, "utah": {"name": "Utah", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Utah’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(17) (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Utah law expressly includes “issuing a prescription in accordance with Section 58-17b-627 [“prescription of drugs or devices by a pharmacist].” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(o) (West 2024).\nHowever, the referenced Utah law prohibits a pharmacist from prescribing a schedule I-IV controlled substance. UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-627(1)(c) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Utah cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances outside of a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement (CPPA). Note, however, that DEA indicates that a Utah pharmacist can obtain a mid-level practitioner registration to “Prescribe Only Pursuant to Collaborative Practice Agreement with Practitioner.” As described in the answer to the \"prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, it is unclear upon what information DEA bases this conclusion, and it may not, in fact, be accurate.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Utah practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow all Utah pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, it only applies to certain forms of buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Utah law includes “administering . . . prescription drugs or devices” but only if certain conditions are met, which differ depending on if the drug is administered on an “inpatient basis” or an “outpatient basis.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(c) (West 2024).\nFor drugs administered on an outpatient basis, the two conditions are that the administration is: (1) pursuant to a lawful order of a practitioner; and (2) performed in accordance with written guidelines or protocols “approved by the division, in collaboration with the board and, when appropriate, the Medical Licensing Board.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(c)(ii)(B) (West 2024). The second condition appears to require a Utah law/regulation/protocol expressly covering a drug or medication’s administration before a pharmacist can administer it.\nIn addition to vaccines and overdose reversal agents, Utah law expressly provides that pharmacists can administer “long-acting injectables intramuscularly.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-625(2) (West 2024). Utah law and regulation does not expressly authorize pharmacist administration of any other drugs or medications.\nThe pharmacist must administer the long-acting injectable “at a clinic or community pharmacy.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-625(3)(b) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain a prescription or other lawful order from a physician.\nAdhere to the educational, training, and other requirements specified in Utah law and regulations. UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-625 (West 2024); UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 156-17b-621, 156-17b-621a (2024).", "2C": "Expand the Utah practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment and not just injectable forms.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Utah law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(c) (West 2024).\nThe only express mention of ordering or evaluating lab tests in Utah pharmacy laws and regulations is in the regulation governing drug therapy management (DTM)/ CPPAs, as described in the response to the \"ordering and evaluating laboratory tests under a CPA\" section.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Utah practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "As described in the information below, Utah laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Utah law includes “collaborative pharmacy practice in accordance with a collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(b) (West 2024).\n“Collaborative pharmacy practice” involves a pharmacist performing “certain pharmaceutical care functions authorized by the practitioner or practitioners.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(16) (West 2024).\n“Pharmaceutical care” means carrying out certain activities “in collaboration with a prescribing practitioner.” Those activities include “designing, implementing, and monitoring a therapeutic drug plan.” However, pharmaceutical care “does not include prescribing of drugs without consent of a prescribing practitioner.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(45) (West 2024). Although not completely clear, this last provision may mean that a pharmacist can prescribe drugs under a CPPA, but only to the extent the collaborating practitioner approves. A CPPA is an agreement that provides for “collaborative pharmacy practice for the purpose of drug therapy management” (DTM). UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(17) (West 2024).\nDTM includes “implementing, modifying and managing drug therapy” under a CPPA. UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 156-17b-611(1)(a) (2024). Although this Utah regulation governing DTM and CPPAs uses the word “implementing,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing any kind of drugs.\nAs described in the answer to the \"independent prescribing of buprenorphine\" section, a Utah’s pharmacist’s general authority to prescribe drugs outside of a CPPA expressly does not extend to schedule I-IV controlled substances.\nDEA’s most recent information (December 2022) about its mid-level practitioner registration indicates that a Utah pharmacist is eligible for that registration, but only to prescribe only pursuant to a CPPA.278 DEA does not provide the basis for this conclusion.\nIn summary, one of two conclusions is possible. One conclusion is that DEA is accurate that a Utah pharmacist can prescribe controlled substances under a CPPA, even though Utah pharmacy law expressly prohibits such prescribing outside a CPPA and the laws and regulations governing CPPAs for DTM are completely silent about pharmacists prescribing controlled substances and obtaining a state/DEA controlled substance registration for this purpose. The other conclusion is that Utah pharmacists cannot prescribe controlled substances under a CPPA, although they likely can prescribe non-controlled substances given a pharmacist’s general authority to do so and the fact that “pharmaceutical care” may include prescribing with practitioner consent.", "4B": "Enter into a CPPA agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": "Revise Utah laws and/or regulations governing CPPAs for DTM to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Utah laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPPAs for DTM.\nAllow Utah pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances for all purposes.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Utah laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” at least to the same extent.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Utah law includes “collaborative pharmacy practice in accordance with a [CPPA].” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(b) (West 2024).\n“Collaborative pharmacy practice” involves a pharmacist performing “certain pharmaceutical care functions authorized by the practitioner or practitioners.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(16) (West 2024).\n“Pharmaceutical care” means carrying out certain activities “in collaboration with a prescribing practitioner.” Those activities include “designing, implementing, and monitoring a therapeutic drug plan.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(45) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the word “implementing,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications.\nA CPPA is an agreement that provides for “collaborative pharmacy practice for the purpose of [DTM].” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(17) (West 2024).\nDTM includes “implementing, modifying and managing drug therapy” under a CPPA. UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 156-17b-611(1)(a) (2024). Although this provision governing DTM and CPPAs uses the term “implementing,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications. In summary, Utah laws and regulations are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can administer drugs and medications under a CPPA for DTM. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer long-acting injectable medications outside of CPPA, the logical answer to this question is “yes,” at least to the same extent as described in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section.", "5B": "Enter into a CPPA agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly provide in Utah laws and/or regulations that “implementing, modifying and managing drug therapy” includes administering drugs, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Utah law includes “collaborative pharmacy practice in accordance with a [CPPA].” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(58)(b) (West 2024).\nA CPPA is an agreement that provides for “collaborative pharmacy practice for the purpose of [DTM].” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(17) (West 2024).\nDTM expressly includes “ordering and evaluating the results of laboratory tests directly applicable to the drug therapy, when performed in accordance with approved protocols applicable to the practice setting.” UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 156-17b-611(1)(d) (2024).", "6B": "Enter into a CPPA agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": null, "7": "A CPPA is a written and signed agreement between “one or more pharmacists and one or more practitioners.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(17) (West 2024).\n“Practitioner” means “an individual currently licensed, registered, or otherwise authorized by the appropriate jurisdiction to prescribe and administer drugs in the course of professional practice.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102(61) (West 2024).\nThe following Utah laws and regulations provides more information on requirements for entering CPPAs for DTM and required elements of CPPAs – UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-102 (West 2024); UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 156-17b-611 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nUtah’s general telehealth/telemedicine law authorizes a “provider” to provide both “telehealth services” and “telemedicine services” within the scope of the provider’s license. UTAH CODE ANN. § 26B-4-704 (West 2024).\n“Provider” includes an individual “licensed under Title 58, Occupations and Professions, to provide health care.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 26B-4-704(1)(f) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.\nUtah pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "A provider offering telemedicine services may not “prescribe a prescription drug based solely on one of the following: (a) an online questionnaire; (b) an email message; or (c) a patient-generated medical history.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 26B-4-704(4) (West 2024).\nUtah laws and regulations governing telehealth include – UTAH CODE ANN. § 26B-4-704 (West 2024) (scope of telehealth practice); UTAH CODE ANN. §§ 26B-3-122 to 26B-3-123 (West 2024) (Medicaid); UTAH CODE ANN. §§ 31A-22-649.5, 49-20-414 (West 2024) (insurance); UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-1-302.1 (West 2024) (temporary license for telemedicine); UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-17b-612 (West 2024) (telepharmacy); UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 156-1-602 (2024) (telehealth generally); UTAH ADMIN. CODE r.\n156-17b-102, 156-17b-610, 156-17b-614a, 156-17b-614g (2024) (telepharmacy); UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 414-42-1 to 414-42-5 (Medicaid).", "9A": "Medicaid members “may receive face-to-face and telephonic Medication Therapy Management (MTM) services provided by a Medicaid enrolled pharmacist in an outpatient setting.”", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Utah Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Utah laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a CPPA for DTM are covered under the Utah Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Utah law still contains a provision allowing a controlled substance prescriber with the now-eliminated Drug Addiction Treatment Act of 2000 (DATA) waiver to use the existence of the prescriber’s waiver “to satisfy the 3.5 hours of the continuing education requirement under Subsection (3) for two consecutive licensing periods.” UTAH CODE ANN. § 58-37-6.5(10) (West 2024).\nUtah regulations governing “outpatient treatment programs” in particular how those programs provide MOUD, could potentially be applicable to pharmacist provision of buprenorphine. UTAH ADMIN. CODE r. 501-21-1 to 501-21-7 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "CSD Portal", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/controlled-substance-database/", "description": "Utah's Prescription Drug Monitoring Program (PDMP) is known as the Controlled Substance Database (CSD), managed by the Division of Professional Licensing (DOPL) within the Department of Commerce. Created July 1, 1995, the CSD collects data on all Schedule II-V prescriptions dispensed by retail, institutional, and outpatient hospital pharmacies, and mail-order pharmacies. URL redirects to commerce.utah.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSD Account Creation Guide", "url": "https://commerce.utah.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/create-a-csd-account.pdf", "description": "Step-by-step guide for prescribers and pharmacists to create a CSD account for accessing controlled substance dispensing data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "How to Run a CSD Report", "url": "https://commerce.utah.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/how-to-run-a-csd-report.pdf", "description": "Guide for running patient reports in the CSD system."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSD Data Submission", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/controlled-substance-database/submit-data/", "description": "Portal and instructions for dispensers to submit data to the Controlled Substance Database."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing: Utah participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing. The CSD integrates with EHR systems through Bamboo Health's PMP Gateway platform."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Utah practitioners are required to check the CSD before prescribing certain controlled substances. All pharmacies must report dispensing data for Schedule II-V controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DOPL Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/pharmacy/", "description": "Utah Division of Professional Licensing (DOPL) pharmacy page within the Department of Commerce. Provides licensing information, board details, and resources. URL redirects to commerce.utah.gov/dopl/pharmacy/. Includes notice regarding elimination of DATA-Waiver program for buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Board", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/pharmacy/board/", "description": "Utah Board of Pharmacy page with board member information and meeting details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Laws and Rules", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/pharmacy/laws-and-rules/", "description": "Comprehensive listing of Utah pharmacy laws and rules, including the DOPL Licensing Act (58-1), General Rule (R156-1), Pharmacy Practice Act (58-17b), and Pharmacy Practice Act Rule (R156-17b)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/pharmacy/contact-us/", "description": "Contact information for DOPL pharmacy staff. Jim Garfield is listed as contact. Email: dopl@utah.gov. DOPL Phone: (801) 530-6628."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Pharmacy Association Laws Page", "url": "https://www.upha.com/page/200", "description": "UPhA page linking to DOPL pharmacy laws and rules for comprehensive information about practicing pharmacy in Utah."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice and Pharmacist Prescribing: Utah allows collaborative practice arrangements. The Pharmacy Practice Act (58-17b) and associated rules govern pharmacist scope of practice. Utah has expanded pharmacist authority including immunization administration and naloxone dispensing under standing orders. Pharmacists can also prescribe certain medications under protocol agreements."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Utah, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory for finding buprenorphine practitioners in Utah."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: VaRonica Little, Utah State Division of Substance Abuse and Mental Health, 195 N. 1950 W., Salt Lake City, UT 84116. Phone: (801) 450-0992. Email: vlittle@utah.gov", "description": "Utah's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA SOTA Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA's full directory of State Opioid Treatment Authorities by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stop the Opidemic Provider Resources", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/providers/", "description": "Utah DHHS Stop the Opidemic page for healthcare providers, including Utah Clinical Guidelines on Prescribing Opioids for Treatment of Pain developed by a multidisciplinary consensus panel."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), providers no longer need an X-waiver. DOPL has published a notice on the elimination of the DATA-Waiver program. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of SUD training for DEA registration. Utah does not impose additional state requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth for Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/statutes-regulations-guidelines/buprenorphine-telemedicine-prescribing", "description": "SAMHSA guidance on buprenorphine telemedicine prescribing. Utah follows federal DEA telehealth regulations."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Utah Medicaid Pharmacy Program", "url": "https://medicaid.utah.gov/pharmacy-program/", "description": "Utah Medicaid pharmacy program homepage with links to the preferred drug list, prior authorization, formulary, and provider manuals. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://medicaid.utah.gov/pharmacy-program/preferred-drug-list/", "description": "Utah Medicaid PDL page. The state belongs to the Sovereign States Drug Consortium (SSDC). Non-preferred drugs require prior authorization per SB 87 (2009). Buprenorphine products require clinical PA forms."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prior Authorization", "url": "https://medicaid.utah.gov/pharmacy-program/prior-authorization/", "description": "Utah Medicaid pharmacy prior authorization page with all PA forms needed to request drugs requiring authorization, including specific Buprenorphine Products PA Form."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Provider Manual", "url": "https://medicaid-documents.dhhs.utah.gov/Documents/manuals/pdfs/Medicaid%20Provider%20Manuals/Pharmacy/Pharmacy.pdf", "description": "Utah Medicaid Pharmacy Services Provider Manual with comprehensive billing guidance, fee schedules, and coverage policies."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Grant and Funding Opportunities: Utah DHHS distributes SAMHSA State Opioid Response grant funding and opioid settlement funds for prevention, treatment, and recovery programs. Contact the Division of Substance Use and Mental Health at sumh.utah.gov for current grant opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "CE Requirements: Utah pharmacists must complete at least 30 hours of continuing education per biennial renewal. Controlled substance prescribers are required to complete at least 3.5 hours of CE in SBIRT training (one-time requirement) which satisfies ongoing controlled substance prescriber CE obligations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "USHP CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.ushp.org/utah-ce-requirements", "description": "Utah Society of Health-System Pharmacists page summarizing Utah pharmacist CE requirements."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.upha.com/", "description": "Utah Pharmacy Association (UPhA) homepage. Provides CE resources, advocacy, and professional development for Utah pharmacy professionals. Located at 7414 S. State Street, Midvale, UT 84047. Phone: 801-438-2524."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division for registration and controlled substance regulations. Under the MATE Act, DEA registrants must complete 8 hours of SUD training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System (PCSS-MOUD) free training for healthcare providers on evidence-based OUD treatment including buprenorphine prescribing."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://vipp.utah.gov/services/syringe-services-programs/", "description": "Utah DHHS Violence and Injury Prevention Program syringe services programs page. Utah legalized syringe exchange in 2016 and has 14 SSPs operating statewide. Services include SUD treatment linkage, HIV/HCV testing, sterile syringes, drug-checking materials (fentanyl test strips), and sharps containers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Syringe Exchange Network", "url": "https://sites.google.com/utah.gov/usen/home", "description": "Utah Syringe Exchange Network information page connecting SSP partners across the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Salt Lake Harm Reduction Project", "url": "https://www.shrpexchange.org/", "description": "Syringe exchange program in Salt Lake City offering free services including sterile injection equipment, HIV/HCV testing, naloxone, and linkage to care. Serves Davis, Salt Lake, Utah, and surrounding counties."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/naloxone/", "description": "Utah Stop the Opidemic naloxone page. Utah has a standing order (since December 8, 2016) allowing anyone to purchase naloxone at a pharmacy without a prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Support and Standing Order", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/naloxone/naloxone-support/", "description": "Additional naloxone support information, including details on the statewide standing order and access points."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Naloxone", "url": "https://www.utahnaloxone.org/", "description": "Utah Naloxone organization run by prescribers and pharmacists. Provides naloxone education, fentanyl test strip information, and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/fentanyl-test-strips/fentanyl-test-strips-distribution/", "description": "Utah DHHS fentanyl test strip distribution page. Utah passed SB 86 in 2023 exempting fentanyl test strips from drug paraphernalia laws. FTS are distributed through SSPs, local health departments, and community organizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://dhhs.utah.gov/health-dashboards/opioid-data/", "description": "Utah Public Opioid Dashboard (UPOD) with interactive data on opioid-related indicators including overdose deaths, prescribing rates, and county-level data. Updated annually by DHHS."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Certified Peer Support Specialists", "url": "https://sumh.utah.gov/education/certification/peersupportspecialists/", "description": "Utah DHHS Substance Use and Mental Health page on Certified Peer Support Specialist (CPSS) program. CPSSs use lived experience in recovery to deliver services promoting recovery and resiliency."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Division of Substance Use and Mental Health", "url": "https://sumh.utah.gov/", "description": "Utah DHHS Division of Substance Use and Mental Health homepage. The state agency responsible for prevention and treatment services for substance use and mental health disorders statewide."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Utah Support Advocates for Recovery Awareness (USARA): USARA is Utah's primary recovery community organization providing peer support, recovery coaching, and advocacy. Contact: (385) 210-0320. Serves Carbon, Grand, Salt Lake, Washington, and Weber Counties."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stop the Opidemic", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/", "description": "Utah DHHS Stop the Opidemic campaign to raise awareness on opioid abuse/misuse and reduce stigma. Provides resources for individuals, families, and providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "211 Utah", "url": "https://211utah.org/", "description": "Utah 211 resource for finding community services including food, transportation, housing, health care, mental health, and substance use treatment."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Call 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Call 211 for community resources. Utah Crisis Line: 1-800-273-8255. For substance use treatment referrals, visit opidemic.utah.gov/resources."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Board of Pharmacy Contact: Utah Division of Professional Licensing (DOPL), Department of Commerce, 160 East 300 South, Salt Lake City, UT 84111. Phone: (801) 530-6628. Email: dopl@utah.gov. Contact: Jim Garfield (jimgarfield@utah.gov)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DOPL Pharmacy Contact Page", "url": "https://dopl.utah.gov/pharmacy/contact-us/", "description": "Contact information for DOPL pharmacy licensing staff."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Utah Medicaid Contact: Utah DHHS Medicaid program. Visit medicaid.utah.gov for pharmacy-related inquiries."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: VaRonica Little, Utah State Division of Substance Abuse and Mental Health, 195 N. 1950 W., Salt Lake City, UT 84116. Phone: (801) 450-0992. Email: vlittle@utah.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.upha.com/", "description": "UPhA homepage. Provides advocacy, CE, and professional resources for Utah pharmacy professionals. Phone: 801-438-2524."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHHS Contact", "url": "https://dhhs.utah.gov/contacts/", "description": "Utah Department of Health and Human Services contact page with links to divisions and programs."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Utah Public Opioid Dashboard", "url": "https://dhhs.utah.gov/health-dashboards/opioid-data/", "description": "UPOD interactive dashboard with five opioid summary indicators, six trend indicators, and county/small area maps. Provides the most current data for opioid-related indicators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "IBIS Health Indicator Report", "url": "https://ibis.utah.gov/ibisph-view/indicator/view/PoiDth.Opi.html", "description": "Utah IBIS public health indicator report on drug overdose and poisoning incidents, including opioid-specific data and trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Violence and Injury Prevention Substance Use Data", "url": "https://vipp.utah.gov/substance-use/", "description": "Utah DHHS Violence and Injury Prevention Program substance use page. Includes SUDORS data, academic detailing, naloxone and fentanyl test strip distribution tracking, and community partnership information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stop the Opidemic Resources", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/resources/", "description": "Utah Stop the Opidemic resources page with links to gabapentin reports, prescription opioid death data, and other surveillance publications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Healthcare Information and Analysis", "url": "https://healthcarestats.utah.gov/", "description": "Utah DHHS Healthcare Information and Analysis Programs with data on opioid prescriptions, ER overdose trends, and treatment utilization. Please verify this link before publishing."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Utah Legislature", "url": "https://le.utah.gov/", "description": "Utah Legislature homepage. Enter your home address to find your legislators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://le.utah.gov/GIS/findDistrict.jsp", "description": "Utah Legislature district map tool. Enter your street address and zip code to find your State Senator and House Representative."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah House of Representatives Contact", "url": "https://house.utleg.gov/contact/", "description": "Utah House of Representatives contact page. 350 North State, Suite 350, Salt Lake City, UT 84114. Phone: (801) 538-1029."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.upha.com/", "description": "UPhA provides advocacy, legislative engagement, and professional resources for Utah pharmacy professionals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Stop the Opidemic Initiative", "url": "https://opidemic.utah.gov/", "description": "Utah DHHS Stop the Opidemic campaign serves as the state's primary public-facing opioid prevention and awareness initiative. Works with communities, providers, and stakeholders to reduce opioid misuse and overdose."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Utah Substance Use and Mental Health", "url": "https://sumh.utah.gov/", "description": "DHHS Division of Substance Use and Mental Health, the state agency responsible for SUD prevention and treatment policy. Coordinates statewide OUD response efforts and distributes SAMHSA block grant and State Opioid Response funding."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NASPA and National Advocacy Resources: For national model legislation and policy templates relevant to pharmacist prescribing and OUD treatment, visit the National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations (NASPA) at https://naspa.us/ and ASHP at https://www.ashp.org/advocacy."}]}]}, "vermont": {"name": "Vermont", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Vermont law does not expressly provide for prescribing drugs. However, it does authorize “the practice of clinical pharmacy.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(15)(A)(vii) (West 2024).\nThe definition of the “practice of clinical pharmacy” in Vermont law includes “prescribing as provided under section 2023 of this subchapter [“clinical pharmacy; prescribing”].” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(15)(B)(iv) (West 2024).\nThe referenced Vermont law provides that as part of clinical pharmacy, a pharmacist “shall not . . . prescribe a regulated drug as defined in 18 V.S.A. § 4201.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(a)(1) (West 2024). Buprenorphine is a regulated drug in Vermont. 13-140-011 VT. CODE R.§ 6.0 (Lexis 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Vermont cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.282", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Vermont practice of pharmacy to include prescribing regulated drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Vermont pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe regulated drugs.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Vermont laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definitions of the “practice of pharmacy” and the “clinical practice of pharmacy” in Vermont law do not expressly refer to administering drugs. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(15) (West 2024). This suggests that a Vermont pharmacist does not have the general authority to administer drugs.\nHowever, the law covering clinical pharmacy prescribing provides that a “pharmacist may prescribe, order, or administer in a manner consistent with valid State protocols” certain drugs, medications, or devices. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(b)(2)(A) (West 2024).\nBuprenorphine is not one of the listed drugs/medications. Because this provision is in the context of pharmacist prescribing (and not the scope of practice in general), it is unclear if the legislature’s use of “or administer” intends to limit the types of drugs or devices a pharmacist can administer to only those specified in the law.\nThe only Vermont pharmacy regulation that expressly addresses administration relates to administration of immunizations. 04-030-230 VT. CODE R.§ 10.35 (Lexis 2024).\nIn contrast, the definition of “pharmacy, scope of practice” in Vermont regulation expressly provides that the scope of practice “embraces . . . immunizations [and] participation in . . . drug administration.” 04-030-230 VT. CODE R. § 1.10(40) (Lexis 2024). This provision does not limit the types of drugs that can be administered and suggests that “drug administration” encompasses more than immunizations. In contrast to Vermont law, this provision could mean that a pharmacist has the general authority to administer buprenorphine.", "2B": null, "2C": "Expand the Vermont practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not include the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definitions of the “practice of pharmacy” and the “clinical practice of pharmacy” in Vermont law do not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(15) (West 2024).\nHowever, the Vermont law covering clinical pharmacy prescribing provides that a pharmacist may “prescribe, order, or administer in a manner consistent with valid State protocols” certain tests. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(b)(2)(A) (West 2024). The identified tests are tests:\n(1) for COVID-19 for individuals by entities holding a CLIA waiver; and (2) for SARS-CoV for asymptomatic individuals or related serology for individuals by entities holding a CLIA waiver. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(b)(2)(A)(xi), (xii) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Vermont practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nUnder Vermont law, a CPPA is an agreement “that permits the pharmacist to engage in the practice of clinical pharmacy.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(20) (West 2024).\nAlthough the practice of clinical pharmacy includes some prescribing authority, as part of such practice a pharmacist “shall not . . . prescribe a regulated drug as defined in 18 V.S.A. § 4201.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(a)(1) (West 2024). Buprenorphine is a regulated drug in Vermont. 13-140-011 VT. CODE R.§ 6.0 (Lexis 2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Vermont laws and/or regulations governing CPAs and clinical pharmacy to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Vermont laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow Vermont pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances for all purposes.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Vermont laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nUnder Vermont law, a CPA is an agreement “that permits the pharmacist to engage in the practice of clinical pharmacy.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(20) (West 2024). The definition of the “clinical practice of pharmacy” does not expressly refer to administering drugs. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(15) (West 2024). The clinical practice of pharmacy definition also includes “practicing pharmacy pursuant to a CPA” which has the circular effect of defining a CPA as an agreement that allows the pharmacist to practice pursuant to a CPA.\nUnder Vermont regulation, “collaborative pharmacy practice” means “that portion of pharmacy practice where a pharmacist may perform certain patient care functions under a protocol of specified conditions or limitations in collaboration with a practitioner.” 04-030-230 VT. CODE R.§ 1.10(a)(8) (Lexis 2024). Vermont regulations do not define “patient care functions” but such functions could involve administering drugs and medications.\nHowever, the definitions for CPA and “collaborative pharmacy practice” note that it involves a pharmacist and “practitioner.” A “practitioner” means “an individual authorized . . . to prescribe and administer prescription drugs.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(16) (West 2024).\nThis could mean that a pharmacist cannot administer drugs under a CPA because a pharmacist is not the “practitioner.”\nThe only Vermont pharmacy regulation that expressly addresses administration relates to administration of immunizations. 04-030-230 VT. CODE R.§ 10.35 (Lexis 2024).", "5B": "Enter into a CPPA agreement (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Vermont laws and/or regulations that the “practice of clinical pharmacy” and “collaborative pharmacy practice” include pharmacists administering drugs, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Vermont laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nUnder Vermont law, a CPA is an agreement “that permits the pharmacist to engage in the practice of clinical pharmacy.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(20) (West 2024).\nThe definition of the “clinical practice of pharmacy” does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(15) (West 2024). The definition also indicates that the clinical practice of pharmacy includes “practicing pharmacy pursuant to a CPA” which has the circular effect of defining a CPA as an agreement that allows the pharmacist to practice pursuant to a CPA.\nVermont law covering clinical pharmacy prescribing provides that a pharmacist may “prescribe, order, or administer in a manner consistent with valid State protocols” certain tests. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(b)(2)(A) (West 2024). The identified tests are tests:\n(1) for COVID-19 for individuals by entities holding a CLIA waiver; and (2) for SARS-CoV for asymptomatic individuals or related serology for individuals by entities holding a CLIA waiver. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023(b)(2)(A)(xi), (xii) (West 2024). However, this provision relates to prescribing pursuant to a “state protocol” which is separate from prescribing pursuant to a CPA and thus may not be applicable. Under Vermont regulation “collaborative pharmacy practice” means “that portion of pharmacy practice where a pharmacist may perform certain patient care functions under a protocol of specified conditions or limitations in collaboration with a practitioner.” 04-030-230 VT. CODE R.§ 1.10(a)(8) (Lexis 2024). Vermont regulations do not define “patient care functions” but such functions could include ordering and evaluating the results of lab tests.\nIn summary, Vermont laws and regulations governing CPAs are unclear about what CPAs can authorize and do not clearly address whether a pharmacist can order or evaluate lab tests under a CPA. Given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that pharmacists have limited authority to order certain tests outside of CPA, the most logical answer is that a pharmacist has at least the same authority under one.", "6B": null, "6C": "Expressly specify in Vermont law and/or regulations that the “practice of clinical pharmacy” and “collaborative pharmacy practice” include ordering and evaluating the results of the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CPA is a written agreement between a pharmacist and “a health care facility or prescribing practitioner.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(20) (West 2024).\n“Practitioner” means “an individual authorized by [state, federal or Canadian laws] to prescribe and administer prescription drugs in the course of his or her professional practice and permitted by that authorization to dispense, conduct research with respect to, or administer drugs in the course of his or her professional practice or research in his or her respective state or province.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2022(16) (West 2024).\nThe following Vermont laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, § 2023 (West 2024); 04-030-230 VT. CODE R.§ 1.10(a)(8)\n(Lexis 2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nVermont’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice act provides that a “health care provider” licensed in Vermont may deliver health care services via telemedicine. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, § 9361 (West 2024).\n“Heath care provider” has the same definition as that used in Vermont insurance law. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, § 9361(a) (West 2024). It includes an individual “that is licensed, certified, or otherwise authorized by law to provide professional health care services, including dental services” in Vermont. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 8, § 4100k(i)(4) (West 2024). This includes pharmacists.\nVermont pharmacy laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "“Controlled substances for use in treatment of opioid use disorder may be prescribed via telehealth in accordance with federal requirements.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, § 4752(d) (West 2024).\nVermont laws and regulations governing telehealth include – VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, §§ 9361 to 9362 (West 2024)\n(telemedicine generally); VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, § 4752(d) (West 2024) (OUD prescribing); VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 8, §§ 4100k to 4100l (West 2024) (insurance); VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 26, §§ 3051 to 3071 (West 2024) (out of state telehealth licensure and compacts); 13-141-001 VT. CODE R.§ 23.0, 24.0 (2024) (telehealth license for physicians); 13-174-03 VT. CODE R § 3.101 (2024)\n(Medicaid); 04-030-230 VT. CODE R § 2.9, 2.10 (2024)\n(telepharmacy).", "9A": "Tobacco cessation, contraceptive prescribing and medication therapy management.283 See also VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 8, § 4099c (West 2024).\nWith respect to commercial insurers, Vermont law contains a voluntary provision that “notwithstanding any provision of a health insurance plan to the contrary, if a health insurance plan provides for payment or reimbursement that is within the lawful scope of practice of a pharmacist, the insurer may provide payment or reimbursement for the service when the service is provided by a pharmacist.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 8, § 4089j(c) (West 2024).284", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Vermont Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Vermont laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a CPA are covered under the Vermont Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Vermont law contains a chapter devoted to OUD. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, §§ 4750 to 4774 (West 2024). Within this chapter are laws “to authorize the Departments of Health and of Vermont Health Access to establish a regional system of opioid addiction treatment.” VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, § 4751 (West 2024). This includes provisions:\n(1) authorizing regulations related to pharmacological treatment, including initial assessments, ongoing follow-up, provider education, and diversion prevention; (2) allowing controlled substances to be prescribed via telehealth; (3) prohibiting the need to document an adverse reaction to a medication prior to prescribing an alternative;\n(4) authorizing care coordination; and (5) limiting prior authorization requirements. VT. STAT. ANN. tit. 18, §§ 4752 to 4754 (West 2024)\nVermont regulations include general requirements for office based opioid treatment (OBOT) providers, OBOT administration and operation requirements, and clinical care and management requirements for OBOT. 13-140-062 Vt. Code R. §§ 1.0 to 6.0 (2024). These requirements address, among other things, assessment and diagnosis, patient evaluation, treatment plans, ongoing treatment and monitoring, administrative discharge, and treating pregnant patients."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://vermont.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "The Vermont Prescription Monitoring System (VPMS) login portal, powered by PMP AWARxE (Bamboo Health). Pharmacists and prescribers use this system to query controlled substance dispensing data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "VPMS Program Information", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/stats/registries/vermont-prescription-monitoring-system-vpms", "description": "The Vermont Department of Health page with information about the VPMS program, including enrollment instructions, contact information, and data resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "VPMS Registration Guide", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/ADAP_VPMS_Registration_Guide.pdf", "description": "Step-by-step guide for registering as a new user in VPMS, including instructions for pharmacists and prescribers to create an account."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Vermont law requires enrollment in and use of VPMS for both prescribers and dispensers of controlled substances. Pharmacists who prescribe or dispense controlled substances must register with and query VPMS."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing / PMP InterConnect: Vermont participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing, allowing authorized users to access prescription data from other participating states through the VPMS platform."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Delegate Registration", "url": "https://vermont.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Delegate accounts can be set up through the PMP AWARxE system. After logging in, authorized users can add delegates following the instructions in the VPMS Registration Guide."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://sos.vermont.gov/pharmacy/", "description": "The Vermont Board of Pharmacy page within the Office of Professional Regulation, Vermont Secretary of State. Provides information on licensing, applications, renewals, and Board meetings."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Statutes)", "url": "https://legislature.vermont.gov/statutes/fullchapter/26/036", "description": "Full text of Vermont Title 26, Chapter 36 (Pharmacies and Pharmacists), the state Pharmacy Practice Act available through the Vermont Legislature website."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules", "url": "https://outside.vermont.gov/dept/sos/office_professional_regulation/professions/pharmacy/pharmacy_administrative_rules.pdf", "description": "The Administrative Rules of the Vermont Board of Pharmacy in PDF format, containing detailed regulations governing pharmacy practice in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Statutes, Rules and Resources Page", "url": "https://sos.vermont.gov/pharmacy/statutes-rules-resources/", "description": "The Board of Pharmacy page linking to all applicable statutes, administrative rules, and additional resources for pharmacy licensees."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute", "url": "https://legislature.vermont.gov/statutes/section/26/036/02023", "description": "Vermont statute 26 V.S.A. Section 2023, which authorizes pharmacists to engage in clinical pharmacy practice, including prescribing within the scope of a written collaborative practice agreement with a prescribing practitioner."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority", "url": "https://legislature.vermont.gov/statutes/section/26/036/02023", "description": "Vermont allows pharmacists to prescribe through collaborative practice agreements under 26 V.S.A. Section 2023. Pharmacists may also prescribe certain medications independently under Board-approved protocols, including hormonal contraceptives and naloxone."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Hub and Spoke System", "url": "https://blueprintforhealth.vermont.gov/about-blueprint/hub-and-spoke", "description": "Vermont's innovative Hub and Spoke model for opioid use disorder treatment. Hubs are licensed Opioid Treatment Programs providing intensive care, while Spokes are primary care providers offering integrated OUD treatment including buprenorphine."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator (Vermont)", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator, which can be filtered to find buprenorphine providers and OUD treatment programs in Vermont. Search by state or ZIP code."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA's locator for practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine. Can be filtered by state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Opioid Prescribing and MOUD Resources", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/health-professionals/opioid-prescribing-and-moud", "description": "Vermont Department of Health page for health professionals with information about Medication for Opioid Use Disorder (MOUD) rules, prescribing requirements, and related resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont MOUD Prescribing Rules", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/vermont/13-062-Code-Vt-R-13-140-062-X", "description": "Vermont regulation governing Medication-Assisted Therapy for Opioid Dependence, including rules for office-based opioid treatment (OBOT) providers prescribing buprenorphine and opioid treatment providers. Includes telehealth provisions allowing MOUD prescribing via telehealth."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine: Eligible MOUD providers in Vermont may prescribe MOUD and conduct evaluations via telehealth in accordance with federal law and clinical need, per the state's MOUD regulations (13-062 Code Vt. R.)."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Medicaid Pharmacy Benefit", "url": "https://dvha.vermont.gov/providers/pharmacy", "description": "The Department of Vermont Health Access (DVHA) pharmacy provider page, the main portal for Vermont Medicaid pharmacy benefits including billing information and resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List and Clinical Criteria", "url": "https://dvha.vermont.gov/providers/pharmacy/preferred-drug-list-pdl-clinical-criteria", "description": "Vermont Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) and clinical criteria for prior authorization. Vermont Medicaid covers all forms of buprenorphine therapy, including buprenorphine and buprenorphine/naloxone preparations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Coverage Lists", "url": "https://dvha.vermont.gov/providers/pharmacy/drug-coverage-lists", "description": "Vermont Medicaid drug coverage lists showing covered medications including buprenorphine products and their coverage status."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Codes and Fee Schedules", "url": "https://dvha.vermont.gov/providers/codesfee-schedules", "description": "Vermont Medicaid fee schedule information for covered services, updated monthly. Includes procedure codes and reimbursement rates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont OBOT Clinical Guidelines", "url": "https://dvha.vermont.gov/sites/dvha/files/documents/providers/Forms/MATclinicalguidelines_8.16.21__MB__.pdf", "description": "Vermont's Office Based Opioid Treatment Practice Guidelines published by DVHA, including Medicaid coverage information for buprenorphine and other MOUD therapies."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Grant and Funding Opportunities: Vermont receives State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA. From FY18-FY22, VDH Division of Substance Use received approximately $18 million in SOR funding. Contact the Division of Substance Use at AHS.VDHDSU@vermont.gov for information on current funding opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Vermont CE Requirements for Controlled Substances", "url": "https://outside.vermont.gov/dept/sos/office_professional_regulation/professions/pharmacy/pharmacy_administrative_rules_effective_2026_0201.pdf", "description": "Vermont Board of Pharmacy Administrative Rules requiring pharmacists with DEA registration to complete at least 2 hours of CE on controlled substance abuse, diversion, safe use, storage, disposal, and use of VPMS every two years. Total requirement is 30 CE hours per two-year cycle."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Pharmacists Association Education", "url": "https://vtpharmacists.com/", "description": "The Vermont Pharmacists Association provides continuing education opportunities, including online CE and educational events. VPA is the primary professional association for Vermont pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Pharmacists Association Helpful Links", "url": "https://vtpharmacists.com/Helpful-Links", "description": "VPA resource page with links to Board of Pharmacy resources, controlled substance CE requirements, naloxone standing order information, and other educational materials."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division FAQ page on buprenorphine, including registration requirements. All practitioners with a current DEA registration that includes Schedule III authority may now prescribe buprenorphine for OUD if permitted by state law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD). Offers free online training modules, webinars, and clinical guidance on buprenorphine prescribing and OUD treatment."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Services Programs", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/disease-control/hiv-sti-hepatitis-community-resources/syringe-services-programs", "description": "Vermont Department of Health directory of syringe services programs (SSPs) operating across the state. SSPs provide free and anonymous services including syringes, supplies, overdose prevention resources, naloxone, and fentanyl test strips."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/emergency/injury-prevention/opioid-overdose-prevention", "description": "Information on Vermont's statewide naloxone standing order, which allows any pharmacy to sell naloxone to any person without a prescription. Insurers and Medicaid cover the cost. The current standing order is effective through August 2027."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order Document", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/RESP_Naloxone_standingorder.pdf", "description": "The actual standing order document issued by the Commissioner of Health authorizing the distribution of naloxone to eligible persons in Vermont."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: Fentanyl test strips are legal in Vermont. In 2023, Vermont enacted legislation explicitly excluding drug testing equipment, including fentanyl test strips, from the definition of drug paraphernalia. Free test strips are available through Vermont's syringe services programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance Dashboard", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/stats/data-reporting-topic/overdose-dashboard", "description": "Vermont Department of Health Overdose Dashboard with monthly overdose death and emergency department visit data, including trends and comparisons to prior years."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Partners of Vermont", "url": "https://vtrecoverynetwork.org/", "description": "Recovery Partners of Vermont (formerly Vermont Recovery Network) provides advocacy, support, and best practices to Vermont's recovery organizations. Includes a directory to find recovery centers by area."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Department of Health Recovery Support", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/how-get-help/find-recovery", "description": "Vermont Department of Health page on recovery support services, including information on Recovery Centers and peer recovery coaching throughout the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Support Services", "url": "https://vthelplink.org/recovery/", "description": "Vermont Helplink recovery services page providing information on peer recovery coaching, recovery centers, mutual aid groups, and other support services. Contact at 802-565-LINK or toll-free 833-565-LINK."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://vtarr.org/", "description": "Vermont Alliance for Recovery Residences (VTARR) certifies recovery homes in the state and provides a directory of certified recovery residences meeting national standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing (VDH)", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/system-care-enhancement/recovery-residences", "description": "Vermont Department of Health page on certified recovery residences, including information about Act 163 (2024) and the state's oversight of recovery housing certification."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://mentalhealth.vermont.gov/", "description": "Vermont Department of Mental Health homepage, which oversees mental health services in the state."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Division of Substance Use Programs", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/programs-services", "description": "The Vermont Division of Substance Use (DSU) within the Department of Health administers prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery programs and services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Vermont has multiple crisis resources. Call 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Contact VT Helplink at 802-565-5465 (toll-free 833-565-5465) for substance use treatment referrals and support."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Board of Pharmacy Contact", "url": "https://sos.vermont.gov/pharmacy/", "description": "Vermont Board of Pharmacy, Office of Professional Regulation. Address: 89 Main Street, 3rd Floor, Montpelier, VT 05620-3402. Phone: 802-828-5032."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Vermont Health Access (Medicaid)", "url": "https://dvha.vermont.gov/contact", "description": "DVHA contact page. Address: 280 State Drive, NOB 1 South, Waterbury, VT 05671-1010. Phone: 802-879-5900. Customer Service: 1-855-899-9600."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/health-professionals/opioid-prescribing-and-moud", "description": "Vermont Department of Health, Division of Substance Use oversees opioid treatment. Contact: AHS.VDHDSU@vermont.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://vtpharmacists.com/Contact", "description": "Contact page for the Vermont Pharmacists Association, the state professional organization representing pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Department of Health OUD Program", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/opioid-overdose-response/vermonts-response-opioids", "description": "Vermont Department of Health page on the state's comprehensive response to the opioid crisis, including prevention, treatment, and recovery initiatives."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/stats/data-reporting-topic/overdose-dashboard", "description": "Vermont's monthly overdose dashboard with data on accidental and undetermined overdose deaths and emergency department visits, including trends and year-over-year comparisons."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Data and Reports", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/substance-use-data-reports/data-and-reports", "description": "Comprehensive page with data briefs, reports, assessments, and survey results on alcohol, opioids, cannabis, and overall substance use in Vermont. Includes the VT Substance Use Dashboard and VT Overdose Dashboard."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Fatal Overdose Data Brief", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/document/dsu-fatal-opioid-overdoses-2023.pdf", "description": "Annual data brief on fatal overdoses among Vermont residents, including monthly opioid-related fatal overdose data and trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data to Action Program", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/document/dsu-od2a.pdf", "description": "Overview of Vermont's CDC-funded Overdose Data to Action (OD2A) cooperative agreement, including surveillance strategies and county-level data collection efforts."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Substance Use Dashboard: The Vermont Substance Use Dashboard provides interactive data on substance use trends statewide. Accessible through the Data and Reports page at https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/substance-use-data-reports/data-and-reports."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Pharmacists Association Advocacy", "url": "https://vtpharmacists.com/", "description": "The Vermont Pharmacists Association advocates for a forward-looking legislative agenda supporting the profession of pharmacy and the health of Vermonters. VPA members provide testimony and advocate on pharmacy-related legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Legislature Bill Tracking", "url": "https://legislature.vermont.gov/", "description": "Vermont General Assembly website for tracking current legislation, including bills related to pharmacist prescribing, OUD treatment, and pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Vermont Legislator", "url": "https://legislature.vermont.gov/people/", "description": "Tool to search for Vermont legislators by name or town to facilitate advocacy and communication about pharmacy and OUD-related issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Opioid Coordination Council", "url": "https://governor.vermont.gov/content/addressing-opioid-epidemic", "description": "Information on Vermont's Opioid Coordination Council (OCC), created by Executive Order to strengthen and expand Vermont's response to the opioid crisis through prevention, treatment, recovery, and enforcement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Vermont Response to Opioids", "url": "https://www.healthvermont.gov/alcohol-drugs/opioid-overdose-response/vermonts-response-opioids", "description": "Vermont Department of Health page detailing the state's comprehensive opioid response, including the Rule Governing the Prescribing of Opioids for Pain, syringe services programs, naloxone distribution, and treatment expansion efforts."}]}]}, "virginia": {"name": "Virginia", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Virginia’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative agreement.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Virginia law does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “practice of pharmacy”).\nHowever, the practice of pharmacy definition includes “the initiating of treatment with . . . certain drugs, devices, or controlled paraphernalia in accordance with the provisions of § 54.1-3303.1.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “practice of pharmacy”). The law does not define the word “initiating.”\nThe referenced law (and associated regulation) contains over a dozen categories of drugs or medications that a pharmacist can “initiate treatment with, dispense, or administer.” The categories do not include drugs or medications for SUD treatment. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303.1 (West 2024); 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE § 110-21-46 (2024).\nMoreover, Virginia pharmacy law provides that a controlled substance prescription may be issued only by a “practitioner of medicine, osteopathy, podiatry, dentistry or veterinary medicine who is authorized to prescribe controlled substances, a licensed advanced practice registered nurse pursuant to § 54.1-2957.01, a licensed certified midwife pursuant to § 54.1-2957.04, a licensed physician assistant pursuant to § 54.1-2952.1, or a TPA-certified optometrist pursuant to Article 5 (§ 54.1-3222 et seq.) of Chapter 32.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303(A) (West 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Virginia cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Virginia practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Virginia pharmacists to the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Virginia laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Virginia law notes that it is a health service “concerned with the art and science of . . . administering . . . and dispensing of drugs, medicines, and devices.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “practice of pharmacy”). This provision does not limit the drugs, medicines, or devices associated with administering and could mean that a pharmacist has authority to administer buprenorphine generally.\nMoreover, the definition of “dispense” in Virginia law expressly includes “the prescribing and administering. . . necessary to prepare the substance for delivery.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “dispense”). Although this appears to support the conclusion that pharmacists in Virginia have broad authority to administer drugs and medications, the provision described in the bullet point below, among others, suggests that the Virginia legislature does not interpret the word “dispense” to include administering.\nBesides the potentially broad authorization noted above, the practice of pharmacy definition expressly allows for the “dispensing or administering of certain drugs, devices, or controlled paraphernalia in accordance with the provisions of § 54.1-3303.1.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “practice of pharmacy”).However, the referenced Virginia law (and associated regulation) contains a specific list of drugs, medications, and other devices, including some controlled substances, that a pharmacist may “initiate treatment with, dispense, or administer” to a person aged 18 or older. The categories do not include drugs or medications for SUD treatment. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303.1 (West 2024); 18 VA. ADMIN.\nCODE § 110-21-46 (2024). This provision could mean that there is no broad authorization to administer drugs and medications in Virginia and it does not allow for administering buprenorphine. The provision also indicates that “dispensing” does not include administering, or else the phrase “or administering” in the law (and similar phrase in the associated regulation) would be superfluous.", "2B": "Obtain a prescription drug order.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the Virginia practice of pharmacy to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not include the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Virginia law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating laboratory tests. However, the definition expressly allows for “the initiating of treatment with or dispensing or administering of certain drugs, devices, or controlled paraphernalia in accordance with the provisions of § 54.1-3303.1.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024)\n(definition of “practice of pharmacy”).The referenced Virginia law authorizes a pharmacist to administer “tests for COVID-19 and other coronaviruses” and to initiate treatment using controlled substances for certain specified diseases or conditions (that do not include SUD) “for which clinical decision making can be guided by a clinical test that is classified as waived under [CLIA].” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303.1(A)(11), (12) (West 2024).", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Virginia practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Virginia law includes the management of patient care under the terms of a collaborative agreement (CA). VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “practice of pharmacy”).\nA CA “may include the implementation, modification, continuation, or discontinuation of drug therapy pursuant to written or electronic protocol.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300.1(C) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “implementation” and “modification,” it does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications.\nVirginia laws and regulations governing CAs provide that a CA must contain a description of the activities a pharmacist may engage in, but they do not expressly address whether such authority may include prescribing drugs and medications. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300.1 (West 2024); 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE § 110-40-40 (2024). Even if a CA could allow a Virginia pharmacist to prescribe drugs, Virginia laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a Virginia pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CA provides.\nIn summary, Virginia laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a drug therapy protocol. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Virginia pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Virginia laws and/or regulations governing CAs to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Virginia laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CAs.\nAllow Virginia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances for all purposes.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Virginia laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Virginia law includes the management of patient care under the terms of a CA. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024)\n(definition of “practice of pharmacy”).\nA CA “may include the implementation, modification, continuation, or discontinuation of drug therapy pursuant to written or electronic protocol.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300.1(C) (West 2024). Although this provision uses the words “implementation” and “modification,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs or medications. However, the provision could be interpreted to allow a pharmacist to administer drugs and medications. Virginia laws and regulations governing CAs provide that a CA must contain a description of the activities a pharmacist may engage in, but they do not expressly address whether such authority may include administering drugs and medications. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300.1 (West 2024); 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE § 110-40-40 (2024).\nIn summary, although Virginia pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine as part of a CA, they also do not clearly authorize it and a pharmacist’s general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CA is also unclear.", "5B": "Enter into a CA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Virginia laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CA include administering drugs and medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Virginia law includes the management of patient care under the terms of a CA. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024)\n(definition of “practice of pharmacy”).\nVirginia law provides that a CA may include “the ordering of laboratory tests.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300.1(C) (West 2024).\nVirginia laws and regulations governing CAs do not expressly address evaluating the results of lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a CA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Virginia laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CA include evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CA is a voluntary, written, or electronic arrangement between “one pharmacist and his designated alternate pharmacists” and four categories of individuals. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “collaborative agreement”).\nThe four categories are: (1) a person licensed to practice medicine, osteopathy, or podiatry together with any person licensed, registered, or certified by a health regulatory board of the Virginia Department of Health Professions who provides health care services to patients of such person licensed to practice medicine, osteopathy, or podiatry; (2) a physician’s office, as defined in in § 32.1-276.3, so long as the CA is signed by each participating physician; (3) a physician assistant working under the supervision of a person licensed to practice medicine, osteopathy, or podiatry; and (4) an APRN working in accordance with the provisions of § 54.1-2957. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3300 (West 2024) (definition of “collaborative agreement”).\nVirginia regulation governing CAs uses the word “practitioner,” and defines it to include the four categories of individuals. 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE § 110-40-10 (2024).\nThe following Virginia laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – VA. CODE ANN. §§ 54.1-3300 to 54.1-3300.1 (West 2024); 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE §§ 110-40-10 to 110-40-70 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nVirginia does not have a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act. However, Virginia health insurance law provides that health insurers must “provide coverage for the cost of such health care services provided through telemedicine services” subject to certain specified requirements. VA CODE ANN. § 38.2-3418.16(A) (West 2024).\nThe term “telemedicine services” refers to activities performed by a “health care provider.” “Health care provider” is not defined in the law, though. VA CODE ANN. § 38.2-3418.16(B) (West 2024).\nHowever, a definition of “health care provider” found in Virginia medical malpractice laws, which is cited as the definition for the term throughout other sections of Virginia laws, expressly includes pharmacists within the definition. VA CODE ANN. § 8.01-581.1 (West 2024).\nMoreover, Virginia pharmacy law expressly provides that a pharmacist initiating treatment with, dispensing, or administering drugs, medications, or devices pursuant to § 54.1-3303 may do so through telemedicine services, as defined in the insurance provision described above, consistent with the applicable standard of care. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303.1(F) (West 2024).", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Virginia laws and/or regulations to provide a general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "A practitioner who has established a bona fide practitioner-patient relationship with a patient may prescribe Schedule II through VI controlled substances to that patient via telemedicine if such prescribing complies with federal requirements for the practice of telemedicine and other requirements specified in Virginia law. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303(B) (West 2024). A bona fide relationship can be established through telemedicine as long as certain requirements are met. VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303(B) (West 2024).\nVirginia laws and regulations governing telehealth include – VA. CODE ANN. § 32.1-122.03:1 (West 2024) (statewide telehealth plan); VA. CODE ANN. § 32.1-325(26) (West 2024) (Medicaid); VA. CODE ANN. § 38.2-3418.16 (West 2024) (insurance coverage); VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303(B) (West 2024) (controlled substances); VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-3303.1(F) (West 2024) (pharmacists initiating treatment); 12 VA. ADMIN. CODE § 30-130-5060 (Medicaid – OBOT); 12 VA. ADMIN. CODE § 30-130-5080 (Medicaid – outpatient treatment – physicians).", "9A": "For Medicaid, Virginia law provides that “when the services provided are by a pharmacist, pharmacy technician, or pharmacy intern (i) performed under the terms of a collaborative agreement as defined in § 54.1-3300 and consistent with the terms of a managed care contractor provider contract or the state plan or (ii) related to services and treatment in accordance with § 54.1-3303.1, the Department [of medical assistance services] shall provide reimbursement for such service.” VA. CODE ANN. § 32.1-325(K) (West 2024).\nLikewise, Virginia health insurance law provides that “if an accident and sickness insurance policy provides reimbursement for a service that may be legally performed by a licensed pharmacist, reimbursement under the policy shall not be denied because the service is rendered by the licensed pharmacist, provided that (i) the service is performed for an insured for a condition under the terms of a collaborative agreement, as defined in § 54.1-3300, (ii) the service is for the administration of vaccines for immunization, or (iii) the service is provided in accordance with § 54.1-3303.1.” VA. CODE ANN. § 38.2-3408(B) (West 2024).288\nReimbursement for telehealth services provided by pharmacists is not permitted, however.289", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Virginia law requires the Virginia Board of Medicine (BoM) to adopt regulations related to “the use of buprenorphine in the treatment of addiction, including a requirement for referral to or consultation with a provider of substance abuse counseling in conjunction with treatment of opioid dependency with products containing buprenorphine.” VA. CODE ANN. § 54.1-2928.2(3) (West 2024).\nThese BoM regulations address general provisions, a requirement to provide counseling or refer patients to it, patient assessment and treatment planning, dosage requirements and recommendations, drug screens, special patient populations, and medical records. 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE §§ 85-21-130 to 85-21-170 (2024).\nThere are similar regulations related to treatment with buprenorphine by nurses. 18 VA. ADMIN. CODE §§ 90-40-250 to 90-40-290 (2024).\nVirginia has specific Medicaid program regulations related to “office-based addiction treatment” and outpatient services by physicians. 12 VA. ADMIN. CODE §§ 30-130-5060, 30-130-5080 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://virginia.pmpaware.net/login", "description": "Virginia's Prescription Monitoring Program (PMP) login portal, powered by PMP AWARxE (Bamboo Health). Used by pharmacists, prescribers, and other authorized users to query controlled substance dispensing data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Program Information", "url": "https://www.dhp.virginia.gov/PractitionerResources/PrescriptionMonitoringProgram/", "description": "Virginia Department of Health Professions PMP page with program information, registration details, and contact information. PMP Director: Ashley Carter. Email: pmp@dhp.virginia.gov."}, {"type": "note", "text": "PDMP Registration: Registration is completed through the PMP AWARxE portal at https://virginia.pmpaware.net. New users create an account and submit required documentation for state approval. Technical support: 855-482-4767."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Virginia law requires enrollment in and use of the PMP for both prescribers and dispensers of monitored drugs. Practitioners must check the PMP before prescribing opioids and benzodiazepines."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing / PMP InterConnect: Virginia participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing, enabling authorized users to view prescription data from other participating states through the PMP AWARxE platform."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegate accounts can be established through the PMP AWARxE system. Prescribers and dispensers may designate authorized delegates to query the PMP on their behalf."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.dhp.virginia.gov/Boards/Pharmacy/", "description": "Virginia Board of Pharmacy homepage within the Department of Health Professions (DHP). Provides licensing information, meeting schedules, and regulatory updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Laws and Regulations", "url": "https://www.dhp.virginia.gov/Boards/Pharmacy/PractitionerResources/LawsRegulations/", "description": "Board of Pharmacy laws and regulations page with links to state pharmacy laws, proposed regulations, and guidance documents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (Code of Virginia)", "url": "https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacodefull/title54.1/chapter33/", "description": "Full text of Virginia Code Title 54.1, Chapter 33 (Pharmacy), the state's Pharmacy Practice Act governing the regulation of pharmacy practice, drug manufacturing, dispensing, and distribution."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Regulations", "url": "https://law.lis.virginia.gov/admincode/title18/agency110/chapter20/", "description": "Virginia Administrative Code Title 18, Agency 110, Chapter 20 - Regulations Governing the Practice of Pharmacy. Contains detailed regulatory requirements for pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Statute", "url": "https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title54.1/chapter33/section54.1-3300.1/", "description": "Virginia Code Section 54.1-3300.1 authorizing pharmacists to participate in collaborative agreements with prescribing practitioners. Pharmacists may prescribe, modify, continue, or discontinue Schedule II-VI controlled substances under a collaborative agreement. Regulations jointly developed by the Boards of Medicine and Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Regulations", "url": "https://law.lis.virginia.gov/admincodefull/title18/agency110/chapter40/", "description": "Virginia Administrative Code Title 18, Agency 110, Chapter 40 - Regulations for Prescriptive Authority for Pharmacists. Details requirements for collaborative agreements including protocols, reporting, and oversight."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Virginia DBHDS Substance Use Services", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/substance-use-services-for-individuals-and-families/", "description": "Virginia Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Services (DBHDS) page on substance use services, including information about Opioid Treatment Programs (OTPs), Medications for Opioid Use Disorder (MOUD), and available resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to find buprenorphine providers and OUD treatment programs in Virginia. Search by state, city, or ZIP code."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA)", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/12VAC35-105-MOUD-Amendments-PowerPoint.pdf", "description": "Virginia DBHDS serves as the State Methadone Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA). Contact DBHDS for information on OTP licensing and MOUD regulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Regulations", "url": "https://law.lis.virginia.gov/admincode/title18/agency85/chapter21/", "description": "Virginia Administrative Code Title 18, Agency 85, Chapter 21 - Regulations Governing Prescribing of Opioids and Buprenorphine, issued by the Board of Medicine."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine", "url": "https://www.ehealthvirginia.org/dea-grants-fourth-temporary-extension-of-flexibilities-for-tele-prescribing-controlled-substances-through-2026/", "description": "Virginia Telehealth Network page on DEA telehealth flexibilities for prescribing controlled substances including buprenorphine, with updates on federal rules for telemedicine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Medication Assisted Treatment Overview", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/2024.01.09-MAT-.pdf", "description": "DBHDS overview of Medication Assisted Treatment in Virginia, describing all three FDA-approved medications for OUD (buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone) and how they are delivered in the state."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://www.dmas.virginia.gov/for-providers/benefits-services-for-providers/pharmacy-and-drug-formularies/", "description": "Department of Medical Assistance Services (DMAS) pharmacy services page with information on the Preferred Drug List, prior authorization programs, and pharmacy initiatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://vamedicaid.dmas.virginia.gov/bulletin/virginia-medicaid-preferred-drug-list-common-core-formulary-and-new-drug-utilization", "description": "Virginia Medicaid Preferred Drug List / Common Core Formulary and Drug Utilization Review Board approved drug service authorizations, including buprenorphine coverage information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Prescription Drug Formularies", "url": "https://www.dmas.virginia.gov/for-members/benefits-and-services/prescription-drug-formularies/", "description": "DMAS page listing Medicaid Managed Care, Dual Special Needs Plans, and Virginia Medicaid PDL Fee-for-Service drug formularies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DMAS Contact for Provider Inquiries", "url": "https://vamedicaid.dmas.virginia.gov/contact-us", "description": "Virginia Medicaid provider contact page. Toll Free: 1-800-552-8627. Local: 1-804-786-6273."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia State Opioid Response Grant", "url": "https://www.virginiasorsupport.org/about-sor", "description": "Information on Virginia's State Opioid Response (SOR) Grant funded by SAMHSA, providing funding for treatment, prevention, and recovery services. Virginia received over $15 million for SOR I and continues to receive significant federal funding."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Opioid Abatement Authority", "url": "https://www.oaa.virginia.gov/", "description": "Independent authority providing grants and financial support for efforts to treat, prevent, and reduce opioid use disorder in Virginia. Localities can apply for abatement funding."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Virginia CE Requirements", "url": "https://virginiapharmacists.org/events/ce-requirements/", "description": "Virginia Pharmacy Association page on pharmacist CE requirements. Virginia requires 15 CE hours annually. Pharmacists were required to complete at least 2 hours on medications for OUD (including buprenorphine, methadone, naltrexone, and naloxone) as a one-time requirement."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://virginiapharmacists.org/", "description": "Virginia Pharmacy Association (VPhA) homepage providing continuing education, networking, and advocacy resources for Virginia pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division FAQ on buprenorphine prescribing and registration. All practitioners with current DEA registration including Schedule III authority may prescribe buprenorphine for OUD if permitted by state law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders (PCSS-MOUD) offering free online training modules, webinars, and mentoring on buprenorphine prescribing and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA MATE Act Training", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/pharmacist-verification", "description": "SAMHSA page on pharmacist verification and the MATE Act training requirement for DEA registrants, applicable to Virginia practitioners prescribing controlled substances."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Comprehensive Harm Reduction Programs", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/disease-prevention/chr/", "description": "Virginia Department of Health Comprehensive Harm Reduction (CHR) program page with an interactive map of authorized CHR sites across the state, providing syringe services, naloxone, fentanyl test strips, and referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "REVIVE! Naloxone Program", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/behavioral-health/substance-abuse-services/revive/", "description": "Virginia's REVIVE! program - the Opioid Overdose and Naloxone Education (OONE) program providing training on recognizing and responding to opioid overdoses using naloxone. Virginia has a statewide standing order allowing pharmacies to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone and Harm Reduction Toolkit", "url": "https://virginiaopioidtoolkit.org/toolkit/naloxone/", "description": "Virginia Opioid Abatement Toolkit page on broadening naloxone access, including information on VDH's Comprehensive Harm Reduction Partner Program (CHRPP) which provides free nasal spray naloxone to approved entities."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: Fentanyl test strips are legal in Virginia. VDH offers no-cost naloxone, fentanyl test strips, xylazine test strips, and benzodiazepine test strips to local Health Departments, Community Service Boards, authorized CHR sites, Free Clinics, and FQHCs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/drug-overdose-data/", "description": "Virginia Department of Health Drug Overdose and Substance Use data homepage with links to overdose death dashboards, ED visit surveillance, forensic epidemiology reports, and locality-level data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Harm Reduction Coalition", "url": "https://www.carrynaloxone.org/", "description": "Virginia Harm Reduction Coalition (VHRC), a peer-run nonprofit offering comprehensive harm reduction services including syringe services, naloxone distribution, and community education."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "DBHDS Office of Recovery Services", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/office-of-recovery-services/", "description": "DBHDS Office of Recovery Services page providing information on peer support services, recovery coaching, and other recovery support resources in Virginia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DBHDS Find Help", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/find-help/", "description": "DBHDS resource page to find Community Services Boards (CSBs) and behavioral health services across Virginia's 39 CSBs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://varronline.org/", "description": "Virginia Association of Recovery Residences (VARR) homepage with information on certified recovery residences throughout Virginia, accreditation standards, and the social model of recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://dbhds.virginia.gov/", "description": "Virginia Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental Services (DBHDS) homepage, the state agency responsible for overseeing behavioral health, substance use, and developmental disability services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis and Warmline Contacts: Virginia has multiple crisis resources. Call 988 for the Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Virginia's Peer-Run Mental Health Warm Line provides non-judgmental support and referrals. Contact local Community Services Boards for SUD-specific crisis services."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.dhp.virginia.gov/Boards/Pharmacy/AbouttheBoard/StaffListing/", "description": "Board of Pharmacy staff listing. Executive Director: Caroline D. Juran, RPh. Email: Caroline.Juran@dhp.virginia.gov. General email: pharmbd@dhp.virginia.gov. Phone: (804) 367-4456. Address: 9960 Mayland Drive, Suite 300, Richmond, VA 23233-1463."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia DMAS (Medicaid)", "url": "https://www.dmas.virginia.gov/about-us/contact-information/", "description": "Department of Medical Assistance Services contact page. Customer Service: 1-855-242-8282. Provider line: 1-800-552-8627."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA): DBHDS serves as the SOTA for Virginia. Contact Marie Bage, Substance Use Treatment Administrator, at 804-857-9874 for OTP licensing and MOUD regulatory inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://virginiapharmacists.org/", "description": "Virginia Pharmacy Association (VPhA) provides advocacy, education, and networking for Virginia pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Department of Health OUD Resources", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/drug-overdose-data/", "description": "VDH drug overdose and substance use data hub with comprehensive opioid data, prevention resources, and public health information."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data Homepage", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/drug-overdose-data/", "description": "Virginia Department of Health Drug Overdose and Substance Use data portal providing resources for drug overdose prevention and response."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Death Dashboard", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/drug-overdose-data/overdose-deaths/", "description": "VDH drug overdose death dashboard with mortality data from death certificates, including data by drug type, demographics, and locality for Virginia residents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ED Visits for Drug Overdose", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/surveillance-and-investigation/syndromic-surveillance/drug-overdose-surveillance/", "description": "VDH syndromic surveillance dashboard tracking emergency department visits for drug overdoses in Virginia, providing near-real-time monitoring of overdose trends."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Forensic Epidemiology Reports", "url": "https://www.vdh.virginia.gov/medical-examiner/forensic-epidemiology/", "description": "VDH Medical Examiner's office forensic epidemiology page with quarterly drug death reports, fatal overdose tables by locality, and substance-specific death data (fentanyl, heroin, methamphetamine, cocaine, prescription opioids)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Opioid Abatement Toolkit Data", "url": "https://virginiaopioidtoolkit.org/", "description": "Virginia Opioid Abatement Toolkit providing data-driven guidance for counties and cities on evidence-based opioid abatement activities, developed by Virginia Commonwealth University and the Opioid Abatement Authority."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://virginiapharmacists.org/", "description": "VPhA advocates for a forward-looking legislative agenda maximizing the profession's contributions to public health and patient care. VPhA is proactive in monitoring and influencing legislation affecting pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia General Assembly Bill Tracking", "url": "https://lis.virginia.gov/", "description": "Virginia Legislative Information System for tracking current legislation, including bills related to pharmacist prescribing, OUD treatment, and pharmacy practice."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Virginia Legislator", "url": "https://whosmy.virginiageneralassembly.gov/", "description": "Online tool where Virginia residents can determine their House and Senate representatives by entering their address, facilitating advocacy on pharmacy and OUD-related issues."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Opioid Abatement Authority", "url": "https://www.oaa.virginia.gov/", "description": "Independent state authority providing grants and financial support for opioid abatement efforts across Virginia. Localities and organizations can apply for funding to support prevention, treatment, and recovery initiatives."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Virginia Opioid Abatement Toolkit", "url": "https://virginiaopioidtoolkit.org/", "description": "Comprehensive toolkit developed by VCU, the Wright Center for Clinical and Translational Research, the Opioid Abatement Authority, and the Virginia Society of Addiction Medicine, providing evidence-based guidance for local opioid abatement efforts."}]}]}, "washington": {"name": "Washington", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Washington’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative drug therapy agreement” (CDTA). WASH. ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-001(11) (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Washington law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024).\nThe practice of pharmacy definition does allow for “the initiating or modifying of drug therapy in accordance with written guidelines or protocols previously established and approved for his or her practice by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024).\nHowever, Washington regulations indicate that for a pharmacist to have “prescriptive authority,” the pharmacist must have a collaborative drug therapy agreement (CDTA) on file with the state pharmacy commission. WASH ADMIN. CODE §§ 246-945-011(11), 246-945-350(1) (2024).\nDEA information last updated in November 2024 indicates that registered pharmacists in Washington can obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to “Prescribe Only.” However, based on the information in Washington laws and regulations described in the response to the \"prescribing buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, this authority applies only to pharmacists acting under CDTAs, even though that limitation is not specified by DEA.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Washington practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Washington pharmacists not operating under CDTAs to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” includes “administering . . . drugs and devices.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications associated with administering and could mean that a pharmacist has authority to administer buprenorphine generally.\nUnlike the laws and regulations of several other states with general language about administration in the practice of pharmacy definition, there are no other Washington laws or regulations that address administration of a small subset of drugs or medications (such as immunizations) that would give the impression that the legislature does not view the “administering . . . drugs and devices” language as a broad authorization.\nMoreover, a Washington Department of Health (WDOH) website entitled “Who Can Prescribe and Administer Prescriptions in Washington State” indicates, within the category of “professions that may administer drugs ordered by authorized prescribers,” that pharmacists can administer prescribed drugs without any further caveat.", "2B": "Obtain a prescription or order from a prescriber.\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below the authorization could be limited slightly.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Washington law does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests. WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024).\nThe practice of pharmacy definition does allow for “the monitoring of drug therapy and use.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024).\nWashington regulation provides that “in the absence of a CDTA,” the phrase “monitoring drug therapy” as used in the practice of pharmacy definition includes “ordering, administering or reviewing laboratory tests, imaging, and social evaluation related to an existing diagnosis and drug therapies for optimization of drug therapy.” WASH ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-355 (2024). This regulation indicates that a pharmacist can order and evaluate lab tests outside of a CDTA.\nNo other Washington pharmacy laws or regulations expressly address ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "3B": "Confirm that the lab test ordered or evaluated fits within the meaning of “monitoring drug therapy.”\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "3C": "If necessary, expand the Washington practice of pharmacy to expressly allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Washington expressly authorizes “the initiating or modifying of drug therapy in accordance with written guidelines or protocols previously established and approved for his or her practice by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024). Although this provision does not expressly refer to prescribing drugs or medications, Washington regulations make clear that it can include prescribing authority. Washington regulation provides that a CDTA is “a written guideline or protocol previously established and approved by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs that enables a pharmacist to exercise prescriptive authority.” WASH ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-011(11) (2024). The regulation governing content of CDTAs also expressly provides that modification or initiation of drug therapy includes prescriptive authority. WASH ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-350(2) (2024).\nWashington laws and regulations governing drug therapy and CDTAs do not expressly address prescribing controlled substances or the need for a pharmacist to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration to do so.\nHowever, a WDOH website on general pharmacy practice provides that “a pharmacist working under a [CDTA] may prescribe controlled substance (CS) prescriptions under the following conditions: (1) the scope of the CDTA must permit this activity; and (2) the pharmacist must have a Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) registration (unless exempted from obtaining a DEA registration, for example see the FAQ on use of the hospital DEA with a suffix).”\nThis conclusion is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Washington can obtain a mid-level practitioner registration.", "4B": "Enter into a CDTA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "4C": null, "5A": "As described in the information below, Washington laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Washington law expressly authorizes “the initiating or modifying of drug therapy in accordance with written guidelines or protocols previously established and approved for his or her practice by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024). Although this provision refers to “initiating or modifying,” it does not expressly refer to administering drugs and medications.\nThe Washington regulation governing CDTAs indicates that a CDTA must detail the type of prescriptive authority authorized as well as include “a general statement of the training required, procedures, decision criteria, or plan the pharmacist is to follow when making therapeutic decisions, particularly when modification or initiation of drug therapy is involved.” WASH ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-350(2) (2024). The provision does not expressly address administering drugs and medications, however.\nIn summary, Washington laws and regulations are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can administer drugs and medications under a CDTA. However, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer any prescribed drug or medication outside of CDTA, the logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a CDTA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly provide in Washington laws and/or regulations that “initiating or modifying drug therapy” includes administering drugs, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Washington laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” at least to the same extent. The definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Washington law expressly authorizes “the initiating or modifying of drug therapy in accordance with written guidelines or protocols previously established and approved for his or her practice by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(32) (West 2024). Although this provision refers to “initiating or modifying,” it does not expressly refer to ordering or evaluating lab tests.\nThe Washington regulation governing CDTAs indicates that a CDTA must detail the type of prescriptive authority authorized as well as include “a general statement of the training required, procedures, decision criteria, or plan the pharmacist is to follow when making therapeutic decisions, particularly when modification or initiation of drug therapy is involved.” WASH ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-350(2) (2024). The provision does not expressly address ordering or evaluating lab tests, however.\nIn summary, Washington laws and regulations are unclear about the extent to which a pharmacist can order and evaluate lab tests under a CDTA. However, given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that a pharmacist has authority to order, administer, or review lab tests as part of monitoring drug therapy outside of a CDTA, the logical answer to this question is that a pharmacist has the same authority under a CDTA.", "6B": "Enter into a CDTA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Washington laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CDTA include ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CDTA is a “written guideline or protocol previously established and approved by a practitioner authorized to prescribe drugs.” WASH ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-011(11) (2024).\nWashington law provides that a “practitioner” means “a physician, dentist, veterinarian, nurse, or other person duly authorized by law or rule in the state of Washington to prescribe drugs.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.011(33) (West 2024).\nThe following Washington regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CDTAs and required elements of CDTAs – WASH ADMIN. CODE §§ 246-945-011(11), 246-945-350, 246-945-355 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nWashington’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law authorizes a “health care practitioner” to provide telehealth services to a patient located in Washington “if the services are consistent with the health care practitioner’s scope of practice in this state, applicable professional practice standards in this state, and requirements and limitations of federal law and law of this state.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.134.030(1) (West 2024).\nThe definition of “health care provider” does not expressly include pharmacists. However, it also includes “a person who is otherwise authorized to practice a profession regulated under the authority of [§] 18.130.040 to provide health care in this state, to the extent the profession’s scope of practice includes health care that can be provided through telehealth.” WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.134.010(4)(a)(vii) (West 2024).\nThe state pharmacy quality assurance commission, established in chapter 18.64 of the Washington statutory code, is included in the list of boards and commissions having authority under § 18.130.040. WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.130.040(2)(b)(viii) (West 2024). As a result, it appears that pharmacists fall within the provision for professions regulated under § 18.130.040.", "8B": null, "8C": "A pharmacy may extend its license to register a remote dispensing site where technology is used to dispense MOUD. WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.600 (West 2024); WASH. ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-457 (2024).\nWashington laws and regulations governing telehealth include – WASH. REV. CODE ANN. §§ 18.134.005 to 18.134.900 (West 2024) (uniform telehealth act); WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 18.64.600 (West 2024) (remote MOUD dispensing sites); WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 41.05.700 (West 2024) (public employees insurance coverage); WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 48.43.735 (West 2024) (health insurance coverage); WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 71.24.335 (West 2024) (behavioral health services); WASH. REV. CODE ANN. §§ 74.09.325 to 74.09.327 (West 2024) (Medicaid); WASH. ADMIN. CODE §§ 182-501-0300, 182-538-195, (2024) (Medicaid); WASH. ADMIN. CODE § 182-531-2040 (2024) (Medicaid – enhanced reimbursement for MOUD); WASH. ADMIN. CODE § 246-945-457 (2024)\n(remote MOUD dispensing sites).", "9A": "Commercial health insurance plans, including managed care Medicaid plans offered through commercial insurers are required to include pharmacists in provider networks and cover pharmacist-provided services. WASH. REV. CODE ANN. § 48.43.094 (West 2024). The above provision does not include Medicare or Medicaid fee-for-service plans, however.\nUnder the Medicaid program, researchers conclude that some pharmacist services are covered including vaccines, HIV/AIDS counseling/testing, tobacco/nicotine cessation counseling, and reproductive health.", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the Washington Medicaid program.\nSpecify in Washington laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a under a CDTA are covered under the Washington Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "There are Washington regulations for a variety of health care professionals governing the co-prescribing of opioids to patients receiving “medication assisted treatment” (MAT). WASH ADMIN. CODE §§ 246-817-976, 246-840-4970, 246-853-780, 246-918-925, 246-919-975, 246-922-780 (2024).\nThere are Washington regulations for a variety of health care professionals that prohibit the discontinuing of MAT when treating acute pain, particularly as to pregnant patients. WASH ADMIN. CODE §§ 246-817-913, 246-817-970, 246-840-4661, 246-840-4950, 246-853-695, 246-853-765, 246-918-835, 246-918-840, 246-918-910, 246-919-885, 246-919-890, 246-919-960, 246-922-695, 246-922-765 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/public-health-provider-resources/healthcare-professions-and-facilities/prescription-monitoring-program-pmp", "description": "Washington State Department of Health Prescription Monitoring Program (PMP) main page with registration instructions. Access is through the Secure Access Washington (SAW) security gateway."}, {"type": "note", "text": "PMP Login: Accessed via Secure Access Washington (SAW) at https://secureaccess.wa.gov. Users must create a SAW account, then add PMP access to query controlled substance dispensing data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PMP Data Exchange Information", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/public-health-provider-resources/healthcare-professions-and-facilities/data-exchange/prescription-monitoring", "description": "Information on PMP web portal access for providers who do not work with an EHR system, and details on EHR integration options."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Washington law requires practitioners to check the PMP before prescribing opioids for more than 3 days. Dispensers must report controlled substance dispensing data to the PMP. Email: prescriptionmonitoring@doh.wa.gov."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing / PMP InterConnect: Washington participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing, allowing authorized users to access prescription data from other participating states."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates can be registered through the PMP system. Authorized prescribers and dispensers may designate delegates to query the PMP on their behalf."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Quality Assurance Commission", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/licenses-permits-and-certificates/facilities-z/pharmacies-and-pharmaceutical-firms/commission-information", "description": "Washington State Pharmacy Quality Assurance Commission page within the Department of Health. The commission is composed of 16 members including pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, and public members."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act (RCW)", "url": "https://app.leg.wa.gov/rcw/default.aspx?cite=18.64", "description": "Full text of Revised Code of Washington (RCW) Chapter 18.64 (Pharmacists), the state Pharmacy Practice Act governing pharmacy regulation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Regulations (WAC)", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/regulations/washington/WAC-246-945-001", "description": "Washington Administrative Code (WAC) Chapter 246-945, Regulations governing pharmacy practice, including definitions, licensing requirements, and practice standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Drug Therapy Agreement Guidance", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/Documents/Pubs/690327.pdf", "description": "Washington State Pharmacy Quality Assurance Commission guidance document on Collaborative Drug Therapy Agreements (CDTAs). Washington statute allows a CDTA to authorize a pharmacist to prescribe any legend drug."}, {"type": "note", "text": "CDTA Regulations: WAC 246-945-350 governs collaborative drug therapy agreements. To exercise prescriptive authority, a pharmacist must have a valid CDTA on file with the commission and their practice location."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CDTA Review Form", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/sites/default/files/legacy/Documents/Pubs//690212.pdf", "description": "Collaborative Drug Therapy Agreement review form required by WAC 246-945-350, documenting the prescriptive authority delegated to named pharmacists."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Use Treatment (HCA)", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/free-or-low-cost-health-care/i-need-behavioral-health-support/opioid-use-treatment", "description": "Washington State Health Care Authority (HCA) page on opioid use treatment resources, including information on finding medication and behavioral health treatment for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Treatment Programs (HCA)", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/billers-providers-partners/program-information-providers/opioid-treatment-programs-otps", "description": "HCA information page on Opioid Treatment Programs using medications for opioid use disorder (MOUD) including buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Treatment Programs (DOH)", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/licenses-permits-and-certificates/facilities-z/behavioral-health-agencies-bha/opioid-treatment-programs", "description": "Department of Health page on OTP licensing requirements and information about buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone treatment options."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to find buprenorphine providers and OUD treatment facilities in Washington state. Search by location or ZIP code."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine: Washington follows federal DEA telehealth flexibilities for buprenorphine prescribing. Providers may prescribe buprenorphine via telehealth in accordance with temporary DEA extensions and state regulations. HCA covers telehealth-provided OUD treatment through Apple Health (Medicaid)."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Apple Health Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/billers-providers-partners/program-information-providers/apple-health-preferred-drug-list-pdl", "description": "Washington Apple Health (Medicaid) fee-for-service pharmacy drug coverage lists, including the Preferred Drug List with buprenorphine coverage information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "HCA Behavioral Health and Recovery", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/about-hca/programs-and-initiatives/behavioral-health-and-recovery", "description": "HCA page on behavioral health integration, including funding for substance use, mental health, and problem gambling services through community-based providers."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Opioid Response Grant", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/about-hca/programs-and-initiatives/behavioral-health-and-recovery/state-opioid-response-sor-grant", "description": "Washington's SOR grant program funded by SAMHSA to increase access to FDA-approved medications for OUD treatment, and to support the continuum of prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery services."}, {"type": "note", "text": "HCA Pharmacy Provider Information: HCA administers pharmacy benefits for Apple Health (Medicaid). Contact HCADBHRInformation@hca.wa.gov for behavioral health and recovery program information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WSPA Billing Resources", "url": "https://www.wsparx.org/", "description": "Washington State Pharmacy Association provides contracting, credentialing, and billing resources for pharmacist-provided patient care services through their Provider Status initiative."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy CE Requirements", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/licenses-permits-and-certificates/professions-new-renew-or-update/pharmacy-professions/continuing-education", "description": "Washington Department of Health page on pharmacist CE requirements. Pharmacists must complete 30 hours per renewal cycle. Required topics include 2 hours on controlled substances and opioid prescribing validation/counseling every two years, 2 hours on medication errors, and 1 hour on health equity."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Washington State Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://www.wsparx.org/", "description": "WSPA provides continuing education events, certifications, training programs, and online CE resources for Washington pharmacists. Includes live CE, technician CE, and health equity CE."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WSPA Advocacy", "url": "https://www.wsparx.org/general/custom.asp?page=Advocate", "description": "WSPA legislative and regulatory affairs page providing advocacy updates and resources for Washington pharmacists."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA FAQ on buprenorphine prescribing and registration requirements applicable to Washington practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders offering free training on buprenorphine prescribing and OUD treatment."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Service Programs", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/you-and-your-family/drug-user-health/syringe-service-programs", "description": "Washington DOH page on syringe service programs with state access recommendations and links to the SSP directory."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Syringe Service Program Directory", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/you-and-your-family/drug-user-health/syringe-service-programs/syringe-service-program-directory", "description": "Directory of syringe service programs in Washington state, searchable by county or program name."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Distribution", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/you-and-your-family/drug-user-health/overdose-education-naloxone-distribution", "description": "DOH Overdose Education and Naloxone Distribution page. Washington has a statewide standing order allowing pharmacies to dispense naloxone without an individual prescription. Free naloxone can be ordered online and delivered to homes through stopoverdose.org. Per RCW 69.41.095, anyone may carry and administer naloxone."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: Fentanyl test strips are legal in Washington state. Washington explicitly removed testing products, including fentanyl test strips, from the definition of drug paraphernalia. DOH distributes fentanyl and xylazine test strips through syringe service programs and other authorized outlets."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/data-and-statistical-reports/washington-tracking-network-wtn/opioids/overdose-dashboard", "description": "Washington DOH Opioid and Drug Use Data Dashboard with counts and rate trends for drug overdose deaths and ED visits among Washington state residents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug User Health Program", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/you-and-your-family/drug-user-health/drug-user-health-program", "description": "DOH Drug User Health Program page with contacts for drug user health policy, data inquiries, and SSP oversight."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Washington Recovery Help Line", "url": "https://www.warecoveryhelpline.org/", "description": "Washington Recovery Help Line (now operated by Crisis Connections) provides 24/7 confidential support for substance use and problem gambling. Call 1-866-789-1511."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://www.recoveryhousingwa.org/", "description": "Washington Recovery Housing Directory listing certified recovery residences accredited by the Washington Alliance for Quality Recovery Residences (WAQRR)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WAQRR", "url": "https://www.waqrr.org/", "description": "Washington Alliance for Quality Recovery Residences homepage with certification standards, operator resources, and recovery residence quality standards."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/about-hca/programs-and-initiatives/behavioral-health-and-recovery", "description": "Washington Health Care Authority Division of Behavioral Health and Recovery, administering state-funded substance use, mental health, and problem gambling services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DSHS Behavioral Health Administration", "url": "https://www.dshs.wa.gov/bha", "description": "Washington Department of Social and Health Services Behavioral Health Administration, supporting sustainable recovery, independence, and wellness."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Crisis Contacts: Washington Recovery Help Line: 1-866-789-1511 (24/7 confidential support). Crisis Connections: 1-866-427-4747. National 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline. Learn About Treatment", "url": "https://www.learnabouttreatment.org/treatment/resources/", "description": ""}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Quality Assurance Commission", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/licenses-permits-and-certificates/facilities-z/pharmacies-and-pharmaceutical-firms/commission-information", "description": "Washington State Pharmacy Quality Assurance Commission. Executive Director: Marlee O'Neill. Address: PO Box 47852, Olympia, WA 98504-7852."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Health Care Authority (Medicaid)", "url": "https://www.hca.wa.gov/", "description": "Washington State Health Care Authority administers Apple Health (Medicaid) programs. Contact: HCADBHRInformation@hca.wa.gov for behavioral health and recovery inquiries."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Washington DOH licenses Opioid Treatment Programs. Contact DOH Behavioral Health Agency licensing for OTP-related inquiries."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Washington State Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.wsparx.org/page/ContactUs", "description": "WSPA contact page for the state's primary professional pharmacy organization."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Department of Health Drug User Health", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/you-and-your-family/drug-user-health/drug-user-health-program", "description": "DOH Drug User Health Program contacts for policy, data, SSP oversight, and harm reduction inquiries."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Opioid and Drug Use Data Dashboard", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/data-and-statistical-reports/washington-tracking-network-wtn/opioids/overdose-dashboard", "description": "Washington DOH interactive data dashboard with counts and rate trends on opioid and drug overdose deaths, ED visits, and other substance use indicators among Washington residents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Unintentional Drug Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://doh.wa.gov/newsroom/new-doh-dashboard-details-drug-overdose-deaths-washington", "description": "DOH news page about the Unintentional Drug Overdose Data dashboard providing county-level data on overdose deaths and circumstances, including drug type and origin."}, {"type": "link", "title": "UW ADAI Research", "url": "https://adai.uw.edu/research_project/washington-state-opioid-response-sor-grant/", "description": "University of Washington Addictions, Drug and Alcohol Institute (ADAI) research on the Washington State Opioid Response Grant, providing evaluation, technical assistance, and substance use data analysis."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SOR Initiatives Brief", "url": "https://nasadad.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/Washington-SOR-Brief-Draft-2024_Final.pdf", "description": "NASADAD brief on Washington's State Opioid Response initiatives, including prevention, treatment, and recovery programs funded by SOR III."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Washington Tracking Network: The Washington Tracking Network provides access to environmental and health data, including substance use and overdose data at the county level, accessible through the DOH data dashboard."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Washington State Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://www.wsparx.org/general/custom.asp?page=Advocate", "description": "WSPA legislative and regulatory affairs page with advocacy updates, resources, and tools for Washington pharmacists to engage in policy advocacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Washington State Legislature", "url": "https://leg.wa.gov", "description": "Washington State Legislature homepage for tracking current legislation, including bills related to pharmacy practice, OUD treatment, and harm reduction."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your Legislator", "url": "https://leg.wa.gov/legislators", "description": "Tool to find Washington state Senators and Representatives by district, with links to contact information and voting records."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Legislators by Email", "url": "https://app.leg.wa.gov/memberemail/", "description": "Washington State Legislature page to send email messages directly to legislators. Legislative Hotline: 1-800-562-6000."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Washington State Opioid and Overdose Response: Washington implements a statewide Opioid and Overdose Response Plan through the Health Care Authority and Department of Health, coordinating prevention, treatment, and recovery efforts across state agencies."}]}]}, "westvirginia": {"name": "West Virginia", "q": {"CPA_Term": "West Virginia’s term for a CPA is a “collaborative pharmacy practice agreement” (CPPA). W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-4 (West 2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe scope of practice for a licensed pharmacist detailed by West Virginia law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10 (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in West Virginia cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the West Virginia scope of practice for a pharmacist to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow West Virginia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, West Virginia laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, the answer is likely “no.”\nThe scope of practice for a licensed pharmacist detailed by West Virginia law expressly includes “provid[ing] drug administration.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10(a)(3) (West 2024). This provision does not limit the drugs or medications for which a pharmacist can administer and therefore could mean that a pharmacist can administer buprenorphine generally.The scope of practice provision also directs that “a licensee meeting the requirements as promulgated by legislative rule may administer immunizations.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10(b) (West 2024). As a result, there are West Virginia regulations that expressly cover the administration of immunizations, including the training necessary to do it.\nW. VA. CODE R. §§ 15-12-1 to 15-12-8 (2024). There are no provisions in West Virginia pharmacy laws and regulations expressly addressing administration of other kinds of drugs or medications, including controlled substances.\nIf the general “provide drug administration” phrase in the scope of practice of a pharmacist section acts as a broad authorization to administer all drugs and medications, it is unclear why there would be specific more limited provisions in law or regulation. Accordingly, a pharmacist’s ability to administer drugs and medications in West Virginia may be limited and not cover buprenorphine.\nThe complicating factor, however, is that as described in the answer to the \"administering buprenorphine under a CPA\" section, West Virginia pharmacy laws prohibit collaborative pharmacy practice agreements (CPPAs) from managing controlled substances. Given this limitation, it seems unlikely that a West Virginia pharmacist would have more authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CPPA than within one.", "2B": "Understand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the West Virginia scope of practice for a pharmacist to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe scope of practice for a licensed pharmacist detailed by West Virginia law expressly includes “order[ing] laboratory tests in accordance with drug therapy management” (DTM). W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10(a)(13) (West 2024).\nHowever, the definition of DTM in West Virginia law provides that it is done “in accordance with the [CPPA].”\nW. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-4 (West 2024). As a result, this provision does not authorize ordering or evaluating lab tests outside of CPPA.\nOther than laws and regulations governing DTM and CPPAs, West Virginia pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the West Virginia scope of practice for a pharmacist to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe scope of practice for a licensed pharmacist detailed by West Virginia law expressly includes “provid[ing] pharmacist care in all areas of patient care, including collaborative pharmacy practice.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10(a)(13) (West 2024).\nHowever, a CPPA “may not include the management of controlled substances.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-19(d) (West 2024).", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise West Virginia laws and/or regulations to allow CPPAs to manage controlled substances.\nRevise West Virginia laws and/or regulations to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances under CPPAs.\nExpressly specify in West Virginia laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPPAs.\nAllow West Virginia pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe scope of practice for a licensed pharmacist detailed by West Virginia law expressly includes “provid[ing] pharmacist care in all areas of patient care, including collaborative pharmacy practice.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10(a)(13) (West 2024).\nHowever, a CPPA “may not include the management of controlled substances.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-19(d) (West 2024).", "5B": null, "5C": "Revise West Virginia laws and/or regulations to allow CPPAs to manage controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in West Virginia laws or regulations that pharmacists can administer controlled substances, or at least all forms of buprenorphine for SUD treatment, under a CPPA.", "6A": "Yes, based on the information described below, but only as to ordering tests.\nThe scope of practice for a licensed pharmacist detailed by West Virginia law expressly includes “order[ing] laboratory tests in accordance with [DTM].” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-10(a)(13) (West 2024). DTM is “the review of drug therapy regimens of patients by a pharmacist for the purpose of evaluating and rendering advice to a physician regarding adjustment of the regimen in accordance with the [CPPA].” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-4 (West 2024).\nWest Virginia law further indicates that DTM includes “ordering screening laboratory tests that are dose related and specific to the patient’s medication or are protocol driven and are also specifically set out in the [CPPA] between the pharmacist and physician.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-4 (West 2024).\nWest Virginia pharmacy laws and joint pharmacy/medicine regulations governing DTM and CPPAs do not expressly refer to pharmacists evaluating the results of lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a CPPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in West Virginia laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CPPA include evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CPPA is a written and signed agreement that is entered into between one or more pharmacists and “an individual physician or physician group, or for a medical provider in training where the agreement is signed by the supervising physician or chairperson of the medical department where the medical provider in training is practicing.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-4 (West 2024).\nThe following West Virginia laws and regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPPAs and required elements of CPPAs – W. VA. CODE ANN. §§ 30-5-18 to 30-5-19 (West 2024); W. VA. CODE R. §§ 11-8-1 to 11-8-9 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nWest Virginia’s general telehealth/telemedicine practice law authorizes telehealth services by “health care practitioners” and requires such practitioners’ regulatory boards to propose regulations governing the practice. W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-1-26 (West 2024).\nThe definition of “health care practitioner” includes a person authorized to practice under numerous sets of statutory provisions, including § 30-5-1 et seq., which covers pharmacists. W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-1-26(a) (West 2024).\nWest Virginia laws and regulations do address telepharmacy.", "8B": null, "8C": "West Virginia law provides that the standard of care for telehealth services adopted by regulatory boards must require an in-person visit within 12 months of initial telehealth visit. However, this requirement does not apply to, among other things, “addiction medicine.” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-1-26(b)(4) (West 2024)\nWest Virginia laws and regulations governing telehealth include – W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-1-26 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); W. VA. CODE ANN. § 5-16-7b (West 2024) (public employees insurance coverage); W. VA. CODE ANN. § 9-5-28 (West 2024) (Medicaid); W. VA.\nCODE ANN § 30-3-13a (West 2024) (physicians); W. VA. CODE ANN. § 30-5-4 (West 2024) (definition of telepharmacy); W. VA. CODE ANN. § 33-57-1 (West 2024) (health insurance); W. VA. CODE R. § 15-1-24 (2024) (telepharmacy); W. VA. CODE R. §§ 11-15-1 to 11-15-11 (2024) (physicians); W. VA. CODE R. §§ 19-16-1 to 19-16-11 (2024) (nurses).", "9A": "Commercial health plans, policies, contract or agreements issued after January 2021 may not deny benefits for any health care service performed by a licensed pharmacist if “(A) The service performed was within the lawful scope of the pharmacist’s license; (B) The plan would have provided benefits if the service had been performed by another health care provider; and (C) The pharmacist is included in the plan’s network of participating providers.”\nW. VA. CODE ANN. § 33-56-1(a)(1) (West 2024).\nThe above provision does not apply to the state Medicaid program, however. W. VA. CODE ANN. § 33-56-1(d) (West 2024).301", "9B": "Allow pharmacists to have “full provider” status under the West Virginia Medicaid program.\nExpressly specify in West Virginia laws and/or regulations that pharmacist services provided under a CPPA are covered under the West Virginia Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "The West Virginia Board of Pharmacy “shall notify a physician prescribing buprenorphine or buprenorphine/naloxone within 60 days of the availability of an abuse deterrent or a practitioner-administered form of buprenorphine or buprenorphine/naloxone if approved by the [FDA]. Upon receipt of the notice, a physician may switch his or her patients using buprenorphine or buprenorphine/naloxone to the abuse deterrent or a practitioner-administered form of the drug” W. VA. CODE ANN. § 60A-9-4(g) (West 2024).\nWest Virginia law contains a “medication-assisted treatment program” licensing act. W. VA. CODE ANN. §§ 16b-13-1 to 16b-13-13 (West 2024). The definition of the phrase “medication-assisted treatment program” includes both OTPs and “office based” programs. W. VA. CODE ANN. § 16b-13-2 (West 2024). The statutes cover, among other things, registration, operational requirements, minimum standards, and rules.\nThe West Virginia Department of Health and Human Services has a set of regulations related to “office-based medication-assisted treatment” or OBMAT. These regulations cover many areas, including registration, administrative organization, operations, staff training/credentialing, medication storage, admission criteria, required services, patient assessment, patient rights, counseling, treatment plans, administrative withdrawal, and drug screening. W. VA. CODE R. §§ 69-12-1 to 69-12-33 (2024)."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal (RxGov)", "url": "https://pmpwv.rxgov.com", "description": "West Virginia's new Controlled Substances Monitoring Program (CSMP) portal, powered by RxGov. The WV Board of Pharmacy transitioned from the legacy CSAPP platform to this upgraded system for improved performance and data quality."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSMP Program Information", "url": "https://www.csappwv.com/", "description": "Information about the WV CSMP transition from CSAPP to RxGov, including registration instructions and migration guidance for existing users."}, {"type": "note", "text": "PDMP Registration: New users who did not have a previously-approved CSAPP account should register at https://pmpwv.rxgov.com. Existing CSAPP users may need to create new RxGov accounts."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: West Virginia requires enrollment in and use of the CSMP for prescribers and dispensers of Schedule II, III, and IV controlled substances. The program is administered by the West Virginia Board of Pharmacy."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Interstate Data Sharing / PMP InterConnect: West Virginia participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing, allowing authorized users to access prescription data from other participating states."}, {"type": "note", "text": "CSMP Contact: Michael Goff, PMP Administrator, West Virginia Board of Pharmacy. Phone: (304) 558-0558. Email: michael.l.goff@wv.gov."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://www.wvbop.com/", "description": "West Virginia Board of Pharmacy homepage with information on practitioner licensing, applications, renewals, forms, continuing education requirements, and protocols."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Current Laws and Rules", "url": "https://www.wvbop.com/article.asp?id=13", "description": "WV Board of Pharmacy page linking to the West Virginia Code Chapter 30, Article 5 (Pharmacists, Pharmacies, Pharmacy Technicians, and Wholesale Drug Distributors), Chapter 60A (Uniform Controlled Substances Act), and all Board rules."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://code.wvlegislature.gov/30-5-4/", "description": "West Virginia Code Section 30-5-4 containing definitions for the pharmacy practice act, including collaborative pharmacy practice agreement provisions."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Board of Pharmacy Rules (CSR): West Virginia Board of Pharmacy Rules are found in Title 15 of the Code of State Rules (CSR), Series 1 through 13. Accessible at http://apps.sos.wv.gov/adlaw/csr/ by selecting \"Pharmacy\" in the Agency dropdown."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Pharmacy Practice Agreement", "url": "https://code.wvlegislature.gov/30-5-4/", "description": "West Virginia Code defines \"collaborative pharmacy practice agreement\" as a written and signed physician-directed agreement between a physician or physician group and an individual pharmacist for drug therapy management. Joint rules exist under Title 11, Series 8 (Boards of Medicine, Osteopathy, and Pharmacy)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Laws Compilation", "url": "https://www.wvbop.com/download_resource.asp?id=329", "description": "Downloadable compilation of pharmacy laws and legislative rules of West Virginia governing pharmacy practice, including scope of practice provisions at WV Code Section 30-5-10."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Help and Hope WV", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/", "description": "West Virginia's comprehensive resource website for substance use disorder information, treatment resources, naloxone access, and recovery support. Includes the Help4WV helpline: 1-844-Help-4-WV."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Help and Hope WV Treatment Locator", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/get-help.html", "description": "Page linking to treatment resources including the ATLAS Addiction Treatment Locator (treatmentatlas.org) for finding and comparing treatment facilities in West Virginia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Office of Drug Control Policy", "url": "https://odcp.wv.gov/", "description": "West Virginia Office of Drug Control Policy (ODCP) within the Department of Human Services, created by the 2017 Drug Control Policy Act. Oversees drug overdose surveillance, treatment resources, and policy responses."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to find buprenorphine providers and OUD treatment facilities in West Virginia."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing: West Virginia Medicaid covers buprenorphine-naloxone and buprenorphine through the pharmacy program when prescribed by any enrolled prescriber with a valid DEA on record. West Virginia Board of Pharmacy provides protocols and guidance for pharmacist involvement in OUD care."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth and Buprenorphine: West Virginia follows federal DEA telehealth flexibilities for controlled substance prescribing. The DEA has extended telemedicine flexibilities through December 31, 2026, allowing continued telehealth prescribing of buprenorphine."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "WV Medicaid Pharmacy", "url": "https://bms.wv.gov/providers/pharmacy", "description": "West Virginia Bureau for Medical Services (BMS) pharmacy provider page with information on pharmacy benefits, SMAC pricing, buprenorphine coverage (Suboxone policy), newsletters, and claim processing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://bms.wv.gov/preferred-drug-list-and-coverage-details", "description": "WV Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) recommended by the Pharmaceutical and Therapeutics Committee. Includes buprenorphine products with coverage details."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Provider Manual", "url": "https://bms.wv.gov/media/22021/download?inline=", "description": "BMS Pharmacy Services Chapter 518 Provider Manual with detailed billing guidance, coverage policies for buprenorphine-naloxone and buprenorphine products, and prior authorization requirements."}, {"type": "note", "text": "BMS Provider Information: BMS administers West Virginia Medicaid pharmacy benefits. Address: Bureau for Medical Services, 350 Capitol Street, Room 251, Charleston, WV 25301."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Grant and Funding Opportunities: West Virginia receives substantial federal funding through SAMHSA's State Opioid Response (SOR) grants. The ODCP oversees distribution of opioid abatement funds. Contact ODCP at https://odcp.wv.gov/ for current funding opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "WV CE Requirements", "url": "https://www.wvbop.com/practitioners/status/app/continuingeducation.asp", "description": "West Virginia Board of Pharmacy CE requirements page. Pharmacists must complete 30 hours of CE every 2 years, including a minimum of 2 hours on drug diversion training and best practice prescribing of controlled substances, and 6 hours through live presentations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WV Pharmacist Renewal Requirements", "url": "https://www.wvbop.com/practitioners/pharmacists/renew/index.asp", "description": "Board of Pharmacy pharmacist renewal page with CE requirements, including mandatory drug diversion and controlled substance training."}, {"type": "link", "title": "West Virginia Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://wvpharmacy.org/", "description": "The West Virginia Pharmacists Association (WVPA) represents licensed pharmacists, pharmacy technicians, and pharmacy students statewide, providing education and advocacy resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://deadiversion.usdoj.gov/faq/buprenorphine-faq.html", "description": "DEA FAQ on buprenorphine prescribing and registration requirements applicable to West Virginia practitioners."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "Provider Clinical Support System for Medications for Opioid Use Disorders offering free training modules, webinars, and clinical guidance on buprenorphine prescribing and OUD treatment."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Harm Reduction Programs", "url": "https://oeps.wv.gov/harm_reduction/pages/default.aspx", "description": "West Virginia Office of Epidemiology and Prevention Services harm reduction programs page. Harm reduction programs have operated in WV since 2011, providing sterile syringes, collecting used syringes, and connecting people to prevention, testing, and treatment services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WV Harm Reduction Programs Directory", "url": "https://oeps.wv.gov/harm_reduction/documents/about/wv_hrp.pdf", "description": "PDF overview of West Virginia Harm Reduction Programs (HRPs) at-a-glance, including certified and non-certified program locations and services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Standing Order", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/naloxone.html", "description": "Help and Hope WV naloxone page. West Virginia has a statewide standing order for naloxone distribution to persons at risk of opioid overdose, family members, friends, and others in a position to assist."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WV Naloxone Standing Order Document", "url": "https://dhhr.wv.gov/office-of-drug-control-policy/news/Documents/2020%20ED%20Naloxone%20Toolkit/Standing%20Order%20for%20Naloxone%20Eligible%20Receipent%20Organizations%2008.10.2021%20-%20FINAL.pdf", "description": "West Virginia statewide standing order for the distribution of naloxone by eligible recipient organizations."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Access: West Virginia has removed fentanyl test strips from the definition of drug paraphernalia. Harm reduction programs provide fentanyl test strips along with other supplies. Contact local harm reduction programs for availability."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://odcp.wv.gov/page/overdose-dashboard", "description": "ODCP overdose dashboard displaying suspected overdose events using the most current data. The dashboard tracks drug overdose surveillance information compiled by the Office of Drug Control Policy."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "HELP4WV", "url": "https://www.help4wv.com/", "description": "HELP4WV offers a 24/7 call, chat, and text line (1-844-Help-4-WV) for any West Virginian struggling with addiction or mental health issues. Many helpline staff are peer-support specialists or recovery coaches with personal recovery experience."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://wvarr.org/", "description": "West Virginia Alliance of Recovery Residences (WVARR) homepage with a recovery housing guide, certification information, and directory of WVARR-certified residences that have completed application review and on-site inspections."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Help and Hope WV Recovery Resources", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/people-recover.html", "description": "Help and Hope WV page on recovery support with information about recovery residences, peer support services, and community-based recovery resources in West Virginia."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Bureau for Behavioral Health", "url": "https://bbh.wv.gov/", "description": "West Virginia Bureau for Behavioral Health (BBH) homepage. BBH works to advance access and quality of statewide behavioral health services including substance use disorder treatment and recovery support."}, {"type": "link", "title": "BBH Programs and Resources", "url": "https://bbh.wv.gov/bbh-programs", "description": "BBH programs page with information on available behavioral health services, crisis support (988 Lifeline), and recovery resources."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: HELP4WV: 1-844-Help-4-WV (call or text 24/7). National 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline: dial 988. Crisis Text Line: text HOME to 741741."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "West Virginia Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://www.wvbop.com/", "description": "WV Board of Pharmacy. Executive Director and CSMP Administrator: Michael L. Goff. Address: 1207 Quarrier St., 4th Floor, Charleston, WV 25301. Phone: (304) 558-0558."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Bureau for Medical Services (Medicaid)", "url": "https://bms.wv.gov/", "description": "West Virginia Bureau for Medical Services administering Medicaid programs. Address: 350 Capitol Street, Room 251, Charleston, WV 25301."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Office of Drug Control Policy", "url": "https://odcp.wv.gov/", "description": "ODCP within the Department of Human Services, overseeing drug overdose surveillance, opioid policy, and treatment resource coordination."}, {"type": "link", "title": "West Virginia Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://wvpharmacy.org/", "description": "WVPA represents pharmacists, technicians, and students in West Virginia, providing advocacy, education, and professional development."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Help and Hope WV Prescriber Resources", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/prescribers.html", "description": "Help and Hope WV prescriber resource page with CSMP contact information, treatment tools, and prescriber education resources."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ODCP Overdose Dashboard", "url": "https://odcp.wv.gov/page/overdose-dashboard", "description": "West Virginia Office of Drug Control Policy overdose dashboard with suspected overdose event data compiled using current technology and methodology."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ODCP Data Dashboards", "url": "https://odcp.wv.gov/data-dashboards", "description": "ODCP data dashboards page with links to overdose data resources, including the CDC DOSE Dashboard for nonfatal overdose data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "CSMP Data Dashboard", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/prescribers.html", "description": "Access to the West Virginia Controlled Substance Monitoring Program 2014-2018 Data Dashboard through the Help and Hope WV prescriber resources page."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WV SUDORS Annual Report", "url": "https://dhhr.wv.gov/vip/SiteAssets/SUDORS_Annual_Report_January2023.pdf", "description": "West Virginia State Unintentional Drug Overdose Reporting System (SUDORS) annual report with drug class and metabolite trends, including fentanyl and fentanyl metabolites in the illicit drug supply."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Help and Hope WV Resources", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/resources.html", "description": "Comprehensive resource page with links to WV-specific and national opioid data, prevention, and response resources, including collaboration between WV Board of Pharmacy, WV Violence and Injury Prevention Program, and WVU Injury Control Research Center."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "West Virginia Pharmacists Association", "url": "https://wvpharmacy.org/", "description": "WVPA provides advocacy and legislative representation for pharmacists in West Virginia, working on pharmacy practice issues and OUD treatment legislation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "West Virginia Independent Pharmacy Association", "url": "https://www.wvipa.org/", "description": "WVIPA educates state legislators, congressional leaders, and the public on the significance of independent pharmacies and their contributions to community health."}, {"type": "link", "title": "West Virginia Legislature", "url": "https://www.wvlegislature.gov/", "description": "West Virginia Legislature homepage for tracking legislation, including bills related to pharmacy practice, collaborative practice agreements, and OUD treatment."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Find Your WV Legislator", "url": "https://home.wvlegislature.gov/directories-info-packets/", "description": "WV Legislature directories and information packets page with legislator contact information, district maps, and comprehensive reference tools for constituents."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Office of Drug Control Policy", "url": "https://odcp.wv.gov/", "description": "ODCP serves as the state's central coordinating body for drug policy, overdose surveillance, and substance use response, implementing the WV Drug Control Policy Act."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Help and Hope WV", "url": "https://helpandhopewv.org/", "description": "Comprehensive state resource hub for substance use prevention, treatment, recovery, and data, maintained in collaboration with the WV Board of Pharmacy and partner organizations."}]}]}, "wisconsin": {"name": "Wisconsin", "q": {"CPA_Term": "Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly address collaborative practice or drug therapy management. As a result, the laws/regulations neither use the phrase CPA nor clearly use any other phrase in its place. However, Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do refer to “delegation” of patient care services by a physician to a pharmacist and require that it be documented. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.033 (West 2024); WIS. ADMIN. CODE PHAR. § 7.12 (2024).", "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Wisconsin law does not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.01(16) (West 2024).\nThe above point is consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Wisconsin cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the Wisconsin practice of pharmacy to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Wisconsin pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Wisconsin law includes “administering prescribed drug products and devices under [§] 450.035(1r) and vaccines.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.01(16)(k) (West 2024).\nThe referenced Wisconsin subsection provides that “a pharmacist may not administer by injection a prescribed drug product or device unless he or she has successfully completed a course of study and training” set out in the law. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.035(lr) (West 2024). Because this provision relates only to administering by injection, it is unclear from it if a pharmacist can administer a prescribed drug product in a manner other than by injection.However, Wisconsin pharmacy regulations make it clear that a pharmacist’s authorization to administer a drug product is not limited to administering by injection. WIS. ADMIN. CODE PHAR. § 7.13(2), (3) (2024).\nA “drug product” is “a specific drug or drugs in a specific dosage form and strength from a known source of manufacture.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.01(11) (West 2024).\nFurther, the definition of “administer” in Wisconsin law expressly includes a pharmacist as an authorized individual. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.01(1)(c) (West 2024).", "2B": "Obtain a prescription for the drug product.\nAdhere to the education, training and recordkeeping requirements in Wisconsin law and regulations. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.035 (West 2024); WIS. ADMIN. CODE PHAR. § 7.13 (2024).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": null, "3A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe definition of the “practice of pharmacy” in Wisconsin law does not expressly refer to ordering lab tests or evaluating the results. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.01(16) (West 2024).\nMoreover, no other Wisconsin pharmacy laws or regulations address ordering or evaluating lab tests.", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the Wisconsin practice of pharmacy to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nWisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, Wisconsin law provides that “a pharmacist may perform any patient care service delegated to the pharmacist by a physician.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.033 (West 2024). Online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Wisconsin pursuant to this delegation authority.\nNo Wisconsin laws or regulations define the phrase “patient care service.” Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations also do not further describe the scope of services that can be delegated by a physician. As a result, although not clear, it is possible this provision allows a physician to delegate prescribing authority to a pharmacist.\nNevertheless, Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a Wisconsin pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what a physician delegates.\nIn summary, Wisconsin law does not address collaborative practice and does not clearly address the scope of physician delegation to pharmacists. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Wisconsin pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Wisconsin laws and/or regulations to expressly address collaborative pharmacy practice.\nRevise Wisconsin laws and/or regulations to expressly allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances pursuant to physician delegation. Expressly specify in Wisconsin laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under physician delegation.\nAllow Wisconsin pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Wisconsin laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section, the answer is likely “yes.”\nWisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, Wisconsin law provides that “a pharmacist may perform any patient care service delegated to the pharmacist by a physician.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.033 (West 2024). Online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Wisconsin pursuant to this delegation authority.\nNo Wisconsin laws or regulations define the phrase “patient care service.” Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations also do not further describe the scope of services that can be delegated by a physician. As a result, although not clear, it is possible this provision allows a physician to delegate administering authority to a pharmacist.\nNevertheless, given the response to the \"independent administration of buprenorphine\" section that a pharmacist has general authority to administer any prescribed drug product, the logical answer to this question is “yes.”", "5B": "Enter into a documented delegation arrangement with a physician (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, independent administration, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Although not completely necessary, expressly specify, either in new Wisconsin laws and/or regulations about collaborative practice or current law governing delegation, what duties can be delegated to a pharmacist and that those duties include administering controlled substances, or at least buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Wisconsin laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nWisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, Wisconsin law provides that “a pharmacist may perform any patient care service delegated to the pharmacist by a physician.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.033 (West 2024). Online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Wisconsin pursuant to this delegation authority.\nNo Wisconsin laws or regulations define the phrase “patient care service.” Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations also do not further describe the scope of services that can be delegated by a physician. As a result, although not clear, it is possible this provision allows a physician to delegate to a pharmacist the authority to order and evaluate the results of lab tests.", "6B": "Enter into a documented delegation arrangement with a physician (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Wisconsin laws and/or regulations what duties can be delegated by a physician to a pharmacist and that those duties include ordering and evaluating the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "Wisconsin pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly mention collaborative practice, drug therapy management, medication therapy management or written agreements or protocols for those acts.\nHowever, Wisconsin law provides that “a pharmacist may perform any patient care service delegated to the pharmacist by a physician” as the term “physician” is defined by Wisconsin law. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.033 (West 2024). Online sources suggest that collaborative practice and CPAs are allowable in Wisconsin pursuant to this delegation authority.\nWisconsin regulation requires the pharmacist to “document the delegation” prior to starting the delegated act(s). WIS. ADMIN. CODE PHAR. § 7.12 (2024).\nWisconsin laws and regulations provide no other information about delegation by physicians or contents of the documentation besides the little that is located at WIS. STAT. ANN. § 450.033 (West 2024) and WIS. ADMIN. CODE PHAR. § 7.12 (2024).", "8A": "Yes, based on the information described below.\nWisconsin does not have a full general telehealth/telemedicine practice act. Wisconsin law does contain a definition of “telehealth” that applies to all occupations regulated by the Wisconsin Department of Safety and Professional Licensing (Department), which includes pharmacists. WIS. STAT. ANN. § 440.001(hm) (West 2024). The definition does not restrict the health care providers to whom this applies.\nMoreover, Wisconsin law requires the referenced definition for telehealth be used “if the department, an examining board, or an affiliated credentialing board promulgates rules related to telehealth.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 440.17 (West 2024).\nAccording to the Department in 2020, “the practice of telehealth is generally allowed under existing Wisconsin law unless there is some profession specific requirement or restriction.”\nThere are no Wisconsin pharmacy laws or regulations that appear to restrict telehealth.", "8B": "Although not completely necessary, revise Wisconsin laws and/or regulations to provide a full general telehealth/telemedicine practice act applicable to all healthcare providers, including pharmacists.", "8C": "Wisconsin laws and regulations governing telehealth include – WIS. STAT. ANN. §§ 440.001, 440.17 (West 2024)\n(telehealth generally); WIS. STAT. ANN. § 440.094 (West 2024) (out of state providers); WIS. STAT. ANN. §§ 49.45(61), 49.46 (West 2024) (Medicaid); WIS. ADMIN. CODE DHS § 107.02(05) (2024) (Medicaid); WIS. ADM.\nCODE MED. §§ 24.01 to 24.07 (2024) (physicians).", "9A": "Wisconsin law provides that the Medicaid program “shall provide reimbursement for services that are reimbursable under this section and that are provided by a licensed pharmacist within the scope of his or her license or are services performed under s. 450.033.” WIS. STAT. ANN. § 49.46(2)(bh) (West 2024) (Medicaid).310\nPharmacists can bill Medicaid for services outside of the scope of practice if the pharmacist has a CPA with a physician that allows the pharmacist to provide the service.", "9B": null, "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "Wisconsin has a regulation pertaining to the provision of “office-based opioid treatment” or OBOT. The regulations do not apply to a “primary care service” or a service providing MOUD to less than 30 patients. WIS. ADMIN. CODE DHS § 75.60 (2024). The regulation addresses, among other things, general requirements, assessment, treatment plans, and prescribing requirements."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Portal", "url": "https://pdmp.wi.gov/", "description": "The Wisconsin Enhanced Prescription Drug Monitoring Program (ePDMP) portal. Provides valuable information about monitored prescription drugs dispensed in the state to aid healthcare professionals in prescribing and dispensing decisions. Administered by the Department of Safety and Professional Services (DSPS)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Registration", "url": "https://pdmp.wi.gov/registration", "description": "Registration page for healthcare professionals, law enforcement agents, pharmacists, and other authorized users to create an ePDMP account. Users select their role type (Healthcare Professional, Pharmacy/Dispensing Practitioner, etc.) to begin the registration process."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Training Materials", "url": "https://pdmp.wi.gov/training-materials", "description": "Training materials and user guides for the Wisconsin ePDMP system. Includes information on registering, querying the system, and setting up delegate accounts."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Wisconsin requires prescribers to check the ePDMP before prescribing monitored drugs. Dispensers are required to report dispensing data for Schedule II-V controlled substances. Wisconsin participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing, allowing out-of-state practitioners to query Wisconsin patient data through their home state PDMP."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Delegates do not register themselves in the Wisconsin ePDMP system. A prescriber or pharmacist must add delegates through their own account. Delegate accounts allow authorized staff to query the PDMP on behalf of the practitioner. See training materials at https://pdmp.wi.gov/training-materials for instructions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Statistics", "url": "https://pdmp.wi.gov/statistics", "description": "Wisconsin ePDMP statistics page providing data on prescription drug monitoring activity in the state."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://dsps.wi.gov/pages/BoardsCouncils/Pharmacy/Default.aspx", "description": "Wisconsin Pharmacy Examining Board homepage, housed within the Department of Safety and Professional Services (DSPS). The Board consists of 5 licensed pharmacist members and 2 public members appointed by the Governor. Phone: (608) 266-2112. Email: dsps@wi.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Practice Act", "url": "https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/statutes/statutes/450", "description": "Wisconsin Statutes Chapter 450 - Pharmacy Examining Board. The full text of the Wisconsin Pharmacy Practice Act, including provisions on licensing, pharmacy practice, continuing education, and regulation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/code/admin_code/phar", "description": "Wisconsin Administrative Code chapters related to pharmacy (Phar), including Phar 6 (Pharmacy Licenses and Equipment) and Phar 7 (Practice of Pharmacy). Contains the detailed administrative rules governing pharmacy practice in Wisconsin."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Rules and Statutes Page (DSPS)", "url": "https://dsps.wi.gov/Pages/RulesStatutes/Pharmacy.aspx", "description": "DSPS page listing relevant Wisconsin statutes and administrative code chapters for pharmacy, including Chapter 15, Chapter 440, Chapter 450, and Chapter 961 (Uniform Controlled Substances Act)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Collaborative Practice Agreement Resources", "url": "https://www.pswi.org/Resources/Toolkits-Manuals/Collaborative-Practice-Toolkit", "description": "Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin (PSW) Collaborative Practice Toolkit. Wisconsin law allows collaborative practice agreements (CPAs) between pharmacists and physicians. CPAs improve the efficiency of collaborative care delivery and expand available services to patients."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Wisconsin does not have broad independent pharmacist prescribing authority. Pharmacists may provide expanded patient care services under collaborative practice agreements with physicians as authorized under Wisconsin Pharmacy Practice Act provisions. The PSW has advocated for pharmacist provider status."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Opioid Treatment and Recovery Page", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/treatment-recovery.htm", "description": "Wisconsin Department of Health Services (DHS) page on opioid use disorder treatment and recovery options, including information on methadone, buprenorphine, naltrexone, clinical supports, peer supports, and recovery residences."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator (FindTreatment.gov) to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Wisconsin, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD treatment. Can be filtered by state."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA) Contact: Mike York, Department of Health Services, 1 W. Wilson St., Room 850, Madison, WI 53703. Phone: (608) 469-9317. Email: michael.york@dhs.wisconsin.gov", "description": "Wisconsin's designated State Opioid Treatment Authority contact as listed by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA SOTA Directory", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/opioid-treatment-program/sota", "description": "SAMHSA's full directory of State Opioid Treatment Authorities by state, including Wisconsin's SOTA contact information."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), healthcare providers no longer need an X-waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of DEA registration or renewal. Wisconsin does not impose additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law. Any healthcare professional may prescribe buprenorphine."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine: Wisconsin follows federal DEA telehealth regulations for prescribing buprenorphine. The WORTH IT program operated by Rogers Behavioral Health provides access to buprenorphine through telehealth. Call 844-582-7827 or email worthit@rogersbh.org."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Addiction Recovery Helpline", "url": "https://addictionhelpwi.org", "description": "Statewide resource for finding treatment services and recovery supports. Free service available 24/7. Call 211 or 833-944-4673."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Resources for Professionals", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/professionals.htm", "description": "DHS page with guidance for doctors, nurses, and pharmacists on addressing the opioid epidemic, including prescribing guidelines, treatment options, and links to naloxone resources."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "ForwardHealth Medicaid Portal", "url": "https://www.forwardhealth.wi.gov/WIPortal/", "description": "The ForwardHealth Portal serves as the interface for Wisconsin Medicaid, BadgerCare Plus, SeniorCare, and other state health programs. Providers access claims, prior authorization, and program information through this portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ForwardHealth Pharmacy Resources", "url": "https://www.forwardhealth.wi.gov/WIPortal/content/provider/medicaid/pharmacy/resources.htm.spage", "description": "ForwardHealth pharmacy provider resources page, including links to the Preferred Drug List, pharmacy billing information, and policy updates."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.forwardhealth.wi.gov/WIPortal/Subsystem/KW/Print.aspx?ia=1&p=1&sa=48&s=3&c=345&nt=", "description": "ForwardHealth Prior Authorization and Preferred Drug List information for Wisconsin Medicaid, BadgerCare Plus, and SeniorCare programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine Prior Authorization (Opioid Dependency Agents)", "url": "https://www.forwardhealth.wi.gov/WIPortal/Subsystem/KW/Print.aspx?ia=1&p=1&sa=48&s=3&c=345&nt=Opioid+Dependency+Agents", "description": "ForwardHealth policy page for opioid dependency agents including buprenorphine. Preferred buprenorphine drugs do not require PA. Non-preferred buprenorphine-naloxone drugs require submission of a PA/PDL form signed by the prescriber, submitted via the pharmacy. PA requests for non-preferred drugs may be approved for up to 365 days."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Buprenorphine PA Form", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/forms/f00081-0118.pdf", "description": "Prior Authorization/Preferred Drug List form for Opioid Dependency Agents - Buprenorphine (Form F-00081). Required for non-preferred buprenorphine products under Wisconsin Medicaid."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDL Quick Reference", "url": "https://www.forwardhealth.wi.gov/wiportal/content/provider/medicaid/pharmacy/pdl/pdfs/quickref010125v4.pdf.spage", "description": "Wisconsin Medicaid, BadgerCare Plus Standard, and SeniorCare Preferred Drug List Quick Reference document listing preferred and non-preferred drugs."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State-Specific Pharmacist Billing Codes: Wisconsin Medicaid (ForwardHealth) does not currently have a comprehensive set of billing codes specific to pharmacist-provided clinical services beyond dispensing. New coverage for peer recovery support services was announced in ForwardHealth Update 2026-05. Contact ForwardHealth for specific pharmacist service billing guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Wisconsin receives approximately $16.9 million annually through the SAMHSA State Opioid Response (SOR) grant, administered by DHS. The state also receives opioid settlement funds. DHS has awarded over $8 million in grants for opioid and stimulant treatment services. A $2 million Recovery Voucher grant program is funded by opioid settlement dollars. See https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/news/releases/042523.htm for details."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://dsps.wi.gov/Pages/Professions/Pharmacist/CE.aspx", "description": "DSPS page on pharmacist continuing education requirements. Wisconsin requires 30 hours of ACPE-approved continuing education per biennial renewal cycle (6/1/even year to 5/31/even year). Includes credits earned in ACPE-approved post-graduate degree programs."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin Education", "url": "https://www.pswi.org/Education", "description": "PSW education page offering continuing education courses, professional conferences, and online CE options for pharmacists and pharmacy technicians in Wisconsin."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PSW Journal CE", "url": "https://www.pswi.org/Education/Journal-CE", "description": "The Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin offers online continuing education credit through The Journal of the Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin. Includes pharmacist and technician CE options."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS provides free training on medications for opioid use disorder, including training options that meet the DEA 8-hour MATE Act education requirement. Funded by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division website for DEA registration, practitioner resources, and controlled substance regulations relevant to buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "UW Addiction Consultation Provider Hotline", "url": "https://www.fammed.wisc.edu/addiction-provider-line/", "description": "University of Wisconsin hotline open to all healthcare professionals seeking guidance on supporting patients with opioid use disorder treatment needs. Provides consultation on next steps for patient care."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Wisconsin does not impose state-specific board-approved SUD or buprenorphine training requirements beyond the federal MATE Act 8-hour training. ACPE-accredited programs are accepted for CE credit."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Wisconsin does not have a comprehensive statewide syringe services program law, but local programs exist. Public Health Madison and Dane County operates a syringe services program. Mail-based syringe access is available through a partnership with Gwayakobimaadiziwin/Bad River Harm Reduction via NEXT Distro."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro Wisconsin", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/wisconsin", "description": "NEXT Distro page for Wisconsin providing harm reduction information, free naloxone by mail, fentanyl test strips by mail, and mail-based syringe access through Bad River Harm Reduction partnership."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Madison Dane County Syringe Services Program", "url": "https://publichealthmdc.com/your-health/syringe-services-program", "description": "Public Health Madison and Dane County syringe services program providing sterile syringes, fentanyl and xylazine drug checking strips, naloxone, safer smoking equipment, sharps disposal, and harm reduction referrals."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Standing Order for Pharmacists", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/standing-orders.htm", "description": "DHS page on statewide naloxone standing orders. The standing order delegates authority to pharmacists to dispense naloxone without a prescription to patients at risk of opioid overdose or to individuals in a position to assist someone at risk. Covers standard dose intranasal naloxone (4mg/0.1ml) and intramuscular naloxone (0.4mg/ml)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access and Distribution", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/aoda/naloxone.htm", "description": "DHS comprehensive naloxone page with maps showing free naloxone locations, pharmacies dispensing naloxone under the standing order, information on obtaining and administering naloxone, and resources for agencies seeking community distribution supplies."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Wisconsin legalized fentanyl test strips in 2022, removing them from the definition of drug paraphernalia. DHS distributes free fentanyl and xylazine test strips. Free test strips are available by mail through NEXT Distro and at various local health departments and harm reduction sites."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DHS Xylazine Test Strips and Naloxone Standing Order Renewal", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/news/releases/090925.htm", "description": "September 2025 DHS announcement about distribution of free xylazine test strips and renewal of the statewide naloxone standing order for pharmacies."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data and Surveillance", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/dashboards.htm", "description": "DHS opioid data summary dashboard providing interactive visualizations of opioid use data in Wisconsin, including deaths, hospitalizations, treatment data, and usage trends."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Peer Services Homepage", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/peer-services/index.htm", "description": "Wisconsin DHS peer services page covering peer recovery support services, peer specialist certifications, peer recovery centers, and peer-run respites. Wisconsin has two types of peer specialist certifications: Certified Peer Specialist and Certified Parent Peer Specialist."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Specialist Certifications", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/peer-services/peer-specialists.htm", "description": "DHS page on certified peer specialist and certified parent peer specialist training, scope of practice, code of ethics, and core competencies in Wisconsin."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Peer Specialist Employment Initiative", "url": "https://www.wicps.org/", "description": "The Wisconsin Peer Specialist Employment Initiative promotes training, certification, and hiring of Certified Peer Specialists and Certified Parent Peer Specialists and supports expansion of peer support services statewide."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Recovery Centers", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/peer-services/peer-recovery-centers.htm", "description": "DHS directory of peer recovery centers across Wisconsin. Eleven locations where adults in recovery from mental health and substance use challenges can receive drop-in peer support in a safe, judgment-free space. No appointment necessary."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Housing Directory", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/guide/recovresdir.pdf", "description": "Wisconsin Recovery Residence Directory (PDF) maintained by DHS. Lists recovery housing options throughout the state for drug-free supportive housing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Recovery Voucher Grant Program", "url": "https://energyandhousing.wi.gov/Pages/AgencyResources/RecoveryVoucherGrant.aspx", "description": "Wisconsin's $2 million Recovery Voucher (RV) grant program funded by opioid settlement dollars, providing housing support for individuals in substance use recovery."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Behavioral Health Agency", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/", "description": "Wisconsin Department of Health Services (DHS) homepage. DHS is the state's primary agency for health and human services, including behavioral health, substance use disorder treatment, and Medicaid."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: Wisconsin Addiction Recovery Helpline available 24/7 at 211 or 833-944-4673. Website: https://addictionhelpwi.org. The 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline is also available 24/7."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Pharmacy Examining Board", "url": "https://dsps.wi.gov/pages/BoardsCouncils/Pharmacy/Default.aspx", "description": "Pharmacy Examining Board, Department of Safety and Professional Services, PO Box 8366, Madison, WI 53708-8366. Phone: (608) 266-2112. Email: dsps@wi.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Medicaid (ForwardHealth)", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/forwardhealth/index.htm", "description": "Wisconsin ForwardHealth (Medicaid) homepage at DHS. ForwardHealth administers Medicaid, BadgerCare Plus, SeniorCare, and other health programs. Provider services line: 1-800-947-9627."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority: Mike York, Department of Health Services, 1 W. Wilson St., Room 850, Madison, WI 53703. Phone: (608) 469-9317. Email: michael.york@dhs.wisconsin.gov"}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin", "url": "https://www.pswi.org/", "description": "Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin (PSW). Vice President of Public Policy and Advocacy: Danielle Womack (dwomack@pswi.org). PSW provides a unified voice, resources, and leadership to advance the pharmacy profession in Wisconsin."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Health Department Opioid Program", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/professionals.htm", "description": "DHS opioid resources page for professionals. Dose of Reality is a joint DHS and DOJ campaign addressing the opioid epidemic in Wisconsin. Contact DHS Division of Care and Treatment Services for program inquiries."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Data and Reports", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/data-reports-studies.htm", "description": "Comprehensive DHS page with links to dashboards, reports, studies, and data related to opioid use in Wisconsin. Includes death, hospitalization, usage, and treatment data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioid Data Summary Dashboard", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/dashboards.htm", "description": "Interactive dashboard providing summary visualizations of opioid-related data in Wisconsin including deaths, hospitalizations, and treatment metrics."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Deaths by County", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/deaths-county.htm", "description": "Interactive dashboard showing opioid overdose death data by county in Wisconsin."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Deaths Dashboard", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/aoda/drug-overdose-deaths.htm", "description": "DHS dashboard on drug overdose deaths in Wisconsin, covering opioid and non-opioid drug categories."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WISH Opioid Overdose Deaths Module", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/wish/opioid/data.htm", "description": "Wisconsin Interactive Statistics on Health (WISH) Query System opioid overdose deaths module with data from 2000 to 2023."}, {"type": "link", "title": "WISH Opioid Hospital Encounters Module", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/wish/opioid/hospital-encounters.htm", "description": "WISH Query System module for opioid-related hospital encounters data."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin SOARR System", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/aoda/wisoarr.htm", "description": "Wisconsin Suspected Overdose Alerts for Rapid Response (WISOARR) system providing near real-time data on suspected drug overdoses to inform community rapid response actions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Treatment by County", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/treatment-data-county.htm", "description": "Interactive dashboard showing opioid treatment data by county in Wisconsin, useful for identifying treatment gaps."}, {"type": "link", "title": "ePDMP Statistics", "url": "https://pdmp.wi.gov/statistics", "description": "Wisconsin ePDMP statistics page with data on prescription drug monitoring activity statewide."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Society of Wisconsin Advocacy", "url": "https://www.pswi.org/Advocacy", "description": "PSW advocacy page providing legislative updates, policy resources, and tools for pharmacists to engage with the Wisconsin State Legislature."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PSW State Resources", "url": "https://www.pswi.org/Advocacy/State-Resources", "description": "PSW page with compiled state resources for pharmacy professionals, including links to DHS, Controlled Substances Board, Wisconsin Statutes and Rules, and state legislative contacts."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wisconsin Legislature", "url": "https://legis.wisconsin.gov/", "description": "Wisconsin State Legislature website for tracking current legislation, finding representatives, and engaging with the legislative process."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Wisconsin Legislators", "url": "https://legis.wisconsin.gov/About/Contact", "description": "Wisconsin Legislature contact page to find and contact state representatives and senators."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Dose of Reality Campaign", "url": "https://www.dhs.wisconsin.gov/opioids/professionals.htm", "description": "Dose of Reality is a joint DHS and Department of Justice initiative addressing Wisconsin's opioid epidemic. Resources include prevention, harm reduction, treatment, and recovery information."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy templates for state-level pharmacy practice issues. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Governor's Task Force on Opioid Abuse: Wisconsin has had a Governor's Task Force on Opioid Abuse which published recommendations for addressing the opioid crisis. The HOPE (Heroin, Opioid, Prevention, and Education) agenda at https://hope.wi.gov/ was a key state initiative. DHS continues to coordinate statewide opioid response efforts including opioid settlement fund allocation."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Recent Legislation: Wisconsin legalized fentanyl test strips in 2022 (signed by Governor). The legislature has also addressed naloxone standing orders, xylazine test strip legalization, and expanded treatment funding through opioid settlement funds."}]}]}, "wyoming": {"name": "Wyoming", "q": {"CPA_Term": null, "1A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe activities described in Wyoming law that will result in an individual being “deemed to be practicing pharmacy” do not expressly include prescribing drugs or medications. WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-124 (West 2024)\nOther Wyoming pharmacy laws and regulations expressly address pharmacist prescribing, but only as to the prescribing of immunizations, “opiate antagonists,” and epinephrine auto-injectors. WYO. STAT. ANN §§ 33-24-157 to 33-24-158 (West 2024); 059-1.18 WYO. CODE R. §§ 1-5 (Lexis Nexis 2024).\nThe above points are consistent with DEA information that registered pharmacists in Wyoming cannot obtain the DEA’s mid-level practitioner registration to prescribe controlled substances.", "1B": null, "1C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Wyoming to include prescribing drugs and medications, or at least prescribing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.\nAllow Wyoming pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "2A": "As described in the information below, Wyoming laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe activities described in Wyoming law that will result in an individual being “deemed to be practicing pharmacy” do not expressly include administering drugs or medications. WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-124 (West 2024). This provision could mean that a pharmacist does not have general authority to administer drugs or medications.However, a separate Wyoming law provides that “unless otherwise provided by law, the provisions of this act do not apply to administration of drugs and medicines, or to persons engaged in the administration of drugs and medicines.” WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-130 (West 2024).\nThe exact purpose of this provision is not clear, but it may mean that a pharmacist (or potentially others) has broad authority to administer drugs and medications including buprenorphine.\nThere are Wyoming laws and regulations expressly addressing the administration of immunizations. WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-157 (West 2024); 059-1.16 WYO. CODE R. § 4(a) (Lexis Nexis 2024); 059-1.18 WYO. CODE R. § 3 (Lexis Nexis 2024). However, there are no provisions expressly addressing administration of other kinds of drugs or medications, including controlled substances.", "2B": "Understand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "2C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Wyoming to expressly include administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "3A": "Yes, but based on the information described below, the authorization is limited and may not include the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe activities described in Wyoming law that will result in an individual being “deemed to be practicing pharmacy” do not expressly include ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests. WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-124 (West 2024).\nHowever, Wyoming regulations indicate that a pharmacist can perform medication therapy management (MTM) services which “is a distinct service or group of services that optimize therapeutic outcomes for individual patients .\n. . [and] encompasses a broad range of professional activities and responsibilities within the licensed pharmacist’s scope of practice.” 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. § 3(i) (Lexis Nexis 2024). Such MTM services expressly do not require a CPA and can include: (1) “ordering or performing laboratory assessments”; and (2) “evaluating the response of the patient to therapy” so long as the pharmacy is a clinical laboratory under CLIA or “the tests do not otherwise require a physician’s order and the pharmacy or service has obtained a CLIA Certificate of Waiver.” 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. § 17 (Lexis Nexis 2024).\nThere are no other Wyoming pharmacy laws or regulations that address ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests", "3B": null, "3C": "Expand the scope of pharmacist practice in Wyoming to allow pharmacists to order and evaluate the results of the types of lab tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "4A": "No, based on the information described below.\nThe activities described in Wyoming law that will result in an individual being “deemed to be practicing pharmacy” include “provid[ing] collaborative pharmaceutical care.” WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-124 (West 2024).\nWyoming regulation provides that collaborative pharmacy practice (CPP) is where pharmacists and practitioners jointly agree to work in collaboration “to provide patient care services to achieve optimal medication use and desired patient outcomes” and “drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist under specified conditions.” 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §§ 3(a), 16(a) (Lexis Nexis 2024).\nWyoming regulation specifies that a CPA must “explain the scope of the pharmacist’s practices” but pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what CPP services may or may not entail and whether that includes prescribing drugs and medications. 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §16 (Lexis Nexis 2024). Even if a CPA could allow a Wyoming pharmacist to prescribe drugs, Wyoming laws and regulations do not account for the fact that a Wyoming pharmacist cannot obtain a federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration, which precludes the pharmacist from prescribing buprenorphine regardless of what the CPA provides.\nIn summary, Wyoming laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from prescribing controlled substances as part of a CPA. However, even if prescribing buprenorphine is theoretically allowed, as a practical matter, there is no way to do it because a Wyoming pharmacist cannot obtain the state/DEA controlled substance registrations necessary.", "4B": null, "4C": "Revise Wyoming laws and/or regulations governing CPAs to allow pharmacists to prescribe controlled substances.\nExpressly specify in Wyoming laws and/or regulations how prescriptions for controlled substances (or at least buprenorphine) work under CPAs.\nAllow Wyoming pharmacists to obtain the federal DEA mid-level practitioner registration needed to prescribe controlled substances.", "5A": "As described in the information below, Wyoming laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nThe activities described in Wyoming law that will result in an individual being “deemed to be practicing pharmacy” include “provid[ing] collaborative pharmaceutical care.” WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-124 (West 2024).\nWyoming regulation provides that CPP is where pharmacists and practitioners jointly agree to work in collaboration “to provide patient care services to achieve optimal medication use and desired patient outcomes” and “drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist under specified conditions.” 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §§ 3(a), 16(a) (Lexis Nexis 2024). Wyoming regulation specifies that a CPA must “explain the scope of the pharmacist’s practices” but pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what those services may or may not entail and whether that includes administering drugs and medications. 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §16 (Lexis Nexis 2024).\nIn summary, although Wyoming’s pharmacy laws and regulations do not expressly prohibit a pharmacist from administering buprenorphine as part of a CPA, they also do not clearly authorize it and a pharmacist’s general authority to administer buprenorphine outside of a CPA is also unclear.", "5B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "5C": "Expressly specify in Wyoming laws and/or regulations that the activities allowed by a pharmacist under a CPA include administering drugs and medications, or at least administering buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "6A": "As described in the information below, Wyoming laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question. However, due to the answer in the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section, the answer is likely “yes,” although the authorization is limited and may not cover the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.\nThe activities described in Wyoming law that will result in an individual being “deemed to be practicing pharmacy” include “provid[ing] collaborative pharmaceutical care.” WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-124 (West 2024).\nWyoming regulation provides that CPP is where pharmacists and practitioners jointly agree to work in collaboration “to provide patient care services to achieve optimal medication use and desired patient outcomes” and “drug therapy management services not otherwise permitted to be performed by a pharmacist under specified conditions.” 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §§ 3(a), 16(a) (Lexis Nexis 2024). Wyoming regulation specifies that a CPA must “explain the scope of the pharmacist’s practices” but pharmacy laws and regulations contain no further explanation as to what those services may or may not entail and whether that includes ordering or evaluating the results of lab tests. 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §16 (Lexis Nexis 2024).\nIn summary, Wyoming and regulations governing CPAs are unclear about what CPAs can authorize and do not clearly address whether a pharmacist can order or evaluate lab tests under a CPA. Given the response to the \"independent ordering and evaluating of laboratory tests\" section that pharmacists have limited authority to order certain tests outside of CPA, the most logical answer is that a pharmacist has at least the same authority under one.", "6B": "Enter into a CPA (see the CPA procedures and requirements section).\nUnderstand the information in the sections regarding Medicaid, other regulations regarding MOUD, and telehealth.", "6C": "Expressly specify in Wyoming law laws and/or regulations that CPP under a CPA includes ordering and evaluating the results of the types of tests necessary for patients undergoing SUD treatment with buprenorphine.", "7": "A CPA is a written and signed agreement between one or more pharmacists and “one or more practitioners” that defines a collaborative practice. 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. § 3(b) (Lexis Nexis 2024). This provision does not define the word “practitioner.”\nA separate regulation provides that a CPA is a written agreement between one or pharmacists and “one (1) or more prescribers.” 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. § 16(a) (Lexis Nexis 2024). This provision does not define the word “prescriber.”\nThe following Wyoming regulations provide more information on requirements for entering CPAs and required elements of CPAs – 059-1.2 WYO. CODE R. §§ 3(a), (b), 16 (Lexis Nexis 2024).", "8A": "As described in the information below, Wyoming laws and regulations do not clearly answer this question.\nWyoming does not have either a general telehealth/telemedicine practice law or a law requiring health insurance companies to cover telehealth/telemedicine services.\nWyoming law authorizes, but does not require, state licensing boards, including the state board of pharmacy, to “adopt rules and regulations allowing the practice of telemedicine/telehealth and the use of telemedicine/telehealth technologies within an applicable profession or occupation consistent with the profession’s or occupation’s duties and obligations.” WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-1-303(a)(iv) (West 2024).\nHowever, there are no telehealth or telemedicine specific laws or regulations for pharmacists in Wyoming, only a law and set of regulations related to telepharmacy. This makes it unclear if pharmacists can provide telehealth/telemedicine services beyond telepharmacy.", "8B": "Adopt regulations to expressly provide that pharmacists can provide telehealth and that such services include providing buprenorphine for SUD treatment.", "8C": "Wyoming laws and regulations governing telehealth include – WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-1-303(a)(iv) (West 2024)\n(authorization to adopt regulations); WYO. STAT. ANN § 33-24-156 (West 2024) (telepharmacy); 059-1.14 WYO. CODE R. §§ 1 to 10 (Lexis Nexis 2024) (telepharmacy).", "9A": "As of July 2023, Wyoming law provides that Medicaid covered services include “the professional services of a licensed pharmacist.” WYO. STAT. ANN § 42-4-103(a)(xxxvii) (West 2024). As of research published in May 2024, the Wyoming Medicaid program had not described how it would operationalize this new provision.316", "9B": "Adopt regulations and billable codes so that reimbursement of SUD treatment-related pharmacist services can occur under the Wyoming Medicaid program.", "9P": "It depends.\nCommercial insurance may cover a limited set of pharmacist services - coverage will vary based on each insurance plan's policies.", "10A": "No.", "10B": "No."}, "resources": [{"category": "PRESCRIPTION DRUG MONITORING PROGRAM", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "PDMP Program Page", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/pdmp", "description": "Wyoming Board of Pharmacy PDMP page. The Board established the Prescription Drug Monitoring Program in July 2004, as authorized in W.S. 35-7-1060. Collects Schedule II-V controlled substance prescription information from all resident and non-resident retail pharmacies that dispense to Wyoming residents."}, {"type": "note", "text": "PDMP Portal (WORx/PMP AWARxE): The Wyoming PDMP uses the PMP AWARxE platform by Bamboo Health. Eligible new users can create an account on the PMP AWARxE Wyoming website. Access the portal through the link on the Board of Pharmacy PDMP page at https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/pdmp."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PDMP FAQ", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/faq/worx-pdmp-1", "description": "Frequently asked questions about the Wyoming Prescription Drug Monitoring Program. For questions, contact the PDMP at 307-634-9636 or bop@wyo.gov."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Mandatory Use Requirements: Prescribers in Wyoming are required to check the PDMP before prescribing controlled substances. Dispensers are required to report dispensing data for Schedule II-V controlled substances not later than the close of business on the business day immediately following dispensing. Wyoming participates in PMP InterConnect for interstate data sharing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Delegate Registration: Prescribers and pharmacists can add delegates through the PMP AWARxE system to query the PDMP on their behalf. See the Quick Reference Guide and User Guide linked on the PDMP page for instructions."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Dispenser Reporting Guide: The Data Submission Dispenser Guide explains the process to register and transmit data to the Bamboo Health PMP Clearinghouse. Zero reports are required when a dispenser has no dispensations to report."}]}, {"category": "PHARMACY PRACTICE REGULATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Board of Pharmacy Homepage", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/", "description": "Wyoming State Board of Pharmacy homepage. Located at Herschler Building East 2nd Floor, 122 W 25th St, Cheyenne, WY 82002. Phone: (307) 634-9636. Fax: (307) 634-6335. Email: bop@wyo.gov. Executive Director: Matthew Martineau (matt.martineau@wyo.gov)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacy Laws", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/laws", "description": "Wyoming Board of Pharmacy laws page with links to the Wyoming Pharmacy Act (Title 33, Chapter 24 - Pharmacy) and the Wyoming Controlled Substances Act (Title 35, Chapter 7, Article 10)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Pharmacy Act", "url": "https://wyoleg.gov/stateStatutes/StateStatutes", "description": "The official Wyoming Pharmacy Act can be found on the State of Wyoming Legislative Service Office website under Title 33 - Professions and Occupations, Chapter 24 - Pharmacy."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Administrative Rules and Regulations", "url": "https://rules.wyo.gov/", "description": "Wyoming Secretary of State's Administrative Rules website. Wyoming Pharmacy Act Rules and Regulations are posted here, including recently revised Chapters 8, 13, 17, 18, and 22 (approved August 19, 2025)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist License Renewals and CE", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/licensing/pharmacist", "description": "Pharmacist licensing page with renewal information. All CE must be ACPE-accredited and reported to NABP's CPE Monitor."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Collaborative Practice Agreements: Wyoming law permits collaborative practice agreements between pharmacists and physicians. The Wyoming Pharmacy Act and Board rules govern the scope of these agreements. Contact the Board of Pharmacy for specific CPA templates and guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Pharmacist Prescribing Authority: Wyoming allows pharmacists to prescribe naloxone under W.S. 35-4-901 through 906. Wyoming does not have broad independent pharmacist prescribing authority beyond naloxone and certain other authorized medications."}]}, {"category": "BUPRENORPHINE ACCESS AND OUD TREATMENT RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Opioid Crisis and MAT Page", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/behavioralhealth/mhsa/mat/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Behavioral Health Division page on the opioid crisis and medication-assisted treatment. Includes information on NARCAN distribution, free fentanyl test strips, and MAT resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Opioids and Other Drugs", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/prevention/substanceabuseandsuicide/opioid-information-wyoming/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Substance Use and Tobacco Prevention Program page on opioids, including information on commonly prescribed opioids, safety, overdose prevention, and links to resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Treatment Locator", "url": "https://findtreatment.gov/locator", "description": "SAMHSA's national treatment locator to search for substance use disorder treatment facilities in Wyoming, including those offering buprenorphine and other medications for OUD."}, {"type": "link", "title": "SAMHSA Buprenorphine Practitioner Locator", "url": "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/treatment/find-treatment/buprenorphine-practitioner-locator", "description": "SAMHSA directory of practitioners who previously held DATA-2000 waivers to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD treatment. Can be filtered by state."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State Opioid Treatment Authority (SOTA): Wyoming does not have a formally designated SOTA according to Pew Charitable Trusts research. The Behavioral Health Division of the Department of Health oversees substance use treatment. Contact: Behavioral Health Division, 122 West 25th Street, Herschler Building West Suite B, Cheyenne, WY 82002. Phone: (307) 777-6494. Toll-Free: (800) 535-4006. Email: bhdmail@wyo.gov."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Prescribing Requirements: Under the MATE Act (2023), healthcare providers no longer need an X-waiver to prescribe buprenorphine for OUD. Prescribers must complete 8 hours of training on substance use disorders as part of DEA registration or renewal. Wyoming does not impose additional state-specific requirements beyond federal law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Telehealth Regulations for Buprenorphine: Wyoming follows federal DEA telehealth regulations for prescribing buprenorphine. As a rural state, telehealth is an important access pathway for OUD treatment."}]}, {"category": "REIMBURSEMENT AND BILLING", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Medicaid Pharmacy Services", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/healthcarefin/medicaid/pharmacy-services/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Medicaid Pharmacy Services page. Pharmacy Services oversees the Wyoming Medicaid Prescription Drug Program and related services. Pharmacy Help Desk: 1-877-209-1264."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Medicaid (Change Healthcare)", "url": "https://www.wymedicaid.org/", "description": "Change Healthcare (CHC) administers Wyoming Medicaid pharmacy benefits. Providers can access the PA system, preferred drug list, SMAC, pharmacy policies, and provider manuals through this portal."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Preferred Drug List", "url": "https://www.wymedicaid.org/pa-pdl/preferred-drug-lists.html", "description": "Wyoming Medicaid Preferred Drug List (PDL) page. Select the desired PDF to view current preferred and non-preferred drug listings. Provider PA Help Desk: 1-877-207-1126."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Buprenorphine Coverage: Buprenorphine and Suboxone are included on the Wyoming Medicaid PDL. The PDL includes specific coverage details for opioid dependency agents. Prior authorization requirements may apply for certain non-preferred formulations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Pharmacist and Provider Resources", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/healthcarefin/medicaid/pharmacy-services/medicaidpharmacy/", "description": "Wyoming Medicaid pharmacy provider page with information on the preferred drug list, P&T committee information, and reimbursement algorithms for legend drugs, diabetic supplies, and OTC medications."}, {"type": "link", "title": "P&T Committee", "url": "https://www.uwyo.edu/DUR/pandtcommittee", "description": "University of Wyoming Drug Utilization Review and Pharmacy & Therapeutics Committee page with information on therapeutic class reviews, PDL decisions, and meeting agendas."}, {"type": "note", "text": "State-Specific Pharmacist Billing Codes: Wyoming Medicaid does not currently have a comprehensive set of billing codes for pharmacist-provided clinical services beyond dispensing. Contact Wyoming Medicaid Pharmacy Services for billing guidance."}, {"type": "note", "text": "OUD Treatment Grants and Funding: Wyoming receives federal State Opioid Response (SOR) grant funding through SAMHSA and CDC Overdose Data to Action grants. The state received $2 million from CDC for overdose prevention. The Behavioral Health Division administers these funds. Contact bhd.grants@wyo.gov for current grant opportunities."}]}, {"category": "TRAINING, CERTIFICATION, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Pharmacist CE Requirements", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/continuing-ed/contedpharm", "description": "Wyoming Board of Pharmacy pharmacist continuing education requirements page. Pharmacists must complete 12 hours of ACPE-accredited CE annually. Beginning with 2020 renewals, 1.5 hours related to responsible prescribing of controlled substances are required every two years. All CE must be reported to NABP's CPE Monitor."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Pharmacy Association Education", "url": "https://wypha.org/", "description": "Wyoming Pharmacy Association (WPhA) homepage. WPhA hosts events including an Annual Convention in June with continuing education, networking, and professional development. WPhA also participates in the Tripartite Committee on Continuing Education for Pharmacists in Wyoming."}, {"type": "link", "title": "PCSS (Provider Clinical Support System) Training", "url": "https://pcssnow.org/", "description": "PCSS provides free training on medications for opioid use disorder, including training options that meet the DEA 8-hour MATE Act education requirement. Funded by SAMHSA."}, {"type": "link", "title": "DEA Registration Resources", "url": "https://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/", "description": "DEA Diversion Control Division website for DEA registration, practitioner resources, and controlled substance regulations relevant to buprenorphine prescribing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "University of Wyoming School of Pharmacy: The University of Wyoming School of Pharmacy, in partnership with WPhA, provides educational and training resources for pharmacists in the state. The P&T Committee at UWyo also offers continuing education related to drug therapy and formulary decisions."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Wyoming does not have state-specific board-approved SUD or buprenorphine training programs beyond the federal MATE Act 8-hour training. ACPE-accredited programs are accepted."}]}, {"category": "HARM REDUCTION RESOURCES", "entries": [{"type": "note", "text": "Syringe Services Programs: Wyoming does not currently have a state-authorized syringe services program. According to NEXT Distro, there is no harm reduction program in the state, though syringes can be purchased online. Wyoming also does not have an overdose Good Samaritan law."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NEXT Distro Wyoming", "url": "https://nextdistro.org/wyoming", "description": "NEXT Distro page for Wyoming providing harm reduction information, free naloxone by mail, and resources. Notes Wyoming's 135 identified overdose deaths in 2023."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Harm Reduction Collective", "url": "https://www.facebook.com/WyoHarmReductionCollective", "description": "Community-based harm reduction organization in Wyoming focused on evidence-based practices, centering voices of people with lived experience. Available on Facebook."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Naloxone Access", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/prevention/substanceabuseandsuicide/opioid-information-wyoming/opioid-overdose-response/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health page on opioid overdose response and naloxone access. Wyoming Statutes 35-4-901 through 906 (effective July 1, 2017) expanded naloxone access to law enforcement, firefighters, the general public, and allow pharmacists to prescribe naloxone. NARCAN is available over-the-counter."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Free NARCAN for Organizations", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/behavioralhealth/mhsa/mat/", "description": "Free NARCAN is available for agencies, businesses, and organizations in Wyoming through the Department of Health. An order form and requirements are listed on this page. Contact Rachel Nuss (rachel.nuss3@wyo.gov) or overdose.prevention@wyo.gov."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Free Fentanyl Test Strips", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/behavioralhealth/mhsa/mat/", "description": "Free fentanyl test strips are available through the Wyoming Department of Health. Each kit includes 5 test strips, a scoop, and test receptacle. Order at the link on the MAT page. Orders ship to physical addresses within Wyoming within 1-2 weeks. Contact bhd.grants@wyo.gov for questions."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Fentanyl Test Strip Legality: Wyoming legalized fentanyl test strips. They are distributed free by the Wyoming Department of Health and available for individuals and organizations. Wyoming law excludes fentanyl and xylazine test strips from drug paraphernalia definitions."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/prevention/substanceabuseandsuicide/opioid-information-wyoming/drug-overdose-data/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health drug overdose data dashboard showing fatal and non-fatal drug overdose information. Fatal overdoses identified through death certificates; non-fatal through ER visits and hospitalizations."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Opioid Epidemic Information Portal", "url": "https://opioid.wygisc.org/", "description": "Wyoming Geographic Information Science Center (WyGISC) opioid epidemic information portal providing mapping and data visualization of opioid-related issues in Wyoming."}]}, {"category": "RECOVERY SUPPORT SERVICES", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Mental Health and Substance Use Treatment Services", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/behavioralhealth/mhsa/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Behavioral Health Division page on mental health and substance use treatment services. Includes links to crisis resources, peer specialists, problem gambling, and community services."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Peer Specialists", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/behavioralhealth/mhsa/peer-specialists/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health page on peer specialists. Peer specialists share the experience of living with psychiatric disorders or addiction and provide emotional support, knowledge sharing, skills teaching, and resource connections."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Behavioral Health Division", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/behavioralhealth/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Behavioral Health Division homepage. Oversees programs for individuals, children and families, the Wyoming State Hospital, Wyoming Life Resource Center, and community mental health and substance use treatment. Phone: (307) 777-6494. Toll-Free: (800) 535-4006."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Recovery Housing: Wyoming does not maintain a centralized state-operated recovery housing directory. The National Alliance for Recovery Residences (NARR) at https://narronline.org/ can be used to search for certified recovery residences. Contact the Behavioral Health Division for local recovery housing resources."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Substance Abuse and Mental Health Ombudsman", "url": "https://www.wyoguardianship.org/", "description": "Wyoming Substance Abuse and Mental Health Ombudsman Program providing help with substance abuse or mental health issues through information, referral, coaching, service support, education, and advocacy."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Crisis Contacts: 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline available 24/7 by calling or texting 988. Community Disaster Hotline: 1-800-985-5990 or text TalkWithUs to 66756. Wyoming Behavioral Health Division: (800) 535-4006."}]}, {"category": "KEY STATE CONTACTS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Board of Pharmacy", "url": "https://pharmacyboard.wyo.gov/", "description": "Wyoming State Board of Pharmacy. Herschler Building East 2nd Floor, 122 W 25th St, Cheyenne, WY 82002. Phone: (307) 634-9636. Fax: (307) 634-6335. Email: bop@wyo.gov. Executive Director: Matthew Martineau (matt.martineau@wyo.gov)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Medicaid", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/healthcarefin/medicaid/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Healthcare Financing (Medicaid) homepage. For pharmacy-specific questions, contact the Pharmacy Help Desk at 1-877-209-1264."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Wyoming Behavioral Health Division (SOTA equivalent): Wyoming Department of Health Behavioral Health Division, 122 West 25th Street, Herschler Building West Suite B, Cheyenne, WY 82002. Phone: (307) 777-6494. Toll-Free: (800) 535-4006. Email: bhdmail@wyo.gov."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Wyoming Pharmacy Association: https://wypha.org/ or https://www.wpha.net/", "description": "Wyoming Pharmacy Association (WPhA). Mission: Advocating, educating, and connecting to improve the health of Wyoming citizens through the advancement of pharmacy. Actively participates in Board of Pharmacy meetings and legislative activities."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Health Department Opioid Program", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/prevention/substanceabuseandsuicide/opioid-information-wyoming/", "description": "Wyoming Department of Health Substance Use and Tobacco Prevention Program opioid page. Contact: 122 West 25th Street, 3rd Floor West, Cheyenne, WY 82002. Email: overdose.prevention@wyo.gov."}]}, {"category": "STATE OPIOID DATA AND SURVEILLANCE", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Drug Overdose Data Dashboard", "url": "https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/prevention/substanceabuseandsuicide/opioid-information-wyoming/drug-overdose-data/", "description": "Interactive dashboard showing fatal and non-fatal drug overdoses in Wyoming. Fatal overdoses identified through death certificates; non-fatal through ER visits and hospitalizations."}, {"type": "note", "text": "NARCAN Distribution Dashboard: Available on the opioid overdose response page at https://health.wyo.gov/publichealth/prevention/substanceabuseandsuicide/opioid-information-wyoming/opioid-overdose-response/", "description": "Dashboard showing NARCAN distributed by the Wyoming Department of Health to organizations statewide, by organization category, county, date, and saturation."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Opioid Epidemic Information Portal", "url": "https://opioid.wygisc.org/", "description": "WyGISC interactive story map providing geographic data and visualizations related to Wyoming's opioid epidemic."}, {"type": "link", "title": "amfAR Wyoming Opioid Profile", "url": "https://opioid.amfar.org/WY", "description": "amfAR opioid epidemic profile for Wyoming showing data on overdose deaths, treatment availability, and federal funding."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Prevention Depot Rx Toolkit", "url": "https://www.wyomingpreventiondepot.org/rxtoolkit/best-practices/prescription-drug-monitoring-programs/", "description": "Wyoming Prevention Depot resource page on prescription drug monitoring and best practices for addressing prescription drug abuse in Wyoming."}]}, {"category": "ADVOCACY AND POLICY TOOLS", "entries": [{"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Pharmacy Association Advocacy", "url": "https://wypha.org/", "description": "WPhA actively participates in Wyoming State Board of Pharmacy meetings and legislative activities including lobbying, testifying, and monitoring bills affecting the pharmacy profession."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Wyoming Legislature", "url": "https://wyoleg.gov/", "description": "Wyoming Legislative Service Office website for tracking current legislation, viewing statutes, and engaging with the legislative process."}, {"type": "link", "title": "State Statutes", "url": "https://wyoleg.gov/stateStatutes/StateStatutes", "description": "Wyoming state statutes online, including Title 33 (Pharmacy Act) and Title 35 (Controlled Substances Act)."}, {"type": "link", "title": "Contact Wyoming Legislators", "url": "https://wyoleg.gov/Legislators/LegislatorList", "description": "Find and contact Wyoming state legislators. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "link", "title": "NASPA Resources", "url": "https://naspa.us/", "description": "National Alliance of State Pharmacy Associations provides model legislation and policy templates for state-level pharmacy practice issues. Please verify this link before publishing."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Key Recent Legislation: Wyoming Statutes 35-4-901 through 906 (2017) expanded naloxone access to the general public and authorized pharmacist naloxone prescribing. Wyoming legalized fentanyl test strips. HB0111 (2023) addressed drug-related provisions. Wyoming does not currently have an overdose Good Samaritan law."}, {"type": "note", "text": "Wyoming Opioid Response: The Wyoming Department of Health Behavioral Health Division coordinates the state's opioid response through federal SOR grant funding, NARCAN distribution, fentanyl test strip programs, and community mental health and substance use treatment grants."}]}]}};
